<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICANS-DEBATE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS CANDIDATES GATHER FOR COURTEOUS DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for rewriting throughout) 
 (sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Resisting their first opportunity to spar directly
with each other on national television, six Republican presidential
candidates instead treated each other on Monday night rather
courteously as they touted their stands on foreign policy, taxes,
education and campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in a Republican forum in New Hampshire last week, where
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas shared the stage for the first time
with his rivals, this time the contenders were far more subtle in
contrasting themselves with the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   And while Bush drew criticism in that event for too often
drawing from his stump speech, he did not put those questions to
rest on Monday night. He appeared a bit more at ease this time but
still offered rather rote responses on matters from his tax-cutting
plan to foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he had learned about foreign policy from a biography
of Dean Acheson _ Bush said last week he was reading the book _ the
goveor repeated from his standard speech and gave no specifics
about Acheson, the secretary of state from 1949 to 1953.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson, he said, ``is that our nation's greatest export to
the world has been, is and always will be the incredible freedoms
we understand in the great land called America.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Sen. John McCain of Arizona seized the
opportunity to demonstrate his mastery of foreign affairs and
history. He answered a question by saying: ``Let me talk about Dean
Acheson for a second. When Dean Acheson walked into Harry Truman's
office in June of 1950 and said, `North Korea's attacked South
Korea,' Harry Truman didn't take a poll. Harry Truman knew what we
had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   For about half of the debate at the Orpheum Theater, the
competitors were allowed to quiz one another. But mostly their
questions sounded like recitals of their own credentials. The
event, which lasted about 75 minutes, was carried live on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Bush repeatedly talked about recasting the image of the
Republican Party as a compassionate party that cared about everyone
_ and he underscored his concern for the less fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who has emerged as a potent rival to Bush in New
Hampshire, trumpeted his prescriptions to reform the campaign
finance system. Although he was hooked up to the event by satellite
from a television studio near Boston, McCain _ as he did last week
_ seemed particularly comfortable fielding questions.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the wealthy publisher, sought to establish his
conservative credentials and hawk his plans for the economy. Gary
L. Bauer, who headed a grass-roots conservative group, played up
his crusade against most-favored-nation status for China because of
human rights abuses. Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah spoke often about his
seasoning after years in the Senate. And Alan Keyes, a former State
Department official, pressed his conservativism.
</P>
<P>
   When the candidates had the opportunity to ask questions, it was
no surprise that the first up, Bauer, turned his attention to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer asked Bush why he, like President Clinton, favored more
open trade with China, as opposed to a sharper confrontation with
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give people a breath of freedom, a taste of freedom, I
think you'll be amazed, Gary, at how soon democracy will come,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer asked, ``Is there no atrocity that you can think of that
would tell you to put trade on the back burner?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in perhaps his most spirited answer, replied: ``If we turn
our back on China and try to isolate China, things will get worse.
Imagine if the Internet took hold in China. Imagine how freedom
will spread.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor used his question, to Hatch, to boast about how in
Texas he had draw significant support from Hispanic voters. ``I
think Governor Bush deserves a lot of credit,'' Hatch said. But the
senator went on to say that many people had suggested that Bush
would be a perfect vice president given that Hatch had more foreign
policy experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have eight years with me,'' Hatch said to Bush.
``Boy, you'd make a heck of a president after eight years.'' The
audience erupted in laughter.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the good manners seemed forced. When Forbes told Bush
he could call him Steve, the governor _ who is not known as being
particularly fond of the publisher _ did not know quite what to
say. Later in the evening, McCain joked that he did not know
whether to call the governor ``George,'' ``W'' or ``Bush'' or
``whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   In his question for McCain, Bush promoted his proposal for tax
incentives for faith-based institutions. McCain complimented the
governor's proposal. But he tried to draw a contrast by suggesting
that Bush relied on rosy, and perhaps unrealistic, projections of
surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference,'' McCain said. ``I do not envision
surpluses forever.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The first round of questions for all six candidates concerned
education, and each candidate used his response principally as an
opportunity to state his general views on the federal government's
role in public education. Those views were alike to the point of
being nearly identical: all the candidates emphasized clear, finite
limits to federal involvement and many advocated at least some
experimentation with vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bauer and Keyes rued the flight of prayer and religion from
classrooms( with Bauer citing that as a reason for violence in
schools. ``I don't think this is a gun problem, as some might
suggest,'' Bauer said. ``I think it's a problem of the heart and
sOul.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes agreed, saying, ``Since we took prayer out, we seem to
have let violence and decline in.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Hatch and Bush talked up the virtues of vouchers, although
Bush did not use that word. Bush reiterated his frequently stated
belief that schools that receive federal funds should face
consequences if the children in those schools are failing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that if the federal government spends money on the
poorest of the poor children, we need to ask a simple question,''
said Bush. ``What are the results? What are the results?''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was reminded of a statement he has repeatedly made that
good teachers should make more than bad senators, whose salary will
raise to $140,000 in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that I would never allege that there are any bad
senators,'' McCain joked. Then, making light of questions that have
been raised about his temper, added: ``I win Miss Congeniality
every year in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   In a move to prevent his rivals from ganging up on Bush, CNN set
ground rules that prohibited the candidates from all using their
allocated question for another candidate on the same person.
</P>
<P>
   McCain did not travel to Arizona to share the stage with his
competitors because, his campaign said, he had long-scheduled
events in New Hampshire and New York on Monday and Tuesday but CNN
agreed to include him by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the civility of the discourse compared to last week,
there were a handful of thinly-disguised digs at Bush. ``Instead of
running on their name or their wealth,'' Mr. Keyes said at one
point. ``Let's seem them run on their abilities, as I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Amen,'' Hatch said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
