<HEADLINE>
MIDWEST RESEARCH INSTITUTE NAMES NEW PRESIDENT AND CEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
<TEXT>
<P>
   James L. Spigarelli has been named the new president and chief
executive officer of Midwest Research Institute, the Kansas
City-based center for applied science and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Spigarelli joined Midwest Research Institute in 1970 and has
held research and line management positions. He had served as chief
operating officer since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Spigarelli holds bachelor of arts and master of science degrees
from Pittsburg State University and a doctorate in chemistry from
Kansas State University, where he was a National Science Foundation
fellow.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Kipp, chairman of the board of the research institute,
said Spigarelli's strong science and management background would be
important to the institute's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this quickly changing world, spurred on more and more by
sophisticated technologies, Spigarelli's science background will
ensure that Midwest Research Institute maintains and enhances its
highly respected position in the research community,'' Kipp said.
</P>
<P>
   Kipp said Spigarelli had demonstrated a keen ability to
establish business relationships and alliances with universities,
government and industry.
</P>
<P>
   Spigarelli succeeds John McKelvey, the institute's president and
CEO since 1975. McKelvey announced his end-of-the-year retirement
at the institute's annual meeting in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
