<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIRANDA-POLICE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE PLAN TO KEEP MIRANDA WARNING, WHATEVER COURT DOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE and TANYANIKA SAMUELS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You have the right to remain silent. Anything you say can be
used against you in a court of law....''
</P>
<P>
   The protection afforded by those words, perhaps the best-known
phrases in American police work, will be reviewed by the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The court on Monday decided to tackle the groundbreaking
question of whether its 1966 ruling that produced the Miranda
warning _ designed to stop forced confessions by giving suspects
the right to a lawyer's help _ was rendered moot by a long-ignored
law Congress passed in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Greg Mills, who oversees the Violent Crimes Division for
the Kansas City Police Department, argued that Miranda should
remain intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that the Miranda ruling should be thrown out the
window,'' Mills said. ``I don't think...it's hampered our ability
to question suspects and get confessions.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's Miranda decision, named for the late Ernesto
Miranda, a career criminal in Phoenix, flowed from the Fifth
Amendment's guarantee that no one ``shall be compelled in any
criminal case to be a witness against himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The court was more liberal then than it is today, and civil
rights advocates hailed the decision. Police and conservatives
argued it would hamstring crime-fighting.
</P>
<P>
   But the court never explicitly said the police warning was
required by the Fifth Amendment. In 1968, Congress passed a law,
known as Section 3501, that states that failure to issue a Miranda
warning does not mean that any evidence obtained must be tossed
out. However, that provision received little attention at the time
and has been ignored since.
</P>
<P>
   The justices said they would rule by this summer whether Section
3501 effectively overruled the Miranda decision.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri and Kansas, prosecutors and defense experts say they
hope the Miranda ruling stands. Miranda, they argue, does not often
interfere with criminal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   They say Miranda is good public relations for authorities
because the public is aware that confessions and evidence must be
obtained according to certain standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing more important than making sure people in law
enforcement are viewed as the good guys,'' said Cass County
Prosecutor Chris Koster. ``To go back to the days prior to Miranda
puts our credibility at risk, and no one wants to go in that
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the court does, law enforcement officials may
continue to recite the warning. Use of Miranda is one more sign
that a confession or piece of evidence is not obtained under
duress, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become as common as putting your seat belt on,'' said
Clay County Sheriff Bob Boydston. ``I don't see us giving it up
that easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Close, the lawyer for the Kansas City Police Department,
said he would recommend that officers continue reciting Miranda
even if the high court does not require it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What better way do you have to go before a judge several
months later and say a confession was voluntary?'' Close said.
</P>
<P>
   The court might cut away at Miranda, ``but police will still say
it to be cautious and err on the side of safety and
admissibility,'' said Platte County Prosecutor Todd Graves.
</P>
<P>
   Whether a suspect talked to investigators rarely hinged on
whether the Miranda warning was issued, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most know their rights, and they're either going to talk to
you or not,'' said Johnson County District Attorney Paul Morrison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
