<SLUG> BC-PBD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDIT QUESTIONS SICK-LEAVE EXPENSES IN POLICE DEPARTMENT  
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH E. IGOE  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Police Department spent almost $4 million
in the last two fiscal years compensating retiring officers on
accumulated sick leave, a figure MIssouri Auditor Claire McCaskill
called ``excessive.''
</P>
<P>
   Clunky, aging cruisers _ some with far more than 100,000 miles _
are also fixed to the tune of thousands of dollars instead of being
replaced, she told the Board of Police Commissioners on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Those areas _ in addition to trimming spending on department
gifts or tables at charitable functions _ topped McCaskill's list
of areas for improvement in the department's use of taxpayer
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The state audit focused on the two fiscal years that ended April
30, 1999. Police board members and department staff members have
pledged to look into the issues she raised and examine solutions
suggested by her staff.
</P>
<P>
   In the two years covered by the audit, the department spent
close to $4 million to compensate retiring employees for their
accumulated unused sick leave. In one case, the audit stated, a
retiree was paid $103,200.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill said she understood the department was probably using
the buyouts to prevent employees from using sick leave
inappropriately. She also acknowledged that the department was
following the city policy. There have been no department studies or
other evidence, however, showing that sick leave buyout programs
are an effective way to reduce use of sick leave.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with other metropolitan law enforcement agencies in the
nation, Kansas City's policy is excessive, she said. Other
departments either offer less money for the accumulated sick leave
or have no buyout program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department's policy is liberal and an expensive one,''
said McCaskill. ``No other department had the buyout program
implemented here.''
</P>
<P>
   Alternatives to encourage employees not to use sick leave, she
said, could include continuing the buyout program but phasing in a
cap on maximum payouts, reducing the payout levels for sick days,
or counting unused sick leave as additional months of service
toward the calculation of retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The department could cut costs by one-quarter or even one-half
if it followed, for example, St. Louis' policy, which simply pays
less for accumulated sick days. Board members said the department
would take up the issue with the City Council at a Thursday
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, City Councilwoman Teresa Loar said that if
the council changed the sick-leave policy for the Police
Department, it should be changed for all departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to do it for specific departments,'' she said.
Some changes ``are certainly something we could take a look at, to
see if that would be beneficial.''
</P>
<P>
   That sick-leave money saved, McCaskill said, could help the
department bolster other areas, such as replacing an aging fleet of
about 750 vehicles, from cruisers to motorcycles. An average
department vehicle is more than 6 years old, auditors noted, with
an odometer reading of about 100,000 miles. About 157 vehicles
exceed 150,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   In the years audited, the department spent about $2.5 million on
new vehicles, including 94 new cars and a $300,000 command-post
bus. That money is either approved by City Council or comes from
other grant sources. But the audit noted that ``the department has
not adopted a vehicle replacement plan which sets guidelines for
the retirement of police vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to maintaining the fleet, McCaskill told the
board, ``we found a number of instances that are particularly
troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the department spent about $10,000 to repair a 1996
Ford Crown Victoria with more than 77,000 miles. Another time the
department dropped $8,000 to fix another 1992 Ford Crown Victoria
that had exceeded 160,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears the department has repaired vehicles which should
have been considered for retirement,'' the audit stated.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill recommended that the department look into buying
several used Highway Patrol vehicles, which are already fully
equipped and usually sell with 50,000 miles on them, because they
would be more cost-effective.
</P>
<P>
   Department staff members responded in the audit that they had
raised the issue of an aging fleet with City Council, which funds
their department. The normal appropriation from the city for
vehicle appropriations is $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Loar, who sits on the Operations Committee that oversees the
fleet, said she would be in favor of providing the department with
more money for vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any place I want to spend money, that is it,'' she
said. ``I want the fleet ready to go when we need them.''
</P>
<P>
   The audit also raised questions about the department's spending
on gifts and nonprofit functions. Department officials approved
spending about $50,000 in the audit period for items _ such as
flowers, cakes, cookies, fruit baskets and retirement rings _ where
a public purpose was not demonstrated or documented.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of the items were for ``morale building'' events
from retirements to comforting a departed officer's bereaved
family, McCaskill said the command staff should look into ways to
offset those costs by tapping into staff good will or other private
sources.
</P>
<P>
   More troubling, she noted, was money the department gave to
nonprofits _ $7,050 in the two years _ for annual dinner banquet
tables.
</P>
<P>
   Said McCaskill: ``It is frankly unnecessary for governments to
spend tax money on those types of activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Bidding practices also were not followed consistently, the audit
stated. The department requires competitive bidding for contracts
of $25,000 or more. But the department contracted with Arthur
Andersen for information technology services at a cost of $63,135.
Because the work was consulting, the department contended it did
not have to bid the work. Auditors disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Using consultants, McCaskill told the board ``does not relieve
you of the responsibility to bid out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 0041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
