<HEADER>
A1397 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-PSYCHE-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      12-07 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHE-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN IS FIERY, DRIVEN BUT `STABLE,' RECORDS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After his years as a Vietnam prisoner of war, John
McCain grappled with a quick temper and an ``unrealistically high''
need for achievement, but he was not diagnosed with any psychiatric
disorder, according to newly released medical records.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who had twice made feeble efforts at suicide when he
neared his breaking point in a Hanoi prison camp, was not inclined
to seek counseling after he was released in 1973, the records show.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, an ``Arizona Republic reporter'' was given permission
to inspect the medical records but was not permitted to make
copies. Over the weekend, McCain showed his medical records to
selected reporters at the Associated Press and the ``New York
Times'' under the same conditions.
</P>
<P>
   McCain ``will probably not seek psychiatric aid,'' said a 1973
psychiatric evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He prides himself on handling his own problems although
underneath this is marked, unmet dependency,'' the report said.
``He would probably seek aid first if needed from various friends
and acquaintances.''
</P>
<P>
   The annual evaluations, which date back to 1973, indicate McCain
adjusted well after his release from a Hanoi POW camp and was
diagnosed as ``stable,'' but that he had some lingering issues
after his ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   On a 1973 psychological questionnaire that had asked, ``What
traits do you have that others object to?'' McCain wrote, ``quick
temper.''
</P>
<P>
   Another psychiatric evaluation, this one from 1974, also
suggested McCain had problems controlling his temper, but concluded
that he had made progress during captivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He learned to control his temper better,'' said the evaluation
by Navy psychiatrist P.F. O'Connell. O'Connell wrote that McCain
had learned ``to not become angry over insignificant things: not
`to go to the mat' over some minor provocation by a guard that
resulted in needless torture.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also had an ``unrealistically high'' need for
achievement, the 1973 evaluation said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may tend to expect too much of himself and take it hard
when/if things don't go as planned,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Annual evaluations were conducted routinely on POWs by Florida's
Naval Aerospace Medical Institute, which has a center devoted to
POW studies.
</P>
<P>
   The evaluations were made available by McCain's presidential
campaign as part of about 1,500 pages of his medical records.
</P>
<P>
   The medical records also indicate that McCain has ``orthopedic
limitations'' resulting from his wartime injuries, but he is
generally healthy. He had a malignant melanoma, a form of cancer,
removed from his left shoulder in 1993, but there has been no
evidence of recurrence.
</P>
<P>
   He also suffers from arthritis in his shoulders and right knee,
which were injured when he ejected over North Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's temper has become an issue in the presidential
campaign. His aides have noted that the evaluations were from long
ago, and that he has worked on preventing outbursts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is 26 years ago,'' said Dan Schnur, McCain's
communications director. ``The most important part of these
records, as they relate to John McCain's temper, is the analysis
from, the psychiatrist (O'Connell) who says that Lieutenant McCain
learned to control his temper while in prison in order to avoid
unnecessary beatings at the hands of his guards.''
</P>
<P>
   As difficult as it was to be imprisoned and tortured, the
experience actually seems to have helped McCain, in an ironic way,
to establish his own identity apart from his father, who was a
four-star admiral, according to the records.
</P>
<P>
   As a POW, McCain ``learned more about himself, about others,
felt that he and his values had been tested, and was reassured that
he had met the challenge successfully and that he had finally
climbed out from under'' the shadow of his father, the 1974 review
said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's plane was shot down over Hanoi in October 1967. He was
held, often in solitary confinement, until March 1973.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's now-deceased father was devoted to the Navy, and became
head of the Pacific fleet while his son, now an Arizona senator and
presidential contender, was a POW.
</P>
<P>
   McCain says he loved and admired his father, even if his dad
wasn't around much when his son was growing up. McCain was placed
in boarding school when he was 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since realizing that he was the son of a famous, highly
successful Naval officer and although proud of his father, he has
been preoccupied with escaping being in the shadow of his father
and establishing his own image and identity in the eyes of
others,'' O'Connell wrote. ``He feels his experiences and
performance as a POW have finally permitted this to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The evaluations continued into the 1980s. In 1979, when McCain
was 42, the review concluded he was proceeding ``confidently'' and
``with a touch of aggressiveness that suggests a little
compensation or Oedipal rivalry, but also with a great deal of
moral concern and feeling of responsibility for the world he lives
in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oedipal rivalry'' refers to tension between a son and his
father.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the McCain campaign showed signs of temper-fatigue.
Several surrogates for the senator took the stage in the press room
at the Arizona debate to let reporters know it was time to back
off.
</P>
<P>
   `We think it's time to put that issue to rest,'' said Sen. Jon
Kyl, McCain's national campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't think it's any longer relevant to the campaign,''
Kyl said. &QL; 
(Arizona Republic writer Kris Mayes contributed to this article.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
