r f BC-BLUE-KAN &LR;      12-07 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE CROSS SENDS CONTRACT AMENDMENTS TO ALL PLAN DOCTORS 
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH and PAUL WENSKE  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In its most far-reaching effort in recent
memory to renegotiate physician contracts, Blue Cross and Blue
Shield of Kansas City on Monday mailed contract amendments to all
3,200 doctors in its health plan networks.
</P>
<P>
   The area's largest health insurer took the action after at least
1,000 of the doctors, in a rare show of protest, declined to sign
or delayed signing the contracts that govern how they work with
Blue Cross.
</P>
<P>
   John P. Mascotte, president and chief executive officer of Blue
Cross, told reporters that the health-care insurer was ``trying to
demonstrate to doctors that we are willing to make changes _ to
work with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors reacted with cautious optimism, viewing the move as an
assurance that Blue Cross intended to work through sticking points
without disrupting patient care.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no small thing for Kansas City,'' said Deborah
Jantsch, president of the Metropolitan Medical Society of Greater
Kansas City. ``In some ways, this is a landmark event. Let's not
make light of it. We were at an impasse.''
</P>
<P>
   Included in the changes is a guarantee that payments to
physicians will not decline for one year. Blue Cross officials also
said they were open to ideas on whether doctors or insurers should
decide what constitutes medically necessary care. However, changes
may not be made in that area before the deadline for doctors to
sign and return their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross emphasized that coverage of doctor bills for its
750,000 members in about 30 counties would not be interrupted
during the negotiations, which could continue for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have spent a great deal of time listening to physicians,
discussing their concerns and looking for ways to address those
concerns,'' Tom Bowser, Blue Cross's executive vice president and
chief operating officer, said in a press release Monday. ``That has
resulted in the contract adjustments we are announcing today.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors who declined to renew their contracts had said that the
contracts unfairly restricted their medical practices. Those
doctors had been scheduled to get termination notices in early
December, with the notices taking effect in early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Under the amendment mailed Monday, Blue Cross said doctors now
had until January to sign their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors who are sent termination notices after that still will
have 90 to 120 days to reconsider. They also will remain in Blue
Cross network directories through the grace period, allowing them
to continue caring for Blue Cross subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The delay ``is a very positive thing,'' said Jantsch, ``because
it will give individual practice groups time to discuss changes
with the plan without the threat of termination hanging over their
heads.''
</P>
<P>
   It also gives assurance of care to patients, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients have been very alarmed by this since it became
public,'' she said. Some had written their congressional
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The contract amendment includes these changes:
</P>
<P>
   - Blue Cross guarantees that doctors' payments will not decline
for one year.
</P>
<P>
   - Blue Cross clarifies requirements on physicians ``personally
performing'' services. This involves situations such as doctors
supervising nurses who give injections.
</P>
<P>
   - Blue Cross limits its authority to require continuing medical
education beyond state requirements.
</P>
<P>
   - Blue Cross will pay for copies of certain records, such as
reports on surgical procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross is inviting doctors to submit ideas for resolving the
medical-necessity issue. This has been a concern of doctors who
think that Blue Cross and other insurance companies wield too much
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new physician agreements have essentially the same
definition of medical necessity as the existing agreements,'' said
Bowser. ``Our language is consistent with that used by other
insurance companies and by Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bowser said Blue Cross agreed with doctors that
``improvements in medical-necessity administration may be
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to reach a conclusion on these improvements and
communicate any changes by the second quarter 2000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowser said Blue Cross officials remained ``very optimistic that
these changes will encourage doctors to move forward to sign the
contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Richard Hellman, president-elect of the medical
society, said some ambiguities remained in the proposed contract
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope doctors read them carefully and consult their
lawyers,'' he said. ``It's a fairness issue, and an issue of
whether doctors think they can provide the care their patients
need.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can, the doctors will feel good about it. If the issue
is still ambiguous, I think there still will be some doctors who
will not sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Hellman said he was concerned that doctors were being asked to
sign their contracts before the medical-necessity issue had been
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross officials said the matter needed study and open
dialogue free of the contract talks. They suggested one resolution
might include having physician peer groups review treatment and
decide what is medically reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Hellman said he thought that doctors would be open to peer
groups reviewing medical care issues rather than having insurers
decide the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased,'' he said. ``This is a step they are making in
the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hellman said, ``This issue has little to do with money
and more to do with the public interest and fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross officials acknowledged that the changes were
influenced in part by a national backlash against managed care. For
example, UnitedHealthcare recently said it no longer would require
doctors to seek approval before recommending medical treatment or
hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are important issues,'' said Mascotte. ``In fact, the
system is evolving, and we want to be part of that evolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Mascotte said he was confident that most of the doctors would
sign over the next three or four months _ all of them, he hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross said members who were undergoing medical treatment
would continue to be covered even if their doctors did not renew by
the end of the grace period.
</P>
<P>
   Bowser said that since Thanksgiving, 115 more doctors had signed
Blue Cross contracts, leaving about 900 who had yet to sign. He
said 300 were close to signing.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross officials said doctors who had signed their contracts
were being asked to sign and return the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross officials said one concern over which Blue Cross had
little control was the complexity of the contracts. A doctor who
wants to be in every plan, for example, must read 92 pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``This recontracting process is primarily driven by our need to
comply with federal and state regulations, as well as requirements
placed upon us by the many customers we serve,'' Bowser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We acknowledge that our new contracts are lengthy and complex.
However, this complexity is unavoidable since these new contracts
govern over $120 million in annual physician payments in six
managed-care programs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
