<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETING MILLENNIUM HYPE IS STARTING TO FIZZLE OUT 
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Millennium this, millennium that. Are you tired of all the
millennium marketing yet?
</P>
<P>
   MMG Worldwide President Clayton Reid certainly is. ``There's so
much millennium advertising out there, specifically from big
advertisers,'' he said. ``It's difficult for a small advertiser to
break through.''
</P>
<P>
   From new-millennium cereal boxes on grocers' shelves to
millennium eve parties with price tags up to six digits, American
businesses are hoping to cash in on the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But all this new millennium fun and hype is starting to get old,
Reid said, and the millennium ad message may no longer be working.
</P>
<P>
   Selling the dawn of a new age ``has not turned out to be the
windfall that a lot of companies thought it would be,'' said Reid,
whose Kansas City ad agency specializes in the hospitality
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Local merchants report that consumers are increasingly blase
about anything Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Many heavily promoted holiday travel packages and New Year's
parties at exotic locales have fizzled, flopped or failed to sell
out, said Reid, in part because of mostly exaggerated fears of
computer meltdowns that might strand travelers or have them
dropping from the skies.
</P>
<P>
   A survey this fall by the Travel Industry Association of America
found that 46 percent of Americans thought computer woes would
cause at least some problems for New Year's weekend travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traveling over the holidays is difficult enough without
worrying about Y2K computer glitches,'' Reid said. ``A lot of
airline seats, cruise ship cabins and hotel rooms are going to be
empty'' over the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Caribbean resorts are only about 70 percent filled for the New
Year's holiday despite a recent marketing blitz, said Bear Stearns
&AMP; Co. analyst Jason Ader. Normally those sun-drenched island rooms
are 90 percent booked this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the exception of hotels in hot spots such as Las Vegas
and New York, we believe that most hotels will not reach the
expectations set for the holiday weekend,'' Ader said.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K fears are certainly part of the reason, but Ader also blames
inflated hotel, airline and cruise fares for applying the brakes to
international holiday travel this year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising said its
surveys in 19 countries found that people were genuinely tiring of
New Year's and millennium hype. The agency is encouraging such
clients as Coca-Cola, General Motors and Nestle to go easy on such
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a fun product, and you want to just have fun, then
it's fine,'' said Joseph Plummer, a McCann executive vice
president. ``But on a deeper level, we're saying to try to
associate with it in a bigger, more long-term way.''
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, for instance, McCann urged some clients to sponsor
the Millennium Wheel or the Millennium Dome, both in England, as a
way to tie in to the New Year in a positive and meaningful way. The
Millennium Wheel in London is a 1,500-ton Ferris wheel, offering
25-mile views, that was built for the millennium and will remain a
permanent tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   The Millennium Dome is a huge exhibition space being constructed
in Greenwich, England. Both are taking corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, the M word is ubiquitous _ sometimes for no
apparent reason.
</P>
<P>
   - Harrah's North Kansas City Casino &AMP; Hotel just launched a
``Millennium Rush Hour'' contest for December that seems to have no
connection to the new era except that the winner's name will be
drawn from a drum Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   - The Missouri Lottery is running a contest that will select one
``lucky daily game'' player as the winner of its ``Millennium World
Traveler'' contest that will award a 24-day trip for two around the
world _ in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   - An ad for KMBZ-980 AM promotes the station as ``News Radio for
the New Millennium.'' Does that mean it wasn't the station for this
millennium?
</P>
<P>
   - One group marketing an honest-to-goodness real millennium
product is the American Heartland Theatre at Crown Center. Its
``Millennium Musical'' opens Jan. 14 and parodies ``1,000 years of
history in 100 minutes,'' said spokesman Robert Barrientos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Mel Brooks meets Monty Python,'' said Barrientos of the
nutty stage production that spoofs civilization from the
Inquisition to bungee jumping.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Convention and Visitors Bureau of Greater Kansas
City has rushed into print with a special millennium brochure that
outlines hotel, restaurant and other New Year's Eve parties and
special events in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where will you be when the clock strikes twelve, ushering in
the new millennium?'' it asks.
</P>
<P>
   The list of parties is impressive. So are some of the price
tags.
</P>
<P>
   - One of the costliest gigs will be at Station Casino Kansas
City, where a $3,000, two-night weekend package for two includes a
suite, a bottle of Dom Perignon champagne, two complimentary robes,
plenty of food and passes to the movie theaters. A standard room
package and modest perks for the big night go for $500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 0046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1401 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-MILLENNIUM2NDTAKE-KAN     12-07 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETING MILLENNIUM HYPE IS STARTING TO FIZZLE OUT 
</HEADLINE>
 2ND TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We don't have a lot of rooms left,'' said John V. Finamore,
Station's Midwest president.
</P>
<P>
   - What absolutely has to be the priciest millennium package in
Kansas City is at the Ritz-Carlton on the Country Club Plaza, and
is being sold just once in every Ritz-Carlton hotel city.
</P>
<P>
   That ultimate experience, $100,000-per-couple weekend is nothing
less than full immersion in unabashed luxury. Millennium souvenirs
include exquisite things made of gold, calfskin and sable _ for
starters. Private chefs and butlers will be on hand, of course,
along with masseuses, limousines, private helicopter rides and
more.
</P>
<P>
   The package is still available in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   - Back to earth, the Embassy Suites in Overland Park is having a
Masquerade Millennium Ball featuring a swing band and souvenir
millennium sweat shirts for $275 a couple.
</P>
<P>
   - Party goers at Kansas City's venerable Italian Gardens
restaurant will receive handmade millennium plates and glasses. At
Historic Suites of America in Kansas City they'll get a
``one-of-a-kind Millennium Champagne gift basket.''
</P>
<P>
   - Kansas City's Science City at Union Station millennium party
has a little something for everyone, with price tags to match.
There's a $1,000-a-couple black-tie dinner and dance, or the
$100-a-couple laser light show and party in the Grand Hall, or the
$10-a-head celebration outside, where there will be fireworks,
music and vendors peddling plenty of hot stuff to drink and eat.
</P>
<P>
   - In St. Louis, the official gathering is a Millennium on the
Mississippi party with fireworks framed by the Gateway Arch for
those who get there early for a good seat.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium marketing has attached itself to plenty of mundane
products too.
</P>
<P>
   Registered trademarks for 272 goods or services bearing the word
millennium _ or, in 21 cases, the misspelled ``millenium'' _ have
been granted by the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office, and the
agency is reviewing requests for 1,415 others.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of 2000 also deck the malls, where shops offer everything
from Millennium Monopoly to Cabbage Patch Millennium babies. Barnes
&AMP; Noble has 113 Y2K titles in its database.
</P>
<P>
   One company expecting a boost in sales is the condom maker
Durex, which commissioned a worldwide survey of 4,200 young adults.
It found that more than half of men and 38 percent of women ages 16
to 21 expected to have sex New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Even food companies are in on the act, from General Mills'
brightly packaged Millennios cereal to Pepperidge Farm packages
that display its little cracker goldfish wearing party hats.
</P>
<P>
   For those with champagne incomes, there are Waterford crystal
millennium champagne flutes for $2,000 and a DeBeers millennium
diamond for $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   For those in the beer-budget set, a mere $4.95 will get you a
``2000 USA Candle'' and $7.95 will bring a ``Having one of those
millenniums'' coffee mug at www.year2000products.com, one of a
handful of Web sites specializing in year 2000 souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   Some area retailers say there is no groundswell of interest in
millennium products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has pretty much fizzled,'' said Harry Lukas, owner of Lukas
Liquors Superstore in Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   Several distillers have come out with products with various
millennium marketing hooks or ``2000'' on the labels, but they
haven't aroused much interest from consumers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anheuser-Busch is one of the few winners. Its millennium gift
packs include a supersize bottle of Budweiser and four glasses for
$40. It's become a popular gift item, Lukas said.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Schaumburg, co-owner of two area Last Chapter bookstores,
said most of the new-millennium books on her shelves had been met
by yawns from the reading public. One exception, she said, is the
My Millennium Memoir, a do-it-yourself journal to write about the
occasion and even record for all posterity what you were wearing.
</P>
<P>
   A millennium edition of the Guinness Book of Records is also a
big seller. Shoppers don't come looking for it but snap it up once
they spot it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the big winner,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Or never mind Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   One American Express ad campaign is selling Y1K.
</P>
<P>
   The company's 36-page ``Mexico Millennium'' promotion in the
December issue of Travel &AMP; Leisure magazine offers package travel
and resort deals that lean heavily on the ancient culture and
sights of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Bookspan Book of the Month Club is using a Y3K
marketing theme for its current catalog sale on the ``Top 10 books
they'll be reading in 3000.'' (Atlas Shrugged, The Autobiography of
Martin Luther King and The Complete Works of William Shakespeare
made the list, by the way.)
</P>
<P>
   And if you're millennium-fatigued already, brace yourself for
sesquicentennial exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of ``KC150'' volunteers are busy planning Kansas City's
150th birthday party on June 3, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It's an all-year celebration, and 131 community events are
already scheduled. (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
