<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SANDERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANDERS MIGHT PROVIDE REMEDY FOR COWBOYS' OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Troy Aikman sees triple-threat Deion Sanders
providing a much-needed dual purpose for the Dallas Cowboys, if he
is moved to offensive side of the ball for the final quarter-season
stretch drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Sanders) can do some things that can be incorporated
into our offense that, hopefully, can help us, either getting the
ball to him or letting Deion draw attention his way and freeing up
some other (receivers),'' said Aikman, who said Monday that he has
grown wary of talking about an offense that, excluding the two
Washington games, is averaging only 1.6 offensive touchdowns per
game this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably at a position offensively where we need to do
whatever we can to get as many playmakers on our side of the ball
as possible ... and Deion certainly is one of those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   End of subject?
</P>
<P>
   You might think so.
</P>
<P>
   Especially after hearing owner Jerry Jones express his desire to
see Sanders get a chance to line up at wide receiver, sooner rather
than later, maybe even Sunday against Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when you see how much help this offense needs and
when you hear Sanders himself say that he is willing to add offense
to his list of duties to perform if it means helping the Cowboys
make the playoffs, which might require running the table over the
last four games.
</P>
<P>
   But coach Chan Gailey remained noncommital Monday, saying that
the team's braintrust will bat it around behind closed doors over
the next couple of days before deciding on whether to give the
NFC's leading Pro Bowl vote-getter in the fan balloting at ``both''
cornerback and kick returner what could amount to as many as 10-12
snaps on offense.
</P>
<P>
   With the possible exception of having only one road victory,
there is nothing more that the Cowboys' offense is lacking than
big-play ability.
</P>
<P>
   Since Michael Irvin was lost Oct. 10 with a cervical injury and
congenital condition, the Gailey offense hasn't had a consistent
big-play threat to complement Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail, who has
become less and less a deep threat, while still piling up twice as
many receptions (65) as the team's second-leading receiver Ernie
Mills (30).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our emphasis is as a running football team,'' said Aikman,
referring to Emmitt Smith's 1,053 yards and that he was on pace to
carry the ball a career-high 400 times before he broke his right
hand and missed 11/2 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put that much emphasis on the running game, then the
passing game is not going to be as sharp when you get into a
passing situation ... but we (in the pass offense) have to work
through that.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Sanders can provide some impetus.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there will be more changes than that. Gailey wouldn't
rule out the possibility of personnel moves this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that you can continue down this road and just
say, `Well, things are OK,' because they're not OK,'' Aikman said.
``I think everyone would expect to see some changes.''
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't, or wouldn't speculate, adding that he hasn't been
told of any chances other than hearing Sanders' name mentioned as a
possiblity at wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deion could force defenses to cover us differently than
they're doing now,'' said Jones. ``I know I'm dreaming because it's
just one week after Deion has had full practice for the first time
this year, but I think he could help us in some of the offensive
packages.''
</P>
<P>
   About Sanders, Gailey said, ``He's the best corner and the best
punt returner in the league. So if now he's on the field for 10 or
12 more plays (at wide receiver), which is not his natural
position, you now put him in an unnatural situation ... (which is)
a possible health risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman emphasized that he has confidence in all his receivers,
even if he doesn't a chance to develop much of rapport with any of
them compared with Irvin, his teammate of 11 seasons, of whom he
said Monday: ``I think there are probably people in the
organization who underestimate what it meant to lose Michael. It
has had a tremendous impact ... (because) Michael is one guy who
had been in big games before, and had made big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have been looking for big-play offense on a
consistent basis since the Sept. 12 season-opener at Washington. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
