<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISET'S STATUS STILL UNCERTAIN FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Stephane Fiset, the Los Angeles Kings'
opening-night goaltender, is back on the ice. When he gets back in
a game is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset practiced with the club Monday, the one-month anniversary
of the deep bone bruise he suffered on his right hand taking
back-to-back shots off his blocker in pregame warmups.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset had the hand packed in ice after Monday's workout and said
he has a little more strength and range of motion. But he is not
ready to squeeze a stick well enough to clear a puck in a game and
that is frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is stronger than it was, but still not right,'' said Fiset,
who last week showed no improvement after the hand was placed in a
cast for five days. ``This is something I figured would be better
in five or six days. Here it is a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Andy Murray said he hopes to have Fiset back within two
weeks, but he has been saying that since early November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're lucky that Jamie Storr has been playing well,'' Murray
said. ``We've been overcoming injuries, but we're definitely
pushing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Payback time: There are a lot of Kings players who agree with
Murray that the power-play goal that gave Tampa Bay a 3-3 tie was a
gift from officials, who botched an earlier play that helped give
the Kings a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Rob Blake was whistled for cross checking even though
replays showed he never touched a Lightning player. That gave Tampa
Bay the man advantage and they scored with 23.8 seconds left to put
the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings claim it was payback for interference by linesman
Baron Parker five minutes earlier that allowed Glen Murray to score
his second goal of the game. Parker was standing along the right
boards when he was struck by a puck coming out of the Tampa Bay
end. Parker was on the Lightning side of the blue line, meaning
Murray picked it up without being offside. He scored an unassisted
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Quick whistles: Murray said the biggest problem with his club
the past few weeks has been its disappearing act in the second
period. An example was the Nov. 27 game against San Jose. The Kings
won, but were outshot 19-4 in the second. Against Tampa, the Kings
had just seven of their 37 shots in the second and did not score
after taking a 2-0 lead.... One of the highlights of Saturday's tie
was the connection Luc Robitaille and rookie Jason Blake made on
the ice. Both worked out on the same line Monday and could be
together if Robitaille double shifts with the fourth unit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
