<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1416 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-DALY-LADN     12-07 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-DALY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS CEO DALY SEARCHING FOR STABILITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the former head of a movie studio, Robert
Daly's seen high-priced box office flops. When he took over as
managing general partner, chairman and CEO of the Los Angeles
Dodgers on Oct. 28, he had first-hand experience with another one.
</P>
<P>
   In his first one-on-one interview since assuming the position,
Daly answered many questions about the Dodgers' past and future.
</P>
<P>
   It's been five weeks since the 62-year-old Daly bought a
minority share of the Dodgers and became the club's top executve.
And while the former Warner Bros. co-chairman admits there's much
more for him to learn, he recognizes the organization's
shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really think there's anything fundamentally wrong with
the organization,'' Daly said at his Dodger Stadium office. ``I
think there's been a lot of things that's taken place over the last
few years that you wish didn't take place. I think the bottom line
is I'd like to see the team win some more ballgames, and I don't
think there's any reason why we shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, what I would love to see is everybody go out there and
play to win and not get involved in any of these differences of
opinions. I think if everyone was rowing together, it would help a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly said the Dodgers need stability.
</P>
<P>
   Since Fox bought the team, the Dodgers fired a manager and
general manager, placed interim labels on their replacements and
then hired a new manager and GM. They revamped the coaching staff,
hired Bob Graziano as president and fired him only to have Daly
re-hire Graziano as the club's president.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox leadership was also faceless, nothing more than a
corporate entity that knew little of running a baseball club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe what has happened to the Dodgers was so
disruptive,'' Daly said. ``There was a tremendous amount of
distractions. Even if you go back to the time Peter O'Malley
announced he was selling the team (January 1996). There was so much
change that took place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have the same general manager, the same manager, the
same coaches (that finished the season). You start off in such a
better position than you were in the last year.''
</P>
<P>
   But as a diehard fan who called from around the globe to follow
the Dodgers, Daly also knows about the turmoil. It began when Mike
Piazza was traded after a contract squabble couldn't be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my understanding, nobody with the Dodgers ever sat down
to talk with Mike Piazza. It was all done through
representatives,'' Daly said. ``That won't happen while I'm here. I
would have looked Mike Piazza in the face and said, `Do please
understand, we would like to keep you but we can't afford the money
you're looking for,' and then we would have at least gotten his
response.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly pledged that before a decision is made on a player's
future, the two will sit and talk. He did it with Raul Mondesi, but
Mondesi still wanted out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a very disruptive way to start next year if
Mondesi stayed here because he didn't want to stay here,'' Daly
said.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a year since the Dodgers signed Kevin Brown to a
record $105 million. It infuriated the rest of baseball, and giving
a then 33-year-old pitcher a seven-year contract added venom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for Los Angeles to have a successful team, not
only for Los Angeles but for baseball,'' Daly said. ``That doesn't
mean we should overpay or set precedents that people get upset by.
The (Kevin) Brown deal was a rich deal. The Green deal was a
totally different deal because, basically, we were getting rid of a
lot of payroll when we got Green, and getting rid of a player who I
personally love as a player but who did not want to play here next
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly also heard of a rift between general manager Kevin Malone
and manager Davey Johnson, one that Malone and Johnson deny.
Players also complained about a lack of communication from the
manager, and as the offseason continued the coaching staff was left
wondering, somewhat perplexed, about their fate. Two weeks ago it
was announced the coaches would return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for communication to be picked up,''
Daly said. ``That means at all levels. From the players, the
coaches, the manager, the general manager, all the way up.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Daly won't do is predict a World Series title. He then
noted the harsh lesson Malone learned after similar comments last
spring.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Daly said is the Dodgers will be better than last
season's 77-85 fiasco, and will likely hike their payroll from $80
million to the mid-to-upper $80 million range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it would be hard to say the Dodgers will be a
profitable team in 2000, based upon the payroll,'' said Daly, who
added the Dodgers lost money last year. ``The payroll for 2000 will
be higher than '99, but we're trying to contain what the up is,
which is why we're looking at all the options.''
</P>
<P>
   Trimming payroll is paramount to turning profit, Daly said, but
it's not the only option.
</P>
<P>
   Dodger Stadium is undergoing a $50 million facelift that
includes luxury suites and club seating, which produces more
revenue sources. But it still won't match the ancillary revenue the
newer parks can produce, so the Dodgers' future at Chavez Ravine
will ultimately be questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't project out to long term, but obviously there's no
plan on changing Dodger Stadium.'' Daly said. ``There's no talk
about moving at the present time. I don't know what will happen
with football in L.A., but this is still a perfect site for a
football stadium, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Dodgers' problems aren't only inherent in L.A. They
still own Dodgertown in Vero Beach, Fla., an extravagant spring
training home that costs millions of dollars every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an economical place for us,'' Daly said. ``We're
still talking to the people at Vero Beach. Hopefully, by the start
of the season we're going to come to grips with whether we're going
to stay in Vero Beach or not. Right now, we don't have an
alternative in front of us.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dodgertown is a long way off. Pitchers and catchers are
still more than two months from reporting, and the Dodgers still
need to dispense salary, probably find a third baseman and
strengthen their bullpen and bench.
</P>
<P>
   In five weeks Daly's brought calm to an organization rife in
turmoil since media magnate Rupert Murdoch took over. Whether Daly
brings the other things needed is open to debate, though he did
say, ``I don't expect to be talking about this stuff in one year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 0118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
