r s BC-BBO-BASEBALL-ESPN-LAD     12-07 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-ESPN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPN, BASEBALL OPT TO KISS AND MAKE UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Having finally figured out that a long-term
courtship would benefit both more than a nasty court battle, Major
League Baseball and ESPN announced a contract extension through
2005 on Monday, hours before a U.S. District Court trial on the
matter was to begin in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported the terms of the six-year
agreement _ which essentially extends the current deal three more
years _ to be in the $800 million ballpark. But neither baseball
commissioner Bud Selig nor ESPN president George Bodenheimer would
confirm the figure.
</P>
<P>
   Both also danced around questions that a judge's suggestion to
settle out of court had anything to do with the timing of the
announcement. Still, each were relieved to avoid the legal
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Partners should do whatever they can to stay out of court,''
Bodenheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased we avoided going to court today; I've tried to
eliminate as much of that as possible,'' said Selig.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the process unfolded, it became obvious this partnership
was under a significant amount of strain and this agreement was
frankly beneficial to both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty much an about-face for Selig, who lashed out when
ESPN announced in 1998 that three Sunday night September games
would be moved to ESPN2 to accommodate a new $600 million-a-season
Sunday night deal with the NFL. Baseball's response then was
telling the network to return those games to the teams.
</P>
<P>
   Its louder response last April was to announce the termination
of the contract after the 1999 season. ESPN countersued in May to
force baseball to uphold the existing deal.
</P>
<P>
   Selig, and baseball, seemed more focused on the fact ESPN2 has
10 million fewer cable homes than ESPN and was being slighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was upset about it and I didn't hide it,'' Selig said. ``You
always learn, and I have in my lifetime, not to let personal events
cloud what we're trying to do. Once the negotiations began, it was
clear ESPN wanted to perpetuate this relationship, but under terms
we could agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do have to learn to disagree, but do it in a way as to not
affect your good judgment moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodenheimer also said he ``wouldn't characterize anything as a
tradeoff'' in the negotiations as far as the NFL was concerned.
``You have to evaluate this in total. I don't think you can focus
on small aspects of the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   So while baseball got its point across with the loud lawsuit,
ESPN seems to have paid the price for hurting its feelings. For
starters, ESPN's cost per season just went up from $112 million to
$133 million over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise on the Sunday night baseball-football conflict
means ESPN and ESPN2, for the first two years of the deal, will
televise two games for every one moved. One of those two telecasts
will come on Fridays in September. The second will be Sunday night
games on ESPN2 earlier in the season. In those cases, it would
create simultaneous games on both channels.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the agreement means an increase from 90 to 108
regular-season games on ESPN and ESPN2. Also, ``Baseball Tonight,''
ESPN's daily studio highlight show, will expand and air
additionally on ESPN2, and there will be more baseball highlights
allowed to be shown on ``SportsCenter.''
</P>
<P>
   That translates to, according to ESPN calculations, more than
800 hours of exposure a year for the game, up from 500 on both
networks in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The ESPN Radio, ESPN Classic and ESPN.com deals were also
extended in this package, as was ESPN's right to develop and market
baseball video games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rest assured, it leaves ESPN with a great deal of value for
us,'' said Bodenheimer, whose team of negotiators came to an
agreement early Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports Net and TBS had made overtures about taking the cable
package if ESPN's relationship with baseball was ending. Selig said
that while other offers were comparable to ESPN's, baseball decided
to stay the course with the cable network as it has the past 10
years once differences of agreement were settled.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball now has deals with ESPN, Fox and NBC that bring the
sport nearly $2 billion, but this will set the groundwork for
baseball to ask for more from Fox and NBC when their regular- and
postseason deals expire at the end of the 2000 season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
