<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLD-CUP (Tokyo) _ Mutual recriminations are flying among
the Japanese broadcast companies that have sought to buy rights to
soccer's World Cup 2002. From their descriptions of the way the
negotiations have been handled, as well as from documents obtained
by The New York Times, a picture emerges of possible conflicts of
interest, noncompetitive deal-making and deep suspicions all around
of secrecy and betrayal. By Howard French.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ARATON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Latrell Sprewell will meet up with
P.J. Carlesimo for the second time in recent weeks when Golden
State plays the Knicks at the Garden on Tuesday night. Maybe this
time, Sprewell should shake Carlesimo's hand. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-GIANTS-PAYTON (East Rutherford, N.J.) _ The Giants stunned
just about everyone with their rout of the Jets on Sunday. They are
now 6-6 and in the thick of both the NFC East race and the NFC
wild-card race. And a good deal of the credit for the victory goes
to the unheralded Sean Payton, the team's quarterbacks coach, who
took over play-calling responsibilities from Coach Jim Fassel. By
Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-LANDER (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Just about now, if things
had gone differently, Wayne Zimmerman would have been waiting
expectantly and nervously for the Mars Polar Lander's mechanical
arm to start digging in the planet's cold ground, searching for
evidence of water ice. Instead, the engineer and others are worried
that the $165 million mission's failure could prompt public and
congressional criticism of the entire Mars exploration program,
including possible calls for severe cutbacks. By John Noble
Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SCHIZOPHRENIA-RESEARCH (Undated) _ Researchers are
beginning, in a systematic way, to investigate the earliest stages
of schizophrenia, attempting to find signs that could predict its
onset. But some of that research has become controversial,
particularly the aspect of treating people with drugs for a
condition they do not yet have. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-THERAPY (San Francisco) _ Two gene therapy advances, in
the treatment of hemophilia and heart disease. By Lawrence M.
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PLANCK-LENGTH (Undated) _ According to recent developments
in the quest to devise a so-called ``theory of everything,'' space
is not an infinitely divisible continuum. It is not smooth but
granular, and the Planck length gives the size of its smallest
possible grains. By George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUBBLE-RESCUE (Undated) _ If all goes according to plan, the
Hubble Space Telescope, a window through which humans have viewed
the edges of space for almost a decade, will soon be reawakened by
the nudging, gloved hands of astronauts replacing and repairing the
failed inner works that forced it into hibernation. Next week, the
space shuttle Discovery is scheduled to blast off on a mission to
restore the observatory. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ARCTIC-WARMING (Undated) _ Evidence continues to accumulate
that global warming is thawing the frozen world of the Arctic and
sub-Arctic, and the findings are spotlighting two increasingly
important questions: Can what is happening in the Great White North
touch off sudden shifts in climate that will transform weather and
disrupt life throughout the Northern Hemisphere? Is the Arctic a
key to the way in which global warming might be translated into
region-by-region climatic changes? By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FIRST-EMIGRANTS (Undated) _ Two genetic surveys of human
populations have brought new evidence to bear on a pivotal event in
prehistory, the first dispersal of modern humans from Africa. One
study, based on analysis of people in East Africa and India,
suggests the first emigration of modern humans was eastward, toward
Asia, and not northward through the eastern Mediterranean. A
second, drawing on DNA data from 50 ethnic groups around the world,
concludes that the ancestral population from which the first
emigrants came may have numbered as few as 2,000 people. By
Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NOTHINGNESS-ESSAY (Undated) _ With physicists' identifying
nothingness as the central mystery of the origin and structure of
the universe, a battle of words has been ignited over the last
several years. The question is whether concepts in physics, biology
and the other hard sciences can shed any light on similar-sounding
concepts in the humanities. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-U.S.-LOST-LAND (Undated) _ U.S. finds wetlands, farmlands
and forest are being lost at an accelerating rate. By William K.
Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIABETES-BRACELETS (Undated) _ In the near future, people
with diabetes may be wearing pain-free bracelets or even earrings
smart enough to sense and report glucose levels continuously to an
artificial pancreas: a surgically embedded pump that dispenses just
the right amount of insulin into the bloodstream. By Anne
Eisenberg.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIET-WEB-SITES (Undated) _ It was probably inevitable that
the World Wide Web would bloom with sites for dieters. But to the
surprise of professional dietitians, many of these sites have
turned out to be not only popular but effective. By David Rampe.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Your science questions answered.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Short items on health and and
fitness.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Drawing on her training as a
therapist and her experiences in self-healing after the death of
her husband, Marta Felber wrote ``Grief Expressed: When a Mate
Dies'' (Life Words, 1997), which can serve as a road map to
recovery for the bereaved as well as a guide to those who wish to
express sympathy and offer comfort and support. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
