<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-COYOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES STEAL VICTORY FROM STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The game was all but over.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Stars simply had to go through their customary
ice-the-puck, seal-the-game final few minutes, and a gap-closing
victory against the Western Conference-leading Phoenix Coyotes
looked to be well in hand Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the time it takes an average commercial to run, the
game was over.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes scored twice in a 26-second span of the third period
to sneak out of Reunion Arena with a 3-2 victory, stopping the
Stars' season-best winning streak at four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we weren't playing bad. What was it 20 seconds or
so?'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher asked. ``It felt like 20
seconds. Bam, bam, you lose the game.''
</P>
<P>
   First, Phoenix forward Trevor Letowski deflected a Jyrki Lumme
shot past Stars goalie Ed Belfour with 3:25 remaining for the tying
goal. Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk had attempted to clear the
puck, but Lumme stopped it along the boards and fired it on net.
</P>
<P>
   Letowski tipped the puck in such a way that it dinged off the
post and in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked, and it was in the net it happened so fast,'' Hatcher
said. ``Maybe in the third period we didn't come at them hard
enough. Maybe, we let down a little bit. I think that's what's more
frustrating about it because there was a good thing, and in 26
seconds, it's a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   An all-too-familiar Coyotes face made sure of it 26 seconds
later.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes forward Jeremy Roenick, who had his jaw broken by a
Hatcher hit the last time he was in the building, scored the
game-winning goal at 17:01 of the third period. His shot sneaked
between Hatcher's skate, Belfour and the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't touch me,'' Hatcher said. ``It went in between my
skate and the post. Eddie said he thinks it hit his skate and kind
of just trickled over. You try that a thousand times, and it won't
go through. That's a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is it did go in, spoiling what had for 56 minutes been
a strong Stars performance and doing to the Stars what they had
done to them Nov. 5. In that game, the Stars scored five goals in
the third period to escape with a 6-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the Stars got scoring from their third and fourth
lines. They killed a four-minute penalty in the third period. They
were limiting the Coyotes' chances.
</P>
<P>
   They did everything they said they needed to do to win the game
except for win it despite having a power play in the final two
minutes. They couldn't even generate a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disappointing loss, especially for as well as we played
and as hard as we played,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We
made two mistakes along the wall, and it ended up in our net. ...
This was a huge game. This would've pulled us within five points of
these guys and would've made for a good run, and we didn't get it
closed off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were 38-2-5 last season when leading going into the
third period. They had that lead Monday night thanks to an unlikely
player _ winger Blake Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   In a game when the Stars couldn't muster a shot on a four-minute
power play, Sloan scored one of those goals usually scored by the
likes of a Mike Modano or a Brett Hull.
</P>
<P>
   He went wheeling around from behind the boards, circling into
the bottom edge of the face-off circle. He then released a pretty
shot that sneaked between Coyotes goalie Bob Essensa's arm and the
post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was starting to bite the bit a little bit,'' said Sloan, who
scored his only other goal this season Oct. 5. ``We put together a
solid 56 minutes or so. Unfortunately, this game was 60 minutes
long. Our stamina for the test wasn't as good as it should've
been.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' other goal on the evening came from third-line center
Guy Carbonneau at 4:34 of the first period. Carbonneau took the
first shot. Essensa made the first save. The rebound stayed on the
tip of his skate. Carbonneau swiped down and knocked it in.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, however, didn't take long to answer. Phoenix winger
Mike Sullivan lifted a rebound of a Radoslav Suchy shot above a
sprawled out Belfour. The shot went straight up, knocking the water
bottle around at 5:48 of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we did a lot of good things,'' Hatcher said. ``I
don't think the game was a total waste. I think that makes it a
little more frustrating to be honest. I don't think we took a step
back. It all comes down to what we do in our next game.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
