<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-SMITH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS SUSPEND ROOKIE AFTER WARRANT ISSUED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ After watching rookie Leon Smith spiral helplessly out
of control over the past three weeks, the Dallas Mavericks finally
made their move.
</P>
<P>
   With Smith reportedly in an undislcosed Dallas facility
receiving psychiatric treatment, the Mavericks removed the
6-foot-10 forward from the injured list Monday and placed him on
the suspended list for an indefinite period of time without pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no longer a basketball issue,'' Mavericks president
and chief executive officer Terdema Ussery said. ``Leon must focus
on getting the care that he needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This action allows him to concentrate solely on that issue.
While we have been told that he is in Dallas and is in an
in-patient facility receiving care, we still don't know exactly
where he is, and accordingly, haven't been able to communicate with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Chicago, a warrant was issued for Smith's arrest
because he failed to appear at a hearing Monday morning. Smith's
bond was posted at $15,000 on Saturday after he was charged with
breaking the windows and ramming a car owned by Vanessa Pondexter,
the mother of his ex-girlfriend, Cappie Pondexter.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest warrant was ordered because Smith's bond slip states
that he was not to leave the jurisdiction of the court of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's attorney, Dennis Berkson, said he doubted Smith would be
arrested in the Dallas facility where he is receiving treatment.
Berkson said he would try to get a court order blocking execution
of the warrant.
</P>
<P>
   However, Berkson said if the court insists that Smith come back
to Chicago to face charges, he would find a way to help Smith
surrender peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and a companion, Fred Shephard, flew to Dallas late
Saturday night, and Smith immediately checked into a treatment
facility. Shephard was an all-state basketball player for Martin
Luther King coach Landon Cox during the early 1980s, and has moved
into Smith's Oak Lawn apartment with strict orders from Cox to keep
an eye on Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Cox accused the Mavericks of not being concerned about
Smith, but only being concerned about finding a way to stop paying
Smith the $37,500 he was receiving every two weeks under terms of
the contract he signed Nov. 3. So far, Smith received two such
payments on the three-year, $1.447 million guaranteed contract that
he signed last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mavericks are just trying to find a way to void this kid's
contract,'' said Cox, who coached Smith at MLK High. ``That's all
they care about.
</P>
<P>
   ``They drafted him and now they don't want him. But the boy is
getting help, and he asked for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith tried to commit suicide on Nov. 14 when he swallowed
several bottles of aspirin and was found passed out in his
apartment by Dallas police. Then, Wednesday he threathened Cappie
Pondexter at Marshall High School with a gun after she spurned his
romantic advances.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was charged with aggravated assault for threathening
Cappie Pondexter, and spent Thursday night in a Chicago jail. Not
long after his bond was posted at $1,000, Smith was arrested again
for the incident involving Vanessa Pondexter's automobile.
</P>
<P>
   Ussery, speaking on behalf of a Mavericks organization that has
been criticized nationally for their handling of Smith, said it's
time for those who are closest to Smith and who really care about
his well-being to step up.
</P>
<P>
   Ussery said: ``We hope that Leon and those closest to him
understand that his playing in the National Basketball Association
is inconsequential at this point and that they'll devote their full
energies to helping Leon become a healthy, productive member of
society again.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
