<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS </SLUG>
 TECH-SEARCH-TEX 
Tech's top top choice bows out (For use by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rich Rodriguez, the Clemson offensive coordinator identified by
Texas Tech officials as the leading candidate to replace departing
football coach Spike Dykes, withdrew his name from consideration
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, a West Virginia native, said a desire to remain close
to family members and a belief that he would ``continue to be
marketable'' for future jobs if Clemson continues to have success
convinced him to remain in Clemson, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   The decision surprised Tech officials, who had begun making
tentative plans for a news conference for Wednesday to present
Rodriguez as Dykes' successor. Now, the apparent front-runner is
Oklahoma offensive coordinator Mike Leach, the only one of three
confirmed candidates to interview with Tech officials who has not
removed his name from consideration.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico State coach Tony Samuel, a former Nebraska assistant,
withdrew his name Friday. It remained unclear last night if
Rodriguez's decision might lead to reconsideration by Samuel.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Rodriguez's announcement, Tech athletic director
Gerald Myers said the school's search would focus on ``four or
five'' other candidates. Myers declined to identify them or
speculate on a timetable for selecting Dykes' successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when you have top candidates, there's a possibility
these things can happen,'' Myers said. ``We accept that. We'll go
on. We have some other candidates who are going to be
outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Leach, who interviewed with Tech officials in Lubbock on Nov.
20, could not be reached for comment last night. Two other
high-profile offense coordinators, Mark Richt of Florida State and
Ralph Friedgen of Georgia Tech, have expressed interest in the Tech
vacancy. As of Monday, both said they had not been contacted by
Tech officials.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, 36, said removing his name from consideration for the
Tech vacancy was ``the most difficult decision I've ever had to
make in my life.'' It came just two days after Tech chancellor John
Montford identified Rodriguez as ``certainly the leading
candidate'' in the school's search process.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 48 hours, I've gone back and forth,'' Rodriguez
said. ``This was by far the best opportunity that's presented
itself in my career and it's been very, very difficult ... to
decide if I wanted to keep pursuing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family is very happy (at Clemson). That was a big factor in
the decision. My goal is still to be a Division I head coach. I
feel pretty good that if we continue to have success ... the right
opportunity at the right time may come up. I may get another chance
down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Rodriguez said his dream job would be to
succeed Don Nehlen, 63, as coach at West Virginia. Accepting a
long-term deal at another school, especially one with a punitive
buyout clause, could prevent Rodriguez from making that move if
Nehlen retires within the next two years. Sources close to the
search confirmed Tech plans to make a buyout clause part of its
agreement with Dykes' replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Myers, however, said the desire for a West Virginia buyout
option never arose in negotiations with Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never mentioned that at all,'' Myers said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
