A1425 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-T     12-07 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERPRICED FREE-AGENT PITCHERS MAKE OFF-SEASON A BARE MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not entirely true that free advice is worth what it costs.
If it's acted on, it might be worth even less.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with that caveat in place, here's a snippet for the
Rangers' Doug Melvin and every other general manager: Don't do it.
</P>
<P>
   Don't pay inflated prices for mediocre pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers _ along with every other major-league team with the
possible exception of the Atlanta Braves and the New York Yankees _
need pitching. There's precious little available on the free-agent
market.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching that's available isn't very good, but it is very
pricy, especially after David Cone, who wore down in the second
half last season and who will be 37 next season, signed a one-year
contract for $12 million to remain with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are interested in keeping Aaron Sele and in signing
Kenny Rogers and Chuck Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Sele wants a four-year deal worth between $36 million and $40
million. He might be worth it, considering he's 29, in the prime of
his career and won 37 games the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates continued to insist that after Pedro
Martinez, Sele was as good as any pitcher in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Sele's earned-run average last season was
4.79, up from 4.23 in '98. The league hit .283 against him in '98
and a robust .293 in '99.
</P>
<P>
   Sele is an innings-eater who gives his team a chance to win, the
kind of pitcher who would be an asset on most staffs. But he's not
an ace, and even in this day and age, $10 million is ace money.
</P>
<P>
   Finley also wants $10 million a season but only for three years.
The length of contract is more palatable to Melvin, who's loath to
go longer than that for a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Finley turned 37 last week.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three seasons he was 13-6 with a 4.23 ERA, 11-9 with
a 3.39 ERA and 12-11 with a 4.43 ERA, decent numbers for the late
1990s. But is it worth taking a $30 million gamble that he'll
remain effective when he's pushing 40?
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Rogers, who wants a five-year deal for at least $42
million and preferably $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving the Rangers as a free agent after the 1995 season,
Rogers is 42-27 with a 4.26 ERA. He has hit double figures in wins
twice _ 12-8 in '96 and 16-8 in '98 _ and has topped 200 innings
once.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers turned 35 last month, meaning he'd also be pushing 40 at
the end of a five-year deal. At his best he's a very good pitcher,
but is he worth a $50 million gamble?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, of course, is no.
</P>
<P>
   Sele, Finley and Rogers are decent pitchers who can help a
staff. They are not difference-makers who can take a team to the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Decent should not cost $10 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Just say no. ROOKIE CLASS WEAK
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last year, when Nolan Ryan, George Brett and Robin Yount
were elected in their first year on the ballot, this year's list of
first-time eligibles for the Hall of Fame is weak.
</P>
<P>
   It's headed by Jack Morris, who has marginal credentials. The
right-hander was the winningest pitcher in the '80s with 162
victories, was a 20-game winner three times and raised his game in
the postseason. Morris won both his starts as the Tigers won the
1984 World Series, and he was 2-0 with a 1.17 ERA _ including a
complete-game shutout in Game 7 _ to pitch the Twins over the
Braves in '91.
</P>
<P>
   However, his 254 victories are well short of the ``automatic''
number of 300. His career ERA was 3.90, and he was never below 3.00
in any season.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers leave Morris on the bubble and certainly aren't
good enough for a first-ballot election.
</P>
<P>
   The best bets to form the Class of 2000 are Carlton Fisk, the
all-time leader in games caught who fell 43 votes short last year,
and Tony Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Ballots were mailed to 10-year members of the Baseball Writers
Association of America last week and must be returned by the end of
December. The results will be announced Jan. 11. NOT SO FAST
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were ready to announce the next piece in their
rebuilding plan. They reached agreement with free-agent closer Mike
Jackson on a three-year, $12 million contract and scheduled a news
conference to announce the signing. The news conference and the
deal were canceled, though, when a physical revealed possible
problems with Jackson's right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies jumped in and signed Jackson to a similar deal,
including option years. HOT STOVE EMBERS
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, reports or the ever-churning rumor mill:
</P>
<P>
   _Despite losing his closer's job to Armando Benitez, John Franco
decided not to ask the Mets to trade him. Franco, a 39-year-old
lefty, has 416 saves, 62 fewer than Lee Smith's career record. But
he said he'd rather stay with the Mets in a setup role. ``I could
go somewhere else and maybe get the saves record, but winning is
more important,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _In perhaps the most shocking news so far this off-season, the
small-market, low-payroll Pirates decided to make a run at Ken
Griffey Jr. The Pirates are not on Griffey's list of approved
teams, though (as a 10-5 player he has veto rights), so talks never
got past the preliminary stage. The Reds are still in pursuit of
Griffey and talked to the Mariners early last week. However, the
Mariners insist on Pokey Reese being in any package, and the Reds
don't want to give him up.
</P>
<P>
   _Manny Ramirez might remain with the Indians beyond this season
after all. He switched agents to Jeff Moorad, who rekindled talks
about a contract extension beyond next season. Moorad, the sixth
agent of Ramirez's career, brokered the deal between the Dodgers
and Blue Jays for two of his clients, Shawn Green and Raul Mondesi,
and negotiated Green's contract with LA.
</P>
<P>
   _The Dodgers need to cut payroll after signing Green to a
six-year, $84 million contract and are talking to the Rockies about
a trade of Eric Young ($4.5 million the next two seasons) and
Ismael Valdes (due at least $4 million in arbitration) for young
right-handers Manny Aybar or Jose Jimenez and other players.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
