<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
COWBOYS DEFENDERS WON'T POINT FINGERS (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ As bad as the mood was at the Dallas Cowboys'
Valley Ranch training complex Monday, things could have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-6 loss to the Patriots on Sunday was the fourth game this
season that Cowboys' defense has held a team to one touchdown. For
the fourth time, the Cowboys lost the game because of an inept
offense.
</P>
<P>
   The environment was ripe for someone on defense to impersonate
Jessie Armstead, the Giants linebacker who created controversy
recently for criticizing his team's offense.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys linebacker Randall Godfrey acknowledges there is some
frustration because the Cowboys are in the thick of a playoff race
and every game is important, but he said nobody is pointing
fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play as a team,'' Godfrey said. ``We know the offense is
going to pick it up. And we got to do it in a hurry. But we really
do play as a team. No one will point fingers. We got too many
valuable players on offense. We know we can get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety George Teague agreed, saying ``we are staying away from
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are frustrated themselves, they are not happy,'' Teague
said. ``We are all trying to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit for the Cowboys' unity goes to Cowboys coach Chan Gailey,
who has talked about winning and losing as team from the start of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about being a team every week,'' Gailey said. ``It's
never going to be a situation where everyone is pulling an equal
load on any team. So, you always talking about being a team. These
guys have pride and want to do well in their area. They want to
win. But you make sure you emphasize the team aspect at all times.
CORYATT BACK IN FOLD
</P>
<P>
   So, linebacker Quentin Coryatt didn't retire after all.
</P>
<P>
   Coryatt, 29, who walked away from football before the season
opener because of injury concerns, has regained his health and is
back with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   His agent, Steve Zucker, said Coryatt and the Cowboys have
agreed to terms on the same three-year deal he signed as a free
agent during the off-season. He will get a prorated portion of his
original signing bonus _ roughly $300,000 _ and $23,529 per game
for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys released guard Chris Brymer to make room for
Coryatt. They are expected to sign Brymer to the practice squad if
he clears waivers.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker said Coryatt was frustrated by a chronic Achilles' tendon
injury that sidelined him for the bulk of training camp and didn't
want to play if he couldn't help the team. Coryatt, who was
originally drafted by the Colts after a stellar career at Texas
A&AMP;M, has spent the past three months getting treatment for the
injury and feels fit to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me back in September, `As soon as I get 100 percent, I
want to play,' '' Zucker said. ``We've kept in touch with the
Cowboys all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Darren Hambrick has played well in Coryatt's place at
strong-side linebacker and will likely keep the starting job, the
Cowboys welcome Coryatt's return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a plus for us,'' Godfrey said. ``He's a proven veteran in
the league. He gives us a lot of depth at linebacker. He can help
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning this season also benefits Coryatt, who hasn't played
in a game since 1997. Considering that his contract voids at the
end of the season, returning gives him a chance to use additional
playing time as a negotiating point when he becomes a free agent,
although Zucker said Coryatt only wants to play for the Cowboys.
INJURY UPDATES
</P>
<P>
   _Gailey said receiver Ernie Mills, who strained his left
quadriceps during pregame warmups Sunday, is a long shot to play
Sunday against the Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   _Gailey said center Mark Stepnoski (strained calf) could return
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _Guard Larry Allen, who has missed the past three games with a
sprained knee, will be sidelined another week, team officials said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
