<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1430 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     12-07 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' DINK-AND-STINK OFFENSE MUST GO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ It's time to be straight up about this: Dallas
Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman has developed a serious dinking
problem.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion is as plain as the scars on his chin: The Cowboys
simply cannot dink and drive.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman's best game-day execution Sunday night, in fact, actually
came ``after'' the Cowboys' abysmal 13-6 loss to the Patriots. No
excuses, he bravely told the assembled media.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent. None granted.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Dink King had thrown a pass long enough for a first
down.
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds like we're hip-shooting anything that moves today,
then you're reading this right. Aikman, as usual, is dead on the
money, but for once his completion went for more than 2 yards.
</P>
<P>
   There are no alibis left for this sorry excuse of an offense.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries? Other teams have key injuries and manage to score
points. Not the Cowboys. Four of their six losses have come when
the defense has allowed only 13 points. Pitiful.
</P>
<P>
   How is it that an offense with future Hall of Famers Aikman and
Emmitt Smith, with what is generally conceded to be the best
offensive line in the league, with a defense-stretching receiver
like Rocket Ismail, cannot score points?
</P>
<P>
   For answers, we go straight to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Chan Gailey, come on down.
</P>
<P>
   Coach, your offense dinks and stinks.
</P>
<P>
   You've taken arguably the best quarterback in the league, a
three-time Super Bowl winner, and turned him into the Dempster
Dumpster.
</P>
<P>
   Your star running back is having a great season _ unless it's
third- or fourth-and-one, when it matters most.
</P>
<P>
   Your team has rung up more penalties than the San Jose Sharks,
the NHL's resident cheap-shot artists.
</P>
<P>
   You have one of the best game-breaking receivers in the NFL at
your disposal, but he rarely goes deep, despite that defenses are
lining up in eight-man fronts to stop the run.
</P>
<P>
   It's way past time to make some changes.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few suggestions, but feel free to improvise on your
own as well:
</P>
<P>
   ``_ Do not make tight end David LaFleur the primary target in
critical first-down situations.'' He has consistently let you down
with dropped passes. It's time to go back to Eric Bjornson, or even
Mike Lucky, at least on most passing downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``_ Remove all dump-off options on third-down plays.'' Send
every receiver on routes beyond the first-down marker, forcing
Aikman to actually throw down field. And don't keep telling us he's
making good decisions. Good decisions lead to first downs and
victories, not punts and losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``_ Fire that sweetheart Richie Cunningham immediately.'' And
don't tell us there are no better kickers out there. He has lost
your confidence, the team's confidence and his own confidence.
Every kick he misses saps vital energy from the offense. You don't
have the luxury of being the patient Mr. Nice Guy any longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``_ Go ahead and (sigh) put Deion into some of the offensive
packages.'' He has bad hands and will almost certainly get hurt
again, but that won't make him unique among your receivers.
Defenses will still have to respect his speed and perhaps that will
free up Ismail more often.
</P>
<P>
   ``_ Put in some plays that start with Emmitt Smith closer to the
line of scrimmage, especially on third and fourth downs when the
defenses are already keying on him anyway.'' Get rid of those slow
developing plays that give defenders ample time to line up on
Emmitt before he can gouge out a yard. Don't be afraid to put a
fullback in the backfield with him, giving defenses another option
to think about.
</P>
<P>
   ``_ Back off on the intensity of the entry onto the field part
of the game plan.'' Ernie Mills, who pulled a quadriceps muscle,
was the second player injured this season by just walking down the
tunnel onto the Texas Stadium turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``_ Stop protecting players who are consistently screwing up,
even if it's a star like Aikman or Smith or a young offensive
lineman.'' The screw-ups are embarrassing your team. Don't be
afraid to return the favor.
</P>
<P>
   The best starting point for salvaging this season is still with
Aikman. How many times have we heard Jerry Jones say that, as long
as Troy's on his feet the Cowboys are a Super Bowl contender?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the King of Dink was still standing Sunday night and the
Cowboys weren't even toilet bowl contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decisions (Aikman) made were based on the things HE
sees,'' Gailey stressed Monday at Valley Ranch. ``It's easy to put
on the film the day after and say, `Boy, it would have been nice to
try and throw the ball here or throw the ball there.' That's easy.
That happens in every film room every Monday around the NFL. But
for the most part, Troy makes good decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that we talk about and make a big deal about is
not turning the ball over. We are playing well on defense, and if
we don't turn it over on our end, you can play the field position
game and have a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I get it now. Forget the scoreboard, the Cowboys won the
turnover game 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   I guess we're all supposed to dink to that. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 0141EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
