<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUN-ORALROBERTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE BEATS ORAL ROBERTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It wasn't magic and it wasn't inspiration. More
like perspiration.
</P>
<P>
   The Cal State Northridge men's basketball team, which put forth
what Matadors coaches said was an extraordinary effort in an
overtime loss two days earlier, beat Oral Roberts 72-59 Monday
night in front of 793 at Matador Gym.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN (3-2) washed away memories of Saturday's loss at Cal Poly
San Luis Obispo with a scintillating first half against the Golden
Eagles, who dropped to 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   But Bobby Braswell, the Matadors' head coach, said he didn't
forget the players' effort against Cal Poly, and he told them
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `I'll always tell you the truth,''' Braswell said.
``You guys played well (against Cal Poly). I was very, very pleased
with their effort, and if they showed the same kind of effort in
this game we would get a win.''
</P>
<P>
   That formula _ hard work _ paid off against Oral Roberts,
especially among the role players. Redshirt freshman center Dan
Read, who starts but plays fewer minutes than Brian Heinle, had six
points in 11 minutes and forward Whitney White had a season-high 10
points and five rebounds in only eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   White, particularly, gave CSUN a boost in the first half when
the Matadors built a significant lead. He had eight of the team's
10 points in a five-minute stretch in which a 28-18 CSUN lead
became 38-26.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches always pressure us in practice to play our
roles,'' White said. ``They call me the `Energizer Bunny,' so I
just try to come in the game with energy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors were sizzling from the floor in taking a 41-27
first-half lead, shooting 66 percent (18 of 27). They also held the
Golden Eagles to eight rebounds in the game's first 20 minutes;
Oral Roberts' tallest starter is 6-foot-6 forward Derrick Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Oral Roberts hung in during the first eight minutes despite not
having starting point guard Eric Perry, who sat out his third
consecutive game with back spasms. But CSUN began pulling away at
the 10-minute mark, and White's basket gave the Matadors their
first double-digit lead _ 28-18.
</P>
<P>
   White, a 6-5 junior from Chicago who only had two points in five
minutes Saturday at Cal Poly, had 10 in only six first-half minutes
Monday. He made 5 of 8 shots in the half and had three offensive
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the closest group of guys I've been around,'' White
said. ``We just stayed together (after losing to Cal Poly). That
was a letdown, but we did what we had to do tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The CSUN players did what starting forward Hewitt Rolle called
``the little things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing out, diving on the floor,'' said Rolle, who had 11
points and 11 rebounds. ``... We were upset by the loss the other
night. That was a team we shouldn't have lost to.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN, which sat on a big lead through the first 14 minutes of
the second half, had its lead reduced to nine _ 58-49 _ when Oral
Roberts' Reggie Tate made a baseline 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   But the Matadors responded with an 8-0 run, which was
highlighted by two three-point plays by Jeff Parris, who led CSUN
with 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors were consistent up and down the lineup; eight
players had at least six points and five had at least four
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are doing everything we've asked them to,''
Braswell said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 0142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
