<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1443 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN     12-07 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGACE(Y) OF PERSEVERANCE   TRAILS EX-KINGS GOALIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For Manny Legace, it could be home for the
holidays or Manitoba by morning. Either way, he is a great story of
perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   You might remember him as the goalie who stepped in for the Los
Angeles Kings last year when Stephane Fiset and Jamie Storr went
down with injuries just seven minutes apart in the fourth game of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of taking advantage of a great opportunity, Legace
stepped into a hockey black hole, going 2-9-2 and 0-6 at home. He
quietly left town last summer and signed with Detroit with little
hope of ever playing regularly again.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, the Red Wings' top goalie Chris Osgood is out at
least two more weeks with a hairline fracture in his right forearm.
Veteran backup Ken Wregget is just 5-6 and not playing well for
perhaps the league's best team.
</P>
<P>
   ``My head is still spinning,'' Legace said earlier this week
after his recall by Detroit. ``I haven't had time to settle down in
one spot yet. I've been on the road the whole year. The whole year
I've been in a hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   Legace's legacy is not just his days in L.A. nor his new role
with Detroit, although it would be fitting to face his former team
Friday when the Kings play the Red Wings at Joe Louis Arena.
</P>
<P>
   There is so much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   After the Kings cut Legace, he signed with Red Wings. He had a
great training camp, but with Wregget around, Legace was going to
get sent down. To do so he had to clear waivers and was claimed by
Vancouver. The Canucks had him on their opening-night roster, but
two weeks later he was back walking the waiver wire.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings reclaimed him and sent him to Manitoba of the
International Hockey League. He was awful at first, then suffered a
badly bruised right knee. But with Osgood out and Wregget
struggling with his confidence, Legace might get a little playing
time.
</P>
<P>
   When he was with the Kings last year, Legace got more action
than he could handle. He was the starting goalie in Long Beach when
Storr and Fiset went down. Over the next 16 games, he made 14
starts. The Kings won just twice during that stretch and never were
heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   Life is better now but still uncertain. Osgood could return
right before Christmas, meaning Legace could be back in the minors
for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wife's not happy,'' said Legace, who also has two small
children. ``I would like to get them (from Winnipeg) as soon as
possible. I haven't seen the kids in forever. If you only spend a
couple days, they've going to forget who their father was. They are
going to think the mailman was their father.''
</P>
<P>
   Fit to be tied: Friday night's 1-1 tie with the Mighty Ducks
wasn't the best way to spark a rivalry. And when the Kings blew a
3-1 lead in the final three minutes of regulation and had to settle
for a 3-3 tie with Tampa Bay, their magical season seemed to have
hit a snag.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion Atlanta should help on Wednesday. A bigger question is
whether the new four-on-four overtime period really has had any
impact.
</P>
<P>
   Statistically yes. There have been 44 percent of ties broken in
OT this year, compared to 23 percent last season when both sides
play five-on-five.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game was the most-exciting overtime this season. The
Kings outshot the Lightning 5-0 and had several great scoring
chances with the man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But against the Ducks, the Kings waddled. The action was so
slow, there never was a question the game would end in a tie.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was it bad for fans who sold out the Pond, it was awful
for conference play. The West is tighter than ever this season. But
teams, who know they will get a point regardless of the final
outcome, are not prepared to lose a point by playing recklessly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The energy level in overtime is better than ever,'' King coach
Andy Murray said. ``It's unfortunate the conference games haven't
been more exciting, but you have to understand what is at stake. A
point here or there could decide this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Daigle no longer dangling: Alexandre Daigle was the first player
chosen in the 1993 draft by Ottawa and twice scored more than 20
goals in the NHL. He was considered one of the league's brightest
prospects except for one thing. Or two. Or three.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Daigle (pronounced Dayg) ever worked at was
honing his bad attitude. He never took the game seriously and
confounded his coaches, who called him lazy.
</P>
<P>
   After five years in Ottawa, the Senators had enough. Then it was
on to Philadelphia, where Flyers coach Roger Neilson said Daigle
``loves everything about hockey except playing the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Daigle couldn't even stick with lowly Tampa Bay, where he played
before the New York Rangers made him a reclamation project this
season
</P>
<P>
   Now 24, Daigle seems to have found his way on the league's most
underachieving team. He continued to play well Saturday, scoring
the tying goal in a 1-1 game against Buffalo. In six games since
Daigle was recalled from Hartford, he has three goals and three
assists.
</P>
<P>
   He also has been the only bright light on a dismal team that has
gotten only one goal in the past 17 games from high-priced free
agent Theo Fleury. The Rangers have the league's highest payroll
and worst power play.
</P>
<P>
   They also have been playing without Brian Leetch (fractured
forearm), Valeri Kamensky (bruised forearm) and Petr Nedved (groin
pull) because of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But coach John Muckler isn't ready to call Daigle a savior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very pleased,'' Muckler said. ``But he has to understand
that he has to continue to do this every night. He has to be held
on a short leash and he has to know that. He has to know that this
is his last opportunity to play in the National Hockey League.
Nobody questions his talent. They've questioned other things, but
they don't question his talent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
