<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-HEAT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS FALL TO HEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Serious Los Angeles Clippers scholars figured out
this team's patterns a long time ago. Pattern one: down and out.
Pattern two: fade.
</P>
<P>
   But through a bit more than the first month of this season,
another pattern emerged: the Clippers were 1-10 against teams from
the Western Conference, but had a relative feast against the East
(3-2).
</P>
<P>
   This incongruity was settled Monday by the Miami Heat, who
defeated the Clippers 99-91 in front of 10,194 at Staples Center,
even though the pattern seemed legit for most of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   However, the now-hackneyed, doomsday script was at full strength
in the second half, permitting the Clippers to end their homestand
at an imperfect 0-5. They will begin a three-game road swing
Wednesday at Atlanta with six consecutive defeats and an overall
mark of 4-13.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Riley's Heat (13-4) maintained the best record among
Eastern Conference heavies and ended a two-game road losing streak.
Miami has won five of six games without point guard Tim Hardaway
(jammed right knee).
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway's understudy, Anthony Carter, provided a career-high,
20-point bonanza for Miami, which also received a 25-point,
11-rebound, eight-block effort from All-Star center Alonzo Mourning
and 20 points from Jamal Mashburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told our guys before the game, during the game and during
the timeouts, `Do not challenge Alonzo,' '' Clippers coach Chris
Ford said. ``You know he's going to come ... find the open man.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Clippers did just that, racking up 22 assists, their
most in one game this season.
</P>
<P>
   The lead pitch man was triple-double threat Derek Anderson, who
responded with his shift to point guard by posting 16 points, 10
rebounds and 12 assists for the Clippers. It was Los Angeles' first
triple-double since Mark Jackson did it in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays hard, he plays well wherever I put him,'' Ford said
of Anderson, whose duties included the futile chasing of the
smaller Carter when the Miami guard spent a great deal of the
second half curling around screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little tired,'' Anderson admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Odom, who added 20 points and seven rebounds, still can't
find much joy in losing, but was encouraged by the improvement his
team made since last Saturday's disaster against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I can go home and sleep after this one,'' Odom said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers also received solid efforts from Maurice Taylor (17
points, 9 rebounds, 8 turnovers) and Brian Skinner (15 points, 6
rebounds), but it wasn't enough to offset Mourning inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the league's toughest players,'' Odom said. ``He's
a monster; he's relentless.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning's 13 points kept the Heat at room temperature through
the first quarter, which ended with the Clippers leading 31-25.
Clarence Weatherspoon (8 points) starred for Miami's bench, which
helped the Heat pull ahead 46-44 at intermission. Miami led 72-66
after three and by as many as 14 in the fourth period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a lot of good things out there,'' said Ford, whose team
outrebounded the Heat 47-41, but was loose enough on defense for
Miami to shoot 51 percent for the game. ``We just have to get some
court awareness; some court savvy.''
</P>
<P>
   And, with three road games against Eastern Conference foes, they
need to resume that pattern.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
