<HEADER>
A1465 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-TRUMP-CALIFORNIA-SFCH     12-07 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: TRUMP COUNTING ON HIS FAME, WEALTH IN POSSIBLE REFORM 
 PARTY RUN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS _ Three months before the March 7 primary, at a
time when most of the presidential field is trooping in and out of
California to scoop up campaign contributions, billionaire Donald
Trump may be the only candidate to actually earn money on a
campaign trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Donald is scheduled to speak Tuesday before a sold-out crowd
of 21,000 at Arrowhead Pond stadium in Anaheim, Calif., as part of
motivational guru Anthony Robbins' ``Results 2000'' seminar _ one
of 10 such speeches for which he'll rake in $100,000 per talk,
sources confirm.
</P>
<P>
   He's even collecting outside contributions _ about $10,000 so
far _ because ``being a smart entrepreneur, he'll never leave
honest money on the table,'' said Trump political consultant Roger
Stone.
</P>
<P>
   During a 20-minute press conference beside the pool on the roof
of the L'Ermitage Hotel, the developer, author and star of TV
commercials assailed the World Trade Organization, said he would
appoint himself U.S. trade representative, slammed Republican
front-runner George W. Bush's tax plan as ``timid'' and said his
gut tells him he could be elected president.
</P>
<P>
   With a ``Trump 2000'' poster beside him, he dismissed his chief
competition for the Reform Party nomination, Pat Buchanan, as a guy
without a chance and dismissed all the other rich guys _ Steve
Forbes, are you listening? _ who've unsuccessfully tried to run for
high office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not them,'' he said simply.
</P>
<P>
   Trump's first trip as a possible presidential candidate to the
nation's most populous state underscored just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we can get the Reform Party nomination,'' he told
reporters. He said he'll decide by late February whether to run to
become the most powerful leader in the free world ``based on
whether or not the election can be won. ... In a three-person race,
we need 33 to 34 percent. So it's not a very large percentage.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump's Reform Party explorations come in a year when such
celebrities as former wrestler Jesse Ventura and actor Warren
Beatty also have flirted with a top run.
</P>
<P>
   But at the exclusive L'Ermitage, where he held court, Trump's
appearance trumped the glitz of Beatty and the gutsiness of
Ventura, forging an almost surreal marriage between marketing
madness and politics.
</P>
<P>
   The developer's aides, razor sharp in black suits and
sunglasses, handed out samples of Trump 2000 hand sanitizer _ a
wink to the candidate's reluctance to shake hands _ and glossy
pamphlets to sell his new book, titled, ``Donald J. Trump for
President?''
</P>
<P>
   Melania Knauss, Trump's lady du jour, stood by demurely, the
very picture of first lady serenity _ with tanned, bare,
up-to-there miniskirted legs and 5-inch spike heels.
</P>
<P>
   Political and entertainment reporters stepped over each other to
catch the action as, across the pool from Trump, Jodie Foster was
doing her own sales job _ interviews for the premiere of the movie
``Anna and the King.'' As if that weren't enough, a bejeweled
elephant in brocade prowled the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Trump's potential appeal to the common voter in the
midst of all this uncommon political splendor, campaign adviser
Stone captured the context.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is the central question when it comes to Trump's
candidacy: Is pop culture more influential in this country than the
old institutions? In the old days, a developer from Queens could
not get elected president, because the institutions in this country
would not allow it. We kind of think in the age of mass
communications, the institutions are losing their power and the
people are making their own decisions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking around at the group of political writers, Stone warned,
``You can laugh at the ... `Entertainment Tonights' and the `Hard
Copies' if you want ... but millions of people are watching those
things, and forming opinions based on what they see.''
</P>
<P>
   At a tony reception, Trump got high marks from 90 Reform Party
leaders from throughout the West who crammed in and grabbed ``Trump
2000'' buttons. But he took some aggressive questions on trade and
campaign finance reform, even as he made his sales pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the purpose in getting the nomination if you can't
win?'' he said. ``If I decide to run, I'd be willing to spend $100
million of my own money. Pat (Buchanan) is not going to do that. He
doesn't have the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump then took his case to ``The Tonight Show with Jay Leno.''
</P>
<P>
   There, introduced as ``the next President of the United
States,'' the billionaire strode onstage to cheers and the sounds
of ``Hail to the Chief,'' his hands raised in victory signs.
</P>
<P>
   Leno, who regularly uses Trump as monologue material, let fly.
``How 'bout a first lady. Would you hold a massive search?'' Leno
asked. ``If you got married in the White House and got divorced,
would she get, like, west of the Mississippi?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to get a prenup, to save the country,'' Trump
deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in Trump's dressing room, Leno said the billionaire has
been a good sport _ and makes better material than most
presidential candidates. (``The toughest is McCain,'' he lamented.
``You can't go there.'')
</P>
<P>
   And the current long presidential campaign _ one that has melded
show biz and politics in a singular way _ may help vet the
candidates better than anything else, Leno said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People understand you have to have a thick skin to do this.
... That's why the American process takes 18 months _ it's a
setup,'' Leno said, slapping Trump on the back. ``After (he's) been
through all of the nonsense ... you won't catch him in a bra and
panties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
