<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1563 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-GRIZZLIES     12-07 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-GRIZZLIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
It ain't over till it's over.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nowhere has that butchered bit of wisdom ever been more true
than in Monday night's game between the Grizzlies and Rockets at
Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   Given the teams involved, this game was destined to come down to
the wire. Why? Because on one hand you had the Grizzlies, who had
seemingly forgotten how to win a game. And on the other you had the
Rockets, a team that seemed intent on inventing ways to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Something had to give, and it turned out to be the Grizzlies,
who did everything but gift-wrap a 102-99 victory for the Rockets,
their third straight win and fourth in their last five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all, people might say, `Oh, the (Rockets) are going to
win that game,' or whatever,'' said Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich
of playing a Vancouver team that is now 3-14. ``But if you lose
this game, it really sets you back.''
</P>
<P>
   And with a quick three-game East Coast trip coming up this week,
the Rockets desperately wanted the win Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But not as desperately as the Grizzlies, who entered the game
with 10 straight losses overall and 29 straight on the road over
the past couple of seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Given their chances, however, the Grizzlies couldn't capitalize
after a fourth-quarter comeback erased a nine-point deficit. They
missed three key free throws in the final 6.2 seconds, and since
these are the Grizzlies, the only one they made in that span was
the one Othella Harrington was trying to miss.
</P>
<P>
   With Vancouver down by two points, Harrington was fouled inside,
but he missed the first of his two free throws. With 6.2 seconds
left, he tried to miss the second, hoping the Grizzlies could get
the rebound and tip it in. But the ball smacked off the backboard
and plopped straight into the basket, leaving them down 100-99 and
out of timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a chance to win the game, and I blew it,'' said
Harrington, who finished with 18 points and seven rebounds but made
just six of his 11 free-throw attempts. ``That was tough. I
couldn't believe it when it came out.''
</P>
<P>
   That, more than anything else, has typified Vancouver's season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hung in there, and the objective is to win,'' said Charles
Barkley, who finished with game highs in scoring (25 points) and
rebounds (11). ``We've played well the last two weeks, and we lost
some games we should have won. We could have a six- or seven-game
win streak (now).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important road trip coming up, and we'll know
where we're at when we come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing, because they appeared to be lost at times Monday
night. And lost could have described Shandon Anderson, who had
scored 53 points in his last two games. He scored just one point
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets found Carlos Rogers, who missed the previous
game against Phoenix with stomach flu. Rogers scored 18 points,
hitting eight of his 11 shots, and picked off seven rebounds in 24
minutes off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed somebody else to step up, and today it was Carlos,''
Tomjanovich said. ``That was big, since he had been sick. That's 18
points where we don't have to call a play for him. He was just
using the system and hustling.''
</P>
<P>
   Also involved in the system was Walt Williams, who hit a huge
3-pointer to put the Rockets up 100-96 with 59.9 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   But that lead wouldn't hold up.
</P>
<P>
   Shareef Abdur-Rahim, who led Vancouver with 24 points in 28
foul-plagued minutes, hit a short hook shot in the lane to pull the
Grizzlies within 100-98 with 41.4 seconds to play. Williams, who
finished with 14 points, rimmed out a 3-point attempt from the top
of the arc, but Barkley grabbed the rebound to maintain possession
for the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   They wouldn't keep the ball long.
</P>
<P>
   After a timeout, Williams was unable to get the ball inbounds in
the allotted five seconds, giving the Grizzlies the ball and a
chance to tie the game in the final 17.6 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good five-second call by the refs,'' Tomjanovich
said. ``You always think it's too fast when it (the call) is
against you. The guys just didn't get open. We had timeouts, but we
didn't call time out.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington then did his free-throw routine, leaving the
Grizzlies pretty much out of gas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
