<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1564 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-VIKINGS-BUCS-HNS &LR;      12-07 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-BUCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
TAMPA, Fla. _ No matter how long he plays in the NFL, Tampa Bay
rookie quarterback Shaun King will never forget the first start of
his career.
<TEXT>
<P>
   King, a native of St. Petersburg, made his starting debut
against the Minnesota Vikings in front of family, friends, a
Raymond James Stadium-record crowd of 65,741 and a Monday Night
Football audience.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the intense pressure of a showdown for a share of first
place in the NFC Central, King played with the poise of a veteran,
throwing two touchdown passes in the Buccaneers' 24-17 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaun played a nice, smooth, efficient game,'' Bucs coach Tony
Dungy said. ``I think we'll keep him starting next week. The team
rallied around him, and he was more calm than I was.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs didn't have the victory secured until their outstanding
defense stopped the Vikings' explosive offense on the last series
of the game. When Jeff George's fourth-and-19 pass with 23 seconds
left was incomplete, the Buccaneers were finally able to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay increased its winning streak to five games and
elevated its record to 8-4, remaining in a first-place tie with the
Detroit Lions, who visit the Buccaneers on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every game in the NFC Central is just as tough
and hard-fought as this one,'' Dungy said. ``We knew we had
Minnesota and Detroit back-to-back. So far, we've done what we set
out to do when our streak started, and now we're playing the Lions
for first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's five-game winning streak ended, and the Vikings
dropped to 7-5, one game behind the division leaders.
</P>
<P>
   King, a second-round pick from Tulane, replaced Trent Dilfer,
who is out for the season with a broken collarbone. He completed 11
of 19 passes for 94 yards and was intercepted once. The Bucs
generated only 190 yards compared to Minnesota's 339.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got a defense like ours, it wasn't necessary for
me to make a lot of great plays,'' King said. ``I didn't want to do
anything stupid. I wasn't nervous. I tried to stay calm. I really
enjoyed this one.''
</P>
<P>
   King outdueled George, who had been unbeatable since being
elevated to starting status six games ago. George's record fell to
5-1 as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota had a chance to tie the score and force overtime on
its last series, but Tampa Bay's defense won that battle.
</P>
<P>
   With 3:24 remaining, the Vikings got the ball at their 30, and
they were on the move. On a fourth-and-one, George threw an
incompletion from the Tampa Bay 44, but a false-start penalty gave
them a reprieve. On fourth-and-six, he completed a 15-yard pass to
Jake Reed.
</P>
<P>
   After two incompletions and another false-start penalty, George
threw to Leroy Hoard, who did a magnificent job of running for a
first down at the 25. After George spiked the ball, the Vikings had
another false-start penalty. Then, cornerback Ronde Barber blitzed
and had a clear path to George for a 10-yard sack.
</P>
<P>
   On third-and-25 from the Bucs' 40, George threw a short pass to
running back Robert Smith, who couldn't get out of bounds after a
six-yard gain, forcing Minnesota to use its last timeout. On
fourth-and-19 from the 34 with 23 seconds left, George's pass
intended for Matthew Hatchette was off target and broken up by
cornerback Donnie Abraham, and the celebration began.
</P>
<P>
   In a sloppy first half, there were six turnovers, three by each
team. The first one came on Minnesota's first series, and it
resulted in Tampa Bay's first touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   On the third play of the game, George threw to receiver Cris
Carter on the right side, but his pass was intercepted by Abraham,
who was blitzing off the slot receiver. Abraham caught the ball in
full stride and had an open field on his way to a 55-yard
touchdown. Rookie kicker Martin Gramatica kicked the extra point
for a fast 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay increased the lead on its next series. After Gary
Anderson missed a 46-yard field-goal attempt for Minnesota, the
Buccaneers drove to the Vikings' two-yard line and settled for
Gramatica's 20-yard field goal and a 10-0 lead early in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings had a chance to score on their next series, but
Abraham intercepted George again. The Bucs gave it right back,
however, when King was sacked by end Chris Doleman. King fumbled,
and tackle John Randle recovered at the Tampa Bay 22. The Vikings
used five plays to cover 22 yards. Hoard scored the touchdown on a
one-yard run, and Anderson made it 10-7 with the extra point.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs committed another turnover when King was intercepted by
safety Robert Griffith. The Vikings couldn't do anything with it,
but when Mitch Berger's punt was fumbled by Karl Williams at the
Tampa Bay 10 with 56 seconds left in the first half, Minnesota took
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   On third-and-goal from the one, George threw a quick touchdown
pass to Carter, his 11th since George replaced Randall Cunningham
6{ games ago for a 14-10 Minnesota lead at halftime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
