<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1573 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-DEBATE-HNS &LR;      12-07 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEBATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP HOPEFULS SPAR _ WITH VERY SOFT GLOVES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Republican presidential contenders sparred gently
Monday night even as stragglers in the contest sought to draw
contrasts with front-runner George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Although the format offered candidates an opportunity to
question one another, it was a surprisingly bloodless affair. There
were as many moments of bonhomie as biting thrust and parry.
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing to a competitive edge in the hourlong session
was the effort of Sen. John McCain of Arizona to appear more well
informed than Bush on the esoteric historical importance of Dean
Acheson, a Democratic secretary of state a half-century ago, and
the role of foreign oil.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain also parted company on the future of the
economy, with the Texas governor defending the soundness of his
tax-cut proposal because, ``I refuse to accept that the surpluses
are going to decline.'' Later in the debate, McCain took pains to
assert: ``I do not envision surpluses forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and the four of his challengers appeared on stage at the
Orpheum Theatre, a 70-year-old vaudeville and movie palace near
Phoenix's modern civic center. McCain participated by satellite
hook-up from Boston after a day of campaigning in the first-primary
state of New Hampshire, where some polls show the senator has
pulled even with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush retains a major polling lead nationally, but that position
could be eroded by a poor showing in the early contests. Other
candidates in the debate were magazine publisher Steve Forbes, Sen.
Orrin Hatch of Utah, conservative activist Gary Bauer and former
Reagan administration diplomat Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, lagging near the back of the pack in polling, took the
most direct shot of the night at Bush, repeating his doubts about
whether the Texan is experienced enough to take on the nation's
highest office.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've been a great governor,'' Hatch said, ``but you need
more experience before you become president.'' Hatch, drawing
laughter from the audience, said he was considering Bush as a
vice-presidential running mate, and predicting that after two terms
at the Utahan's side, Hatch said Bush would ``make a heck of a
president.''
</P>
<P>
   In questioning from CNN correspondents and other candidates,
Bush defended his education plan and his approach to China against
suggestions that they were similar to those of President Clinton _
and, by extension, of Vice President Al Gore, front-runner for the
Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   When a CNN reporter questioned how Bush's proposed reliance on
federal mandates in schooling was different from Clinton's, the
governor shot back: ``It's not even close.'' He cited his advocacy
of school vouchers, to allow parents greater choice in schools for
their children, and said: ``My plan says less power in Washington,
not more.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first round of candidate-to-candidate questions, Bauer
challenged Bush on the governor's support for China to become a
member of the World Trade Organization, which he said was an
embrace of the Clinton policy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he rejected the Clinton approach to China as a
``strategic partner'' of the United States and would redefine it as
``one of competitors.'' But he strongly defended his call for more,
not less, commercial dealings with the Asian giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in our best interest to sell to China,'' Bush said,
saying even conservative critics such as Bauer might ``be amazed at
how soon democracy will come. ... But if we turn our back on China
things would get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   In that answer and most others, Bush relied on long-tested
snippets from his stock campaign speech.
</P>
<P>
   In a debate last week, Bush pointed to a book about Acheson as
something he was currently reading, so a CNN reporter asked him
what lessons he had drawn from the volume.
</P>
<P>
   With only passing reference to the book, Bush launched into the
foreign policy segment of his stump speech, saying, ``The United
States must not retreat within our own borders'' and must promote
peace through strategic alliances, free trade and a strong
military.
</P>
<P>
   During his next response, McCain, unbidden, said: ``Let me talk
about Dean Acheson a second,'' pointing out that the diplomat and
President Truman decided to move U.S. forces to Korea ``without a
poll.'' McCain contrasted that with the ``feckless, photo-op
foreign policy'' of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Forbes tried to pin Bush down on how to lower crude oil
prices and asked him to name a favored selling price.
</P>
<P>
   After Bush stressed the need for increased domestic oil and
natural gas production, McCain, in a later, unrelated answer on
faith-based institutions, did a short riff on the importance of
energy supplies in Azerbaijan and the need to ensure that Russia
does not exert undue influence in the Caspian region.
</P>
<P>
   Although the format allowed candidates to question each other
directly, only one query in each of three rounds could be directed
to any one candidate, so any thought of directly ganging up on
front-runner Bush had to be laid aside. Bush drew the first
question in two of the three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   A new Newsweek poll among New Hampshire Republicans found Bush
and McCain in a statistical dead heat, with Bush favored by 38
percent and McCain by 33 percent. The margin of error was plus or
minus 7 percentage points. A Boston Herald poll, of New Hampshire
Republicans, published Sunday, found an even closer race, with Bush
leading McCain 34 percent to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The session in the Arizona capital came four days after a New
Hampshire forum, the first debate that Bush agreed to join. Next
Monday, the candidates meet in Des Moines, Iowa, for their third
pre-Christmas debate. Iowa, with its Jan. 24 caucuses, is site of
the first major primary-season event. McCain is not an active
participant in the Iowa caucuses, but will appear in debates there.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, during a town-hall meeting in Farmington, N.H.,
McCain said he would shut down the federal government if necessary
to restrain pork-barrel spending. Aware that shutting the
government in a fiscal fight with President Clinton cost
Republicans public support earlier in the decade, McCain aides
rushed to say that the senator was not looking for a disruptive
political fight with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain was explicit on the point when asked by a voter if he
would veto all spending bills and allow the government to close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure I would,'' he replied. ``If we don't change business as
usual in Washington, people will be deprived of their
representation.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain does not mention a shutdown in anti-pork barrel
television ads scheduled to begin airing this week in New Hampshire
and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will refuse to sign any pork barrel bill that crosses my
desk,'' McCain says in the ad, the text of which was released by
his campaign. ``And if Congress overrides my veto and tries to
force me to waste your money, I'll make sure you know who they are,
every single one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Farmington, McCain said he would ``make them famous'' by
naming names.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's debate was a make-up session for Bush, who skipped the
Arizona Republican Party's candidate forum last month.
</P>
<P>
   Although Arizona is McCain's home state _ and he was re-elected
last year with 70 percent of the vote _ Bush's popularity in the
state has made the local GOP presidential contest a competitive
one. Bush led in statewide polling earlier in the year, but a late
October sampling for KAET-TV by Arizona State University found
McCain leading Bush 39 percent to 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The polling raised questions about the pre-debate claim of Rep.
J.D. Hayworth, a local U.S. House member, that Arizona is ``McCain
country.'' The senator especially has been embarrassed by the
decision of Gov. Jane Hull to back Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Republicans hold a primary Feb. 22, one of the earliest
state tests for the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
