<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1580 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-TIME-CRAZE-KANSAS-KAN     12-07 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIME-CRAZE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA IS GOING TIME-CAPSULE CRAZY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES A. FUSSELL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a paradox for the ages: Time capsules, buried to help
future generations remember the past, are instead one of the most
forgotten items on earth.
</P>
<P>
   It's true, said Paul Hudson, co-founder of the International
Time Capsule Society at Atlanta's Oglethorpe University. Even
though about 10,000 time capsules have been buried worldwide this
century, we don't have a clue where most of them are. According to
Hudson's estimates, 9 out of every 10 time capsules buried are now
officially lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's human nature,'' said Hudson. ``We move on. There's a lot
of excitement when people bury (a capsule). But they tend to forget
them almost the day after they seal them up.''
</P>
<P>
   So are we just wasting our time with time capsules?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But it doesn't seem to be stopping us. As we roll toward
the start of a new millennium, time capsules _ containers filled
with items meant to give future generations a glimpse into life in
the past _ have never been hotter.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is going time-capsule crazy,'' said Hudson. ``With the
millennium coming, people sort of want to write themselves into
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Time capsules have never been easier to find. Scads of capsules
are offered on the Internet and in an increasing number of stores.
They can also be found on cereal boxes, in various museums and sold
through catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Jim Croce wished he could save time in a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he could. In a bottle, jug, vat, tube, safe, aluminum
cylinder or polymer storage pod. Manufacturers report surging sales
of containers, ranging from $9.99 to more than a thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Cities are making them. So are schools, scout troops, churches,
corporations, individuals and agencies of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Why the rush?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess what they're all looking for is an independent voice
to the future,'' Hudson said. ``We all want to know we made a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of schools in the Kansas City area will either open or
bury a time capsule in 2000. On Jan. 1, 2001, Kansas City officials
will open one 100-year-old time capsule and leave behind another. A
committee is working on what to put in that capsule.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate its legacy of world-class science, the U.S.
Department of Energy's Brookhaven National Laboratory in Upton,
N.Y., will bury two time capsules on its site. The specially
designed, flame-sealed glass capsules will contain documents,
photographs, scientific objects and other memorabilia. A monument
will be placed at the burial site.
</P>
<P>
   The Motorcycle Hall of Fame in Pickerington, Ohio, is also
getting in on the fun. It's collecting messages at $50 to $100 a
pop to send to future bikers.
</P>
<P>
   And in New York, a group of would-be preservationists is raising
money to create a flying time capsule named KEO that will orbit the
Earth. Participants are being asked to write messages of up to
6,000 characters and submit them through a Web site (www.keo.org).
Messages will be stored on special, glass-tempered CD-ROMs and sent
into space in a satellite that is supposed to fall to Earth in
about 50,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson has been watching the increasing interest in time
capsules with delight. A historian, he became enamored of them
after discovering the Rolls-Royce of all capsules, the ``Crypt of
Civilization,'' buried at Oglethorpe in 1940. The crypt is not set
to be opened until _ hold on to your time machine _ 8113.
</P>
<P>
   The swimming-pool sized crypt holds thousands of items _ from
dental floss and newsreels of Adolf Hitler to the works of
Shakespeare and more than 640,000 book pages on microfilm.
</P>
<P>
   It even has a specially sealed ampule of Budweiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``So whoever opens the crypt in 8113,'' Hudson said wryly,
``that Bud would be for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The crypt's creator, Thornwell Jacobs, chose that date based on
his calculations that in 1936, the year of his inspiration,
civilization was at a halfway point from the date when the Egyptian
calendar was established in 4241 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of preserving one's life and times for the future began
with the Egyptians. While the pyramids were designed as vessels to
the afterlife, they were also vessels to the future.
</P>
<P>
   The first modern time capsule was created in 1876 in
Philadelphia for the United States' centennial, said Will Jarvis, a
librarian at Washington State University who is working on a book
on time capsules.
</P>
<P>
   President Gerald Ford opened the so-called ``Century Safe'' in
1976 during the country's bicentennial. It contained a few
autographs and photos. Nothing particularly valuable.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``time capsule'' was first coined by George Edward
Pendary, the publicity director for Westinghouse at the 1939 New
York World's Fair, Jarvis said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, ``they're just all over the place,'' he said. ``This year's
new Cheerios are called Millennios. When you are done with the
cereal you're supposed to turn the box into a time capsule. Then
there's the Mars Candy Co. It has an M&AMP;M millennium time capsule
kit. Just about every museum catalog has a time capsule, and a lot
of kids' hobby catalogs have them.''
</P>
<P>
   There are even television specials about time capsules.
</P>
<P>
   The History Channel aired a special called the Times Capsule on
Monday night. Among other things, the special documented the
construction of a capsule made by the editors of The New York Times
Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The paper invited 48 designers, architects and engineers to
suggest items to include in the capsule, which is to be installed
later this year at the American Museum of Natural History in New
York. Suggestions included the complete works of Dr. Seuss and the
diary of an American teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Rosenthal, the magazine's editor, said the capsule also
will contain many newspaper articles. Using a technology called
HD-Rosetta, the magazine plans to etch data onto a nickel disc
using a charged particle beam. The 2-inch disc can hold more than
90,000 pages of 8-by-11-inch text pages.
</P>
<P>
   What should you put in your time capsule?
</P>
<P>
   A survey by Korbel Champagne Cellars, which has no small
interest in New Year's Eve, asked consumers what single item should
be included in a capsule bound for the year 3000. Top vote-getters
included a laptop computer, audio and videotapes, CDs of popular
songs and CD-ROMs.
</P>
<P>
   But therein lies a problem. Such technologically dependent
products may not work in the future. The data will degrade _ some
of it surprisingly quickly. Even at room temperature, magnetic
videotapes have an expected shelf life of only 20 years. CDs are
expected to last only 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   So what should you put in?
</P>
<P>
   Photos are good. So are letters. Newsprint tends to break down.
So does rubber or thin plastic.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of container?
</P>
<P>
   Although you can buy specialty capsules on the Internet, people
often use whatever they can find around the house, Hudson said,
including Mason jars, Tupperware, pop bottles, plastic bags and
cookie tins. He's even heard of coffins being used for time
capsules.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would certainly preserve the artifacts,'' he said, ``But
it sort of takes the zest out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, you can use just about anything. As long as it's dry,
dark and durable.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson encourages everyone to make time capsules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just think if somebody put their baseball cards in a time
capsule,'' he said. ``What a collection they could have! And just
think if your grandfather had done a time capsule for you, what a
gift that would be for future generations. It doesn't have to be
expensive. It's the thought that counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't forget where you buried it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
