<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1582 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-TIME-SIDEBAR-KANSAS-K     12-07 1475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIME-SIDEBAR-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ABOUT TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES A. FUSSELL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Throughout the Kansas City area, people are looking for a way to
commemorate the coming of the new millennium. Like countless others
nationwide, many have chosen time capsules.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: It not only marks the occasion in the present but
also preserves it for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention it's just plain fun.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly and Ed Stewart of Paola, Kan., are planning to bury a time
capsule in their back yard on Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   They got the idea after finding all sorts of interesting things
squirreled away in the 95-year-old house they are restoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we took the trim off around the door, we found a 1903
datebook with carpenters measurements inside,'' Kelly Stewart said.
``We also found a small perfume bottle just inside the attic hatch
in my daughters room. It's neat. We just imagined that some girl
many years ago had a father who wouldn't allow her to have perfume.
And maybe she hid it there. We're just speculating, but it's fun.
And we found some old coins, and two 11/2-cent stamps and an old
medicine bottle. That sparked our interest in the objects that
people use in everyday life, and that there may be things that we
have today that some future generation might get a kick out of
seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   So they're putting together a small box of their own neat things
to leave behind for someone else to find.
</P>
<P>
   They plan to include pictures of their house, a list of owners
and pictures of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also thought about enclosing a Christmas card so they would
see the traditions of Christmas,'' Kelly said. ``I have a Paola
tourism brochure, a Miami County map. And we will put in some 1999
coins.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1 they will seal their bounty in a Tupperware container
and place it in their back yard under a steppingstone. They haven't
determined how long to leave it there. But they don't intend to let
people forget about it, either. They plan to turn the steppingstone
into a dated plaque that indicates the time capsule buried beneath.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Yacht Club at Lake Lotawana also is planning to
make a time capsule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are doing something that is rather poignant in a
way,'' member Sherry Cromwell-Lacy said.
</P>
<P>
   The capsule, to be buried for a quarter century, will contain a
professionally shot and produced documentary video called ``Hello
2025.'' The idea, Cromwell-Lacy said, is to ``send a message
through time'' to descendants of current members.
</P>
<P>
   ``This particular community is unique because it contains so
many second- and third-generation families,'' Cromwell-Lacy said.
``We have people here who brought the first water skis from Cypress
Gardens to the lake, and now they have grandchildren who are expert
skiers. And hopefully those grandchildren will have their own
children who can then hear their ancestors talk about lake living,
and those traditions can be passed on.''
</P>
<P>
   The capsule will be sealed in a moisture-proof container, buried
on clubhouse grounds and marked with a plaque.
</P>
<P>
   A time capsule is also the choice of Jerry Wolfskill, director
of the regional police academy at Johnson County Community College.
The capsule will serve double duty. In addition to marking the
millennium, it will aid in dedicating their new police academy
building on campus, set to open in November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to put the capsule in the building's cornerstone and
have it opened in 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to keep it on permanent record with the college,
in the archives,'' he said. ``Of course we are making an assumption
that the college will be here in 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Items being considered for the capsule include police training
films, photographs of people involved in the academy, a list of
current laws, predictions, letters to as-yet-unborn relatives, a
police baton, a share of Microsoft stock and a bank book containing
a small deposit. (Even a dollar with compound interest, Wolfskill
figures, would accrue to a significant amount over the next 100
years.)
</P>
<P>
   Future openers of the capsule would be instructed to give the
money to the college.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Martha Peterson. Unlike most time capsule
planters, the 69-year-old Peterson doesn't care if her capsule is
ever found.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she'd prefer it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Her family has owned the Osawatomie farm she lives on since
1914.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us kids were born and raised there,'' she said, with a
hint of nostalgia in her voice. ``Grandpa gave dad the farm in 1919
when he got married. I had a mother, father, two brothers and a
sister, and the only one left is me.''
</P>
<P>
   And now she'd like nothing more than to know that a little bit
of them will remain a part of the farm for all time.
</P>
<P>
   So she picked a container and began sifting through her life.
Then she wrote a story of everything that had happened on the farm
over the years. She included a picture album, chose articles about
ancestors and placed them in the capsule with stamps, coins, a
small porcelain Betty Boop figure and a Blue Jay Beanie Baby that
holds special significance for her. Then she added some glittery
confetti, complete with little hearts and angels, and planted it in
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't want anybody to find it,'' she said. ``I just
wanted a little piece of all us there forever. Like my daughter
told me, `Mom, you just buried yourself a kind of eternal flame.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Making your own: Some ageless advice
</P>
<P>
   Making a time capsule? Here are some tips:
</P>
<P>
   - Choose a container that is tough, sealable and moisture-proof.
</P>
<P>
   - If you're serious about wanting items to last a long period of
time, invest in a capsule that lets you pump out the oxygen and
replace it with an inert (or non-reactive) gas, such as argon.
</P>
<P>
   - Include items that don't require any technology or equipment.
CDs and videotapes, for instance, may not be playable in the
future. How many of you have 8-track players or Beta VCRs, hmm?
</P>
<P>
   - Avoid plastics, especially when thin. They cannot be counted
on for long-term survival.
</P>
<P>
   - For long-term storage, choose black-and-white photos and
pencil over color pictures and ballpoint pen. Colors,
preservationists say, can fade or even disappear. Remember to write
a dated description on the back of each photo in pencil.
</P>
<P>
   - To keep the emulsion surfaces of your photos from sticking
together, sleeve the photos with archival-quality photo envelopes.
</P>
<P>
   - Newspapers are not only highly acidic and deteriorate quickly
over time but also can hasten the deterioration of other items. If
possible, photocopy any valuable articles you may want to keep onto
high-quality archival paper.
</P>
<P>
   - Remember to remove all staples and paper clips. They corrode
easily.
</P>
<P>
   - To help reduce moisture, include packs of moisture-absorbing
substances. These are often included in the packing materials for
various electronics equipment.
</P>
<P>
   - Document your time capsule on the outside with a permanent
marker. Tell the date it was made, who made it and give a ``do not
open until ... '' date.
</P>
<P>
   - Do not bury your capsule. Instead, keep it in a dark, dry
place, such as an attic, or in another place of honor that you will
remember. It has been estimated that for every 1,000 capsules
buried, only one is ever found. If you must bury your capsule, mark
it with a permanent plaque or sign that notes what it is, where it
is and when it was buried.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Jackson County Historical Society will provide advice
on assembling a time capsule. You can receive a packet of
information by calling the society at (816) 252-7454. You also can
speak to an archivist at that number or by sending e-mail to
research &LR; jchs.org. Sources: The Smithsonian Institution, the
History Channel and various archivists and preservationists.
</P>
<P>
   Capsule information
</P>
<P>
   Looking to buy a time capsule? You can get them in many places,
including some card shops, in many museum catalogs and on dozens of
sites on the Internet. Here is a list of some of the reputable
manufacturers assembled by the Smithsonian Institution.
</P>
<P>
   - A-1 Time Capsule
</P>
<P>
   Work Pro Inc.
</P>
<P>
   1345 E. Lebanon Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury, Calif. 91010
</P>
<P>
   (626) 836-7236
</P>
<P>
   - Affordable Time Capsules
</P>
<P>
   3507 Clayton Road, No. 105
</P>
<P>
   Concord, Calif. 94519
</P>
<P>
   e-mail: mrgrinch &LR; value.net
</P>
<P>
   - Barr Technologies
</P>
<P>
   2885 Whipporwill Drive
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Hill, Calif. 95037
</P>
<P>
   (408) 779-2345
</P>
<P>
   - Erie Landmark
</P>
<P>
   4449 Brookfield
</P>
<P>
   Chantilly, Va. 22021-1642
</P>
<P>
   (800) 874-7848
</P>
<P>
   - Future Archaeology
</P>
<P>
   P.O. Box 1130
</P>
<P>
   Ansonia Station
</P>
<P>
   New York, N.Y. 10023
</P>
<P>
   (212) 877-4310
</P>
<P>
   - Time Capsules Inc.
</P>
<P>
   P.O. Box 650
</P>
<P>
   Nampa, Idaho 83653
</P>
<P>
   (208) 466-8712
</P>
