 Tuesday, Dec. 7, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PENNIES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Seems a penny's not worth your thoughts
any more. Store clerks ignore them and customers leave them on
counters. So some people advocate ditching them altogether. By ALAN
WECHSLE.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATUERS (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HERBAL-REMEDIES (San Antonio) _ Joie Davidow's curiosity in the
herbal remedies provided by her Hispanic neighbors sent her on a
two-year adventure of research and interviews that resulted in her
book, ``Infusions of Healing: A Treasury of Mexican-American Herbal
Remedies'' (Fireside Books, 340 pages, $14.). The author says her
research was ``like unlocking a dark closet and seeing it was
filled with treasure.'' By DANIEL J. VARGAS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GREATEST-VIDEOS (Albany, N.Y.) _ ``MTV's 100 Greatest Videos
Ever Made,'' compiled by nearly 50 representatives of MTV and TV
Guide, is a weeklong look back at what this group considers the
best of the 19,000 videos that have aired on the cable network over
the past two decades. By MARK MCGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ What really happened in Seattle
last week was a testimony to this flawed but magnificent democracy
of ours. Some 50,000 people made their way to the city to tell the
representatives of 135 nations that they value some things more
than the fat, juicy fruits of a booming economy. And all but a tiny
percentage of those people did their telling in nondestructive
ways, exercising the same methods of civil disobedience that have
been used by protesters from Selma, Ala., to Washington, D.C. By
STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The year is 2003, and there is an
election happening in San Francisco to determine who will be the
second mayor of the new millennium. In that year, high-rises and
fancy restaurants ring the waterfront, and the Bay Bridge is a
closed parking lot. Rents finally stabilized at $2,500 for studios
when the Internet and the Siliconomy went bust in the Great Y2K
Recession. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Society has the unavoidable
obligation to take care of those who are incapable of caring for
themselves. This will take greater resources, but it is the only
available solution to the nation's homeless problem. By HARRY
ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-GAMBLING (Oneida Nation Territory, N.Y. ) _ Racism and
fear-mongering are accompanying a new legal battle between the
Oneida Indians and the state of New York that could result in a
second tribe-run casino closer to New York City. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
</TEXT>
