<HEADLINE>
HOWEVER YOU EXPLAIN IT, WE'RE SEEKING HONESTY IN OUR LEADERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'll never forget the 1996 presidential campaign, with poll
after poll declaring that voters didn't care about a candidate's
honesty or personal character _ what they wanted was a president
``who cares about people like you.''
</P>
<P>
   So the choice was a no-brainer. Here was Mr. Compassion, Bill
Clinton, a man who had the integrity of a rattlesnake but felt our
pain; and there was Bob Dole, a man whose word was his bond but
conjured up images of the crabby neighbor who was always screaming,
``Get off my lawn!''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cared about people like us. To prove it, he could cry on
cue. Dole wouldn't have cried if you'd poked him in the eye with a
stick.
</P>
<P>
   It was thoroughly baffling. Clinton had proved beyond a shadow
of doubt in the first four years of his presidency _ heck, the
first four days _ that he was pathologically dishonest. Not only
was he a compulsive liar, as anyone who was paying attention could
see, but he couldn't keep a promise for more than 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon told one gigantic lie _ ``I am not a crook'' _ and
was driven from the presidency. Clinton seemed to lie every time he
opened his mouth for four years _ and won a second term without
breaking a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   But guess what? As the 2000 presidential campaign picks up
steam, the electorate has apparently changed its tune.
</P>
<P>
   According to a public-opinion poll commissioned by The
Associated Press and conducted by ICR of Media, Pa., the most
important characteristic that voters are looking for in a potential
president this time around is _ are you ready for this? _ honesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honesty was mentioned ahead of compassion, leadership skills
and political philosophy,'' the AP reported. ``One-third of
Americans mentioned honesty as the `most important' quality they're
looking for in a presidential candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   The AP quoted a voter from Virginia: ``How can you tell your
children not to lie if the president is not telling the truth?''
</P>
<P>
   Good question.
</P>
<P>
   And about time. Remember all those polls that came out during
the sex-and-lies scandal that culminated with Clinton's impeachment
trial in the Senate? You know the polls I mean: the ones that said
hardly anyone cared if the president cheated on his wife, lied to
the country or robbed a Brink's truck _ as long as the economy was
strong and most Americans had jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, only the most avid Clinton-haters were grumbling
about how awful it was to have a notorious liar living in the White
House and commanding the world's greatest armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   What changed?
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe all the years of presidential mendacity and all the
months of investigation and scandal just finally took their toll.
Maybe voters have decided that it's not such a good idea to entrust
the keys to the Oval Office to an individual who can't be trusted _
even if he does care about people like them.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe nothing has changed. Maybe the polls suggesting that
the American people didn't care about their president's character
and honesty were an anomaly _ a fleeting phenomenon fueled by
disgust with investigators, news organizations and politicians who
made a federal case out of Clinton's character flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible that the ``we-don't-care'' attitude that seemed
so pervasive during the scandal wasn't all it was cracked up to be?
Could it be that what the American people really were saying was,
``We don't care this much''?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps sensible Americans were simply reacting to what they
viewed as overkill in the investigators' pursuit of the president _
and the media's coverage of the pursuit and related events.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the public didn't change its attitude virtually overnight
from not caring about honesty at all to caring about it more than
anything else. Surely the electorate can't be that confused and
indecisive.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. The AP poll is good news because it tells us that
voters have regained their senses _ if they ever lost them. And
because it sends a message to all the would-be presidents: Liars
need not apply.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
