<HEADLINE>
WHERE'S HEAT? DEBATE NEVER IGNITES FIREWORKS  
 (THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE DEC. 7 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By XXXXXX  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - If Monday evening's debate among all six Republican
presidential aspirants proved anything, it was this: Given a chance
to grill each other, none of these fellows ever met a softball
question served gently over the plate that he didn't like.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as the season's first unscripted, unpredictable GOP
debate thanks to a format that allowed candidates to query each
other reporter-style, the event at the lovely Orpheum Theatre in
downtown Phoenix produced just occasional fireworks. And most of
that involved simply some low-caliber testiness between Texas Gov.
George W. Bush and publisher Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Note to Miss Manners: Is it OK for presidential candidates to
address each other by their first names?
</P>
<P>
   Blissfully genteel, each of the Republican Six seemed intent on
using the debate, televised nationally on CNN, to fine-tune his
image.
</P>
<P>
   George ``Dubya'' Bush, the acknowledged front-runner, wishes,
like the current, lip-biting officeholder, to be viewed as
``compassionate.'' But conservatively compassionate.
</P>
<P>
   While the Texas governor believes, like Clinton, in federal
support for education at home and the inclusion of China in the
World Trade Organization abroad, his notions on those subjects
``are not even close to Clinton's,'' he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's edgiest moments came when Forbes _ who has devoted
almost his entire campaign focus to attacking Bush _ got to ask the
Texan a question. But a fairly interesting query about what Bush
might do to lower oil prices quickly devolved into snippiness over
whether to address each other by first names.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown candidate Sen. John McCain, who joined the event
electronically, adroitly worked the Forbes-Bush snit to his own
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a Bush question about faith-based ministries,
McCain said, ``I think you're on the right track, Governor . . . or
George . . . or Dubya . . . or whatever you want.''
</P>
<P>
   As is becoming tradition, McCain also managed a bit of
self-parody regarding his infamous temper, this time regarding the
mysterious Senate colleagues who reportedly have been accusing him
of tantrums.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his contention that a good teacher should never be
paid less than a bad senator, McCain said, ``I would never allege
that there are any bad senators. I win the Miss Congeniality Award
every year.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also worked his image as a maverick-minded reformer. With
the generous aid of pro-life activist Gary Bauer, McCain repeatedly
identified his primary campaign weapon _ campaign finance reform _
as one of the most important issues of the entire campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And while still providing lustrous oratory, Alan Keyes seems to
be settling into a campaign of symbolism, marking his responses
repeatedly with references to slavery, serfdom and racism. Keyes,
the sole African-American among the six, has accused the press of
neglecting his campaign out of racism.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it was a debate that produced few surprises, and
left Bush and McCain untoppled as the front-runners. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
