<HEADLINE>
SAINTS' BONES HOLY TO SOME, MACABRE TO OTHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   St. Therese of Liseux, known as the ``Little Flower,'' won over
many people deep in the heart of Texas last week.
</P>
<P>
   The bones of St. Therese, perhaps the most revered of modern-day
saints, reached Fort Worth-Dallas during a U.S. tour that began in
October in New York City. Thousands visited her relics in San
Antonio and Houston later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   I was among thousands who lined up to see the gold and wooden
box, called a reliquary, containing her bones. Some came in
wheelchairs. Many carried roses. A tradition holds that when St.
Therese heals or blesses someone, that person receives a rose, or
is aware of the scent of the flower.
</P>
<P>
   Why so much attention to this French Carmelite nun who died at
age 24 more than a century ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``She gives us hope,'' said Edith Raoult of Garland, a native of
France who was one of those braving a crowd of about 10,000 at the
Arlington Convention Center to view the relics and attend a Mass.
``She knew suffering. She understands us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Most Rev. Joseph P. Delaney, bishop of Fort Worth, was the
principal celebrant at the Mass. He was joined by other bishops.
Behind them was a larger-than-life picture of the gently smiling
blue-eyed saint.
</P>
<P>
   People do not regard St. Therese's remains as mere bones, said
the Most Rev. Patrick V. Ahern, associate bishop of New York, who
presented the homily. They feel they are drawing close to a real
saint and therefore are closer to God.
</P>
<P>
   Not a lot of precise Catholic teaching exists about a
Christian's obligation to honor relics, according to University of
Dallas faculty member Marcellino D'Abrosio.
</P>
<P>
   But honoring the bones of people of great faith has been a part
of the Christian practice since Roman times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tradition comes from the Old Testament idea that holy
people leave a certain spiritual power in the things they touch and
use, and also in their bones,'' D'Abrosio said.
</P>
<P>
   People gathered up the bones of Polycarp, the bishop of Smyrna,
after he was burned at the stake by Romans in A.D. 155. The
86-year-old martyr's bones were put in a place of honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``His bones were considered more precious than gold,'' D'Abrosio
said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in the second century, the site of St. Peter's grave was
visited as a shrine. Later, Constantine built St. Peter's Basilica
over the apostle's grave.
</P>
<P>
   Not all see the importance of relics, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think that this is awfully medieval and
unsophisticated,'' he said. ``Some who feel that way are professors
and some are priests.''
</P>
<P>
   But D'Abrosio, a Catholic layman, contends it is foolish to look
askance at a practice that has blessed many people, including
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 20, I made a pilgrimage to Rome and had a very
profound experience that really changed my life when I visited the
tomb of Pope John XXIII,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged, though, that many have misused relics,
regarding them in a superstitious way as good luck charms.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time St. Therese's bones have been in the
United States, and large crowds have assembled.
</P>
<P>
   People may be drawn to her because outwardly she seemed like one
of us. She could boast of no great deeds. She was relatively
unknown when she died of tuberculosis in 1897.
</P>
<P>
   But she left a spiritual legacy that has touched the world. She
was made patroness of France along with St. Joan of Arc.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern noted that when she died, she told those around her, ``I
am not dying. I am entering into life. My mission is about to
begin.''
</P>
<P>
   Her autobiography, ``Story of a Soul,'' first published in 1898,
still is inspiring many in their search for true spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   It contains teachings many of us can apply in this frenzied
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``What matters in life,'' she wrote, ``is not great deeds, but
great love.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
