<HEADLINE>
MOONLIGHT AND LOVING HEARTS CONQUER FEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is nothing as black as a Mississippi night, nothing as
lonesome or frightful.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this explains how so much evil has been played out there.
The nights always seem to match the terrifying deeds.
</P>
<P>
   But I am also reminded of sweeter moments, of dusty gravel
roads, a white wood-frame church with its squeaky piano always in
need of tuning, and riding with my sisters in the back seat of my
uncle's car, smelling of Listerine he kept handy for his chronic
bad breath.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't thought much about those nights of my childhood or the
wonderful splashes of moonlight giving life to the ghosts
inhabiting the big, towering oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Much later, of course, I realized the ghosts were not real. But
I was just a little girl then, like Noni, frightened by my own
imaginings.
</P>
<P>
   I remember this as I read ``Tambourine Moon'' to my daughter
Asha. This is where we meet Noni and Grandaddy walking along dark
city streets.
</P>
<P>
   The shadows of parked cars are as huge as giants to her, and the
houses all have mean expressions on their faces, but they conjure
memories from another time for Grandaddy.
</P>
<P>
   Noni wants only to get home. He pauses instead and stares at the
moon, that thing, Grandaddy tells her, that ``works the night shift
so that the sun can get some rest.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Joy Jones' ``Tambourine Moon.'' The tale bounces back
and forth from Noni and Grandaddy in the city, to a time when
Grandaddy was just a boy. And scared of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Based loosely on her father's recollections of his roots in
Selma, Ala., and nearby King's Bend, Jones celebrates love, family
and storytelling in one fell swoop, saving us from the dark just
like the moonlight.
</P>
<P>
   But if her story is lost on you _ and I suspect this won't be
the case _ brilliant splashes of color by Texas illustrator Terry
Widener hold you spellbound till the very end.
</P>
<P>
   You will believe Grandaddy, believe how Grandma Ismay and her
tambourine calmed his fears one night and guided him home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of me shaking the tambourine, the tambourine was
shaking me,'' he says. ``Then all of a sudden, that tambourine
jumped right out of my hand! It shot itself up higher, higher,
higher till it settled in the sky. That big yellow tambourine, just
hung there, glowing and pouring light all over the night like
butter running down the sides of a hot biscuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Before you know it, he and Noni have walked the distance home,
and Asha and I are left with the warm fuzzy feeling that you get
from knowing the familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a nice story, huh, Mommy?'' Asha asks.
</P>
<P>
   I tell her ``yes.'' She lingers, thumbing through the colorful
pages over and over again as if to soak up their words and their
images.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, she kisses me and leaves for her bed. I am left
with memories of Mississippi nights, dark gravel back roads and
trees with terrifying expressions.
</P>
<P>
   I was Noni, needing to get home, but finding comfort in
Grandaddy's memory of the Alabama moon. But I was Grandaddy, too,
discovering, in a nighttime moment of dread, Grandma Ismay and the
magic of her yellow tambourine.
</P>
<P>
   That's how my nights always turned out. One moment I was shaking
with fear and the next jumping for joy.
</P>
<P>
   And so it occurred to me while reading ``Tambourine Moon'' that
that's how it is in real life, too. In our darkest hour, God always
shines some light, even moonlight, that thing which ``works the
night shift so that the sun can get some rest.''
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gstaples(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
