<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MAZDA MPV COULD BE FAMILY'S MVP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mazda, the Japanese automaker mostly owned and solidly
controlled by Ford Motor Co., has a credible new entry in the
minivan market with the completely redesigned 2000 MPV.
</P>
<P>
   This company was one of the first Japanese automakers to roll
out a good minivan with the original MPV in 1989. It was among the
best-selling import vans for years. But because it had not has
significant changes in style or interior setup since introduction,
sales steadily declined the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   For 2000, the MPV joins the rest of the pack with dual sliding
doors, and it has a feature not found on the competitors: real
windows that actually roll down into those sliding doors.
Unfortunately, Mazda is not offering automatic electric sliding
doors like some of the competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The new MPV is a bit larger than its predecessor, but smaller
than most of the competition. It's about on par with the short
version of the Plymouth Voyager/Dodge Caravan.
</P>
<P>
   It's narrower than the competition, too, a necessity for Mazda
in its home market. Japanese city streets are rather narrow, and
Japanese drivers prefer cars that are easy to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   I believe the smaller size _ Mazda calls it ``smart sized'' _
will appeal to many U.S. buyers, especially people who want a
vehicle that is easy to park and fits into the family garage.
</P>
<P>
   Interior space really doesn't suffer. The van is still roomy and
comfortable for seven people.
</P>
<P>
   The exterior styling and interior layout are similar to those of
the new Honda Odyssey. One big plus for the Mazda is the price: You
can buy a base DX model equipped with air-conditioning and other
popular amenities for $19,995 (plus $480 transportation). That
price allows the MPV to compete against the bargain-priced
entry-level minivans from DaimlerChrysler. No other imports have a
base price this low.
</P>
<P>
   A midlevel LX model, which adds power windows and door locks and
heated power mirrors, lists for $22,050 (plus transportation). This
is close to the entry-level price for most of the Japanese
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Load up the MPV with all the best amenities, including leather
seats and a premium audio system, and you get the ES model with a
reasonable list price of $25,550. A comparable competitor's model
would would run a few thousand dollars higher.
</P>
<P>
   Only one engine is offered in the MPV. It's an all-aluminum,
24-valve, 2.5-liter V-6 provided by Ford. It's rated at 170
horsepower (160 in California) and 165 foot-pounds of torque. This
is the smallest six-cylinder engine offered in a minivan, but don't
immediately dismiss it as too small. The MPV is several hunded
pounds lighter than competing vans, so the little V-6 provides more
than adequate power for most uses. The vehicle does strain a bit
climbing hills fully loaded, but that's true of some other popular
minivans and sport-utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The ride is comfortable if not cushy. The suspension is a bit
stiffer than that of a luxury passenger car. The payback is that
the vehicle handles better. It's no sports car, but it handles much
better than the average van.
</P>
<P>
   The four-speed automatic transmission shifts smoothly and
effortlessly, and the brakes are very efficient, thanks partly to
the relatively light weight. Front discs and rear drums are
standard. Antilock braking is optional on base models but was
included on our test vehicle, the top-of-the-line ES.
</P>
<P>
   There is seating for seven, with two buckets up front, Mazda's
patented ``side by slide'' dual middle-row captain's chairs, and a
tumble-under third-row bench seat that folds flat into the floor
when you need to get it out of the way. The middle seats can slide
together to make a two-person bench, or push to the two outboard
positions to make separate seats. Each can quickly be removed, and
at 37 pounds each, they're easy to carry.
</P>
<P>
   There is ample cargo space behind the third seat. A deep well
holds groceries in place, even when they are packed into plastic
bags. This is in marked contrast with some of the competition.
Total cargo space with all the seats in place is a highly
respectable 17.2 cubic feet. That expands to 54.6 cubic feet with
the third seat folded into the floor.
</P>
<P>
   There are almost too many cup holders to count, which is good
for a minivan loaded with the neighborhood soccer team. And
speaking of that, the third seat can be set up backward so you can
sit in it and look out the rear hatch to watch the team play; it
makes for a great tailgate party.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-volt power outlet is provided at the rear for camping
accessories and other devices.
</P>
<P>
   Driver and passenger get front air bags; side air bags for the
front seats are optional.
</P>
<P>
   The base stereo includes AM/FM/compact disc, but an optional
in-dash six-disc CD changer ($600) is offered.
</P>
<P>
   Our test model's list price, with options, was $27,330 including
transportation. That price included the in-dash CD changer and a
power moon roof ($700). And it's well below some of the
best-equipped competitors.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings are 18 miles per gallon in the city and
23 mpg on the highway. The tank holds 18.5 gallons of gasoline, and
unleaded regular is recommended.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE:
</P>
<P>
   2000 Mazda MPV ES minivan
</P>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Five-door, seven-passenger, V-6 powered,
front-drive minivan Highlights: Completely redesigned for 2000, the
MPV is among the best of the minivan crop; it comes with V-6
engine, superb seating arrangements, good ride and handling and a
bargain price when compared with some competitors.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: A higher-powered engine would be a nice option; no
automatic electric sliding doors are available.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: Ford Windstar, Mercury Villager/Nissan Quest,
Chevrolet Venture, Honda Odyssey, Pontiac Montana, Oldsmobile
Silhouette, Dodge Caravan/Plymouth Voyager, Chrysler Town &AMP;
Country, Toyota Sienna.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY: 18 miles per gallon city/23 highway.
</P>
<P>
   BASE PRICE (ES model): $25,550 plus $480 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE AS TESTED: $27,330, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: A.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
Texas 76021; his E-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com.
Fax: (817) 685-3883. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
