<HEADLINE>
THE WONDERFUL WARTS OF DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's been a long time since we've read about
``anarchists'' in the streets of a U.S. city. And ``radicals.'' And
``anti-capitalists.''
</P>
<P>
   What's next? ``Subversives?'' ``Outside agitators?''
``Radic-libs?'' ``America - Love It or Leave It?''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle, 1999. Tear gas. Night sticks. Broken plate glass.
Emergency curfews. Mass arrests. The National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   As the Buffalo Springfield sang 32 years ago: ``There's
something happening here; what it is ain't exactly clear.''
</P>
<P>
   But what it ain't is clear, even though the dramatic images you
saw on your television screen and newspaper front page _ and the
understandable kvetching from Seattle residents _ might indicate
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Most of what happened in Seattle last week, as World Trade
Organization delegates met and tens of thousands of people
protested their meeting, was not about vandalism, looting or
calculated violence. It was not about anybody, including Seattle's
mayor or its police force, making the city look bad.
</P>
<P>
   In this increasingly polarized time of ours, it would be helpful
to keep those facts in mind.
</P>
<P>
   What really happened in Seattle was a testimony to this flawed
but magnificent democracy of ours.
</P>
<P>
   Some 50,000 people made their way by plane, boat, car and foot
to northwestern Washington to tell the representatives of 135
nations that they value some things more than the fat, juicy fruits
of a booming economy. And all but a tiny percentage of those people
did their telling in nondestructive ways, exercising the same
methods of civil disobedience that have been used by protesters
from Selma, Ala., to Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that tiny percentage, a mayor and a police force who
had hoped their laid-back city could best handle protests by
remaining laid-back did what a lot of municipal officials do when
surprise violence erupts: They panicked and overreacted. Peaceful,
even retreating demonstrators were tear-gassed or shot in the back
with rubber bullets; all protesters lost their right to peacefully
assemble anywhere near the WTO meeting headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   That overreaction was ugly, but it doesn't make Seattle Mayor
Paul Schell, his police chief or the city's cops Nazis _ or as one
Seattlite put it, ``wimps'' _ anymore than the tiny percentage of
marauders makes the majority of protesters looters and thugs.
</P>
<P>
   One other thing you might want to keep in mind: With everything
that did occur in Seattle, not a protester or cop was killed or
seriously wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, some folks who didn't deserve it got hurt. Yes, some small
businesses that didn't deserve it lost money. Yes, some property
got damaged. Things like that can happen when 50,000 people are
allowed to descend upon a small area for a week of public protests.
</P>
<P>
   But the day we no longer risk such loss to allow such protest is
the day we kiss this flawed but magnificent democracy goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
