<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAZING INTO SAN FRANCISCO'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The year is 2003, and there is an election
happening in San Francisco to determine who will be the second
mayor of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing is that we won't hear anything about anyone
leading San Francisco into the new millennium. We will already be
there, and we will still be complaining.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Brown could be leaving office and returning to his law
practice, running for the Senate or being appointed as head of the
World Trade Organization - after all, like a Sta-Prest suit he
would sooner die than wear, he travels well.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ammiano could be at the end of his first term, challenged by
Clint Reilly and Frank Jordan on the right and a transgender
union-rep bicycle messenger with a grass-roots coalition of people
of piercing on the left.
</P>
<P>
   This is San Francisco. There's someone to the left of anyone.
</P>
<P>
   What will San Francisco look like after four years of Ammiano or
a full eight years of Brown?
</P>
<P>
   It's 2003, and the once and future King Willie has ruled for
eight years. Let's look into the court wizard's crystal ball.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's traffic and parking plan finally reached completion. As
he promised during the 1999 run-off race, he has turned the
Candlestick lots _ where the 49ers stadium and mall still isn't _
into commuter parking and mud baths.
</P>
<P>
   The financial and high-tech district now sprawls in a highrise
strip to Potrero Hill. Rush hour now starts at 4 a.m. and ends at 9
p.m. The Bay Bridge still hasn't been rebuilt across the conference
center, resort and shelters for homeless mayoral aides on Treasure
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Every neighborhood now has a convenient Home Depot, brought to
you by Jack Davis, lobbyist, political consultant and theme party
planner.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the affordable housing give-back demanded by Brown,
each of these chain stores includes a Homeless Depot, specializing
in cardboard of all types, ranging from underpass-home-construction
grade to will-write-on-for-food grade.
</P>
<P>
   Rents in San Francisco start at $800 per month for a good spot
in the privatized homeless camp next to the used car lots in the
Presidio. Young couples can still find the occasional
$5,000-a-month loftette in the upscale Mission District.
</P>
<P>
   City Hall looks better than ever with its new gilt. The Board of
Supervisors still follows orders with no guilt.
</P>
<P>
   The Municipal Railway still doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   It's 2003, and Ammiano has presided over his first four-year
plan. Let's check with his Ministry of Information to see if
production quotas were achieved.
</P>
<P>
   The Ammiano tax plan has been worked out in compromise form.
Those making more than $100,000 a year can pay a 10 percent fee for
an exploiter's license or agree to house two homeless people per
thousand square feet of living space.
</P>
<P>
   The living wage has been adjusted for inflation up to $22 an
hour, still not quite enough to live on, even in an Ammianoville
workers commune.
</P>
<P>
   It took four years for young workers to learn how to Rollerblade
in the same lanes as bicyclists in the Old Folks on Spokes program,
but Ammiano's transportation plan finally went into operation.
</P>
<P>
   The Ammiano commuter surcharges on the bridges ($1 per occupant
or $3 if they're in German cars or sport utility vehicles) have
proven popular with San Franciscans. Delays caused by the
construction of border crossings into San Mateo County have not.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano's neighborhood car-share program has had its problems
because of high demand for cars to get out of San Francisco, the
world's first meat-free zone.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has also been declared a Starbucks-free zone, a
developer-free zone, a smoke-free zone and a city of refuge for the
oppressed politically correct of America.
</P>
<P>
   City Hall's party facilities are now vegetarian soup kitchens
and homeless shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Muni still doesn't work, but Ammiano still rides it.
</P>
<P>
   Well, in 1999 that's the way the two candidates for mayor were
seen by their opponents, as well as by many undecided voters who
faced a tough decision in that run-off election of Dec. 14, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we know what really happened.
</P>
<P>
   In 2003, highrises and fancy restaurants ring the waterfront,
and the Bay Bridge is the closest parking lot - at rush hour or any
time. Rents finally stabilized at $2,500 for studios when the
Internet and the Siliconomy, as it is now known, went bust in the
Great Y2K Recession.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic tickets went up to $500 for triple parkers impeding the
flow of meter persons' scooters, the only traffic that's flowing.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers stadium-mall still doesn't exist, but then neither do
the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   In 2003, everyone hates the mayor. But City Hall still looks
good, whoever runs it until 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Muni still doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
