<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HOMESLESS DESERVE SHELTER 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Homelessness is much with us this season every
year as the nights turn bitter cold, compelling society to sort out
the rights and wrongs of letting people sleep outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   What to do about the homeless this year is sharpened because of
its emergence as an issue in the pre-campaign stage of New York's
race for U.S. Senate. That's a guarantee that the problem will not
as quickly fade from the public stage as it would have if New York
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton had
not chosen to argue about it.
</P>
<P>
   During the Great Depression, the homeless were mostly men unable
to find work at a time when unemployment affected probably a
quarter of the working population. Some of them hit the rails,
vagabonding from one place to another, seeking a job, sleeping in
shantytowns and Hoovervilles. It was a time when the president,
Franklin Roosevelt, saw ``one-third of a nation ill-housed,
ill-clad, ill-nourished.''
</P>
<P>
   Today we're not talking about a third of our people; it is a
tiny, but intractable, fraction. These people too often are shunted
aside for being different, a judgment impaired by ethical myopia.
</P>
<P>
   Surely today's homeless people are also jobless, but not because
there are not enough jobs to be had. It is our special blessing
that there are more jobs available today than there are people to
do them. Many today are both homeless and out of work because they
suffer from mental illness or are paralyzingly addicted to drugs or
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   This hard-core cadre of homelessness makes the problem so
injurious, elusive of both quick or even long-range fixes.
</P>
<P>
   Those homeless people not plagued mentally or by addiction can
be more easily assisted in a straightforward way. That requires a
commitment to spend the money to house them temporarily while they
are guided and trained to get work, helped by the governmental
support systems designed to see them through tough times. Too
often, those people who have had the good fortune never even to
have come close to the affliction of homelessness are quick to
grumble about taxes going to support what they consider
free-loaders feeding on the body politic.
</P>
<P>
   Even if these grumblers are so hard-hearted as not to recognize
society's moral responsibility, they ought to be shrewd enough to
recognize their own self-interest in providing such aid.
Homelessness undermines the stability of society, and, in time, the
comfortable existences of everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   But that leaves unattended and unaided that major sector of
today's homeless who are mentally ill. Mental institutions, which
once upon a time housed these people, were shuttered for several
reasons. Many of them were bedlams, so atrocious in their treatment
of their patients that they could not be permitted to continue to
operate. They also were costly.
</P>
<P>
   So when science discovered drugs that stabilized the mentally
ill, permitting them to function more or less successfully in the
larger world, there was a belief that a magic bullet cure had been
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   The euphoria was not long-lived. It became clear that
unsupervised the mentally ill often elected not to take the drugs
they needed. And the smaller community centers that were supposed
to replace the large institutions, in which mentally ill people
would receive some supervision, were not put in place. They were
both too costly and too inconvenient to be accepted in residential
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   For that callousness we have been paying a large and disturbing
price. Incidents of sudden, irrational violence unleashed against
innocent passersby occur year after year.
</P>
<P>
   We shove the homeless here and we shove them there, anywhere to
get them out of sight. But both the stringency of the law and the
stinginess of the public commitment have made dealing with the
hard-core ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   What clearly is required is the re-establishment of facilities
for the custodial care of the mentally ill as well as treatment
centers for drug and alcohol addicts, to which sufferers of these
maladies could be legally committed.
</P>
<P>
   Just because earlier institutions failed in their
responsibilities does not mean that better ones could not be set
up. Having the bad example of the past in mind, they should provide
the necessary medical care and personal supervision that was
lacking in the previous ones. The new hospitals would also require
hard-nosed outside oversight to make certain to avoid a repetition
of previous mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   This will take even greater resources, but it is the only
available solution. Society has the unavoidable obligation to take
care of those who are incapable of caring for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
