<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBAL-REMEDIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR EXAMINES THE ROOTS OF HISPANIC HERBAL REMEDIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANIEL J. VARGAS  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ When Joie Davidow moved from New Jersey to Los
Angeles, she knew very little about Mexican-American herbal
remedies. Once she settled in a mostly Hispanic neighborhood and
got to know her neighbors, they offered her soothing teas when she
wasn't feeling well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drank them and they worked,'' said Davidow, 52, the author
of a new book on herbal treatments. ``I would see the herbs in
supermarkets. I wanted to learn more about this tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Her curiosity sent her on a two-year adventure of research and
interviews that resulted in her book, ``Infusions of Healing: A
Treasury of Mexican-American Herbal Remedies'' (Fireside Books, 340
pages, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like unlocking a dark closet and seeing it was filled
with treasure,'' Davidow said of her research.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, she thought it was going to be a simple
project because she already knew a lot about herbs. It turned out
to be a gigantic undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   Davidow traveled the Southwest and talked to curanderas
(healers) and yerberas (herbalists), abuelas (grandmothers) and
young women. She also scoured records on the Internet from Mexican
universities on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned what was being practiced in the Mexican-American
neighborhoods _ they were legacies from Aztec medicine,'' she said
of the indigenous Indian civilization of Mexico. ``It was an
integral part of their religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidow said the Aztecs had detailed botanical records and
cultivated botanical gardens. When the Spanish conquered the
Aztecs, the practice was outlawed because some of the herbal
concoctions had ties with their religious beliefs and practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The practice went underground and became a folk tradition
being passed from generation to generation,'' she said in a recent
interview. ``I wanted to make sure I talked about the Aztec's
contributions to medicine. If you don't, it's out of context and
missing the point.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Infusions of Healing,'' Davidow describes 250 herbs and
plants from A to Z to help ease everyday ailments such as
indigestion, congestion, diarrhea, migraines and arthritis. She
includes English, Spanish and botanical names with notes on their
origin and primary uses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to choose the ones that are easy to find, commonly
used and ones that I could talk about their known medicinal
properties,'' Davidow said, adding that two of the more popular
herbs are spearmint (yerba buena) and chamomile.
</P>
<P>
   Next, readers are told how to prepare the herbs from warm teas
(infusions) and compresses to soothing liniments. Teas are the most
popular.
</P>
<P>
   The author does warn that people should be aware of possible
allergic reactions to herbs. And, she said, people should always
tell their doctor what herbs they are taking because of potential
interactions with prescription and/or over-the-counter medication.
</P>
<P>
   Davidow said there is a rebirth of herbal remedies in part
because of the burgeoning natural supplement industry, which has
sales of $12 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? An estimated 25 percent of all modern
pharmaceutical drugs are derived from herbs, including aspirin,
which comes from white willow bark.
</P>
<P>
   The author is such an herbal remedy fan that she has a '`great
big collection'' of herbs in her kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grow my own herbs in my garden, and I dry them out myself,''
Davidow said.
</P>
</TEXT>
