<SLUG> BC-TRENDS-TEENS-NEXT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTENTION EDITORS: THIS INTRODUCTORY COLUMN MAY BE PUBLISHED ONLY
BY SUBSCRIBERS TO ``NEXT,'' A NEW COLUMN ON TRENDS FOR THE UNDER-30
CROWD, WRITTEN BY JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM, PRESIDENT OF YOUTH
INTELLIGENCE. FOR INFORMATION ON BECOMING A CHARTER CLIENT _ OR TO
SEE MORE SAMPLES _ CALL YOUR NEW YORK TIMES SYNDICATE SALES
REPRESENTATIVE AT (888) 269-8796. EDITORS WHO SIGN UP BEFORE THE
END OF THE YEAR WILL GET A COPY OF YI'S RESPECTED ``CASSANDRA
REPORT,'' WHICH FOCUSES ON WHAT'S HOT AND WHAT'S NOT WITH
GENERATIONS X AND WHY?  
 (FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE) 
 WHAT'S A TREND? WHAT'S A FAD?
</HEADLINE>
  By JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I first start talking about a trend, people typically have
one of two responses. Either they tell me they've already seen it,
and therefore it can't be that ``trendy,'' or they say they've
never even heard of it, so they can't believe it could become
popular.
</P>
<P>
   But trends are more than just what colors the latest fashions
will come in or which video MTV can't play enough. Trends are about
changes in the way we think, act and live.
</P>
<P>
   Trends show us the subtle ways in which society is changing and
the direction in which it is heading. We did not wake up one day to
a nation that puts Jerry Springer on top of the TV ratings. Nor did
women earn the right to vote simply because men decided it seemed
fair. Trends, both large and small, helped achieve both of these
ends.
</P>
<P>
   So where do you find trends? They come from music, politics,
travel, the Internet. They are in every ad you see and every
magazine you pick up. They evolve everywhere. And they can come
from anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Before you can spot them, however, it's important to know the
difference between a fad and a trend.
</P>
<P>
   When companies go hunting for ``the next big thing,'' too often
they invest energy and resources in products or people who fade out
before they can deliver. Fads are like crushes. They burn fast and
hot but die quickly and often leave a bitter taste. They don't
survive because they are not grounded in anything real. Bell
bottoms, Green Day and Jennifer Aniston's haircut are all fads that
came and went quickly (albeit some not quickly enough). They were
not rooted in anything with foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Trends, on the other hand, are most important when they emerge
from a behavioral shift or psychological belief that gives them
reasons for existing. There are two types of trends: macro and
micro.
</P>
<P>
   Macro trends are about the ``big'' issues: our definitions of
happiness, success, fulfillment. These come from the way people
think, and they develop over a longer period of time. They emerge
when people feel a dissatisfaction with the status quo _ in their
own lives and in society.
</P>
<P>
   Micro trends emerge from macro trends. They are more tangible
offspring of what people are feeling. They manifest themselves
through fashion, music, sports, activities. Micro trends reveal to
us that a macro trend exists, showing us that people are ready for
something new.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a current macro trend is the general
dissatisfaction with the work world. As a general rule, young
people no longer believe that they will join a company and leave 30
year later with a gold watch and a cushy pension plan. Corporate
downsizing, mergers, takeovers and massive layoffs have all shown
that the career pact as previous generations knew it no longer
holds true. In addition, people are questioning whether they even
want their boss's boss's job or whether 14-hour workdays are worth
the supposed end benefits.
</P>
<P>
   People are questioning the work code, not the work ethic. This
general dissatisfaction is a macro trend.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that doesn't mean that corporate America will shut down as
people leave in droves to pursue more ``meaningful'' livelihoods.
But a micro trend that has emerged is the shift toward casual work
clothes. Workers no longer subscribe to the idea that wearing a
suit means you're doing a good job. In fact, many have begun to
believe that you can do a better job if you're more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   This trend has happened slowly, moving from avant-garde
companies in the fields of advertising and design to more
mainstream offices. Today, ``Casual Fridays'' are commonplace.
Don't confuse this with a fad. Khakis may be the ``hot'' pant this
year, and Cargos may replace them next year, but ``casual'' will
stay for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Other micro trends emerging from this ``dissatisfaction''
include the rise of entrepreneurism, an increase in flex time and
an acceptance of multiple midlife career changes.
</P>
<P>
   What's on the horizon? Expect to see more women giving up their
jobs to stay home and take care of children. Anticipate a more
flexible workday, with employees choosing their own hours. We may
even see a four-day office week with all employees working from
home on Fridays. (Now wouldn't that be nice!)
</P>
<P>
   It won't happen overnight. Trends don't. But if you watch
emerging trends, you'll have a better idea of where we may be going
and what may be changing in your life in the not-too-distant
future.
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; BOX: HERE TODAY/COMING TOMORROW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HERE TODAY: Sony Playstation. COMING TOMORROW: Sega Dreamcast.
</P>
<P>
   HERE TODAY: Animal prints. COMING TOMORROW: Reptile prints.
</P>
<P>
   HERE TODAY: Tattoo necklaces. COMING TOMORROW: Nameplate
necklaces.
</P>
<P>
   HERE TODAY: Victoria's Secret underwear. COMING TOMORROW:
Shopgirl underwear.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rinzler Buckingham is the president of Youth Intelligence,
a market-research firm specializing in the 7- to 35-year-old
market. Her company publishes the Cassandra Report, a comprehensive
survey focused on identifying emerging trends among Generations X
and Why?
</P>
</TEXT>
