r l BC-FALL-WORKSHOP09-COX     12-07 0242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-WORKSHOP09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seal up cracks and keep winter chill at bay
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Dec. 9.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's never too late to insulate doors and windows to
prevent cold air from seeping through.
</P>
<P>
   Although older homes are more likely to need insulating, newer
ones aren't guaranteed to be properly sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Nichols, a store associate at Home Depot in Atlanta, says
one way to determine if your door needs weatherproofing is to look
for gaps of light around doors and windows.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols recommends using high-density weatherstripping for
doors, because it is more durable. He recommends low-density
weatherstripping for use around windows, because it is more
flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Step 1: Measure the top of the door and the door jamb (where
hinges are located) to determine how much weatherstripping to
purchase. Remove worn weatherstripping. Fit insulation into door
jamb; work from top to bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Step 2: Cut insulation at bottom where door jamb ends. Make sure
weatherstripping is even with the bottom of the door.
</P>
<P>
   Step 3: Remove adhesive tape, starting from top. Repeat the
process on top of door.
</P>
<P>
   S U P P L I E S
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  High-density foam rubber adhesive weatherstripping for doors
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Utility knife
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
