A1667 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-QUICK-TIPS09-COX     12-07 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUICK-TIPS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quick fixes for sprucing up your home for the holidays
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Dec. 9.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In January, you swore you would repaint that dining room. In
April, you promised that your tax refund would go for carpeting. In
September, you vowed to replace that drought-scorched landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? It's December, and dozens of guests are headed your
way for that office party you foolishly volunteered to host or that
family dinner you insisted it was your turn to prepare. Suddenly,
you recall all those projects you wanted to tackle before another
friend or relative set foot in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Yikes! Too late.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we have a lot of people coming in to do the quick
fixes before the holidays,'' said Cris Lasco, manager of the new
Expo Design Center in Alpharetta, a one-stop decorating outlet.
</P>
<P>
   But with a mere 16 days left until Christmas, what's doable _
short of Martha Stewart, B. Smith and Bob Vila riding in on white
horses to rescue your home from the decorating doldrums?
</P>
<P>
   Lots, if you ask the folks who perform such wonders for a
living.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, if your domestic prowess extends only to changing light
bulbs and fluffing pillows, you may find it tough to hire a
carpenter, decorator or electrician in time for the holidays. But
with two weekends to go, even the inexperienced can still repaint a
room, hang wallpaper or replace the kitchen cabinets' hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Often, buying a few accessories or simply updating what you have
_ a new shade for that lamp, finer frames for those pictures _ can
work wonders, said Tracy Hughes, who leads Expo's designer team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has family coming in, and they want to show off a
little,'' she said. ``The best thing they can do in the time they
have left is to think about focal points.''
</P>
<P>
   The front door is the first thing visitors see, so spruce up
your entrance. Give the door a fresh coat of paint, preferably in a
different color. Put down a new doormat and haul in a pair of
planters with boxwoods or other lush evergreens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Update your address numbers and dress up a wooden door with a
new kickplate,'' said Raphael Williams of Restoration Hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, hang, or lean, an oversize mirror over the mantel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without going to the trouble of painting walls, you can add a
real splash of color with new pillows or window treatments,''
Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   And don't worry about finding a seamstress on such short notice.
Instead, take the no-sew route by hanging decorative brackets over
a window and draping a bold fabric over them.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, a fresh look doesn't have to cost a dime. Simply
rearrange what you have.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite trick of designers on a tight decorating budget is to
empty a room of all its accessories, place them on the kitchen
table and put them back in the room one by one, editing the duds
from the keepers. It's an enlightening exercise that can save you
trips to the store.
</P>
<P>
   But rest assured, their staffs will be armed with ideas just the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you get into December,'' said Leslie McLenon, manager of
Pottery Barn, ``we call it fun desperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
