<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HOLLYWOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKLISTEE LOOKS BACK IN WISDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
HOLLYWOOD EXILE 
Or How I Learned to Love the Blacklist 
By Bernard Gordon 
University of Texas Press, 303 pp., illustrated, $34.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bernard Gordon hasn't really stopped worrying or started loving
the blacklist, any more than we've really stopped worrying and
learned to love the bomb. But the blacklisted screenwriter sets up
that very smart subtext with the Kubrickian subtitle to clue us in
that this memoir is a recollection leavened by age, history, and a
sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood Exile, or How I Learned to Love the Blacklist''
isn't just about the blacklist, Hollywood's menu of alleged
Communists and communist sympathizers considered unemployable
because of their political affiliation. It's about the mad, mad,
mad, mad world of moviemaking.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon had joined the Communist Party at 22, when he was just
getting his start in Hollywood. Over the next 30 years, he would
write or produce more than 20 films. But not before learning to
live with the blacklist, a tale he tells here. While he loathed the
dark days of the anti-communist witch hunt _ and has a venomous
hatred for the poison spewed by the House Committee on Un-American
Activities and by Senator Joseph McCarthy's vilifying speeches _ he
also understands that there are plenty of documents and testimonies
to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who saw communism as a way to fight against big business
and the forces that led to the Great Depression, wasn't
anti-American. ``Joining the party was certainly not a path to
success, either financial or professional,'' writes Gordon. ``Right
or wrong, people were there because they were outraged about the
existing woes and evils of the world and wanted to do something to
correct them. The meetings were painfully boring, but this was the
price we had to pay for saving the world.''
</P>
<P>
   While never losing sight of the injustices of the era, Gordon's
story doesn't end with the blacklist. Thank goodness, because the
most entertaining and revealing portions of the book involve his
work with producers Philip Yordan and Samuel Bronston in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   As his fellow blacklistee, director Abraham Polonsky, points
out: ``Survivors took refuge in small islands of protests and work
at home and abroad. One was in Spain, and there Bernard Gordon
continued his screenwriting career while maintaining the integrity
of his morality and politics.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Polonsky might have added, maintaining his sense of humor,
business savvy, and observational acuity.
</P>
<P>
   He tells some great stories about Kirk Douglas, whom Gordon
tried to interest in a role in a script called ``The Afrikan
General.'' Richard Harris was in line for one key role and Gordon
wanted Douglas for the other. Gordon was so excited about Douglas's
interest, he flew to Tel Aviv, where the star was finishing up his
portrayal of Israeli Colonel David Marcus in ``Cast a Giant
Shadow'' (1966). Douglas turned down the role with arrogant aplomb.
Gordon takes the opportunity to set the record straight on
Douglas's claim that he was the first one to give a blacklisted
screenwriter, Dalton Trumbo, full credit for his work on a film _
it was ``Spartacus'' (1960). According to Gordon, when Trumbo urged
Douglas to give him screen credit, the star-producer hemmed and
hawed, explaining that ``he would have to deal with Universal on
that question and could not promise anything. Only after Otto
Preminger, producer and director of `Exodus,' announced publicly
that Trumbo would receive credit for `Exodus' did Douglas come
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is also refreshingly frank when it comes to his own work.
Producer Yordan wanted a movie about the Boxer Rebellion, a movie
that eventually starred Charlton Heston and was released as ``55
Days at Peking'' (1963). ``We had no story, no plot ideas, no
characters, and only the sketchiest notion of what the Boxer
Rebellion had been about.'' And this coming from a communist?
</P>
<P>
   One of the great ironies of Gordon's work in Spain is that it
was made economically feasible by Generalissimo Francisco Franco,
Spain's fascist dictator. Franco was so enamored with the film
industry, and so eager to generate business, that he loaned his
soldiers and military equipment to dozens of productions, including
``The Battle of the Bulge,'' a Gordon film.
</P>
<P>
   The financial machinations, as producers offered things with one
hand while taking them away with the other, also make for
entertaining, revealing reading. The details of complicated
co-productions in different countries, with a variety of
currencies, sound as if they had all the makings of a Marx Brothers
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who now lives and writes in Los Angeles, hasn't lost the
social rage that brought him to the Communist Party in the first
place. Of America he concludes that ``you can't turn it into a
grand new mansion, but maybe you can make it habitable by fixing
the leaky roof and plumbing, and improving the heating, and making
it a place with living space for all, regardless of race, color,
creed. But keep hammering away.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon hasn't really stopped worrying. And that's what makes his
memoir such a quietly remarkable addition to film literature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
