<HEADLINE>
AEROSMITH'S ROCKIN RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can it be? Is that actually Aerosmith greeting you before the
start of a Walt Disney World ride called the Rock 'n' Roller
Coaster Starring Aerosmith?
</P>
<P>
   No. But you may be forgiven if you thought the Boston rockers
were actually present: What you're seeing is a holographic movie.
And that's just the first surprise at this Disney-MGM Studios
attraction. When you ride the coaster, here's what happens:
</P>
<P>
   --You travel on a track that is 3,043 feet long _ more than a
half-mile of twists, turns, loops, corkscrews, hills, and dips. The
ride is Disney's first coaster in the United States that features
inversions.
</P>
<P>
   --The high-speed launch catapults each 24-person car, or
Limotrain, to 60 m.p.h. in 2.8 seconds. That's similar to the
feeling you'd get in a supersonic jet as it blasts off from the
deck of an aircraft carrier.
</P>
<P>
   --You encounter a force of nearly 5 Gs in the transition from
launch to loop in the ride's first inversion. In contrast, space
shuttle astronauts encounter only 3 Gs at liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   --Each Limotrain has 120 speakers, and each plays a different,
specially recorded Aerosmith song (for instance, ``Love in an
Elevator'' has been transformed into ``Love in a Roller Coaster'').
In all, the attraction has 900 speakers and
</P>
<P>
   more than 32,000 watts of audio amplifier output power. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --And, oh yes, this speedy, sonic ride all happens indoors . . .
and in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of Disney: ``Mousetales, the Unofficial Newsletter of
Walt Disney World'' is offering 10 tips for visiting the Year 2000
celebration at Epcot. The tips include the best time to visit
Millennium Village (11 a.m. to 1 p.m.), the best places to view the
Tapestry of Nations Parade (the Germany or Italy areas of World
Showcase) and Illuminations 2000 (the bridges between the United
Kingdom and France), and where to snag three free souvenirs (the
Innovations buildings). For a free copy, send a self-addressed,
stamped envelope to Mousetales, PO Box 383, Columbus, OH 43216.
(For a year's subscription to the quarterly newsletter, send
$12.95; for a single issue, send $4.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: What is Mexico's largest lake? (Answer at end of
column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
In a name: Many assume Angel Falls in Venezuela got its name
because of its heavenly height. (At 3,212 feet, it is the world's
highest waterfall.) But the real reason is because it was
discovered by Jimmy Angel, a pilot. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Wonderful, wonderful, sublime, indescribable,
incomprehensible; I never saw anything so truly and appallingly
grand.'' _ P.T. Barnum, after his first visit to California. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bus drivers' joke (Santa Fe): A tour-bus driver calls over to
another tour-bus driver parked nearby: ``Hey, I see they finally
gave you your license back!'' The second driver replies, ``Right.
And how did your eye surgery go?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: Texas requires a permit for people to go
barefoot. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Getting around: In San Juan, 40 policemen have donned in-line
roller skates to patrol tourist areas and shopping centers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mailbag: Jeff Coyne of Roslindale begs to differ with our statement
that Lhasa, Tibet, is the world's highest capital. Citing the
Encyclopedia of World Geography, he writes: ``LaPaz, the capital of
Bolivia, is 13,461 feet above sea level. This tops Lhasa by 1,374
feet.'' Merriam Webster's Geographical Dictionary agrees that LaPaz
is the highest capital, but puts its altitude at 12,001 feet,
topping Lhasa by just 171 feet. Other sources offer still different
figures but put LaPaz on top. So Jeff is right. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Lake Chapala in the state of Jalisco, Mexico. The
651-square-mile lake is 50 miles long. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
