<HEADLINE>
SOME GOOD DEALS IN Y2K PACKAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Believe it or not, if you want to go where it's warm for the
millennium, you can, and without paying a premium. And, if you want
to go where it can be cold, very cold, few places say winter with a
warmer welcome than Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people have been turned off by the prices being quoted
for trips over the millennium. Too high a price to pay for the trip
of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, all that's changing,'' said Claire Gorayeb, vice
president of marketing at TNT Vacations. TNT is known for offering
value-packed charter vacations, and for the millennium they have
not only some great prices, but also space.
</P>
<P>
   Aruba has packages beginning at $999 leaving Dec. 25-26 (only
Dec. 26 departures are sold out); other destinations with space
available leaving on either Dec. 25 or 26 are Cozumel (was $1,199
now beginning at $899); Antigua (was $2,049, now from $1,049);
Cancun (was $1,799, now $999); St. Maarten, now from $1,399; Punta
Cana, now from $1,599, and Playa del Carmen, was $2,399 and now is
from $1,499.
</P>
<P>
   Also available are all-inclusive vacations (all meals, drinks,
and more) to Cancun from $1,449, St. Maarten at $2,349, and Playa
del Carmen at $1,499. Travel agents have details, or call
800-GO-TNT-GO.
</P>
<P>
   And, if you are looking for the hot spot of 2000, Gorayeb says,
it's Punta Cana in the Dominican Republic. The beach is
unbelievable, and the prices are great, she says.
</P>
<P>
   In Quebec even the snowmen have a jolly look and welcoming smile
_ especially that happy symbol of the Quebec Winter Carnvial,
Bonhomme Carnival. This annual winter festival, Jan. 28-Feb. 13, is
one of the biggest in the world and includes dog sledding, ice
climbing, a canoe race across the frozen St. Lawrence River,
glittering night parades, tobogganing, snow sculpture competition
(last year 19 countries participated), and a lot more.
</P>
<P>
   Quebec City, North America's only walled city, is particularly
beautiful in winter, with lots of wonderful places to stay and
dine.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for some wonderful cultural experiences,
Montreal is the place to head. In winter, you can travel throughout
the city without ever stepping outdoors. Underground Montreal is a
place to discover.
</P>
<P>
   So think winter, think Quebec for some new experiences. Skiers,
too, will find new discoveries at Mont Tremblant, just outside
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   In the last couple of years Tremblant has been transformed into
a world-class ski resort with a wonderful village almost slopeside,
grand new hotels, and new ski facilities. This season Tremblant has
even added 20 percent more skiing terrain.
</P>
<P>
   For information on the province of Quebec, Montreal or Quebec
City, call 800-363-7777.
</P>
<P>
   Many events are held on the Plains of Abraham where activities
are held for all ages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fun in the sun
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barbados offers its seventh annual Paint It Jazz festival Jan.
12-16. Featured will be Wynton Marsalis, Luther Vandross, and
Regina Belle. For information, call the Barbados Tourism Authority
in New York at 800-221-9831.
</P>
<P>
   Every Tuesday, Friday, and Saturday evening through April 15 Bay
Street in Nassau will be jumping to the sounds of music and
entertainers. More than 70 of the duty-free shops will be open. For
information, call 800-4-BAHAMAS.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
BTV
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BTV stands for Before Television and it's the subject of a
fascinating exhibit at the Norman Rockwell Museum in Stockbridge,
Mass. ``Prior to the early '50s, mass-circulation magazines like
the Saturday Evening Post built their audiences around the visual
appeal of illustrations, especially on magazine covers,'' said
Christopher Clarke-Hazlett, guest curator at the museum. ``The Post
circulated among more American households, generated more
advertising revenue, and exerted more influence over popular
opinion than any other American magazine for the better part of
four decades.'' Norman Rockwell was one of the Post's top
illustrators. ``Before TV: American Culture, Illustration and the
Saturday Evening Post'' continues through June 11.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Need a nanny?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Families visiting Aruba can now have the services of a nanny.
The Aruba Sonesta has begun an ``Island Nanny Program'' that
provides a nanny for the duration of the family's stay. The service
costs $120 a day from 8 a.m. to midnight for two children. For
information on the nanny program, call Coleta Zschuschen at
011-2978-36000. For reservations, call 800-SONESTA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
