 ART ADV.: Photos with FEDERAL-CASELOAD and BIOTECH-COMPUTER are
being ransmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-WOMEN (Jiangyong, China) _ For thousands of years, women
in remote southern China have shared a secret. Denied a formal
education, socially and intellectually isolated, they devised a
language to use after they were separated by marriage. Now only a
handful are left who still know it. By Indira A.R. Lakshmanan. 1400
words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-VILLAGE (He Yuan, China) _ Young women say life has
changed in villages that spoke the secret language, nd they no
longer neeit. By Indira A.R. Lakshmanan. 450 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FEDERAL-CASELOAD (Boston) _ With criminal cases clogging dockets
in border states like Arizona and California, federal judges have
turned to Massachusetts -- and cutting-edge technolgy -- to reduce
caseloads. Judges in Boston, which has a comparatively light
caseload, are handling pretrial motions in civil cases via video
hookups with courts out west. By Shelley Murphy. 1000 words. PHOTO
</P>
