<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS HAVE TO BEAT COLTS TO STAY ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Super Bowl comes early this year for the
Patriots. fact,t comes in five days.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots don't return from Indianapolis Sunday with a
victory, they will not be traveling to Atlanta the week of Jan. 30
for Super Bowl XXXIV. Frankly, it's not likely they'll be going
there whether they beat the Colts or not, but if they don't win
this Sunday, they know they won't be going anywhere but home after
Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   No playoffs. No Super Bowl. No nothing.
</P>
<P>
   They are not in a must-win situation, they are in a MUST-WIN
SITUATION. Their backs are not against the wall, they're through
the wall. The fat is not the only thing in the fire. So is the
muscle if they lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already in playoff mode,'' said safety Lawyer Milloy
Monday. ``We're in playoff mode pretty early but that's nobody's
fault but our own. The fortunate thing is we're used to this
situation. We've been in it for three years, so we're used to
fighting through this.''
</P>
<P>
   They may be used to it, but they aren't happy about it. Nobody
wants to go to the RCA Dome and face the 10-2 Colts in a game you
cannot afford to lose. That's because the Colts haven't lost in two
months, have the highest-scoring offense in the AFC, and possess a
quarterback, a running back, and a wide receiver who can beat you
on their own if given the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky we got them early the first time,'' Milloy said.
``They got that big lead (28-7 at the half) but we were able to
catch them because they didn't know how good they could be yet. We
can't let that happen again. Now they play with great confidence.
Now they play like a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they play like the Patriots always think they're going to
play each September but never quite seem to. Because of that, each
December has been a survival test for Pete's Patriots, and the fact
is you don't always survive such tests.
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Pete Carroll might tell you these experiences have
helped build character ihis team, and he might be right about that,
but nobody needs or wants as many character-building opportunities
as there have been in New England the last three Decembers.
</P>
<P>
   What's worse this time is that there is more of a trick to the
situation. First, the Colts are no longer the AFC East doormat. Now
they are the attic. They are the best team in the division and
maybe the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Yet more important even than the presence of the Colts is the
absence of the slightest bit of room for error for the Patriots.
Desperate as their straits have been in the past, the Patriots
always had room for a small faux paus in December. One tiny slip-up
would not undo them completely.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that could save New England after a loss to the
Colts would be a total collapse of the Miami Dolphins or Buffalo
Bills (which is unlikely), and even if that happened, the Patriots
still would have to win their last three games just to be 10-6 and
grasping at straws.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for this are clear, but let us reiterate them. The
Dolphins, who are 8-4, already have swept New England, so they are
really two games ahead of the 7-5 Patris because a tie with the
Dolphins at the end of the year is a loss for New England. No
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo already has a win over the Patriots as well and has a
two-game lead in division losses, so even if New England wins the
rematch for a 1-1 split, the Bills would end up a game ahead in
division losses unless someone else helps out the Patriot cause.
Failing that, it means one thing. No playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts are the only division team contending for the playoffs
that New England could sweep, but even so, the Patriots still would
trail Indianapolis by two games with three to play and would be one
game down in division record and two down in conference play. So a
tie with the Colts would lead to _ you guessed it _ no playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, New England must win in Indianapolis or accept
that in three years it has gone from AFC champion to AFC also-ran.
This is not how the no-longer-quite-so-young Patriots see
themselves, but it is how many of the pundits saw them before the
season.
</P>
<P>
   There was much scoffing in New England when many observers of
the NFL scene picked the Patriots to finish fourth (or in some
cases last) and miss the playoffs for the first time in four years.
Yet here it is December, and if the season ended today, they would
be exactly where those experts said they'd end up.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth place and out of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to believe what you guys write in August,'' wise old
Bruce Armstrong said recently, ``but here we are in fourth place
ith a month to go, so you do have to wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes you do, which is at least what will make the Patriots what
fns always hope they will be. It will make them interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Unless they lose in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Then they won't be interesting anymore. They'll be DOA.
</P>
<P>
   As we said, the Super Bowl is coming early in New England. It's
coming in five days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
