<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACHES AND GAINS FOR TED JOHNSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ There were no quick movements as Ted Johnson
methodically got out of his car, put one foot on the ground, then
dragged the other one down to the pavement and slid his hurting
body out of the seat, starting the long walk to the front door
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has moved faster than this before. Most likely he will
again. But this was the morning after his first football game in a
year. It hurt to smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty sore,'' said the Patriots linebacker, whose team
kept alive its playoff hopes with a 13-6 victory over the Dallas
Cowboys Sunday. ``It's been a while since I've felt these aches.
It's a shock to the body to have that kind of contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some respects, I could have played better, but my body
responded well. It didn't shut down on me like I thought I would.
That was good. The offense kept the ball f ite a while. I only had
35 plays, which is very average.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is precisely the number of plays the Patriots had in mind
when they cleared Johnson, who had torn a biceps tendon in training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dramatic night. The Patriots chose to introduce the
dfense to the Foxboro Stadium crowd before the game, and Johnson
was announced last. It was a gesture of respect for him and an
attempt to inspire the crowd and the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was electric out there when Ted was introduced,'' said
defensive lineman Chad Eaton. ``It was like I almost had tears in
my eyes because he's gone through so much and tried so hard to come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Rams linebacker Todd Collins, Johnson's former teammate and a
friend to whom he speaks on a regular basis, had told him not to
come back so quickly. Collins told the Globe a few weeks ago,
``This is his career. He needs to take care of himself and not let
anyone pressure him to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody _ at least a lot of the players _ just said
to me, `Dn't rush it,' '' said Johnson. `` `Don't do anything
stupid.' Family and friends pretty much across the board said the
same thing. I took that into consideration. I know when I'm ready.
I talked to Todd; he said don't rush it. I need to call him today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun being out there,'' said Johnson, who made six
tackles. ``It felt like it always felt. There were things that I
wished I had done better.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was encumbered by a huge arm brace, but he said, ``There
wasn't anything I didn't feel I could d. I was so eager to get in
the flow. I thought they'd run the ball more than they did. I was a
little rusty on my play-action. My reads weren't as clean as they
should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing he looked for was a little contact, and it came
very early, on the Cowboys' first series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how I feel I'm in the flow of the game,'' said Johnson.
``I was looking for a good collision. I got one. They ran a little
trap on me and I got a solid hit on the guard and I felt I was
back, right then and there.''
</P>
<P>
   The brace, which he'll wear for the rest of the season, is very
restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nuisance,'' said Johnson. ``Running isn't easy. Other
than that, I've been working with it for a month now. It's not a
big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was foremost in the coaching staff's thoughts after the
game. In the postgame press conference, coach Pete Carroll
mentioned his ``presence,'' though defensive coordinator Steve
Sidwell took a more cautious outlook and tried to downplay
Johnson's contribution on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said he'd take a two-week approach to evaluate ohnson.
The coach wants to see how Johnson reacts to getting back on the
field for practice Wednesday, after ``looking like he'd been hit by
a truck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
