<HEADLINE>
WITH RAMOS, REVOLUTON HAVE A MIDFIELD LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A &UR;  &LR; soccer team's foundation is established through the middle of
the field. And that is what the Revolution are emphasizing as they
announced the acquisition Monday of Bolivian midfielder Mauricio
Ramos from the Tampa Bay Mutiny in a trade for an allocated player
to be named later.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos, 30, is expected to be the Revolution's midfield
choreographer. He will play in front of defensive midfielder Leonel
Alvarez, with newly-acquired Eduardo Hurtado and Giovanni Savarese
at forwards. The Revolution must yt reinforce their central
defense, butt ganization is clearly changing the direction of the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone we are bringing in is a good player and has the right
attitude to make the team go the way I want it to go,'' coach
Fernando Clavijo said. ``Mauricio is one of the best playmakers in
the league but he hasn't been able to prove it because of the
difficult situation he was in.''
</P>
<P>
   Expectations will be high for Ramos, who played for Bolivia in
the 1994 World Cup finals, but performed in a secondary role to
Carlos Valderrama in Tampa. Ramos is a dynamic playmaker with a
dangerous leftfooted shot from long range. He scored 12 goals in 52
games for the Mutiny after playing for Destroyers, Guabira,
Bolivar, and The Strongest in Bolivia and Cruzeiro in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos, like D.C. United's Marco Etcheverry, is from Santa Cruz
and was developed by the Tahuichi Academy. He was in the starting
lineup in Bolivia's 3-1 loss to Spain in the 1994 World Cup in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a copy of Marco Etcheverry,'' Clavijo said. ``He plays
the same position, he is from the same country, and now he will be
playing for a team which specifically needs a No. 10. He is very
quick, he has great vision, and he makes what seem to be very easy
passes out of nowhere. He is the type of player who can make the
players around him better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos will have an advantage over past Revolution midfield
leaders. Not only does he have the coach's seal of approval, he is
being installed as the team leader long before the start of
training camp, which begins next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to bring in players from abroad,'' said Clajo,
who will be scouting in Portugal this week. ``It is difficult to
adapt to the US. I am filling my needs with people who have been in
the country, who know it is very disciplined here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we need to bring in a defender. If we can find a sweeper,
we can play three in the back, but we need someone with the speed
to cover people and the experience to read the game and ability to
give instruction and direction.''
</P>
<P>
   With prominent roles being filled by foreign players, questions
are raised about the status of John Harkes, who is among the team's
highest-paid performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harkes is still a focal point of the team,'' Clavijo said.
``Everyone will have a role to make the team successful. He is
definitely a key player and he still has many years more to play.
My job as coach is toimprove the team, and there are many other
roles John can play and be helpful to the team. I need to talk to
him about it but I am sure he would be more than happy to play for
a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clavijo will have to decide if it is sensible for Harkes to
be in a complementary role while being paid the salary of a marquee
player. The Revolution have room for one more foreign player on
their roster.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moore finds work
</P>
<P>
   Joe-Max Moore, the Revolution's all-time leading scorer,
received his work permit and could play for Everton at Exeter City
in an FA Cup match Saturday . . . Clavijo was impressed with
20-year-olds Ebbie Kodiat of Boston United and 6-foot-6-inch
Sullivan Phillips of Bermuda during a tryout camp Saturday at
Foxborough. They will likely be among 25 players who will be
invited to return for a combine next month. The Revolution will
probably not consider older players such as Jesus Rolando
Justiniano Rojas, formerly of Oriente Petrolero in Bolivia, and
Liberian national team member Jonathan Sogbie of the Connecticut
Wolves . . . The Boston Bulldogs will continue to tap talent from
El Salvador. Midfielder William Renderos Iraheta, formerly of FAS
and Luis Angel Firpo, will join Elias Montes with the Bulldogs this
season . . . The US will probably meet the Republic of Ireland at
Foxboro Stadium in the US Cup, scheduled June 3-11. Mexico and
South Africa are also in the tournament, which will also be played
in Chicago, New York, and Washington. Ireland has a 1-2-1 record at
Foxboro Stadium, with a victory over Portugal (2-0) June 7, 1992, a
tie with the US (1-1) June 1, 1991, and losses to Italy (2-0) June
4, 1992 and the US (2-1) June 9, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No respect for Italy
</P>
<P>
   Italy could be facing a World Cup 2002 qualifying group of
Germany, Croatia, Slovenia, Georgia, and Belarus. The Italians were
surprisingly not placed at the head of a group for Tuesday's
qualifying draw in Tokyo. In fact, Italy was ranked 12th in Europe
by the bizarre criteria of a nation's performance in qualifying
matches for France '98 and Euro 2000. Previously, seedings had been
determined by how a nation finished in the three previous World Cup
finals. The top European teams are Spain, Romania, Norway, Sweden,
Holland, Czech Republic, Germany, Belgium, and Yugoslavia. A record
197 nations have entered the competition for the finals, scheduled
June 1-30, 2002 in Japan and South Korea. The North Koreans, who
had been invited to participate as a host nation, failed to enter.
Meanwhi, the US will not start qualifying until next October. There
will be three CONCACAF groups, headed by the US, Jamaica, and
Mexico. The top two teams from each group will advance to a final
round-robin, home-and-away playoff for three places in the Cup
finals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
