<SLUG> BC-OLY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC SET TO VOTE ON REFORM PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One year after the Salt Lake City payoff scandal that turned the
International Olympic Committee inside out, the Lords of the Rings
will be voting on a massive reform package in Lausanne,
Switzerland, next weekend dealing with everything from membership
to bid-city visits. Among the 50 recomenatns urged by the special
IOC 2000 commission are a cap of 115 members, an age limit of 70,
eight-year terms, a screening committee for new members, detailed
(and public) financial reports, and stricter control over would-be
Games hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Though nearly everything is expected to be rubber-stamped, two
proposals will be sticky _ a ban on individual visits to bid cities
and a renewable term for the IOC president. What may happen is that
members will have to ask permission to visit a city, with the IOC
footing expenses, and the president will be allowed one additional
term of four or eight years. While the reformwon't satisfy the
harshest critics, who want more outsiders involved, the changes are
still historic by the IOC's insular (and conservative) standards.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blunder down under
</P>
<P>
   Sydney organizers are trying to recover from a public relations
nightmare after secretly holding back hundreds of thousands of
premium seats from the Australian public. Already criticized by the
IOC for high prices, SOCOG had to admit that domestic buyers had
almost no chance to get tickets to the hot events like opening
ceremonies, swimming, and the women's 400 in track, where native
Cathy Freeman is favored. Amid the furor, the organizers have
dumped their ticket manager and released more than a half-million
tickets to the public. As expected, anything the Aussies are good
at _ track and field, swimming, basketball, rowing, cycling, field
hockey _ has been oversubscribed for months. The Australian public
has been guaraeed half of the 10 million tickets . . . More than
100,000 of the 250,000 tickets allocated for Americans are still
available in tour packages from Cartan Tours of Manhattan Beach,
Calif. Figure on paying $5,000 per person at the low end . . .
Though tickets to the premier events in Salt Lake City will be at
Super Bowl levels ($425 the top for hockey and $400 for figure
skating) the average price will be $82, with 78 percent of the 1.6
million tickets less than $100 and 50 percent less than $60. The
organizers are planning to set aside 20 percent for Utah residents
and auction off another 10 percent on the Internet. They aren't
saying what opening ceremonies tickets will go for, but they
promise it'll be less than what Sydney is charging. Sales will
begin next fall . . . Powder (the hare), Copper (the coyote), and
Coal (the bear) are the names of the mascots for the 2002 Winter
Games, chosen from a bunch suggested by Utah schoolchildren . . .
Primo Nebiolo, who died last month at 76 after ruling world track
and field as a dictator for 18 years, went out in Caesarean style.
His coffin was put on a pedestal at Italy's national Olympic
headquarters in a room with murals portraying Roman emperors and
Benito Mussolini, while six athletes stood guard. Though Nebiolo
was widely criticized as Machiavellian and tyrannical (he held up
the master scheduling for both the 1996 and 2000 Olympics to
demonstrate track's primacy), he transformed the sport, for better
and worse, from amateur to professional witworld championships,
prize money, a TV exposure. Lamine Diack, a Senegalese lawyer, is
serving as interim successor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi takes charge
</P>
<P>
   Bela Karolyi, newly named coordinator (but not coach) of the
United States women's gymnastics team, isn't wasting any time
whipping his charges into shape. He will hold an orientation
meeting in Tulsa, Okla., this weekend and a training camp next
month at his woodsy ranch near Houston. And the Olympic hopefuls
can forget about holiday vacations, Karolyi says. Except for
Christmas Eve, Christmas, and New Year's Day, he wants them in the
gym. After placing only sixth at this year's world meet in China,
they're in no position to argue . . . Though she's a full-time
freshman at UCLA, Michelle Kwan found time to qualify for next
month's Grand Prix figure skating finals in France. Kwan, who
didn't compete in the event last year, will be the favorite in a
field that includes four Russians. Tim Goebel will be the only US
male in the field since national champ Michael Weiss, nursing a
stress fracture in an ankle, didn't make the cut. The Americans
didn't qualify in either pairs or dance . . . Season over (and
future uncertain) for US pairs skater Paul Binnebose, who fractured
his skull after falling during a star lift in practice at the end
of September. Binnebose, just released from the hospital, still has
some paralysis and will be rehabbing at home. He and partner Laura
Handy were world team members and likely Olympians . . .
Encouraging showing by the US lugers on the World Cup circuit so
far.Mrk Grimmette and Brian Martin are second in the doubles
standings, Becky Wilczak is eighth on the women's list, where
Westborough's Ashley Hayden ranks 17th, and Adam Heidt is 10th on
the men's. Italy's Armin Zoegeller is tearing up the overall men's
standings with four victories in four races and the German women,
as usual, are dominating behind Sylke Otto. Meanwhile, Duncan
Kennedy, the best luger in US history, appears to be finished. He's
abandoned his comeback after dizziness and nausea from brain-stem
bleeding recurred during training. The 31-year-old Kennedy won 21
World Cup medals during his two-decade career, but none at Olympus
. . . Why did Winchester bobsleder Jim Herberich call it a career
last month? After 14 years and three Olympics, ``it was an
appropriate time to retire,'' said Herberich, who was the top US
finisher (seventh in the two-man) at the Nagano Olympics and
already had made the World Cup team for this season. His former
teammates have yet to make the medal stand in two races. The US
women, meanwhile, ruled their Cup opener in Calgary with drivers
Jean Racine and Jill Bakken swapping off 1-2 on the two-day event.
They don't have another Cup race until the end of January . . .
Next up for the US women's hockey team are games at Princeton,
Harvard (Dec. 17), and Dartmouth (Dec. 18) before a post-Christmas
tournament against the Russians and Swedes in Lake Placid, N.Y.
They'll spend January and February training in Walpole and playing
exhibitions before the world championships in Toronto in April . .
. The US men's volleyball tam just missed qualifying for the
lympics last week despite beating world champion Italy at the World
Cup in Japan. A stunning loss to the South Koreans and Cuba's upset
of the Italians did in the Yanks, who can still get a ticket to
Sydney by winning the regional qualifier next month in Winnipeg,
Manitoba. The US women, who ended up ninth, get another shot, too.
Russia, Cuba, and Italy earned the automatic men's berths; Russia,
Cuba, and Brazil earned the women's . . . Only one medal for the US
_ a bronze from 16-year-old Cheryl Haworth _ at the recent world
weightlifting championships in Athens. The Americans earned the
full four Olympic slots for women but only two for men.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from interviews, wire services, the US Olympic committee,
and sports federations was used to compile this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
