<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPLORING THE `MAGIC NEGRO' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood dearly loves its cliches.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how shopworn they may be, there are certain tried,
tested and tired devices writers and directors just can't seem to
resist. Hence, just because we've seen a zillion mismatched buddies
in action comedies _ such as the Mel Gibson-Danny Glover ``Lethal
Weapon'' films _ it doesn't mean Hollywood isn't going to keep
cranking them out _ like the more recent ``Rush Hour,'' which
starred Chris Tucker and Jackie Chan.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same old thing with some characters. There's the dumpy
wisecracking gay best friend (see Nathan Lane); the debonair
wisecracking gay best friend (see Rupert Everett); and, of course,
the wisecracking not-as-attractive best friend, usually a woman,
who makes the lead actress look that much better (see Rosie
O'Donnell).
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the ``Magic Negro.''
</P>
<P>
   I first heard a variation of this term after seeing the film
``Clara's Heart'' with a friend about a decade ago. In this 1988
drama, Whoopi Goldberg played a Jamaican maid who transforms the
lives of a well-to-do white Maryland family. The family is
completely falling apart until Clara, with her honeyed patois and
no-nonsense emotions, comes on the scene to set everything right.
It's a backbreakingly earnest, and irritating film, which led my
friend to utter a phrase I never forgot:
</P>
<P>
   ``Damn, I can't stand them `magic (Negro)' movies,'' she hissed,
although in the heat of the moment, she didn't use the word
``Negro.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a Washington Post film critic, Stephen Hunter, used
the term to lambaste ``American History X.'' In that film, Edward
Norton starred as Derek Vinyard, a virulent neo-Nazi skinhead who,
after being imprisoned for murdering two young black men, is
converted to goodness and light by a fellow inmate, a black man.
While complimenting Guy Torry's role as Derek's savior, he skewered
the part as ``a lie from start to finish; it reflects a secret
bigotry that sees black people only in terms of what they can do
for white people, but has no other interest in them.''
</P>
<P>
   I found myself thinking about this at a recent screening of
``The Green Mile,'' which opens Friday. The film, based on a
best-selling six-part Stephen King novel, stars Tom Hanks as a
death-row guard in a 1930s Louisiana penitentiary, and Michael
Clarke Duncan as a hulking black man who is possessed of
extraordinary healing powers, but is condemned to death for the
murders of two little white girls. He can barely spell his name,
but he spends much of his time healing white people, at the drop of
a hat.
</P>
<P>
   (A celluloid flip side of the Magic Negro is the White Savior,
wherein a white crusader manages to save all the cowering black
folks from really, really bad white people, as seen in such films
as ``Mississippi Burning'' or ``Ghosts of Mississippi.'')
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there have been such characterizations at least since
the 1950s, when Hollywood put its hand over its liberal heart and
pledged to create films designed to teach white moviegoers all
sorts of nice things about black folks in general, and race
relations in particular. So we got films like ``The Defiant Ones,''
with Sidney Poitier and Tony Curtis as escaped convicts shackled
together, and Ethel Waters dispensing advice to Julie Harris in
``Member of the Wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, and these ``Touched by a Negro'' films are
still with us. There was last year's ``Shadrach,'' with John
Franklin Sawyer as the title character, a 99-year-old former slave
who returns to 1930s Virginia to be buried on the plantation where
he was born. Of course before he dies, he teaches a young white boy
about about life, death and the resilience of the human spirit. And
it's much of the same in Whoopi Goldberg's maid trilogy _ ``Clara's
Heart,'' ``The Long Walk Home'' (1990), and ``Corrina, Corrina
(1994). All of these films reduced its black characters to
walking-and-talking totems of kindness, understanding, and means to
heal the white soul of whatever ails it.
</P>
<P>
   And lest anyone forget, in such films the black character, for
all his or her saintliness, is often in a subservient position _ as
maid, as ex-slave or, in the case of ``The Green Mile,'' a man
awaiting a date with Old Sparky.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in its haste to counter negative stereotypes, Hollywood
overcorrects, and creates simple _ and simple-minded _ characters _
who are just as offensive. Despite their unfailing goodness, they
lack complexity, nuance, and the two things they seem so eager to
share _ heart and soul. While the idea may be well-intentioned,
black characters who exist solely for the betterment of their white
counterparts, are at best laughable, and at worse cloyingly
conscending.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes in Hollywood, even when its heart is in the right
place, its mind is out to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
