<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-LAWYER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER RESCUES DEBTORS IN DISTRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As consumers find themselves getting buried under an avalanche
of holiday credit-card debt, Andrew F. Capoccia sounds almost too
good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   A smooth-talking lawyer who rails with religious fervor about
the predatory practices of the nation's giant credit-card
companies, Capoccia promises to slash the debt of each client by 50
percent to 70 percent or more and help them steer clear of
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   His strategy for his clients is as blunt as a bare knuckle: Stop
making even minimum payments to the credit-card giants, sue the
companies if they violate the law, and starve them into submission.
For his services, Capoccia takes a fee of 28 percent of whatever he
saves the customer.
</P>
<P>
   Credit-card companies are not known for rolling over, but many
have decided that it's smarter to settle for 30 cents to 50 cents
on the dollar rather than tangle endlessly with Capoccia or see the
debtor end up in bankruptcy with the entire debt wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, we're a consumer-protection firm that says
negotiate first and, if that doesn't work, file bankruptcy,'' said
the 57-year-old Capoccia. ``Before we came along, it was a
slam-dunk for the creditors.''
</P>
<P>
   Capoccia's tactics are hardly novel, but he has taken them to
new heights. He estimates that he has saved his clients $21 million
so far this year, a figure that would net him nearly $5.9 million
in fees.
</P>
<P>
   In less than three years his business has grown from three
employees to 150, and now he is starting to expand outside his
Albany, N.Y., base. He opened a clinic last month in Cambridge,
Mass. and soon hopes to go national. If Congress approves a pending
bill that would make it more difficult to file for bankruptcy, his
business could explode. Capoccia is helped by the industry's
practice of sending out increasing numbers of card applications
each year _ a total of 3.5 billion in 1998, according to the
Consumer Federation of America.
</P>
<P>
   But his success also has drawn controversy. Some debt
specialists question whether Capoccia's debt-reduction program is
in every client's best interest. Richard Hackel, a consumer
bankruptcy attorney from Boston, said the impact of Capoccia's
program on a customer's credit would not be that much different
from a bankruptcy, yet with a bankruptcy the consumer's entire
unsecured debt could be wiped out at less cost and under court
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement and judicial officials also are attacking his
tactics. New York Attorney General Eliot Spitzer sued Capoccia last
month, charging him with deceptive advertising and making false
claims. Several New York judges have imposed sanctions on him
exceeding $1 million for filing what they consider frivolous
lawsuits. And the sanctions have spurred the Committee on
Professional Standards, New York's lawyer-disciplinary body, to
charge him with misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Capoccia is no stranger to the Committee on Professional
Standards. Twice before, while a divorce attorney and a personal
injury lawyer, he was suspended briefly from the practice of law.
The last time, in 1988, it was for depositing checks owed to a
client into his own escrow account. In 1989, Capoccia also was
warned to tone down his ads, which characterized him as a ``smart
tough lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Capoccia said there is no pattern of wrongdoing here. He said he
is at war now with the New York legal establishment because of his
crusade against credit-card companies. He has countersued Spitzer,
appealed the sanctions (pointing out that the judge who imposed the
heftiest fines formerly worked for a law firm specializing in debt
collection) and forced the disciplinary body to open its
proceedings to public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious that Capoccia is seen as a tremendous threat to
the way business has been conducted in New York,'' said his Boston
attorney, Harvey Silverglate.
</P>
<P>
   When a client signs on with Capoccia, the firm's first action is
to notify every creditor that the client is now represented by
counsel and that direct contact with the client is no longer
permitted. Capoccia urges clients to document any creditor contact
and sues the creditors if they violate the law.
</P>
<P>
   Capoccia also demands a mountain of information from every
creditor and then combs through the documents looking for errors
that would invalidate some or all of the debt. Capoccia said he is
not trying to get his clients off on technicalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't write these laws,'' he said. ``We just use them.''
</P>
<P>
   The typical customer is someone with a job who is struggling to
make the minimum payments on anywhere from four to a dozen credit
cards. Capoccia's staff estimates how much the debt can be reduced
and the firm's fee, and then starts drawing from the client's bank
account on a monthly basis to raise the necessary funds. Then the
waiting game begins.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Scott of Buffalo, who works in the cardiac-care department
at a local hospital, said she was paying somewhere between $300 and
$400 a month and wasn't making a dent in her $7,000 debt. After
signing on with Capoccia in July 1998, she started to pay $209 a
month into an escrow fund.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen months later she settled with her creditors, paying
them a total of $2,279. She also paid Capoccia's firm a fee of
$1,192.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything they said came true,'' she said. ``Now I feel free
in my own home. Before, I was a prisoner.''
</P>
<P>
   David Smith of Delmar, N.Y., who got into financial trouble when
his wife quit her job as their son began kidney dialysis, said it
took him just over two years to complete the Capoccia program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think their debts will magically disappear, but
that's not reality,'' said Smith. ``It took years to create the
debt, and it's going to take some time to get rid of it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Capoccia, creditors settle with him 90 percent of
the time. He even has lucrative standing settlement agreements with
some creditors. Collect America, a company that buys uncollected
debt from credit-card companies, has agreed to settle with Capoccia
for 50 cents on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   On an annual basis, Collect America is handling about $2 million
in debt with Capoccia. That means Collect America takes in $1
million, Capoccia's customers save $1 million, and Capoccia gets
$280,000, or 28 percent of the savings, mostly for processing
paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Klein, a consumer credit specialist with the National
Consumer Law Center in Boston, said Capoccia is filling a need.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are hundreds of thousands of families out there who are
looking for help with their debts,'' he said. ``If he's able to get
good agreements, more power to him.''
</P>
<P>
   David Herwitz, a law professor at Harvard University who has
signed on as an ombudsman for Capoccia's firm, said he has had few
complaints to deal with so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have formed a favorable impression of him,'' said Herwitz.
``I think the courts in New York have gone mad with the sanctions
and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The drawback to Capaccio's approach is that, as consumers wait
for settlement agreements with their creditors, their credit
reports take a beating. They get hit with late fees, higher
interest rates, delinquencies, and court judgments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a difficult way to go about it,'' said Debbie Eaton,
senior vice president at the Consumer Credit Counseling Service of
Southern New England, a program set up by credit-card companies to
help consumers shed their debt.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Fisher, of Solomon &AMP; Solomon in Albany, who represents
Citibank and other major credit-card companies, said Capoccia may
not fully inform clients that many companies won't settle on the
cheap and will pursue court judgments that can garnish wages and
place liens on homes.
</P>
<P>
   Capoccia, who noted that all of the risks are spelled out in the
legal representation agreements clients are required to sign, said
he is helping clients who want to avoid bankruptcy and attack their
debt head-on. He said credit-counseling services, such as Eaton's,
fail because they never attack the principal of a client's debt,
only the interest costs going forward.
</P>
<P>
   While Capoccia's clients may take a beating on their credit
report, there often is no permanent damage. Six Capoccia clients
interviewed by the Globe said their credit rating suffered in the
debt-reduction program, but that did not stop credit-card companies
from continuing to mail them preapproved credit-card applications,
convenience checks, or home-equity-loan applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the sick part about all this,'' said Edward Ruede of
Albany. ``I've learned to live without credit cards. It's like
going cold turkey on heroin. But the companies keep pushing credit
at you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
