<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFECT PRESENTS FOR WORDY FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do clone, smog, and solar heating have in common? All three
words were first recorded in _ can you guess? _ the year 1903,
according to John Ayto's ``Twentieth Century Words,'' a timely
compendium of the century's lexical innovations from Oxford
University Press ($25).
</P>
<P>
   (Sure, the Greenwich Observatory says the century rolls on for
one more year, but publishers know better than to let scientists
dictate their schedules. Any potential turn-of-the-whatever gift
book has to be out there competing in the '99 holiday marketplace _
and if we celebrate again next year, so much the better.)
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly indexed, as a good reference book should be,
``Twentieth Century Words'' is also eminently browsable. With
chapters arranged by decades, it's a review of history through the
lens of English: Word by word, new terms spring up to meet the
needs of the times. A page from the '40s gives us telethon,
terrorist, and thought police; the '80s bring policy wonks,
post-feminists, and Prozac. Often there are surprises: People were
still dancing the hully gully (1964) when someone coined hypertext,
now familiar from the Web's HTML, or ``hypertext markup language.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everything worthy, of course, can fit into a 600-page
volume. Science fiction furnishes William Gibson's cyberspace and
John Wyndham's triffids, but Robert Heinlein's grok doesn't make
the cut. Sociologist Robert K. Merton's ingenious self-fulfilling
prophecy is missing, but Richard Rosen's psychobabble is here.
Nobody will feel shortchanged, though, not even millennial
hard-liners: Since the book starts with the year 1900, it supplies
100 years' worth of words, even without the novelties 2000 is sure
to bring.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for a splashier gift, the ultimate word book,
of course, is the Oxford English Dictionary. But even deep-pocketed
gift givers have some tough decisions to make about format. For
someone with plenty of shelf space and no computer, the 20-volume
dead-tree edition is a real deal this year at $995 list, down from
the regular $3,000. Plus shipping charges, of course, and the visit
to the chiropractor after you've lugged the packages into the
house.
</P>
<P>
   Or there's the CD-ROM version, only $395 and (for some of us,
anyway) more gratifying than any Tiffany trinket or Rolex
``timepiece'' could be. Even partisans of the printed word are
suckers for this disk, which offers instant access to definitions
and quotations in big, readable type _ and weighs less than your
cell phone, too. ``Word heaven,'' one blissed-out user called it,
though heaven must wait till spring if you're a Mac user; for now,
it runs on Windows only.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the OED is planning a great leap Netward in March _
will the on-line version be even more wonderful? Yes, in that it
will be updated regularly; no, perhaps, for someone whose Internet
service is spotty or slow. And promise a subscription only if you
can write a blank check; rates have not yet been set, according to
the publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Another gift you can promise, but not yet deliver, is Barbara
Wallraff's ``Word Court,'' due next month from Harcourt Brace
($25). Inspired by Wallraff's Atlantic Monthly column of the same
name, ``Word Court'' builds on the magazine's advice-column format
but makes room for more leisurely excursions into jargon,
diagramming, and a host of other word byways. I've already
photocopied her lucid discussion of why English allows us to say
``When baby boomers' joints start to go, so does their identity''
without sweating number agreement; Wallraff picks her way through
such language thickets with a sure step and a generous attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Until ``Court'' is in session, you can while away the hours with
William Safire's 11th collection of columns, ``Spread the Word''
(love that title!), $26 from Times Books. Even regular Safire
readers have reason to check out the books, which allow space for
letters from readers _ including such worthies as Alistair Cooke
and Jacques Barzun. ``Spread the Word,'' incidentally, marks
Safire's 20th year in what he calls the language dodge.
</P>
<P>
   For the ambitious readers who make up Steven Pinker's following,
this year's treat is ``Words and Rules'' (Basic Books, $26), a
return to the territory of his 1994 bestseller, ``The Language
Instinct.'' In ``Words and Rules,'' Pinker homes in on irregular
verbs to illuminate the way language works. Our treatment of
irregulars, he says, shows how we combine a store of memorized
words, using the rules of ``mental grammar,'' to create an infinite
variety of linguistic expression. Not everyone agrees with Pinker's
model, but you don't have to take sides to enjoy his elegant, funny
prose. You do have to pay attention: This is a tightly argued book,
with less room for pure entertainment than ``The Language
Instinct.'' If you liked that book, this is next year's course, as
it were. But give it to someone who dreams of going back to school,
not the callow graduate who has just fled academia without a
backward look.
</P>
<P>
   If the callow youth is off to a job, say ``Yes, Virginia'' (or
Victor), ``there still are rules about writing clearly'' _ and wrap
up a copy of Becky Burckmyer's ``Why Does My Boss Hate My
Writing?'' (Adams, $9). Despite the unfortunate title, Burckmyer's
book is what the revised ``Elements of Style'' should have been _ a
readable, practical guide that doesn't waste your time with
gimmicks, vampires, or excessive puns. Burckmyer's simple strategy
for checking parallel structure, for instance, is a trick many
journalists could profit by. And the book goes beyond grammar to
help novices compose smart memos and business letters. I've got
several giftees in mind _ but I'm keeping a copy for myself.
</P>
<P>
   Ready for some wordplay, after all that work? Several of the
year's books lend themselves to entertainment, even to parlor
games. We took Merriam-Webster's Dictionary of Allusions ($15), by
Elizabeth Webber and Mike Feinsilber, on a vacation with friends
this fall, and we had a fine time quizzing one another on the
Battle of Hastings, the Heisenberg principle, and Heloise
(Abelard's girlfriend, not the mistress of household hints).
</P>
<P>
   You can do the same thing with ``The Big Book of Beastly
Mispronunciations'' (Houghton Mifflin, $15), a combined and
expanded version of Charles Harrington Elster's earlier ``There Is
No Zoo in Zoology'' and ``Is there a Cow in Moscow?'' (there is).
Nobody reads Elster without an occasional howl of disbelief: Do I
really have to put two syllables in mirror, abandoning my
Midwestern dialect? At least Elster allows that route is right
either way _ ROOT or ROWT _ and I've noticed with satisfaction that
techies talk Midwestern when they say mail router, pronouncing it
ROWTER, like the woodworking tool.
</P>
<P>
   Elster likes to argue, so it's satisfying to be able to argue
back: He wants the last syllable of bouillabaisse pronounced BASE,
but my dictionary and I like the Frenchier BESS (we agree it's
never BAZE). While he's threading his way through the pronunciation
maze, though, he loses sight of spelling, so the entry reads, big
and bold, bouillabase. Paging Houghton Mifflin: Is there a
proofreader in the house?
</P>
<P>
   Prefer baseball to bouillabaisse? The year also brought The New
Dickson Baseball Dictionary ($35 hardcover, $20 paper), a
substantial revision of Paul Dickson's guide to the game's language
and lore. I wish this book had been around last year, when we were
wondering why Robin Williams had fondly referred to South Boston as
``a can of corn.'' Even Dickson can't explain what Williams meant,
but he knows everything else about the possible origins of can of
corn (a high fly ball that's easy to catch) and many another
baseball term.
</P>
<P>
   Lovers of wordplay are mourning the master of the game, Willard
R. Espy, who died in February, but his work lives on: ``The Best of
An Almanac of Words at Play'' (Merriam-Webster, $20), a new
compilation from his classic ``Words at Play'' volumes. This
collection of puzzles, palindromes, and other linguistic diversions
makes a fine introduction for an Espy novice, and it's supposed to
last all year. But don't be surprised if the recipient skips and
browses; Espy gratification can be hard to delay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jan Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write to her
at The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. Please
include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
