<HEADLINE>
VIDEO LETS JUDGES PRESIDE FROM AFAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The image of a federal judge sitting in Boston is
beamed into a courtroom 3,000 miles away in Phoenix, where lawyers
appearing in front of a television screen argue over the copyright
to a horror movie and whether tons of pet food were contaminated by
tainted wheat.
</P>
<P>
   It's an exercise that tests the limits of technology and
long-distance justice, while helping some of the nation's busiest
courts clear their crowded dockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to go to virtual courtrooms,'' said Chief US
District Judge William G. Young, who is presiding over the Arizona
cases from a Boston courtroom. ``I much prefer that trials take
place with judges in a courtroom. But these people in Arizona are
waiting to get justice in their cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Video conferencing, which so far has been restricted mainly to
bankruptcy proceedings and civil pretrial hearings involving
prisoners, may soon result in the first complete video trial in
federal court in Boston, as some of the 20 civil cases transferred
from Arizona edge toward trial. It would make Boston one of a small
number of federal courts around the country to hold video trials.
</P>
<P>
   While Young said he wouldn't try a jury trial via video because
he strongly believes that juries and judges must interact directly,
he said many jury-waived cases built mainly on documents could
easily be tried in a remote courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of what might be called paper cases,'' said
Young, noting that one Arizona case he is handling involves a
dispute over how much it cost to repair the roof of a commercial
building.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen McNamee, chief judge of the US District Court in
Arizona, said judges in the Phoenix division carry an average
caseload of 500 civil cases and 100 criminal cases, while those in
the Tucson division shoulder about 250 criminal cases and 100 civil
cases.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, federal judges in Massachusetts have an average
caseload of about 250 civil and 28 criminal cases, according to
statistics compiled by the administrative office for the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Young credits the low caseload in Massachusetts _ the 13th
lowest in the country last year _ to the fact that there are 14
sitting judges in the district and no vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, federal courts along the southern border of the
United States are clogged with criminal drug and immigration cases,
causing many civil cases to languish on dockets for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a huge problem with our border courts. They are
overwhelmed,'' said Karen Redmond, a spokeswoman for the
Administrative Office of the US Courts in Washington. ``We have
fewer resources. Congress is definitely encouraging us to do more
video conferencing.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven federal courts have video conferencing capability,
according to Redmond, and officials are considering revising
regulations on the use of video in criminal proceedings. While
video trials are prohibited in criminal cases under federal
regulations, there is a move to use video in some criminal pretrial
hearings. Still, the biggest push for video conferencing is in
civil cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have litigation that spans the globe, this type of
technology will have to come to the forefront because of the cost
factor,'' McNamee said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton signed a bill last week that allows for the
appointment of four more federal judges in Florida, three in
Arizona, and two in Nevada, but it will take time for nominations
and confirmations.
</P>
<P>
   For the past eight years, McNamee said, the federal court in
Arizona has been transferring blocks of 20 cases to other judges in
the Ninth Circuit, which includes Alaska, Arizona, California,
Hawaii, Idaho, Montana, Nevada, Oregon, and Washington, as well as
Guam and the Northern Mariana islands.
</P>
<P>
   Most civil cases settle before trial, but in cases that do not,
the out-of-state judges have traditionally traveled to Phoenix or
Tucson to conduct trials.
</P>
<P>
   When Young volunteered to help, McNamee said, it was agreed to
try to save money by using video conferencing as much as possible,
rather than have Young travel to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were curious to see how it was going to
work,'' said attorney Randy Wahl of Scottsdale, Ariz., who
represents two screenplay writers who filed suit in June 1998
against a production company for copyright infringement of a horror
movie.
</P>
<P>
   During a video conference in Phoenix, Wahl said Young's face
appeared on a small television screen in the courtroom, creating,
``a virtual-type judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it seemed a bit strange at first, Wahl said his clients
are happy because the case is moving swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas G. Ryan, a Phoenix attorney who represents a wheat
supplier being sued by a pet food company, said his 1995 case
languished before being assigned to Young this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a virtual guy, but I think it's a good idea,
especially for the pretrial aspects of the case,'' said Ryan, who
has practiced law for 24 years. ``What you sacrifice in spontaneity
has more than been made up for in efficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Young listens to lawyers in Phoenix in Judge Nancy
Gertner's high-tech courtroom, which is equipped with several large
television monitors and computer screens that broadcast the
lawyers' arguments to monitors on the judge's bench, the clerk's
desk, the court reporter's desk, and the jury box.
</P>
<P>
   Other federal judges in Massachusetts, including Gertner and US
District Judge George O'Toole, have offered to take cases from
overwhelmed districts. Florida is awaiting final approval to send
federal cases to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously everyone's first preference is to be in the
courtroom with everyone present,'' said McNamee. ``But given the
cost and the crowded court dockets, that's just not always
possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
