<SLUG> BC-CHINA-VILLAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CHANGING TIMES, A LOST HERITAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Sidebar with China-Women)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HE YUAN, China _ Stepping onto the flagstone path that winds
between the ancient houses nestled cheek-by-jowl in He Yuan village
is like a journey back in time.
</P>
<P>
   The pathway is plied not by cars but by puppies, chickens, and
children. Elderly people whose mouths have never met a toothbrush
gather in dim courtyards to gamble with handmade cards, using
sunflower seeds as chips. At first glance, He Yuan seems unchanged
since medieval times.
</P>
<P>
   But something is different. Here in one of two villages where
the women's-only Nushu script was ``discovered'' in the 1950s,
there are no young women left. Relatives explain that nearly every
female between the ages of 15 and 30 has gone to a town or city for
schooling or for lucrative jobs in offices or bars. They send money
home, but have no intention of moving back.
</P>
<P>
   In a bare stone house at the end of the path lives He Yanxin,
60, one of three women alive known to read and write Nushu. Her
daughters were not interested in learning, because Nushu songs
``sounded like crying. `It's terrible, so sad,' they said. `Why do
you sing like that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   He, who still comforts herself by singing Nushu songs, tried to
tell them that the script was a way of venting boredom or
loneliness that women could not otherwise express. But her
daughters could not relate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls now go to school, they work. It's meaningless for
them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Like He's daughters, other young women from the Nushu villages
see no need for the script. Chen Meijun, 22, who came to Jiangyong
city to work as an accountant, laments that a valuable piece of her
heritage is dying. But she admits she never thought of asking her
grandmother to teach her.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang Yau, 21, a karaoke bar owner, was one of the girls chosen
to learn Nushu songs for a video made by Chinese Television for a
1995 women's conference in Beijing. She has since forgotten the
songs, and says that with no practical use for Nushu, girls today
will not study it.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that the language was on the verge of extinction, the
government tried to start a Nushu class a few years ago and printed
some textbooks. But there were not enough resources or takers.
</P>
<P>
   A researcher, Zhou Shuoyi, said Nushu must be preserved because
it is ``the written history of our women's fight for equality.'' He
suggests drumming up interest among tourists and locals by selling
Nushu crafts and scrolls. But others, like Yang Huangyi, the oldest
surviving woman who knows Nushu, said Nushu's death may be a good
thing; it proves how far women have come.
</P>
<P>
   ``If girls don't want to use it now,'' she said with a shrug,
``let them be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 1420EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1718 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CAMPAIGN-COST08-COX     12-07 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-COST08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE, FIRST LADY FREQUENT FLYER MILES BILLED TO TAXPAYERS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hillary Rodham Clinton breakfasted with black
clergy in New York City, then jetted over to Buffalo for lunch and
back to Great Neck for dinner, as she toured the state she wants to
represent in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   On that same day, Nov. 30, Vice President Al Gore was pumping
hands and giving speeches in three New Hampshire cities on his 20th
visit this year to the first-in-the-nation presidential primary
state.
</P>
<P>
   As both pursued their political ambitions, taxpayers were
footing most of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Because the first lady and vice president travel aboard military
aircraft, accompanied by official staff and guarded by Secret
Service agents, their dozens of campaign trips this year cost tens
of thousands of dollars apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Although their campaigns reimburse the U.S. Treasury for some of
the expenses, the repayments don't come close to the total cost.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Mrs. Clinton generally flies aboard a version of
the C-20, similar to a Gulfstream corporate jet. The cost to
operate it is $4,059 an hour, said Sgt. Dan Neely, spokesman for
Andrews Air Force Base, Md., which oversees the presidential fleet.
Expense for the crew is extra, but the Air Force does not calculate
the amount.
</P>
<P>
   Gore usually takes the larger C-32A, similar to a Boeing 757,
which costs $10,000 an hour to fly, according to the Air Force
estimates, again not including the expense of the crew. At that
rate, just one of Gore's 10 trips to vote-rich California this year
costs a minimum $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Yet following rules set down in 1982 by the Reagan
administration, officials are required to pay only the equivalent
of a first-class ticket for themselves and their campaign aides for
political trips. If a trip includes official events such as
announcing federal grants, the government can be charged for all or
nearly all the travel costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reimbursement by politicians for their travel has always been
frankly ridiculous, and a little bit of a wink and a nod routine by
all these folks,'' says Charles Lewis, who heads the non-partisan
Center for Public Integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, the party out of the White House has usually
withheld criticism of the practice of traveling on the public dime,
since both parties have long taken advantage of the practice.
</P>
<P>
   However, Republicans are now trying to make the frequent flying
by Gore and Mrs. Clinton an issue. They lampooned the first lady's
11 visits to New York in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the Republicans criticized Gore when his aides
acknowledged that they were seeking out official events and
announcements around the country so that he could conserve his
campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides insist they are going by the book when it
comes to travel.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Gore travels with a government-paid entourage
including a personal aide, secretary, doctor, photographer,
military aide and Secret Service detail. All have been cleared by
the legal counsel as essential, said Gore spokeswoman Melissa
Radcliff.
</P>
<P>
   In the first lady's case, no clear precedent exists, since no
presidential wife has ever before run for public office.
</P>
<P>
   She travels aboard military aircraft because the Secret Service
prefers that method for security, said press secretary Marsha
Berry. Mrs. Clinton takes an official photographer and a trip
director as well as her security detail on trips, all paid for by
public funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``She follows the rules that the (Federal Election Commission)
has in place for anyone in the situation she's in,'' Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that the first lady had no plans to change her travel
practices now that she has removed the name ``exploratory'' from
her Senate campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republican rivals, although cautious in their direct attacks,
have positioned themselves on the high ground when it comes to
travel.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 30, when Mrs. Clinton was flying around New York, her
apparent rival for the Senate, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
was visiting Texas, raising money and conferring with Republican
front-runner Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the expenses being incurred on this trip are being paid
for by the campaign committee,'' said his press secretary Bruce
Deidelbaum.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to say how Giuliani was traveling on his Texas trip.
The mayor has in the past used corporate jets, which companies make
available to politicians, who are required to pay only the
equivalent of first-class fare.
</P>
<P>
   Several presidential candidates, including Republican Sens. John
McCain of Arizona and Orrin Hatch of Utah and Democrat Bill
Bradley, have also availed themselves of corporate aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The practice has brought charges of conflicts of interest and
influence peddling.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has avoided that controversy. The governor flies by
Gulfstream jets chartered by his campaign, which is flush with
cash. Bush has not flown on a Texas-owned aircraft since last
spring, when he addressed a college commencement in the state,
spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Bush has forgone his governor's salary on days when he
campaigns for president. As of the end of November, he had given up
pay for 49 days for a total of $15,489, Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has not been cost-free for Texas taxpayers.
The bill for ``executive security'' has gone up to $1.8 million
this year, a ninefold increase over the average annual cost before
Bush began his presidential quest.
</P>
<P>
   The figures were released by the Texas Department of Public
Safety after a freedom-of-information request by the
Austin-American Statesman and other news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Security costs for the vice president and first lady are
classified secrets that have never been made public. Nor are the
total travel costs for to officials ever fully disclosed, to the
frustration of groups such as Lewis's Center for Public Integrity,
which conducted an investigation of the costs for President
Clinton's 1996 campaign travels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never got a good, straight answer out of anybody,'' Lewis
said. ``Every day we should know what they are spending, if it's
taxpayer money.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Lewis: ``They get away with it because other politicians,
including Clinton, have.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
