<HEADLINE>
ROCKETTES KICK OFF CHRISTMAS SPECTACULAR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The holiday season is a time for nostalgia, and anyone whoever
bundled up against the Eastern cold and headed into New York City
for seasonal entertainment can summon those warm fuzzy feelings
with the latest edition of the ``Radio City Christmas
Spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a few new elements to the program, but the fixtures
that have been there for decades, ``The Parade of the Wooden
Soldiers'' and ``The Living Nativity,'' among others, are as
impressive as ever.
</P>
<P>
   This company of 18 Rockettes is as sharp as the New York City
crew has always been, from the first kickline in the opening number
to the ragdoll dance in the ``Santa's Workshop'' scene. Its
precision in the wooden-soldiers routine is remarkable,
particularly in its ending.
</P>
<P>
   Radio City makes a tame concession to current pop culture with
``Santa's Gonna Rock,'' which includes a rapping elf.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, the show is a throwback to the June Taylor and
Ernest Flatt dance troupes that charmed TV audiences in the '60s
and '70s, especially in its ``We Need a Little Christmas'' and
``Christmas in New York'' numbers. It's probably Radio City's
strong sense of tradition that keeps the show a few decades behind
the rest of live entertainment. After all, who'd pay to see Santa
Claus surfing a mosh pit of tattooed and pierced Rockettes?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Santa, the big guy really anchors this production,
bridging the numbers and appearing in nearly every scene but the
Living Nativity. Brad Oscar has donned the red suit and lends his
pleasant baritone to several songs.
</P>
<P>
   In a production made up of show-stoppers, ``Santa's Workshop''
stands out, particularly the r&AMP;b-flavored singing-and-dancing
poinsettias and Christmas trees. It also features the raggedy
Rockettes who, at one point, apply their precise timing to tapping
out ``Jingle Bells'' on the xylophone strapped to the back of their
nearest dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from the musicians' union, and no doubt some
ticketholder complaints, Radio City has brought in a live orchestra
for this year's show. The live sound is definitely better than
canned music, but the band unfortunately has been tucked into a
curtained alcove on the left side ofthe auditorium so the
traditional ``pit'' position can be used for VIP seating. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The show: ``Radio City Christmas Spectacular.'' &QL; 
Where: Universal Amphitheatre, Universal City. &QL; 
When: Through Dec. 28. &QL; 
Tickets: Tickets range from $22.50 to $63.50 and are available at
the Universal Amphitheatre box offices and Ticketmaster locations,
or by calling Ticketmaster at (213) 252-7497. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
