<HEADLINE>
IN CHINA, AN OLD WRITTEN WORD IS DYING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With sidebar, China-Village)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JIANGYONG, China _ For hundreds or perhaps thousands of years,
women in this remote pocket of southern China have shared a
remarkable secret.
</P>
<P>
   Legend holds that it began with a concubine of a Song Dynasty
emperor who was so lonely in the palace that she devised a way to
write letters about sorrows that only friends and family could
read.
</P>
<P>
   Men may joke that women share a language that men cannot
understand, but in Jiangyong County, a rural community of 230,000
people, that was literally the case.
</P>
<P>
   But now, it is on the verge of disappearing. As Chinese women
got schooling and freedom, women here have seen little need to
maintain Nushu, or ``women's script.'' Only three women still are
known to read and write Nushu, and what may be the world's only
women's written language will probably die with them. Even if
scholars preserve the texts, the language will become a fossil.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that, after centuries when authorities might have
wanted to stamp out the language, the cash-strapped local
government now wants to preserve Nushu as cultural heritage and a
tourist draw. But with no money to teach it _ and no interest in
learning it _ an extraordinary legacy that survived for perhaps two
millennia may last only a few years into the next one.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the oldest remaining woman who knows Nushu lives
quietly in a brick, stable-like dormitory of a grapefruit orchard.
She farms as she always has, writes Nushu poems, and sings them for
the occasional visitor who makes the five-hour drive by a sometimes
bumpy dirt road from the nearest airport.
</P>
<P>
   Yang Huangyi is 92, and her tiny, deformed feet _ bound when she
was a child in the fetish tradition of imperial times _ are a
testament to past inequities between men and women. Yang's
sun-bronzed face is still astonishingly beautiful and seems
permanently creased in a broad smile.
</P>
<P>
   She digs into a plastic bucket where she stores her notebooks
and crinkles her nose as she begins to sing, her voice vibrating in
a plaintive, longing lament not unlike some American Indian chants.
The lyrics are about a husband who goes to town for a job, leaving
his new wife alone and miserable.
</P>
<P>
   The script is simple and abstract compared to Chinese;
characters resemble fishbones, arrowheads, stick figures, or the
stylized outline of a fish. The characters are curved or linear,
compared with the square shapes of Chinese, which one researcher
says may have made it easier to weave the words into cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Yang learned Nushu when she was about 15 from friends and
relatives in her village, and she used it while doing ``women's
work'' _ making shoes, knitting, embroidering, and singing. But it
was most important for wedding ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Tradition in this county held that female friends moved in with
the bride-to-be for the month before her marriage to keep her
company, and during this time they pledged their ``sworn
sisterhood'' and wrote poems about friendship. For three days
before marriage, the bride was expected to cry to show how sad she
was to leave home. Then, three days after the wedding, the bride
returned to live at home for her first three years of marriage, and
again exchanged Nushu embroidery, handmade books, and songs with
her friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would write to our `sworn sisters' on paper fans and
handkerchiefs,'' Yang said. ``In the old days, boys and girls were
separated . . . so the boys didn't know what we girls were doing.
My husband never saw me studying it. He maybe knew it existed, but
didn't really know what it was and didn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   There are happy Nushu songs, but many speak of the drudgery of
marriage, and of the importance of ``sworn sisters'' as allies. One
proverb recounts that ``beside a well, one does not thirst; beside
sisters, one does not despair.''
</P>
<P>
   Yang's daughter-in-law, Yi Ruiyi, regrets she never learned
Nushu. She came from a village where it did not exist and married
Yang's son after the 1949 Communist Revolution, when Nushu was cast
aside as irrelevant and later banned. Communist propaganda ballads
replaced Nushu as songs of camaraderie, and women did not have the
need for Nushu that their mothers did.
</P>
<P>
   ``In old China, newly married girls' position was very low.
Daughters-in-law were oppressed. But they could not express it
because it was the custom to obey,'' said Yi, 63. ``They were
isolated in their husband's family and depressed. So when they went
home to visit, they gossiped about their mother-in-law and husband.
Nushu was like a secret code between friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The origin of Nushu is debatable. One theory is that women
adapted the script from embroidery patterns or tried to imitate
written Chinese, simplifying it along the way. But perhaps the most
plausible explanation comes from Zhou Shuoyi, the largely
self-taught local researcher who ``discovered'' the script in 1954.
Zhou, now 74, had first seen Nushu years earlier as a boy, when his
grandmother visited a village and brought home a poem in Nushu.
Zhou's father was puzzled by the writing and said it looked like
ancient Chinese. The mystery haunted Zhou until he encountered it
again while collecting folk poems.
</P>
<P>
   Zhou has traced Nushu characters to ancient Chinese script, and
he believes it dates back more than 2,000 years, to the time of Qin
Shihuang, the man who unified China and became its first emperor.
Qin eliminated all local written languages, currencies, weights and
measures, and decreed one standardized script. The penalty for
creating new languages was death _ for oneself, one's family, and
nine related families.
</P>
<P>
   Facing such a penalty, men abandoned local written dialects and
learned to write Mandarin Chinese. Most women, however, were denied
education and kept at home, where their activities were not
scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   The ancient marriage traditions of Jiangyong predated Qin and
were not targeted for elimination. Zhou's theory is that women _
barred from learning Chinese _ quietly kept using the local script,
and since women's activities had no official use, men paid no
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken Nushu is the local dialect, and can be understood by both
men and women. When written, only women could decode it.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Revolution, women in the two villages where Nushu was
found kept the ``Third Day Book'' ceremony alive and continued
their evenings of ``women's work.'' But after 1949, Communist
China's founder, Mao Zedong, declared gender equality, assigning
women the same jobs as men. Old culture and customs were
discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   During a purge in 1958, Zhou was accused of propagating old
ideas and was sent to a labor camp for 21 years. His Nushu writings
were burned. Local lore holds that in the 1960s, paranoid
authorities suspected it was code for espionage. When the
government relaxed and Zhou was released in 1979, he went back to
studying Nushu, but found few women who still knew it.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, a Chinese academic learned about the script
from a report Zhou submitted to the government. The man reviewed
Zhou's work, conducted research, and published a book heralding the
discovery as his own. Since then, numerous people from China and
abroad _ lecturers, doctoral students, a filmmaker _ have made
careers on the back of Nushu.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the women . . . didn't realize it was anything special,''
said Wan Jufeng, a Jiangyong official.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, modern life has succeeded where Emperor Qin could not;
it has stamped out the language by making it irrelevant. Girls are
schooled in Mandarin and have much the same freedom as men to work
and travel, making Nushu an anachronism. The women who still know
Nushu have not taught it to anyone; no one wants to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Yang, the 92-year-old, mused that with greater freedom to leave
home, ``girls aren't as close to each other as they used to be.''
But now, she added with satisfaction: ``They can have a better
life, better clothes, work for themselves. I hear that some girls
now make hundreds and send it home to their villages. That's great.
We couldn't do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
