<HEADLINE>
BATTLE IN SEATTLE SENT A MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seattle may be remembered less by many people for being the host
of the recent World Trade Organization meeting than for the violent
protests over the trade gathering and the crackdown by police and
the National Guard against the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   But to many others, including some of the protestors, Seattle
will be remembered as the city where the massive protests sent a
strong message to the world.
</P>
<P>
   That message is that the WTO, viewed by the protestors as
representing corporate global interests, can no longer make
decisions on free trade without hearing from the groups that would
be most affected, including labor groups, environmentalists,
farmers and other workers from developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps for the first time, these groups combined to develop a
strong voice that the representatives of the 135-nation WTO clearly
heard during its gathering.
</P>
<P>
   While there have been many media and other public comparisons
between the 1999 battle in Seattle and the movement of the 1960s,
including the Chicago street protests of 1968, there were notable
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Although young people were at the vanguard of demonstrations
both in the 1968 and 1999 protests, there appeared to be a much
larger number of older protestors -- many in their 40s and 50s --in
Seattle than their were in Chicago, according to some observers of
both demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference appeared to be in purpose. In Chicago, the
largely young protestors wanted not only an end to the Vietnam War,
but the beginning of a new world. In Seattle, the young protestors,
many of them environmentalists, seized the streets. The older
protestors from the United States and other countries ( including
China, Japan, and European nations) were there to force the WTO to
focus on child labor problems, health problems, and the lack of
environmental protections around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO gathering also brought together two groups - organized
labor and the environmentalists- which had different purposes. But
in Seattle they agreed on one purpose: change the way the WTO
operates, and force the WTO to put their issues on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``The labor movement and the environmentalists forced the WTO
delegates to focus on human rights, labor rights, and environmental
rights,'' said Jeff Crosby, president of the North Shore Labor
Council in Lynn, who was among a group of Massachusetts union
leaders, environmentalists and others who joined the protest in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the protesters included not only trade unionists and
environmentalists but also also workers from the Caribbean, South
Africa, China, and farmers from Japan and France, Crosby said the
protest in Seattle ``was truly an international response.''
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton ``was bringing up the rear and started
talking about labor standards and possible sanctions against
companies who violated these standards, it appears that the labor
movement and the environmentalists were driving the agenda,''
Crosby added.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby was referring to Clinton's suggestion to the WTO trade
ministers that trade sanctions be used against countries in
violation of basic labor standards, including exploitation of
workers and suppressing workers rights.
</P>
<P>
   Among the protesters' concerns: whether a new WTO trade policy
would have some of the negative impacts it has had on some workers
in the United States and in other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby and others in Seattle recall one worker at an
American-based automobile plant in Mexico who said at a labor rally
that she was earning more money before NAFTA (North American Free
Trade Agreement) went into effect and less money after NAFTA was
enacted..
</P>
<P>
   A single mother of two, she also found herself working many more
hours a week -- around 74 -- simply to make barely enough money to
support her family, she said. Asked what she wanted, the woman
answered: ``I just want to see my children.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, billions of people from around the world,
including in the United States, will see that the battle in Seattle
made a difference. They now know what the WTO does, and why it must
change to make the world truly better - for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
