<HEADLINE>
ESPN, MLB SETTLE THEIR DIFFERENCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESPN and Major League Baseball settled their little spat Monday,
and the result was no surprise: ESPN forked over a bunch of money
to keep baseball on its air for the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, a sports rights package defied logic. Once again,
substandard television ratings didn't preclude a huge rate hike
(233 percent). Not even bad feelings could stop the relentless
chase for exposure and advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   It will never stop.
</P>
<P>
   With a federal court case looming, ESPN agreed to pay MLB $800
million for six years, about $133 million per year. The last
contract was worth about $40 million a year. In exchange, ESPN and
ESPN2 will receive about 290 hours of programming, including a
minimum of 44 night games (on Wednesdays, select Sundays, and
holidays) and a new baseball show, ``Baseball2Day,'' on ESPN2
Sunday afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   Things change when money is on the table. Not too long ago,
Major League Baseball, mf that ESPN bounced three of its Sunday
night games to ESPN2 when there was a conflict with football,
terminated its contract with the Disney-owned network. ESPN quickly
filed suit, and a hearing in federal court was scheduled for
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In settling, ESPN and MLB agreed to air no Sunday night baseball
games during football season for the first two years of the new
cntract. For each game preempted, ESPN will air two games _ one on
a Friday in September on ESPN, and one on a Sunday night on ESPN2
earlier in the baseball season.
</P>
<P>
   The beat goes on. With legal matters resolved, MLB is now poised
to strike up a new deal for its over-the-air rights. Fox and NBC
currently split those rights, but ABC and CBS are eager to bid on
postseason games. The current deals expire at the end of next
season, but negotiations start in January.
</P>
<P>
   The market is extremely hot, and baseball is guaranteed to at
least double its revenue from television networks. Fox now pays
$575 million, while NBC pays about $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder MLB and ESPN officials were at peace Monday.
ESPN, which recently lot a bid to acquire the NCAA basketball
tournament, has a new deal that includes Internet and radio rights,
while MLB has a good partner willing to give its game prime-time
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``MLB is pleased that the arrangement with ESPN will continue,''
said baseball commissioner Bud Selig. ``ESPN has been a valued
partner for the last decade. We appreciate the network's
professionalism and dedication to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN was equally mushy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We greaty value our relationship with MLB,'' said ESPN
president George Bodenheimer said. ``Our passion for the sport has
been evident each day since our first agreement a decade ago, and
we will continue to dedicate ourselves to serving baseball and its
fans better than anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 1424EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1728 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      12-07 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNS PUSHES BRUINS AT PRACTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They took to the FleetCenter ice about 11 a.m. Monday
with little or no dialogue among them, the atmosphere businesslike
and more than a tad subdued. They had their sticks in hand but
there wasn't a puck in sight.
</P>
<P>
   For the first hour of practice, the Bruins looked like a group
of players in the beginning of training camp, participating in
conditioning drills and going one-on-one in exercises designed to
get the competitive juices flowing.
</P>
<P>
   At exactly noon, the Bruins retired to the dressing room before
returning at 12:14 for another 45 minutes on ice, this time with
pucks. The reason? Certainly, Boston's hideous 9-3 loss to the
Chicago Blackhawks Saturday night was the rock-bottom explanation
for Monday's punishment duty. However, this attett attitude
adjustment has been coming for quite a while.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday may have been the worst game the Bruins have played in
a very long time, but the fact is, since a 5-3 victory over the
Rangers Nov. 18, the Bruins have not been performing well. In the
last seven games, the Bruins are 2-3-2 and have come out of the
gate poorly in each one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it isn't acceptable, no matter how you look at it,''
said coach Pat Burns, who was as testy as he's been since arriving
in Boston 2 1/2 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here to ridicule anybody. I'm not here to put on a
show for anybody. I'm here to make sure everybody gets hard work
and an effort in. We didn't have one in the game Saturday night,
therefore we'll have one today. You look at the tape again and you
realize that for some reason or other _ I don't know what it was _
it was an embarrassing performance by everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The club didn't have ice time Sunday, but if they had, it's
likely Burns would've used it to deliver his message. Instead, he
spent Sunday stewing about the situation, particularly Saturday's
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the worst weekend because I felt embarrassed all day,''
he said. ``I certainly hope they felt embarrassed because I did.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other contributing factors in Saturday's outcome
besides the horrible performance by the Bruins. The Blackhawks had
had a front office shakeup, with president Bob Pulford taking over
a general manager and head coach. Such a move usually lights a fire
under a team. It certainly did in this instance. The last time
Boston was in such a position was Nov. 26, 1997, in a 10-5 losin
Florida after Doug MacLean was fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at the fact that when a team changes coaches
or replaces a coach, that usually happens,'' said Burns. ``It
happened against us against the Florida Panthers but did it
continue after that? No. Will the Hawks be able to do that every
night?I doubt it. But there's a natural reaction of a pickup for
maybe one, two, or three games. We were on the receiving end of it
and we've been on the receiving end of it twice for teams that have
let coaches go but there's no excuse for it. There's no excuse in
your own building for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins also miss the grit of defenseman Kyle McLaren and
right wing Rob DiMaio, both of whom could be available for
Thursday's game against Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had absolutely no character whatsoever,'' said Burns. ``We
had guys who couldn't possibly be hurt after the game because there
were no body checks whatsoever. There was no passion. It's
embarrassing in your own building when you get run over and you
don't respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe with the addition of a Kyle McLaren or a Rob DiMaio or
even a Joe Murphy, all of a sudden the club becomes a little bit
taller, a little bit stronger, one guy throws a hit and then
everybody follows from then on. I think it's just a question of
lack of passion, lack of aggressiveness, and lack of wanting to be
aggressive and lack of wanting to be passionate about the game.
Maybe these guys coming back will help that, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Jason Allison is just hoping that this won't come back to
haunt Boston down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the ones you look at at the end of the yearnd say,
`Would've, could've, should've,' '' sai Allison. ``We can't make
them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison recognized the warning signs all along as the Bruins
have dug holes for themselves in games. In some, they dug
themselves out, but it was bound to come back to bite them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've played well the last seven games, even the
ones we were winning,'' he said. ``We're not playing together as
well. We're not jelling on the ice. I don't think it's that we're
not working hard or shooting enough. We're missing coverage maybe,
but that's part of jelling, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were playing well after the first few games at
the start of the season even though we weren't winning. It was not
great but we had guys missing camp or who were hurt or unsigned. We
weren't as good a team as we are now. I thought we were playing
better but we were finding ways to lose games.''
</P>
<P>
   Nw, they're just playing poorly with no plausible explanation.
</P>
<P>
   If Burns has anything to say about it, that will change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
