<SLUG> BC-BOX-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUIZ CAN'T PIN DOWN GRANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This weekend, Chelsea's John Ruiz will put his World Boxing
Council No. 1 ranking on the line in a place called Tunica, Miss.
It is no place to take a chance, even if the fight will be held at
a casino, but Ruiz always has been willing to gamble on himself. He
just wishes he could make a bigger bet.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, Ruiz offered to fiht hot prospect Michael Grant
even before Grant got knocked on his nose by Andrew ``No Mas'
Golota two weeks ago. The offer remained in effect even after Grant
righted himself and convinced Golota to quit on his feet despite
holding an insurmountable points lead in the 10th round of a fight
that proved two things: Golota can't fight and Grant doesn't know
how to fight. At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the claims of Grant's management that he is the best
young heavyweight in the world, no deal between Ruiz and Grant, who
is right behind Ruiz in the WBC's ratings, has yet been made. Both
sides continue to s thy want it and talks are ongoing, but money
and the wishes of HBO appear to be standing in the way even though
all Ruiz has asked for is the same money HBO was willing to pay
David Tua, the International Boxing Federation's No. 1 contender,
to fight Grant.
</P>
<P>
   That figure is $1.5 million, and Tua rejected it while Ruiz is
saying he'll accept it even knowing a third of it would end up in
the hands of his promoter, Don King. To further those efforts,
Ruiz's manager, Norman Stone, and attorney, Tony Cardinale,
recently sent a letter to WBC president Jose Sulaiman urging him to
order a boxoff between the two top contenders to establish not only
the undisputed No. 1 contender but also to provide the most
attractive opponent for undisputed heavyweight champion Lennox
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The WBC responded with a letter saying it would ``absolutely
approve any elimination bout'' but went on to point out that Lewis
did not have a mandatory title defense due for another year.
Regardless of the wait, Ruiz and Stone are ready to put their
rating on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would clear everything up with the WBC and with the WBA
by us fighting,'' Stone said. ``If they're so sure _ which
everybody in the world seems to be _ that Grant can handle Johnny,
then just do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they win, they got Grant in the mandatory position and they
got King out of the heavyweight picture. HBO would have the
champion, Tua, and Grant. So if they're all so sure Johnny can't
fight and Grant can, why not make the fight? Maybe they ain't so
sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grant is a tough kid but he don't know how to fight,'' Stone
said. ``They've already made millions with Grant. They have nothing
to lose. onny has everything to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   hat will be true Saturday night as well when Ruiz faces Jade
Scott, who once was a contender but always seemed to be one built
on air rather than on fights. Although Scott is 25-3, Ruiz's people
took the fight because their fighter needed a payday and the WBC
was pushing King to put Ruiz in with a top 15 contender, which
somehow Scott is.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, King tried to push Larry Donald as an opponent for
Ruiz but Stone and Cardinale smelled a rat and refused. Donald is a
cute boxer who runs for a living. He is difficult to hit, elusive,
rfuses to fight if he can avoid it, and is just the type to steal a
decision from a more ponderous mover like Ruiz. That is especially
true because his manager is named Carl King.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to guess who Carl's father is, do you?
</P>
<P>
   ``We told King there's no sense fighting a top 10 opponent for
less than a million,'' Cardinale said. ``So Johnny ended up with
Scott knowing there's no such thing as a tuneup fight for a kid in
his position. The way we see it, it's a fight that gets us closer
to Grant.''
</P>
<P>
   And, they hope, closer to that million-dollar payday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   Looks like after all the talk of a Felix Trinidad-Oscar De La
Hoya rematch and then a Trinidad-David Reid showdown for the super
welterweight title, what we're going to end up with is Trinidad
defending the WBC welterweight title against Derrell Coley, which
should last about two rounds, in mid-March and De La Hoya fighting
World Boxing Organization welterweight champion Ahmed Kotiev Feb.
26 at Mason Square Garden. If the latter fight comes off, unbeaten
welterweight prospect Vernon Forrest likely will fight former
junior welterweight champion Vince Phillips on the undercard . . .
Kotiev successfully defended his title and kept his unbeaten streak
intact (25-0) with a win over Daniel Santos and it may land him
that Feb. 26 shot at De La Hoya. Why's that? Because more fights
fall out than happen. . . . The International Boxing Federation got
more bad news this week when a US District Court judge found
prosecutors would be likely to prove racketeering charges against
IBF president Bob Lee. Because of that, judge John W. Bissell
ordered that the IBF cannot pay more than $5,000 to any entity in a
single week without court permission and barred Lee and the IBF's
other officials from destroying documents or concealing funds . . .
Muhammad Ali may be done fighting but he still needs a manager. And
he got a new one last week when Bernie Yuman, who manages the Vegas
illusionists Siegfried and Roy, announced he was now Ali's
exclusive manager. He has managed Siegfried and Roy for 24 years,
the last nine during their stay at the Mirage in Las Vegas . . . In
Toronto, a bearded Sikh boxer won a court order allowing him to
fight with whiskers. But rather than let him fight for a Canadian
amateur title, the Canadian Amateur Boxing Association canceled the
light flyweight bouts he was scheduled to compete in because
bearded fighters are banned in international competition. The
associaion said it feared international sanctions on the eve of the
2000 Olympics. Pardeep Nagra said he would wear a net on his face
if necessary. That's what he did when he won the Ontario flyweight
title earlier this year. Said Anne Lowthian, executive director of
the World Sikh Organization of Canada, ``There is no justification.
Not legally. Not morally.'' I cannot make this stuff up . . . No
one will see the fight, but ex-world champion Gerry Penalosa, who
once looked like a potential great, takes on unbeaten WBC super
flyweight champion Injoo Cho Jan. 2 at the Sheraton Hotel in Seoul.
Cho upset Penalosa to win the title in August 1998 and this is a
classic rematch of a stylish boxer (Cho) vs. a power puncher
(Penalosa, who is 40-2-2, 24 KOs). Unlike what we've seen too much
of with bigger names, the fighters and managers did all they could
to finalize this fight when Penalosa waived a $25,000 penalty he
was supposed to receive if the bout was postponed from its original
Dec. 26 date . . . Word out of Europe is that longtime promoter
Mogens Palle is retiring at 65 and turning his boxing enterprise
over to his daughter, Bettina . . . Here's Tony Ayala Jr.'s take on
the troubles of Mike Tyson. ``Mike Tyson is a jerk,'' Ayala said
recently in Los Angeles. ``Four years in jail, $100 million in
purses, and he cries to the world that he's misunderstood.'' Ayala,
who served 16 years in a New Jersey prison himself, faces the
biggest fight of his life Saturday in San Antonio against Tony
Menefee. It's Ayala's biggest fight not because Menefee is the
toughest opponent the 36-year-old former contendr has faced but
because he knows at his age he cannot afford a defeat if he's ever
going to get the title shot that eluded him when he was
incarcerate. ``At this stage of my life, people aren't really going
to tolerate many losses,'' said Ayala (24-0, 22 KOs, two wins since
his comeback began) . . . In case you missed it, WBC lightweight
champion Stevie Johnston easily defended his title two weekends ago
in England over Billy Schwer at Wembley Arena. He won 10 of 12
rounds on all judges' cards . . . Six boxers who appeared at the
1996 Olympics in Atlanta now have won world titles. The latest was
German Markus Beyer, who won the WBC super middleweight title
recently with a decision over champion Richie Woodhall. Both Beyer
and former German teammate Sven Ottke hold world titles. This is
believed to be the first time two members of a non-American Olympic
team have held world titles at the same time since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Around and around
</P>
<P>
   Here's the latest ratings miracle: Mikael Rask has had just 13
professional fights but he's slated to step in with WBC junior
middleweight champion Javier Castillejo Dec. 17 in Madrid.
Castillejo was briefly considered as a possible opponent for De La
Hoya until the former welterweight champion decided to forego a
quick move up to 154 and remain in the welterweight division. As
for young Rask, he miraculously shot up 11 spots in the WBC
rankings into the top 15 to qualify for a world title fight.
According to the WBC rule book, a minimum of 15 professional fights
is required of all title contenders. But this being the holiday
season, WBC president Sulaiman apparently decided to give out a
gift. To Castillo . . . Castillejo is 46-4 and has defended his
title (if you want to call it that) three times since he won it
from Keith Mullings. One of these days, Castillejo actually will
have to fight someone in danger of fighting back, but not this time
. . . Don't ask me what he's done to justify it, but Hector Camacho
Jr. (26-0) was named the WBA's No. 1 rated super lightweight last
week. He has fought seven times this year and plans to fight again
next month . . . Looks like an Erik Morales-Marco Antonio Barrera
showdown is headed for Mandalay Bay on Feb. 19, with HBO televising
. . . After three years of battling, Arizona senator John McCain
lost his fight to see the Muhammad Ali Boxing Reform Act passed
when the full Senate was blocked from voting on it because of
procedural moves by two Democratic senators. The bill previously
had been passed twice by the Senate and once by the House but
because of changes made in the House version it had to be revoted
in the Senate but was blocked from consideration. McCain promised
he would attempt to bring the bill back next year because, ``The
boxing industry is in crisis and the Ali Act would have provided
urgently needed reforms such as limiting coercive option contracts,
establishing fair business practice guidelines for rating
organizations, and requiring key financial disclosures on promoters
and organizations of major boxing events.'' . . The date for
Tyson's next fight has been moved to Jan. 29 and probably won't be
in Wales. It's now more likely to be at the new MEN Stadium in
Manchester, England. Same opponent, light-hitting and glass-jawed
British heavyweight uius Francis. Generally, a British heavyweight
is a lightweight, which is why Tyson's people want to make the mat.
If Tyson puts on a strong performance, don't be surprised to see
him bac in Europe, possibly against WBO champn itali Klitschko.
Klitscko's manager, Klaus-Peter Kohl, said from Berli last week
that his man will fight in gust in Hamburg but ources close to
Tyson said, ``That's just a guy trying to get publicity for his
fighter. Mike's not fighting anybody in Germany. We don't even know
for sure if and when he's fighting in England.'' . . . Tyson's
schedule change means Roy Jones headlines the first card ever at
Radio City Music Hall in New York Jan. 15 without television
competition. Originally, Jones was scheduled to fight Graciano
Rocchigiani but when HBO executives asked to see a signed contract
from Rocchigiani no one could produce one so hard-hitting David
Telesco was substituted. Telesco has pursued Jones at many a
postfight press conference, demanding a title shot. Now he's got it
. . . After all the hue and cry over the Evander Holyfield-Lewis
draw in their first fight, New York Gov. George Pataki quietly
vetoed legislation recently that would have required judges'
scorecards to be publicly posted after each round. Politicians,
like fight promoters, never will change . . . December's best fight
could be 34-year-old middleweight champion Bernard Hopkins's title
defense against hard-hitting Antwun Echols Sunday on Fox Sports
Net. HBO tried to sign Hopkins for more money and a side deal to go
down to 154 pounds and challenge Fernando Vargas and Reid, but
thatell through because of promotional ontract problems with
America Presents. Instead an angry Hopkins gets only $100,000 for
the Echols fight. Hopkins hasn't lost since he was outpointed by
Jones six years ago and even though Echols (22-2-1, 22 KOs) hasn't
lost in three years he'll be in with the division's heavy iron in
Hopkins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
