   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES FOUR COLOR PHOTOS, TWO COLOR PHOTO ILLUSTRATIONS
</P>
<P>
   POKEWEED: The lowly pokeweed may be about to come into its own.
For years, scientists have known that a deadly poison in the weed
has antiviral and antitumor properties. Now researchers are racing
to nail down the ability of the substance to destroy HIV and may
even kill the virus in areas current HIV drugs fail to find it.
(Includes 4-column color illustration of pokeweed.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ENDOSCOPE CONTROVERSY: A microbiologist debates the
cleanliness of endoscopes. (Includes 1-column color photo of a man
holding an endoscope.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REPETITIVE MOTION: Can stretches help relieve symptoms of
repetitive-motion disorders?
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PREVENTION: A newly appointed official with the Centers
for Disease Control talks about ways to combat illness. (Includes
6-pica color mug of CDC official.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH AND MEDIA: Publishers offer numerous books on
herbal remedies. (Includes two 6-pica color photos of book jackets,
one 6-pica color illustration of a computer.)
</P>
