<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
 Attn Sports Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for
Wednesday, Dec. 8.
</P>
<P>
   VECSEY-COLUMN (New York) _ Something has gone wrong. When we
used to talk about the National Basketball Association, we
discussed moves _ the agile, brazen creations of the giants who
roamed the earth. Now it is no longer about the game. Now it is
about the subtext, the potential gestures and snubs, who is dissing
whom. Now it is not about gymnastics and accuracy but rather about
personalities, a soap opera instead of the ballet. By George
Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS-WARRIORS (New York) _ Golden State at New York, 7:30
p.m. By Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-COLUMN (New York) _ On basketball on the Warriors-Knicks. By
Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JETS-SALE (Undated) _ On the ongoing bidding process for the
Jets franchise. The final day for potential owners to submit bids
is on Wednesday. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS (East Rutherford, N.J.) _ New Jersey plays
host to Pittsburgh, 7:30 p.m. By Alex Yannis.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-PENGUINS-LEMIEUX (Pittsburgh) _ Feature on Mario Lemieux in
his new role as principal owner of the team he led to two Stanley
Cups. By Joe Lapointe.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-GREAT-EIGHT (Chicago) _ The Great Eight tournament in
Chicago gets under way with a doubleheader: Kansas vs. Michigan St.
at 7 p.m., and Arizona vs. Connecticut at 9 p.m. By Bill Dedman.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-COLUMN (Undated) _ On Baseball column: With the signing of
David Cone to a one-year $12 million deal, the Yankees indeed seem
to be on their way to becoming the first professional sports team
with a $100 million payroll. By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other sports
stories from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News Service,
Hearst News Service, The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco
Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
