<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Wednesday, Dec. 8.
</P>
<P>
   SHITNEY-BIENNIAL (New York) _ When the Whitney Museum of
American Art announced last March that for the first time in its
70-year history a team of outside curators would produce its
Biennial, no one involved was quite sure how the process would
work. A look at how the six curators put it together. By Carol
Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   SALZBURG-FEST-DIRECTOR (Paris) _ The celebrated Salzburg
Festival, which was thrown into turmoil this summer when Austria's
president led a conservative attack on its eclectic programming,
has named Peter Ruzicka, a 51-year-old German conductor and
composer, as its artistic director. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICAN-FILM-FEST (Undated) _ A festival of films about the
African diaspora.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICAN-SALSA (Dakar, Senegal) _ Arts Abroad: The African
version of salsa, salsambalax, in Senegal. By David Hecht.
</P>
<P>
   ROYAL-OPERA-FALSTAFF (London) _ Its housewarmings completed, its
30-month renovation almost so, the Royal Opera House opened for
business here on Monday night with a new production of Verdi's
``Falstaff. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   CRADLE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Review of ``Cradle Will Rock,''
directed by Tim Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   REFLECTIONS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Richard Bernstein reviews
``Reflections on a Ravaged Century,'' by Robert Conquest (Norton).
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other
entertainment stories from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
