 AM-R-NYT-BUDGET  
(nk) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Dec. 8:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL  &LR;  (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ALBRIGHT (Jerusalem) _ Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright met with President Hafez Assad of Syria in Damascus on
Tuesday, before heading to Israel. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-RUSSIA (Dateline to come) _ What the battlefield looks
and smells like, and what the Russians' strategy is. By Michael
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-SERBIA (Belgrade/Nis) _ Fourteen trucks carrying heating
fuel donated by the European Union arrived Tuesday at the customs
bureau in Nis, an opposition-controlled town in southern Serbia,
after being blocked for nearly two weeks at the border by Yugoslav
authorities. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With map and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-DIVISIONS (Beijing) _ Senior North Korean diplomat lashes
out at South Korea, denouncing ``unprecedentedly gigantic wall''
dividing the countries _ which doesn't exist. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-DEMOCRACY (Havana) _ Cubans struggling to make ends meet
still say more democracy would help the economy, but they say they
still revere Castro. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-U.S. (Washington) _ NATO's new secretary-general meets with
Clinton and Cohen. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-SURVEY (Undated) _ Survey of the homeless based on
census figures provides snapshot of who they are: almost half
worked at some time during the year, many suffer from psychiatric
problems. By Nina Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE-POLICE-CHIEF (Seattle) _ Police Chief Norm Stamper of
Seattle is planning to resign and says he takes full responsibility
for his department's handling of the protests that disrupted last
week's World Trade Organization meeting. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   UTAH-CAMP-ATTACK (Cedar City, Utah) _ The survival camp for
troubled youth, from which eight teenagers escaped over the
weekend, is part of a growing number of similar alternative
schools. Over the past several years, the number of such schools
has doubled as parents search for different ways to deal with
difficult teens. Meanwhile, the authorities continue to search for
two youngsters still missing. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   MODIFIED-FOOD (Undated) _ On Monsanto paying people to
demonstrate in favor of genetically modified food and the growing
movement by biotech companies to recruit grass-roots people to
support modified food. By Iver Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   MARS-MISTAKES (Undated) _ A string of embarrassing mistakes that
doomed the $125 million Mars Climate Orbiter in September also
probably contributed to the apparent loss this week of the $165
million Mars Polar Landar, NASA officials and engineers said
Tuesday. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   MARS-LANDER (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Developments. By John Noble
Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   CHEMICAL-TOYS (Undated) _ Chemical softener suspected of causing
illness is still turning up in plastic toys, group says. By Holcomb
B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TEACHERS-CHEATING (New York) _ The special investigator for
NYC schools finds widespread cheating on standardized tests
involving 30 schools and 50 teachers and two principals. Among the
offenses: outright giving students the answers. The scandal comes
at a time administrators are under increasing pressure to get good
results, with their jobs at stake. By Abby Goodnough.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   NY-SCHOOL-CHEATING (New York) _ Interviews at a school where
teachers corrected their students' reading tests answers in
mid-test, raising reading scores by 20 percentage points. By Randal
C. Archibold.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-RDP (Washington) _ Cases decided Tuesday include an
inheritance tax case and a criminal records case from California.
By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-TANKERS (Washington) _ Court hears arguments in a case
from the state of Washington on whether coastal states can impose
regulations on oil tankers that are stricter than federal
requirements or those set by international treaties. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
