<HEADER>
A1781 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BIOTECH-COMPUTER-ART-     12-07 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-COMPUTER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS REPLACING `WET' EXPERIMENTS IN THE BIOTECH LAB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As science over the years has vanquished some of the world's
most dreaded diseases, from diptheria to malaria and polio, the
credit has gone to scientists who wear white jackets and work in
laboratories filled with test-tubes and bubbling flasks.
</P>
<P>
   But as pharmaceutical researchers probe the genetic building
blocks of life to attack more complex illnesses, this expensive
``wet science,'' as it is known, is no longer where drug
discoveries initially are made.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of working at laboratory benches, many of today's
leading-edge researchers can be found hunched in front of computer
screens, manipulating multiple databases to analyze and visualize
biological and chemical and molecular information that could lead
to the the next generation of wonder drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of going out to a garage and setting up beakers and
petri dishes and looking at an experiment are long gone,'' said Dr.
Stephen Friend, president and chief scientist of Rosetta
Inpharmatics Inc. and a former associate professor of pediatric
medicine at Harvard Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now teams of scientists work together using many different
databases to find key pieces of information with the `wet' science
becoming a member of the research team and together they solve
problems that can lead to new drug discoveries _ that's something
we did not see five to seven years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in a shift from traditional patterns of pharmaceutical
research, much of this work, known as bioinformatics, is being done
at dozens of young companies like Rosetta, in such high-tech
centers as Cambridge, Mass., California's Silicon Valley and the
Seattle area. They see researchers treading water in
ever-increasing oceans of data looking for better and faster ways
to dive down and find the critical knowledge and easily display it
without drowning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a problem that scientists had in visually representing
hundreds of compounds, each with a host of different data elements
but without having to turn to heavy-duty statisticians,'' said
Christopher Ahlberg, founder and chief executive of Spotfire Inc.
The company, nearly three years old, has 40 employees in Cambridge
and 30 more researchers in Goteburg, Sweden, where it got its
start. ``Text-oriented computers cannot handle it, so you have to
develop a way of seeing all this information,'' Ahlberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Ahlberg developed the idea for Spotfire while a doctoral student
at the University of Maryland's Human Computer Interaction
Laboratory. He targeted the pharmaceutical and biotechnology
industries as his customers, with solid results: 24 of the top 25
pharmaceutical companies, along with 50 biotech firms, use
Spotfire's Web-based software programs, paying between $100,000 and
$1 million for the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   At Merck &AMP; Co., researchers use Spotfire software to access and
analyze information about relationships between chemical structures
and biological activity. The programs ``will help our project teams
make decisions faster to shorten the drug development cycle,'' said
Seth Pinsky, senior director of research information systems at
Merck.
</P>
<P>
   To help scientists ``see,'' or visualize, the compounds they are
working with, Spotfire software employs conceptual graphics.
</P>
<P>
   One application, for example, helps to sort out complexities of
molecular chemistry by placing different colored boxes on computer
monitor screens to represent 400 chemical compounds or proteins,
clustered based on their molecular weight. But when different
structural criteria are put into the program, as many as 350 of
these may disappear from the screen. Diagrams and graphs can be
called up to help uncover trends and anomalies within the data from
a multitude of different databases.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to identify early what experiments are likely to hit
a dead end. In ``wet'' laboratory science, much of this is achieved
by trial and error, with an enormous failure rate. Only one in 300
drugs that advance to clinical trials on humans ever win final
government approval. Hundreds more never even get to the trial
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Researchers working in teams need to understand and act on
more and more data types and see the failures early, because then
they can work with ones that work,'' Ahlberg said.
</P>
<P>
   His young company also mirrors the field of other bioinformatics
companies that are focused on related issues.
</P>
<P>
   With names like Molecular Applications Group, Pangea Systems,
Netgenics Inc., Informax Inc., Genomica Corp. and Rosetta, they
provide a range of search and retrieval software.
</P>
<P>
   ``We estimate that what once took us four years to carry out
from concept to the start of clinical trials is now done in two
years,'' said Victoria Sato, senior vice president of research at
Vertex Pharmaceuticals Inc. in Cambridge, a major user of multiple
databases for drug design. ``For us, working with biology,
chemistry and genomic databases is one thing; extracting the
information you need is another.''
</P>
<P>
   Bioinformatics increasingly is viewed as the glue that will hold
the discovery of new drugs together, with its capabilities linked
closely to two other cutting-edge research techniques _
high-throughput screening, where 100,000 compounds can be tested
per day in the hopes of finding those that make effective drugs;
and combinatorial chemistry, where substances are collected and
analyzed for potential drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Frost &AMP; Sullivan, a New York market research company,
estimated US pharmaceutical companies spent $1.2 billion on
bioinformatics products _ and predicted that amount would double in
the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for this growth is the development of programs that
enable researchers to ask many, sometimes open-ended questions
across multiple databases, said Friend, who is president of
Rosetta, based in Kirkland, Wash. This, he said, ``compares to just
five years ago when people created databases as a tool to ask just
one particular question.''
</P>
<P>
   Friend's five-year-old company, like Spotfire, is typical of
many bioinformatics companies, formed in the past three to seven
years with venture capital financing. Some have revenues of $5
million to $10 million, but few are profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Spotfire expects to have sales of $7 million this year, up from
$1.8 million in 1998. Ahlberg said he expects to see his first
profits in early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting to look beyond medicine to other fields in
chemistry and material science, where there is a massive amount of
data and few ways of getting access to it to make critical
decisions, Ahlberg said. ``We've just begun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
