<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1785 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap1     12-07 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap10-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: THE RAINBOW MADONNA  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 10 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   If the world was going to end, thought Max, the best place to be
was in a traffic jam on U.S. 19, one of America's ugliest roads and
biggest parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more tourists and ``snowbirds'' flocked to West
Florida, the development and traffic clotted Route 19 to the point
of arteriosclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a good day to die,'' said Max to his Mustang,
quoting an old Native-American saying, and looking north toward
Clearwater and an endless line of traffic. Apocalypse today might
be considered a form of euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
   For the next half hour he inched by one strip shopping mall
after another, their stores offering everything from lawn furniture
to used cars to fast foods to lingerie modeling. Finally, he came
upon the landmark he was looking for, a large billboard inviting
one to stop in for a ``Quick Lube.''
</P>
<P>
   Max pulled the Mustang, its temperature gauge pointing toward
hot, into a big lot and parked it under a shady tree and pulled up
the top to avoid bird bombing runs. He had come here to meet Father
Ralph Rizzo and to sort out the things he had seen and heard at The
Watchers' initiation ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   He could not erase from his mind the image of Angela Powers,
naked as a newborn, shimmering wet in the moonlight. He told
himself that his thoughts about her were not lustful, that they
aroused in him a different kind of yearning, a fatherly desire to
save a lost daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Father Ralph stood in the parking lot wearing sandals, khaki
shorts, a Hawaiian shirt, and a Yankees cap. As Max approached him,
Ralph swept his hand and pointed dramatically: ``Behold. There she
is. Our Lady of Clearwater. The Rainbow Madonna.''
</P>
<P>
   It clicked now in Max's mind. He looked up to see on the glass
panels of a bank building the most remarkable image _ a
multicolored pattern of wavy bands that formed the familiar cloaked
outline of the Blessed Virgin Mary. Max remembered reading about
it. How a palm tree had been removed. How water from the sprinkler
system had washed upon the glass. How chemicals had bonded to form
this startling icon of red, blue, gold and violet. How this was now
a destination for pilgrims and preachers and miracle seekers.
</P>
<P>
   Max noticed about 100 votive candles before the image, along
with dozens of handwritten messages tacked to the fence. ``Dear
Mother of God. I am only 10 years old. My dad is sick and doesn't
have any money. Please help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph told Max that he came here once in a while to collect
messages, to greet pilgrims, and to minister to those seeking help.
He often directed them to food banks, or hospices, or AIDS clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two stories from the Gospel that always impressed
me,'' said Ralph, leading Max to a white plastic bench under a
tree. ``The first one is about this sick lady who figures that if
she can just touch the hem of His garment, she would be healed. It
says that Jesus felt the power going out of Him. In another town,
Jesus can't perform any miracles because the people there had no
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get it,'' said Max.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think God reached down from the sky and with some big
magic marker drew a picture of Mary on that glass? No. I think the
sprinkler system did that. The power is not in that image, but in
the faith of that 10-year-old boy who wants to help his father.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But people can believe in the wrong thing. The Nazis had faith
in Hitler. The Watchers have faith in Raoul Glaber.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why does that name sound familiar to me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been talking about him for weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is the first time I've focused on his name. Is this
the guy you saw on the boat _ with that beautiful girl?'' Max
nodded. ``Do you think Glaber has the hots for her?''
</P>
<P>
   It was a funny expression for a priest to use, and it evoked
from Max a muffled laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph turned professorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're seeing in The Watchers turns out to be a very old
story, Max. Social movements inspired by the millennium take many
shapes, but they always have two distinct features _ it's been that
way since the Middle Ages. I taught this stuff for years. First,
you need an alienated, disenfranchised, impoverished group _ in the
Dark Ages it was the peasants. And then you need a charismatic
leader who is self-important and usually a little loony. This Raoul
Glaber has obviously targeted the dispossessed young for
indoctrination. And he holds himself up as a kind of savior.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What amazed me, Ralph, is that I know this guy's a jerk, but
he makes a kind of perverse sense. It's hard to deny that we've
sort of screwed over a generation of young people. And we've
committed such atrocities over this century, some in the name of
religion. Maybe we've lost the chance to be saved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bull----,'' said Ralph. ``There are only three kinds of people
in the world. The ones like Glaber who look at things and see the
end. The ones, like that 10-year-old boy, who have hope even in the
dark days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the third kind?''
</P>
<P>
   ``People like you, Max, who can't make up your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How could a just and merciful God allow something like the
Holocaust to happen? I'm not trying to be disrespectful, Ralph. I'm
just trying to get inside Glaber's head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the oldest trap in the world, Max. It's shows that, deep
down, you're a believer. If you believe only in chaos or accident
or biology, then you can account for someone like Hitler _ a crazy
person in a crazy world. If you believe in God, you've got some
work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you're not supposed to understand. Maybe you're just
supposed to act. To investigate this Glaber guy. And write a great
story. And save the life of that beautiful young woman. Maybe
that's the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come here for a counseling session, Ralph.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you come here for?''
</P>
<P>
   ``To try to learn more about this millennium stuff. We may be
entering a new era, but I think I'm beyond the kind of rejuvenation
you're preaching, Ralph.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You once had so much energy and passion. I admired that in
you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've collected too many barnacles, Ralph, even for a good hull
scraper like you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Haven't you ever seen a piece of driftwood polished into
something glorious? Maybe God ain't done with you yet, Max.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph got up from his seat to greet a tall, thin man with long,
unkempt hair, and a scraggly beard that flowed to his breastbone.
His face was gaunt, and Max could see that his belongings were
piled nearby in a grocery cart.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph, a foot shorter than this man, locked him in a bear hug
and dragged the man by the arm into the shade of the tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max,'' he said, ``I want you to meet Louis. He's a friend of
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: WALKIN' THE DOG
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
