<HEADER>
A1789 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap1     12-07 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap14-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: INTO THE LION'S DEN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 14 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: What Father Ralph teaches Max about the Year
1000 leads Max to a startling conclusion: that Raoul Glaber is not
the real name of The Watcher leader.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   From a distance the Conquistador Hotel looked like a friendly
old soul, a small but elegant pink lady, born in the roaring 20s,
and preserved with several discreet face lifts. For 150 bucks,
tourists could buy the right to lay themselves out in the sun and
burn to a crisp _ ensuring, if they lived long enough, skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   From the vantage point of Max's Mustang, driving through
Gulfport toward the beach, it was hard to imagine anything more
malevolent happening here than, say, a post-prom booze party or
your standard adulterous affair. Even the president of the United
States once spent the night here. ``It sure is pink,'' he was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   But as Max drove closer and closer, the look of the place got
weirder and weirder. An attendant dressed in white stopped him at
the front gate and with friendly insistence pressed Max to learn
the nature of his business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you a guest at the hotel, Mr. ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Timlin. No, but I've heard this was a special place, so I
thought I'd take a look for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The young man, he looked bleached blond, took Max's license and
recorded his tag number, slid a pass onto his dashboard, and
pointed to a place in the shade where he could park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enjoy the day, sir, and don't forget to stop into the Globe
Room. You'll enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Max saw lots of tourists, and a few Watcher acolytes dressed in
black, and many more initiates in blazing white regalia.
</P>
<P>
   Though it was warm, Max dressed in black for dramatic effect. As
he walked around he got the impression of a gilded cage, a
too-perfect community in which everything was Watched. It reminded
him of the resort in Wales that became the set of the 1960s British
TV series ``The Prisoner.'' He started whistling the theme song,
``All You Need Is Love.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent about two hours scouting the place, its little
restaurants, shops, tennis courts, boardwalk, cabanas, and down one
end a dock for boats. He could see Glaber's cigarette boat in the
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, behind the dunes, he could see a large round white mark
along the beach with concentric circles _ like a target _ or
perhaps a landing pad for hang gliders or even a small helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   What interested Max most was the absence of Watcher insignias or
other public displays that might indicate who owned the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   He took an elevator to the fifth floor, which opened to a
mahogany reception desk behind which sat an attractive young woman
dressed in a handsome white suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in white and I'm in black,'' said Max, still wearing
his sunglasses. She smiled at him blankly. ``The prince of parking
told me I should check out the Globe Room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Please sign in here, sir, and then take those steps to the
right.''
</P>
<P>
   He followed her directions and stepped into a remarkable
setting. The room was the world, or to be more precise, a globe.
Inside, Max could see a map of the world rendered in magnificent
stained glass, lit from behind. You could only move across the room
on a thin walkway which served as the sphere's diameter.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to a spot that marked the center of the Earth. A
recorded voice came on. It was Raoul Glaber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand beside you, watching our magnificent world. But what
shall become of it?'' What followed was five minutes of standard
Watcher fare _ apocalyptic doom softened by New Age mythology.
</P>
<P>
   Max looked up and noticed a security video camera. He smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can turn back and walk out the way you came in,'' said
Glaber's soothing voice, ``or you can move forward beyond this
great world to something ever more glorious.''
</P>
<P>
   Max shrugged and walked 10 steps toward the door beyond him. It
opened automatically. The hall beyond had a great W on the wall.
This was The Watcher sanctum, busy with Watcher workers in white,
moving in and out of offices, or stretched out before banks of
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Max was approached by a handsome black woman with her short hair
dyed blond. ``Dennis Rodman's sister,'' he thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to The Watchers, sir. I'm Denise and you're ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Timlin. Max Timlin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome, Max. I'm here to watch over you so you can learn more
about The Watchers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'd like that. I'm a reporter and would like to interview
Raoul Glaber.''
</P>
<P>
   Her expression darkened. ``Wait right here, sir. Don't move.''
She ran off.
</P>
<P>
   Within 15 seconds, Max was surround by burly blond attendants;
they resembled personal trainers in dress and physique, but Max
guessed they constituted the palace guard.
</P>
<P>
   An older man, his head shaved bald, approached him. ``I
understand you are a reporter, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's correct. I'm a free-lance writer and I'd like to
interview Mr. Glaber.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider ourselves to be a very open organization. We
conduct much of our business in public.'' Max pulled out his
notebook and began scribbling. ``I'm afraid I'm going to have to
ask you to put that away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, sure. I'm not here to make a scene. I'm Max Timlin. And
your name sir is?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not required to give you my name, sir, but it's Monty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``May I write that down?''
</P>
<P>
   Monty shook his head sternly. ``Mr. Timlin, have you read
stories in the press about The Watchers?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, of course, I've been doing research.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you seen a story about us that didn't portray us as some
kind of kooky cult? We've been so badly used, we've had to ban
reporters from our premises. I'll give you all the literature
you'll need to understand who we are and what we stand ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, Mr. Full Monty, I don't take handouts from flacks, and
I'm not intimidated by blond Nazi boys dressed like ice-cream
vendors.''
</P>
<P>
   They seemed to flex as one, but Monty held up a hand to restrain
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why shouldn't I have you escorted from the premises _ and
roughly?''
</P>
<P>
   Max reached in his pocket and pulled out an index card and
clicked his pen and scribbled two quick sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's why. Be so kind as to show this to Mr. Glaber. I'll
wait here with your goons.''
</P>
<P>
   Monty took the card, read it, his face flushing with anger.
``Watch him,'' he said, and spun away. Max put his shades back on,
crossed his arms, and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: AN ECLIPSE OF THE SUN
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
