<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEWARE YULETIME CREDIT CARD TINSEL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SHANNON BUGGS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite some retailers hanging fake holly and white lights in
October, the holiday shopping season is now officially upon us.
</P>
<P>
   Joy.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed in with the glossy wishbooks and greeting cards cramming
your mailbox are letters from credit card companies eager to give
you an extra line of credit for your holiday shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe you qualify for a 10 percent discount on your first
purchase using a brand-new department store charge card. And then
there is the kindest offer of all: skipping December's payment with
your creditor's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   As tempting as these gifts are _ not to mention the tennis
bracelet, the Big Bertha stainless steel irons or the Barbie Dream
Kingdom that could be bought with the extra credit _ resist the
urge to take a break from your bills.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SKIPPING PAYMENT IS COSTLY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skipping a payment, even at a credit card company's behest,
doesn't stop the clock on finance charges.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a credit balance of $2,000 with an average interest
rate of 18 percent and you skip a minimum payment of $20, your
effective interest rate jumps to 25.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you were trying to erase that debt in a year by paying
$180.65 each month and you didn't send in December's check, then
you just tacked on two or three more months of payments, says Steve
Rhode, president and co-founder of Debt Counselors of America in
Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid adding to your debt, even if it means passing up a
discount on the perfect outfit for dancing away the century this
New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing store chains and department stores usually charge 18 to
22 percent to use their cards. Unless you pay the balance
immediately, you will wind up giving back the discount in interest
payments.
</P>
<P>
   And those of you thinking you can get a china cabinet or a
sleeper sofa using one of those ``buy now, pay later'' credit plans
that department and furniture stores offer this time of year had
better be disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   The ``free'' period isn't free.
</P>
<P>
   Interest accrues on your purchase from the day you sign the
credit card receipt. By the end of the 90 days or six months, the
debt needs to be paid in full to avoid a balance ballooned by
finance charges.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if your credit card company raises your spending limit,
don't take that as a sign from Santa Claus to overspend. Some banks
charge a fee for extending you more credit, even if you didn't ask
for it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
STICK WITH JUST TWO CARDS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can avoid all of this by paying cash for everything.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're like me and haven't been saving spare change and
bagging your lunch to build up a holiday shopping fund, then you
need to use your credit cards strategically. No one wants to spend
the summer paying off last year's spending spree.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to avoid the urge to splurge is to make a budget
that includes all of your expenses, from gifts and wrapping paper
to travel and eating out.
</P>
<P>
   If you can locate your receipts and bills for last year's
Hanukkah, Christmas or Kwanzaa purchases, use them to figure out
how much money you'll need this year. If that's impossible, use
your checkbook register and credit card statements to piece
together how much damage you did.
</P>
<P>
   Build into your budget a cushion of up to $100 for unplanned
expenses. Make sure you keep a running tally of how much you spend,
so that you are constantly aware of how much you have left.
</P>
<P>
   Add your credit card purchases to your checkbook register. As
you subtract credit debt from the available balance in your
checking account, you get a reality check on whether or not you can
afford to give that gift.
</P>
<P>
   Take only two credit cards to the mall.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a card with a zero balance, use it for purchases
that will be paid in full when the bill comes. If not, try to find
the cash to pay for the gifts rather than add to your revolving
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Use the other card _ the one in your wallet with the lowest
interest rate _ for purchases that will be paid over time.
</P>
<P>
   The American Bankers Association surveyed 1,000 consumers last
month and found that only 28 percent had a spending plan for the
holidays. What's worse is that 61 percent underestimated the time
it takes to pay off holiday debt.
</P>
<P>
   The association says it takes at least four months to get rid of
your holiday charges. Just in time for you to muster up enough cash
to pay your tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
