<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN CHIEF RETAINS POWER AS GOVERNORS COME, GO 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ONEIDA INDIAN NATION TERRITORY _ At day's end Sunday, pale pink
sunlight glowed luminously through December clouds huddled over the
western horizon.
</P>
<P>
   The light washed eerily over signs that a half-dozen
demonstrators were waving outside the Oneida Indian Nation's
fabulously successful gambling casino-resort complex here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indians get the gold mine and white people get the shaft,''
read one sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smart Indian, dumb white man,'' read another.
</P>
<P>
   Still another sign reminded gamblers cruising through the gate
for a fun-filled evening of losing money that the casino has been
the target of bomb threats.
</P>
<P>
   The point was clear: Gamble here, and you could end up dead.
</P>
<P>
   Racism and fear-mongering.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly stuff _ especially when you consider that the Oneidas'
entrepreneurial efforts have brought unexpected prosperity to a
previously depressed region of central New York state.
</P>
<P>
   From a bingo hall that local authorities fought to close decades
ago, the Oneidas have created a collection of thriving,
gambling-related businesses on their ancestral land that have
generated nearly 6,000 jobs in the greater Utica area.
</P>
<P>
   Those businesses also pump nearly $160 million annually into
state coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Now state government is locked in a legal battle with these
stubborn, enterprising people that could result in a second Oneida
casino closer to New York City, which currently supplies fewer than
10 percent of the customers to this one.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike gubernatorial administrations, problems seldom have
terminal dates.
</P>
<P>
   This problem the State of New York has with the Oneida Indian
Nation has dragged on for a quarter century, with no end in sight,
unless Gov. George Pataki's administration decides finally to come
to grips with it.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, essentially, is this: The Oneidas have sued,
claiming that the state long ago wrongly grabbed 250,000 acres of
their land.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the vast majority of that land is in the hands of
20,000 private citizens, many of whom are furious over the Oneida
lawsuit despite the dollars the tribe has showered on this region.
</P>
<P>
   The state is negotiating to settle the claim.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Halbritter, the Harvard-educated lawyer who is the chief of
the Oneidas, has made clear that he would like this settled
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The Oneidas don't want title to anybody's house.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they would prefer state permission to install slot
machines at their Turning Stone Casino.
</P>
<P>
   They would like state approval to serve liquor at the Oneidas'
hotel and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, though, any settlement probably would include
the transfer of state-controlled land to the Oneida Nation,
probably in the economically depressed Catskills, which could
benefit greatly from the jobs the Oneidas would provide there.
</P>
<P>
   The very prospect of a casino in the Catskills terrifies big
money interests with heavy investments in Atlantic City casinos _
people like Donald Trump, for instance, who make political
contributions _ so negotiations are slow. Perhaps so slow, in fact,
that the matter won't be resolved during Pataki's second term.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1,100 People of the Standing Stone, as the Oneidas call
themselves, are going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Neither, apparently, is the soft-spoken Halbritter, who has been
the chief for 25 years and has demonstrated an enviable deftness in
tweaking the nose of the State of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Before Harvard, when he was an ironworker, Halbritter returned
to the reservation to bury an aunt and uncle killed in a house
trailer fire. How did this happen, he asked? The local fire company
wouldn't come on the reservation, he was told.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe had to come up with the cash to buy a fire truck,
Halbritter decided.
</P>
<P>
   His plan: bingo.
</P>
<P>
   A court battle with local law enforcement authorities ensued,
and when the dust had settled, Halbritter was the Oneida nation's
first bingo caller.
</P>
<P>
   After that came involvement in the arcane world of Oneida
politics.
</P>
<P>
   It's a world in which the eldest women in each of the three
tribal clans _ turtle, bear and wolf _ jointly select the 27
members of the men's council, which then selects the nation
representative, or chief.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take Halbritter long to figure out that, if he wanted
to be chief, he had only to convince two elderly women that he was
the best person for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Having won election, he then decided that if he was going to
battle the white man's establishment, he would need training and
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   First came a political science degree from Syracuse University.
Then came the Harvard law degree.
</P>
<P>
   And, all the time, the Oneidas were building, building,
building, under his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The creation and growth of this huge enterprise has been largely
Halbritter's work, and he's not finished.
</P>
<P>
   As this has dragged on, New York governors have come and gone.
</P>
<P>
   But Halbritter seems firmly established as the man any governor
will have to deal with for as long as cars pour by bitter
protesters outside the glittering casino.
</P>
<P>
   The casino that has made a penniless people prosperous, proud
and nobody to be ignored any more.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
