<SLUG> BC-PARK-TRAFFIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAN SOUGHT ON ALL-TERRAIN VEHICLES IN NATIONAL PARKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A coalition of environmental organizations urged
the National Park Service on Tuesday to prohibit dune buggies and
other all-terrain vehicles on parkland.
</P>
<P>
   The 68 organizations petitioned Park Service Director Robert G.
Stanton to extend existing restrictions on vehicle use to all
beaches, trails and primitive roads.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey, the Bluewater Network, a San Francisco group that
also has led a fight against noisy jet boats in California
waterways, said it found Jeeps, sand buggies and other off-road
vehicles tearing around 56 of 108 of the nation's largest parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general public is unaware that off-road vehicles are even
allowed in our national parks units,'' said Russell Long, executive
director of Bluewater Network. ``Clearly, this use violates the
charter for our park systems, which is to keep resources unimpaired
for future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dennis Cox, editor of Dirt Wheel Magazine in Valencia,
Calif., cited the rapid growth of all-terrain vehicles, reaching
480,000 drivers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental petition would keep much of the public from
enjoying the remote spots, Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think that the outdoors shouldn't be used at all, or it's
for an elite few to look at in coffee-table books and not to
experience,'' Cox said of the environmental coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in favor of responsible use and not abuse,'' he said.
``We want to preserve the environment for our children as well. We
don't want to go out and brutalize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on questionnaires and interviews with park rangers, the
Bluewater Network found that 23 parks allowed off-road vehicles on
beaches as well as on back-country and four-wheel-drive roads.
</P>
<P>
   Another 33 followed a general Park Service policy of prohibiting
off-road vehicles. Yet rangers reported significant illegal use,
according to the San Francisco organization. In many cases, they
saw injury to animals and loss of habitat in deserts, forested
mountains, streams, mud flats and dunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems include endangering and harming wildlife such as
the desert tortoise, Florida panther, piping plovers and bald
eagles,'' Long said. ``The noise angers many other park users who
visit for peace and solitude.''
</P>
<P>
   A 50-page study that accompanied the petition said, ``The use of
the thrillcraft appears to serve as high entertainment for a
privileged minority of motorized `cowboys' who behave as though
national parks are their personal tramping grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The off-road all-terrain vehicles produce 118 times as many
smog-forming pollutants as are produced by modern cars on a
per-mile basis, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, any vehicle that isn't licensed for streets is
prohibited in national parks. In addition, all vehicles must stay
in parking areas, specially designated routes and roads.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists say the agency doesn't go far enough
because it permits vehicles on back-country and unmaintained roads.
In some cases, the national parks may adopt regulations that allow
off-road vehicles in certain areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Bluewater Network already has filed a petition with the Park
Service asking for a ban on Jet Skis, which it has promised to do
in about two dozen parks by January. The group also asked for a ban
on snowmobiles, which the Park Service has said it will propose
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition of organizations behind Tuesday's petition
includes the Golden Gate Chapter of the Audubon Society, the
American Lands Alliance, Friends of the Earth, Greenpeace, the
International Rivers Network, the Sea Turtle Restoration Network
and the Southwest Center for Biological Diversity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
