<HEADLINE>
MAYOR SEEKS MORE HEALTH CLINICS IN HIGH SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ILENE LELCHUK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Advancing his pledge to provide health care to
people without insurance, Mayor Willie Brown said he would put
health clinics in some public high schools next year.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who has been heavily lobbied by student groups asking for
the clinics, is not sure yet how much his plan will cost, where the
money will come from or how many schools might benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's challenger in the Dec. 14 run-off election, Board of
Supervisors President Tom Ammiano, also pledged support for the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is sure that at least a pilot program in several high
schools will be possible next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my next term I'm going to form a partnership with the
school district and we are going to do health clinics in the public
schools. That is how I begin to cover 140,000 people that the
voters said we should cover,'' Brown said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano, a former schoolteacher and school board president, also
said he supports putting clinics in high schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It basically just takes political will,'' Ammiano said.
</P>
<P>
   Election-year promises by Ammiano and Brown are a hit with Youth
Vote, a student civic group that is calling for health centers in
the city's seven comprehensive high schools at an estimated cost of
$1.4 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   Of San Francisco's 22 high schools, only one has a health
clinic. Three schools have nurses who visit one or two days a week.
</P>
<P>
   The student lobbying already has persuaded Brown and the
governing Board of Supervisors to create a $550,000 budget for
clinics in two high schools for the next school year.
</P>
<P>
   The original budget that Brown drafted this summer included less
than half that amount. The students helped to persuade the board to
raise the budget.
</P>
<P>
   The new clinics will not provide full medical services like the
school-based health center at Balboa High School, which costs about
$600,000 per year to run. Instead, the new centers will combine
some treatment with referrals to Department of Health specialists
as well as to private physicians and counselors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping for something bigger _ more schools _ but I'm
just glad we got two schools,'' said Downtown High School student
Shirley Escobar, 17, who participated in the lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's pledge follows his 1998 unveiling of a plan for a
universal health care system, which, if achieved, would be a first
in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for insuring those without health insurance by
pooling money for city, school district and community college
district employees and retiree medical coverage with federal and
state health care funds, then teaming with small businesses to buy
insurance at cheaper rates.
</P>
<P>
   But that program, under scrutiny by public employee unions and
retired employees, remains just a concept.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
