<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HACKERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SAY COMPUTERS VULNERABLE TO ACTS OF TERROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Computer security experts warn that the
United States remains dangerously vulnerable to hacker attacks on
computer and communications networks.
</P>
<P>
   Computer crime costs companies more than $100 million per year,
but a far worse loss _ perhaps in an international catastrophe
triggered by a lone hacker _ is possible, the experts said at a
conference held Monday at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our national security and economy is extremely dependent on
automation,'' said Alan B. Carroll, an FBI agent who works at the
recently formed National Infrastructure Protection Center (NIPC) in
Washington, D.C. ``In fact, it's probably too dependent. We are an
extremely target-rich environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll urged those at the conference to imagine a computer or
communications version of the World Trade Center bombing, a
disaster that brings down, say, computer or telephone networks on
which society depends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that we haven't seen a major disaster and, therefore,
there's no problem is a very slippery slope on which to base your
assumptions,'' computer security specialist Peter G. Neumann told
the conferees. The conference, titled ``International Cooperation
to Combat Cyber Crime and Terrorism,'' was held at Stanford's
Hoover Institution.
</P>
<P>
   The millennium computer glitch, or Y2K problem, has received the
lion's share of attention in recent months, yet it is only the tip
of the iceberg, said Neumann, principal scientist at the Computer
Science Laboratory at SRI International in Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   One concern is that on Jan. 1, a Trojan horse virus disguised as
a Y2K virus could proliferate through world computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   A crash, he said, might prove difficult to resolve, because
investigators might mistakenly blame it on the Y2K bug.
Investigators might take months to spot the virus' true identity,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts fear that many computers originally programmed
to recognize only the last two digits of a year will fail or
malfunction on Jan. 1, 2000, when the machines will assume it is
1900.
</P>
<P>
   Leading companies claimed $124 million in losses in 1999 because
of computer crimes and security breaches, said Richard Power of the
Computer Security Institute in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The losses for 1997 and 1998 were, respectively, $100 million
and $137 million. Power's figures appear in the latest issue of
Computer Security Issues &AMP; Trends, the institute's newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Just one hacker _ the notorious Kevin Mitnick _ accounted for
about $300 million in losses claimed by companies that he
penetrated in the early 1990s, Power said. Mitnick was eventually
arrested and sentenced to 46 months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The losses could be higher, but the survey covered only several
hundred of the largest companies. One problem is that many
companies fail to estimate their losses to computer crime and
breaches, Power said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually international terrorists might try to bring down U.S.
computer networks, Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   The intent of the NIPC, which opened in 1998, is to protect U.S.
society against major threats, including terrorist attacks on
computer and communications networks.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorists are not the only threat, Carroll said. He cited a
case last year in which hackers, including two 16-year-olds in
Cloverdale, Calif., broke into military computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were not Middle Eastern terrorists, and it showed us how
vulnerable we are,'' Carroll said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
