<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1821 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      12-07 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGHT LID, TASTY FISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The classic technique of cooking en papillote is the essence of
minimalism, but this dish streamlines it even further. Rather than
sealing fish and aromatic vegetables in individual packets of
parchment or foil to bake, you just lay the fillets over leeks in a
casserole with a snug lid. The resulting dish combines wonderful
textures and flavors with a minimum of ingredients, no added fat
and almost no preparation or cooking time.
</P>
<P>
   As with the best minimalist dishes, everything counts here: the
flavorful fish; the leeks that stay crisp and assertive, thanks to
the quick cooking time; and a little wine or stock for juice and
flavor. For a little more potent flavor, Dijon mustard provides a
bit of a kick.
</P>
<P>
   As with cooking en papillote, the ingredients, all quick
cooking, essentially steam in their own juices in the tightly
covered container. I use a Corning Ware-type casserole, but any
covered dish that lets a minimum of moisture escape will do the job
perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Doing this in a casserole instead of in individual packages is
not just much easier. It also lets you check on how far the cooking
has proceeded without tearing open the packages.
</P>
<P>
   In this dish I like a thick fish like cod, salmon or halibut.
Leeks are the best member of the onion family here, both because
they do not go limp and because their flavor is strong but not
overwhelming. Thinly sliced onions will do the job nearly as well.
In place of the mustard, you might consider soy sauce; chopped
fresh herbs, like a couple of teaspoons of thyme; or a teaspoon of
curry powder or another spice mix.
</P>
<P>
   This technique is almost infinitely variable but is especially
useful for all types of fish and boneless chicken breasts, which
cook just as quickly and remain fairly moist. If you use a
vegetable that will create some of its own juice, like a thick
slice of tomato, you can reduce or nearly eliminate the added stock
or wine. Or you can just use a sprinkling of olive oil or lemon
juice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FISH BAKED WITH LEEKS  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds leeks, trimmed, washed and chopped
</P>
<P>
   { cup dry white wine, or chicken or fish stock
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard (optional)
</P>
<P>
   About 1{ pounds cod, salmon or other fish fillet, about 1 inch
thick.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Scatter leeks over the bottom of
an ovenproof casserole. Mix with wine or stock, salt, pepper and
mustard. Top with fish, and sprinkle with salt and pepper. Cover
casserole.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bake 10 to 15 minutes, or until a thin-bladed knife meets
little or no resistance when inserted into thickest part of fish.
Uncover, and serve the fish with leeks and pan juices spooned over.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 1548EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT &LR;      12-07 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK: ZINFANDELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ERIC ASIMOV    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zinfandel is America's own wine, which is remarkably liberating
for American winemakers. For once, they don't have to respond to
critics who might otherwise compare their pinot noirs and cabernet
sauvignons with Burgundies and Bordeaux. The grape is turned into
wine only in the United States, hence the attitude, ``We can do
anything we want with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, zinfandel does have family in the Old World. Genetic
testing has linked it definitively to the robust primitivo grape of
southern Italy, which itself is beginning to gain a certain amount
of popularity in the United States. Chances are, though, you will
not see someone sniff a glass of zinfandel and declare it, ``Good
enough, but certainly no primitivo.''
</P>
<P>
   Zinfandel can be rich, luscious and heavy, or it can be light
and breezy. It can be brawny or elegant. And yes, it can be pink
and fizzy. White zinfandel had its heyday in the 1980s, but with
the return to red-wine drinking in the 1990s, original zin is back.
</P>
<P>
   These days, most zinfandels are high-alcohol monsters, often
more than 14 percent and sometimes topping 15 percent, but it
wasn't always that way. Recently, I tasted a mellow Ridge zinfandel
from the late '70s that was not only light-bodied but also only 11
percent alcohol, less than you'd find in almost any wine except
some German rieslings.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, like most good wines, zinfandels cost much more
than they used to. Ten years ago, even the best zins were generally
no more than $15; now they hover around $25. But you can still find
good wines for less. The lower-priced, simpler wines of zinfandel
specialists like Rosenblum Cellars, Ridge and Ravenswood don't have
the structure, power or elegance of the more expensive versions,
but they are reliably enjoyable, as are these six.
</P>
<P>
   MONTEVINA, AMADOR COUNTY BRIOSO, 1997 $6
</P>
<P>
   Fresh, light and uncomplicated.
</P>
<P>
   GALLO OF SONOMA, DRY CREEK VALLEY, 1995 $10
</P>
<P>
   Peppery, lean but attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ST. AMANT, LODI, MOHR-FRY OLD VINES, 1996 $15
</P>
<P>
   Powerful, rich and full of fruit.
</P>
<P>
   GUNDLACH BUNDSCHU, SONOMA COUNTY, RHINEFARM VINEYARDS, 1997 $20
</P>
<P>
   Well-balanced berry and mint flavors.
</P>
<P>
   STEELE, MENDOCINO COUNTY, PACINI VINEYARD, 1997 $22
</P>
<P>
   Elegant with an unusual mint-and-anise scent.
</P>
<P>
   NIEBAUM-COPPOLA, NAPA VALLEY, EDIZIONE PENNINO, 1997 $32
</P>
<P>
   Fruity and herbal with structure and a long finish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
