<HEADER>
A1836 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-RESTAURANT-COMPLAINTS     12-07 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANT-COMPLAINTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GO AHEAD AND COMPLAIN, BUT DO IT NICELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Everyone has a story, or more to the point, a
complaint, about dining out in New York. But Jeffrey Steingarten's
is by far my favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at the old Bouley in that postage stamp-size lounge,''
Steingarten, the food writer for Vogue and author of ``The Man Who
Ate Everything'' (Alfred A. Knopf), recalled last week. ``As we
waited, new people arrived, and we stood together like in the
subway. Finally, after 40 minutes, my wife, Caron, pulled out her
cell phone, called a pizzeria and ordered. In a very loud voice,
she gave the address and said, `We're starving here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``No more than two minutes later, the maitre d' whisked us to
our table. He begged for the name of the pizzeria so he could call
and cancel.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, why didn't I think of that? Why didn't you?
</P>
<P>
   As anyone knows, who's pressed the redial button 50 times to
make a reservation, the restaurant boom has made the complaining
issue more timely than ever. Compounding the problem is the
accompanying shortage of experienced staff, which means the person
to whom you complain, may not know what to do, or may simply be
stretched too thin to be immediately effective.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Zagat, publisher of the Zagat Surveys, says most New York
complaints are about service, noise and crowding. What his survey
doesn't quantify, though, is how some diners manage to get what
they want, while others are left seething.
</P>
<P>
   What is the best way of getting results when you're not happy in
a restaurant _ short of phoning in a pepperoni pie? What can you do
to be seated faster or better, get bad wine replaced or food redone
to your liking?
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to remember, in all cases, is to speak up. But
nicely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any complaint is legitimate,'' says Danny Meyer, an owner of
Union Square Cafe, Gramercy Tavern, Tabla and Eleven Madison Park.
``What's difficult about so many of them is that instead of being
phrased as a simple request, they are covered with layers of
assumed personal rejection.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing personal about bacteria in a cork that was
picked in Portugal and put into a bottle in Bordeaux. But with all
complaints, I'd much rather know right when it happens than hear
someone say on the way out, `We always get the worst table.' The
customers have spent two hours seething and feeling personally
rejected. That's not what most restaurants are trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Being Seated
</P>
<P>
   This very big sore point encompasses being seated on time and
being seated at a table that is agreeable to you.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Friedland, an executive editor at HarperCollins who is
also the director of cookbook publishing, recalls a business lunch
a few years ago at Sushisay in Midtown. Crammed into a table for
two, cheek-by-jowl with others, she requested a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officious maitre d' told me that the only thing available
was the smoking section,'' she recalled. ``Then two men seated on
my right made the same request and were taken to the table I had my
eye on. I sent a letter to the restaurant and got the most lovely
letter back from the owner, who was a woman. She said, `We try so
hard to avoid this kind of treatment, please come back.' I did, and
she made the maitre d' come over and apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is willing to speak up, however. Suzanne Goodson, a
lawyer, says she never complains about the service or the seating,
no matter how bad she thinks it is. ``It makes me nervous,'' she
admits. ``I hate to be with people who make scenes. I was with
someone once who actually sent the water back. I just hate
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Marie Brenner, writer at large for Vanity Fair. ``When a
restaurant does not honor reservations on time, I storm out and
almost never go back,'' she says. ``It happened to me recently at
Tabla. I was so angry, but I couldn't leave because I was in a
group. I feel that restaurants purposefully overbook just to get
people to go to the bar.''
</P>
<P>
   Three approaches, same result: none got the table she wanted
when she wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurateurs are aware of the problem and say there are some
preventative steps diners can take. ``Reservation times are what we
get the most complaints about,'' Meyer says. ``In the restaurant
business, as opposed to the theater, center orchestra is an 8 p.m.
reservation. Orchestra on the side is 7 or 8:30. Mezzanine is 6 and
9. But people don't take it personally when they call the theater
and can't get what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   They certainly do in restaurants. Jerry Della Femina, who opened
a branch of his busy Hamptons restaurant Della Femina in Midtown,
says: ``Everyone wants to book at the same time. When people get
stacked up, we give a complimentary drink to anyone waiting more
than 10 minutes. That goes a long way. People just want you to
acknowledge that you see them standing there.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Recently, my husband and I went to Beacon with another
couple who had made the 8:30 reservation. By 8:50, we were still
waiting. When questioned, the maitre d' led us to a table upstairs.
Our hostess balked. She had requested a table downstairs, closer to
the open-fire cooking the restaurant is known for.
</P>
<P>
   She told the maitre d' how much she had liked her meal the last
time, how eager she had been to return. He smiled and nodded and 15
more minutes passed, while we resumed our position near the door.
Finally, my husband walked through the downstairs and counted six
empty tables for four. Anticipating the traditional restaurant line
about no-shows, he confronted the maitre d'. ``Who are you holding
these for, the Aly Khan?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The maitre d' said: ``Don't worry. I'll give you a bottle of
Champagne.''
</P>
<P>
   I lost it. ``I don't like Champagne,'' I yelled. ``I want to eat
the dinner I was supposed to start 40 minutes ago.''
</P>
<P>
   After some whispered consultations, we were finally seated.
Downstairs. A complimentary bottle of wine appeared, and dinner
proceeded. The food was fine, but I would never go back. Who needs
it?
</P>
<P>
   The flip side to the reservation problem is diners who don't
call to confirm, yet show up expecting to be seated. One of the
Zagat Survey dining tips calls this ``doing your part.'' If you do,
the restaurant will generally hold your table 15 minutes, sometimes
more, though if you are running late, you should call. This is an
area where customers need to take responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Nieporent, an owner of Myriad Restaurant Group, which
includes Nobu and Montrachet, says: ``My motto has always been
`nice gets nice.' But if people walk into a busy restaurant and
have no reservation and lie or they never called to confirm, I'll
say, `We'll try to work with you.' If they're nice, I'll jump
through hoops of fire to help them. But if someone does what I call
a verbal mugging, dropping a million names and trying to bully his
way in, I say, `There's nothing I can do.'''
</P>
<P>
   To review: If you have confirmed the reservation, arrived on
time and have been kept waiting more than 10 or 15 minutes (and
didn't yell), you may reasonably expect a free drink and an
apology.
</P>
<P>
   Corked Wine
</P>
<P>
   Is it or isn't it? This is a sensitive subject, especially with
expensive bottles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wine is not like a pair of shoes that you can sell to another
person,'' Nieporent says. ``At the moment the wine is tasted, the
risk is taken. You don't change your mind five minutes later after
the other people at the table decide they don't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Cannon, an owner of Judson Grill, says: ``Corked wine
happens all the time. The wine industry has expanded, and there's
not a supply of corks sufficient to meet the demand. We'll always
take it back. If it's bad, we'll throw it out, but if it's not,
I'll give it to the bartender to sell by the glass.''
</P>
<P>
   To review: If you know what you're doing, you won't have a
problem. If you don't, consider beer.
</P>
<P>
   Solo Dining
</P>
<P>
   This can be a sore spot, especially with women. One woman I know
recently went alone to the newly opened Morrell Wine Bar and Cafe,
and the maitre d', faced with a sea of empty tables, led her to the
back corner, behind the swinging kitchen door. She refused. After
insisting that all seats were reserved, he finally moved her up
front. When another single women came in, she was led to the
original spot, where she sat uncomplaining.
</P>
<P>
   All the owners I spoke to applauded the woman who spoke up for
herself. ``Be direct and ask,'' Meyer says. ``Don't take anything
personally. Our goal is the same as the diner, for you to leave the
restaurant happy. Do us a favor and give us clues.''
</P>
<P>
   Della Femina agrees. ``The real terror is the customer who won't
tell you what's wrong, but leaves the restaurant and tells the next
500 people they see.''
</P>
<P>
   To review: Sit where you're comfortable, but don't be
unreasonable. No one will give you the table for four, so forget
it.
</P>
<P>
   Food
</P>
<P>
   Here's the good news. When the meal finally shows up, people are
happy to eat it. Though Cannon says, ``They'll ask for a duck
breast well done and then complain that it's tough.'' But not only
will he take it back, he'll send dessert.
</P>
<P>
   So the moral of the story is this: If you want to be treated
well by a restaurant, treat the restaurant well. Confirm your
reservation. Be on time. And don't act out. You have not become
Louis XIV simply because American Express issued you a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a complaint, identify it and deal with it when you
have it. If the restaurant behaves badly, don't go back. And if
that's not enough, buy a voodoo doll, take out an ad or open a
place of your own.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe most important, remember Ms. Friedland's advice in the
face of all restaurant adversity: ``It's just a meal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
