<HEADER>
A1849 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      12-07 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A $500 CELLAR, PRESENT COMES BEFORE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long ago, it would have been relatively simple to conjure up
a modest little wine collection costing about $500. A case of this,
a case of that, a few bottles of something else and you had an
authentic ``cellar.''
</P>
<P>
   I recalled those days recently while leafing through a catalog
from a New York wine shop. It listed the 1996 Romanee-Conti,
admittedly a good Burgundy, at $2,500. Not for a barrel, not for a
case, but for a single bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Romanee-Conti is for collecting. Even in these flush
times, not many of us are going to open a bottle like that with the
lamb chops. But does it mean that amassing a decent wine cellar is
no longer possible for people of modest means? Not at all. You can
still begin with $500, or even less.
</P>
<P>
   If the longest journey starts with a single step, there is no
reason why a good wine cellar can't start with two or three
bottles. Every wine cellar begins with the decision to buy a few
extra bottles for future use _ even if the future is next month.
</P>
<P>
   There are no rules. Well, maybe one: buy only what you like.
Last week, writing about the physical aspects of a wine cellar, I
mentioned a fellow who, suddenly enamored of classical music,
bought an instant collection of musical masterpieces, most of which
he never played. Had he bought slowly and judiciously, he might
have created a record library to enjoy for years.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with wine. Too many people buy wines they think they
should have, rather than wines they enjoy. A Beaujolais fan should
try half a dozen different Beaujolais, then buy a case of the one
he likes best.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't the purpose of a wine cellar to store valuable wines
that need aging? Not necessarily. It's a place to store the wines
you like to drink right now. After you have accumulated a stock,
then you might choose to invest in good Bordeaux or California
cabernets that will benefit from aging.
</P>
<P>
   Building up a cellar of reasonably priced wines will force you
to become eclectic. For variety's sake, you will want to try
Italian wines, Spanish wines, Chilean wines, other varieties of
French wines. If you like Champagne, buy half a dozen brands. If
you like sherry or port, add a few. None of this need be done
overnight, but you'll be surprised how fast your cellar grows.
</P>
<P>
   If you are relatively new to wine, buy bottles or mixed cases at
the outset. Not sure what white wine you prefer with fish? Make up
a case: from France, a couple of Sancerres, a Quincy, a Macon
blanc, a St.-Veran and a petit Chablis; from California, two
chardonnays, a sauvignon blanc and a dry chenin blanc; a pinot
blanc from Oregon; and a pinot grigio from Italy. Decide which you
prefer and buy a case of each. Remember, there is almost always a
10 percent discount on a case.
</P>
<P>
   Do the same with reds: from France, go for the cru Beaujolais,
like Fleurie and Morgon; try some lesser-known Bordeaux chateaux,
and some reasonably priced wines from the Rhone like Gigondas and
Cotes du Rhone. For my money, Italy has left every other wine
country far behind when it comes to moderately priced reds. There
are literally dozens of great wines from every part of the country,
from the Alps to Sicily, from Venice to Sardinia.
</P>
<P>
   From California, there are cabernet sauvignons and merlots and
zinfandels. Oregon offers good pinot noirs, and Washington State
has its own style of cabernets and merlots. Determining which ones
you like enough to add to your cellar can be a long and delightful
task.
</P>
<P>
   Being cautious will mean that you will know all your wines and
can deploy them intelligently. All these everyday wines can be
found at $20 a bottle or less, which means a good working cellar
can be pulled together relatively quickly.
</P>
<P>
   At that point you might begin to think of laying down some
better wines, like barolos and barberas from Italy, good Bordeaux
and Burgundies, the more expensive California cabernets and pinot
noirs. You can buy them early and, with luck, watch them increase
in value.
</P>
<P>
   For those who feel ready to cellar better wines that should
improve with age, the 1998 Bordeaux vintage provides some good
opportunities. These are wines bought as ``futures,'' that is,
purchased now for delivery in 2001 after bottling and aging.
Bordeaux prices are at all-time highs, but there are still some
values for people eager to play in this market, and the wines are
expected to increase in value.
</P>
<P>
   As for that $2,500 Romanee-Conti, at least one critic,
Pierre-Antoine Rovani, recommends holding it for a few years and
drinking the 1997 first. This is a break, if you are into
high-priced Burgundies, because the price of the 1997, which is not
yet released, is expected to be only around $1,400. Put that in
your new wine cellar.
</P>
<P>
   Nice wines for an everyday cellar might include these whites:
</P>
<P>
   Sancerre Chateau de Sancerre, 1997; Lapostolle; $15
</P>
<P>
   Quincy Les Glaneuses, 1998 Jean Sauvion; $10
</P>
<P>
   Sonoma Cask Chardonnay, 1997 Sebastiani; $11
</P>
<P>
   Dry Creek Vineyards Chenin Blanc, 1998; $9
</P>
<P>
   Pinot Grigio, 1998 Alois Lageder; $11
</P>
<P>
   Pouilly-Fuisse, 1997 Georges Duboeuf; $15
</P>
<P>
   And the following reds: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gallo Stefani Vineyard Cabernet Sauignon, 1994; $20 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Strong Pinot Noir Russian River, 1997; $15 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chateau Bernadotte, 1996 Haut-Medoc (Bordeaux); $19 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fleurie, Chateau des Deduits, 1997; Georges Duboeuf; $12 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Notarpanaro 1994, Rosso del Saento Taurino; $10 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chianti Classico Riserva Ducale, 1995; Ruffino; $18 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These Bordeaux are good choices to buy as futures: Chateau La
Grave a Pomerol, $325; Chateau Lafon-Rochet (St.-Estephe), $285;
Chateau de Sales (Pomerol), $290; Chateau La Pointe (Pomerol),
$325; Chateau Canon-Moueix (Fronsac), $185; and Chateau d'Armailhac
(Pauillac), $265. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
