<HEADER>
A1853 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-BROADWAY08-COX     12-07 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BROADWAY08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Leading Ladies' strut their Broadway stuff
 &HT;    By Kathy Janich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any ``Great Performances'' event about musical theater is reason
to salivate, uh, celebrate for Broadway fans outside New York. For
better or worse, it keeps us in touch with the art form we love
most. There's plenty of better here, and a tad too much worse. No,
we're never satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly ``My Favorite Broadway: The Leading Ladies'' is very
good. What takes it down a peg is what _ or who _ isn't here.
Broadway's leading ladies, hmm? Where are Patti LuPone and
Bernadette Peters? Donna Murphy and Betty Buckley? Angela Lansbury
and Donna McKechnie? Liz Callaway and Carolee Carmello?
</P>
<P>
   Still, this special, edited into 90 tantalizing minutes from a
September 1998 Carnegie Hall spectacular, is worth your time, if
just to see Audra McDonald, who, in her 20s, is a three-time Tony
Award winner _ not to mention enjoying still more success in the
Broadway production of ``Kiss Me, Kate.'' She doesn't disappoint,
showcasing her Juilliard-trained soprano on the anthemic ``Love
Changes Everything'' (from Andrew Lloyd Webber's ``Aspects of
Love'') and striking a jazzy, bluesy mood on ``Down With Love''
from the little-known 1937 musical ``Hooray for What!''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Love Changes Everything,'' McDonald _ who sings with the
Atlanta Symphony in April _ is one-third of a showstopper. With her
on this Lloyd Webber tour de force are Marin Mazzie (``Ragtime,''
``Kiss Me, Kate'') doing ``Unexpected Song'' from ``Song and
Dance'' and Judy Kuhn (``Les Miz,'' ``She Loves Me'') doing ``I
Don't Know How to Love Him'' from ``Jesus Christ Superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mazzie's bewitching ``Bewitched, Bothered and Bewildered''
from ``Pal Joey.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Karen Ziemba and Bebe Neuwirth singing and slinking like peas
in a pod to ``Chicago's'' ``Nowadays'' and ``Hot Honey Rag.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Priscilla Lopez still feeling ``Nothing,'' as she re-enacts
her Tony-winning turn in ``A Chorus Line.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Faith Prince sneezing through ``Adelaide's Lament,'' as she
re-enacts her own Tony-winning performance in ``Guys and Dolls.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lea DeLaria scatting through ``I Can Cook Too'' from ``On the
Town.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Cabaret's'' Kit Kat Girls sharing the spotlight and a few
props for ``Life Upon the Wicked Stage'' from ``Showboat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And the legendary Elaine Stritch doing ``Company's'' ``Here's
to the Ladies Who Lunch'' as if it were her first time, not her
thousandth.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's most embarrassing moment? A beefy Liza Minnelli
sloshing through ``Some People,'' that glorious battle hymn from
``Gypsy.'' Liza makes up her own lyrics, her own melody, even her
own rhythms, giving a great impersonation of fingernails on a
blackboard.
</P>
<P>
   And just once could a TV show about musical theater give us a
decent curtain call instead of pulling the camera back to the
balcony so we see teeny-tiny faces as the credits roll. No, we're
never satisified. As Liza would say in her own sloppy,
spit-propelled way, ``Sheesh!''
</P>
<P>
   ``My Favorite Broadway:
</P>
<P>
   The Leading Ladies''
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight on WPBA ; 10 p.m. Dec. 15 on WGTV.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
