<HEADER>
A1854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CADILLAC-SMITH-ART-NY     12-07 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADILLAC-SMITH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I DO BREAKFAST AND I DO LUNCH, BUT DINNER IS FOR MY CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 (Eds: John F. Smith, 48, is in charge of the Cadillac division at
GM and is a rising star in the corporation. He is also the father
of 15-year-old Lindsey and 11-year-old Roland. Robyn Meredith is a
Times reporter.)  (DW) 
 By JOHN F. SMITH with ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We have regional marketing managers and they travel to Detroit
to discuss future marketing plans. Then everyone goes out to
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   For me, it was just one more night away from home. So I said,
``Tell you what. Why don't we have dinner at my house, and when I
say dinner, I mean pizza and beer. I've got a pool table, I've got
a football table.''
</P>
<P>
   They said great.
</P>
<P>
   What I forgot to do was mention it to my wife, Nancy. My
secretary called to make arrangements, and then she caught up with
me on a business trip to tell me I'd better call my wife.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy was a little excited. But I told her, ``We'll order the
pizza, and I've already got the beer.''
</P>
<P>
   We had a great time. We probably had 20 or 22 people at the
house. The kids had a hoot. People were playing with their game
tables. Nancy was down there shooting pool with them, too.
</P>
<P>
   You have to plan way ahead to make sure you can play equally
well to your personal and professional life. I'm going to be
missing meetings occasionally because of my kids' audition or
performance.
</P>
<P>
   But when they're looking for you and they see you, and you see
the smile that breaks on their face, you know it really means
something to them. That's worth missing a business dinner. It is
worth cutting a meeting short.
</P>
<P>
   I don't see the kids in the morning. I leave at 6:30, and I'm
usually at work by 7. If people ask me to dinner, I'll say I can do
breakfast or I can do lunch.
</P>
<P>
   When my kids' school calendars come out, I lay their events in
my calendar and, to the extent that I'm able, work around them.
Sometimes things are scheduled on top of those days that are
precious to me, and as many days as not, I may be late to those
meetings or not going to dinners that conflict with their
performances. I try like crazy to be home as many times for dinner
with the kids as possible. When 6 o'clock rolls around, I try to be
in the car so I can get home and ask them the 20 questions that
drive them crazy about what they did at school today.
</P>
<P>
   I have not made every teacher conference. I haven't made every
performance. I remember one occasion when we had
take-your-daughter-to-work day, and Lindsey was interested in
coming. I was out of the country. There was not much I could do.
</P>
<P>
   I probably do better than most in terms of making some conscious
choices. I only have a few years to be part of their lives and to
instill in them a notion of family. I just choose as often as I can
in their favor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
