<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Dec. 7, 1999   Editors  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: POSTAL-CRUSH; SCOTUS-OIL; SCOTUS-RECORDS; BUSH-2000;
COMPUTER-HACKERS; PARK-TRAFFIC; MONEY-BAG; SCHOOL-CLINICS;
MONEY-COLUMN; and FBC-UH-COACH.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-WARNING (Washington) _ George Roberston, NATO's
secretary-general, warns Russian leaders that their threat to kill
all residents left in the Chechen capital of Grozny on Saturday is
``utterly unacceptable.'' Russia's threat, targeted at civilians,
``is something civilized, decent people are not willing to
tolerate,'' he says. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   POSTAL-CRUSH (Washington) _ With the annual crush of holiday
mailing under way, the U.S. Postal Service announces that it has
posted its fifth consecutive profitable year. By ANDREW BROMAN.
</P>
<P>
   PEARL-HARBOR (Washington) _ The nation's capital marks the 58th
anniversary of the surprise attack on Pearl Harbor with solemn
wreath-laying ceremonies and a sharp debate over who was
responsible for the lack of readiness by U.S. forces that allowed
Japanese planes to pull off a historic raid on the U.S. fleet. By
CHARLES J. LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-OIL (Washington) _ The Clinton administration asks the
Supreme Court to rule that petroleum tanker operators must comply
with federal regulations designed to prevent oil spills, not
standards set by state governments. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-RECORDS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court upholds a
California law limiting access to police records containing the
names and addresses of arrested suspects and crime victims. By a
7-2 vote, the justices said the law does not trample on the rights
of companies that would use the information to solicit business
from suspects or victims. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Undated) _ George W. Bush, in the wake of his second
debate, may be finding his winning smile may be his worst enemy
when it turns into a smirk. Political experts say it can work
against him if it becomes part of the larger picture of the ``empty
suit.'' Bush defended himself against the smirk in a news
conference that focused more on Bush's attitude than what he said
in the debate. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-ENDORSE (Washington) _ Three liberal House members from
the West Coast _ Democratic Reps. George Miller and Pete Stark of
California and Jim McDermott of Washington _ endorse Bill Bradley
for president. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HACKERS (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ Computer security experts
warn that the United States is dangerously vulnerable to hacker
attacks on computer and communications networks. Computer crime
costs companies more than $100 million per year, but a far worse
loss _ perhaps in an international catastrophe triggered by a lone
hacker _ is possible, the experts say. By KEAY DAVIDSON. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   PARK-TRAFFIC (San Francisco) _ A coalition of environmental
organizations is urging the National Park Service to prohibit dune
buggies and other all-terrain vehicles on parkland. The 68
organizations petitioned Park Service Director Robert G. Stanton to
extend existing restrictions on vehicle use to all beaches, trails
and primitive roads. By JANE KAY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-BAG (Dallas) _ A man and woman who found a paper bag
stuffed with $300,000 in Dallas have turned it in to the police.
Besides the trove of cash, the bag contained a handgun and
ammunition. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-CLINICS (San Francisco) _ Mayor Willie Brown and his
opponent in this month's run-off election both support a plan
sought by students to provide health clinics in public high
schools. Brown sees it as a larger part of his goal to provide
health services to the city's uninsured residents. By ILENE
LELCHUK. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Houston) _ As tempting as credit cards are around
the holidays _ not to mention the tennis bracelet, the Big Bertha
stainless steel irons or the Barbie Dream Kingdom that could be
bought with extra credit _ resist the urge to take a break from
paying your bills. By SHANNON BUGGS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-UH-COACH (Houston) _ University of Houston Athletic Director
Chet Gladchuck denies a broadcast report that says former Nebraska
football coach Tom Osborne will be the next coach at Houston. By
JERRY WIZIG. With: FBC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ This is a happier Christmas for
Hillary Clinton than last year's holiday when her husband faced an
impeachment trial. She showed off the White House decorations this
week in what may be one of her last official acts as first lady.
She won't be around much after she moves to New York and trades her
role as president's partner for that of Senate campaigner. By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
