<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Wednesday, Dec. 8. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ALBRIGHT (Jerusalem) _ As Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright was about to land here Tuesday night, Ehud Barak, the
prime minister of Israel, sought to defuse growing tensions with
the Palestinians by pledging to halt the expansion of Jewish
settlements in the West Bank. Barak stopped short of baldly
declaring a freeze on construction, partly _ and unsuccessfully _
to avoid provoking the right-wing members of his coalition. But, in
an unexpected change of approach, he called a moratorium of several
months on new settler neighborhoods to avert confrontation during a
delicate period, as the parties seek to reach a framework final
peace agreement by February. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST-DAWN (Gisborne, New Zealand) _ The first sunrise of the
new millennium will be a cold and lonely moment as the midnight sun
dips below the horizon near Dibble Glacier in Antarctica, then, a
few minutes later, creeps up again. At the western edge of the
international dateline, the silent Antarctic dawn will take place
14 hours before the big ball descends to mark the new year in Times
Square _ and more than 21 hours before the sun rises in New York at
7:20 a.m. on Jan. 1, 2000. But no one is likely to be there on the
distant glacier to see the century's first dawn. This has touched
off a rough and tumble competition among the islands of the South
Pacific for the claim of being the first inhabited place to witness
the first fresh sunbeams of the future. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-RUSSIA (Primykaniye, Russia) _ Just last week, it was
the Islamic rebels who held this bucolic settlement, a mere two and
half miles from the outskirts of Grozny. But as Russian troops
rushed to encircle the Chechen capital, the outnumbered rebels were
routed in a furious 10-hour firefight against Russian helicopters,
artillery, and tanks. Russian commanders boast about their use of
maneuver and deception. But the most enduring impression from a
three-day visit to Chechnya is of massive firepower. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-DEFENSE (New York) _ Speaking on the anniversary of the
attack on Pearl Harbor, Sen. John McCain on Tuesday called for the
nation to adjust its national security policy to the post-Cold War
era by rebuilding its military to meet the new threats posed by
rogue states, terrorists and ethnic conflicts. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HOMELESS-POLITICS (New York) _ As protests over the arrests
of homeless people mount on the eve of Mayor Rudolf Giuliani's all
but certain U.S. Senate campaign, a mayor who likes to talk tough
is attempting to extract himself from a political crisis by saying
he is misunderstood, and that it is more ``loving'' to get the
homeless off the streets _ and using first-lady-like language of
compassion that his critics say is foreign to him. By Elizabeth
Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   UTAH-CAMP-ATTACK (Cedar City, Utah) _ The survival camp for
troubled youth, from which eight teenagers escaped over the
weekend, is part of a growing number of similar alternative
schools. Over the past several years, the number of such schools
has doubled as parents search for different ways to deal with
difficult teens. Meanwhile, the authorities continue to search for
two youngsters still missing. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE-POLICE CHIEF (Seattle) _ Amid a continuing swirl of
criticism over the police department's handling of the protests
last week that engulfed Seattle's streets and eclipsed the WTO
meeting here, the city's police chief, Norm Stamper, announced on
Tuesday that he would resign. Stamper said that he wished to
``de-politicize'' the investigations that are underway into police
preparations for the trade talks. The demonstrations turned
violent; while police sprayed tear gas at peaceful protesters near
the meeting, they failed to stop the looting done by a small group
of vandals nearby. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TEACHERS-CHEATING (New York) _ Exposing what they called one
of the largest cheating scandals in the recent history of American
public schools, investigators charged on Tuesday that 52 teachers
and principals in 32 of New York City's public schools had helped
students cheat on the standardized tests that help determine how
their school is ranked and whether the students move on to the next
grade. By Abby Goodnough.
</P>
<P>
   MARS-LANDER (Pasadena, Calif.) _ In the aftermath of the failed
$165-million Mars Polar Lander mission, NASA on Tuesday promised a
thorough investigation of its causes and implications and a ``major
rethinking'' of the strategy for the entire Mars exploration
program. The next landing mission, planned for launching in 2001,
may well be postponed for more than two years. That spacecraft is
almost identical to the polar lander and so may have to be modified
to correct any shortcomings revealed in the investigation. By John
Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   MARS-MISTAKES (Undated) _ A string of embarrassing mistakes that
doomed the $125-million Mars Climate Orbiter in September may have
contributed to the apparent loss of the $165 million Mars Polar
Lander, NASA officials and private experts said on Tuesday. Last
month, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration issued a
blistering 45-page report on the loss of the Climate Orbiter, the
first of two spacecraft meant to renew NASA's exploratory push this
year to the red planet. Those findings and recommendations also
suggested ways to avert disaster with the sister craft, which has
now fallen silent since Friday's scheduled landing. By William J.
Broad.
</P>
