<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSHER EGG ROLL SKINS  
 STORING TOMATOES  
 FRESH SEAWEED  
 USING SIFTING FLOUR  
 REMOVING EGGSHELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Where can I buy kosher egg roll skins for a Chinese dinner I
am making at home? And how do you get the small pieces of egg into
fried rice? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Kosher egg roll wrappers, made by Nasoya, are sold in
packages of about six dozen for under $3, and can be found in the
produce section of many supermarkets. If you don't use all at once,
freeze the leftovers for up to 3 months, tightly wrapped in
plastic.
</P>
<P>
   As for the fried rice, the easiest way to create those little
morsels of scrambled egg is to pour beaten eggs into the fried rice
mixture while it's still in the pan. Then stir the rice over high
heat until the egg pieces are cooked through, 1 or 2 minutes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do you recommend storing fresh tomatoes? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. While most vegetables keep fresh longer in the refrigerator,
tomatoes are definitely an exception. In her book Cookwise (William
Morrow, 1997), the food scientist Shirley Corriher writes that
semitropical fruits and vegetables like bananas, pineapples and
tomatoes are at their best stored at around 50 degrees. If they are
refrigerated, these fragile fruits will stop ripening and lose
flavor. Tomatoes are especially delicate, and refrigerating them
will not only dull their bright flavor, but give them a mushy
texture as well. But storing these fruits at room temperature, out
of the line of direct sunlight, is perfectly fine. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Where does one buy fresh seaweed? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In Hawaii, China and Japan, many varieties of fresh seaweed
are commonly sold in markets. But in New York, seaweed is a rarity
because it is quite perishable and demand is low. High-end Japanese
and other Asian restaurants generally import it themselves, but
most Japanese restaurants use either reconstituted dried seaweed,
or frozen seaweed from Chile, Japan or Canada, which I haven't been
able to find in stores.
</P>
<P>
   This said, there are two fresh seaweeds available on a limited
basis. One is fresh wakame. This popular seaweed, often added to
miso soup, has a deep greenish brown color and ruffled edges.
Katagiri a Japanese specialty store in Manhattan (212-755-3566),
sells fresh salted wakame, $2.99 for 500 grams. The other type,
Salicornia, also known as sea beans, is not a true seaweed, but a
spiny plant that grows near estuaries, many in Europe, and is often
used as seaweed or a `sea vegetable.' It has a briny, fresh flavor
and can be eaten raw in salads, or lightly steamed as a vegetable.
Salicornia is available in specialty shops in season, from summer
to early fall.
</P>
<P>
   Since seaweed dries extremely well and will then last for years,
reconstituted dried seaweed (found in packages at most Asian
specialty stores) is probably the best bet for the home cook. If
you are looking for fresh seaweed simply to use as a garnish or as
a bed for shellfish (not to eat), friendly fishmongers and
specialty stores will sometimes let you have some free. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I do a lot of baking and have noticed that some recipes call
for sifted flour and some do not. What are the guidelines for
sifting flour? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Flour is sold presifted these days, which is why most recipes
do not instruct you to sift (to rid the flour of any impurities or
bits of bran). But sifting is called for when the flour needs to be
lightened and aerated, which makes it easier to fold into delicate
preparations like souffles and sponge cake batters.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to note whether the recipe calls for a measure of
sifted flour (1 cup sifted flour) or for flour that is to be sifted
after measuring (1 cup of flour, sifted). The actual amount of
flour is different in each instance. One cup of all-purpose flour,
measured using the dip-and-sweep method, weighs 5 ounces, whereas
one cup of sifted flour (that is, sifted, then gently spooned into
the measuring cup) weighs only 4 ounces. So make sure to follow the
directions of the recipe you are using.
</P>
<P>
   Since flour settles and compacts, some cooking authorities
advise fluffing it with a spoon or wire whisk before measuring. In
general, the most accurate way to measure flour is to weigh it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is it true that if you drop a shard of eggshell into a
mixture you should use a larger piece of eggshell to scoop it up? I
have heard that the shard will gravitate to the larger piece like a
flea to a dog? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This is just a culinary old-wives tale. In fact, Linda Braun,
the Consumer Service Director of the American Egg Board, warns
against this practice, since there is a minute chance that the egg
shell might contain traces of salmonella. The best solution is to
fish the piece out with a clean utensil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
