<SLUG> BC-TEA-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING TEA ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SHELLY BELZER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Online tea fanatics will ignore www.bengalbay.com at their
peril, but watch out for the terrible puns. The home page has
departments to click on like ``Communitea,'' where tea drinkers
share recipes and discuss topics like the strongest brews they
know. There is also a searchable guide to tea shops, tea bars and
tearooms in the United States, with some in Canada and Britain,
called ``Localiteas.''
</P>
<P>
   Click on that, and a map comes up. Click on the shape of New
York, and up comes a list of tea spots in the Northeast, ranging,
north to south, from the House of Flower Wind in Boston to the
Victorian Rose Tea Co. in Occoquan, Va. The information includes
street addresses, phone numbers, e-mail addresses, hours,
handicapped access and public transportation (where available), but
nothing about the menus.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, the site is a marketplace, providing 17 brands of
tea, including Stash, Eastern Shore Tea Co. and Harney &AMP; Sons,
along with more widely distributed names. Tea drinkers can browse
among black, green, herbal and organic teas. The roster of 80 black
teas, priced from $2.29 (for a box of 20 Foojoy China Oolong bags)
to $7.89 (for a six-ounce tin of Harney's loose lapsang souchong),
includes 11 varieties of Earl Grey, four of them decaffeinated.
</P>
<P>
   There are also tools like tea balls, strainers and infusers. A
gold-plated English tea strainer, for instance, sells for $3.49.
Click for pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Bengalbay.com donates 1 percent of revenue from its sales to the
nonprofit Women in Livestock Development program of Heifer Project
International, helping women to provide for themselves and their
families. Donations from this site go to tea-growing countries.
</P>
<P>
   Tea enthusiasts will also want to know about
www.republicoftea.com, which sells only high quality Republic of
Tea products, including organic, herbal, black and green teas,
prized for flavors like mango, ginger peach and cinnamon plum. An
Earl Greyer (cq) tea is described as ``more of a good thing tea''
(3.5-ounce tin or 50 bags, $8). Teapots and cups are also
available. A tip: the online catalog is called ``Your World
Embassy,'' reached by clicking on ``Journey of Discovery'' and then
the elephant. The site still has rough edges.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other Food Bytes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Food With a Mission &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Alice Waters, the founder and chef of Chez Panisse in Berkeley,
Calif., has joined forces on the Web with Dr. Andrew Weil, the guru
of alternative medicine. She can be found online at
alicewaters.com, a sibling site to Weil's own. For the time being,
Dr. Ruth Westheimer's sexual-health site is also a click away from
the others.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Waters believes that cooking and sharing food connects
people to the earth and to one another. The site offers recipes
from her Chez Panisse cookbooks. You can search by ingredients like
eggplant and garlic, which figure prominently in her cooking. She
also answers questions, for example, on how to give variety to a
vegetarian diet.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Waters is on the board of the Ferry Plaza Farmers' Market in
San Francisco, and there are plans to put a national directory of
farmers' markets on the site. Users will be able to type in their
zip codes and learn where the nearest ones are. Guides to fruits
and vegetables in season, with recipes, are also in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
