<HEADER>
A1882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-CHINESE-BOOK-REVIEW-N     12-07 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECIPES THAT DON'T COMPROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chinese cookbooks often make too many concessions to what can
easily be found in the average supermarket. Others are
interpretive, presenting the author's personal take on the cuisine.
Too few offer uncompromising recipes for classic regional dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese Kitchen'' by Eileen Yin-Fei Lo (William Morrow,
$35) is one of the exceptions. Ms. Lo grew up in Sun Tak, in
Canton, before moving to the United States in 1959. She has taught
Chinese cooking for 20 years and has written six cookbooks. But
this one is her most ambitious, with 250 recipes plus chapters on
Chinese wines, teas, ingredients and culinary history.
</P>
<P>
   It includes definitive, well-tested recipes for familiar dishes
as well as for dishes not often translated onto English menus in
Chinatown. A banquet dish called Buddha Jumps Over the Wall takes
two full days to make and uses more than 27 ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   There are also plenty of surprises. Smithfield ham, steamed with
brown sugar, makes a stand-in for unobtainable Yunnan ham, Ms. Lo
writes. And green tea leaves are used in a version of a classic
shrimp dish from the imperial court of Beijing. If you've ever been
curious about how to prepare jellyfish, Ms. Lo details it for you.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not a book for the easily intimidated. Ms. Lo is
bent on preaching the purity of China's food ways. She offers no
shortcuts; the recipe procedures are exacting and can require many
steps and several sub recipes.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the steps are difficult, and many of the more
confusing ones are carefully _ and beautifully _ photographed in
color. If you were unsure exactly how to insert an air pump into a
neck for Peking duck, turn to the photos.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lo lists few Western substitutions for hard-to-find
ingredients. I'm the type of cook who enjoys perusing the aisles of
bustling Chinatown markets to unearth boxthorn seeds or red dates.
But others with less patience might find it maddening. It took me
more than two hours of shelf searching to put together the
ingredients for the six recipes I wanted to test.
</P>
<P>
   I should have taken Ms. Lo's suggestion and brought along the
book or a photocopy. Then I would have been able to show the
shopkeeper the Chinese characters for the ingredients, which are
included in the informative pantry section of the book.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, I could not find the Tianjin preserved vegetable
(salted bok choi) for the Superior Soy Noodles in any of the
supermarkets I canvassed, so I had to return with the book the next
day. I was finally handed an earthenware crock with an untranslated
label as my prize. But the noodles were worth the trip.
</P>
<P>
   If you are willing to follow Ms. Lo in her mission, you will be
rewarded with often revelatory meals. Each dish I concocted tasted
as if it could have come from my favorite restaurant in Chinatown.
Chives stir-fried with shrimp were complex yet elegant; snow pea
shoots with crab meat were simple to make and delightful to eat.
</P>
<P>
   General Tso's chicken, which Ms. Lo explains goes by a different
name in China, was outstanding: pungent, spicy-sweet and perfectly
balanced. I even made soup dumplings, which burst with hot broth
when bitten into and barbecued pork, things I did not think could
be done at home. Ms. Lo's experienced, straightforward prose urged
me on.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few frustrating inconsistencies in the text. In a
recipe for shark's fin soup, for example, the ingredient list calls
for Chinese red vinegar. On the opposite page, another recipe
specifies Chinese red wine vinegar, while the recipe for the
dipping sauce for soup dumplings calls for Chinese red rice
distilled vinegar. The cook has no way of knowing if these all are
the same or three different vinegars. (They are not all the same.)
</P>
<P>
   A list of mail-order sources would be helpful, too, so you could
track down obscure ingredients _ without having to lug a heavy book
around Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   CHIVES STIR-FRIED WITH SHRIMP (GAU CHOI CHAU HAR) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Chinese Kitchen'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   \ pound garlic chives (see note)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons seafood, chicken or vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   } teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   } pound medium shrimp, shelled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Chinese white rice wine or gin. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash chives well, then pat them dry. Cut hard stems at bottom
into \-inch pieces, and softer green parts into {-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a small bowl, whisk together stock and cornstarch until
smooth. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat a wok over high heat for 30 seconds. Add peanut oil, and
use a spatula to coat wok with oil. Add sugar and salt, and stir
briefly. As soon as you see white smoke, add ginger and hard stems
of garlic chives. Cook, stirring, for 30 seconds, until fragrant.
Add shrimp, and stir well. Add wine and green parts of chives, and
lower heat to medium. Cook, stirring, for 1{ to 2 minutes, until
chives are bright green and shrimp turn pink. Add stock and
cornstarch mixture, and stir until it thickens, about 1 minute.
Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: You may substitute regular chives. If you do so, cut them
into {-inch pieces and add with wine.
</P>
</TEXT>
