<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-RETAIL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND JOB IS A HOLIDAY FROM REAL WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., N.J.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MELISSA STANTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTFIELD, N.J. _ Since it opened last year, the Williams-Sonoma
store here has recruited some pretty high-caliber part-time help.
Among its hires have been a Wall Street analyst, an auditor and a
human resources administrator.
</P>
<P>
   They are not between jobs, and they do not need the money ($6.50
an hour) or the employee discount. What they and others like them
are after is fun and relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   Fun and relaxation? On retail's frontlines? Oddly, yes. For
professionals tethered to tedious or stressful desk jobs, and for
women who delay their careers to care for children, working a cash
register, stocking shelves, even being at the beck and call of
customers can be downright therapeutic.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Glacken, 25, of Edison, N.J., works more than full time
as an analyst for a Wall Street investment bank. To wind down a
bit, he spends one day a weekend as a sales associate at the
Williams-Sonoma in Westfield. ``The pace I go at all day at work is
one of absolutely never-ending phone calls,'' he says. ``At the
store, I get a chance to take it all in: the kids running around,
the people talking about their families, about cooking. I love the
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   For Glacken's colleague, Patty Scanlon, 32, a quality-control
auditor for an industrial gas company who is now on leave to care
for her newborn son, working part time at Williams-Sonoma was a way
to rev up, not decompress.
</P>
<P>
   ``My full-time job wasn't particularly stressful, but all day
long it was business, business, business,'' Ms. Scanlon says. ``My
husband worked at the company, too, and sometimes, that's all we
talked about. I was fairly new to the area, and I wanted to get out
and meet people. At Williams-Sonoma I got to work with people my
own age. We talked about things like cooking. It was just so
different from my full-time job.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every upwardly mobile professional feels the need to be a
sales clerk in his or her spare time, of course. But such a choice
is not all that surprising, according to Barbara Reinhold, a
psychologist and the author of ``Toxic Work: How to Overcome
Stress, Overload and Burnout and Revitalize Your Career'' (Plume,
1997).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sound career-management and life-management tool,''
says Reinhold, the director of the career-development office at
Smith College in Northampton, Mass. ``For somebody who needs to
move around, to spend 40 hours a week in front of a computer, with
no other outlets, is an invitation to depression, anxiety, lower
back pain or abandonment by their immune system.'' Several of her
clients have taken retail jobs for fun, she says, and most are
``either stir-crazy moms of toddlers yearning to hear a complex
sentence again or extroverts who have ended up doing solitary work
such as writing, research or Web design and just need a periodic
hit of people chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Interaction with people is a big attraction for the
moonlighters, but for varying reasons. Perry Dixon, 36, an
industrial designer for ProD, a product-design company, says
working evenings and weekends at Restoration Hardware in Manhattan
helps him do his real job better. ``I'm fascinated by what people
buy and why,'' Dixon says. ``As a professional designer, I rarely
get to see a customer's reaction to what I've designed. Working
retail gives me a sense of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynette Duncan, 29, a human-resources administrator for Qumas, a
software company in Summit, N.J., began working part time at
Williams-Sonoma last year because her husband traveled a lot for
his job. ``I thought rather than sit home alone I'd get a second
job, be productive and meet people,'' says Ms. Duncan, who now
works at the store in Bridgewater, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Fuchs, 51, of Roselle Park, N.J., a full-time receptionist
at a pediatric practice, has returned for a second holiday season
at the Westfield Williams-Sonoma. She says the store and the
customers put her in the holiday spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their motives, the store's manager, Amy Better, 28, is
glad to have the part-timers' help. Because they are having fun,
there is a levity that makes the customers ``less cranky and more
apt to be patient,'' she says. Since the part-timers want to work
during the holidays, they make the season less stressful for the
full-timers who  &UR; have  &LR; to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could quit tomorrow if I wanted to,'' says Jennifer Davis,
35, a materials engineer for the Nuclear Regulatory Commission. Ms.
Davis works up to 20 hours a week at the Restoration Hardware in
Tysons Corner, Va., to keep busy and have fun.
</P>
<P>
   Her day job is in an office and involves a lot of paperwork and
technical writing, she says, so even when she is tired, ``I get a
second wind at the store.''
</P>
<P>
   For people with corporate careers _ or memories of them _ a big
attraction of working part time in a store is a lack of stress.
Jennifer Better, Amy's 35-year-old sister, used to be a brand
manager for companies like Reebok and Tumi but quit after starting
a family.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Better just began her second holiday season at
Williams-Sonoma, and, she said, ``When you walk out the door at the
end of your shift, you really are walking away.'' Her temporary job
has another benefit, she says: It teaches her daughters, age 4 and
2, `that mommies go to work, too.''
</P>
<P>
   So are the professionals who take part-time retail jobs
embarrassed when people they know spot them at the cash register?
Not at all, they say. Working at an upscale store like
Williams-Sonoma or Restoration Hardware is not like working in a
fast-food restaurant, which might give the impression that they are
in financial straits.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the pay is negligible for most of them. Even though
Glacken, the Wall Street analyst, has worked at Williams-Sonoma for
a year, he has to check his pay stub to be reminded he earns $6.50
an hour, the same as the temporary holiday hires. ``Well,'' he says
with a laugh, ``I should ask for a raise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
