<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYER AND EMPLOYEE IN THE WALTZ OF THE CALENDARS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LISA BELKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a changing rhythm in the workplace, a new dance between
employer and employee. Workers are proclaiming that their lives
count, and managers are responding with everything from job sharing
to on-site lactation rooms. I am a beneficiary of this evolution,
and a champion of it. But I never stopped to focus on how it looks
like from the other side _ the boss' side _ until my baby sitter
had a baby.
</P>
<P>
   That little girl was two months old when her mother broke the
news that she had decided to shorten her workweek to four days,
from five. I was racing to finish a book at the time, and I needed
her eight days a week, not four. I adored this woman. More
important, my sons adored her. She had been picking them up at
school since before they could remember, and they so loved their
afternoons at her house that they periodically asked to move in.
</P>
<P>
   How could I, who had left a structured job in the newsroom for a
more flexible life writing books, dismiss another mother for also
wanting to have more time for her children? On the other hand: What
about my work? I knew I couldn't do it in four days.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the decision grid of the turn-of-the-millennium
workplace, says Michael Losey, president and chief executive of the
Society for Human Resource Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Net additions to the work force are the lowest they have been
in half a century,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Translated, that means there are 1 million to 2 million fewer
workers than there are jobs. This is why we are all working longer
and harder. It is also why companies that want to attract and
retain the shrinking pool of good workers (in my case, a great baby
sitter) have to be in the business of helping those workers manage
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be, `We start at 8:30 and end at 5, and this is the
color shirt you wear,''' Losey says. ``Now it's, `What about flex
time? What about alternative work schedules?' It used to be, ``Your
child's sick, that's your problem.' Now it's, `We will pay you to
stay home with your sick child.'''
</P>
<P>
   Employers _ and here's the rub _ expect something in exchange
for all this caring. ``There's a point where the job has to get
done,'' says David Buda, executive vice president of Tzell Travel
in Manhattan which has a staff of 250 people on three floors, most
of them free agents whose success profits the company. To keep them
happy, the company built them a new $20,000 gym and a $70,000
outdoor deck. Exotic trips are awarded regularly and workers are
paid while they are off in Paris or Rio. This year's Halloween
celebration lasted the whole week.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting amid the carefully constructed happiness is the
receptionist, who dreams of being a rock star, and who started
taking off chunks of time earlier this year to promote her CD. ``We
were pulling for her to succeed,'' Buda says, but there was the
pesky problem of all those calls which weren't being answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally told her, `As much as we love you and want to
support you, we also need you here,''' he says. She was offered
three extra unpaid weeks off each year, in addition to her two
weeks of paid vacation, if she agreed to come in the rest of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   I worked out a similar arrangement with my baby sitter. Whenever
possible I cobbled alternate arrangements for Friday afternoons,
relying on friends, grandparents and high school students, who all
had complicated schedules of their own. But on weeks when all else
failed, and particularly on those Fridays when I was out of town,
she took the boys for an extra afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   We made this work for several months until her husband changed
jobs and she and her family moved away. Now my children come home
to an au pair, who doesn't want to even think about having babies
of her own until she finishes school and opens her own child care
center. What she does want, however, is to fly home to Halifax for
Christmas and stay there through New Year's _ if that's OK with me.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I have a deadline smack in the middle of those 10 days,
and my husband is on call. But she's wonderful with the boys, we're
lucky to have her, and I can write early in the morning if I really
have to. So she's booked her nonrefundable ticket, and I've blocked
out an unscheduled vacation. If my first column of the new year is
a little late, I'm sure my editor will understand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
