<HEADER>
A1891 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-REFLECTIONS-BOOK-REVI     12-07 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFLECTIONS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REFLECTIONS ON A RAVAGED CENTURY': `ISMS' IN PRISMS OF HISTORICAL
HINDSIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Conquest calls Part I of his new book ``Mindslaughter,''
which is a suggestive and potent neologism if ever there was one.
Part II is ``Facing the Consequences,'' and anyone familiar with
this distinguished British historian's work will be able to guess
what consequences Conquest has in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has chronicled the ravages of the 20th century more than
Conquest has, especially those caused by humankind's fatal and
fateful 20th-century belief that the world can be remade according
to a utopian design. His essential point in his new book,
``Reflections on a Ravaged Century,'' is that ideas were at the
root of 10 of millions of unnecessary deaths. They were, Conquest
writes, `` &UR; ideas &LR;  that claimed to transcend all problems, but were
defective or delusive, devastated minds and movements and whole
countries, and looked like plausible contenders for world
supremacy.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, Conquest is eminently worth reading, even if many of
the arguments one encounters in this new book have a familiar ring
and the book as a whole has a fragmentary quality. Here and there,
especially in Part II, he doesn't so much make arguments as express
irritation, for example, at what he sees as the ideological
excesses of environmentalism and feminism, and the way
``mindslaughter'' has affected liberal education, and the way the
pictorial arts have descended into ridiculousness.
</P>
<P>
   Readers who disagree with Conquest _ and there have always been
many _ will not be persuaded by these somewhat scattershot and
epigrammatic contentions, and those who agree will find little that
hasn't been said before on these topics.
</P>
<P>
   But Conquest is an eloquent and incisive man, and on his main
subjects _ the tenacity of malign ideas and humankind's seemingly
limitless capacity for deceit and self-deception _ he provides many
glowing embers of reasoned and wise argument. There is no crowing
in this book, no triumphalism over how its author, treated in many
circles as a Cold War ideologue, has been demonstrated by the
passage of time and the release of new documents to have been
correct in his most important descriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Conquest's new book is an extended, discursive stock-taking,
like an urbane and erudite after-dinner speech delivered to an
ideologically friendly audience. He muses in melancholy judgment
over the century's great ``isms,'' Nazism and communism. He
searches for the underlying historical reasons that some societies
are closed while others are open. He asks in what ways
``mindslaughter'' remains an affliction.
</P>
<P>
   In one chapter, ``The Marxist Irruption: How and Why,'' Conquest
surveys the characteristics that gave Marx's 19th-century dogma
such appeal. Among them is the interesting idea that Marxism ``had
the advantages of both simplicity and complexity.'' It put forward
a powerful concept: that one class in society would inherit the
earth and in doing so usher in a utopia in which the state would,
as Marx wrote, ``wither away.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Marxism's complexities required that it be
interpreted by an intellectual vanguard. This vanguard thus had a
pretext for occupying positions of extreme power even while
supposedly melding with that working class whose hardships and
calluses it didn't have to suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Conquest cites British parliamentarian Hugh Gaitskill in this
regard: ``Vagueness and complexity are not really limitations, but,
on the contrary, advantages. For they make the task of criticism
tedious and difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The author then turns to what he calls ``a sort of secondary
infection of the mental atmosphere of the West which still to some
degree persists.'' He means the odd and perplexing attraction that
Leninism and Stalinism had for many people in democratic countries,
especially the United States and Britain. Conquest reminds us of
some of the most familiar misjudgments of the Soviet Union, from
George Bernard Shaw's impression that no one was afraid of Stalin
and that ``everyone trusts him,'' to New York Times correspondent
Walter Duranty's failure to report on the devastating man-made
famine in the Ukraine in 1933.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were minds like jelly, ready for the master's imprint,''
Conquest remarks of the many travelers who went to Stalin's Russia
and returned favorably impressed. He accounts for the lapse in
critical judgment in several ways: the good reputation gained by
the Soviet Union for its support of the republicans in the Spanish
Civil War, the shock in the West over the ravages of capitalism,
and the use of the nice-sounding word socialism, which Conquest
calls ``a major mind-trap.''
</P>
<P>
   More sinister, in Conquest's view, was what he calls
``mirror-image McCarthyism,'' by which those who accused others of
being Soviet agents or spies in the West were in turn accused of
``smearing'' people or of being informers. ``If you do not like
communism, you are a red-baiter,'' George Orwell wrote.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear, as Conquest covers this ground _ or rambles
over it _ that he quite accounts for the mystery that he evokes. He
cites W.B. Yeats' famous lines about the best lacking all
conviction while ``the worst'' are ``full of passionate
intensity.'' The reader, especially perhaps the sympathetic reader,
wishes that Conquest had more deeply explored the phenomenon of
passionate intensity, the power of uncomprehending
self-righteousness.
</P>
<P>
   But these ``reflections on a ravaged century'' are just that,
reflections rather than full-fledged examinations. In this sense
they are illustrations of Conquest's own temperament, his effort
over many years to hammer out a humanistic understanding, so that
``mindslaughter'' won't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `REFLECTIONS ON A RAVAGED CENTURY'
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Conquest
</P>
<P>
   317 pages. W.W. Norton. $26.95. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
