<HEADER>
A1905 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AFRICAN-SALSA-NYT &LR;      12-07 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICAN-SALSA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENEGAL TAKES SALSA, ADDS MBALAX AND MAKES MAGIC  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID HECHT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAKAR, Senegal _ There's hardly a sound at three in the morning
in front of Chez Anthiou, a house much like any other on a sandy
middle-class street in this sub-Saharan city. But walk through a
leafy courtyard where couples embrace in the dark and open the
front door to this clandestine club.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, illuminated by just one pink neon light, a self-styled
Latin band, Super Cayor, is performing for a hot and sweaty crowd.
Friday, after the main Islamic prayer of the week, is salsa night.
But if it's an authentic salsa you're after, this is the wrong
place.
</P>
<P>
   On the dance floor the men are mostly still dressed in the long
flowing robes they wore to the mosque. Though many by now are
inebriated, they're mostly still deft at easily fitting the tricky
three-part salsa step into the four-four rhythm without stepping on
their partner's toes. But then, in the middle of a song, Super
Cayor speeds up the salsa beat and mutates it into Senegal's
polyrhythmic brand of Afro-pop known as mbalax. So salsa becomes
something else. The couples let go of each other and dance together
in groups, men lifting their knees into the air, women making
exaggeratedly sexual hip movements and teasing little skips and
jumps that bear little resemblance to anything Latin.
</P>
<P>
   Super Cayor's instrumentation is closer. The percussion section
does not have the essentials for the original salsa sound, like
congo drums, timbales or tumbas. The group has no trumpeter,
trombonist or any brass section at all, but Mbaul Birane Cisse, the
rhythm guitarist, said, ``We do have a toukhoro,'' a traditional
Senegalese wooden flute, ``and we imitate brass instruments on the
synthesizer.''
</P>
<P>
   Super Cayor does have its comparative advantages: a devastating
Senegalese percussion section, consisting of three types of local
sabar drums and the tama, or talking drum. It also has three strong
singers, though only one, Pascal, whose real name is Abdou Fata
Dieng, sings in a vaguely Latin style. The voices of the two
others, Mame Pathe Gadiaga, alias James, and Iba Ndiaye, alias
Mosquito, are distinctively Senegalese, a mix of Islamic and
pre-Islamic West African vocal traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Many of their tunes _ which can be heard on ``African Salsa,'' a
CD compilation issued this year by the British label
Earthworks/Sterns _ are based on Cuban classics. But the lyrics are
in Senegalese languages, either the rhythmic Wolof or the poetic
Serer.
</P>
<P>
   Super Cayor toured Europe over the summer, performing at 14
festivals and seamlessly slipping between salsa and the very
different mbalax, which the singer Youssou Ndour made popular in
the 1980s by fusing traditional Senegalese songs with rock and
jazz. When mbalax and salsa are heard separately, it's hard to
imagine how they could ever work together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the ones that figured out the logic shared by both
kinds of music,'' said Cisse, who is also the band's manager. ``We
are the inventors of salsa-mbalax.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees. Senegal has had many salsa musicians over
the years, many of whom incorporate local mbalax-type rhythms and
musical tunes. Various Latin styles that now fall under the
category of salsa have been popular here since at least the 1940s,
when Senegalese soldiers fighting World War II for France brought
back recordings of Latin bands popular then in Paris. Salsa was the
main pop music throughout much of Africa until the '60s, when
Africans began creating the various forms of Afro-pop, although
salsa never disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Since the earlier 1990s a rotating ensemble of well-known
African and Hispanic musicians have recorded together under the
name Africando. Though their hit song ``Yaye Boy'' is in Wolof, a
dozen or so singers from Cuba to New York have made their own
versions.
</P>
<P>
   Though Super Cayor may sound Latin, it remains close to its
Senegalese roots, taking its name from the ancient kingdom of
Cayor, which fought French colonial domination. The band members
mostly come from Thies, a crossroads town for many of Senegal's
ethnic groups and musical cultures. Two of the group's singers are
from griot families, the musician caste in many West African
societies, who traditionally go from town to village, a little like
troubadours in medieval Europe, singing and reciting local
histories.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the members also all grew up listening to salsa. ``Back
then people thought of salsa as a higher, more civilized form of
music than our own,'' Cisse says. ``We weren't even aware that it
was rooted in the music slaves brought from here to the New
World.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisse remembers the moment he became aware. He was listening to
a 1960's recording, ``Bembeya Jazz,'' from neighboring Guinea.
``Suddenly I realized there was something very familiar about the
rhythm,'' he said. ``It's no coincidence salsa and mbalax can be
interchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the musicians liked the idea of salsa-mbalax, Cisse
said. ``Some thought of it as old-fashioned.'' One even quit the
band, he said without specifying which one. ``But after a few
months he saw we were pulling in big crowds and he begged me to let
him back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Cuban salsa is almost forgotten in Senegal. ``Salsa-mbalax
is more alive,'' said Pierrot Ndour, an accountant who is often at
Chez Anthiou, ``because of course it doesn't have to follow the
rules.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
