<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Dec. 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A potent area of low pressure will move out of the southern
Rockies and into eastern Texas on Wednesday, bringing a swath of
snow with it. Snow will be heaviest in the front range of the
Colorado Rockies and will extend out into the Plains of eastern
Colorado and western Kansas. On the eastern edge of the
precipitation, there will be some rain mixing with the snow. Snow
will also fall in the mountains of New Mexico and eastern Utah.
Ahead of the low pressure system, moist flow from the south out of
the Gulf of Mexico will lead to showers in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Farther east, high pressure will dominate the weather across the
Middle Atlantic states and into the Northeast. Very warm air over
this region will lead to afternoon readings being as much as 15 to
20 degrees above seasonal levels in spots. Most of the Southeast
will also be sunny and mild, although a few clouds and showers are
possible across the southern portion of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds will be found across the northern Plains ahead of an area
of low pressure crossing the Canadian Prairie. Behind this front,
winds will descend the northern Rockies, drying the air and
bringing periods of sunshine to the far western Plains of Montana
and extreme northern Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another Pacific storm will approach the Northwest Coast on
Wednesday, triggering some showers in coastal Washington. Most of
the rain associated with the system will remain offshore, however.
Farther south, abundant amounts of sunshine will stretch from
southern California into the deserts of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Jet Stream &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jet stream winds over 180 mph were clocked at 30,000 feet above
the western Pacific on Tuesday. Coming on the anniversary of the
bombing of Pearl Harbor, the observation was a reminder that the
sub-tropical jet stream was discovered during World War II. Before
then, high cirrus clouds streaking across the tropical sky had
hinted at fast westerly winds aloft. Proof of the jet stream's
existence waited until head winds forced U.S. bombers enroute to
Japan to turn back. Once, a bomber with an air speed of 200 mph
encountered mighty head winds that reduced the plane's ground speed
to zero. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
