<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-ENDORSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE LIBERAL HOUSE MEMBERS ENDORSE BRADLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley's long-shot presidential
bid received the backing of three House Democratic members from
western states Tuesday, raising his Capitol Hill endorsement total
to six House members and three senators.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's latest backers _ Reps. George Miller and Pete Stark of
California and Jim McDermott of Washington _ cited his universal
health care plan and pro-environment record as the main reasons for
their decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley has put forward a big solution to one of the
biggest problems facing Americans today,'' Stark said, referring to
the 44 million who have no health insurance, 14 million of them
children. ``Mr. Bradley is the only candidate who's been willing to
say this is a problem we must address ... realizing there's a cost
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's congressional endorsements have been dwarfed by the
more than 130 that his competitor for the Democratic nomination,
Vice President Al Gore, has collected.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has consistently led Bradley in the polls, sometimes by as
many as 30 percentage points. Bradley, however, has gained on Gore
in New Hampshire, which holds the nation's first primary on Feb. 1.
A recent poll in the Concord (N.H.) Monitor put the two in a dead
heat with Gore at 45 percent and Bradley at 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott, a psychiatrist who represents Seattle, said at a news
conference that both Gore and Bradley ``are good candidates and
would make good presidents. It isn't that we have anything bad to
say about Al Gore. We really feel Bill is the best one to do the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said: ``It really is about understanding what needs to be
done so we can stop the number of children who are losing health
care, stop the number of children not getting an adequate
education, and start closing the gap between minority and majority
children in our educational system.''
</P>
<P>
   The three especially praised Bradley's health plan, which he has
said would cost $55 billion to $65 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has criticized the plan as too costly and potentially
damaging to those with some insurance coverage. Bradley seemed to
play into Gore's hands last week when he said he would, if
necessary, consider raising taxes to pay for his plan.
</P>
<P>
   Stark said voters don't care much about the tax-hike issue
although, he added, ``maybe they will when all they get to see is
15-second sound bites. For now, we have the luxury of talking about
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller praised Bradley's environmental record, saying he was a
leader in a 1992 congressional battle over legislation to allocate
scarce water in California's agricultural Central Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. Bradley was willing to take this fight on ... in the face
of a very well-organized constituency of large corporate farmers''
who threatened to withdraw financial support from lawmakers and
work against them unless they supported these farmers' water needs,
Miller said. ``He showed a great deal of integrity, courage and a
lot of skill in negotiating this through the Senate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
