<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLALOTTERY-HOWMANY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What's your game? A lot depends on your economic status
 &HT;    (EDS: Part One/Sidebar _ runs with FLALOTTERY-MAIN1.)
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Though three out of four Floridians play the
Florida Lottery, how much they gamble and what games they play vary
widely.
</P>
<P>
   For most middle-class and well-to-do Floridians, lottery means
Lotto, the agency's flagship game that dangles millions, even tens
of millions, as a possible reward for a $1 bet.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Palm Beach Post newspaper computer analysis, the
best-educated Floridians spend an average $102 a year per person on
lottery tickets _ 51 percent of it on Lotto. A mere 16 percent goes
toward Cash 3 and Play 4 _ the daily games modeled after the
illegal numbers rackets that predate the advent of modern state
lotteries.
</P>
<P>
   In the poorest, least-educated neighborhoods, those percentages
are almost completely reversed.
</P>
<P>
   In the 25 neighborhoods with the lowest education levels, the
average lottery spending was $221 per person _ only 21 percent of
it on Lotto and 36 percent on the daily games.
</P>
<P>
   The considerably higher per-person spending meant residents of
poorly educated neighborhoods still spent nearly as much as their
well-educated counterparts on Lotto; it's just that they spent four
times as much on Cash 3 and Play 4.
</P>
<P>
   Why the great interest in games whose top prizes are $500 and
$5,000?
</P>
<P>
   Because, said Duke University lotteries expert Philip Cook,
those smaller jackpots aren't so small to those who don't make much
money to start with.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people who are just getting by, those numbers are very
good,'' Cook said. ``For more comfortable people, those three-digit
winnings are not the stuff fantasies are made of.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, whether Cash 3 or Lotto, the long-term payoff is
statistically the same: For every $1 you win, you will have paid $2
for the pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the daily games and Lotto is the odds.
</P>
<P>
   Betting $10 a night on Cash 3, and its 1,000-to-1 odds, you will
likely have won the $500 top prize once after just 3 1/2 months,
but will have spent $1,000 doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Betting $10 two nights a week on Lotto and its nearly
23,000,000-to-1 odds, you will _ if you could somehow live so long
_ likely have won an $11.5 million jackpot after 22,000 years. You
would have gambled $23 million winning it.
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 1742EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1921 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLALOTTERY-MAIN1-COX     12-07 1905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLALOTTERY-MAIN1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lottery draws least-educated, poor
 &HT;    (EDS: Package one/Part one; runs with FLALOTTERY-HOWMANY.)
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ If your first-grader gets to attend
brand-new Binks Forest Elementary in Wellington next month, thank
Delray Beach appliance installer Howard Anthony James.
</P>
<P>
   If your daughter goes to Florida State on a Bright Futures
Scholarship, thank West Palm Beach shipyard retiree Eddie
``Cowboy'' Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's James _ $10 in lottery tickets a day _ and Brown _
$20 to $30 a day _ and hundreds of thousands like them in Florida's
least-educated, poorest communities who disproportionately buy
Florida Lottery tickets _ and thus lighten the education tax load
on everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   How disproportionately?
</P>
<P>
   People in Florida's least-educated neighborhoods spend an
average of $221 a year on lottery tickets, twice what those in the
best-educated areas spend, according to a Palm Beach Post newspaper
computer analysis.
</P>
<P>
   If income is factored in, the contrast becomes yet more stark:
Florida's least-educated spend nearly seven times as much of their
income on lottery tickets as Florida's best-educated, 2.35 percent
compared to 0.35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   These spending patterns have not gone unnoticed by the lottery:
In Florida's least-educated neighborhoods, there are three times as
many lottery outlets _ convenience stores, liquor stores, even pawn
shops and payday loan stores _ as there are in the better-educated
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   And now, lottery marketing experts want to promote the low-prize
games favored by players like Brown and James to increase sales
even more next year, according to documents obtained by The Post.
</P>
<P>
   The Post's findings match patterns nationally. What sets Florida
apart are the games' proceeds, much of which now flow to
public-school construction and state university scholarships. The
overwhelming majority of the new schools built with lottery money
are in middle- and upper-middle-class suburbs _ the fastest-growing
neighborhoods in Florida. Almost 90 percent of the university
scholarships generated by the lottery go to middle-class and
affluent children.
</P>
<P>
   Which means this: The poorest, least-educated Floridians bear
the greatest burden paying for new schools their children don't
attend and scholarships their kids rarely win.
</P>
<P>
   Players are not equal
</P>
<P>
   Approved by voters in 1986, the Florida Lottery has been running
instant, daily and weekly games since 1988. It, like other
lotteries in other states, is the single largest gambling
enterprise in Florida, selling about $2 billion in tickets each
year.
</P>
<P>
   But while the lottery depicts a Florida where nearly all its
residents participate in a harmless, entertaining fashion and
roughly equally across ethnic and socio-economic boundaries, The
Post's analysis rebuts that contention.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery play is closely tied to educational attainment. In the
100 neighborhoods with the most poorly educated adults, per-capita
lottery spending was $177 in budget year 1998-99. In the 25
least-educated neighborhoods _ where an average 58 percent of the
adults did not graduate high school _ the per-person spending is
$221.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, spending in the 25 most highly educated
neighborhoods _ where only 8 percent of adults haven't graduated
high schools and nearly half have a bachelor's degree or higher _
is $102 per person.
</P>
<P>
   The 25 poorest neighborhoods have per-capita lottery spending of
$191. The 25 neighborhoods with the greatest proportion of blacks
spend $182 a person, while the 25 most Hispanic neighborhoods spend
an average $224 per person on lottery tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery, meanwhile, has made it easier for their best
customers to buy their tickets, flooding those communities with
ticket vendors.
</P>
<P>
   In the 25 most poorly educated neighborhoods, there are 973
residents per lottery vendor. In the 25 best-educated
neighborhoods, lottery vendors are nearly three times as scarce:
2,521 residents per outlet.
</P>
<P>
   The Post's findings match those of the lottery itself, which, in
an August 1998 survey, found that college graduates
disproportionately make up the Floridians who never play the
lottery. Conversely, high school dropouts are disproportionate
among those Floridians who play it the most.
</P>
<P>
   The Post's results also closely match those of the National
Gambling Impact Study Commission's survey released this summer of
more than 6,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   A call for limits
</P>
<P>
   That report found that 20 percent of all lottery players buy 82
percent of all the tickets. And within that 20 percent, there are
twice as many dropouts and blacks as there would be in the general
population.
</P>
<P>
   In its final report, the commission recommended ``that states
with lotteries reduce their sales dependence on low-income
neighborhoods and heavy players in a variety of ways, including
limiting advertising and number of sales outlets in low-income
areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush _ who said he disliked the lottery's ``something
for nothing'' ethic when he took office but since then has asked
the lottery to increase sales by $524 million over the next four
years _ called The Post's analysis ``potentially flawed'' and
``statistically questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush cited lottery department figures showing that the income
and educational levels of the average player are slightly higher
than those of the average Floridian _ a statistic that fails to
address how heavily or lightly various segments of the population
buy lottery tickets. He did not respond to questions asking him to
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery Secretary David Griffin said he didn't accept the
methodology of matching lottery sales in a particular neighborhood
with overall demographic characteristics. ``That right there, to
me, is flawed,'' he said, adding that the analysis could not tell
which residents within a particular neighborhood were buying the
most or fewest tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin, who worked at the Ohio Lottery prior to coming to
Florida in July, added that he was not familiar with the national
commission's study results.
</P>
<P>
   Other lottery experts, however, validated The Post's approach.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Cook, a professor of economics and sociology at Duke
University and the author of a book and numerous academic articles
on state lotteries, said the sales-to-neighborhood analysis, while
not perfect, is useful. ``It gives you a rough idea of what's going
on,'' he said. ``There's no perfect method.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally known anti-gambling activist Tom Grey said lotteries
around the country try to dismiss statistics that show heavy
lottery sales in poor, largely minority communities. But if the
communities' residents aren't buying all those tickets, Grey asked,
who is?
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a lot of wealthy people driving into those poor
neighborhoods to buy their tickets?'' Grey wondered, laughingly.
``Most people avoid those neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Florida Lottery's own surveys show that most
players buy tickets in their own neighborhoods for the sake of
convenience. The August 1998 survey found that up to 77 percent of
players buy their tickets close to home, while 11 percent buy them
near work and the remainder buy them at both places.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin did not dispute the heavier concentrations of lottery
vendors in poor neighborhoods, but said that is a function of
zoning laws and the locations of convenience stores and mom-and-pop
grocers that have traditionally wanted to sell tickets. ``It's just
the way the layout is,'' he said. If poor people are playing the
lottery more, he added, that's their right as adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell anyone, whether they are poor, whether they are
wealthy: The lottery is here. It offers hope,'' Griffin said. ``I
wouldn't want anyone to buy a lottery ticket instead of a loaf of
bread. But you know what? If they are, that's their choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Lottery as a pastime
</P>
<P>
   Lottery players in the poor neighborhoods that accounted for
some of the top sales in Palm Beach, Martin and St. Lucie counties
told The Post that they buy lottery tickets _ $10, $20, up to $100
a day _ for the entertainment value and with more of a sense of
resignation than hope. They know they are losing money.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 80, the shipyard retiree, said he won $5,000 in July but
knows he spends more than he's won. ``I'm not married and I guess
it's a habit,'' he said. ``Whatever I have, I play.''
</P>
<P>
   James, 45, the appliance installer from Delray Beach, said he is
irked that poor neighborhoods do not see the new schools that the
wealthier areas are getting from Lottery proceeds, but he continues
to play anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``A poor guy like me is going to work and make a million and buy
a Mercedes?'' asked James. ``I play and I'm still losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, at the same time, players tell the lottery's marketing
consultants their main reasons for buying tickets are ``to make
extra money'' and ``to fulfill dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambling experts said the contradiction is typical among
frequent gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see themselves as lucky,'' said Robert Ziller, a
professor of social psychology at the University of Florida and a
former Air Force psychologist in Reno, Nevada. ``They see
themselves as in control. Of course, in order to do that, they have
to fudge the figures in their minds. . . . They selectively attend
to the wins and not to the losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke University's Cook, who co-authored the national gambling
commission's survey this summer, said poorer, less-educated players
particularly are prone to the superstitions, such as numerology and
astrology, that attempt to turn picking numbers into a science.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes more like investing in the stock market than
rolling the dice,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   But whether players know exactly what they're doing is beside
the point for gambling foes. The real question, said Stanley
Marshall, director of the conservative James Madison Institute in
Tallahassee: Ought state government encourage and profit from the
lottery habits of the worst off?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to live to see the day when we've either abolished the
lottery or changed it so it doesn't exploit the poor,'' said
Marshall, a former president of Florida State University.
</P>
<P>
   Answered Lottery Secretary Griffin: ``The people voted and said,
`We want a lottery.' I'm not going to debate about whether it's
wrong or right.''
</P>
<P>
   HOW THIS SERIES WAS DONE:
</P>
<P>
   _ Sales figures and the locations of the 12,751 Florida outlets
that sold 2 billion lottery tickets in budget year 1998-99 were
obtained from the Florida Lottery and sorted by postal ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   _ Population and demographic data were obtained from the U.S.
Census Bureau for all Florida ZIP codes, and updated using 1998
bureau estimates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tourist centers, outlets on Florida's northern border and
areas where census data could not be linked to ZIP codes were
eliminated from the analysis. Because of this, 9.8 percent of
lottery sales and 6.7 percent of total population were discarded
from the final analysis.
</P>
<P>
   _ Using a computer, the demographic data was linked to the
lottery data, producing a snapshot of the racial and economic
makeup of the neighborhoods surrounding lottery outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Jenny Staletovich contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
