<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-WARNING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN LEADERS BLAST RUSSIAN ULTIMATUM IN CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a growing chorus of outrage, leaders of western
nations condemned Russia on Tuesday for threatening to kill all
residents left in the Chechen capital of Grozny as part of a
campaign to end a move toward independence by the Russian republic.
</P>
<P>
   George Robertson, NATO's new secretary general, warned Russian
leaders that their threat is ``utterly unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's ultimatum for residents to leave Gorzny or face a
massive artillery and aerial bombardment ``is something civilized,
decent people are not willing to tolerate,'' Robertson told
reporters Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after a meeting with President Clinton, Robertson called
the on-going Russian military assault on the city and the looming
threat ``disproportionate'' to the goals they seek.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said western leaders were not trying to isolate Russia
diplomatically. ``The message we give to them is not one of
hostility, it is of constructive advice on how we believe they
could best deal with the serious situation that they confront in
Chechnya,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that they will change their tactics and bear in mind
very much the humanitarian concerns being expressed across the
globe, as well as the implications for surrounding states,'' said
Robertson, who assumed the top NATO post in October.
</P>
<P>
   Russian leaders on Monday issued the ultimatum to Grozny
residents in the form of leaflets air-dropped over the republic
capital. ``You are surrounded, all roads to Grozny are blocked. You
have no chance of winning,'' read one such leaflet. ``Those who
remain will be viewed as terrorists and bandits ... All those who
do not leave the city (by Saturday) will be destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen, while expressing support for
the Russian military's bid to ``combat terrorism'' in the region,
said Tuesday that ``the manner in which they are carrying out this
activity is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said Russian troops ``appear to be engaged in
indiscriminate killing of innocent civilians, and on a rather
substantial scale.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that they must arrive at a political solution and
encourage them to do that,'' Cohen added.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart repeated a warning President
Clinton made Monday. ``They will pay a price for pursuing a policy
that isolates them from the international community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   European leaders expressed similar outrage Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac called the Russian assault
``unacceptable'' and urged a peaceful solution. Italy's Prime
Minister Massimo D'Alema said Tuesday that Russia's ``horrible and
unacceptable'' offensive must stop.
</P>
<P>
   While the West has ruled out a military response to the Russian
actions in Chechnya, European leaders were mulling possible
economic sanctions against Moscow, a topic expected to come up this
weekend at a European Union summit in Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook warned of economic
repercussions if Russia does not reverse course. The West ``cannot
continue to assist Russia if Russia does not respect basic
humanitarian norms,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, however, took a different view on aid to
Russia, saying economic aid to Russia serves U.S. national
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the aid that we provide to Russia, the vast
majority of it is to make our life safer,'' said Lockhart. ``The
vast majority of that aid goes to reducing their nuclear threat,
and I don't know the productivity of removing that assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Humanitarian workers believe that the war in Chechnya has killed
hundreds of civilians, while causing up to 200,000 refugees to
flee. There are believed to be about 40,000 residents left in the
city, which once had a population of 400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya declared independence from Moscow in 1991 as the Soviet
Union was disintegrating. Russia launched a military campaign
against the republic and destroyed much of Grozny in 1994 through
1996, although Russian forces ended up retreating from the region
after suffering heavy casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent military foray, which includes about 100,000
Russian troops, was launched after several bomb attacks in Moscow
were blamed on Chechen separatists.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address: eric (at) hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
