<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 1756EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1929 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLALOTTERY-MAIN2-COX     12-07 1744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLALOTTERY-MAIN2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ads aim to sell tickets, not highlight long odds
 &HT;    (EDS: Package 2/Part 1 _ This main story runs with
FLALOTTERY-PUBLIX and FLALOTTERY-HISPANICS.)
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ A $2 billion-a-year industry doesn't survive on
luck alone.
</P>
<P>
   Sophisticated marketing efforts make up the backbone of the
Florida Lottery, which each day, seven days a week, 365 days a
year, spends an average $99,000 encouraging Floridians to gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing, for example, that took note of two years of increases
for the low-prize Cash 3 and Play 4 games, and now plans to boost
sales by another $10 million this year with a spring advertising
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Or, for instance, that saw the tendency of many Lotto players to
open their wallets only when the jackpot hits ridiculous levels _
such as Wednesday's drawing, now estimated at $42 million _ and
responded with a plan to increase the game's take by $96 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bright, snazzy television commercials, catchy radio jingles,
newspaper ads that glamorize the fun and excitement of winning big
money _ all designed, according to internal Lottery Department
documents, to get the 25 percent of Floridians who don't now buy
lottery tickets to start, and the 75 percent who already buy them
to buy even more.
</P>
<P>
   How much more?
</P>
<P>
   This year, under a new governor who says he opposes the
lottery's ``something-for-nothing'' ethic, the agency wants
Floridians to spend $200 million more on lottery tickets than they
did last year, on the way to spending $500 million more _ a 25
percent increase _ by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Such numbers are ambitious targets for a lottery whose sales
have been essentially flat for nine years, and Florida Lottery
officials have undertaken a major restructuring to get there,
including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Retooling the flagship Lotto game to increase the number of
large jackpots the lottery believes are necessary to bring out
frenzied ticket-buying from infrequent players. Officials
accomplished this by worsening the already astronomical odds by 65
percent and doubling the frequency of drawings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Introducing, with a big advertising campaign, yet another game
to fill a perceived niche between the $20,000 prize available in
Fantasy Five and the multimillion jackpots in Lotto. ``Mega
Money,'' with its $200,000 top prize, debuted in May, and officials
hope it will sell $106 million in tickets by the end of the budget
year next June.
</P>
<P>
   _ Researching and specifically targeting, according to documents
obtained by The Palm Beach Post newspaper, players of Cash 3 and
Play 4. These games are highly popular among the poorest,
least-educated players, a Post computer analysis shows.
</P>
<P>
   This last goal, if accomplished, would only increase the already
disproportionate amount of money wagered on the lottery by
Florida's worst-off residents. According to the Post's computer
analysis, the lowest average education levels already account for
twice as many lottery tickets per capita than the best-educated
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   If income is factored in, then the least-educated and poorest
Floridians are spending nearly seven times as much of their money
on lottery tickets as the best educated and wealthiest _ with the
bulk of those sales concentrated in instant tickets and the two
daily games.
</P>
<P>
   The Post analysis also found that the least-educated
neighborhoods already have three times as many lottery outlets per
person as those neighborhoods where Florida's best-educated live _
with lottery vendors in thousands of convenience stores, 800 liquor
stores, even 156 payday loan stores and five pawnshops.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not just bad public policy,'' said Stanley Marshall,
head of the conservative James Madison Institute and a former
president of Florida State University. ``That's borderline
immorality.''
</P>
<P>
   Targeting gamblers
</P>
<P>
   Lottery officials cringe at the notion that they target any
socioeconomic or ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not targeting advertising,'' Lottery Secretary David
Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the agency's own marketing documents show the lottery and
its advertising agencies use sophisticated analyses to aim both
products and pitches directly at specific audiences.
</P>
<P>
   A July 15 marketing plan by the Miami advertising agency Sanchez
and Levitan, for instance, concluded that among Hispanic players,
the average jackpot needed to boost ticket sales increased from $24
million in 1998 to $31 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   To counter the already prevalent notion among players that the
odds are too poor, the report advised that the recent Lotto
restructuring needed to be sold as ``a way to improve perceptions
of winning viability'' and doubling both ``fun'' and ``the chances
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though Griffin disavows the ad agency's report _ as
well as any report predating his July 19 arrival, for that matter _
the advice was followed to the letter when the lottery rolled out
new and improved Lotto in October: ``The result will be more
chances to win, more rollovers that yield larger jackpots over the
long run, and a lot more excitement all the way around!'' according
to the department's news release announcing the change.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in the news release was mentioned that the odds got far
worse: from 1 in 14 million under old Lotto to 1 in 23 million in
new Lotto.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery's print and television ads promoting new Lotto do
state _ in tiny print _ the odds for winning the new game, but
don't mention that they are considerably worse than before.
</P>
<P>
   Selling a dream
</P>
<P>
   Advertising experts point out that the medium's role is not to
tell the whole truth, but to sell a product. Just as McDonald's
doesn't explain in its ads how much fat and cholesterol are in a
Big Mac, the lottery ought not be expected to emphasize its lousy
odds, said Florida State University advertising Professor Barry
Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advertiser is not going to present both sides of the
equation,'' Solomon said. ``Advertising is a form of advocacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all states with lotteries, however, sell them that way.
</P>
<P>
   Some, for example, ban the portrayal of children in lottery
advertising, under the rationale that minors are inappropriate in
something that promotes gambling. Others, like Wisconsin, require
that the odds of winning be prominently stated. Billboards there
devote more than half the available space to a listing of the odds
for the various prize levels.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia bans advertising that encourages anyone to play. ``No
inducements. Information only. We don't show Rolls Royces and
mansions and things,'' said spokeswoman Sherie Phaup, explaining
that the mere presence of a lottery was divisive in such a
conservative, religious state. ``It was a touchy issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The state of Massachusetts three years ago banned all
advertising except for ``point-of-sale'' displays, leaving a
$400,000 annual advertising budget for signs and posters in the
stores that sell tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Florida has no such restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery has used children in ads, in speaking roles in spots
highlighting families who have won Lotto. It has produced big,
extravagant ads that portray lottery games as high excitement. And
up until Griffin's arrival late this summer the odds of winning
weren't given at all.
</P>
<P>
   That has now changed, Griffin said. ``Odds go on everything.
That was my directive.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin said he doesn't know why some Lotto billboards _ one in
Tallahassee, for example, about a block from lottery headquarters _
still do not present the odds of winning, but promised that, too,
will be corrected.
</P>
<P>
   An $800 million habit
</P>
<P>
   When Gov. Jeb Bush took office, he said he did not like the idea
of the state, through the lottery, promoting a
``something-for-nothing'' ethic.
</P>
<P>
   How does he reconcile that with his approval for the lottery to
boost its sales from $2 billion to $2.5 billion by 2003?
</P>
<P>
   Bush told The Post that the state's obligation to maximize
education money from the lottery while preserving the ``dignity of
the state and the welfare of its citizens'' was ``a unique
challenge that requires a balance.'' He called the goal to increase
sales by $500 million _ and the lottery's contribution to education
by $200 million _ consistent with his goal ``to promote the slow
and sustained growth of the Florida Lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, of course, is not the first governor to start out
criticizing the lottery but come, if not to embrace, then at least
to accept the agency that funnels $800 million into the state
treasury each year. Gov. Lawton Chiles called the lottery ``a
sucker's bet'' when he took office nine years ago, yet by the end
of his second term agreed to pledge 30 years of lottery proceeds to
pay off $2.5 billion in school construction bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Just as lotteries can make addicts of their players, critics
charge, so can they hook the state governments on the money they
generate.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why even anti-gambling governors such as Chiles and
Bush can learn to live with a $2 billion-a-year gambling
enterprise, said the Rev. Tom Grey, an Illinois minister who
travels the nation fighting attempts to institute lotteries and
casino gambling. To do so is easier than try to wean the government
off so much easy money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's government's dirty little secret,'' Grey said. ``It's
better to take the money and not look.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Florida, state government has proven it can rid itself of
a tax that generates $1 billion _ if it wants to, said Marshall of
the James Madison Institute, which this year merged with
then-candidate Bush's Foundation for Florida's Future, a nonprofit
think tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a precedent,'' he said: the intangibles tax, which
Marshall's group strongly supported eliminating because of its
effect on people who save, rather than spend, their money as well
as on businesses. The legislature and Bush are on their way toward
eliminating the various elements of the tax over several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a political will to do it, there's a way,'' said
Marshall, whose group provided the intellectual underpinnings for
the intangibles tax repeal as well as public school vouchers _ both
of which were embraced by Bush and Republican leaders. ``If we can
do it for the intangibles tax, why can't we do it for the
lottery?''
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
