<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1932 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLALOTTERY-HISPANICS-     12-07 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLALOTTERY-HISPANICS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV ads for Hispanics reflect cultural spin
 &HT;    (EDS: Package 2/Part 3 _ This story runs with FLALOTTERY-MAIN2
and FLALOTTERY-PUBLIX.)
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ They know where you live. They know how much
Spanish language television you watch. They know how much you spend
on Lotto each week, and they think they have a way to make you
spend more.
</P>
<P>
   They are the Florida Lottery's Hispanic marketing experts, and
they've got your number.
</P>
<P>
   Lapsed Lotto player? Forty-four percent are Cuban, 12 percent
Puerto Rican and 22 percent Nicaraguan, according to research
generated by Sanchez and Levitan, the Miami-based advertising
company that handles the lottery's Hispanic advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Over 50 years old? Hispanics that age who play the lottery ``are
heavy television users'' but ``light newspaper users,'' according
to a July 15 marketing plan that talks about increasing sales of
the flagship game by 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   New Florida Lottery Secretary David Griffin said the report was
created before his arrival and therefore carries no weight with
him, even though it was prepared and presented under interim
Secretary Sue Cobb, a fellow appointee of Gov. Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he does not intend to specifically target
minorities or demographic groups but did not see anything wrong
with a marketing plan aimed at Florida's largest ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   Other parts of state government also make a point of seeking out
and addressing Hispanic residents _ the Health Department, the
Division of Elections, the Department of Education, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Those agencies, however, typically provide the same message to
Hispanics that they provide to the general population, just in
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery, in contrast, pays Sanchez and Levitan $300,000 a
year _ on top of $2.5 million a year for its general marketing
campaign _ to treat Hispanics as a completely separate market for
its tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Commercials are not only in Spanish, but aim at a completely
different popular culture. Witness last year's Candido the lucky,
dancing ticket vendor, who cavorts among a troupe of young,
beautiful women who sing his virtues as gold coins fall from the
sky.
</P>
<P>
   One recent television commercial in English is a series of
people winning the lottery to the jingle of ``Whole Lotta Lotto
Going On,'' a take off of ``Whole Lot of Shakin' Going On.'' But
that doesn't translate well into Spanish and commercials on Spanish
television are rarely based on a jingle.
</P>
<P>
   So for Spanish-language television, advertisers created ``Manolo
el Bodeguero,'' a caricature of the Cuban-Hispanic stereotype of a
know-it-all who talks so fast and incessantly that no one else can
get a word in. A bodeguero is a man who runs a bodega, a small
corner convenience-grocery store, the kind that sell so many
lottery tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Sanchez and Levitan declined to be interviewed for
this report, referring all questions on the ad campaign back to the
Florida Lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Monika Gonzalez contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
