<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1933 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLALOTTERY-PUBLIX-COX     12-07 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLALOTTERY-PUBLIX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Publix the top seller when it comes to lottery
 &HT;    (EDS: Package 2/Part 2 _ This story runs with FLALOTTERY-MAIN2
and FLALOTTERY-HISPANICS.)
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Pop quiz: Of the following, the number one
purveyor of gambling last year was:
</P>
<P>
   A) Gulfstream Park;
</P>
<P>
   B) Palm Beach Kennel Club;
</P>
<P>
   C) Dania Jai-Alai;
</P>
<P>
   D) Publix supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   If you guessed Publix _ the same company that resisted opening
its stores on Sundays until 1983 and to this day avoids the word
``Halloween'' in its ads for much of Florida _ you guessed right,
according to statistics provided by the Florida Lottery and the
state Department of Business and Professional Regulation.
</P>
<P>
   In budget year 1998-99, the 483 Publix stores in Florida sold
more than a quarter of a billion dollars in lottery tickets,
accounting for one of every eight tickets sold in the entire state.
The total represents more than any other gambling enterprise in
Florida _ with the possible exception of casinos run by American
Indian tribes and the so-called ``cruises to nowhere,'' neither of
whom have to report their revenues to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Publix spokeswoman Jennifer Bush said the grocery chain offers
lottery tickets for the same reason it carries laundry detergent or
orange juice: The customers want it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a moral issue. We are a retailer. We don't take
positions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our eyes, lottery tickets are just like a gallon of milk
... We know we have a lot of customers, obviously, who want to buy
that product.''
</P>
<P>
   Company officials have attributed the reluctance about Sunday
hours to the desire to let employees spend the day with their
families. And using ``Fall Festival'' or ``Oktoberfest'' instead of
``Halloween'' in its Central and North Florida advertising was to
avoid offending some religious sensibilities _ similar to using
``Happy Holidays'' instead of ``Merry Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the company, which received $15.6 million in
commissions last year, sells tickets as a service to its customers,
not the 5.5 cents it gets per $1 ticket sold. Lottery tickets are
sold at a separate counter, not the checkout aisles, and because
each sale is a relatively lengthy transaction, the company sees
little if any profit, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Publix, of course, is just one among thousands of chain and
independent stores selling lottery tickets at a total of about
11,500 outlets. Retailers start out selling only instant
``scratch-off'' tickets, and can, based on sales performance, be
awarded one of the 8,500 computerized ticket machines needed to
dispense tickets for Cash 3, Play 4, Fantasy 5, Mega Money and
Lotto. Vendors can lose their terminals if on-line ticket sales
fall below $800 a week for four straight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the other major supermarket chains in Florida _
Winn-Dixie and Albertson's _ also sell tickets, as do convenience
stores like 7-Eleven, Texaco, Lil' Champ, Circle K, Shell, Mobil
and Amoco.
</P>
<P>
   Some 800 liquor stores, package stores and bars also offer
tickets, as do 161 check-cashing stores, high-interest ``payday
loan'' establishments and pawnshops.
</P>
<P>
   And just as the vendors vary in their demographics, so do their
tickets sales.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than half of all tickets sold last year by Publix
stores _ typically found in middle- or upper-middle-class areas _
were for Lotto, favored by middle- and upper-middle-class lottery
players who hope one day to strike it really rich.
</P>
<P>
   In the liquor stores, located on average in poorer areas, Lotto
accounts for only 27 percent of all lottery sales. The daily Cash 3
and Play 4 tickets make up 32 percent, and instant tickets _ those
criticized by compulsive gambling experts as most often used by
addicts _ account for 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And at the check-cashing stores and pawnshops, Lotto accounts
for 17 percent of sales, while instant tickets make up 43 percent _
a percentage attributable to the fact that more than three-quarters
of the stores sell only instant tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. shirishdate(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
