<HEADLINE>
TRACKING DOWN A SONG ABOUT AMY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find the song ``Once in Love with Amy''?
</P>
<P>
   _ K.M.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Once in Love with Amy,'' a Frank Loesser song featured in
the 1949 stage musical ``Where's Charley?,'' has been performed by
three different members of the Rat Pack.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sinatra sings it on ``Best of Columbia Years _ 1943-45''
and ``Columbia Years _ Complete Record,'' Dean Martin sings it on
``Capitol Sings Frank Loesser'' and Sammy Davis Jr. sings it on
``The Sounds of '66.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Bolger, who performed the song in ``Where's Charley?,''
contributed a version to the Broadway collection ``Front Row
Center.''
</P>
<P>
   All these albums are in print and should be available for
special order from music retailers. One Web store that stocks them
is CDNow at www.cdnow.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to the Famous Artists School?
</P>
<P>
   _ L.W., Granbury, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Famous Artists School, Cortina Learning
International, 7 Hollyhock Road, Wilton, CT 06897 or visit the Web
site members.aol.com/cortinainc.
</P>
<P>
   The school sells four how-to art instruction books: ``How to
Draw Animals,'' ``How to Draw Human Figures,'' ``How to Draw and
Paint Landscapes'' and ``How to Draw and Paint Portraits,''
</P>
<P>
   Each book costs $7.95 plus $2 postage and includes a free
``mail-in art lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How old were they, and from what did Montgomery Clift and
Robert Walker die?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.H., Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Robert Walker was 32 when he died in 1951 from an accidental
overdose of medically administered sedatives.
</P>
<P>
   Because Walker was still working on the film ``My Son John''
when he died, filmmakers used outtakes from his performance in
``Strangers on a Train'' to complete the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after finishing ``The Defector'' in 1966, Clift died at
age 45 of a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
