<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1951 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WHITNEY-BIENNIAL-ART-     12-07 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITNEY-BIENNIAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE WHITNEY, CHOOSING A PALETTE OF BIENNIAL ARTISTS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT18 and NYT19 have been sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By CAROL VOGEL  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Whitney Museum of American Art announced in
March that for the first time in its 70-year history a team of
outside curators would produce its Biennial, no one involved was
quite sure how the process would work. Each of the six curators who
had agreed to help put together the giant survey of contemporary
art was from a different part of the country. None lived in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Whitney curators and the consultants they sometimes
hired usually spent about a year scouring the United States in
search of the best of contemporary art for the Biennial, the most
anticipated and the most criticized exhibition the museum produces.
It is the show everybody loves to hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us had trepidations at first,'' said one of the
curators, Lawrence Rinder, director of the Institute for
Exhibitions and Public Programs at the California College of Arts
and Crafts in San Francisco and Oakland. Andrea Miller-Keller, an
independent curator from Hartford, Conn., described the process as
``trying to tame an unhousebroken mongrel.'' And Valerie Cassel,
director of the visiting artists program at the School of the Art
Institute of Chicago, said she felt as if she were part of a
``six-headed monster that was ingested in one stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Whitney and its new director, Maxwell Anderson, had
little choice but to look entirely outside the museum. After
Anderson reorganized the curatorial staff on his arrival in
September 1998, the curator in charge of the Biennial resigned and
another senior curator left the museum. The remaining Whitney
curators were busy putting the finishing touches on ``The American
Century: 1900-2000,'' a two-part show that runs through January.
</P>
<P>
   Now, eight months after the team's first meeting, it has
produced the long-awaited list of artists whose works the curators
feel reflect the best of what has happened in contemporary art
during the last two years. The list is the culmination of hundreds
of visits to artists' studios from Lubbock, Texas, to Berkeley,
Calif., countless hours poring over slides and long debates in
cyberspace. The team also met the old-fashioned way, in person.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Biennial, which opens March 23 and runs through June 4,
is one of the Whitney's largest, with 97 artists. It is also one of
the most international. Twenty-one of the artists in the show were
born abroad but have migrated to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The artists who made the cut, especially the younger emerging
ones, are likely to see an instant boost in their careers. Even for
well-known artists inclusion in a Whitney Biennial offers an
instant status that can significantly increase the value of their
work.
</P>
<P>
   The show has no overriding theme, the curators said, but they
noted that painting is alive and well, and video is more important
than ever. So is technology.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to buck the trend of previous Biennials, which have
been criticized for being too reflective of the cliquish New York
art establishment and too reliant on ideas from the Whitney's
staff, this team selected a surprising group of artists with a
broad range of ages and mediums and a careful balance between the
sexes. The curators said they avoided picking too many of the
artists shown in trendy galleries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the least gallery-driven Biennial that we've
seen for a long time,'' said Michael Auping, chief curator at the
Modern Art Museum in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller-Keller said that before any of the curators agreed to
do the show they ``insisted on building a fire wall between
trustees, important collectors and influential galleries and
dealers.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of selected artists includes some of today's hottest
names, like the winners of this year's Venice Biennale: Cai
Guo-Qiang, the Chinese-born installation artist; Doug Aitken, a Los
Angles video artist; and Shirin Neshat, an Iranian-born artist who
creates videos about the separation of the sexes.
</P>
<P>
   Other names will surprise the art world: for example, William De
Lottie, , 57, an abstract painter and installation artist who works
out of his garage in Eastford, Conn., or E.V. Day, 32, who lives in
Brooklyn and is known for cutting spectacular evening dresses into
hundreds of pieces as if they had been in a violent explosion and
then suspending them in midair to suggest a mushroom cloud.
</P>
<P>
   Another unexpected name is James Drake, 53, a photographer from
Lubbock who focuses on the lives of people he has met through the
Mexican Federation of Private Health and Community Development
Associations, an organization that deals with prevention and
treatment of diseases and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the range of backgrounds, a large number of participants
work in New York. ``Where we are today in terms of art is a
reflection on our migratory age,'' Ms. Cassel said. Many curators
said it was frustrating to discover that an artist from, say,
Miami, had moved to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, many works deal with political issues, curators
said, a reflection of what artists are thinking about in the here
and now.
</P>
<P>
   There are well-established artists like the sculptor Richard
Tuttle and the photographer John Coplans, and midcareer artists
like Dennis Adams, Dawoud Bey, Louise Lawler, Robert Gober and
Annette Lemieux. Curators said they sought a diversity of styles,
from the nontraditional portraiture of Salomon Huerta, Kurt Kauper
and Lisa Yuskavage to the abstract work of Ghada Amer, Linda
Besemer and Katherine Sherwood.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty artists will create site-specific installations,
including Rina Banerjee, whose elaborate assemblages of everyday
materials reflect her Indian heritage.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time the Whitney will include Internet art.
Visitors will be able to view the works on a large-screen
projection in the main exhibition as well as on a Web site. Works
by 27 cinematic artists will be on view at the Whitney as well as
at the institutions of the Biennial curators. The museum will also
introduce an audio tour that includes interviews with the artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an enormous amount of winnowing out,'' said Jane
Farver, director of the List Visual Arts Center at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology and one of the curators.
``Everyone had people they wanted in the show that didn't make
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the list is final, every curator has some complaint.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no significant senior women and I'm smarting about
that,'' Ms. Miller-Keller said.
</P>
<P>
   The curator Hugh Davies, director of the Museum of Contemporary
Art in San Diego, said: ``If I were to do this again I would have
wanted more Los Angeles artists. I kept arguing that New York may
be the commercial center of the art world, but in terms of
creativity and education Los Angeles is perhaps eclipsing New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   In putting together the show from long distance, the curators
faced several obstacles. They had scheduled only three face-to-face
gatherings _ in Chicago, in San Diego and at the Whitney _ but as
they progressed they decided that neither electronic communications
nor conference call could substitute for meeting in person, so they
got together again at the Whitney. Still, most discussions and
presentations took place via e-mail, conference calls and on a
special password-protected Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Auping, the Fort Worth curator, said he couldn't imagine doing a
show like the Biennial without computer technology. ``I would feel
like the Flintstones,'' he said, adding that the images on the Web
site were handy reminders of the artists' work.
</P>
<P>
   When the group first met in April at the University Club in
Chicago, each curator was asked to submit a list of about 50 names
as an exercise meant to foster an understanding of each
participant's thinking. ``We were shocked and excited that there
were almost no overlaps,'' Rinder said. ``This meant we'd all learn
something and that there was no confirmed canon.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial list of artists was broken down by career stage:
emerging, middle, senior. By July curators were told to create new
lists that would contain 20 emerging artists, 20 midcareer artists
and 10 older ones. Film, video and Web-based artists were
considered separately.
</P>
<P>
   At first the curators decided that each would be allowed what
they called three passion votes, but in the end that is not how it
worked. Each curator voted on each artist and mostly at the
face-to-face meetings. But curators let their passions be known and
could often persuade colleagues to vote for an artist they probably
would not have considered had they been doing the show alone.
</P>
<P>
   Votes were cast over time. A curator could cast either a
three-vote (meaning the work of art was one they could not live
without), a two-vote (a work they endorsed) or a one-vote (they
would not die if the work wasn't accepted). The group slowly
trimmed a list of more than 200 artists to fewer than half that
number.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson did not vote, but did weigh in with considerations like
space limitations. ``I was the time-keeper, the pragmatist, '' he
said. ``I helped shape the show and gave the curators a sense of
what was possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Auping volunteered to be in charge of the installation, which is
to be designed by Lana Hum, the Whitney's in-house exhibition
architect. ``I want to keep it as clean and straightforward as
possible,'' he said. ``We don't need to accelerate this show with
anything jazzy.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't signal how the Biennial will look. ``It will
have a messy vitality,'' Davies said. ``It's bound to have some
rough edges. Maybe if we had another year it would be more
homogeneous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
