A1966 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-PEARL-HARBOR-HNS &LR;      12-07 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEARL-HARBOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS CITE `GOVERNMENT-WIDE FAILURE' FOR PEARL HARBOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES J. LEWIS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A panel of historians and retired Navy officers
debated Tuesday _ the 58th anniversary of the Japanese raid on
Pearl Harbor _ whether the Navy and Army commanders there should be
blamed for allowing Japan's successful surprise attack that brought
the United States into World War II.
</P>
<P>
   A thin consensus emerged among the 10 panelists, commentators
and scholars that it was a ``government-wide failure'' that enabled
Japan to pull off one of history's most successful surprise
military attacks. A total of 2,403 U.S. military and civilian
personnel were killed in the Dec. 7, 1941, attack.
</P>
<P>
   The debate preceded a somber wreath-laying ceremony at the U.S.
Navy Memorial on Pennsylvania Avenue that was attended by a handful
of surviving crew members of the cruiser USS St. Louis, one of the
few American ships to get under way during the attack and engage
the Japanese carrier-based airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about who was responsible for letting Japan's attack
succeed have centered on the roles of the U.S. commanders there _
Navy Adm. Husband Kimmel and Army. Lt. Gen. Walter Short _ and on
the top military and civilian leaders in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   David A. Rosenberg, a historian and faculty member at the
National War College, said the evidence shows that Pearl Harbor
``was a government-wide failure'' because of mistakes in the
Washington headquarters of the Navy and War departments and at
Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg praised the Clinton administration's 1995
re-examination of Pearl Harbor responsibility that made the same
finding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spreading the blame widely is a good conclusion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The questions debated by the panelists included whether Kimmel
and Short were unfairly treated when they were relieved of their
commands and retired at lower ranks after the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Many participants agreed that even if the Pearl Harbor
commanders had been on a high state of alert, the overwhelming
numerical advantage held by the attacking Japanese force would have
inflicted the same catastrophic damage on the fleet, though at a
higher price in terms of Japanese planes lost.
</P>
<P>
   If the fleet had left Pearl Harbor to avoid the air attack, some
panelists said, the U.S. ships would have been vulnerable to
Japanese submarines. And if the U.S. ships had been sunk in the
deep ocean, U.S. Navy salvage crews would not have been able to
raise and repair the vessels, as they did in the relatively shallow
waters at Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Love, professor of history at the U.S. Naval Academy,
said Kimmel deserved to be relieved of his command because he no
longer had the confidence of President Franklin D. Roosevelt or the
Navy establishment or the American people. Love said dismissing
commanders was a common penalty among armed forces around the world
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Love also noted that some U.S. military personnel in the
Pacific, including some ship commanders at Pearl Harbor, were at a
higher state of alert than was Kimmel.
</P>
<P>
   He said Kimmel should have told more of his subordinates about
the official ``war warning'' that Washington sent him on Nov. 27 so
the fleet would have known that top Navy officials were convinced
that war with Japan would start ``within the next few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Kimmel critic, author Norman Polmar, said Kimmel ``had
to know'' that Pearl Harbor was susceptible to a surprise air
attack because such a maneuver had been a common U.S. fleet war
game in the 1920s and 1930s and the attackers invariably won.
</P>
<P>
   Polmar also noted that one of Kimmel's fellow admirals warned in
1937 in an official Navy publication that Japan would likely launch
a surprise attack on a weekend, as in fact happened. Kimmel also
had to know about the British success in launching a surprise air
raid on the Italian fleet at Taranto in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Polmar also argued that Kimmel should have been more suspicious
when his intelligence aide told him that U.S. radio trackers had
lost track of Japan's aircraft carriers in early December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carrier strikes on Pearl Harbor should have been on his
mind,'' Polmar said.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmel's defenders argued that the Navy Department in Washington
had withheld key intelligence, obtained by breaking Japanese radio
codes, that pointed to Pearl Harbor as the likely target for the
widely expected Japanese attack. The withheld intelligence also
indicated that the attack would come at dawn on Sunday, Dec. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Edward L. Beach, a retired Navy captain, Pearl Harbor historian
and novelist, said the infamous ``war warning'' messages sent to
Kimmel were ``models of obfuscatory language.'' Indeed, the Nov. 27
warning sent to Kimmel specifically cited the Philippines or Borneo
or the Malay Peninsula as the likely places where Japan would
strike but made no mention of Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese attack, despite its tactical brilliance, was a
strategic disaster for Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers hit Pearl Harbor when all three aircraft carriers
assigned to the U.S. fleet were elsewhere. The attackers also
failed to bomb the huge oil storage depots at Pearl Harbor, the
loss of which would have crippled the U.S. fleet even more. And the
attack abruptly ended the debate then raging in the United States
about whether to intervene in the war that had been raging for more
than two years in Europe and for 4 1/2 years in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember Pearl Harbor!'' became the rallying cry for American
war mobilization and inspired the state of super vigilance that
characterized the United States during the 44 years of the Cold War
that began soon afterward.
</P>
<P>
   (Charles J. Lewis can be reached at 202-298-6920 or via e-mail:
chuck &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 1824EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
