u e BC-TV-NOTES-NYT &LR;      12-07 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TV NOTES: NICKELODEON'S MILLENNIUM; NEWS NIELSENS; McCULLOUGH; FOX 
(bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The World On Nickelodeon
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon, the cable channel for children that takes its
audience very seriously, has come up with its own way to observe
the Year 2000 in a special it has called the ``largest global
multimedia event'' ever produced for children: a 24-hour
commercial-free broadcast featuring children from around the world
describing the future they would like to see.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``Nickellennium,'' the special is a six-hour film that
includes profiles of children representing a range of nations and
cultures and their comments about the world they live and the world
they would like to live in, as well as some music videos and other
entertainment segments. The film will be translated into nine other
languages and will use subtitles to translate for viewers in still
other languages.
</P>
<P>
   In a display of the global reach of Nickelodeon, the number of
countries carrying the film is 122. In the United States, Britain
and Australia, the film will run for 24 hours straight during New
Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   While it has no commercials, it does have a sponsor. McDonald's
is the one corporate underwriter for the project and is
participating in a tie-in that involves getting children into a
McDonald's sometime between now and New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   In McDonald's they can pick up what Nickelodeon is calling a
``wish bag.'' In each U.S. time zone (and all the others where
McDonald's restaurants are participating in the promotion) children
will be asked to make a wish, blow up their bags and pop them
together at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   In another effort to extend the global theme, the channel will
observe the start of the new year each hour beginning at 6 a.m.
Eastern Standard Time, when the new year begins in Tonga.
</P>
<P>
   The film is the work of Linda Schaffer, a filmmaker commissioned
by Nickelodeon to travel the world for a year talking to children
about their views of the future.
</P>
<P>
   She found children around the world united in one concern: the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon expects children to drop in on an hour of the film,
not to watch it in one six-hour burst. In addition, Apple Computer
will offer a streamlined 90-minute version of the film over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The channel estimates that ``Nickellennium'' will be available
in almost 100 million homes worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Leads With News
</P>
<P>
   The ``NBC Nightly News'' solidified its leadership in the
network evening news competition, a race that may take on more
significance with the election year.
</P>
<P>
   In the November sweep rating period that concluded last week,
NBC won in virtually every significant category, with ABC's ``World
News Tonight'' second and the ``CBS Evening News'' third.
</P>
<P>
   NBC averaged 11.36 million total viewers, up about 6 percent
from last November. ABC had just under 11 million viewers, about
the same as last year. CBS had 9.7 million viewers, down 7 percent
from last November.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's lead was about the same among viewers of ages 25 to 54,
which is the main advertiser target for news programming.
</P>
<P>
   This was the 10th straight sweep month in which NBC's newscast
has finished first (one was a tie) but it was NBC's biggest winning
margin since May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough Leaving
</P>
<P>
   David McCullough, the longtime host and voice of the
award-winning ``American Experience'' series on PBS, announced
Tuesday that he was leaving the series in May at the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough, who won a Pulitzer Prize for his biography of Harry
S. Truman, has been with the series for its entire 12-year run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt now was a good time,'' he said in a telephone
interview Tuesday. ``It's a little bit like an actor who's been on
a show a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The big reason, he said, was his desire to focus on his next
book, a biography of John Adams that he has been working on for six
years.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough became a signature voice of the historical
documentary on public television, beginning with early work with
Ken Burns on films like ``The Brooklyn Bridge'' and continuing
through his first job as host on the program ``Smithsonian World.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he concluded that after several years with ``Smithsonian
World'' that television was taking too much of his time.
</P>
<P>
   But he relented when the producers of ``American Experience''
offered to film all of his introductions in his own home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've written all my own introductions,'' he said. He also
served as the narrator for several of the program's award-winning
films, including ``LBJ,'' ``D-Day,'' ``America 1900'' and ``The
Donner Party.''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough, a writer by trade and disposition, said he wound up
turning down ``more offers than I can remember'' for voice work,
including ``some for wine companies that would have helped with the
years we had tuitions to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   PBS has not yet named a replacement as host of the series. ``The
American Experience'' has become one of the most honored programs
on public television, having won 13 Emmy Awards, along with two
Alfred I. duPont-Columbia University Awards and three George Foster
Peabody Awards.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough said he would serve as host on all the films this
season. Among the subjects, he said, are Houdini and Eleanor
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Entertainment
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Grushow, chairman of the 20th Century Fox television
studio, who recently expanded his duties to include running the
entertainment division of the Fox network as well, announced that
not one but two executives would succeed him as president of the
studio, Dana Waldren and Gary Newman.
</P>
<P>
   Both executives had served as executive vice presidents under
Grushow and they will continue to report to him. Under the new
structure at Fox Grushow has overall authority over both the
studio, which produces shows for every network, and the Fox
entertainment division, which remains the principal buyer of of
those shows.
</P>
<P>
   Grushow noted Tuesday that unlike ABC, which merged the
network's entertainment division with the production studio owned
by its parent company, Walt Disney, Fox would keep its two entities
``entirely separate.''
</P>
<P>
   Grushow acknowledged Tuesday that problems with Fox's prime-time
schedule _ the network failed to initiate a single new hit show
this fall _ have absorbed most of his time since he expanded his
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to roll up my sleeves and roll around at the
network,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for some short-term issues at the network, Grushow said he
did not plan to expand Fox's game show ``Greed'' to more than one
night after ABC's announcement that ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' would be broadcast three nights a week starting in
January.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Greed'' is being tried out on both Thursday and Friday
night this week. Grushow said Fox wanted to see if ``Greed'' could
``solve some problems for us on Friday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
