<SLUG> BC-HDEPOT-ANALYSTS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot conference outlines plans
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot is expected to leave a good impression with
analysts as the retailer wraps up its annual conference today.
</P>
<P>
   About 180 investors and analysts are attending the two-day
meeting at Home Depot's headquarters in Atlanta. On the heels of a
strong quarterly earnings report, Home Depot will likely reiterate
its road map for long-term growth. The retailer plans to release a
conference summary today.
</P>
<P>
   Although Home Depot has been keeping a lid on the details of its
Internet strategy, analysts will certainly have some questions
about electronic commerce. Last month Atlanta-based iXL Enterprises
announced it would help Home Depot with its Internet plans. The
retailer intends to open its Web site for product sales in the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Other presentations will likely include early results from
Villager's Hardware, a new small-store concept being tested in New
Jersey, and the progress of the upscale Expo Design Centers. Home
Depot also has been testing a new store layout in four cities,
including Alpharetta, an Atlanta suburb.
</P>
<P>
   International growth is rising on analysts' radar, too. Home
Depot, which will have roughly $40 billion in revenue this year, is
expanding in Chile and Argentina. Over the summer it announced a
major expansion in Canada. Analysts expect Europe to become Home
Depot's next big move abroad.
</P>
<P>
   This year's analyst conference is Home Depot's third in as many
years. ``We originally planned to hold it every other year, but we
have so much to report on our new initiatives that we made it an
annual event,'' said Kim Shreckengost, vice president of investor
relations. ``We feel a responsibility to keep our investors
updated.''
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
