<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1977 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGO-SERBIA-ART-NYT &LR;      12-07 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-SERBIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB OFFICIALS RELEASE HOME HEATING OIL TO `OPPOSITION' TOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic and map are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The towns of Nis and Pirot were
celebrating on Tuesday night after Serbian customs officials
released 14 tankers of heating fuel from the European Union that
had been blocked at the border for nearly two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very pleased that this is over,'' said Mayor Zoran
Zivkovic of Nis, which was scheduled to receive the bulk of the
fuel. ``It has been like a national version of Hannibal crossing
the Alps.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke by telephone from Nis just before going on stage at an
opposition rally.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the fuel to the two opposition-controlled towns
was more a relief than a victory for the local mayors and their
European benefactors, after wrangling with Serbian customs since
Nov. 24. Zivkovic has championed the plan as a chance for Serbia to
reopen ties with Western Europe. Yet it was not at all clear
whether future consignments would be allowed through any more
easily.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, called Fuel for Democracy, is Europe's attempt to
deliver aid to ordinary Serbs while circumventing the Belgrade
authorities. Last week, it appeared close to failure, when European
officials tried to recall the tankers.
</P>
<P>
   The 350 tons of fuel in the tankers represent three days of
heating fuel for the towns.
</P>
<P>
   The shipment is politically charged, because it is being sent
specifically to local authorities who oppose President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have criticized the plan as discriminatory
and say any assistance should be available to all Serbs. The
customs authorities held up the trucks for days with bureaucratic
checks, but released them on Monday night to proceed to Nis. The
tankers completed customs formalities today and delivered the fuel
to the heating plants.
</P>
<P>
   The customs officials gave no explanation for the change of mind
and seemed to have ignored a request by the European Union three
days earlier to let the tankers return to Macedonia. European Union
officials struggled on Tuesday to interpret the reversal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remain very reserved,'' the chief of the European Union
mission in Yugoslavia, Michael Graham, said. ``The whole story has
been so bad that I remain very skeptical.''
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting on Monday, European foreign ministers decided to
explore other ways to send the fuel. They had also planned to look
at expanding the program to other communities. But the delays with
the first delivery put off that decision.
</P>
<P>
   The ministers sent a tough message to Milosevic by doubling the
names on their list of Serbian officials who are barred from
traveling to European Union countries. Close to 600 people,
including relatives and business allies of Milosevic, as well as
government officials, are prohibited from obtaining visas. The
first list, of 305 officials, was published in May during the NATO
air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Like the fuel project, the travel restrictions are intended to
hurt Milosevic's government while sparing ordinary Serbs. This
week, Britain resumed issuing visas for Serbs in Belgrade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
