<HEADER>
A1982 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MUSIC-COUNTING-CROWS-     12-07 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-COUNTING-CROWS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTING CROWS FRESH OUT OF FODDER 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box at bottom) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As Counting Crows singer Adam Duritz straddled the
Wiltern Theatre stage monitors Monday, eyes squeezed shut and
yelping, ``I wish I was a girl,'' while his improbable dreadlocks
swayed to and fro, you couldn't help thinking this was a band
that's clearly come off the rails.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bay Area group's debut album was issued at the tail end
of 1993, the rootsy sound of such classic-rock-tinged songs as
``Mr. Jones,'' ``Perfect Blue Buildings'' and ``Round Here''
provided a refreshing alternative to the steady stream of grunge
wanna-bes clogging the modern-rock airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Duritz and company have had a difficult time coming
up with a consistent product, instead taking solace in an
increasingly overbearing wall of guitars and meandering tuneage. As
evidenced on their latest disc, the uneven ``This Desert Life''
(DGC/Geffen), Counting Crows has plainly run out of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   In concert, the ever-tortured Duritz is the focal point, and his
often unbearable, self-pitying lyrics and delivery detract from the
overall picture.
</P>
<P>
   But the musicians themselves are no slouches and when the
rock-star posturing and guitar antics subside long enough for a
song to be allowed to breath, such as during memorable performances
of ``A Long December,'' ``Rain King'' and ``Anna Begins,'' subtle
touches of accordion or Hammond organ lift the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, keyboardist Charlie Gillingham is the band's most
valuable if under-utilized asset.
</P>
<P>
   Opening with a muted reading of the hit ``Mr. Jones,'' the Crows
focused on new tunes such as ``Hanginaround'' from the current
album, a collection of sometimes melancholic pieces that lack the
spark of joy that fueled earlier tunes.
</P>
<P>
   The Counting Crows show _ which returns to the Wiltern on
Thursday and Friday and again Dec. 20-22 _ actually got off to a
distracting start. The band had unwisely chosen to preface its
appearance on stage with a driving segment from the original
recording of the Beatles tune ``Magical Mystery Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, there were several times during the next 90 minutes where
you got the feeling it would've been far more satisfying to have
simply sat in the darkened theater listening to that entire Beatles
album. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
Who: Counting Crows, Joe 90. &QL; 
Where: Wiltern Theatre, 3790 Wilshire Blvd., Los Angeles. &QL; 
When: 7 p.m. Thursday, Friday and Dec. 20-22. &QL; 
Tickets: $30 and $35. &QL; 
Information: (213) 480-3232. &QL; 
Our rating: two stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 1845EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TREE-SITTER-NYTR &LR;      12-07 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREE-SITTER-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVIST HOPES TO END 2-YEAR STAY IN A REDWOOD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE GENIELLA   NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAFFORD, Calif. _ Environmental activist Julia Hill, facing a
third winter of wind and rain from her tree-top perch in a northern
California redwood tree, says negotiations are under way with
Pacific Lumber Co. to end a protest that's attracted worldwide
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful, but feeling very cautious,'' Hill said Monday via
a cellular phone from the tarp-covered platform 180 feet up a
ridge-top redwood she calls ``Luna.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Dec. 19, 1997, Hill has been living in the tree to keep
Pacific Lumber from finishing a controversial logging operation
along a ridgetop above the Humboldt County community of Stafford.
The redwood tree, estimated by state foresters to be 600 years old,
was to be cut under terms of a state-approved timber harvest plan.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Lumber representatives confirmed the talks with Hill's
representatives but, like Hill, declined to discuss details or
speculate on the possible outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're very concerned about her health and safety,''
said a company representative, who asked not to be identified
because of pledges of confidentiality both sides have made. Pacific
Lumber is willing to ``lean over backwards to reach reasonable
terms, but we would like to point out that we're not holding her
hostage. She can come down any time,'' said the representative.
</P>
<P>
   The talks have heartened the 25-year-old Hill, who acknowledged
her tree-top vigil has been ``the hardest two years of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   As a chilly Pacific storm front moved across the redwood region,
Hill said she's been assured by representatives who are negotiating
on her behalf that Pacific Lumber has agreed to spare the huge
redwood and a 200-foot buffer zone around it.
</P>
<P>
   The tree is growing near the site of a massive mudslide that on
Jan. 1, 1997, destroyed or damaged several homes in Stafford.
Activists contended the mudslide was triggered by logging
operations, but Pacific Lumber foresters have maintained it was a
natural occurence typical of what happens in one of the nation's
most geologically unstable regions.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, better known as Julia ``Butterfly'' in protest circles,
declined to talk about what she and environmental groups that have
supported her might have to give in return for saving the tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of respect for Pacific Lumber, I'm going to keep to an
agreement to not discuss certain details,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the talks said that, under terms of a proposed
agreement, Hill and her supporters would have to pay $50,000 to
Pacific Lumber in return for the company imposing a logging ban at
the site. The money, the sources said, would in turn be donated to
Humboldt State University to fund future forestry research.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Lumber also is seeking signed statements from Hill that
the company hopes will discourage future tree-sits as a protest
tactic, believing they are inherently dangerous, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said if the current talks succeed, she hopes within the
next several days to climb down and touch ground for the first time
in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to do the right thing. I'd like to be able to spend
Christmas with my family,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   She said, however, she's prepared to stay and weather another
winter if the negotiations fail, as similar efforts did last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's tree-top antic began in late 1997 when she joined in an
Earth First! logging protest after the Arkansas native viewed the
redwoods for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   After deciding to stay in the tree until it was permanently
protected from cutting, Hill attracted national notoriety as the
months turned into years. She's been interviewed via cell phone,
and in a few cases in person, by reporters from around the world.
Hill also has been visited by numerous celebrities at the protest
site, including actor Woody Harrelson and singers Bonnie Raitt and
Joan Baez. Earlier this year, Hill was chosen one of the 20 most
fascinating women in politics by the late John Kennedy Jr.'s George
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Hill has completed a book on her experiences, which is scheduled
for publication next spring by Harper San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said she's ready to get on with her life. She said she
hopes a scheduled rally Sunday in Stafford to mark the second
anniversary of her protest will turn into a homecoming celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an agreement is reached, it would be the best gift I could
ever receive,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 1845EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1985 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-BONFIRE-ESSAY-2500(2T     12-07 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-ESSAY-2500(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY GROW UP FAST AND THEY DIE QUICKLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JENNIFER BRIGGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the day after the Bonfire tragedy at Texas A&AMP;M University.
I am pulling into my parents' driveway in Arlington, Texas. There
is a strange car there. I see the Corps of Cadets sticker on the
back window. Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Oh my gosh, it's Ethan. One of two nephews who are like sons to
me. He's here. I just want to touch him. To feel his flesh. To feel
for sure that the tall, muscular body is warm as I grab his neck.
</P>
<P>
   He really is alive. He drove up here from College Station. So he
really is alive. He really was at the bottom of that Bonfire stack
as it fell. His brother Stuart is alive, too, though I haven't got
to touch him yet. Lord, how we all want to touch him.
</P>
<P>
   As I look back at what happened, and look forward at how we help
them heal, nothing is in order in my head because there is little
we can do to help them.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Ethan, the freshman, was next to climb the stack the night of
the accident that took the lives of 12 people. Literally seconds
from scaling that big nest of logs he had helped cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just heard this weird creaking noise,'' he said. ``The
snapping. And then the screams. There were screams everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   As it was, he was at the base, on the side where everything
fell. So many were trapped where he was.
</P>
<P>
   They dropped the big log his group was carrying and ran away,
with trees chasing them, and just as fast they ran back to pick
through the dead and injured. He and one other cadet were told to
run to the Corps dorm and alert their commanding officer.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lights of my life, whom I see here in a
Superman-suit-and-cowboy-hat photo, was running through the dark at
3 a.m., a mile, to alert the sleeping cadets to the worst news they
may ever hear.
</P>
<P>
   They called their commanding officer ``Mister,'' as the freshman
are told to do. And then they told him. Then, hearts beating like
sparrows, they ran, banging on doors.
</P>
<P>
   Something terrible has happened at the stack. Help.
</P>
<P>
   And it was Stuart's shift, also. He is my oldest nephew, who had
been stupid a few weeks earlier and had ridden a motorcycle a half
block and fallen over somehow. As a senior, he was scheduled to be
at the top of that pile on one of those ropes during the very
moment it collapsed. An injury on the bike prevented it. If not for
a matter of seconds and stupidity, we could have lost two boys.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   We coax our children onto the Shock Wave or the Texas Giant at
Six Flags when they are little. We run them up to the hospital when
they fall at a garage sale and they separate a shoulder _ and no
one knows for sure at first that they are hurt, because we hold our
breath for those five precious seconds after a child's fall,
waiting to see if they are just scared or really hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Today, we know they are scared and hurt. But as the older
people, the alleged grownups, we know not where the hurt comes from
or where it will go. And we long for soccer bruises and
water-up-the-nose-at-the-lake tears.
</P>
<P>
   That water weenie of a little boy we bribed into a wet maze at
Sesame Place ran one mile to bang on doors and tell several hundred
young men about something the state of Texas will regret, but he
will never forget.
</P>
<P>
   He is the little boy I see here in a photograph of a plastic
swimming pool, all out of sorts because water went up his nose.
</P>
<P>
   I am in from out of state and sitting in the room I grew up in.
There is a quote as big as an old Polaroid at the top of Page 15A
of the Star-Telegram from Ethan: ``It was unmistakable. You could
hear the creaking, snapping sound and then the screams. There were
screams everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Will I ever be able to quit looking at it?''
</P>
<P>
   Below it, he is that half-naked portrait in a swimming pool,
smiling and squinting, fat-bellied, like some little Austin Powers
clone, sans suit.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   We are at Sesame Place. They are both less than 10 years old.
Stuart and I go through the maze in that water thingy. Ethan will
not go through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be a baby, Ethan,'' I say as I push him away and force
him into that hose vortex.
</P>
<P>
   Today, I cannot hold him close enough. That little boy at the
bottom of the stack, the bad part of the stack where everything
fell, after assisting those he could get to, ran a mile.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over it plays out in my head until I am sick of my
brain replaying it. I just want to touch his flesh over and over.
But I don't. I don't know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   We are standing at the funeral of Jerry Don Self, one of those
killed in the collapse. Ethan is back at A&AMP;M. Stuart has his arms
wrapped around the woman he will propose to two days later. These
are babies.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart takes off his Corps hat. The program from his Uncle Bud's
funeral in July is folded neatly inside the plastic lining along
with the program for this funeral.
</P>
<P>
   They play Taps. It is warm. The heels of women's shoes poke into
the parched Texas soil. The clouds close in, and the sky begins to
cry little tears.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny droplets roll down shaved heads.
</P>
<P>
   I pick lint off his uniform. Such an absurd gesture at such a
time when a flag is flying halfway down a pole and tears are
rolling down young men's cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Don Self's mama looks like she has been in a terrible
accident. And she has. How can his grandmas even walk?
</P>
<P>
   Stuart looks like he did the day one of his grandfathers died,
drawn and red-eyed, almost 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   I notice the tiny imperfections in the skin on his shaved head.
I want to touch his shoulder, to lean on him, but it is a private
grief I cannot fix.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   We go back to the day it happened.
</P>
<P>
   I have a dream in the middle of the night. I believe it is real
at the time. It is maybe 1:30 or so. I think the old Arlington
Stadium, or maybe The Ballpark at Arlington, is falling.
</P>
<P>
   I dream The Boys are out there, and there are big brown bricks.
It may be the same time that the Bonfire is falling. I do not know.
But I know they are OK and something important has fallen.
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask me how in the world I could know anything like that.
</P>
<P>
   At College Station, it is 3 a.m., and it is not a dream. Our
youngest is picking through the dead and injured. Then he is
running.
</P>
<P>
   It is a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   My mother comes in at 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuart and Ethan are OK,'' she says, near crying. ``Something
collapsed by the stadium, and they were there. Ethan was on it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that,'' I said. ``It all fell. I know they are OK.''
</P>
<P>
   My husband asks, ``How could you know that?''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unmistakable. You could hear the creaking, snapping
sound and then the screams. There were screams everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   That quote happens to be sitting on a desk with the pictures of
these two young men. The three of us coming off Mr. Toad's Wild
Ride at Walt Disney World. We are laughing hysterically.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   I walked down the corridors of Baylor Medical Center with arms
on their shoulders, trying to explain that Christmas Eve in the
1980s, what it means when your mamma has a miscarriage.
</P>
<P>
   Or the day Pawpaw Cecil was buried, the future Corps of Cadets
chaplain crawled from bed and came to me at 1 a.m., asking what it
would be like when Jesus came again and if we would see Pawpaw
Cecil.
</P>
<P>
   I could even wiggle out of that one and try to explain my
thoughts on the matter, how if it happened like we thought it
might, we'd all be in the same place when the whole big drama had
played itself out.
</P>
<P>
   But I cannot explain this.
</P>
<P>
   So, though as a journalist I hate to admit it because of how we
are, but as a Christian, I must. I pray.
</P>
<P>
   So what do I say to the chaplain of the Corps of Cadets as he
grapples with his own grief and attempts to console so many others,
500 of whom he is in charge of, when he is only 22?
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you need me to pray for?'' I ask in one of perhaps
seven phone calls made to his room the day that it happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pray for Ethan,'' he says on the phone. ``He saw a lot more
than I did.''
</P>
<P>
   And Stuart was off to counsel four cadets and move logs.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   I look again at all the photos before me.
</P>
<P>
   There he is in his boots _ not his senior boots of the Corps,
but the little ones. He has some play gun in his hand and some
Speed Racer kind of helmet on. It looks worse than the time Lisa
Green and I dressed up like Totie Fields and walked to Buddies
supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   We are in parks; we are playing baseball as a family and wading
into water after a flood while my mother is hollering that we could
drown. Stuart and I are laughing.
</P>
<P>
   They are my dates at sports banquets I covered as a writer. I
reasoned that I would have a date, a boyfriend, for a moment in the
scheme of things, but these were my boys forever.
</P>
<P>
   Now I know they aren't. In the long run, I guess they all belong
to God. If they were terminally ill, either of them, I could send
them to Disney World and make them tuna sandwiches, wipe their
foreheads and fill them with Dr Pepper.
</P>
<P>
   They are just terminally hurt.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unmistakable. You could hear the creaking, snapping
sound and then the screams. There were screams everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Did this little boy I built a wagon for on Christmas Eve in 1983
really see that?
</P>
<P>
   On that Monday, they played Taps at Moore Funeral Home. That's
where most of the dead in our family are. Even a dog's ashes were
recently (and surreptitiously) interred there.
</P>
<P>
   But don't tell anybody we put 'em there with my Uncle Bud.
</P>
<P>
   As the cadets filed past the Self family, I went over to see
Uncle Bud. I told him something that someone in the family did that
was stupid and funny. Then I told him why we were all there.
</P>
<P>
   They would have been atop that pile, I explain. We were even
down there at College Station when they cut the logs, and then
Ethan came in all tired and dirty, happier to sleep than to eat the
hamburgers at the Aggie home we were at.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Look at your 1-year-olds. If you raise them good, their strength
may be inestimable.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how much you love them, someday, their grief may
be insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   There is no ice pack, no splint, no chocolate or Power Rangers
coloring book that makes this ever go away.
</P>
<P>
   It is just there.
</P>
<P>
   Prayer and verses may help seal the wound for the religious. But
the bleeding will never stop for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   In the room I am in, there is this huge bear that Stuart used to
sleep on. I got it when I worked at Six Flags Over Texas when he
was a baby and I was still a child. It is partially blind, having
lost one plastic eye in the procession of years that lead to garage
sales. He was salvaged. A little Febreeze and an eye transplant,
and he will be passed to our next generation.
</P>
<P>
   Dear God, thank you we still have a next generation.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Three generations of women stand in the rain, watching them get
ready to pull out of a house on Westwood Drive and go back to A&AMP;M
after the funeral. It is the driveway of their grandparents, where
they learned about road rash on trikes and sold Dr Pepper to the
lines of cars waiting to see the Christmas lights in the
Interlochen neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   They were driven out of this driveway to see Nolan Ryan's
5,000th strikeout. Today I stand in this driveway, after a funeral,
wondering how I can fix this. They separate that shoulder, break an
arm at soccer, don't make the baseball team in high school. That
can be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   There are words that grownups with more experience at being
grownups than a 22-year-old can suck up through their throat and
spit out to both babies and grown children in other rough
situations.
</P>
<P>
   You tell them you are proud of them anyway, though these two
seldom failed. It's OK that you didn't make varsity.
</P>
<P>
   Or you throw 'em in the car and get over to the hospital for
those stitches.
</P>
<P>
   And you watch the wound heal.
</P>
<P>
   My nephews, whom I sit here this minute and look at in
photographs, with a doctor's kit, by a Christmas tree, with a
Superman suit in a cowboy hat, have more healing to do than they
can even know, and I can only guess at.
</P>
<P>
   What do we do? Send them cookies and Gumby's Pizza gift
certificates? Pray? Take them to CiCi's?
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   Both of them have witnessed what is clearly an unspeakable
tragedy. There are no words to give our children at a time like
this.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Just after the funeral, Stuart says he is on the list of people
taking Aggie charters to California for another funeral.
</P>
<P>
   I hold my breath. I sigh, ``Well, that's good,'' half lying in
how I feel about a kid who has faced so much death going halfway
across a continent and back in a day on an unknown charter.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot fix this, either.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Here is the church where I answered an altar call when I was 10.
Gave my heart to Jesus by a Southern Baptist pulpit, as many good
Texans _ and bad ones _ do.
</P>
<P>
   We sing about saving a wretch like me, and sawing varsity's
horns off _ short. Two thousand mighty voices. I think how I have
got to call my friend Lisa, now in Indiana, and tell her we sang
the ``Aggie War Hymn'' in church and said ``hell,'' twice, right
there in First Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   I think about how Mr. Self's mamma looks like she could ...
well, not faint, but just implode.
</P>
<P>
   I think about this peri-menopausal thing and wonder if that is
why I feel like I could faint dead away right there _ or is it
because I will have no words for The Boys because I have no words
of comfort for myself, for anyone?
</P>
<P>
   We cannot fix this. It is not a broken arm.
</P>
<P>
   Here is where I went to vacation Bible school. Here is where one
of my dearest sits in a uniform, wearing his senior boots. Alive.
Crying like a guy cries.
</P>
<P>
   Here is where grief has come home to rest.
</P>
<P>
   But it will not sleep long.
</P>
<P>
   We are at a funeral. Singing the ``Aggie War Hymn.'' The act
itself is a reminder that, we, my family, could be doing it alone.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many are.
</P>
<P>
   They grow up so fast. They die so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Briggs is a former Fort Worth Star-Telegram writer, in
town writing a book about Tom Landry. She has covered Major League
Baseball, the NFL and NBA. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
