A1990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NYTIMES-FILM-CRITICS-     12-07 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTIMES-FILM-CRITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. TIMES NAMES 2 NEW CRITICS FOR GROWING FILM FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Times has appointed two new film critics
to review the growing number of new releases, executive editor
Joseph Lelyveld announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The critics, Elvis Mitchell, 41, of The Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, and A.O. Scott, 33, the Sunday book critic at
Newsday, will assume their duties in January, joining Stephen
Holden, who has been a staff critic for The Times for 11 years. The
three will share responsibilities, with Holden in particular also
writing regular critical essays in the Arts &AMP; Leisure section on
Sundays, said Lelyveld.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Maslin, the newspaper's senior film critic, announced
Sept. 21 that she was leaving the paper after 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, The Star-Telegram's film critic for two years,
previously reviewed films for The Los Angeles Herald-Examiner and
The Detroit Free Press. For the last 15 years, he has also been an
entertainment critic for ``Weekend Edition with Scott Simon'' on
National Public Radio. He was also host of the film-related
interview program ``The Treatment'' for KCRW, Santa Monica's public
radio station, and the host of the Independent Film Channel's
``Independent Focus'' program.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell has also written on movies for Rolling Stone, GQ and
Interview magazines. He was brought up in Detroit and attended
Wayne State University.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Newsday last April, Scott wrote for The New York
Times Book Review, The New York Review of Books, The Nation and The
New Yorker. He has been an editor at The New York Review and Lingua
Franca and has been a regular contributor on culture and politics
to the Internet magazine Slate. A recent article in Slate on Martin
Scorsese drew him to the attention of The Times, said Lelyveld.
Scott has a B.A. in literature from Harvard and a master's degree
in English from Johns Hopkins University.
</P>
<P>
   Lelyveld said the increase in the number of critics was a
response to the growing number of movie releases. In 1990 The Times
ran 325 movie reviews; so far this year, the number is 375.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 1848EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1994 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-CIDER-HOUSE-REVI     12-07 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CIDER-HOUSE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use Friday, Dec. 10 or later. Fact box at bottom.) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saying that ``The Cider House Rules'' is the best John Irving
adaptation to ever hit the screen is a little like saying that
lethal injection is our most wonderful form of capital punishment.
With Irving movies, what are the alternatives? The bittersweet and
brainless ``The World According to Garp''? The witless ``Hotel New
Hampshire''? The sappy ``Simon Birch''?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Irving has not been well-served by cinema, which could
be why he decided to write the screenplay for ``Cider House''
himself. And while the movie is a decided improvement over the
recent six-hour stage version, ``Cider'' remains a pretty thin
coming-of-age tale that frames its moral concerns in ways that are
a little too obvious. It's a decent film that's hampered by its own
illusions of grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cider House'' follows the story of Homer Wells (Tobey
Maguire), a young man who grows up in the sheltering atmosphere of
the St. Cloud's orphanage in Maine. Homer is the favorite of the
orphanage's director, Dr. Wilbur Larch (Michael Caine), but as he
grows older, he begins to feel confined. He also doesn't approve of
Dr. Larch's side business _ performing abortions.
</P>
<P>
   When Candy Kendall (Charlize Theron) and Wally Worthington (Paul
Rudd) pay a visit to the good doctor, Homer decides to adopt them
and liberate himself from St. Cloud's. Homer sees the ocean for the
first time, picks apples with a group of itinerants and falls in
love with Candy after Wally leaves for Air Force duty in World War
II. He gradually forgets St. Cloud's, but Dr. Larch can't shake the
memory of Homer (although he tries, using generous doses of ether).
</P>
<P>
   It's all pleasant enough, with the low-key Maguire turning in
another fine performance, albeit one that is growing somewhat
familiar. The story's conflict comes when Homer is confronted with
a situation that tests his long-held views on abortion. If there's
little question about Homer's choice, it's because Irving has so
completely stacked the deck in his story, producing a situation
that would probably make Pat Robertson jettison his beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, instead of delivering a truly provocative film, Irving's
``Cider House'' stands as a pretty slight tale of moral relativism.
Swedish director Lasse Hallstrom displays an eye for wintry
landscapes, which is appropriate, given the film's cold and
somewhat distant tone. Nobody, save Caine, makes much of an
impression, and his screen time is too scant to truly make you care
about his complex character.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax, the film's distributor, will undoubtedly spend millions
of dollars selling ``Cider,'' as this is the Oscar-hungry studio's
only real chance for academy gold. If they somehow manage some
nominations for this modest movie, it will be time for other
studios to wave the white flag and rename the Oscars in Harvey
Weinstein's honor. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
The film: &LR;  ``The Cider House Rules'' (PG-13; mature thematic
elements, sexuality, nudity, substance abuse and some violence. &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Tobey Maguire, Charlize Theron, Michael Caine. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Directed by Lasse Hallstrom. Screenplay by John
Irving, based upon his novel. Released by Miramax Films. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  Two hours, five minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Playing: &LR;  AMC Century 14 in Century City; Laemmle's Sunset 5
Theatres in West Hollywood; Laemmle's Monica in Santa Monica. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  2 1/2 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 1850EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
