<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMF-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS COMPLAIN THAT WEST LINKS IMF AID TO CHECNYA CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian officials on Tuesday reacted angrily to Western
condemnation of Moscow's military tactics in Chechnya, warning that
threats to impose sanctions or interrupt aid are unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Several officials insisted that Russia is already feeling the
effects of the West's criticism through the International Monetary
Fund's decision in the past week to once again postpone delivery of
a $640-million credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that in this case, political considerations were
crucial in the decision-making,'' said First Deputy Prime Minister
Victor Khristenko. ``The IMF's status as a non-political
organization is in question.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military's ultimatum to residents of the Chechen
capital of Grozny to get out of the city by Saturday or risk death
has provoked a torrent of criticism in Western capitals. In
Britain, Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said that European Union aid
to Russia would be reviewed at a meeting next week if the Russian
military does not observe ``basic humanitarian norms.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has warned Moscow that it would pay ``a heavy
price'' if it continued killing civilians in a war that Russia
contends it is waging against terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, a Foreign Ministry spokesman rejected the warnings.
``The language of economic sanctions and diktat is unacceptable,
all the more so when it concerns the issue of Russia's territorial
integrity and the fight against terrorism,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Western leaders and diplomats do not challenge Russia's right to
protect its territory against the Chechen separatists, and have
expressed support for Moscow's efforts to suppress guerrillas whose
attacks last August on a neighboring Russian region ignited the
latest conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But they have been increasingly outraged by what NATO
Secretary-General George Robinson called Russia's ``hamfisted''
tactics in a war that has caused uncounted civilian deaths, and a
chaotic exodus of more than 200,000 refugees. Robertson said the
Russian military campaign was both counter-productive, and
unacceptable to the international community.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the heels of Western indignation over Russian
financial scandals, the criticism of the Chechen war has cast a new
pall over Russia's relations with the West, and several Russian
commentators are already warning of a new Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia is heavily indebted to its Western creditors, and the
Russian government, now as during the NATO war in Kosovo, has been
careful not to close off its relationship with Western partners.
But Russia's economic dependence is itself a source of bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been eagerly awaiting the latest installment of
credits from the IMF; Russia has pledged to use the money simply to
offset outstanding debts to the fund. Without the money, Russia
would have cut back on its spending, and dip into hard currency
reserves. Otherwise, it would fall short of the tight budget
policies it pledged to adhere to in an agreement with the IMF last
year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The $640 million credit, the second part of a $4.5-billion
package approved last year, was originally to be delivered in
September, once Russia showed it was in full compliance with the
fiscal requirements set forth in the agreement. But the fund
postponed the loan and pressed for new conditions, at the urging of
leading industrial countries. The conditions were aimed largely at
structural economic reforms, in part as a result of the Russian
financial scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to meet those new conditions - which include measures
setting higher standards of accountability and openness for
financial institutions - have been cited by IMF spokesmen as the
reasons for the latest delay.
</P>
<P>
   But Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, speaking to reporters
Tuesday, said he was not convinced that the reasons were not
political. ``The formal pretext is a supposed failure to implement
certain obligations,'' he said. `'We do not think so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
