<HEADLINE>
HANCOCK WIDENS SEARCH FOR MISSING CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Widening its search for scores of missing customers,
John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. has asked top state
officials across the country to help it track down policyholders
eligible for compensation when the big insurer converts to a
publicly-traded company.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, in a December 6 letter to the Massachusetts Division of
Insurance, said it had contacted 13 secretaries of state from coast
to coast last month to ask for assistance in tracing policyholders
with unknown whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   The move came after Massachusetts Secretary of State William
Galvin, who has criticized the Boston-based insurer for not keeping
tabs on customers, conducted his own search of state databases last
month and located 23,000 in-state customers.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, a leading life insurer, has drawn criticism for losing
track of one quarter of its 3.3 million insurance customers. It has
found half of them but still has to locate some 400,000 people
nationwide, including 73,600 in Massachusetts. The company has 3.3
million policyholders overall, but in its letter to the Division it
claimed 5 million customers across all businesses, including its
mutual fund operations.
</P>
<P>
   About 2.9 million policyholders are eligible for stock, cash, or
beefier policies when Hancock issues $2 billion in an initial
public stock offering on Jan. 27 or 28.
</P>
<P>
   The insurer wants help from authorities in California, Florida,
Michigan, New York, Ohio, Vermont and other states where residents
bought Hancock insurance in previous decades, typically burial
policies worth less than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Policy holders are the nominal owners of a mutual.
</P>
<P>
   About 94 percent of voting policyholders, or over 1 million
people, approved Hancock's conversion last week. Missing
policyholders, who may have moved without leaving forwarding
addresses or died, cannot now vote but have until the end of the
year to step forward and elect stock or cash. Most policyholders
had until Nov. 30 to choose the form of compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock president and chief executive-elect David D'Alessandro
said the insurer would allow missing customers to come forward and
claim stock up to seven years after the initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Burgay, a Hancock spokesman, said Tuesday that the time
period for claiming compensation after the public offering would
vary by state. ``It will vary from state to state, depending on the
laws,'' Burgay said.
</P>
<P>
   But Galvin cast doubt on the offer. ``Keeping the option open
after the IPO has raised concerns with the SEC,'' he said. The
Securities and Exchange Commission overseas Hancock's initial
public offering, while Galvin and the Division of Insurance have
regulatory power over the insurer.
</P>
<P>
   Galvin said Hancock was concerned that missing policyholders
could intentionally delay coming forward in order to profit from
gains in the new stock, which is expected to rise in value. He also
criticized Hancock for not contacting approximately 15,000
Massachusetts customers whose addresses he said his office had
forwarded to Hancock one week before the Nov. 30 policyholder
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's bookkeeping has enraged some customers who claim they
were never mailed any information about the company's conversion.
Elsie C. Flaherty, a long-time policyholder, said she had received
no mailings from the insurer in a while. ``How can they just lose
everything?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock says its problems stem from customers who move without
leaving forwarding addresses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
