<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE, GETTING OVER FLU, SAYS HE'S COMING BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He admits the last little stretch hasn't been a whole
lot of fun. The Bruins have been in a downward spiral the last
seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Independent of that, Ray Bourque said, he hasn't felt his best,
and it has been apparent on the ice. The unlimited energy the
Bruins' captain usually displays and the extra jump that has so
often been his hallmark have been lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said the flu knocked him for a loop and he's just now
starting to feel like his old self. He missed practice back on Nov.
19 because of the illness, but suffered through the schedule
because he didn't want to miss any more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a fever and I was tired and weak,'' said Bourque. ``I
wasn't feeling right. I had that for about a week. I played a
couple of games with it and you're just trying to survive the
games, more or less. I did that and I felt better after a while.
Now, I just want to get to where I was before that happened and I
think I'm getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, who turns 39 this month, started the season feeling
great physically. As frustrating as it was for the Bruins to go
winless in their first nine games (0-5-4), he said he had a lot of
energy. Now, after battling the flu, it's just starting to come
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to play better, and I'll get there,'' he said. ``When
you get run down and you're not feeling too well, just energywise
and skatingwise, it takes time to get that back, and that's the
thing that was lacking is that extra step you might have when
you're feeling really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque endorsed the last two days of hard skating that coach
Pat Burns put the players through. He said it was a chance for the
club to regroup, especially after the horrifying 9-3 loss to the
Chicago Blackhawks at the FleetCenter Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's well needed,'' said Bourque. ``Right now, it's a good
week to work on conditioning and skating. We've worked hard the
last couple of days. We know we're a good team and we had a tough
game on Saturday and it's a matter of rebounding and getting back
to the things we should be doing and doing them better and harder
and I think that'll happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of his 21 seasons, Bourque said, invariably
there is at least one game a year when the video should be burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year you go through certain times where it might be a
game or a stretch of games where you're not doing the right things
and you're not doing the job you should be doing,'' he said. ``We
had a good month last month and we won a lot of games and got
ourselves back into the race. Of late, we were getting ties or the
odd win but we weren't playing as well as we did at the beginning
of that month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something you could kind of sense. Little things were
kind of creeping in, and when you have a game like we did against
Chicago, it kind of brings everything to the forefront where you
say, `Hey, it's time to shape up here and get back to doing the
things that we should be doing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, like everyone on the team, suffered from execution
problems Saturday. It was so bad, it was shocking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievable,'' he said. ``You're sitting on the bench
and thinking, `Man, this has got to end.' But we still had a period
and a half or a period. We gave up nine goals but they easily
could've scored a dozen. We just didn't want them to get to 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough. You just want to try to survive those games or
have them end real quick. It was a long night and having it at home
is the tough thing. Fans are expecting you to play hard and they're
paying good money for the tickets and that's really tough because
you really feel for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that you're not trying, you just can't get anything
done. We were just horrible. It's kind of embarrassing when it
happens to you at home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
