<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 WINE POTPOURRI: All That Sparkles Is Not Gold   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO  _ Champagne, the mere mention of the word makes most
people happy. Could it be the bubbles or is the excitement all
about the wine? Whatever the reason, when people want a festive
drink, they usually turn to Champagne.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long ago, Champagne producers had it all, since there were
no serious challengers at the time to the best sparkling wine in
the world. Then, a few of the larger Champagne houses began to look
outside the Champagne region for new places to make sparkling
wines. In the early 1970s, Moet &AMP; Chandon founded Domaine Chandon
in the Napa Valley and the race was on.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, other houses came onboard. But it wasn't until about 10
years ago that the quality of California sparkling wines began to
give the Champagne producers cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
   Champagne, and most sparkling wines made by the  &LR; m &LR; e &LR; thode &LR; 
 &LR; champenoise &LR; , are blends of Pinot Noir, Chardonnay and for some
producers, a little Pinot Meunier. Pinot Noir provides body and
structure, while Pinot Meunier lends ripe fruitiness and Chardonnay
gives the wine delicacy, finesse and freshness.
</P>
<P>
   By law, Champagne is restricted to three grapes, while sparkling
wine producers elsewhere in France and in other countries use other
grapes, like Pinot Blanc, Chenin Blanc and Riesling. Many of the
world's sparkling wines are excellent in their own style, but none
should be confused with Champagne. While California's Roederer
Estate, Domaine Chandon-Australia and Italy's Ferrari produce
exciting elegant stylistic sparkling wines, they are not Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   All Champagne and the best sparkling wines, are fermented and
aged in the bottle. The process, which can involve up to 300
hands-on steps, produces steady streams of pinpoint silvery
bubbles, a complex bouquet of fruit and a toasty yeast, not unlike
the scent of warm bread dough. The wines are balanced, crisp and
very refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Champagne Bible &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Champagne story is a fascinating one and few people are more
qualified to tell the tale than Tom Stevenson, an award-winning
English wine writer, who has earned the title ``champagne guru''
within the wine community.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson's new book, ``Christie's World Encyclopedia of
Champagne &AMP; Sparkling Wine,'' is a comprehensive timely examination
of Champagne and other French sparkling wines, plus a look at
sparkling wines from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Working from an assessment of 100 points, Stevenson rates the
hundreds of Champagne houses and other sparkling wine producers (98
is the highest rating for the likes of Krug, Pol Rogercq, Dom
Perignon and Salon). Scores drop off dramatically for the sparkling
wines of other countries, although Stevenson ranks Roederer Estate
(90) and Iron Horse (88) as two of his California favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson's book on Champagne and sparkling wine has become the
new bible for sparkling wine fans and is highly recommended.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``Christie's World Encyclopedia of Champagne&AMP;Sparkling &LR; 
 &LR; Wine,'' by Tom Stevenson (Wine Appreciation Guild, San &LR; 
 &LR; Francisco; 335 pages, hardcover; &LR;   &LR; $50). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Everyman's Guide &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If the Stevenson encyclopedia is too serious and too expensive,
take a look at the latest wine entry in the Dummies series,
``Champagne for Dummies,'' by New York writer and educator Ed
McCarthy. Billed as ``A reference for the rest of us,'' the Dummies
book is an easy-reading guide to all aspects of Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy touches all the bases, from an explanation of the
Champagne method, to buying, storing and serving Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   It would be unfair to compare this guide to Stevenson's
comprehensive encyclopedia. Let's just say, that if you're looking
for essential information in an easy-to-read format, ``Champagne
for Dummies'' is your reference book.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``Champagne for Dummies,'' by Ed McCarthy (IDG Books &LR; 
 &LR; Worldwide; 286 pages, softcover; $16.99). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Sparkling End Note &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Much has been written about the use of the names ``Champagne''
and ``sparkling wine.'' Some will tell you that Champagne is a
generic name like aspirin, while others, like myself, claim that
Champagne is made only in that region of France and everything else
is a sparkling wine. Campaigners for use of the word Champagne for
any wine with bubbles say that sparkling wine sounds blah. Well,
sparkling wine is the best term we have and I say let's keep using
it until someone comes up with something better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
