<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2017 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-AFRICA-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      12-07 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS FAULT CLINTON ON AFRICA POLICY FOLLOW-UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ No United States leader has voiced a stronger
commitment to Africa than President Clinton, but nearly two years
after he made an unprecedented tour of the continent, critics say
substance has yet to follow the US rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   This harsh assessment comes from former President Jimmy Carter,
who charged this week that US policy was scuttling efforts to end
Sudan's brutal civil war, and from a range of academics in both
Africa and North America.
</P>
<P>
   It was two years ago that Clinton whistle-stopped across the
continent, apologizing for slavery and for turning his back on
Rwanda's 1994 genocide, and promising a new era of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, a parade of cabinet secretaries and special envoys
has voyaged across Africa. Earlier this week, midway through a
10-state tour to ``elevate African issues on our list of national
priorities,'' Richard Holbrooke, US ambassador to the United
Nations, vowed in a speech in South Africa that Washington would
focus on African crises when it assumes the presidency of the
United Nations Security Council next month.
</P>
<P>
   But back home, the African Growth and Opportunity Act, the
cornerstone of Clinton's African trade policy, languishes in
Congress. American aid to South Africa has dropped from $210
million in 1994 to $47 million today. Africa accounts for just 2
percent of total US trade, and in relation to its population, the
United States ranks as the lowest donor to Africa of the 24 most
industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the critics say, the United States has yet to
formulate an effective response to ongoing wars in Congo _ Africa's
first major multinational conflict _ or in Angola, where the rebel
movement, which was propped up by Washington during the cold war,
has obstructed attempts at peaceful democratic change.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is not a serious power in this part of the world,''
said John Stremlau, a visiting professor of international relations
at the University of the Witswatersrand in Johannesburg. ``There's
ample evidence of talking the talk, but they're not walking the
walk.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the US State Department did not respond Tuesday
to several requests for comment on the criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   Some say US policies do more harm than good. When the leaders of
Sudan and Uganda meet Wednesday in Kenya to discuss how to end the
16-year civil war in Sudan, their work will be complicated by a
food aid bill signed by Clinton last week.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan's is Africa's longest running conflict and has claimed
close to 2 million lives. To the peril of regional stability, the
Clinton administration has used northern Uganda as a military
training ground for southern Sudanese rebels fighting the Muslim
government of Khartoum, which Washington accuses of supporting
terrorism. The new food legislation funnels relief exclusively to
the south, a step that aid officials and analysts say will enable
the rebels to spend resources rearming rather than feeding
civilians caught in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in Sudan want to resolve the conflict. The biggest
obstacle is US government policy,'' said former President Carter in
an interview last week in Mozambique. ``The US is committed to
overthrowing the government in Khartoum. Any sort of peace effort
is aborted, basically by policies of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recent bill that the president signed is a devastating
obstacle to any furtherance of peace,'' added Carter, who is to
mediate the Sudan talks. ``For the first time, we have authorized
food aid just for the revolutionaries in southern Sudan. . .
Instead of working for peace in Sudan, the US government has
basically promoted a continuation of the war.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech this week in South Africa, Holbrooke cited various
measures and figures to demonstrate that Clinton is following
through on his commitment to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, Holbrooke said, the administration has helped to
develop local peacekeeping capacity through the African Crisis
Response Initiative. The United States contributed $8 million to
the Organization of African Unity, the continent's broadest
multinational organization; delivered $6 million last week to West
African security forces to help defuse the civil crisis in Sierra
Leone; and this week will make $1 million available to the Joint
Military Commission created by the terms of the recent cease-fire
between warring parties in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke also cited the payment of $926 million in arrears to
the UN and an allocation in the new budget of more than $100
million in debt relief for the poorest African nations.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say those numbers pale in comparison to the
financial and military commitment the Unitrf States made earlier
this year in Kosovo _ $5 billion and 7,000 troops _ and fade to
insignificance in the context of Congo's war.
</P>
<P>
   From South Africa, Holbrooke moved on to explore solutions to
the conflicts in Congo and Angola.
</P>
<P>
   The parties to the Congo fighting signed a cease-fire last July
in Lusaka, Zambia. It hasn't held. In Angola, meanwhile, government
and rebel troops resumed full-scale civil war a year ago after the
gradual disintegration of a 1994 accord.
</P>
<P>
   The UN is preparing to deploy 500 military peacekeeping monitors
in Congo, Holbrooke said, but the international community won't
become involved until ``the parties to the Lusaka Agreement. .
.respect their commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   That position is a cover for no US commitment at all, said Makau
Mutua, a professor of international law at the State University of
New York at Buffalo. The United States, he argued, could put
pressure on Uganda and Rwanda, the two countries that sparked the
war in Congo, to withdraw their support for the rebel factions. But
those countries are Washington's key regional allies in its stance
against the Sudan government, and Clinton so far has done more to
support them than rein them in.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the US intervened in Kosovo it faced a much more
formidable army,'' Mutua said. ``All the West has to do is put
10,000 troops in Congo and lean on Rwanda and Uganda. The crisis
would end in a minute. The fact is, the US has no intention to
intervene in Congo.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke also said the administration will back sanctions
against the Angolan rebels, who finance their war largely with
smuggled diamonds from the country's lucrative mines. ``We will . .
. hold a special Security Council meeting on Angola in January, and
we will immediately begin to seek ways to tighten the sanctions
regime,'' Holbrooke said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   That's a welcome start, Stremlau and Mutua said, but it is late
and insufficient. During the Cold War and apartheid, the United
States and South Africa were instrumental in creating Unita, the
Angolan rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
   Both have since distanced themselves from Unita, but Washington
and Pretoria ``bear a legal and moral responsibility to force an
end to Unita's murderous campaign,'' Mutua said. Given the close
ties between the United States and South Africa today, ``there is
no reason why they are not doing that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
