<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute
Recipe takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast and
Fresh. 
 
 WORKING COOK: Simple Fare Puts Guests at Ease  By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; When you're stocking up on beef jerky, propane and
Power bars in case the Y2K meltdown actually happens, grab a few
lamb chops and some fish while you're at it. Even if you don't feel
like planning a big blow-out dinner for New Year's Eve, you can
still entertain at home with one of these low-key but stylish
recipes.
<P>
   The fastest recipe of the week, Ginger-Steamed Fish, is based on
a quick and easy Chinese cooking technique _ steaming fish fillets
with aromatic ginger and green onion, and seasoning them with a
mixture of vinegar, soy sauce and sesame oil. These simple
components serve as both a quick marinade and a light sauce after
the fish is finished.
</P>
<P>
   The Mint-Crusted Lamb Chops With Cranberry Couscous are a bit
more involved but still quick, since thin lamb chops take almost no
time to broil.
</P>
<P>
   Coat the chops with honey mustard to heighten the sweet and
spicy flavors in their minty breadcrumb coating. The crust itself
is a heady mix of fresh mint, garlic, seasonings and Panko
breadcrumbs, a great Japanese product that many supermarkets carry.
When piled upright on a bed of cranberry-jeweled couscous, the
crispy lamb chops make an impressive presentation for a dinner
party.
</P>
<P>
   If you're planning to have lots of people over and you don't
want to do a lot of last-minute cooking, prepare the Winter
Vegetable Stew With Cornbread Cobbler. The sweetness of carrots,
red onions and sweet potatoes are balanced by a hearty spice
mixture, and cauliflower, which is fairly neutral, soaks it all up.
But the best part of all is the savory cornbread cobbler topping.
</P>
<P>
   The stew takes some time to prepare, but the steps are easy and
the dish is such a cozy choice for New Year's Eve at home _ and
vegetarians will feel like they're celebrating, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FAST &AMP; FRESHL dinner in about 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; GINGER-STEAMED FISH
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups medium-grain rice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   6 teaspoons rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds thin white fish fillets, such as cod or red snapper
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   3 large green onions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Begin cooking the rice according to package directions.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together the vegetable oil, vinegar, sesame oil and soy
sauce in a small bowl. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Tear off 4 pieces of foil, about 12 x 6 inches each. Place a
fish fillet on each piece of foil. Turn up the edges by a few
inches around the fish to create a rim around the fish, so that
each fillet is in a tray that won't allow liquids to get out but is
still open on top.
</P>
<P>
   Season each fillet with salt. Spoon equal parts of the soy sauce
mixture on each fillet. Sprinkle the ginger and green onions on
top.
</P>
<P>
   Set up a large steamer, either bamboo or metal-mesh type, and
place 2 packages inside. Cover and steam until flaky, about 6 to 8
minutes, depending on the thickness of the fish. Repeat with the
remaining fillets.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the packages carefully, reserving cooking juices. Place
each fillet over a bed of rice and drizzle with the juices.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 550 calories, &LR;   &LR; 45 g protein, 57 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 14 g fat (2 g saturated), 117 mg cholesterol, 480
mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 30-MINUTE MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; MINT-CRUSTED LAMB CHOPS WITH CRANBERRY COUSCOUS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey mustard
</P>
<P>
   11/2 to 2 pounds lamb chops, no more than 1-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Breadcrumb Coating
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch mint, leaves only
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Panko breadcrumbs (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   Pinch cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   Couscous
</P>
<P>
   21/4 cups low-salt chicken broth or water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coarsely chopped dried cranberries
</P>
<P>
   1 (10-ounce) package instant couscous
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to broil.
</P>
<P>
   Place the honey-mustard in a small bowl. Season the lamb chops
with salt and pepper. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place the mint leaves in a food processor. Process until minced,
then add the garlic cloves and process until pureed. Add the
breadcrumbs, salt, pepper and cayenne. Pulse until the breadcrumbs
are fine and all ingredients are incorporated. Place the mixture in
a shallow bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Begin bringing 21/4 cups broth or water to a boil in a medium
saucepan.
</P>
<P>
   Using a pastry brush, coat the top of the lamb chops with the
honey-mustard. Dip each coated chop into the breadcrumb mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Place the chops crumb-side up on a foil-lined pan and broil
until browned, about 4 minutes. Remove pan from broiler, flip the
chops over and brush honey-mustard over the top and sides of the
chops. Sprinkle liberally with the crumb mixture, pressing it on to
form a crust. Return to the broiler and cook until medium rare,
about 4 minutes, depending on thickness of chops.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, add the salt, oil and cranberries to the boiling
water. Stir in the couscous, cover and cook for 1 minute. Remove
from heat and let rest 5 minutes, covered.
</P>
<P>
   Fluff the couscous with a fork, divide among serving plates and
top with the chops.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Look for these high-quality Japanese dried breadcrumbs
in the Asian food section of your supermarket, or in Japanese
grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 717 calories, &LR;   &LR; 51 g protein, 91 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 16 g fat (5 g saturated), 122 mg cholesterol, 1,186
mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; NOW &AMP; LATER: dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; WINTER VEGETABLE STEW WITH CORNBREAD COBBLER
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 red onions, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 celery stalks, cut in large dice
</P>
<P>
   6 carrots, peeled and cut in large dice
</P>
<P>
   6 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons spicy chile powder
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 (10-ounce) package large red or white pearl onions, cut in
half through root end
</P>
<P>
   10 cups vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   5 large sweet potatoes, peeled and cut into large dice
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1 head cauliflower, cut into flowerets
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   Cornbread Cobbler Topping (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a large heavy stockpot over medium-low
heat. Add the onions, celery, carrots, garlic, bay leaves, chile
powder, cumin, coriander, cinnamon, salt and pepper. Saute,
stirring often, until the mixture is juicy, about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While the vegetables are cooking, bring a small saucepan of
water to a boil and prepare a bowl of ice water.
</P>
<P>
   Place the pearl onions in the boiling water and blanch until
skins are loosened, about 1 minute. Drain. Transfer the onions to
the ice water. When cool, remove the skins and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Add the stock to the sauteed vegetables, stirring to scrape up
all the savory bits stuck to the bottom of the pan. Add the sweet
potatoes and tomato paste. Bring to a boil, reduce heat and simmer
for 10 minutes. Add the cauliflower and pearl onions. Cover and
simmer 5 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the cauliflower is
tender.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the liquid from the vegetables into a large pot.
</P>
<P>
   Stir together the water and the cornstarch until dissolved.
Bring the stew liquid back to a boil and keep it at a simmer as you
slowly add the cornstarch mixture, stirring constantly, until the
liquid thickens.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the vegetables between 2 large casserole dishes and add
the thickened vegetable liquid to cover. (Set aside any excess
liquid for another use.) Top with large dollops of the cornbread
topping.
</P>
<P>
   Bake about 30 minutes, or until the top is golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12 to 14.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 295 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g protein, 46 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 10 g fat (4 g saturated), 16 mg cholesterol, 741 mg sodium, 5 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; CORNBREAD COBBLER TOPPING
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Vegetarian Cooking for Everyone,'' by Deborah
Madison (Broadway Books, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons butter, cut into pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the flour, cornmeal, baking powder, salt and sugar in a
bowl. Work in the butter until incorporated. Mix in the milk until
just moistened.
</P>
<P>
   Drop large spoonfuls of dough on top of the stew until almost
completely covered but still lumpy on top.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
