r d BC-BOOKSAVEUR-SFCHRON &LR;      12-07 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKSAVEUR-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 COOK'S BOOKS: Saveur Goes Overboard With French Cookbook  &HT;       
 By David A. Steinberg 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; French cuisine has always had its unrepentant
boosters, and none more so than the editors at Saveur magazine. The
handsome food periodical covers the whole spectrum of the world's
cuisines.
<P>
   Even so, the editors are, in their own words, not just
Francophiles, but outright French snobs. They set out to prove just
how snobbish with their newest compendium of recipes, and they
succeed _ big time.
</P>
<P>
   As a whole, the recipes are exacting but often lacking in
technical detail. This is definitely not a book for a novice, and
in some cases not even for an intermediate cook. But if you have
the time and patience _ and pick and choose among the recipes _ the
results can be worth it.
</P>
<P>
   The  &LR; Civet de Lapin  &LR; (Rich Rabbit Stew, to us Anglophones) is
wonderfully rich and satisfying, even if it did take almost six
hours to get to the table. The timing of the cooking was wildly
miscalculated: Reducing the sauce, for example, took four times
longer than specified. The recipe has several steps requiring
several pots and an infinite amount of patience, so be warned.
</P>
<P>
   The  &LR; Poussin Vall &LR; e &LR; e d'Auge  &LR; (Baby Chicken With Calvados and
Cream) was far more successful. While it, too, was undertimed in
the recipe, when cooked until done the results were spectacular and
as a whole much simpler and straightforward, with amazing flavor _
rich, tender meat in a cream sauce punctuated by Calvados. Use the
real stuff, though; substituting an inferior brandy will impact the
taste.
</P>
<P>
   In a myriad of ways, this is more than a cookbook. It reads like
a J. Peterman catalog of French cooking. Halfway through, I was
ready to scream if I encountered one more description of the
authors meandering through the wilds of Provence only to discover
the best duck demi glace ever created, or some such thing.
</P>
<P>
   With the majority of recipes, the editors inform you that the
dish cannot even hope to reach the pinnacle of culinary ecstasy
that it represents without a specific fish or wine or cheese that
can only be found in one certain section of France. They do offer
substitutes, but the subtext seems clear: Why bother _ it won't be
nearly as good. Argh!
</P>
<P>
   What, exactly, is the point of a cookbook that teases you with
recipes you can't possibly reproduce? Like the magazine, this is a
beautifully produced book with high-quality printing and an elegant
format, but the editors seem to be thinly disguised tourism agents
more than cooks.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't mind the frustration of not being able to live for
months at a time in some small farmhouse in the French countryside
or cursing the high tariff on imported French foodstuffs, then by
all means, this is a good book to buy. I'll stick with ``Julia &AMP;
Jacques.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Saveur Cooks Authentic French,'' by the editors of Saveur &LR; 
 &LR; magazine (Chronicle Books; 320 pages, hardcover; $40).  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BABY CHICKEN WITH CALVADOS &AMP; CREAM
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 poussins or Cornish hens
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cups pearl onions
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Calvados
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Rub the poussins with butter and season inside and out,
generously, with salt and pepper. Truss poussins by folding back
the wing tips beneath the shoulders and tying the legs together
with kitchen string.
</P>
<P>
   Place the birds in a roasting pan so they do not touch. Scatter
the unpeeled pearl onions around the birds, then place the pan in
lower third of oven and cook for at least 45 minutes, until juices
run clear.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the poussins and onions to a serving platter and tent
with foil to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Place the roasting pan on top of the stove and bring the pan
drippings to a boil over medium-high heat, scraping with a wooden
spoon to loosen any browned bits stuck to the bottom of the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Warm the Calvados in a small pot, then add to the pan juices,
and carefully ignite with a kitchen match. Keep a lid nearby to
extinguish flames if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   When the flames die out, stir in the cream and continue to
reduce the sauce until thickened, about 5 minutes. Adjust
seasonings as needed. Untie the string and discard. Pour sauce over
and around the poussins.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 690 calories, &LR;   &LR; 60 g protein, 12 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 42 g fat (18 g saturated), 250 mg cholesterol, 182
mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
