<HEADLINE>
THE COUPLE THAT PLAYS TOGETHER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   In preparation for holiday parties, Details magazine tackles the
toughest issue of the season: When a couple attend a party
together, are they expected to stay with each other all night, or
is it permissible for each to talk alone with other people?
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of a party is to mingle and talk to people other
than your girlfriend,'' says  &UR; Hilda Klinkenberg  &LR; of Etiquette
International.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the partner who knows more people should introduce
the other to the known people. If a name has been forgotten, admit
it and attempt an introduction anyway. ``Everyone forgets names,''
said Klinkenberg. ``It's a temporary embarrassment that's forgotten
in two seconds. However, people remember for a long time not being
introduced.''
</P>
<P>
   Each time you pass your significant other, take two seconds to
acknowledge him or her. Nod at each other if you catch each other's
eyes across the room.
</P>
<P>
   Be close when you're eating. And if one person wants to leave
and the other decides to stay, the stayer should give the leaver
``not a peck, a smooch,'' say the experts.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Self magazine warns of the etiquette gaffe of saying ``Hi''
when one is introduced to someone else. The proper greeting is
``Hello'' or ``How do you do?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PICKING ON US &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Can't get enough of hating  &UR; Richard Nixon &LR; ? Recently released
tapes reveal new levels of bigotry _ against Jews, blacks, Mexicans
and gays, for example _ including a special slam at everyone's
favorite city. In a recent Chicago Tribune column,
 &UR; James Warren  &LR; quoted a 1971 presidential conversation with  &UR; John &LR; 
 &UR; Ehrlichman &LR; , in which both were lamenting the rise of liberalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco has just gone clear over,'' says Ehrlichman.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not just the ratty part of town,'' says the leader of
the free world. ``The upper class in San Francisco is that way. The
Bohemian Grove, which I attend from time to time. It is the most
faggy goddamned thing you could ever imagine, with that San
Francisco crowd. I can't shake hands with anybody from San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Sally Jessy Raphael &LR;  will be out with her own makeup line
soon, reports Allure magazine, which also notes _ in possibly
related news _ that on average women cry between four and eight
times a month.
</P>
<P>
   _ In its year-end roundup, California Lawyer notes that
 &UR; Bernard Lewinsky &LR; ,  &UR; Monica &LR; 's father, received a solicitation
letter from  &UR; President Clinton &LR; 's legal expense trust. He returned
it with a note: ``You must be morons to send me this letter.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Is time passing you by? Throw this log on the fire of worries:
 &UR; Jane  &LR; `` &UR; Campion  &LR; is a major filmmaker who needs to outgrow her
ideological astringency,'' writes  &UR; Owen Gleiberman  &LR; in the latest
issue of Entertainment Weekly, ``which is starting to look TRES
early '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Peter Sussman &LR;  was astounded to hear in Oklahoma Gov.  &UR; Frank &LR; 
 &UR; Keating &LR; 's official statement about this week's shooting that the
event ``must serve as a call to arms'' to address its causes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RENT-A-DUKE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; duke of York &LR; , who friends say regards a day without golf
as a day wasted, is planning to rent himself out to corporations as
a golf partner to raise money to improve the golf course at Windsor
Castle, says the Times of London.
</P>
<P>
   The duke's dream _ to make the castle's nine-hole course a full
18 _ would cost $500,000, which he's hoping to earn by
participating in ``corporate days.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GIFT GUIDE NO. 10 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For those who can't resist those nocturnal urges, Hammacher
Schlemmer offers a $59.95 lighted bocce ball set, ``with
illuminated balls that are visible up to 100 feet away.''
</P>
<P>
   Removable batteries embedded in the balls ``should provide up to
30 hours of nighttime play.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talk to guests, I usually tell them beforehand that if
I ask anything too personal they should just tell me and I'll move
on to something else. ... It gives me license to ask personal
things and gives them the power they already have, which is to not
answer. ... It's not easy to be a celebrity in the United States
today; people don't treat you like you're human. And what makes
news in the tabloids and some of the celebrity press is when the
journalist is able to reveal something humiliating about the
celebrity. So they often come to interviews with their defenses
up.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; National Public Radio's Terry Gross in Bitch magazine.
</P>
