<HEADER>
A2029 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SECRET-RIBS-SFCHRON &LR;      12-07 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-RIBS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Short Ribs Enhance Any Occasion   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  I first encountered the braised short ribs with
truffles and Madeira sauce at Campton Place, the restaurant that
launched the careers of Bradley Ogden, Jan Birnbaum, and now Todd
Humphries.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Humphries left in 1999 to become executive chef of the
floundering Wine Spectator Greystone Restaurant in St. Helena. He
also took his signature recipe with him. No matter where it goes,
it's a must-order item.
</P>
<P>
   The Madeira gives the fork-tender ribs a hint of sweetness
balanced by the earthiness of truffles. Since truffles are
expensive and not readily available to the home cook, you can leave
them out or substitute three or four finely diced shiitake
mushrooms, or a spoonful of white truffle oil at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   The rich, aromatic dish is served with creamy mashed potatoes
whipped with lots of butter and cream. If you're like me, you won't
be able to stop eating them. The entire dish is a blend of luxury
and comfort food, making it a perfect dish for stay-at-home New
Year's entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   These delicious short ribs fit nicely into the menu at this
impressive casual restaurant that's run by the Culinary Institute
of America. With an open kitchen in the middle and an expansive
loftlike feel, the restaurant in the historic stone building is a
popular stop for people visiting Napa Valley. Since it's located on
a hill, the terrace in front offers a sweeping view of the valley.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Wine Spectator Greystone Restaurant, 2555 Main St. (Highway &LR; 
 &LR; 29), St. Helena; (707) 967-1010. Open for lunch and dinner &LR; 
 &LR; daily. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _  &UR; An overnight rest. &LR;  The meat acts like a sponge and soaks up
the aromatic braising juices when allowed to sit overnight in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Reduce. Reduce. Reduce. &LR;  Reducing first the Madeira, then the
chicken stock, and finally the veal stock adds complexity and
intensity to the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Glazing the meat. &LR;  The cooking liquid is used as a glaze for
the meat, adding even more flavor to the ribs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BRAISED SHORT RIBS WITH PUREED POTATOES &AMP; MADEIRA TRUFFLE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   12 beef short ribs, bone-in
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 celery stalk, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle (750 ml) ruby port
</P>
<P>
   11/2 quarts veal stock
</P>
<P>
   Potato Puree (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Madeira Truffle Sauce (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Fresh chervil sprigs for garnishing
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large Dutch oven over medium-high heat. Season
the short ribs with salt and pepper and add to the pan. Brown on
all sides, turning as needed. This should take about 10 minutes. As
the ribs brown, remove them from the pan and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Add the onion, celery and carrot to the pan and saute over
medium-high heat until lightly brown, about 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Drain excess fat from the pan. Add the port and boil until
reduced by about three-quarters, about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Return the ribs to the pan and add veal stock to cover. If the
stock doesn't completely cover the ribs, add a little water.
</P>
<P>
   Bring to a boil. Cover and bake until the ribs are tender, about
2 to 21/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from oven, uncover, and let cool to room temperature.
Cover and refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Discard any fat that has solidified on top of the ribs. Bring
the ribs to a boil over high heat. Cover and place in the oven for
10 minutes to warm through. Transfer the ribs to a platter, tent
with foil, and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Place the Dutch oven over high heat. Bring to a boil and reduce
the juices to a glaze consistency; this should take about 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Place a mound of Potato Puree in the center of each dinner
plate. Make a well in the center of the potatoes. Place 2 short
ribs in the well. Spoon Madeira Truffle Sauce over the ribs and
garnish with chervil.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING (short ribs only): &LR;   &LR; 1,070 calories, &LR;   &LR; 88 g
protein, &LR;   &LR; 21 g carbohydrate, 53 g fat (21 g saturated), 250 mg &LR; 
 &LR; cholesterol, 178 mg sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; MADEIRA TRUFFLE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   This sauce takes a while to reduce, but it may be prepared a day
ahead and reheated just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 winter truffle, fresh or frozen, finely chopped, or 3 or 4
finely chopped fresh shiitake mushrooms, or 1 teaspoon truffle oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 cups Madeira
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 cups veal stock
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a saucepan over medium-high heat. Add the
shallot and chopped truffle or shiitake mushrooms. Season with salt
and pepper. Add the Madeira. Bring to a boil and reduce until
almost all the liquid has evaporated, about 15 to 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the chicken stock and boil until the sauce is reduced to a
syrupy consistency, about 15 to 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the veal stock and reduce by half, about 10 to 15 minutes.
(If using truffle oil instead of the truffle or mushrooms, add it
here.) Season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 185 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 14 g carbohydrate,
4 &LR;   &LR; g fat (2 g saturated), 11 mg cholesterol, 41 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; POTATO PUREE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 russet potatoes, peeled
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup heavy cream, warmed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter, cut into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground white pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Cook the potatoes in a large pot of boiling salted water until
tender, about 45 minutes. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Cut potatoes into eighths and run through a food mill. Transfer
to a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Bring the cream just to a simmer in a small saucepan. Add the
cream and the butter to the potatoes. Mix well and season with salt
and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 280 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 11 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 26 g fat (16 g saturated), 82 mg cholesterol, 143 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 1908EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
