<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Best Way'', a
column in which the Food staff tries to establish the most reliable
way to cook many of our favorite foods. 
 
 BEST WAY: Martini Time   By Sean Forsha 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Aman traveling to Martinez, Calif. in the 1860s
asked San Francisco bartender Jerry Thomas to mix him a
``pick-me-up'' _ and the martini was born.
<P>
   Since then, the drink has come to symbolize urban elegance. And
as quitting time on another year quickly approaches, the martini is
the cocktail that will escort many revelers blissfully into the
next century.
</P>
<P>
   To determine the best way to make the classic martini, the
Chronicle's Food department evaluated brands of gin, ingredient
proportions and mixing methods.
</P>
<P>
   We put 10 gins to the test _ five in the medium price range and
five more expensive ones.
</P>
<P>
   Our mid-range winner was 80-proof Gilbey's London Dry ($8.99 per
750 ml), favored for what one staffer described as a ``distinct
juniper aroma.'' The upper echelon champion was the venerable
94-proof Bombay Sapphire ($16.99 per 750 ml), with the ``cleanest
flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Next we used the Bombay Sapphire to mix with Martini and Rossi
dry vermouth in five combinations, ranging from six parts gin and
one part vermouth up to 15 parts gin and one part vermouth. We also
used straight gin as the control.
</P>
<P>
   The ratio of 12 parts gin to one part vermouth _ 3 ounces of gin
to 1/4 ounce of dry vermouth _ was the clear winner, providing a
pleasant balance of flavors. The six-to-one ratio had what one
staffer described as a ``biting'' flavor, while the 15-to-1
combination did not provide the traditional martini taste.
</P>
<P>
   We next tested whether the blending method affects the drink.
</P>
<P>
   Shaking is said to ``bruise'' the gin which, for better or
worse, can bring different flavors and aromas into the cocktail.
The agitation of shaking dilutes the drink but at the same time
creates ice crystals which keeps the drink colder overall.
</P>
<P>
   Stirring the martini, which keeps the alcohol intact by
discouraging dilution, supposedly doesn't blend the flavors as well
as shaking.
</P>
<P>
   The test revealed very subtle differences between the two
methods. The chill of the shaken version made the cocktail more
drinkable. But in general, the flavors of both versions were much
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Our final test was to determine how the more moderately priced
Gilbey's gin, shaken in the preferred 12-to-1 ratio, would measure
up to the Bombay Sapphire. The more expensive gin won _ tasters
preferred the Bombay Sapphire martini, saying it was smoother and
more drinkable. But the Gilbey's produced a martini strong on
classic gin flavors and aromas. Ultimately, they were two different
cocktails, good for different drinkers. Such is the nature of the
martini _ it's a matter of personal preference.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE BEST WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   We found the best martini was made with 12 parts gin to one part
vermouth (3 ounces to 1/4 ounce), shaken or stirred _ depending on
whether you like the drink colder and slightly less alcoholic.
Using the higher priced Bombay Sapphire makes a smoother drink, but
the Gilbey's produces a classic cocktail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
