 TASTER'S CHOICE: Top Products Can Help Harried Host   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Looking for shortcuts for holiday entertaining?
Several products sampled by The Chronicle's Taster's Choice panel
over the last 18 months will save time and still please your
guests. The following scored best in their categories.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a small dinner party, try serving the  &UR; crab cakes &LR;  from
Mollie Stone's ($3.69 each at Mollie Stone's) as a starter.
Accompany with lemon wedges and a dollop of storebought aioli.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Riviera dei Fiori green olive tapenade &LR;  (61/2 ounces, $3.39 at
Draeger's) works well for a cocktail buffet or as a passed
appetizer. Put the pungent olive mixture in a pretty bowl
surrounded by toasted baguette slices. Or, spread the mixture on
crostini and top it with mild crumbled feta cheese, then arrange
the crostini on a platter.
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Asian peanut sauce from House of Tsang &LR;  (111/2 ounces,
$3.79-$3.99 at many supermarkets) can also be a time-saver. Put a
bowl of the lemongrass-scented sauce on a buffet table surrounded
by cubes of grilled chicken breast for dipping. Or, use the sauce
to dress a Chinese chicken salad of iceberg lettuce, grilled
chicken strips and crisp-fried chow mein noodles. The sauce also
works well on a hot or cold salad of Asian noodles, chicken,
blanched snow peas and cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Dessert can be the most time-consuming of all, but you can
simplify by serving ice cream sundaes.  &UR; Haagen Dazs vanilla ice &LR; 
 &UR; cream &LR;  (1 quart, $5.19-$5.69 at many supermarkets) topped our
vanilla ice cream tasting. Drizzle it with  &UR; Susan Elaine's &LR; 
 &UR; Incredibly Rich Fudge Sauce &LR;  (93/4 ounces, $5.49 at Andronico's),
which scored first in the fudge sauce sampling. Baked cookies made
from  &UR; Tom's refrigerated prepared cookie dough &LR;  (1 pound,
$4.99-$5.25 at some supermarkets), which comes preformed into
rounds, pairs well with the ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   And since no holiday party can be complete without a cheery
glass of eggnog, try serving the panel's favorite brand:  &UR; Berkeley &LR; 
 &UR; Farms &LR;  (1 quart, $1.99-$2.99 at many supermarkets).
</P>
</TEXT>
