 CHRON  
 Shake, Rattle and Stir Those Holiday Party Drinks  &HT;       
 By Tilde Herrera 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  Cocktails will be flowing just as swiftly as
Champagne this holiday season, so it helps to have a few
ready-to-go recipes on hand to make the mixing easier.
<P>
   We have compiled a selection of special mixed drinks, including
a nonalcoholic specialty, that will add zest to any holiday
celebration. Some drinks are twists on standards, while others
create a new taste using old reliables.
</P>
<P>
   But first, a few tips to make your bartending successful.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Get creative, but not too creative.  &LR; A little of this and a
little of that sometimes produces a fine drink but more often than
not forces you to dump the mixture straight down the kitchen sink.
Often, a simple variation on a classic, time-honored cocktail is
all you need to create a fresh, exciting drink.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Plan proper amounts.  &LR; Choose a small number of cocktails but
keep essentials (beer, soda, bottled water, etc.) on hand. A good
rule of thumb when planning how much alcohol to buy is to figure
two to three drinks for each guest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Set up ahead.  &LR; Organize and chill ingredients. Keep lots of
ice on hand.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Remember the small touches.  &LR; Shake drinks thoroughly and use
proper glassware _ it will make you look like a pro.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Above all, be responsible.  &LR; Too many fruit and alcohol
combinations are not a good idea. These drinks have a large amount
of alcohol in them, so serve them in moderation only. Be wary of
guests who have more than one or two drinks per hour.
</P>
<P>
   To moderate the effects of alcohol, serve bread-based hors
d'oeuvres such as crostini, breadsticks or chunks of sourdough
served with a spinach dip.
</P>
<P>
   Holidays are meant to be festive. With creative yet sensible
planning, you will have a fabulous, safe soiree.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BROWN RUSSIAN
</P>
<P>
   This variation of the classic White Russian uses chocolate milk
instead of cream. The result is a cozy, mocha-flavored drink
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce vodka
</P>
<P>
   11/2 ounces Kahlua
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces chocolate milk
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Fill a collins glass or other tall 12 ounce glass with ice. Pour
in the vodka and Kahlua, then add the chocolate milk. Amount of
chocolate milk may be adjusted according to taste.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Alternate serving suggestion:  &LR; Cold coffee may be substituted
for the chocolate milk. Simply pour freshly brewed hot coffee into
a cocktail shaker full of ice, shake, then strain into a collins
glass with the vodka/Kahlua mixture. If you like your coffee sweet,
dissolve sugar to taste in the coffee before you shake it with ice.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 1.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 330 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 35 g carbohydrate,
4 &LR;   &LR; g fat (2 g saturated), 14 mg cholesterol, 68 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; HAWAIIAN SIZZLE
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Hawaiian inspired the flavor combination, but adding
Champagne or sparkling wine gives an unexpected punch.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 ounce blue curacao
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce coconut-flavored rum, such as Malibu or Parrot Bay
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces pineapple juice
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces Champagne or sparkling wine
</P>
<P>
   Small wedge fresh pineapple for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the curacao, rum, pineapple juice and Champagne in an
oversize 10-ounce Champagne flute.
</P>
<P>
   Make a small cut in the pineapple wedge and slip it onto the rim
of the glass.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 1.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 230 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 14 g carbohydrate, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fat, 0 cholesterol, 8 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; GINBERRY FIZZ
</P>
<P>
   Don't mistake this for the classic Ramos Gin Fizz. Here the
sugar, gin and lemon wedge are muddled, similar to an
Old-Fashioned. But there is nothing old-fashioned about the
refreshing flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   11/2 ounces gin
</P>
<P>
   1 small lemon wedge
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces club soda
</P>
<P>
   Splash of cranberry juice
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the sugar and gin in an 8- to 10-ounce rocks or
old-fashioned glass. Squeeze the lemon wedge into the glass and
drop it in. Muddle with a spoon until the sugar has dissolved and
the lemon is nicely pulverized, about 1 minute. Fill with ice, then
pour in soda followed by a splash of cranberry juice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Serving suggestion:  &LR; Other juices may be substituted for the
cranberry, such as grapefruit, lime or lemonade.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 1.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 131 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 6 g carbohydrate, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fat, 0 cholesterol, 25 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; THE GRASS SKIRT
</P>
<P>
   This is a smooth, delicate sweet-tart cocktail, sure to seduce
even those who don't like ``sweet'' drinks. But beware _ it's
potent.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; 1/2 ounce amaretto
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; 1/2 ounce Chambord
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; 1/2 ounces spiced rum, such as Captain Morgan
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; 3 ounces pineapple juice
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in an ice-filled cocktail shaker. Shake,
then strain into a chilled, over-size 6-ounce martini glass. Or,
pour into an ice-filled rocks or old-fashioned glass.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 1.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 135 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 18 g carbohydrate, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fat, 0 cholesterol, 2 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; PINK ORANGEADE
</P>
<P>
   This nonalcoholic drink is perfect for sipping.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces lemonade
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces orange juice
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces soda
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle of grenadine
</P>
<P>
   Maraschino cherry for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Thin slice of lemon for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the juices and soda in an ice-filled 14-ounce collins or
other tall glass. Drizzle in grenadine and garnish with a
maraschino cherry.
</P>
<P>
   Make a small slit in the lemon slice and fit onto the rim of the
glass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Serving suggestion:  &LR; Vodka flavored with lemon or orange, such
as Absolut's Citron or Mandarin, may be added to turn this
``mocktail'' into a refreshing cocktail.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 1.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 80 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 20 g carbohydrate,
0 &LR;   &LR; fat, 0 cholesterol, 14 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
