<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2038 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-CHAMPAGNE-SFCHRON &LR;      12-07 4142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAMPAGNE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM ENTERTAINING ISSUE  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   Bring on the Bubbles: Two sparkling menus guarantee a stylish 
 start to the New Year  
   
 By Janet Fletcher 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; If you're among the many who will fete the
millennium by staying safely at home, you're probably planning a
minor splurge for dinner. Or maybe a major splurge. Chances are
you'll open a fine wine or two and pop a Champagne cork at
midnight.
<P>
   But given how rarely a new millennium rolls around, you might
want to consider an unconventional alternative: serving sparkling
wine from start to finish around a menu specifically designed for
it. Bubblies are made in so many styles, from bone-dry Ultra Brut
to gently sweet Extra Dry, so an all-sparkling wine evening can
provide a variety of tastes as well as a guaranteed good time.
</P>
<P>
   To do it right, we turned to two San Francisco chef-sommelier
duos who would know just how to orchestrate such an evening. We
asked chef Gary Danko of Gary Danko restaurant and chef George
Morrone of Fifth Floor to design three-course menus to go with
sparkling wines selected by their respective sommeliers,
Renee-Nicole Kubin and Rajat Parr.
</P>
<P>
   Morrone's menu includes a first course, main course and dessert.
Danko's opens with an appetizer, followed by soup and a main
course. To conclude the meal, he suggests a salad of winter greens
with blue cheese, walnuts and pears.
</P>
<P>
   The menu and sparkling wine choices follow (including a standard
retail price), along with the sommeliers' comments. We also asked
these two wine professionals to describe the various sparkling wine
styles and suggest some food affinities, and to give a quick primer
on opening and serving bubbly. Kubin's first rule: ``Do it more
often.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
George Morrone's Millennium Menu
</P>
<P>
   Wines selected by sommelier Rajat Parr
</P>
<P>
   _ Lobster Carpaccio With Blood Orange and Fennel Salad
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 1993 Roederer Estate L'Ermitage &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Roast Pheasant With Sugar Pumpkin and Pimiento Essence
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 1990 Charles Heidsieck Brut &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Chilled Pineapple Soup With Pomegranate Sorbet
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Non-Vintage Veuve Clicquot Demi-Sec &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Gary Danko's Millennium Menu
</P>
<P>
   Wines selected by sommelier Renee-Nicole Kubin
</P>
<P>
   _ Buckwheat Blini With Caviar or Smoked Salmon
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Laurent-Perrier Cuvee Ultra Brut  &LR; or &LR;  1993 Louis Roederer &LR; 
 &LR; Cristal &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Truffled Winter Vegetable Soup
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 1993 Roederer Estate L'Ermitage  &LR; or &LR;  1990 Bollinger Grande &LR; 
 &LR; Annee &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Roast Loin of Veal With Chanterelles
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Vilmart Cuvee Rubis Rose  &LR; or &LR;  1991 Taittinger Comtes de &LR; 
 &LR; Champagne Rose &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GEORGE MORRONE'S MILLENNIUM MENU
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Lobster Carpaccio With Blood Orange and Fennel Salad; 1993 &LR; 
 &UR; Roederer Estate L'Ermitage  &LR; ($30).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the finest example of sparkling wine outside of
Champagne and definitely the best sparkling wine from California,''
Parr says. ``It has citrusy flavors, an orange zest nose and
amazing complexity. It's very fresh, very creamy. You don't want
sparkling wine to be too austere and lean.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Roast Pheasant With Sugar Pumpkin and Pimiento Essence; 1990 &LR; 
 &UR; Charles Heidsieck Brut  &LR; ($47).
</P>
<P>
   Parr says 1990 is the best vintage since 1959. ``The '90s have
amazing acidity but are very powerful, very rich. The Charles
Heidsieck in particular is nutty, smoky, almost like caramelized
pear. It is not an oyster Champagne, not a shellfish wine. You
definitely need meat to go with it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Chilled Pineapple Soup With Pomegranate Sorbet; Non-Vintage &LR; 
 &UR; Veuve Clicquot Demi-Sec  &LR; ($32).
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way you can have dessert with Champagne is to have it
with sweet Champagne,'' Parr says. ``This one is not cloyingly
sweet. It's almost like Moscato d'Asti in sweetness; it has orange
blossom and quince flavors. It's pretty rich, but with fresh
acidity, and it's very fragrant. There are tropical aromas in the
wine and the pineapple soup.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a sorbet, sparkling wine is always a good choice because
it's cold. If you have a cold dessert and a room-temperature wine,
your palate is going to be shocked. Here you have cold wine and a
cold dessert.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; GARY DANKO'S MILLENNIUM MENU
</P>
<P>
   Sommelier Renee-Nicole Kubin offered two sparkling wine choices
for each course, the first more moderate in price.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Buckwheat Blini With Caviar or Smoked Salmon;
Laurent-Perrier &LR; 
 &UR; Cuvee Ultra Brut  &LR; ($53) or &UR; 1993 Louis Roederer Cristal  &LR; ($135).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to balance a meal as a chef, and it's equally
important to do so as a sommelier,'' Kubin says. ``The first wine
should be almost aperitiflike in style _ crisp and dry with no
 &LR; dosage &LR;  (no added sugar), but something that has a creamy texture.
The Laurent-Perrier Ultra Brut has no  &LR; dosage &LR;  and is the only
ultra-brut widely available in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people talk about the best wines of the world, without
question someone will throw in either Cristal or Dom Perignon or
Krug. These are absolutely stunning wines, but they are expensive.
I wouldn't pair them with food for any reason, because price
usually is an object. But they are truly a millennium treat.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Truffled Winter Vegetable Soup; 1993 Roederer Estate &LR; 
 &UR; L'Ermitage  &LR; ($30) or  &UR; 1990 Bollinger Grande Annee  &LR; ($60).
</P>
<P>
   ``On several occasions I've tried wines that basically overwhelm
that exotic (truffle) flavor, and that's a shame because the
truffle is the point,'' Kubin says. ``To make that flavor linger,
you need a toasty, yeasty quality that's usually only found in true
Champagne (from France), although Roederer L'Ermitage is a heck of
a wine. It's my favorite producer in California, hands down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bollinger 1990 is not too easy to find. Along with Krug,
it's one of two producers that actually use (barrel fermentation).
That gives great complexity and depth and richness.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Roast Loin of Veal With Chanterelles; Vilmart Cuvee Rubis
Rose &LR;  ($42) &UR;  &LR; or  &UR; 1991 Taittinger Comtes de Champagne Rose  &LR; ($168).
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, people still think that rose is going to be
sweet. Or they say, `I don't want anything fruity.' I like for
people to think of rose as a red wine that has a bit of sparkle.
It's Pinot Noir,'' Kubin points out. ``The veal with chanterelles
is an elegant dish rather than meaty and powerful, so a rose works
beautifully. It's a very pretty match. One doesn't dominate the
other. The rose just brings out more flavor in the veal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vilmart is so wonderful. It's a family-run house and the
production is very small. It's been discovered here over the last
one to two years. It's quite deep in color, more than most ros &LR; e &LR; s.
That comes from leaving the fermenting wine on the grape skins,
versus adding color back (by adding red wine). At this price level,
few ros &LR; e &LR; s are made with such care.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Best Way to Open the Bubbly &QL;  &LR; 
Many eyes have been lost to sparkling wine corks, according to
Kubin's optometrist father. Sparkling wine should always be opened
with attention and care.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Kubin's method:
</P>
<P>
   _ Use a knife to remove the top part of the foil by cutting
around the lower lip of the bottle. Leave the remaining foil on the
bottle for appearance.
</P>
<P>
   _ The cork will be covered with a wire cage. Do not remove the
cage until the cork is out of the bottle. Instead, with one thumb
firmly over the cork, untwist the cage wire with your other hand.
Then, still with your thumb over the cork and cage, angle the
bottle away from everyone and very slowly twist the bottle, not the
cork.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you feel the cork releasing, tilt the cork to release the
pressure slowly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't aim for the loud pop that people associate with
Champagne drinking. It's not only dangerous; it's bad for the wine.
A properly extracted cork releases a sigh, not a shout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; There's a Style and Type of Bubbly for Every Dish &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In general, when serving sparkling wines, follow the same
principles for matching still wines with food: Serve light, fresh
sparkling wines with lighter food, richer sparkling wines with
richer food. Work from lighter to heavier during the course of the
meal. Pour nonvintage wines before vintage wines.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a description of the various sparkling wine types:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Blanc de blancs &LR; : Made entirely from Chardonnay, blanc de
blancs are the cleanest, freshest-tasting, most austere of
sparkling wines.
</P>
<P>
   When young, they are a good aperitif; serve them with hors
d'oeuvres or smoked fish.
</P>
<P>
   As they age, they become more ``biscuity and briochelike,'' Parr
says. Pair older ones with a fish course or pate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Blanc de noirs &LR; : Made mostly or entirely from red grapes,
usually Pinot Noir blended with Pinot Meunier. These are typically
richer, bigger and more powerful than blanc de blancs.
</P>
<P>
   When young, they can accompany a fish course, including salmon
or tuna. When aged, serve them with poultry.
</P>
<P>
   The Champagne houses of Bollinger and Krug make the most
powerful blancs de noirs; older vintages can stand up to fillet of
beef.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Brut &LR; : Champagne or sparkling wine made in a dry style, as
the vast majority are. An all-purpose sparkling wine likely to go
with many things, and usually made from a blend of white and red
grapes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Ultra Brut/Extra Brut/Brut Sauvage/Brut Zero &LR; : These are all
names for sparkling wines that have no dosage, meaning no sugar
added when the wine is disgorged.
</P>
<P>
   They are bone dry, appealing before dinner or early in the meal
with raw oysters, shellfish, caviar or crudites.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Rose &LR; : When made by high-end producers in France and
California, these are the richest, most powerful and most
sought-after of sparkling wines.
</P>
<P>
   They are dry, never sweet. Their color comes either from
steeping the juice with the grape skins briefly during
fermentation, or from the addition of red wine at a later stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not a sissy thing,'' says Kubin, who likes them with
substantial dishes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Extra Dry &LR; : Few producers still make this style which,
paradoxically, is not dry but slightly sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Serve this style with ham, pork, smoked turkey or chicken,
especially if there's a fruity accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   Kubin suggests it for holiday meals with sweet components, such
as sweet potatoes or cranberries.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Demi-Sec &LR; : Sweeter than Extra Dry. ``Absolutely charming and
festive,'' says Kubin, who pours it with fruit tarts, apple
strudel, fruit sorbets and panna cotta.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Doux &LR; : Sweeter than Demi-Sec; serve with custard desserts,
such as creme caramel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Tips on Serving Sparklers &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are answers to frequently asked questions about serving
sparkling wine.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's the best serving temperature?
</P>
<P>
   Cold but not icy. Chill the sparkling wine for several hours in
the refrigerator and keep it in a bucket of ice water (not just
ice) between servings. Serve vintage sparkling wines slightly
warmer to savor their nuances.
</P>
<P>
   _ How high do you fill the glass?
</P>
<P>
   To keep sparkling wine cold, fill the glass only halfway or a
little more, say Parr and Kubin. You can top it offup often; it
doesn't mean you're drinking more.
</P>
<P>
   _ What about leftovers?
</P>
<P>
   Use a sparkling wine bottle stopper to recork the bottle and
refrigerate. It should stay fresh and bubbly for a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   _ How long can you keep an unopened bottle in the refrigerator?
</P>
<P>
   For months if it's on its side; for no more than two weeks if
it's standing in the refrigerator door.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; GARY DANKO'S BUCKWHEAT BLINI
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Top hot blini with a dab of creme fraiche and either caviar
or smoked salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buckwheat flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   13/4 cups milk, warmed to body temperature (98)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Clarified butter or vegetable oil as needed
</P>
<P>
   Garnishes
</P>
<P>
   Creme fraiche
</P>
<P>
   Caviar or smoked salmon
</P>
<P>
   Fresh chives or chervil sprigs
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Stir together 1/2 cup of the buckwheat flour, 1/2 cup of the
all-purpose flour, the sugar and yeast. Whisk in 1 cup of the warm
milk. Cover with plastic wrap and let rest in a warm area for 1
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in another bowl, stir together the remaining 1/2 cup
buckwheat flour, 1/2 cup all-purpose flour and the salt.
</P>
<P>
   Using a blender, combine the eggs yolks with the remaining 3/4
cup milk until foamy, then whisk into the dry ingredients. Cover
with plastic wrap and let rest for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Combine both batters.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the egg whites to soft peaks, then gently fold into the
batter.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the cream into the egg-white bowl and beat until soft peaks
form, then gently fold into the batter. Let rest for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the clarified butter or vegetable oil in a nonstick skillet
over moderate heat. When hot, drop the batter by the tablespoonful
into the skillet. Fry until golden brown on both sides, turning
once. Transfer to paper towels to drain briefly, then to warm
plates.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: Top each tiny pancake with a dab of creme fraiche and
either a spoonful of caviar or a slice of smoked salmon. Garnish
with chopped chives or a delicate sprig of fresh chervil.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 40 blini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER BLINI: &LR;   &LR; 35 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 5 g carbohydrate, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fat (1 g saturated), 14 mg cholesterol, 63 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TRUFFLED WINTER VEGETABLE SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 leek (white part only), thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound celery root, peeled and cut in 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 parsnip, peeled and cut in 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound large red potatoes, peeled and cut in 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 sprig fresh thyme, or 1/8 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   4 cups vegetable stock, chicken stock or water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 ounce fresh black truffle, finely chopped, or finely chopped
canned truffle to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a medium saucepan over medium heat. Add the
leek, celery root, parsnip and potatoes. Stir, cover and cook
gently for 15 minutes. Add the thyme and bay leaf; cover and cook
for 10 minutes. Add the stock and bring to a boil. Reduce heat and
simmer until the liquid is reduced by half.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the truffle and 1/2 cup water in a blender; puree. Add
to the soup along with the heavy cream. Season with salt and
pepper. Slowly return to a boil. Remove the thyme sprig and bay
leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Puree the soup, then reheat gently to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 190 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 19 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 12 g fat (7 g saturated), 38 mg cholesterol, 113 mg sodium, 2 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ROAST LOIN OF VEAL WITH CHANTERELLES
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 boneless loin of veal, about 2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup breadcrumbs
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped pistachio nuts
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/2 garlic clove, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   The Mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 pound chanterelle mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   The Sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 cups veal stock
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Trim off all fat and silver skin from the meat, then tie into a
roast with butcher's twine (or have your butcher do this).
</P>
<P>
   Combine the breadcrumbs, pistachios, parsley and garlic. Brush
the meat with mustard, then coat with the breadcrumb mixture. Place
on a plate, cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate until needed.
</P>
<P>
   Clean the chanterelles well and slice them. Melt 1 tablespoon of
the butter in a nonstick pan over moderately high heat. Add the
mushrooms and saute until they render juices. Drain in a sieve and
reserve juices. Return the mushrooms to the pan, add the remaining
1 tablespoon butter, the parsley and garlic. Season with salt and
pepper and saute briefly to incorporate seasonings. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Bring the veal to room temperature. Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Place the veal on a rack in a roasting pan. Roast until a meat
thermometer registers 125 degrees when inserted in the thickest
part of the roast, about 60 minutes. Let rest in a warm place for
10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While the meat rests, reheat the mushrooms and make the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the mushroom juices to a pan and reduce to a near-glaze
over high heat. Add the veal stock and reduce to 1/2 cup. Remove
from heat and whisk in the butter. Season with salt. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly season the roast with salt. Slice thinly and arrange on
warm plates (remove the butcher's twine); add the chanterelles,
then spoon the sauce over the veal.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 310 calories, &LR;   &LR; 38 g protein, 10 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 14 g fat (6 g saturated), 139 mg cholesterol, 262
mg sodium, 2 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LOBSTER CARPACCIO WITH BLOOD ORANGE &AMP; FENNEL SALAD
</P>
<P>
   If blood oranges are not in season, substitute Satsumas.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 live lobsters, about 2 pounds each
</P>
<P>
   1 small fennel bulb
</P>
<P>
   2 blood oranges
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon capers, minced
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   8 slices brioche or egg bread, toasted, each cut in half on the
diagonal
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To cook the lobsters:  &LR; Bring a large pot of salted water to a
boil. Plunge the lobsters into the pot and cook 4 minutes. Remove
lobsters and immediately place in ice water to stop the cooking.
When the lobsters are cold, drain and pat dry.
</P>
<P>
   Separate the tail from the body. Using a sharp knife, cut the
tail in half lengthwise. Remove the meat. Crack the lobster claws
and extract the meat, being careful to keep the claw meat intact.
Crack the knuckle and extract the meat, discarding the shell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the salad:  &LR; Place the lobster claw and knuckle meat in
a bowl. Using a mandoline or a very sharp knife, shave the fennel
crosswise into very thin slices and add to the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the zest from the lemon and mince it. Cut the zest from 1 of
the oranges and mince it. Remove any remaining skin and pith from
this orange and separate the segments from the membrane. Add the
segments to the bowl. Squeeze the juice from the remaining orange
into the bowl as well. Add the juice of the lemon and 1 tablespoon
of the olive oil. Season with salt and pepper and mix gently.
</P>
<P>
   Place 1 lobster tail half between 2 sheets of plastic wrap.
Using a meat mallet or a rolling pin, gently pound the meat until
it is paper thin. Be very careful not to puncture the plastic wrap.
When the tail is evenly pounded, use a plastic spatula or pastry
scraper to shape the ``carpaccio'' into a circle. Cut away excess
plastic. Repeat with the remaining lobster tail halves.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully remove the top sheets of plastic wrap. Invert each
carpaccio onto a chilled plate. Remove remaining plastic wrap.
Brush the carpaccio liberally with olive oil. Season with salt and
pepper. Sprinkle with parsley, capers, garlic, lemon zest and
orange zest.
</P>
<P>
   Add any remaining olive oil to the salad. Pile salad in the
center of each lobster carpaccio, making sure each portion gets 1
claw and 1 piece of knuckle meat. Garnish each plate with toasted
brioche triangles.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 395 calories, &LR;   &LR; 20 g protein, 33 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 21 g fat (3 g saturated), 128 mg cholesterol, 481
mg sodium, 3 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ROAST PHEASANT WITH SUGAR PUMPKIN &AMP; PIMIENTO ESSENCE
</P>
<P>
   The pheasant stock, roasted pumpkins and pimiento essence may be
made one day in advance. Cool everything completely, then
refrigerate in air-tight containers until ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 fresh pheasants, about 3 pounds each
</P>
<P>
   4 large carrots, peeled and roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 celery ribs, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 large yellow onions, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 head garlic, broken into cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup grapeseed oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 small sugar pumpkins, about 1/2 pound each
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   6 fresh pimiento peppers or small red bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons white truffle oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cooked dried beans, preferably cranberry beans
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped mixed herbs (parsley, thyme and tarragon)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   For each pheasant, cut off the legs where the thigh meets the
body. Cut out the backbone, leaving the whole breast still on the
bone.
</P>
<P>
   Put the backbones in a roasting pan with half of the carrots,
celery, onions and garlic. Drizzle with one third of the grapeseed
oil. Place in the oven and roast about 35 minutes, stirring
occasionally, until the bones and vegetables are well browned.
Drain off any fat in the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce oven temperature to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the bones and vegetables to a stock pot, cover with
cold water and bring to a boil. Skim off any foam, reduce heat to
low and simmer gently for 2 hours. Strain. Reserve broth.
</P>
<P>
   While the bones and vegetables are simmering, place the
remaining carrots, celery, onions and garlic in a roasting pan.
Season the pheasant legs with salt and pepper and place on the
vegetables. Roast until the meat juices run clear, about 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While the legs roast, prepare the sugar pumpkins. Cut off the
top third of each pumpkin and reserve. Scoop out the seeds with a
spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle a little olive oil inside each pumpkin, using 1
tablespoon total for all 4 pumpkins. Season with salt and pepper,
and replace the pumpkin lids. Roast in a 350 degrees oven for 45
minutes, or until the pumpkins are just tender. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle the pimiento peppers with the remaining 1 tablespoon
olive oil and season with salt and pepper. Roast in a 350 oven for
25 minutes, turning frequently until the skin blisters. Transfer to
a bowl, cover with plastic wrap and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the peppers and remove stem and seeds. Set 1 pepper aside
for garnish. Put the remaining peppers and their juices in a small
saucepan with 1 cup of the pheasant broth. Bring to a boil, then
puree in a blender until smooth. Season with salt, pepper, lime
juice and coriander. Strain and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   When the pheasant legs are cool enough to handle, remove the
meat in bite-size pieces and place in a bowl. Discard bones.
</P>
<P>
   Rub the pheasant breasts with the truffle oil. Season liberally
with salt and pepper. Heat the remaining grapeseed oil in a large
skillet until almost smoking. One at a time, sear the breasts
skin-side down until golden brown. Transfer to a roasting pan and
roast in a 350 degrees oven for 20 to 25 minutes. Remove from oven,
lightly season with salt and pepper. Cover with foil and let rest
for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Dice the reserved pimiento pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Place the cooked beans in a saucepan; add the pheasant leg meat
and 1 cup pheasant broth. Bring to a simmer and cook 3 minutes. Add
the butter, the diced pimiento and the herbs. Season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the pheasant breasts off the bone by running a sharp knife
along the breast bone separating the 2 halves. Leave the wing bone
intact. Slice each half-breast into 3 pieces.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Assembly:  &LR; Spoon a pool of pimiento puree in the center of each
warmed dinner plate. Place a sugar pumpkin in the center. Fill the
pumpkin with the cranberry bean ragout and top the pumpkins with
their lids. Arrange a sliced half-breast of pheasant on each plate.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 890 calories, &LR;   &LR; 75 g protein, 27 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 54 g fat (12 g saturated), 228 mg cholesterol, 148
mg sodium, 7 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; CHILLED PINEAPPLE SOUP WITH POMEGRANATE SORBET
</P>
<P>
   Do not use bottled pomegranate juice for this recipe. The best
way to juice fresh pomegranates is with a professional citrus
juicer.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Soup
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh pineapple juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   1 whole clove
</P>
<P>
   1 juniper berry
</P>
<P>
   The Sorbet
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh pomegranate juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   The Fruit
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup diced pineapple
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup diced fresh fruit, such as strawberries or mango
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the soup:  &LR; Place all ingredients in a nonaluminum pot.
Bring to a boil. Remove from heat, let cool. Refrigerate for at
least 12 hours. Strain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the sorbet:  &LR; Combine the sugar and water in a saucepan
and bring to a boil, stirring to dissolve the sugar. Remove from
heat. Add pomegranate juice and corn syrup; stir well. Refrigerate
until chilled, then freeze in an ice cream maker according to
manufacturer's directions.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, spoon diced fruit into the center of serving bowls.
Top with a scoop of sorbet. Spoon the pineapple soup around the
fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 180 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 46 g carbohydrate,
0 &LR;   &LR; fat, 0 cholesterol, 7 mg sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
