<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-CAHOON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTHA CAHOON, 94; WAS RENOWNED PRIMITIVE ARTIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Martha Farham Cahoon, a primitive painter whose home is
now a museum of Americana in Barnstable, died Sunday in Cape Cod
Hospital in Hyannis. She was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cahoon was born in Boston. She was the wife of the late
Ralph Cahoon, who was also a primitive painter of national repute.
Their work consists predominatly of whimsical paintings on wood
with themes that often involved mermaids and hot air balloons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 17, I went to work for my father who was a
furniture painter in Harwich,'' Mrs. Cahoon said in a story
published in the Globe on April 2, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   After learning how to paint furniture, she taught her friend
Ralph the art of decoration, and after their marriage in 1932, the
couple were furniture decorators.
</P>
<P>
   One of their clients was Joan Whitney Payson, the future owner
of the New York Mets, who at that time had an antiques shop on New
York's Long Island. Admiring the Cahoons' work, she suggested one
day in the 1950s: ``Why don't you put frames around this stuff?''
</P>
<P>
   The couple did and soon their framed pictures were being bought
by the likes of Paul Mellon, Felix duPont, Joan Fontaine, and
Jacqueline Onassis, when she was married to President John F.
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   After her husband's death in 1982, Mrs. Cahoon retired from
painting and turned her attention to crayon sketches.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, the Cahoon Museum of American Art opened in the
couple's former home and studio.
</P>
<P>
   She leaves a son, Franz of Cotuit; a sister, Osa Goldsmith of
Harwich; a brother, Eric Farham of Harwich; a grandson; and a
great-granddaughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
