<SLUG> BC-SCYTHIANS-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOLDEN LEGACY OF SCYTHIAN WARRIORS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RITA REIF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ In the fifth century B.C., the Greek historian
Herodotus met the Scythians on the northern coast of the Black Sea
and was so impressed by their customs and their splendid gold
artifacts that he wrote vividly about them in ``History.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today, that account provides historians with a broad sketch
of the lifestyle of these nomad warriors, the spiritual ancestors
of the Cossacks who moved swiftly _ and with bells on _ through
history. They migrated in the eighth century B.C. from Central Asia
to Assyria and then to the rich grasslands north of the Black Sea,
now called Ukraine, before disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the Scythians, how they lived, died and were buried
with the things they coveted _ gold, jewels, armor and pottery _ is
told in ``Gold of the Nomads: Scythian Treasures From Ancient
Ukraine,'' an exhibition of 171 objects here at the San Antonio
Museum of Art, through Jan. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The show was organized by the museum and the Walters Art Gallery
in Baltimore, where it moves in March. It travels then to the Los
Angeles County Museum of Art, the Brooklyn Museum of Art, the Royal
Ontario Museum in Toronto, the Nelson Atkins Museum of Art in
Kansas City, Mo., and the Grand Palais in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Herodotus wrote in greatest detail about the funeral rites of a
Scythian king who was embalmed and whose body was then taken by
wagon on a 40-day procession seen by all the people under Scythian
rule. The king was buried on a straw mattress, flanked by spears,
and under a canopy of beams covered with reed thatching. Buried
with him were a concubine, members of his household and
possessions, especially his gold artifacts. The grave was marked by
a monumental mound of earth.
</P>
<P>
   What mystifies some historians today is Herodotus' geographical
description of the royal cemetery's location, which he wrote was at
Gerrhus, ``in the land of the Gerrhi,'' a site that has never been
found. Archaeologists began to unearth Scythian gold objects in
Ukraine and elsewhere 250 years ago. The objects were dated, but
the original owners were not identified, and the pieces were sent
to the Hermitage Gold Collection in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Since excavations began again in the late 1970s, scores of the
thousand-plus tombs in Ukraine have been opened and studied, and
their contents have remained in Kiev, either at the Institute of
Archaeology or the Museum of Historical Treasures of Ukraine, the
museums that lent most of the works in this show.
</P>
<P>
   In organizing the exhibition, Gerry Scott III, curator of
Ancient Art at San Antonio, worked with Ellen D. Reeder, curator of
Ancient Art at the Walters. Ms. Reeder, the show's curator and the
editor of its catalogue with Harry N. Abrams ($60, hard cover; $39,
paper), will become the deputy director for art at the Brooklyn
Museum next month.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts agree that recent excavations and modern
scholarship have answered some questions about the art of the
Scythians. The information available goes well beyond what was
known in 1975, when Scythian gold was last seen in a museum
exhibition in this country in ``From the Land of the Scythians:
Ancient Treasures From the Museums of the U.S.S.R.,'' at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   The excavated gold serves as the best guide to the Scythian
customs and their travels. Armor and swords were found buried with
both men and women, who were also warriors, in some of the earliest
tombs from the seventh and sixth centuries B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Other early possessions also reveal the tribal culture that the
Scythians brought with them to Europe. That expressed the animal
style in imagery of the cycle of life and transformation: birds
emerging from the antlers of a deer, a recumbent stag looking
vulnerable or ready to spring from earth to sky and, on a
cone-shaped finial, a fallen deer heroically resisting a spotted
leopard.
</P>
<P>
   Scythian goldsmiths adapted the imagery of other people in their
own imaginative ways. They borrowed the linear mane of Assyrian
horses to portray that of a boar in panels of scrolls on a Scythian
scabbard. And like the Assyrians, the Scythians embellished
drinking vessels with animals, as is seen in one of the show's
charmers, the handle of an ancient cup in the form of a boar with
silver fangs and flat feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek influence was even stronger. ``Only a handful of
objects in this show would be considered purely Greek,'' Ms. Reeder
said. ``A lovely sphinx earring is Hellenistic in style, but the
less refined nose suggests that the maker probably did not study in
Athens.''
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, the forms may be Greek but the custom
represented is not: an image of a woman on a bow-and-arrow case
looks Greek until you notice that she is perched on an upended
footstool, something no proper Greek would do, Ms. Reeder said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Scythians' own inimitable style, sound and motion
were paramount. ``Sounds were as vital as speed to Scythian
warriors,'' Ms. Reeder said. ``They were a people on the move with
hoofs pounding, wheels creaking and the blowing of horns in the
wind. They created things that came alive with sound. They wore
rustling gowns, tinkling earrings, robes awash with pendants that
jingled. Even the finials on their wagon poles rattled to announce
their coming.''
</P>
</TEXT>
