<HEADLINE>
NEAPOLITAN WINE FINDS HIGH NOTES, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Sidebar with NAPLES-RESTAURANTS)  
 (bl)  
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATRIPALDA, Italy _ One of the most startling changes in
Campania, the region of Naples, has been the improvement in the
local wines in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Mastroberardino firm, headquartered here in the hills east
of the city, has set the pace for generations. In recent years it
has produced classic wines made from native Campanian grapes _ a
premium white Fiano di Avellino, fresh yet honeyed, called More
Maiorum, and a majestic, long-lived red, Radici Taurasi, made from
aglianico and often called the Barolo of the south. Both varietals
date to the time of the Greeks and the Romans.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Mastroberardino family has split, but Piero
Mastroberardino, 33, continues to innovate and to modernize; the
winery is one of the most technically advanced in all of Italy. In
March, he will introduce a new premium wine called Historia, a
robust red with long aging in oak.
</P>
<P>
   Mastroberardino has plenty of competition these days, which you
can sample at some Naples restaurants. At Don Salvatore, I drank a
refreshing, slightly sharp wine from the D'Ambria vineyards on
Ischia. Masaniello offers a subtle, intense fiano made in small
lots by Romano Clelia.
</P>
<P>
   Other names to look for include Villa Matilde, for red aglianico
and fruity white made from falanghina, another intriguing old
grape, and Feudi di San Gregorio, for a whole line of exceptional,
well-balanced wines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Villa Matilde's wines, fairly widely distributed in the United
States, are often a bargain, at well under $20 a bottle. High-end
Mastroberardino and Feudi di San Gregorio wines can be expensive
(as much as $60), but both firms also make smaller wines, like
Greco di Tufo, a brisk white, that cost only about $10 to $15. They
are also widely available in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
