<HEADLINE>
BOND YIELDS DOWN FOR 3RD STRAIGHT DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond yields fell for the third consecutive day
Tuesday after government reports showed a rise in productivity and
a drop in labor costs, easing investor concern about inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year bond rose 17/32 to 99 1/32. The yield,
which moves in the opposite direction, dropped to 6.20 percent,
from 6.24 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The government raised its estimate of growth in third-quarter
productivity to 4.9 percent, the fastest pace in almost seven
years, from a prior estimate of 4.2 percent. Productivity is an
index of output per hour worked.
</P>
<P>
   In another report, the Labor Department said unit labor costs
for the third quarter declined 0.2 percent, which brought the
year-over-year trend to just 1.5 percent, down from 2.3 percent in
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fine, the chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management,
said, ``It soothed the market's inflationary concerns at least for
the time being and resulted in a further decline in bond yields.
However, this drop in bond yields is not likely to last into the
first quarter, as investors' inflationary expectations and desired
real rate of return will likely push bond yields back up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed,'' said Fine, ``with the economy continuing to grow
very strongly, and with the unemployment rate at 4.1 percent, the
Fed is likely to remain in a tightening mode until it sees
definitive signs that economic growth is slowing to a
noninflationary pace. While no move is expected at the Dec. 21
Federal Open Market Committee meeting to ease the transition
through Year 2000 concerns, the central bank appears to be on a
direct course to raise short term rates once again during the first
quarter of the Year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The government also auctioned $10 billion of a new 52-week bill.
They were awarded at a rate of 5.35 percent, which was a bit better
than expected, with the bid to cover ratio, or the number of bids
compared to the total amount being sold, decent at 3.21 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury securities also received a boost in the afternoon after
the Federal Reserve Board entered the market to buy long dated
issues, and Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, made no
mention of monetary policy in a midmorning speech at the Commerce
Department.
</P>
<P>
   While the market hit the daily highs after Greenspan's speech,
most market participants attributed the gains to a ``coupon pass''
or the outright purchase of Treasury securities by the Fed, which
bought $915 million worth of securities maturing between Aug. 15,
2022, and Nov. 15, 2027.
</P>
<P>
   With trading activity on the decline heading into the year-end,
traders said the Federal Reserve's purchases were enough to lift
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this thin market it doesn't take much to push the market
either way,'' said Robert Pugliese, a senior vice president and
director of fixed income for J.W. Genesis Financial Corp. in Boca
Raton, Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
