<HEADLINE>
HILLARY'S HOLIDAY FAREWELL
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This is a happier Christmas season for Hillary
Clinton than last year's holiday when the president was being
impeached by the House and about to face trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   She soldiered on with a smiling face and a heavy heart,
presiding with composure over the annual White House festivities as
though she had not a worry in the world. The parties went on as
usual. The country saw a president and first lady determined to
prop up the nation's spirits no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   But Monica Lewinsky is now a receding memory, the Clinton
presidency has survived and the first lady is about to make history
as a Senate candidate in New York. This year she really does have
something to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Right after Christmas she will leave behind the unique trappings
and public exposure of the White House, as soon as the Secret
Service completes the installation of security features in her new
home in a New York City suburb. In what was one of her last
appearances as an active first lady, she showed off the latest
glorious White House decorations on Monday for a mob of reporters
and camera folk.
</P>
<P>
   It was a muted variation on the bizarre scene of a year ago,
when the good cheer inside the White House contrasted sharply with
the political gloom outside. The journalists didn't come just for
the decorations then, and they didn't come just to ogle the
gingerbread houses, the swooping ribbons, hand-crafted ornaments
and shimmering trees now either.
</P>
<P>
   They came to get a glimpse of Hillary Clinton's magic act,
always a classy performance. Martha Stewart would have been proud
of the first lady's earnest spiel on behalf of the skilled artists
who decked her marble halls and created nearly 12,000 ornaments for
the Blue Room tree alone. Yet Clinton seemed uncomfortable in her
hostess role, a bit less sparkly than usual, her thoughts already
shifting from her role the president's partner to her new status as
the New York Democratic Senate challenger.
</P>
<P>
   She said that the extended Clinton family will spend this
Christmas together in the White House. The mansion is so
beautifully enveloped in soft red velvet swags, fruit-laden Della
Robbia wreaths and elegant gold bows that it would be a crime not
to hang around to enjoy it. But she refused to answer a question
about her holiday plans for next year, which will come in her
husband's last month as president.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the chatter in the tabloids, it is unlikely that the
couple will divorce, at least so long as he still holds office. But
a separation short of the legal niceties seems the way they are
going.
</P>
<P>
   Her friends suggest that she will spend more time in New York
than originally planned when she said she would be in Washington
roughly one week every month. She has been criticized for coasting
on her status as first lady instead of sufficiently making the
required rounds in her adopted political base. It is becoming
urgent that she spend a lot more time in the state so that the
perception of her identity shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the nation's capital, she is seen as a political bird in
flight, leaving us behind for an unknown future as a candidate in a
race she could well lose. But if she wins, she will be back as a
senator and will need yet another new address, inevitably one less
grand than the mansion she now occupies.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she still nominally presides over a White House
that is always at its most spectacular during the December
holidays. The staff begins preparing for the extravaganza in
February. There is nothing else like it.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 12,000 shrimp and 285 gallons of eggnog will be
served at receptions during the next two weeks. Inside the White
House there are 28 decorated Christmas trees and 324 wreaths. Some
2,000 musicians will perform in the mansion during tours and
receptions.
</P>
<P>
   This year's theme honors national treasures _ those historic
structures, documents and art that record our history and our
traditions. Hillary Clinton has led a crusade in the past year to
preserve these objects, many of which are threatened by decay,
natural disasters and improper conservation. Replicas of some of
our most famous landmarks and public figures carved in wood or
marzipan line marble mantels, stand on tables and hang from the
central East Room tree.
</P>
<P>
   Such a fantastic setting can be hard to leave behind for the
horrors of a New York campaign. But what's wrong with a somewhat
early departure? She would have only one more year there anyway.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
