<SLUG> BC-SALZBURG-FEST-DIRECTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERNIST TO LEAD SALZBURG FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mg) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The celebrated Salzburg Festival, which was thrown into
turmoil this summer when Austria's president, Thomas Klestil, led a
conservative attack on its eclectic programming, has named Peter
Ruzicka, 51, a German conductor and composer, as artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   He will succeed Gerard Mortier, who will step down in September
2001 after 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In picking Ruzicka after a nine-month search, the festival's
board has refused to bow to pressure to appoint a traditionalist as
director. Rather, with the presidency of the festival already
occupied by a conservative, Helga Rabl-Stadler, music experts said
the board had opted for someone who would probably continue
Mortier's policy of encouraging both contemporary music and
contemporary interpretation of the classical repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Ruzicka, who is artistic director of the Munich Biennial for New
Music Theater and artistic adviser to the Royal Concertgebouw
Orchestra in Amsterdam, has made his name as a manager and a
musician in several significant positions in Germany, and as
artistic director of the Berlin Radio Symphony Orchestra and of the
Hamburg State Opera and the Hamburg State Philharmonic Orchestra.
He has not yet indicated his plans for his first Salzburg season in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Mortier, artistic director of the Theatre de la Monnaie in
Brussels before accepting the Salzburg post long held by Herbert
von Karajan, quickly upset traditionalists by introducing 20th
century composers as well as avant-garde theater directors.
Opposition to what the festival called the reform era surfaced
after Mortier announced in March that he would not seek a third
five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech in Salzburg last summer, Klestil, whose position as
Austria's president is largely ceremonial, called for a return to
the ideals of the festival's founder in 1920, composer Hugo von
Hofmannsthal.
</P>
<P>
   Klestil described Mortier's approach as ``confrontation instead
of harmony, provocation instead of agreement, spectacle instead of
fidelity to the work, `demolition' drama instead of humanistic,
spiritually elevating theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Mortier responded with a letter to Klestil and, when that went
unanswered, counterattacked in interviews, noting that the
president's speech was a reflection of the state of culture in
Austria.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is being asked for here is the kind of art that lies, and
alongside that, an attempt to limit Austria to a small fraction of
itself,'' Mortier said in one interview. ``It is as if Alban Berg
were not precisely as Austrian as Mozart.''
</P>
<P>
   For a festival with Mozart as its spiritual father, Mortier's
definition of its program policy gives a sense of how priorities
have changed. It reads, ``The classical heritage should be conveyed
through a contemporary idiom, for today's audiences; the great
works of the 20th century are to be presented in a valid form;
ample space is accorded to contemporary works.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year's festival, which runs from July 23 through Aug. 31,
will include three Mozart operas, operas by Berlioz, Offenbach,
Gluck and Wagner, and the world premiere of ``Love From Afar,'' an
opera by the Finnish composer Kaija Saariaho.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
