<SLUG> BC-CAR-GORDON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon sacks crew chief Whitesell
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ That feel-good feeling between driver Jeff Gordon and
crew chief Brian Whitesell took a surprising turn on Tuesday.
Whitesell was replaced by Petty Enterprises' Robbie Loomis.
</P>
<P>
   Loomis, crew chief for the No. 43 car and John Andretti for nine
years, had spent all of his 14-year NASCAR career working for Petty
Enterprises. He had turned down numerous job offers during the
years because of loyalty to the Petty family.
</P>
<P>
   But Loomis finally changed his mind when given the chance to
work with a perennial Winston Cup contender.
</P>
<P>
   Whitesell, who appeared to be on the way to a lengthy working
relationship with Gordon as crew chief, was moved to the position
of team manager. He was Gordon's hand-picked successor when
long-time crew chief Ray Evernham resigned in October to lead
Dodge's return to Winston Cup competition.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon won his first two races at Martinsville and Charlotte
after Evernham's departure. But the honeymoon ended quickly after
Gordon failed to finish higher than 10th in the final five races,
including a disastrous 38th in the season-ender at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Whitesell became a prime target for criticism from the driver's
die-hard fans, who claimed that Evernham already had the car setups
in place for Martinsville and Charlotte before leaving Hendrick.
Crew chiefs normally complete basic preparations at least two races
in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon also lost five members of his ``Rainbow Warriors'' pit
crew, who signed contracts to work for Robert Yates Racing this
season without notifying Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has been dedicating most of the off-season to structuring
a new pit crew from outside candidates and those in the Hendrick
organization. ``I'm really excited to have someone with such great
talent and experience join our team,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in the Winston Cup garage knows (Robbie's)
capabilities. His expertise and racing savvy will add a great deal
of depth to our team. And he and Brian will make a great
combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
