<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-LAURA-INGRAHAM-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST CALL FOR THE TAX-AND-SPENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Campaign
Countdown commentary column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MS-NBC host Laura Ingraham.) 
 By LAURA INGRAHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    During the 1980s the Republican Party won three consecutive
elections, in part by convincing the public that Carter, Mondale
and Dukakis were ``tax and spend'' liberals ready to blow the
taxpayers' money on ineffective social programs.
 &HT;    And with the next presidential election only 11 months away,
that old charge is flying again. But this time it's the Democratic
frontrunner who is playing the deficit hawk: In a recent attack on
rival Bill Bradley's health-care plan, Vice President Al Gore
sounded more like Reagan than like Roosevelt.
 &HT;    After feeling Bradley breathing down his neck in New Hampshire
earlier this fall, Gore has seen his popularity rise again after he
launched an aggressive, no-prisoners assault on his opponent. So
last week, when Bradley told The Washington Post that he wouldn't
rule out a tax increase to expand health-care coverage to millions
who are uninsured, Gore pounced.
 &HT;    ``Look, we have the largest surplus in the history of the United
States,'' he told reporters. ``This is not the time to be talking
about tax increases.''
 &HT;    Gore even sidestepped a question about whether there is any
current domestic priority he feels strongly enough about to raise
taxes.
 &HT;    What's going on here? Al Gore, a fiscal conservative?
 &HT;    Not quite. But it's more evidence of how profoundly the
conservative economic message has affected the American political
debate, and how well Al Gore has learned from his boss.
 &HT;    Despite his left-leaning, ``Earth in the Balance'' proclivities,
Gore apparently realizes that none of that nonsense resonates
beyond the Ivy League elites who still think that the government
should grow, not shrink.
 &HT;    Bill Clinton sailed into office pledging a new, centrist
Democratic agenda, then turned his back on that with Hillary's
big-government health-care reform. The results were disastrous, and
in no time at all the president was pushing for more money for the
Pentagon and proposing a tax-reduction package of his own, albeit a
minuscule one.
 &HT;    Sure, his State of the Union pronouncement that ``the era of big
government is over'' may have been just another clever White House
spin, but it helped condition the public against those that would
take the country the other way.
 &HT;    Gore may be trying to keep Clinton's character at arm's length,
but he desperately hopes that some of the president's campaign
savvy has rubbed off on him. Hence his effort to use Bradley's
``maybe-I'll-tax'' slipup to position himself as the pragmatic
Democratic choice.
 &HT;    ``I'm talking about tax cuts, Sen. Bradley is talking about tax
increases,'' Gore said.
 &HT;    Maybe George W. Bush or John McCain can borrow some of Gore's
best anti-Bradley lines if Gore implodes and Bradley actually gets
the nomination.
 &HT;    Ever vowing to stay out of a dogfight with Gore, Bradley was
forced to backpedal after the vice president's sharp attacks. A
Bradley spokesman insisted that the candidate was speaking only
hypothetically, and wasn't really for tax increases. But the damage
had already been done.
 &HT;    For the past six years, editorial pages have regularly predicted
that the ``far right'' or ``Christian right'' of the Republican
Party would cause the GOP to crash and burn. The public simply
isn't that socially conservative, the argument goes.
 &HT;    Speaker Newt Gingrich's abrupt departure from the House this
year, like Congress' wobbly popularity, suggests that those
prognosticators had a point. America doesn't want a crusade,
whether led by self-proclaimed Republican ``revolutionaries'' or by
self-righteous Democrats.
 &HT;    Bill Bradley doesn't understand this. He speaks of the need for
candor in politics as he earnestly outlines his crusade for
national health-care insurance.
 &HT;    ``This is about just going out and saying who you are and what
you believe,'' he told campaign workers recently, ``and maybe you
can win by doing that.''
 &HT;    Not if recent history is any guide. While America may not be
salivating for a Forbes-style tax cut, neither is it in the mood
for a tax increase, even one that addresses a growing domestic
concern. Democrats who want to dabble in new, large-scale
government spending are in a fiscal box. Gore is using it to his
political benefit, while Bradley is just, well, cornered.
 &HT;    Today's Democrats are a far cry from the struggling liberals of
the 1980s. Thanks to President Clinton, they've shed their
pacifist, anti-military, anti-free-market, pro-big-government
reputation. Reagan-era Democrats would have been openly calling for
increased federal oversight of the Internet, while this
administration has been wary of stepping on the toes of the
economy, which has won Al Gore some key supporters in Silicon
Valley.
 &HT;    Of course Bradley isn't alone in thinking that liberal crusades
can work nationally. We saw successful crusades last week in
Seattle, with unions and environmentalists teaming up to disrupt
the administration's efforts at global-trade talks. Positioning
themselves against efforts to open world markets, they are
yesterday's left.
 &HT;    But Gore has to do more than simply paint Bradley as a knee-jerk
liberal if he wants to take the baton from his old pal Bill. He
himself must resist what still comes naturally _ proposing
government solutions and government controls on the scale demanded
by the old left.
 c.1999 Laura Ingraham  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Laura Ingraham is a lawyer and the host of the MS-NBC daily
program ``Watch It! With Laura Ingraham.'' She is the author of the
upcoming book, ``The Hillary Trap: Looking for Power in All the
Right Places,'' due from Hyperion in 2000.)
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MS-NBC host Laura Ingraham.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _ _  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
