<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-DIVISIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREAN DIPLOMAT RAILS AGAINST NONEXISTENT `WALL OF
DIVISION'  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A North Korean diplomat used a rare news conference
here on Tuesday to rail against a nonexistent 150-mile-long
concrete ``wall of division'' that the South Koreans supposedly
erected 20 years ago across the buffer zone between North and
South.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomat, Chu Chang Jun, is North Korea's longtime
ambassador to China, one of his country's few allies. He demanded
the ``immediate dismantling of the cursed reinforced concrete wall
that artificially bisects the nation that had lived in harmony
generation after generation.''
</P>
<P>
   In a ``never to be pardoned criminal act,'' the wall was erected
across the peninsula 20 years ago this Dec. 29, Chu said. It is ``a
huge structure,'' he said, 16 to 26 feet tall and 33 to 62 feet
wide at the base. Far from a defensive rampart, it is a ``northward
invasion bridgehead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The wall exists only in North Korean propaganda, according to
South Korean and American diplomats and others who have visited the
area. But with a hostile North Korea keeping large numbers of
troops and tanks near the border, the South Koreans, aided by the
United States, have strewn large concrete tank barriers and sentry
stations as well as fences and minefields along their side of the
tense demilitarized zone.
</P>
<P>
   The bitter Korean War of 1950 to 1953 ended with a truce but no
treaty, and the buffer zone separating the peninsula has been
volatile ever since.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Chu gave an implacable summary of North
Korean views on relations with the South and its sponsor, the
United States. He spoke beneath large pictures of the late North
Korean leader, Kim Il Sung, and his son, the current leader, Kim
Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
   Chu's comments seemed out of step with diplomatic developments,
making the news conference seem even odder. Reeling from years of
economic collapse and famine, North Korea seems to be opening its
doors a crack in a quest for more economic aid, diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea and Japan are seriously discussing a restoration of
diplomatic relations. The United States lifted many trade
restrictions after North Korea agreed not to carry out a second
test of a long-range missile, and talks on improving ties have
proceeded fitfully.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's president, Kim Dae-jung, has pursued a ``sunshine
policy'' of broader economic and cultural contacts with North
Korea, and the North has recently allowed more exchanges. Chu said,
``the sunshine policy brings confrontation instead of
reconciliation,'' and called it ``very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Chu also denied reports _ verified by many journalists and
diplomats _ that tens of thousands of North Koreans had crossed the
border into China to escape famine and hardship. ``There have been
no illegal border crossings,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
