<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2076 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-TANKERS-SPI &LR;      12-07 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-TANKERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON STATE'S TOUGH TANKER SAFETY RULES ARGUED IN SUPREME
COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Washington state's tough safety rules for oil
tankers navigating Puget Sound came under attack at the Supreme
Court Tuesday from an odd alliance of tanker owners and the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The state enacted the rules in 1994 in an effort to prevent a
disaster like the Exxon Valdez oil spill of 1989, which caused
environmental damage in Alaska. Among the regulations at stake are
requirements that crew members be drug- and alcohol-free, that an
extra pilot be on board during bad weather, and that the officers
and deckhands speak a common language.
</P>
<P>
   But the oil industry and the Clinton administration argued that
the state has no right to regulate oil tankers plying local waters
because they are already regulated under a federal law called the
Oil Pollution Act of 1990. Also, they argued, various international
treaties require uniform criteria for oil tanker operation.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court is expected to decide by next summer whether
to uphold or overturn the state regulations, which previously were
upheld by the U.S. District Court for the Western District of
Washington and by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   The justices gave little indication of how they might rule.
Several, including Justices Stephen Breyer, Anthony Kennedy, David
Souter and John Paul Stevens, expressed consternation at the
reasoning the Appeals Court used in upholding the state law, but
they did not express an opinion about the result.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the justices, particularly Justice Sandra Day O'Connor
and Chief Justice William Rehnquist, expressed concern about
whether federal regulators could adequately address the
peculiarities of local waters.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist referred to a ``very strong local interest'' in a
requirement such as ``in heavy fog in Seattle harbor you have to
have a tug.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I, for one, would be loathe to read some general federal
statute as preempting something like that,'' Rehnquist said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's arguments were from a consolidation of two lawsuits,
United States vs. Gov. Gary Locke and International Association of
Independent Tanker Owners vs. Gov. Gary Locke. The dispute has
drawn broad attention because of its import for environmental
protection and for states rights.
</P>
<P>
   Among those filing briefs in support of the state are seven
Washington counties that border on Puget Sound, 21 states and
territories, seven fishing groups from around the country, a
variety of environmental organizations, and a citizen's group from
Prince William Sound, Alaska, where the Exxon Valdez ran aground.
</P>
<P>
   The tanker industry and the federal government have won support
from 15 foreign governments and a variety of shipping associations
and business groups. Those groups are largely concerned with
preventing their members from having to comply with different
regulations in different states, which they say would be confusing
and potentially dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The debate inside the courtroom featured an arcane discussion of
the circumstances under which states can regulate merchant vessels
that are already regulated by the Coast Guard under federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Benner, an attorney for the tanker owners, said that
throughout American history it has been the job of the federal
government to regulate merchant shipping. He said that the state's
regulations are ``an intrusion by state government into an area
exclusively regulated by the federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   David Frederick, the assistant to the solicitor general at the
Department of Justice, warned that state regulations would
``eviscerate thousands of pages of international treaty law'' and
that ``It would greatly upset uniformity if each of the 23 coastal
states could pick and choose which requirements it wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Frederick said that state officials are ``proposing to
imprison'' tanker operators for failure to comply with state rules.
(State officials say that during the five years the rules have been
in effect, no one has been imprisoned, and few tanker operators
have even been cited for a violation.)
</P>
<P>
   Washington state was represented by William Collins, a senior
assistant attorney general, who argued that the state is entitled
to enact regulations that complement, and do not contradict,
federal tanker rules. He called state regulators ``a second set of
eyes on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the state's legal brief, the waters of Washington
state are more difficult to navigate than those in Prince William
Sound because of persistent fog, heavy fishing traffic and narrow
waterways. State officials argue that an oil spill could be
devastating to fish and wildlife and to the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, the sides squared off over the
environmental issues. Jeffrey Needle, an attorney for
environmentalists, blasted President Clinton for allowing his
Justice Department to argue against Washington state regulators
just a week after extolling the importance of the environment in a
speech before the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of Washington's environment should not be
sacrificed in the name of international trade,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, the state lawyer, said that with five oil refineries in
Washington state, it is important that state officials be able to
protect the environment and the economy from the damage of an oil
spill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Coast Guard is a hardworking organization, but they have
limited resources,'' Collins said. ``In the state of Washington,
we've stepped up to the plate and dedicated some of our resources
to try to protect our own waters. If the court rules against us,
then ... that choice will be taken away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   But Benner, the industry lawyer, said tanker owners want to be
environmentally responsible but are entitled to a uniform set of
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We trade all over the world, and we don't want to have safety
procedures that vary from place to place and locale to locale,''
Benner said. ``We're very sure we're on the environmental high
ground here. There's an extensive federal system in place ... and
if you start tinkering with it around the edges ... these vessels
are put in harm's way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
