<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2079 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-MARKPRICE-COX     12-07 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MARKPRICE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Price returns to Tech as member of coaching team
</P>
<P>
   By J.C. Clemons
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mark Price left the glitz and glamour of an NBA
playing career and a seven-figure salary. Price swapped them to
become an assistant college basketball coach whose paycheck only
approaches six figures.
</P>
<P>
   But don't cry for Price.
</P>
<P>
   For the former NBA player of the year turned No. 3 Georgia Tech
assistant, the price of the trade is just right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was the right time to call it a career,'' said
Price, 35, who after 13 NBA season retired a year ago before the
1999 season. ``Of course, I miss playing a little bit, but my body
tells me every day it was the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of other factors, too, especially my family
situation. I played for three different teams the last three years,
and we were tired of moving around.''
</P>
<P>
   Price will be on the bench in Athens tonight when Tech (3-1)
plays its annual grudge match against Georgia (3-3), and nobody is
happier with his move to the sidelines _ besides Yellow Jackets
coach Bobby Cremins _ than his wife.
</P>
<P>
   With four children under the age of 10, family matters played a
major factor in their return to campus life.
</P>
<P>
   Five-star hotels ? Gone. Limousine rides to NBA All-Star-Game
functions? A thing of the past. The roar of the crowd? No more.
</P>
<P>
   In their place comes bedtime stories read by dad, dinner
together most nights and school field trips and church gatherings.
All as a family, and the Prices are eating it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's really great,'' Laura Marbut Price said. ``We're
loving it because we just really needed time for family. It so
great for the kids. It's liking having a really normal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The benefits we have for the family far outweigh the joy we
had watching him play. The lifestyle that went along with playing
in the NBA, I don't miss that at all. It sounds selfish, but it's
selfish for all the right reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there was a bit of altruism involved as well.
</P>
<P>
   Price was one the first top recruit Cremins landed after
arriving at Tech in 1981-82 from Appalachian State. After Tech
struggled to a 10-16 finish in Cremins' first season, Price arrived
from Enid, Okla., and fortunes turned.
</P>
<P>
   Tech went 13-15 in '83, but Price averaged 20.3 points. More
importantly, he was named ACC rookie of the year, an honor seven
other Jackets would achieve as Cremins' recruiting prowess grew.
</P>
<P>
   In '84, Tech reached the NIT, and Cremins first NCAA Tournament
appearance came the next season. That began a string of nine
consecutive NCAA berths, including a Final Four march in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the Jackets have made the NCAA field just once,
1996, in the past six seasons. Having returned to Atlanta, it was
hard for Price to witness the decline of the once-proud program.
And even tougher, the criticism directed at Cremins, the man who
built it.
</P>
<P>
   Price who spent his first year of retirement volunteering as an
assistant to Duluth High coach Joe Marelle, who was battling
cancer. But when vacancies became available after last season's
15-16 finish, he signed on with Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark did it for me, and for Georgia Tech,'' Cremins says.
``It's worked out well. Everybody respects him. He has such a great
presence and is such a wonderful person (that) players respond to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Price, who accepted a non-recruiting position to stay close to
home, focuses mainly on player development and already is producing
results. Seemingly overnight, point guard Tony Akins has been
transformed from shaky freshman -- 32 percent field-goal shooting,
148-138 assists to turnovers -- to dependable veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible to be able to work with a great NBA point
guard like Mark Price,'' says Akins, who is averaging 13.6 points
and 6.0 assists, is making 41.4 percent of three-pointers and is
operatging with a 2.3-1 assists-to-turnover ratio. ``When he says
something, you just know he knows what he's talking about. ... You
listen and take it to heart because he's done it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Price, who made an NBA record 90.4 percent of his career
free-throw attempts, has played shot doctor for the Yellow Jackets,
especially forward Alvin Jones. A career 56 percent free-throw
shooter entering the season, Jones has made 30 of 44 (68.2
percent).
</P>
<P>
   Good shooting, Price says, is a result of form -- and hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is teaching, a lot of it is mental approach,''
Price said. ``But it's a process that doesn't happen overnight.
Once you get a guy with better technique, then he has to go out and
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   With such sudden success, could a head-coaching shot be in
Price's future? His father, Denny, coached at the high school,
college and pro levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been the type of guy who focuses on what I'm doing
right now,'' he said. ``I have no master plan.''
</P>
<P>
   MARK PRICE FILE
</P>
<P>
   Born: Feb. 16, 1964, Enid, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   College career: Four-year letterman at Georgia Tech (1983-86);
first-team All-America guard '85 (16.7 ppg.), and ACC player of the
year; finalist for John Naismith and John Wooden player-of-the-year
awards in '86 (17.4 ppg.); ACC rookie of the year in '83 (20.3
ppg.); Yellow Jackets third-best career scorer (2,193 points);
school-record 240 career steals; shot 85 percent from the
free-throw line, to rank third in school history.
</P>
<P>
   NBA career: Drafted in the second round by Dallas Mavericks in
'86; traded to Cleveland Cavaliers, where he played through '95;
played one year each with Washington, Golden State and Orlando
before retiring before the '99 season; four-time NBA All-Star,
named first-team NBA in '93, third team in '89, '92 and '94. Member
of '94 Dream Team II. Averaged 15.2 ppg. for his career (10,989
points); Cavs all-time leader in assists (4,206) and three-pointers
(734); NBA's best career free-throw percentage (90.4).
</P>
<P>
   Coaching career: First year as Tech assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Wife, Laura; daughters, Carolina (9) and Brittany (6),
and sons, Hudson (5) and Joshua (nine months).
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Clemons writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
