<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YAHOO LEAP HELPS DRIVE NASDAQ TO 4TH STRAIGHT RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Techno-mania continued in the stock market Tuesday as
the Nasdaq composite index rose to a fourth consecutive record,
partly because of a huge jump in the price of shares of Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   But other indexes struggled, and ended lower. Trading volume was
heavy.
</P>
<P>
   Led by a second big drop in the price of Coca-Cola, the Dow
Jones industrial average slumped 118.36 points, or 1.05 percent, to
11,106.65. A number of Wall Street analysts downgraded Coke's stock
Tuesday, a day after the beverage giant's chairman and chief
executive said he would resign his positions in April, an
announcement that stunned the business world.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Coke closed at 60, down 4. Since M. Douglas Ivester
said he was leaving the company, the stock has lost 7 percent of
its market value.
</P>
<P>
   A bad day for drug stocks contributed to a slide in the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which closed at 1,409.17, down 14.16
points, or 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the performance of the Dow and S&AMP;P was
eclipsed by continued rapid demand for the technology shares that
dominate the Nasdaq composite index. Issues like Cisco Systems,
Ciena and Yahoo pushed the Nasdaq composite index up 40.91 points,
or 1.15 percent, to 3,586.92.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange was 1.09 billion shares,
and more than 1.5 billion shares traded on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, much of the session was dominated by Yahoo, the Internet
media company that at the close of trading became part of the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   The imminent addition of Yahoo to the index prompted mutual
funds that mimic the composition of the S&AMP;P to sell shares of the
499 other companies to make room for Yahoo. Yahoo will have a far
bigger weighting than the company it is replacing, Laidlaw Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's shares have been rising steadily since Nov. 30, when the
S&AMP;P said Yahoo was going in its index. But analysts were stunned by
what happened yesterday: Yahoo's shares closed at 348, up 67 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a week almost $42 billion in Yahoo's market capitalization
has been created out of thin air,'' said William Meehan, chief
market analyst at Cantor Fitzgerald. ``The only news has been that
the stock is being added to the S&AMP;P index.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks that are added to a widely-used index like the S&AMP;P
generally rise after the decision is made to put them in. But the
54 percent gain in Yahoo's shares in the last week is a seismic
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, stocks back off about three percent after the
change in the index is made,'' Meehan said. ``Given the run-up in
Yahoo's shares we have seen in the last week, I suspect that in
this case it might be a little bit more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Herrman, chief investment officer at Waddell &AMP; Reed in
Overland Park, Kan., which has some $27 billion under management,
called the run-up in Yahoo's stock ``unbelievable.'' But in the
next breath he added that for a while yet technology shares are
likely to appreciate further.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a performance basis, everybody is forced to put more money
into technology,'' he said. ``Right now, technology is nearly 30
percent of the S&AMP;P 500 and people are talking about it going to 40
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have this vision of the Nasdaq as a diver that is about to
jack-knife,'' he added. ``But I don't think we will visit that
issue until sometime next year.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a bad day for big drug stocks and health company issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers Squibb fell 3 1/2, to 66 11/16. Eli Lilly dropped
by 3, to 66 1/2. And Johnson &AMP; Johnson slumped 3 7/16, to 93 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Those losses were mild compared to the experience of Visx Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Visx stock tumbled 36 1/8 to 52 on the Nasdaq market after a
judge for the International Trade Commission ruled that the
company's patents were not infringed upon by vision-correction
lasers sold by Nidek Co., a rival. Analysts said the ruling could
hurt Visx's sales and licensing negotiations. The company said it
would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a better tone in the bond market helped to buttress
financial service company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter gained 3 3/4, to 131 5/8. AIG, the
big insurance company, gained 2 11/6, to 106 1/16. And Citigroup
gained 1, to 57 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Russell 2000 index of small company stocks was
little changed, closing at 465.70, down 0.05.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
