<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-RUSSIA-345&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW EASES DEMAND THAT CIVILIANS LEAVE CHECHEN CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (also see CHECHNYA-RUSSIA-MILITARY)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOZDOK, Russia _ The Russian government on Tuesday backed away
from an ultimatum that civilians leave the Chechen capital of
Grozny by Saturday or face a deadly bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Russian warplanes dropped thousands of leaflets over Grozny in
recent days, urging residents to use any means possible to escape
the city before Dec. 11.
</P>
<P>
   The demand spurred alarms in Western capitals that thousands of
Chechnya's civilians could be killed or injured. President Clinton
said he was gravely concerned, and there were calls in some Western
European capitals to cut off Western credits in protest.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, Russian Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo
softened Moscow's stance, saying there was no deadline for the
civilians to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not set any time period,'' Rushailo said during a tour
of Chechnya, which ended with a stop at the sprawling Russian air
base base here. ``We think that people who are capable of leaving
the war zone should do it as soon as possible so not to risk their
lives and those of their relatives.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this means that the Russians plan to cease their
punishing artillery and bombing attacks on Grozny. The Chechen
capital has been pounded as the Russian military has tried to force
the Islamic fighters into submission. Refugees say the strikes have
been much fiercer than during the 1994-96 Chechen war, when Russian
tried to suppress a secessionist movement.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it mean that Russia has given up its attempt to
persuade the thousands of civilians still in Grozny to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military is in the process of establishing a safe
corridor for refugees from Grozny leading north to the town of
Pervomaiskoye, where a checkpoint has been established. There the
refugees will be processed and sent to two tent cities at
Znamenskoye in northern Chechnya, which the military is rushing to
complete.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Russia is no longer insisting that Grozny's residents
leave by this Saturday, and it has stopped issuing the chilling
warnings to civilians that they risk death if they stay after that
date.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some officials suggested that the Russian military had caught
Russian civilian policy-makers by surprise with its Saturday
deadline and created an unnecessary international firestorm.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Russia climbed down from the talk of a deadline,
however, top officials expressed scorn for the West. Prime Minister
Vladimir Putin, the favorite to succeed President Boris Yeltsin,
complained that the West simply did not understand the situation in
the Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
   That is a sentiment that has a lot of support among the Russian
public, which blames the rebels for a rash of bombings in Moscow
and other Russian cities and for hundreds of kidnappings before the
war that made Chechnya one of the world's most lawless and
dangerous regions.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's poll ratings have risen sharply after he initiated the
military campaign against the Chechen rebels last September and
displayed his willingness to stand up to the West. And there was
far more of an outcry in the West over the ultimatum than in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If representative of foreign countries are so worried about
the events in the northern Caucasus they should not only exert
pressure on the Russian leadership,'' Putin said. ``Let them use
their influence to persuade the bandits to free Russian citizens
who have been taken hostage and the many foreign hostages who are
still kept by the bandits.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the Russians relaxed their ultimatum to the civilians,
there was no softening of the Russian line regarding the Islamic
militants. Col. Gen. Victor Kazantsev, the commander of Russian
forces in the northern Caucasus, insisted that there was no
ultimatum for civilians, but that the rebels had a week to leave
Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   How the Russian military plans to enforce its demands to the
militants remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The larger question, however, was not the political sparring
between the East and West, but the fate of Chechnya's civilians.
</P>
<P>
   In a day of often-confusing statements, it was still unclear
whether many of Grozny's civilians would use the new safe corridor.
Some are too sick to leave, while others may be afraid of arousing
the rebels' ire.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is apparent how the checkpoint and tent cities could
accommodate a new flood or refugees if Grozny's residents are in
fact persuaded to evacuation the city.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Koshman, the deputy prime minister in charge of policy
on Chechnya, has estimated there are still 45,000 to 50,000
civilians in Grozny. Other estimates put the number at 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rushailo said the checkpoint at Pervomaikoye will be able to
process about 3,000 people a day, but the tent cities at
Znamenskoye only have room for 4,500. That means that that the rest
of the refugees would have to find accommodations with relatives or
in camps that have yet to be built.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
