<SLUG> BC-BKN-ODOM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Odom gives Clippers hope when not much else does
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They are the Lost Angeles Clippers, a team seemingly
destined to wallow in a nether world of underachievement and
malady.
</P>
<P>
   So, when three teams passed on Lamar Odom in the June draft, the
feeling permeated that maybe the succession of calamities that have
enveloped L.A.'s other team could be near a merciful conclusion.
Without hesitation, the Clippers snapped up Odom, generally
regarded as the most skilled player in the draft but passed over
because of a series of questionable acts.
</P>
<P>
   After making himself eligible for the draft and hiring an agent,
Odom had tried to renege. He was a no-show at the Chicago predraft
camp, and he broke all but one appointment for individual workouts
He also did not attend the predraft media session in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When Odom did work out for four teams, the Clippers were
impressed at his ability, at 6 feet 10, to make plays from the
perimeter and inside, through scoring or passing. They wanted him.
</P>
<P>
   And for a change in Clippers lore, Odom wanted the Clippers,
inasmuch as he wanted anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost a challenge; I love challenges,'' he said.
``That's what pushes everybody in the world, whether you're working
on Wall Street or you're sweeping. It's a challenge to prove
everybody wrong and show everybody that we can play in the NBA and
be competitive and, hopefully, make a run for it.
</P>
<P>
   He made those comments before the season began, so he knew full
well how difficult the process will be with the Clips. As usual in
the franchise's cursed past, injuries beset the club and stunted
the kind of growth expected from its young talent. Center Michael
Olowokandi and forward Maurice Taylor both missed time because of
injury.
</P>
<P>
   And with a questionable backcourt, Odom's display of star
potential has been enough to net the Clippers only a 4-13 record
going into tonight's meeting with the Hawks at Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Odom's presence gives the Clippers hope. He's averaging
18.5 points, 7.8 rebounds and 3.4 assists, and, along with
Houston's Steve Francis, is an early front runner for NBA Rookie of
the Year. And for the first time since anyone can remember, they
have a player other fans want to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lamar, to be a rookie and only 20 years old, has so much
confidence,'' Clippers point Eric Murdock said. ``I think all great
players have a certain cockiness about them that allow them to
think they can't be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   His signature game so far came last month in Minnesota, when
Odom could not be stopped by the Timberwolves and Kevin Garnett in
the late stretch of an 89-85 Clippers victory. Odom played the
entire game, getting 13 of his 22 points and notching the decisive
basket over Garnett with 16 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed why he's probably going to be the rookie of the
year,'' Minnesota coach Flip Saunders said.
</P>
<P>
   Odom's response to the display? ``The best part about playing in
the league is that every night you're going against somebody that's
going to make you bring it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he brought a less-than-sparkling personal history with
him, Odom has been diligent about letting what he calls the ``real
Lamar Odom'' show. And in the discovery, Odom brings a youthful yet
sound approach to life and basketball.
</P>
<P>
   He calls his purchase of a penthouse with a beach view in the
Los Angeles area his most prized acquisition since getting a
three-year, $7.5-million contract. Unlike most NBA players, or most
people, Odom does not own car. In fact, he doesn't even know how to
drive. He catches rides with teammates or takes taxis to games or
practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a New York thing,'' the Queens native said.
</P>
<P>
   He and his girlfriend have a two-year-old daughter, and she
represents Odom's lifeblood, even more than basketball does. His
father left home when Odom was 6 and later became addicted to
heroin, although he since has beaten that habit. Odom lost his
mother to colon cancer when he was 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a good father is very important to me, because I didn't
have the best relationship with my father,'' he said. ``Those teen
years, I couldn't be told anything. I had a little bit of erratic
behavior, and I just want to be there for my daughter so she
doesn't have to go through the same things that I went through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I've made some mistakes. I'm only (20). But I think
that I've learned from my mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The mistake now evident is that by the Chicago Bulls, Vancouver
Grizzlies and the Charlotte Hornets, all of whom passed on Odom's
limitless talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge, huge steal,'' Olowokandi said. ``Those teams
that passed on drafting him, I don't have a clue why they did that.
Reports say that he wasn't decisive, but the last time I checked,
that wasn't a personality or character flaw.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
