<HEADLINE>
NASA PROMISES THOROUGH INQUIRY OF FAILED MARS MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MARS-MISTAKES) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ In the aftermath of the failed $165 million
Mars Polar Lander mission, the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration on Tuesday promised a thorough investigation of its
causes and implications and a ``major rethinking'' of the strategy
for the entire Mars exploration program.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials said that as a result, the next landing attempt,
planned for launching in 2001, might well be postponed for more
than two years. That spacecraft is almost identical to the polar
lander and so may have to be modified to correct any shortcomings
revealed in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not convinced we will go forward with a lander in '01,''
said Dr. Edward J. Weiler, NASA's associate administrator for space
science. ``Right now, I have no confidence that that would be a
successful mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiler said in a teleconference with reporters from NASA
headquarters in Washington that the goal was still to return a
sample of Martian soil and rock in 2008, but that it might prove to
be impossible without extensive improvements in flight hardware and
interplanetary communications.
</P>
<P>
   He said the goal of searching for evidence of past Martian
climate and conditions possibly conducive to life remained valid
and would not be changed. ``I would not like to miss an opportunity
if it can be avoided,'' Weiler said, ``but we're not going to be a
slave to schedules.''
</P>
<P>
   An independent review of the exploration strategy was expected
to examine whether the design, size and relatively low budget for
the polar lander were adequate for the task of flying to Mars,
landing on strange terrain and working in an extremely cold
climate. After the $1 billion Mars Observer vanished in 1993, NASA
shifted from such large, high-priced spacecraft for new planetary
expeditions to a ``faster, cheaper, better'' policy. Several small,
low-cost craft could be launched at frequent intervals for the cost
of a large craft and reduce the risk of all being lost in one
mishap.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were serious failures,'' Weiler said, referring to the
polar lander and its companion, Mars Climate Orbiter, which
disappeared while approaching the planet in September. ``Perhaps
they are teaching us a lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   Mission officials said the exact cause of the polar lander's
failure might never be determined because they could not receive
any engineering data from it during the final 11 minutes before the
planned soft landing. Even if the craft's antennas had had a clear
view of Earth, signals from the transmitters could not have
penetrated the envelope of electrified gases surrounding the craft
as it heated up on the plunge through Martian atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Weiler and mission officials suggested that one modification on
the next landing spacecraft might include a larger radio
transmitter and a greater supply of electrical power to maintain
contact with Earth through the entire descent.
</P>
<P>
   Other ideas to be considered by the review board include the
possibility of replacing one or more spacecraft now planned for
flight in 2001, 2003 and 2005 with substitutes that would be sent
to Mars mainly to test improved and more reliable technologies.
Another proposal, Weiler said, is to place several communications
satellites in Mars orbit to improve Mars-to-Earth radio links and
perhaps radio beacons to help spacecraft zero in to an orbit of the
planet or to a landing. The beacons, he said, might have helped the
climate orbiter correct its trajectory before it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Polar Lander appeared to be heading right to its target
near the south pole when it was last heard from before its final
descent. With the communications blackout depriving them of clues,
mission engineers declined to speculate on what possibly went
wrong. All they know is that they have listened seven times for
some radio signal, without success.
</P>
<P>
   After the latest attempt early on Tuesday, Richard Cook, the
project manager, said that flight control team had ``played its
last ace,'' but would continue trying to make contact for another
two weeks or so, though their chances of hearing anything were
extremely remote. They are considering a plan to command the Mars
Global Surveyor, orbiting the planet since 1997, to fly over the
landing site in coming weeks and take pictures that might reveal
the polar lander's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly disappointed,'' Cook said, ``but we're
extremely determined to recover from this and go on.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
