<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2097 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-RDP-450&AMP;ADD-NY     12-07 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RDP-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT BACKS LIMIT ON SPREAD OF POLICE RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SCOTUS-TANKERS) 
(bl) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday upheld a California
law that bars commercial information services from obtaining some
police records that are made available routinely to journalists and
others who agree not to use the information ``to sell a product or
service.''
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 7-2, the court resolved a closely watched First
Amendment case on narrow, largely procedural grounds, making little
if any new law. Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist's majority
opinion said the case was not about restricting commercial speech _
the basis on which the lower federal courts had found the 1996 law
unconstitutional _ but about access to government records, which
the government has a nearly free hand to grant or to withhold.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 California law, similar to laws in many other states,
allows access to police records showing the addresses of people who
have been arrested or are the victims of crimes to broad categories
of users, including journalists, scholars and private
investigators. But the law bars access to those who cannot
truthfully sign a statement that the information ``shall not be
used directly or indirectly to sell a product or service.''
</P>
<P>
   The law was challenged, before it took effect, by United
Reporting Publishing Corp., which sells arrest records to lawyers,
insurance agents, alcohol counselors and other clients who plan to
use the information in their businesses. United Reporting, which
also publishes a newsletter containing arrest information, sued to
block enforcement of the law without first trying to meet
conditions for access. It is now free to make a new effort to
qualify, as a preface to challenging the law ``as applied'' rather
than ``on its face,'' Rehnquist said.
</P>
<P>
   As a suit challenging the validity of the untested law on its
face, he continued, the case was essentially abstract and presented
the court with ``nothing more than a governmental denial of access
to information in its possession.'' He added: ``California could
decide not to give out arrestee information at all without
violating the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision, Los Angeles Police Department vs. United Reporting
Publishing, No. 98-678, overturned a ruling by the 9th Circuit U.S.
tates Court of Appeals, in San Francisco. Further proceedings in
the lower courts could clarify or even change the decision; United
Reporting might, for example, be able to show on the basis of the
newsletter it publishes that it is engaged in journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the decision disappointed organizations that had looked
to a court that has been notably solicitous of commercial speech to
place some limits on the government's ability to set differential
access restrictions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The decision ``creates more questions than answers,'' said
Ronald Plesser, a lawyer who filed a brief representing a group of
electronic publishers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm an online information service, am I a journalist or a
commercial republisher?'' Plesser asked in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   As a hypothetical question, Plesser wondered whether, if the
Supreme Court had a Web site, it could prohibit downloading by
anyone who was going to repackage and sell the information.
</P>
<P>
   In a concurring opinion, Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg emphasized
that ``once address information is in the public domain, the
statute does not restrict its use in any way.'' She also said that
while California could limit its release of government information,
it could not do so on impermissible grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``California could not, for example, release address information
only to those whose political views were in line with the party in
power,'' Ginsburg said.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice John Paul Stevens, joined by
Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, said that while he agreed that the case
presented an issue of an access restriction rather than a direct
restriction on speech, the law was so irrational as to be
unconstitutional. While California's goal was to protect personal
privacy, Stevens said, that goal could not be served by the
restriction on commercial use as long as the news media and others
could obtain the information and publish it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That the state might simply withhold the information from all
persons does not insulate its actions from constitutional
scrutiny,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Goldstein, who successfully argued the appeal for the Los
Angeles Police Department, said in an interview Tuesday that at its
simplest level, the decision meant only that ``you shouldn't go
around invalidating statutes without seeing how they work in
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Goldstein added that the online information industry's
``core concern that they'll be cut off from information in a
discriminatory way remains a live and unresolved question.''
</P>
<P>
   While six justices signed onto Rehnquist's opinion, each of the
six also wrote or joined a concurring opinion elaborating on the
chief justice's spare eight pages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
