<P>
   CHECHNYA-WARNING (Washington) _ George Robertson, NATO's
secretary-general, warns Russian leaders that their threat to kill
all residents left in the Chechen capital of Grozny on Saturday is
``utterly unacceptable.'' Russia's threat, targeted at civilians,
``is something civilized, decent people are not willing to
tolerate,'' he says. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   POSTAL-CRUSH (Washington) _ With the annual crush of holiday
mailing under way, the U.S. Postal Service announces that it has
posted its fifth consecutive profitable year. By ANDREW BROMAN.
</P>
<P>
   PEARL-HARBOR (Washington) _ A panel of historians and retired
Navy officers debate, the 58th anniversary of the Japanese raid on
Pearl Harbor, whether the Navy and Army commanders there should be
blamed for allowing Japan's successful surprise attack that brought
the United States into World War II. A thin consensus emerged among
the panelists that it was a ``government-wide failure'' that
enabled Japan to pull off one of history's most successful surprise
military attacks. By CHARLES J. LEWIS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-OIL (Washington) _ The Clinton administration asks the
Supreme Court to rule that petroleum tanker operators must comply
with federal regulations designed to prevent oil spills, not
standards set by state governments. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-RECORDS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court upholds a
California law limiting access to police records containing the
names and addresses of arrested suspects and crime victims. By a
7-2 vote, the justices said the law does not trample on the rights
of companies that would use the information to solicit business
from suspects or victims. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Undated) _ George W. Bush, in the wake of his second
debate, may be finding his winning smile may be his worst enemy
when it turns into a smirk. Political experts say it can work
against him if it becomes part of the larger picture of the ``empty
suit.'' Bush defended himself against the smirk in a news
conference that focused more on Bush's attitude than what he said
in the debate. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-ENDORSE (Washington) _ Three liberal House members from
the West Coast _ Democratic Reps. George Miller and Pete Stark of
California and Jim McDermott of Washington _ endorse Bill Bradley
for president. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
