u a BC-PROFESSOR-RESIGNS-BOS     12-07 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFESSOR-RESIGNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BU PROFESSOR WHO DIDN'T ATTRIBUTE SENTENCE QUITS POST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The professor forgot to attribute one sentence in a
lecture, and the lapse cost him his job.
</P>
<P>
   Now, colleagues at Boston University of media professor John
Schulz have rallied to his defense, complaining that the climate in
the academic world has become so frenzied that repeating even a
quick proverb can be construed as cribbing.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz, the chairman of the department of Mass Media,
Advertising, and Public Relations, resigned his administrative post
Tuesday after he admitted pulling a passage from a weekly political
magazine and using it, unattributed, in a lecture in front of 400
freshmen last week. He will keep his position as a professor.
</P>
<P>
   Some colleagues protested the resignation, noting that his
explanation was plausible _ he failed to attribute the brief quote
because he was pressed for time to finish the lecture _ and
questioning whether it was truly plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   But Schulz himself insisted that an ethical lapse, no matter how
small or unintended, must be punished.
</P>
<P>
   ``The act was accidental, and not intentional, but that is
immaterial,'' said Schulz, in his formal resignation statement to
the faculty Tuesday. ``The failure to attribute a source is a
serious offense in a university dedicated to the pursuit of truth
and in a college that is committed to teaching ethics to future
communicators.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulz, a decorated war hero and 21-year journalist with the
Voice of America, appeared as a guest lecturer in ``Perspectives in
Communication'' last week, and ended his lecture by reading a
seven-line sentence taken from an article in the Nov. 29 issue of
The Nation.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, a student posted a note in the chat room for
the course and sent a note to the dean of the School of
Communications, saying she had just read the same sentence in the
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Brent Baker called Schulz into his office Friday and asked
him about the incident. Schulz acknowledged using the passage, and
instantly said he would resign as department head.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz said he had walked out from behind the podium with a
wireless microphone, trying to project a more relaxed atmosphere in
the lecture hall. As he reached back to the podium to get the notes
where he had written down the quote, he caught a glimpse of his
watch and noticed that he was running six or seven minutes behind
the time he'd allotted for the lecture. He was eager, he said, to
leave enough time for questions and answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listening in horror, I thought, `My Gosh,' I think (the
student) is right,' '' Schulz said Tuesday, recalling his
conversation with the dean. ``I could see that watch in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident recalls another case at the BU School of
Communications eight years ago, when Dean H. Joachim Maitre was
forced to resign after the Globe reported that he had used a film
review by critic Michael Medved as a commencement speech. Maitre
remained on the faculty for several years, resigning only his
dean's position. Baker said Tuesday that he has asked Schulz to
stay on the faculty, as well, and teach his usual load of courses
in international communications.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz appeared in front of the class again Tuesday to apologize
to the students, explaining that he had indeed lifted the phrase,
which likened Italian media magnate Silvio Berlusconi to an amalgam
of American political and media figures, from George W. Bush to
Donald Trump. When he finished, the students applauded.
</P>
<P>
   But his colleagues questioned whether Schulz had to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the scheme of things, this seems very minor,'' said
communications professor Norman Moyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I tell a group of journalism students, `The job of a
newspaper is to comfort the afflicted and afflict the comfortable,'
and I don't say it's from `The Front Page' or Ben Hecht, is that
plagiarism?'' he asked. ``You try to attribute things, but when
you're speaking for an hour and a half and you're trying not to
lose the attention of your students...the whole thing just makes me
sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since it's his decision, it's hard to criticize, but in a lot
of ways I'm sorry he did. If it had been ordered by the powers that
be, I would have protested it.''
</P>
<P>
   Journalism professor Caryl Rivers questioned whether the lapse
really meets the definition of plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plagiarism implies publication. Most professors don't see
their classroom lectures as publications, and do not say, what have
I annotated, what have I cited,'' she said. ``It's very different
from when we give a formal lecture. A classroom lecture, you want
to be a freewheeling one. Do you have to worry, `Did I have a
source for everything I said?' That's one of the questions being
asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said he accepted the resignation with regret, and the
``utmost'' respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reason the faculty is so upset is that we respect
John so much,'' he said. ``They're sort of falling to both sides of
the issue. They have a lot of respect for someone who would stand
up and teach the students that there's no double standard for
faculty and students. You just don't see this much in America
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulz himself pushed aside any questions about whether this is
really plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing in the definition that says `purposeful' or
`accidental,' '' he said. ``It's just, `misrepresenting of others'
works or ideas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 2016EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
