<HEADER>
A2101 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-FREEAGENTS     12-07 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-FREEAGENTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deadline looms as Braves free agents wait
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Faced with losing up to 20 percent of its postseason
roster in one swoop, the Atlanta Braves played it close to the vest
Tuesday night. As close as rules allow.
</P>
<P>
   The National League champions withheld making formal arbitration
offers to their free agent players until the midnight deadline,
leaving the fate of six players uncertain to the last moment.
</P>
<P>
   While the Braves are hardly expected to make an arbitration
offer to retain 40-year-old Otis Nixon, the team faces a critical
decision on whether to keep outfielder Gerald Williams. Other
Braves who have filed for free agency but can be retained with an
offer to arbitrate a 2000 salary include shortstop Jose Hernandez,
outfielder-first baseman Brian Hunter, catcher Greg Myers and
right-handed reliever Rudy Seanez.
</P>
<P>
   All teams faced the midnight deadline for offering players who
had filed for free agency an opportunity for arbitration. Those
players have until Dec. 19 to accept the offer, or are subsequently
prevented from negotiating with their former clubs until May 1.
</P>
<P>
   All but Seanez were on Atlanta's postseason roster last October
and Seanez would have been, had it not been for August elbow
surgery. With 15 veterans already under contract, the Braves can
help determine the veteran makeup of the 2000 roster by how many
arbitration offers it makes.
</P>
<P>
   Williams remains the most important component, after emerging as
a critical player when he was moved to a full-time leadoff hitter
Aug. 5. The Braves finished 39-14 with Williams batting first and
while he is less than a prototypical No. 1 hitter (.339 onbase
percentage), his value grew higher as the season wore on.
</P>
<P>
   He may able to more than triple his $1.4 million 1999 salary on
the open market. As an alternative, the Braves are keeping close
watch on prospect outfielder George Lombard, who was hitting .278
in the Venezuelan Winter League.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
