<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CHECHNYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING WITH FIRE IN CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Russia's war to recapture Chechnya has been waged from the start
with a blatant indifference to the suffering of civilians, but
there is something particularly ominous about the ultimatum the
Russian military command has issued to civilians trapped in the
city of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   During a break in the bombing and shelling of the Chechen
capital, leaflets were dropped warning civilians to leave the
encircled city before this Saturday ``by any means possible.'' The
accompanying threat could not have been more chilling. ``Only in
this way,'' the leaflet said, ``will you be able to avoid death.''
</P>
<P>
   This threat would be bad enough if it meant merely that the
current Russian tactic of standing off and firing bombs, shells,
and rockets into Grozny will continue. There have been signs,
however, that something much more lethal is being planned _ a
resort to terror weapons that would not only violate the 1949
Geneva Convention against the targeting of civilians but would
transform Russia into a rogue state comparable to Saddam Hussein's
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Last month a former US national security adviser, Zbigniew
Brzezinski, citing Central European intelligence sources, wrote in
The Wall Street Journal of a Russian plan to use fuel-air
explosives and chemical weapons to exterminate large numbers of
Chechens. Last week the same warning came from Pavel Felgenhauer,
who is known for his longstanding contacts in the Russian military
command and who was defense analyst for many years in Red Star, the
paper of the Red Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sources in the Russian military say plans are made to use
aerosol explosive bombs, also known as `vacuum bombs,' in Grozny,''
Felgenhauer wrote last Thursday in the Moscow Times. These bombs
form flammable clouds that are then ignited and can kill everyone
hiding in underground bunkers built in Grozny during Soviet times
to withstand a nuclear attack. If these weapons ``don't dislodge
the Chechen fighters from Grozny, other, even more powerful weapons
of mass destruction may be considered,'' Felgenhauer warned.
</P>
<P>
   A story that the Chechens are preparing to use nerve gas against
Russian forces _ a rumor spread by Russian intelligence and
recycled in the Russian press _ ``may be a pretext for the Russian
military to begin a gas attack themselves and to blame it on the
Chechens beforehand,'' Felgenhauer reported. He explained that the
rumor was preposterous because the Chechens do not have access to
Russian nerve gas stockpiles, cannot mass-produce chemical agents,
and lack an effective delivery system for chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   A resort to weapons of mass destruction would come as the
logical culmination of Russia's tactics in Chechnya. It has been
clear for some time that Russian political leaders and military
officers want to avoid the calamitous tactics of the 1994-96 war in
Chechnya. Russian soldiers will not be sent into Grozny to wage
urban guerrilla warfare against Chechen fighters.
</P>
<P>
   It is equally clear that the Kremlin's anti-Chechen and
antiterrorist propaganda has prepared the Russian public to accept
the most inhumane methods to expunge Chechen ``banditry'' and
Chechen independence. The Clinton administration and its allies
should be no less clear in warning the Kremlin not to use weapons
of mass destruction in Chechnya.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
