</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROYAL-FALSTAFF-OPERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPSY FALSTAFF TOASTS A NEW COVENT GARDEN
</HEADLINE>
 (mg) 
By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Its housewarmings completed, its 30-month renovation
almost so, the Royal Opera House opened on Monday night with a new
production of Verdi's ``Falstaff.'' Behind it, or so the company
hoped, are years of financial turmoil, questionable management and
a creaky if endearing physical plant.
</P>
<P>
   From the listener's point of view the work is done. The theater
has the glow of gilt and red plush without the total loss of
patina. The glassed-in Floral Hall adjacent to the Covent Garden
site offers open spaces suitable for serious milling and personal
display at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   News that construction work was still going on backstage came
indirectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Le Grand Macabre,'' the Ligeti opera scheduled to open in a
few days, had been canceled. ``Falstaff,'' in Graham Vick's jokey
staging, passed without serious incident, though rumors coming out
of rehearsals had predicted otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Vick and his production team of Paul Brown, Thomas Webster and
Ron Howell made sure our eyes did not forget the centrality of
tipsiness to this compact beauty of an opera from Verdi's old age.
</P>
<P>
   Scene 1 was bathed in red, and so steeply raked and bowed was
the stage that players threaten to slide feet first into the
orchestra pit. Not only were the abilities to sing and act
required, but so was the sureness of the mountain goat.
</P>
<P>
   The scene changes were clever. Beds inflated and deflated,
appearing and disappearing _ as do people and props _ through
trapdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Scene 2 was a charming abstraction of rolling green hills; lemon
trees rose like periscopes from the stage floor. In the laundry
basket sequence, acrobats were busy.
</P>
<P>
   Vick was eventually the victim of his own cleverness.
</P>
<P>
   The pranks and surreal look in Act III wore out their welcome.
The production had its moments of high and provocative fun, but
Falstaff himself, who is after all more tragicomic than ridiculous,
seemed a little out of place in the middle of all the high jinks.
</P>
<P>
   He was played, superbly, by Bryn Terfel. The body makeup helped,
but it was Terfel's manner that turned him from young singer to
tired lothario. The diction was extraordinary. The voice never
forced, never faltered. The singers around him were first rate:
Barbara Frittoli, Desiree Rancatore, Bernadette Manca di Nissa and
Diane Montague as Verdi's quartet of women, and the excellent
Roberto Frontali as Ford.
</P>
<P>
   The lightness of Kenneth Tarver's tenor as Fenton did not matter
in a house that continually surprises the infrequent visitor with
its paradox of grandness and intimacy. Bernard Haitink conducted
with his customary muscle and enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Falstaff'' was preceded by a gala evening on Wednesday that
was repeated on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Split between opera and dance, the program offered different
meanings of the word gala. Music told us that opera was serious
business and that patrons ought not to forget it. Dance gave the
opinion that galas were a form of flattery: Here are snippets of
what we do best. Here is what has endeared us to you.
</P>
<P>
   The musical half, taken up largely by scenes from Wagner and
Beethoven, verged on grimness, flattered the operatic voice not at
all. ``Die Walkure'' (here the end of Act I) was vocally a labor of
love but labor nonetheless. Deborah Polaski's bruising,
hard-working soprano showed the wear of her long and profitable
career in the Wagner repertory. Placido Domingo worked hard to make
Siegmund sound liquid, almost Italian.
</P>
<P>
   The finale of ``Fidelio'' had little to do with singing at all.
Beethoven bends the human voice against its will to his musical
designs. The choruses were thrilling and the vocal counterpoint
ingenious, but one can think of more succulent advertisements for
the new Royal Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's gala made it clear that this was an opera house, not
a concert hall. The house orchestra could barely fit onstage, with
string players spilling on either side. Live and present in the pit
for ``Falstaff,'' the instruments sounded blunt and remote in their
elevated state. Singers, equally live and present on Monday, stood
out beyond the proscenium and were not easy to hear.
</P>
<P>
   The wonderful Overture to Weber's ``Oberon'' at the start
enjoyed soft, lovely (and extremely difficult) horn playing. The
ballet excerpts, so swiftly managed and gracefully organized,
delighted the audience. Next to them the medium of opera was made
to sound glum and puritanical.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 2023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
