<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-CEOS-COX     12-07 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-CEOS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CEOs don't stick around
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The penthouse office is a vulnerable and volatile
place to be these days.
</P>
<P>
   Turnover at the top has been rampant most of this decade, as
chief executive officers at more than half of the nation's Fortune
500 firms have departed. The latest to join the long list of
short-term CEOs is Coca-Cola Chairman and Chief Executive M.
Douglas Ivester, who will be leaving in April after 2 1/2 years in
the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``CEOs are changing like baseball managers,'' said John
Challenger, head of Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas, an international
outplacement firm that tracks workplace trends. ``The focus and
pressure is so intense now. They're under so much pressure today to
meet high earnings expectations that are jacked up quarter by
quarter. They're also facing much more activist boards.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all are being forced out. Others _ many of them years
younger than their predecessors _ are cashing in lucrative stock
options and leaving for even richer career paths or new challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Since August, some 200 CEOs have retired, switched jobs or been
ousted. Last month alone, 70 CEOs _ roughly three each business day
_ left their companies, up from 54 in October, according to
Challenger.
</P>
<P>
   In the revolving-door world of the new executive suite,
long-reigning CEOs _ like General Electric's Jack Welch and
Ivester's predecessor, the late Roberto Goizueta _ are increasingly
rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see the dynastic reign anymore,'' says Jeffrey
Sonnenfeld, an Atlanta expert on CEOs who last year headed a panel
commissioned by the National Association of Corporate Directors to
examine CEO succession.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a shift in the (work) ethic regarding the tenure and
the desires of senior executives,'' said Paul Winum, Atlanta-based
managing director of RHR International, a firm that has management
psychologists who work with top management around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The climb to the top is no longer marked by longevity at one
company.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, time at the top is short _ and so is the patience of
highly ambitious CEOs looking for continual challenges and for
investor-minded corporate boards intent on improving record
performances.
</P>
<P>
   The average CEO stays less than five years now vs. eight to 10
years in the 1980s, according to SpencerStuart, an executive search
firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it was because of forced resignations,'' said
Alexandra LaJoux, research director for the Washington-based
National Association of Corporate Directors. ``Now, it's because
they're wealthy and they can jump to better and better
compensation. There's a great demand for CEOs. They're not going
out to pasture or to be with their grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their predecessors, many of today's top executives reach
the pinnacle of their careers relatively early.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual today for a person to be appointed CEO of a
major corporation in their 30s and 40s, said Carl Sloane, a Harvard
Business School professor of business administration. ``It's no
longer reserved for gray hairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the ambitious executive elite gets antsy after a
few years in the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people at the top have enjoyed tremendous financial
benefits, which have been related to the tremendous growth in their
companies, and the compensation levels are extremely lucrative,''
said Winum.
</P>
<P>
   CEO compensation has come under fire, especially this decade, as
top executives' pay has far outpaced ordinary workers' incomes.
Some shareholders and labor unions have complained for years that
even the worst-performing CEOs are paid handsomely.
</P>
<P>
   Executive compensation, frequently including stock options, has
paralleled the rise in the stock market. As a result, those
lucrative packages have helped many top executives walk away
wealthy at a relatively young age.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure to deliver on analysts' expectations quarter
after quarter after quarter becomes very wearing,'' said Paul
Lapides, director of the Corporate Governance Center at Kennesaw
State University. ``CEOs more so than in the past are finding
themselves wearier keeping up with those expectations over longer
periods of time. So after two, three or four years, a CEO may
decide to move on to a different career challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of them are walking away with millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester's stock holdings, for example, are worth $188 million.
Similarly, Carl Ware, head of Coca-Cola's Africa Group who recently
announced he was leaving at the end of 2000, will get $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compensation, especially at Coca-Cola, has been extremely
lucrative for executives,'' notes Judith Fischer, managing director
of Executive Compensation Advisory Services in Alexandria, Va.
Fischer also noted that many executives ``break out of brick and
mortar (industries) and enter into high-tech start-up businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   George Shaheen, former chief executive of Andersen Consulting,
in September became head of Webvan, an Internet grocer.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, corporate boards _ determined not to repeat the
messy showdowns with CEOs that plagued companies such as General
Motors Corp., Sears, Kodak and Kmart earlier this decade _ have
taken more strident roles and have put top management on short
leashes.
</P>
<P>
   If CEOs can't cut it, boards will cut them loose. ``It's very
rare that you see cronyism between boards and the CEO,'' Sonnenfeld
said. ``There was a lot more protection in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Joyner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 2028EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
