s e BC-LOAMY-ART-$ADV12-NYT &LR;      12-07 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOAMY-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOAMY ART IN NEED OF COSMETIC RAKING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 William Harris writes about avant-garde art, dance and theater.  
 By WILLIAM HARRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If outdoor earthworks are difficult to preserve, an
``interior earth sculpture,'' which is how the conceptual artist
Walter De Maria described his 1977 installation in a building in
Manhattan, has its own upkeep demands. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two years ago, De Maria transformed a desirable
3,600-square-foot piece of SoHo real estate into something useless.
``The New York Earth Room'' is 250 cubic yards of earth, piled 22
inches deep. It was introduced at what was then the Heiner
Friedrich Gallery and was intended to be the gallery's last show.
</P>
<P>
   Friedrich, who went on to help found the Dia Center for the
Arts, left the heaps of dirt in situ. In 1980, Dia decided to
reopen the installation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today, the work has art historical significance and also
provides a welcome respite from the shopaholics on SoHo's crowded
streets. Some 10,000 people visit the piece annually. One can't
walk on it _ a glass barrier contains the earth and keeps people
out _ but a loamy smell definitely permeates the space.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can ask questions of Bill Dilworth, the project's
caretaker-curator for the last decade. He's there every Wednesday
through Saturday, from noon to 6 p.m. Dilworth, 45, can supply
arcana like the field from which the dirt was gathered, the
landscaping company that sifted it and the fact that the former
factory space in which it is housed was designed to hold 120 pounds
per square foot. ``The Earth Room,'' says Dilworth, ``breaks down
to 77 pounds per square foot.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once a week, he waters and rakes it to keep the piece looking
fresh and fertile. In the summer when the space is closed, Dilworth
digs holes in selected spots to make sure there is no damage to the
floor. ``Micro-organisms survive in it,'' he says. ``Mushrooms
grow. They used to come up more regularly than they do now. I ate
them, and they were delicious.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dia maintains two additional De Maria installations. ``The
Broken Kilometer,'' comprising 500 solid-brass rods, has been
housed in SoHo since 1979. (Guess what needs to be polished?)
``Lightning Field,'' 1977, a one-mile-by-one-kilometer outdoor
sculpture made up of 400 stainless-steel poles, in Quemado, N.M.,
is low-maintenance by De Maria standards. Still, lightning strikes
the poles very occasionally, and sometimes someone has to repair a
bend or a melted tip.
</P>
<P>
   All earthworks need upkeep of some sort. There is one exception
to that rule, however: Robert Smithson's famed ``Spiral Jetty'' of
1970, which has been submerged for years in the Great Salt Lake in
Utah.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 2028EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
