<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2111 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PLAIN-LANGUAGE-ART-2T     12-07 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAIN-LANGUAGE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC EDICT REVIVES PUSH FOR SHORT SENTENCES AND PLAIN PROSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md., Texas, N.J.) (ART ADV: A photo, NYT21, has been sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A streamlining process designed to add value for
consumers of content by reducing their comprehension experience is
currently being efforted by public-sector entities and
bleeding-edge corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Both government agencies and some companies are now trying to
use clearer, simpler writing than they did in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Ah-ha!
</P>
<P>
   The plain-language movement is enjoying a resurgence, and this
time it could have staying power. Disdaining jargon and celebrating
short, conversational sentences with active verbs, the latest
effort began two years ago when the Securities and Exchange
Commission ordered mutual fund companies to rewrite their
prospectuses by Dec. 1, 1999. With the help of consultants, the
movement has expanded to other government agencies and to companies
like Ford Motor and Charles Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton instructed federal agencies last year to
rewrite by 2002 all documents that the public sees. The Food and
Drug Administration this year mandated that labels on
over-the-counter drugs be easier to understand by 2005. The SEC is
mulling similar rules for two popular financial products sold by
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the push is a recognition that new sources of information
_ like the Internet, 24-hour cable television and an explosion in
junk mail _ have overwhelmed people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volume of information that people get and the speed at
which they get it has grown exponentially,'' said Irene A. Etzkorn,
an executive vice president at Siegel &AMP; Gale, a New York consulting
firm. She oversees the division that rips up and rewrites
documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people can't quickly discern information,'' she added,
``they discard it.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials hope their use of simple language will make
Americans more likely to trust what they hear from Washington.
Marketers, for their part, see a golden opportunity to rise above
the cacophony and convince consumers that they should buy a
product. Plain English can also help corporate managers explain
their company's strategy to employees and thereby increase
workplace efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, simpler writing bolsters revenue and cuts costs.
The Veterans Benefits Administration, for example, said it expected
to save about $500,000 a year because, after training employees in
its life insurance division how to write more clearly, the response
rate on one of its letters shot up to 62 percent, from about 35
percent. One telecommunications company, which Ms. Etzkorn declined
to identify, came to Siegel &AMP; Gale after its confusing bills caused
cellular-phone customers to spend an average of 45 minutes a month
talking to a service center, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At its worst, the detractors of plain English say that it can
dumb down documents, making them less accurate or less useful to
the experts who make up much of their audience.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the debate over sparse language is not new.
Aristotle, Renaissance philosophers, the authors William Strunk Jr.
and E.B. White and the investor Warren E. Buffett have all weighed
in on the topic. Others, including some in the Carter
administration, made pushes to encourage plain English that did not
stick.
</P>
<P>
   But today's effort is more sustained, partly because it
intersects with several economic trends that favor it. Deregulation
can cause onetime monopolies like local phone companies to want to
communicate with their customers more clearly. The Internet forces
marketers to think about presenting information in catchy new ways.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the SEC's ruling on prospectuses has created a cottage
industry of plain-language consultants, like Simplify in New York
and Firehouse Communications in Malden, Mass., that are seeking to
drum up new business by rewriting annual reports, 401(k) statements
and financial-services brochures. Siegel &AMP; Gale, which pioneered
the business almost three decades ago, has seen its document group
double in size since 1996. Some big law firms have also tried to
become experts in the area.
</P>
<P>
   When the consultants finish with a report, the differences can
be stark. Consider Texaco, whose executives began to think more
carefully about how they write after hearing about the SEC's ruling
on mutual funds. Many sections of their 1996 annual report _ the
last before their plain-language initiative _ appear as a sea of
uninterrupted text, highlighted by bureaucratic words (heretofore)
and oil-industry jargon (maturing fields).
</P>
<P>
   Try wading through this one: ``Texaco's total cash provided by
operating activities of $3.8 billion for the year 1996 reflected
strong operational earnings and a net inflow of $375 million,
primarily comprised of a cash dividend from Caltex (related to the
sale of Caltex' interest in NPRC), proceeds from advanced payments
on long-term natural gas sales agreements and the collection of
nonrecurring receivables (primarily insurance recoveries relating
to environmental matters), which were partially offset by payments
related to litigation and other matters.''
</P>
<P>
   If you picked up the report, said Joseph DeNardo, a Texaco
accountant and one its authors, ``you'd want to throw the book
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent annual report, by contrast, features narrow
columns of text, which are easier to read, and short, explanatory
sentences. Many sections start with a definition, rather than a
string of revenue numbers: ``In our upstream business, we explore
for, find, produce and sell crude oil, natural gas liquids and
natural gas.''
</P>
<P>
   The first sentence of the letter from Peter I. Bijur, the
company's chairman, contains 15 words, down from 51 two years ago _
despite the hard times for the oil industry that might have given
him reason to obfuscate Texaco's 78 percent decline in net income.
</P>
<P>
   Making such changes is not easy, however. ``People think it's
like a translation, that you turn big words into small words.
That's not it at all,'' said William M. Lutz, an English professor
at Rutgers University in Camden, N.J., and perhaps the most famous
plain-language advocate today. He has a consulting business and
earlier this year published ``Doublespeak Defined'' (HarperCollins,
1999), a dictionary of jargon.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Lutz joined two Postal Service employees at the
agency's headquarters in Washington to make final changes in its
annual report. They had sent a rough draft to 40 of the agency's
top officials and were now squirreled away in a cubicle the size of
a conference room, surrounded by Thanksgiving leftovers and
McDonald's wrappers, scribbling away and dodging yet more
bureaucratic bullets. Colleagues kept stopping to drop off their
own suggestions. One manager debated which preposition to use in
one sentence. Their intentions were usually good, said R. Timothy
MacDonald, one of the writers, but convoluted language crept in.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `You have to be perfect and exact and include
every little nuance,''' MacDonald said. ``Finally, you've got this
beast.''
</P>
<P>
   So he and a colleague, alongside Lutz, sifted through every
comment, at one point wrangling for 20 minutes over a sentence.
Lutz left at 7 p.m. to take a train to Philadelphia so he could
teach a class the next day. MacDonald stayed at the office until
1:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody will confuse the final product with an E.B. White essay,
but the emphasis on simplicity is apparent throughout the report.
It uses ``we'' and ``our,'' rather than ``the Service'' and
``USPS's.'' The section on transportation is only 27 lines, down
from 42 last year, because many of the statistics that had appeared
in long-winded sentences are now part of a chart.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Such struggles are common, particularly because the changes
often involve blunt criticism. ``There was a tremendous objection
to this at the beginning,'' DeNardo of Texaco said. Almost three
years later, though, the practice has become ingrained, and some
managers use plain language even in internal memos, he added.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Similar changes have happened at Schwab and at American Century
Investments, both of which have simplified many documents besides
prospectuses. When employees ``saw we could do this with something
as complicated as a prospectus, there was a shift in perspective,''
said Roberta Laughlin, American Century's manager for education and
guidance. ``It's almost a mantra now.''
</P>
<P>
   Plain-language advocates hope they can next persuade phone and
cable companies to simplify their materials as they begin competing
with one another. Already, AT&AMP;T has hired Siegel &AMP; Gale to design
monthly bills that the company sends separately from local phone
companies.
</P>
<P>
   But with a few notable exceptions _ among them the annual report
by Texaco and sales and leasing contracts for Ford cars _ plain
language is not yet common outside of the government and the
financial-services industry. Even in finance, said Paula R. David,
the director of client marketing at the Boston consulting firm,
Funds Distributor Inc., ``We had expected the industry to embrace
this more than it did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority decided merely to comply'' with the SEC rules
rather than rewrite all of their documents, Ms. David said.
</P>
<P>
   The language mavens say that raises a disquieting question,
particularly in the ninth year of an economic expansion: If a
recession comes, will companies decide that cutting consulting
costs is more important than cutting words? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
