u f BC-COKE-MAIN-COX     12-07 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke stock sinks after Ivester's retirement announcement
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nearly every company pays the price on Wall Street
when it's the subject of unexpected and disappointing news.
</P>
<P>
   But for Coca-Cola, known over the years for running a smooth
operation with stellar management and predictable performance, the
price appears to be quite high when it drops a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive day Tuesday, the company's stock got
hammered after news that Chairman and Chief Executive M. Douglas
Ivester will retire in April, passing the torch to Douglas Daft.
</P>
<P>
   Shares fell 6.25 percent, or $4, to close at $60.
</P>
<P>
   The selling accelerated Tuesday as more than 18 million shares
changed hands, compared with about 13 million Monday. That far
surpasses the average daily volume of about 4.4 million shares
during the past six months.
</P>
<P>
   Since Monday's announcement, the stock has lost 12 percent of
its value.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really extraordinary, what's happened,'' said Manny
Goldman, global beverage analyst with Merrill Lynch. ``It's the
perception of management uncertainty that I think has hurt the
stock. When push comes to shove, it's management that counts,
whether it's Coca-Cola or Intel.''
</P>
<P>
   Daft, whose main experience with the company has been in Asia,
is the company's new president and chief operating officer. He is
slated to succeed Ivester in the top spot at the annual shareholder
meeting in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have great confidence in Doug Daft,'' analyst Andrew Conway
of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter wrote Tuesday in a research report.
``However, Mr. Daft has a huge job in transitioning to his new
role. We do not believe he has the breadth of experience that Mr.
Ivester has accumulated.''
</P>
<P>
   Conway, who downgraded the stock to ``neutral'' from
``outperform,'' said it will take time for Daft to become more
familiar with regions for which he has not been responsible,
including the Americas and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the reasons Ivester is scheduled to stay at the
helm until April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug Ivester and Doug Daft will be working together closely
for the next few months in order to ensure a thorough transition,''
said company spokesman Ben Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   That transition will be on the minds of the company's board of
directors when it meets next Wednesday in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the company's troubles on Wall Street is concern about
whether Ivester's retirement means its financial rebound may be
weaker or slower than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Conway, for example, predicts next year's growth in case sales
will be 5 percent _ still well below the company's historical
target of 7 percent to 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, investors looked at Coca-Cola as a company that
can grow earnings from now until the end of time,'' Goldman said.
``That perception has been diminished. ... Coke has had
earnings-per-share growth in the mid-teens or higher for many
years. Now people are questioning that going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
