A2114 &Cx1f; tad-z
b p BC-MCCAIN-DEFENSE-COX     12-07 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-DEFENSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain touts military pay hike
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) sketched out a plan
for national defense Tuesday that would boost soldiers' morale by
fattening their wallets.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential candidate proposed salary increases
and tax cuts for men and women in the armed forces that would cost
$5.7 billion over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   The package is aimed at 12,000 enlisted personnel who need food
stamps and other aid to make ends meet, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a stain upon the nation's honor that should shame us
all,'' McCain said, using the 58th anniversary of the Japanese
attack on Pearl Harbor to talk about military preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed both Democrats and Republicans for allowing a
deterioration of the military and pledged to get rid of unneeded
defense programs, including the Georgia-built C-130J transport
plane, to pay for higher wages and a more efficient fighting force.
</P>
<P>
   McCain continued to lavish attention on New Hampshire as a new
poll Tuesday showed him narrowly leading Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Reuters/WHDH-TV poll showed McCain leading Bush 35 percent
to 32 percent. The difference is within the the poll's margin of
error of 4.7 percent, but the survey is significant because McCain
trailed Bush by 19 points in the same organizations' poll in
October.
</P>
<P>
   McCain appeared to benefit from his performance in the Dec. 2
debate in New Hampshire, the first to include Bush, according to
the poll.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's outline for the military was the second in a
string of policy speeches he is giving in December.
</P>
<P>
   As in his talk on foreign affairs last week, McCain called for
building a missile defense system that would also be extended to
American allies around the globe. He acknowledged that such a
system would violate the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty with
the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would try to negotiate with the Russians to modify
it, but that he would withdraw from the treaty if the Russians
refused.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also discussed his ``rogue-state rollback,'' a plan to
use a variety of means including covert military aid to push for
new leaders in Iraq, North Korea and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's most specific proposal was to increase military pay
3 percent a year for the next three years, on top of the 4.8
percent raise in the new federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, men and women stationed overseas would not have to
pay federal income taxes, McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modernizing weapons systems is important, but personnel issues
must come first,'' McCain said in remarks prepared for delivery
Tuesday night in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The pay increase would cost $4.3 billion over three years, while
the tax break would come to $800 million a year, McCain spokeswoman
Nancy Ives said.
</P>
<P>
   Talking to reporters following a speech at the Concord Rotary
Club, McCain actually spoke of a larger salary increase, totaling
16 percent over four years. Ives said he used the wrong numbers.
</P>
<P>
   McCain traveled to New York to receive the Intrepid Freedom
Award at the Intrepid Sea Air Space Museum. He served aboard the
aircraft carrier in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
