<HEADER>
A2115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MARS-MISTAKES-NYT &LR;      12-07 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-MISTAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SAY STINTING OF TIME, PEOPLE AND MONEY LED TO LOST MARS
MISSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MARS-LANDER) 
(sw) 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A string of embarrassing mistakes that doomed the $125 million
Mars Climate Orbiter in September may have helped pave the way for
the disappearance this week of the $165 million Mars Polar Lander,
NASA officials and private experts said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
issued a blistering 45-page report on the loss of the climate
orbiter, the first of two spacecraft meant to renew NASA's
exploratory push this year to the red planet. The report's findings
and recommendations included suggested ways to avert disaster with
the sister craft, which has fallen silent since trying to make its
planned landing on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the November report found potential problems
in the complexity of the lander's engines and called for much
last-minute polishing and repairing to try to increase the odds of
a safe touchdown near the Martian south pole.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, in light of the new failure, experts inside and
outside the space agency said that common troubles in the sister
programs and perhaps the anticipated engine woes accounted for the
current ominous silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fell into cutting too many corners,'' a senior official at
the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, which designed the two
spacecraft, said in an interview. ``We have to be smarter.''
</P>
<P>
   John E. Pike, head of space policy at the Federation of American
Scientists, a Washington group, said NASA's climate orbiter
investigation showed that the Mars program had been desperately
short of time, personnel and money, with designers pushed to the
breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all seen this,'' Pike said. ``Anybody who has tried to
do too much work without enough people immediately recognizes the
symptoms. Stuff doesn't get done. Things fail.''
</P>
<P>
   The common problem behind the setbacks, Pike added, ``is some
combination of inadequate funding and inadequate management
preparation for low-budget missions.''
</P>
<P>
   The analysis of the first failed mission found poor training,
communication and support for the spacecraft team. Such failings,
experts said, will be key suspects in the new investigation as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the successful 1997 Mars Pathfinder mission, which the
Jet Propulsion Laboratory built and ran, the Mars Climate Orbiter
and Mars Polar Lander were designed by the Pasadena laboratory but,
in a cost-cutting move, built by Lockheed Martin Astronautics of
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The current pair of lost spacecraft cost about half as much as
their predecessors, the $270 million Pathfinder and its companion
orbiter, the $300 million Mars Global Surveyor.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation into the recent climate orbiter failure was
conducted by a nine-member NASA panel led by Arthur G. Stephenson
of the Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Ala., and its
findings were made public on Nov. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, painting a picture of widespread design and
management woes, cited not only a single main culprit but eight
contributing factors ``that led directly or indirectly to the loss
of the spacecraft.''
</P>
<P>
   A mixup between English and metric units in navigation data was
cited as the main reason the spacecraft went off course, and
probably to its destruction, as it was trying to orbit Mars in
September. All radio contact with the craft was lost.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing flaws cited by the panel included insufficient team
training, undetected errors in computer models of thruster firings,
failures of the navigation team to know the spacecraft's
orientation in space, inadequate effort by system engineers to
track and double-check all mission aspects, a tendency for
communications to be too informal, failure to weigh the need for an
additional engine firing and the overworking of the navigation
team.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators also faulted communications between the design
team at the Pasadena laboratory and the spacecraft builders in
Denver, calling some of the technical dialogues ``inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the panel made eight observations and
recommendations about the Mars Polar Lander in a bid to ward off
related failures. Several significant ones centered on the engines
and the lander's descent.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the panel warned that the hydrazine fuel for the
lander's retrorockets might freeze in space, producing ignition
delays, irregular pulses and possibly leading to a topsy-turvy
landing.
</P>
<P>
   The panel suggested that fuel-line heaters be turned on early to
begin warming the hydrazine, a precaution that NASA officials said
on Tuesday was taken before the lander began its descent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also expressed worry that the lander's 12 thrusters
had to act ``in unison to ensure a stable descent,'' and that such
a complex feat had never been tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be recognized that under extreme, worst-case
conditions,'' the panel said, ``some thrusters could produce near
zero thrust and some could produce nearly twice the expected
thrust.''
</P>
<P>
   It called for the design team to thoroughly review descent
preparations ``because of the extreme complexity of this landing
maneuver.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edward Stone, the Jet Propulsion Laboratory's director, said
in reaction to the November report that the laboratory had
``mobilized the very best talent'' to fix identified flaws.
``Special attention,'' he said, ``is being directed at navigation
and propulsion issues.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a member of the reporting panel said its findings
were ``very valid'' in light of the new failure and were ``the
beginning of what we're doing'' by way of conducting an intensified
probe.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edward Weiler, NASA's head of space science, told reporters
on Tuesday that a formal investigation of the polar lander
disappearance would include many experts who had investigated the
loss of the orbiter.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the particular kind of navigation error that
doomed the Mars Climate Orbiter in September was clearly not to
blame in the current vanishing act, since all signs in the final
hours and minutes of mission indicated that the Mars probe was
right on target.
</P>
<P>
   However, he added that factors like quality control would be
looked into carefully in the new investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's off the table,'' Weiler said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
