<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2116 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-METROPOLITAN-OPERA-AR     12-07 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METROPOLITAN-OPERA-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MET AS A DRAMA IN ITSELF  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Characterizing New York City in a phrase or a
sentence is usually the activity of people who don't live here.
Those who do live here realize the vastness and the endless
contradiction of this wonderful, if trying, place and leave the
pronouncements to visitors. One description, however, does seem to
apply: ``world capital of success; world capital of failure.''
</P>
<P>
   A metaphor and microcosm of such a New York is certainly the
Metropolitan Opera, if indeed an operation so big can be called a
microcosm of anything. So large are its resources, so intricate its
workings and so wide its ambitions that the triumphs take on a
special profile, while the less than glorious hours present a
target unusually hittable by those who do not especially wish the
house well.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Met's ups and downs is a prime entertainment for
any music-loving city dweller. Though many call the house's vision
dull, its week-by-week operation offers plenty to chew on. Wagner's
``Tristan und Isolde,'' now near the end of its limited run, has
been a considerable success.
</P>
<P>
   Assembled were Jane Eaglen and Ben Heppner, two principals who
represent the present and the future of an opera notoriously hard
to cast. With them was one of the important Wagner conductors of
the century, James Levine, and a pit orchestra as good as any in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Levine's ``Tristan,'' like much of his Wagner, is very slow, but
it was salutary to surrender to a different point of view and
follow it to a conclusion: a trip worth taking.
</P>
<P>
   In this production, high-resolution reproductions of Romantic
realism are abandoned in favor of something more abstract and
compact. Geometry replaces trees and rocks. Dieter Dorn creates
stage pictures that are unadorned and filled with a dignified
quietude. The Met's Tristan and Isolde are very big people, and yet
with their tenderest moments cast in silhouette and shadow, the
music of Act II floats largely free of corporeal references, and
the stage becomes true to both eye and ear.
</P>
<P>
   Three or four years ago, I would have agreed that Ms. Eaglen and
Heppner were more Wagnerian voices than Wagnerian singers. I think
that with this ``Tristan,'' the passage from technique to pure
music has largely been made. We seem to be climbing out of the
trough of mediocre singing that has trapped opera for almost a
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking still is an Italian-repertory tenor to succeed Luciano
Pavarotti and Placido Domingo, but there is youth and strength
nearly everywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The triumph of this ``Tristan,'' and I don't think triumph is
too strong a word, seems startling next to Boito's ``Mefistofele,''
a few weeks prior. The Met bears no original responsibility for
this seedy affair, which arrived here as a loaner from a consortium
of other opera companies. But one wonders how it was let inside at
all.
</P>
<P>
   The opera, despite a few soaring moments, is a little vulgar to
begin with. The present production had made its way from Europe
across much of the United States and, along the way, settled into a
vague dilapidation. Its garishness, which no amount of age and
fading can expunge, includes troupes of color-coded angels and
devils with wings and horns.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of this production created a lose-lose proposition.
For if the humor is unintentional, they are naive; if it is
intentional, they become something worse: cynical.
</P>
<P>
   A cultural machine as big as the Met's necessarily generates
politics and business as well as art. ``Mefistofele'' is at the Met
because of who took the title role. Samuel Ramey has made a
subspecialty of the part, and the current production has traveled
with him, providing its star not quite a one-man show but something
close to it.
</P>
<P>
   Ramey is a distinguished performer, and who is to deny him? His
international career is huge, but he is faithful to his American
roots and more particularly to the Met. He does the role well, and
the house can please a loyal son and his fans without the expense
of building a production of its own.
</P>
<P>
   At the performance I saw, the audience had a good time, but by
any measure this is not the quality of opera Metgoers are used to.
Put it down, perhaps, to the pressures of a repertory house: seven
performances, six days, a week.
</P>
<P>
   Some productions are just bad judgment to begin with, but in the
case of singers, the margins for error are thin indeed. Sudden
illness can tear a hole in an otherwise luxurious event, one that
no substitute can adequately fill. It happened with Verdi's
``Traviata'' last year, when multiple cancellations left the house
with upscale sets and mediocre or inappropriate singers wandering
around them.
</P>
<P>
   Second casts, the singers who relieve first-string operatives at
later performances of a run, can be unrelievable disasters,
especially at the prices the house is obliged to charge. One Met
official told me in a moment of weakness that there were evenings
when he wished he could simply cancel the performance and go home.
But for a financially self-sustaining operation like the Met, a
dark house means serious money trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the wonderful evenings spent in this house: at
Tchaikovsky's ``Queen of Spades,'' Britten's ``Death in Venice''
and ``Billy Budd,'' or Offenbach's ``Tales of Hoffmann.'' Now,
after the elaborate cleverness of John Corigliano's ``Ghosts of
Versailles'' and the general paleness of Philip Glass' ``Voyage,''
the Met tries a new American opera again, this time with John
Harbison's ``Great Gatsby.'' Good or bad, we won't be bored.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
