<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2118 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RAC-PINCAY-TEX     12-07 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PINCAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINCAY POISED TO SET ALL-TIME VICTORIES RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before Ricky Walker retired as a jockey to become a racing
steward in Texas, he gave a shot at competing against the best in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   One of Walker's most memorable times on the track was not about
a horse he rode, but about a jockey he competed against, Laffit
Pincay Jr., who is ready to break Bill Shoemaker's all-time victory
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I rode against him, I was in front of him
turning for home,'' Walker said. ``But he was pretty hard with his
whip, and you could just hear him coming from back there.''
</P>
<P>
   When Walker got back to the jock's room after the race, he could
see why Pincay was such a powerful presence. All it took was for
Pincay to take off his shirt before he dressed into a new pair of
silks for the next race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a massive little muscle man,'' Walker said. ``A ball of
muscles.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay is 52 years old, but the muscles haven't gone away. And
just like that day he was riding behind Walker, people at the
racetrack can hear him coming.
</P>
<P>
   Through 36 years and more than 44,500 rides, Pincay has won
8,831 races. It leaves him two victories short of tying Shoemaker's
record, three to beat it. And, with Pincay scheduled to ride seven
horses Wednesday at Hollywood Park, the record could be history by
day's end.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, as Pincay has drawn closer to ``Shoe,'' he
has been riding at a furious rate. Going into the weekend, Pincay
had ridden 26 winners in 23 days. He leads the jockey standings for
the first time in years at Hollywood Park. And he won his first
major stakes races in almost a year on Sunday when he rode Lazy
Lode to win the $400,000 Hollywood Turf Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, he's one of the greatest riders we've seen in our
game,'' Hall of Fame trainer Ron McAnally said. ``He's riding
terrific right now.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case not so long ago. In fact, it looked as if
Pincay was washed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only me, but I think even Laffit was wondering a few years
ago if he could still do this or if he should retire,'' said
McAnally, who once put Pincay on horses like two-time Horse of the
Year John Henry in the '80s and two-time Breeders' Cup winner
Bayakoa in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The low point possibly came at Santa Anita near Pasadena,
Calif., in 1997. Pincay lost the first 38 rides of the meet before
he finally got one to the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   But Pincay wouldn't have ridden that winner if it weren't for
the fact that the scheduled rider showed up late for work.
</P>
<P>
   So, after the race, Pincay admitted he was thinking about making
some drastic changes to his career. He was considering moving from
the competitive Southern California circuit to Northern California.
In terms of comparison, it would almost be like a baseball player
moving from the majors to Triple A.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record means a lot to me, first of all, because I think
`Shoe' is the greatest rider I have ever ridden against,'' Pincay
said. ``It's a record I thought no one would ever break.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, when I got to 8,000 wins (in 1993), I thought I might have
a chance at it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pincay was losing the battle in Southern California. He
always had trouble maintaining the required weight for a jockey.
That's less than 120 pounds, and Pincay says doctors have told him
he normally should weigh 140 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Pincay would eat one cracker for lunch _ and
scrape away the salt before eating it. And there's another part of
his diet that has become one of the legendary stories in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay was traveling with trainer D. Wayne Lukas when lunch was
being served on the airplane. Pincay turned down the meal, and
instead took a peanut out of his shirt pocket. He split the peanut
in two and slowly ate the first half. He waited, then slowly chewed
the remaining portion.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas might have seen it that one time, but Pincay said he has
had many one-peanut meals.
</P>
<P>
   The weight struggle, made harder with advancing age, was getting
to him. He said he came close to fainting several times _ even
while on a horse. With young riders such as Gary Stevens, Alex
Solis and Kent Desormeaux becoming more established in California,
trainers were using Pincay less and less.
</P>
<P>
   So, Pincay actually retained a Northern California agent to
start booking rides. But when the time came, Pincay wouldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to give it another try,'' he said. ``I didn't
want to move. I just bought a house, and I didn't want to leave my
wife here.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Pincay knew, if he had to move to a less competitive arena
in order to break the record, he would cheapen something very
important to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing pretty bad at the time,'' he said. ``I was
desperate to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than leave, Pincay kept fighting. He started
experimenting with foods he had never eaten much before. He
consumed fruits and gave up bran. He ate less fatty meats like
chicken and fish.
</P>
<P>
   And he increased his exercise regimen. In that new home, he
added a small gym and ``I reacted in a way I never thought I
would,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he could keep going. He said he won't retire immediately
after breaking the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enjoying riding more than any other time in my life,''
Pincay said. ``As long as I feel that way _ I don't know if it's
going to be one, two or three more years _ I'm going to keep
riding.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe set a record that will never be broken. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
