year due to immunizations gone wrong.)
</P>
<P>
   But in more than 30 countries in the Mideast, South Asia and
east and central Africa, the polio virus still circulates freely,
attacking children 3 years old and younger, and crippling them for
life.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the CDC, WHO, UNICEF and other organizations launched
an international collaboration to eliminate polio from the world _
a goal that has been reached for only one other disease, smallpox.
Since then, recorded cases of polio have sunk from more than
350,000 to about 6,000 worldwide, though experts fear 10 times as
many cases go unreported because of poor public-health surveillance
in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   Because polio causes symptoms in only a percentage of those who
are infected _ and because trade and rapid travel have created
intimate connections between countries _ authorities believe the
whole world will remain at risk until polio is eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   To reach that goal by the end of 2000, and confirm it by the end
of 2005, requires three separate strategies, Cochi said: high
levels of routine vaccination among children less than a year old;
sophisticated surveillance and laboratory analysis to identify
cases that occur despite vaccinations; and special efforts to
blanket under-developed countries with additional protection
through national one-day mobilizations and house-to-house ``mopping
up'' campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   WHO has made the special-effort campaigns a high priority in 10
countries, five with the highest remaining rates of polio
transmission and five where ongoing wars make thorough immunization
difficult: Afghanistan, Angola, Democratic Republic of the Congo,
Somalia, Sudan, Bangladesh, Ethiopia, India, Nigeria and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Combatting polio in those countries is extremely expensive and
labor-intensive. During National Immunization Days, which happen in
polio-endemic countries at least twice a year, it demands enough
organization to line up every child in the country younger than 5
to receive a dose of vaccine, as well as enough coordination to get
viable vaccine to the thousands of stations distributing it. One
such campaign is scheduled for Dec. 19 in India.
</P>
<P>
   Between campaigns, polio eradication requires having enough
trained staff to make regular visits to rural hospitals and
clinics, identifying cases of paralysis from recent records; track
down the sick child in rough or disorganized terrain; take careful
samples that are forwarded to a worldwide laboratory network; and
find the child again 60 days later to see whether the paralysis has
persisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the greatest need will be for these funds,''
Cochi said. ``To carry out these activities successfully, you have
to have a structure and network in each country, going down to the
district level, with trained personnel who are that country's
nationals.''
</P>
<P>
   The newly donated funds will also go to support the
international network of laboratories that analyze potential cases
of polio and alert health authorities to its persistence, the UN
Foundation's Harwood said. That will bring ongoing benefits once
polio is eliminated, he added: ``What the polio-eradication
initiative really wants to do is train people in the countries, so
a public-health infrastructure is created and the knowledge the
personnel gain can be sustained. That way it can be used in the
future, against other diseases beyond polio.''
</P>
<P>
   Though eliminating polio is a cherished global goal,
international authorities had recently warned that it could not be
achieved without significant additional investment. WHO estimated
earlier this year that the eradication campaign would fall $500
million short of its $1.25 billion price tag.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, WHO, UNICEF and the service organization Rotary
International, the volunteer shock troops of the anti-polio effort,
warned that an additional $50 million was needed just to buy the
vaccines that should be administered next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on track to eradicate polio,'' WHO Director-General Dr.
Gro Harlem Brundtland said Tuesday in response to the Turner and
Gates gifts. ``One of the biggest challenges we now face is raising
the necessary funds to finish the job on time. With this kind of
contribution, a polio-free world is within reach and one of the
world's largest health initiatives can be brought to a successful
conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
