<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-AUTO-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA COMPANY BUYS AUTO INDUSTRY DATA NETWORK
</HEADLINE>
  (mg) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ A privately held California company announced on
Tuesday that it had bought the assets and operations of the auto
industry's private data network, the latest in a series of moves by
automakers as they begin switching their vast purchasing systems to
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co. have been developing
software to set up electronic marketplaces next year on the
once-obscure private network. The marketplaces could be used to
conduct bidding and to place purchase orders for auto parts or even
for services like health care for employees.
</P>
<P>
   GM plans to use the software on the Internet as well. Ford hopes
to do so but still has concerns about whether Internet transactions
will be safe.
</P>
<P>
   The Automotive Industry Action Group, a consortium of GM, Ford,
DaimlerChrysler AG and 1,600 of their parts suppliers, sold the
network's computers, software, patents, copyrights and brands to
the Science Applications International Corp., a company in San
Diego. SAIC will manage the Automotive Network Exchange, as it is
known, although auto industry executives would remain on the
network's governing committee. Terms of the sale were not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Buchanan, a steel industry executive on one of the
committees that helped design the Automotive Network Exchange, said
the sale was necessary because the group did not have the money
needed to expand the network.
</P>
<P>
   ``SAIC brings some deep pockets to the table,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   SAIC said it planned to add features, including video
conferencing.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers believe that the network offers tighter security than
the Internet. Users have special phone lines to the network's
computers, although there are plans for dial-up access.
Transmissions would be heavily encrypted.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers are working on ways to take bids for
multimillion-dollar auto parts contracts over the Internet but are
wary that rivals might figure out a way to steal information.
Whatever system is used ``has to be secure, because none of us want
to be able to see each other's product development plans as they're
buzzing through the lines,'' said Mark Baughman, Ford's manager of
supplier electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   David Barnas, a GM spokesman, said the automaker believed it
could safely conduct electronic commerce with suppliers over the
Internet and did not need to rely exclusively on the elaborate
security of the private data network.
</P>
<P>
   The network connects the automakers' computers to those of 250
suppliers; 200 more suppliers have applied to join the network. The
network has already been used to exchange confidential blueprints
of car models and to transmit bids for auto parts contracts.
Automakers also use the network to send hourly updates of assembly
plant activity to suppliers, who then send auto parts in time for
them to be installed on vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The data network will be expanding into other industries tied to
the automakers.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals and health care insurers in southeastern Michigan will
start using the network next spring to exchange information, said
Dennis McCafferty, the vice president for product development at
the Greater Detroit Area Health Council.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Trent, SAIC's senior vice president for e-business, said
the company hoped to bring other industries onto the network.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   SAIC is owned by its 36,000 employees and is best known for its
purchase in late 1997 of Bell Communications Research, the research
arm of the regional Bell telephone companies. SAIC, which had $4.7
billion in revenue last year, also designs military and scientific
computer systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
