<HEADER>
A2123 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-SALE-NYT &LR;      12-07 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-SALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNER OF TAMPA BAY TEAM TRIED TO SELL IT TO BUY N.Y. JETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a strange twist to the nearly completed process of selling
the Jets, the owner of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers last month
attempted to engineer the sale of his own football team in order to
make a run at buying the New York Jets, three people involved in,
or familiar with, the proposed transaction said this week.
</P>
<P>
   The brief, but audacious, maneuver began in late November when
Malcolm Glazer, the Bucs' owner, assigned his investment banker, SG
Cowen, to find a buyer for the Bucs. The maneuver now appears to be
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Glazer, an executive vice president of the Bucs and one of
three Glazer sons involved with the team, denied the story through
a spokesman, Reggie Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for SG Cowen, a prominent sports industry financier,
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   For Glazer to execute his unusual plan, he would have most
likely required the approval of the finance committee of the
National Football League, if not the entire ownership. One owner
said, ``I don't think the league would stand for it.'' Glazer is a
member of the finance committee.
</P>
<P>
   The only transaction in the NFL that was remotely similar to
Glazer's proposal occurred in 1972, when Robert Irsay bought the
Los Angeles Rams and then swapped them for the Baltimore Colts,
owned by Carroll Rosenbloom. If the league had approved Glazer's
plan, he would have then placed the team in trust for SG Cowen to
sell because he would not have been able to sell the Bucs in time
to buy the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   He would have also needed to persuade the Hess estate and
Goldman, Sachs, which is handling the Jets' sale, to delay the
process in order for him to formally apply to buy the New York team
and to examine the Jets' finances. Wednesday is the deadline for
bidders to submit final offers for the Jets. Charles Dolan, the
chairman of Cablevision; Robert Wood Johnson IV, an heir to the
Johnson &AMP; Johnson fortune, and Sam Grossman, a real estate
developer from Phoenix, are the leading suitors.
</P>
<P>
   Three executives who spoke on the condition of anonymity said
that Glazer believes the Bucs have attained maximum value because
of the success of the $168 million Raymond James Stadium, which
opened in 1998. It was financed when Hillsborough County voters
approved a half-cent sales tax increase in 1996. The vote survived
a lawsuit that charged that the stadium served no public purpose.
</P>
<P>
   NFL teams are selling at a premium, with the Washington Redskins
(plus FedEx Field) going for $800 million and the new Houston
franchise costing $700 million earlier this year. Forbes magazine
recently estimated that the Bucs are the league's third-most
valuable team, at $502 million. Forbes valued the Jets at $363
million, No. 17 on its list.
</P>
<P>
   Had he been able to unload the Bucs (8-4), Glazer would have
sold a team now in a first-place tie with the Lions in the National
Football Conference Central division. Tampa Bay plays Detroit on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Glazer would very likely have had a more difficult time
attaining maximum value with the Jets, who have a lease at Giants
Stadium that yields relatively low revenues. One of the pitches
used to market the Jets is the possibility of a new stadium in the
future, which would have much more lucrative terms for the owner.
</P>
<P>
   Glazer, 71, who is from Rochester, N.Y., acquired the Bucs four
years ago for $192 million, then a record, after several attempts
to buy an NFL team, including the New England Patriots. He is the
president of First Allied Corp., a holding company for his
investments in food service equipment, food packaging,
broadcasting, health care and marine protein.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
