<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2124 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SEATTLE-POLICE-CHIEF-     12-07 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-POLICE-CHIEF-ART-735(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE POLICE CHIEF RESIGNS IN AFTERMATH OF PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT30 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Amid continuing criticism over the police department's
handling of the protests here last week that eclipsed the World
Trade Organization meeting, the city's police chief announced
Tuesday that he would resign.
</P>
<P>
   The chief, Norm Stamper, said he wished to ``de-politicize'' the
investigations that are under way into police preparations for the
global trade talks, which drew 35,000 protesters downtown. The
demonstrations quickly turned into a tumultuous affair, televised
worldwide, in which the police sprayed tear gas and rubber pellets
at many peaceful protesters along police lines near the meeting but
failed to stop the window-smashing and looting by a relatively
small group of vandals less than a block away. The National Guard
was called in to help restore order.
</P>
<P>
   In his resignation letter to Mayor Paul Schell, Stamper praised
his officers for the ``restraint, discipline, perseverance and
incredible courage'' he said they showed in the face of the
protests, and noted that there were no deaths or serious injuries
reported during nearly a week of unrest.
</P>
<P>
   But the police and Schell have been hit by complaints from
virtually all sides: from protesters and residents of neighborhoods
in and around downtown who say the tear gas, pepper spray and
rubber pellets they endured were wildly inappropriate; by merchants
who say the vandalism caused at least $3 million in damages and
much more than that in lost holiday sales, and even from some
police officers, who have spoken up to assert that the department
was unprepared for the protests.
</P>
<P>
   In handing in his resignation, Stamper may take a bit of the
political heat off of Schell, although the mayor made a point of
dismissing any suggestion that he had sought or forced the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision was Norm's, and Norm's alone,'' Schell said at a
news conference Tuesday morning, adding that he had tried to talk
the chief out of resigning. But the mayor's critics, including some
City Council members, quickly cast the resignation as an effort to
make Stamper the scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   And the resignation may be only the beginning of the political
fallout from an event that was intended to showcase Seattle as a
world-class city and friend to both free speech and free trade.
Schell, who is up for re-election in 2001, turned back questions
Tuesday morning about whether he himself might resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to step down,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   Schell, a former director of community development and dean of
the University of Washington's school of architecture and urban
planning, had wanted to provide the protesters a broad forum to
make their points, and he and Stamper had spent months working with
leaders of the protest forces to ensure the demonstrations would be
peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor spoke of Seattle offering a model of ``constructive
debate'' on trade issues, and, as the protests got out of hand, he
appeared stunned and saddened, saying: ``This administration has
people who marched in the 1960s _ the last thing I wanted was to be
mayor of a city that called in the National Guard.''
</P>
<P>
   For that approach, he has certainly drawn some praise, and one
snap poll late last week by a local television station, KOMO-TV,
the ABC affiliate in Seattle, found that 26 percent of Seattle
residents interviewed said they had a higher opinion of the mayor
at the end of the week than they had at the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   But in the main, he has been roundly criticized for the way the
city prepared for and handled the protests. The City Council is
opening hearings into the events, which will be open to protesters,
residents, merchants, police officers and anyone else who wants to
testify.
</P>
<P>
   At least two civil-rights groups are calling for investigations
into police conduct, and the local branch of the NAACP also called
for an inquiry into an incident in which officers stopped a black
City Council member, Richard McIver, who was headed to a WTO
reception. Despite showing his identification, McIver said, he was
pulled out of his car, had his hands wrenched behind his back by
two officers and was nearly arrested.
</P>
<P>
   And the local chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union has
sharply criticized the city's imposition of what the group believes
was an unconstitutional no-protest zone in a roughly 30-block area
of the downtown.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There was something of a subtext to the chain of events leading
to the decision by Stamper, 55, to resign after nearly six years as
head of the force. While widely praised in some quarters of this
relatively liberal city for his numerous outreach efforts to the
community, he was deeply unpopular with many conservative political
leaders and with some police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Just half a year after taking over in February 1994, he upset
some officers when he wore his uniform in a gay-pride parade but
forbade his officers from wearing their uniforms at a ``March for
Jesus'' on the same weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when one of his officers shot and killed an unarmed
black man during a domestic-violence dispute, Stamper apologized at
a community meeting organized by black leaders for what he termed a
``wrongful death.'' Later, though, he told reporters that he
supported an inquest jury's conclusion that the shooting had been
accidental.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, he told a Seattle Post-Intelligencer columnist that as
a young police officer in San Diego, he had beaten up gays and used
racial slurs to harass members of minority groups. ``Gay bashing
was not only acceptable, it was more or less required,'' he said,
and he added that he had ``regularly jacked around young people and
people of color.''
</P>
<P>
   While he expressed deep remorse for those actions and gained
some praise for his candor, many police officers in Seattle and
elsewhere were outraged, believing Stamper had branded them all
racists and gay-bashers. Shortly after the column appeared, Stamper
interrupted a vacation to apologize in person to veteran officers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And most recently, Stamper's department was weathering a scandal
over its failure to unearth details about a case in which a veteran
homicide detective was suspected of stealing $10,000 from a crime
scene and his sergeant was accused of covering up the crime. (A
first trial of the detective ended in a hung jury.)
</P>
<P>
   Stamper alluded to some of his roller-coaster history in his
letter to Mayor Schell, saying: ``Although my personal beliefs and
political views have often been at odds with many of my colleagues,
I've managed to love almost every moment of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Stamper's action Tuesday was clearly linked to the
handling of last week's protests.
</P>
<P>
   While merchants and many protesters were furious, so were police
officers. Some have already talked of suing the city, and Tuesday
morning the police union president, Mike Edwards, said that many
officers were equipped with deficient equipment and forced to spend
as much as 20 hours straight on the police lines without food or
other support.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Smith, a 10-year veteran of the force, complained last
week to the Seattle Post-Intelligencer that the department was
completely unprepared, despite advance warning that the town would
be flooded with protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like they closed their eyes and said, `I hope
nothing happens,''' he told the newspaper, which also reported news
of Stamper's impending resignation in this morning's edition, hours
before the mayor made it official.
</P>
<P>
   Stamper said he had intended to resign sometime next year
anyway, after he had seen the force through both the WTO
demonstrations and any disruptions that might occur in the city
because of the Y2K computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   But the chief, who once wrote an undergraduate thesis at San
Diego State University titled ``The Community as DMZ: Breaking Down
the Police Paramilitary Bureaucracy,'' said he decided to make it
clear now that he was intending to leave, probably sometime around
the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's natural for people to say, `Well of course the
police chief is going to say this or say that, do this or do that
because he wants to keep his job,''' he said Tuesday at the news
conference. ``What I've said is, I'm not abandoning my job, I'm
retiring from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schell, by contrast, said that he had no intention of his
leaving his job, and believed that he could be a part of bringing
the city back together.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole community's hurting, I'm hurting,'' said the mayor.
``And I think that it's time to understand what happened, what can
we learn from it as a community. And before we start assigning
guilt the first step is, let's get the facts. All of us, together.
And then make our conclusions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 2048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2127 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-SON-COX     12-07 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-SON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Profile of the Father: Daft's son speaks out on newly-announced
CEO dad
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The next boss of the world's biggest soft drink
company didn't join the corporation 30 years ago to sell more
Coca-Colas.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Daft, who grew up in a small coal-mining city in
Australia, just wanted to see the world, says his 21-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad had always wanted a chance to travel overseas,'' says
Nicholas Daft, a senior majoring in Asian studies at Williams
College in Williamstown, Mass. ``I don't think he had ever traveled
out of Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick's father phoned him at his dorm room Saturday morning to
say it looked like he would be getting a new job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, 'Oh really?'
</P>
<P>
   `` 'Yes. Mister Ivester is retiring, and he asked me to be
chairman.'
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was very emotional,'' Nick says. ``It was something
that my dad had not expected at all. All I could think was how
proud I was of my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coca-Cola board held a special meeting the next day to vote
on the changes, and on Monday, the company announced Ivester's
planned retirement and Daft's selection as his eventual
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't working at Coke with the desire to be chairman,''
Nick says.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the son's descriptions of his 56-year-old father.
Coca-Cola's next leader appears to be unlike Ivester, a former
company accountant who often works seven days a week and publicly
shows few interests outside of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Nick says his father works hard during the week, ``but for him,
weekends are times for him to enjoy himself.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't been easy lately. As head of Coca-Cola's Middle and
Far East Group, Daft has spent the last two years trying to undo
the company's troubles in nation's where economies have been on the
slide. He travels two or three weeks a month and endures three or
four days of jet lag each time he returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has traveled more in the last couple of years than he ever
has,'' Nick says. ``My mother (Delphine) has traveled with him and
that has made it a lot easier for my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   In a management restructuring in October, Ivester gave Daft
additional responsibilities to head operations in Africa and at the
new Schweppes Beverages Division. This week, Daft was promoted to
president and chief operating officer, and the board indicated he
will become chairman and chief executive officer in April.
</P>
<P>
   Nick says his father likes to joke around, but one thing
particularly irks him: people giving up when faced with difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done that a couple times. My dad is a big believer in
just sticking with something.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Daft fly fishes with a passion: in Utah, in
Massachusetts near his son's college and in Switzerland, where the
family owns a chalet and has often spent summers and Christmas
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 42, Douglas Daft began taking ski lessons, so that
he could join his children on the slopes. (His daughter, Alexandra,
26, is married and works at a department store in Portland, Ore.)
</P>
<P>
   The family remains close, according to the son.
</P>
<P>
   Daft and his wife see their children regularly. They have
visited their son at college six times just since September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a time for me to have a good meal out of the dining
hall,'' Nick says. But they don't go to college bars. ``My dad is
usually asleep by 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick describes his father's upbringing in New South Wales as
middle class. Douglas Daft's parents owned a shoe store near the
city of Cessnock about two hours north of Sydney in eastern
Australia. It's a community where the dominant coal mining industry
has been on the wane for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``They worked hard,'' is the message Nick has gotten about his
grandparents. But it wasn't all sweat. Douglas Daft played piano
and, along with a friend, would trot out show tunes at a local
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always felt he would do well in life,'' said Daft's
80-year-old mother, Bessie, who still lives in Australia, ``because
of the way he went from better to better.'' Daft also called his
``mum'' about the good news. She told the Australian press she
``went wobbly at the knees'' after learning of the promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Daft encourages his son to do well at school, ``but he said
sometimes he himself didn't do quite as much work as he should have
done'' in college. After college, the elder Daft got a job as a
math and science teacher at a high school in Sydney. It was there
that he met Delphine, a French teacher, whom he would later marry.
</P>
<P>
   Daft joined Coca-Cola as a planner in Sydney, but it led to a
life on the road for him and his family. Nick was born in Hong
Kong, his sister in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   The family later moved to Japan, then to Atlanta, when Daft got
a promotion eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the travel and the many countries, Nick said his
father repeated a basic motto: ``Be kind with everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   When it came to business, his father was most proud of his
success in building up Coca-Cola's sales in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad is just a hard worker who has confidence in what he is
doing,'' Nick says. ``But he will listen to other people's
advice.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Daft has most often sought counsel from retired
Coca-Cola President Donald Keogh and Steve Weiss, a longtime friend
and consultant to Coca-Cola who came to Atlanta around the same
time as Daft and his family.
</P>
<P>
   As for his father's new job, Nick says, ``I think my dad just
wants to restore the confidence in Coke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes that it really is a great product, that it serves
a great purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
