<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHILE-POLITICS-2TAKES     12-07 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-POLITICS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOCIALIST, MINDING THE PAST CAREFULLY, CLOSES IN ON CHILE'S
PRESIDENCY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ In a country still emerging from a quarter of
a century of revolution and counterrevolution, the presidential
campaign of Ricardo Lagos flies the red Socialist Party flag and is
infused with the memories of revolutionary dreams dashed by the
military coup of 1973.
</P>
<P>
   A Lagos campaign headquarters here is decorated with a poster
emblazoned ``With Allende Always,'' memorializing the last Chilean
Socialist Party member to occupy the presidential palace. When
Lagos joined in a televised debate with Joaquin Lavin, the main
conservative candidate, last month, the widow of President Salvador
Allende Gossens, who died in the coup, sat in the front row
cheering the man she hopes will revive her husband's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   But with Lagos slightly ahead in the polls as Sunday's election
nears, he and his aides have engaged in a critical reassessment of
the party's performance in the Allende years in speeches,
interviews and before a panel of military officers and human rights
lawyers negotiating how to atone for the thousands of people who
disappeared during the regime of Gen. Augusto Pinochet, who
overthrew Allende.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos and other Socialists have implicitly blamed the party's
radicalism for the country's hyperinflation, shortages and economic
collapse in 1972 and 1973. They have conceded that the Socialists
went far beyond their governing partner, the Communist Party, in
encouraging peasant land invasions, worker takeovers of factories,
and even calling on military units to mutiny, acknowledging that
such actions were a crucial cause for the coup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put the interests of the party before the interests of the
people,'' Lagos said last week at a campaign stop full of symbolism
_ the presentation of a book of speeches and essays written by
Radomiro Tomic, the Christian Democrat who ran for president
against Allende in 1970. Quoting Tomic, Lagos added, ``There are no
innocents in the destruction of Chilean democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ricardo Nunez Munoz, the Socialist Party president, said in
an interview: ``It's wrong to say that the CIA, the armed forces
and the bourgeoisie alone brought down the Allende government. It's
obvious we need to admit we made critical economic and political
errors that were as decisive if not more decisive.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It's possible some are frightened by the prospect of
another Socialist president, but while Ricardo Lagos is a son of
the Allende years, he and we know another Allende-like experiment
would only be a colossal failure.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the self-criticism are in large part tactical at
a time when most Chilean voters reject either political extreme.
But the often painful reflections underscore how far the Socialist
Party has come from the days it sent fighters to join Che Guevara
in Bolivia, declared its overriding philosophy as Marxist-Leninist
in 1967, and accepted the help of East German intelligence agents
to spirit out its main party leader in the days after the coup.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that many Christian Democrats and other moderate
voters are still fretful that a victory for Lagos could threaten
the country's stability even though he is running in a coalition
supported by the Christian Democratic Party. That swing vote _
representing up to 10 percent of the electorate _ is also being
sought by Lavin, a former low-level economist in the Pinochet
dictatorship whose campaign statements have been surprisingly
moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jose Antonio Viera-Gallo, a Socialist who served as deputy
secretary of justice in the Allende government, said, ``Lagos has
to win the heart of the Christian Democratic Party and show he is a
candidate of unity.''
</P>
<P>
   Lagos was poised to become Allende's ambassador to the Soviet
Union at the time of the coup. Now, after stints as education and
public works minister in two governments led by Christian
Democrats, he hews to an extremely moderate line. During the
campaign he has posed with David Rockefeller and George Soros for
photographs that have been displayed prominently in the Chilean
press, and he has pledged to push forward with privatization of the
ports and public water systems.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   As for the state copper company, expropriated and nationalized
by Allende, Lagos has pledged to seek joint ventures with foreign
investors to expand the company's reach to international markets.
He has promised not to negotiate with the Communist Party to win
its backing if, as expected, no candidate wins a majority on
Sunday, forcing a runoff election in January.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos has even broken with human rights advocates by pledging
that if elected he will continue the current government's policy of
contesting the efforts by a Spanish judge to extradite Pinochet
from Britain and try him on charges of torture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the limits of the possible and I understand that I have
an obligation to lead the citizenry on a responsible path,'' Lagos
told business leaders last month. Lagos did not name Allende in his
speech _ he rarely ever mentions the former president _ but he
repeatedly drew a sharp distinction between the government he plans
to lead and the only one previously led by a Socialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about opening the Pandora's box of populism,'' Lagos
told the business leaders. ``The world has changed and we have all
learned.''
</P>
<P>
   The learning process, Lagos and other Socialist Party leaders
said, began almost immediately after the coup, when Socialist
activists spread throughout Europe and Latin America in exile. Many
party members gradually moderated their views while living in the
Netherlands and Sweden, where they were influenced by local Social
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Most party leaders went to East Germany, where they were treated
to generous allowances and special educational and housing
privileges otherwise granted only to East German Communist Party
leaders. But tensions grew in the party when the German hosts told
the Chilean Socialist rank and file that they did not have the
right to travel outside East Germany, or even move from one East
German town to another, without the explicit permission of their
party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The party finally split in 1979 between a pro-Soviet faction and
a more Social Democratic faction, which moved to join other exiles
in Italy and France and some even back to Chile to organize
nonviolent protests. The reformist winds of Eurocommunism made a
big impact on many in the party.
</P>
<P>
   Enrico Berlinguer, the reformist Italian Communist Party leader,
made an important impression on the Chilean Socialists when he
wrote three essays criticizing the Allende government for pressing
a far too radical agenda without first organizing broader support.
Out of those writings came Berlinguer's eventual coalition with the
Italian Christian Democrats, and they contributed to the Chilean
Socialists' own alliance with the Chilean Christian Democrats
despite that party's early support for the Pinochet coup.
</P>
<P>
   Also vital to the transformation was the rise of Solidarity in
Poland in the early 1980s, when many Chilean Socialists came out in
support of the union against the communist regime. ``You can't cry
out for human rights and fight for a dictatorship of the left,''
Viera-Gallo said.
</P>
<P>
   But despite all the changes there are still Socialist Party
members who express discomfort with the free enterprise system. In
a nod to the left, Lagos has run on the slogan ``Growth with
Equality'' and promised to make the fight against unemployment his
No. 1 priority. Socialist leaders cannot help but express their
glee over the irony that their candidate is the likely next
president, while Pinochet has been under house arrest outside
London for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-seven years after being thrown out so cruelly in a
coup, a president of our party taking power would give us great
satisfaction,'' said Nunez, the Socialist Party president with a
mirthful grin. ``But Lagos is not going to enter La Moneda as the
second Allende.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
