<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2133 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRAZIL-SAFRA-NYT &LR;      12-07 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-SAFRA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EMPIRE-BUILDING SAFRAS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Brazil, France, Lebanon, Syria, Israel)   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ When the Safra family built a mansion
resembling the palaces of Roman nobles in this city's opulent
Morumbi neighborhood, Joseph Safra, the younger brother of the late
financier Edmond J. Safra, acknowledged that the structure was
``out of context'' for a relatively poor country like Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the building is indicative of the grandiose
dealings of a family who, since their arrival in Brazil in the
early 1950s, after fleeing from Lebanon, have assembled one of this
country's largest conglomerates. Whether it is in banking,
telecommunications or even in the cultivation of eucalyptus trees
used to produce paper, the Safras have been synonymous in Brazil
with financial might.
</P>
<P>
   So it is no small wonder that news of the death last week in
Monte Carlo of Edmond J. Safra, a naturalized Brazilian who helped
construct his family's enterprises here in addition to his own
banking empire, shook this country's business culture. The shock
was magnified by the realization that violent deaths can occur in
wealthy places far away from crime-plagued urban Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is large that Edmond Safra left what is thought to
be a dangerous place only to die such a way in a reputedly safe
place,'' said Fernao Bracher, president of Banco BBA-Creditanstalt,
a Sao Paulo investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Safra's death seems to have been far stranger than
originally reported. The police first said that hooded intruders
killed Safra in an arson attack on his penthouse. They have now
charged an American nurse of Safra, Ted Maher, with starting the
fire. Maher reportedly told the police that he had not intended to
kill anyone and had fabricated the intruder account. He said he set
fire to a waste basket in the apartment in an effort ``to draw
attention to himself'' and win the gratitude of his boss for
thwarting the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Many puzzling questions remain, including how such a person
could have penetrated the inner circle of a reclusive banker who
had been preoccupied with his security.
</P>
<P>
   The Safras have been known in Brazil for the lengths to which
they go in search of security. For example, Joseph and Moise Safra,
the main surviving shareholders of Banco Safra SA, Brazil's
fifth-largest bank, commute by helicopter to avoid traffic jams and
the potential danger that kidnappers are lurking somewhere on the
way from their residence to the bank's headquarters in Sao Paulo's
financial district.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Ezequiel Nasser, a nephew of Edmond, Joseph
and Moise Safra, was kidnapped here and held until his captors
received an unspecified ransom. Afterward, the Safras, one of
Brazil's most prominent Jewish families, hired a squad of Israeli
security agents to train their Brazilian bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   If members of the Safra family shared a concern for security,
they built businesses with similar gusto.
</P>
<P>
   Edmond Safra left Brazil in the early 1960s for Switzerland to
establish his own bank, an institution that was a precursor of
Republic New York, part of the family's efforts to cobble together
a small banking group. The torch was handed to Joseph Safra, now
60, to lead the family's growing enterprises in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Banco Safra, their flagship company, has emerged as
one of Brazil's soundest and most respected financial institutions,
largely focused on a small, affluent clientele with origins similar
to the Safras, who were originally bankers in Aleppo, Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond banking _ including financial institutions in the United
States, Israel and Uruguay _ the family has branched into other
areas. In telecommunications, the Safras own a big minority stake
in BCP Telecomunicacoes, the Sao Paulo cellular phone unit of
BellSouth, and they are important competitors in Brazil's
eucalyptus pulp industry, through a minority stake in Aracruz
Celulose SA, the country's largest pulp company.
</P>
<P>
   The Safras are also large landowners and have established
extensive cattle-ranching operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other Jewish family in Brazil, and few other Brazilian
families for that matter, rival the Safras in the scope of their
business strategies since they are transnational and very Brazilian
at the same time,'' said Jeffrey Lesser, a professor at Connecticut
College, who has written on the history of Brazil's Jews.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a Brazilian clan that personified the globalization
of business and finance, it would probably be the Safras. The
languages that are used in the family's dealings _ a reflection of
their diverse group of clients and business partners _ include
Portuguese, English, French, Spanish, Hebrew and Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I don't express myself well in Portuguese,'' Joseph
Safra, who arrived in Brazil after he turned 20, said in a rare
interview with the news magazine Veja in 1998. ``I'm afraid of
being interpreted wrongly.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the country's 110,000 Jews, the Safras are known for their
philanthropy. They recently financed the construction of the
largest temple in the country, an ornate structure serving Sao
Paulo's Sephardic Jews _ largely of Spanish, Portuguese, Middle
Eastern and North African descent.
</P>
<P>
   The family is also known for its efforts to soothe tensions
between the country's Sephardic Jews and the East and Central
European-descended Ashkenazic Jews. The Safras supported a recent
resurgence of interest among some Ashkenazim here in Orthodox
Jewish culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Safras, and Edmond Safra especially, were able to
transcend the concern with parochial things,'' said Henry Sobel,
senior rabbi of Brazil's largest Ashkenazic synagogue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
