<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2134 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-DEBATES-2TAKES-N     12-07 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DEBATES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SEEKS TO COUNTER PERCEPTION THAT HE IS A LIGHTWEIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Alan Keyes spoke unspecifically about candidates who
seemed merely to repeat scripted lines and might not get anywhere
without their family connections.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain offered an anecdote about former Secretary of State
Dean Acheson that implicitly underscored George W. Bush's failure,
after receiving a question about Acheson, to provide any similarly
concrete information.
</P>
<P>
   And Orrin Hatch relegated his commentary on Bush's abilities to
a broad joke based on the presumption that Hatch would win the
Republican nomination and be in a position to select Bush as his
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have eight years with me, and, boy, you will make a
heck of a president after eight years,'' Hatch told Bush during the
forum for Republican presidential candidates here on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the levity, subtlety or indirection in their
approaches, these three candidates were essentially calling Bush a
lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   And they were signaling that in the few precious months before
the thicket of Republican primaries in which Bush remains a heavy
favorite, perhaps the most vigorous line of attack against him will
be that he lacks the intellectual heft and poise to lead the
country.
</P>
<P>
   As the jokes and jabs fired off by comedians like David
Letterman and Jay Leno and cartoonists like Garry Trudeau suggest,
that is the most popular evolving caricature of Bush: nice suit,
nobody in it.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference here on Tuesday morning, Bush articulated
his defense against that insinuation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `Here's my credentials','' Bush, the governor of Texas,
said. ``I've been in the business world. I've been an entrepreneur.
I've been in a decision-making position in the second largest
state. I've been elected governor twice in an incredibly important
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he possesses an advantage that Senator Hatch of Utah
and Sen. McCain of Arizona, despite their longer careers, do not
have.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys, the other two elected officials, have spent a lot
of time in Washington,'' Bush said. ``If you listened carefully,
everybody was attacking Washington last night. Well, I'm the one
person who's been a chief executive outside of Washington. But
people are going to have to make up their minds. We've all got our
strengths, we've got our weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The forums on Monday night and last week were in part
opportunities for his opponents to home in on Bush's perceived
weaknesses, just as the events were chances for Bush to counter the
perception that he is intellectually unprepared for the presidency.
But his caution and reserve have made it nearly impossible for him
to accomplish that so far.
</P>
<P>
   One did not have to be a student of Bush's prior public comments
to hear, in most of his remarks during Monday's debate, ready-made
sound bites and locutions that were anything but spontaneous. Bush
was clearly reciting bits of prewritten text _ hardly unusual for a
political candidate _ but he sometimes had to travel a good
distance from what he had been asked to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing a question about the lessons of a biography of
Acheson that he had said he was reading, Bush worked his way around
to this line: ``Our nation's greatest export to the world has been,
is and always will be the incredible freedoms we understand in the
great land called America.''
</P>
<P>
   It was straight from his standard stump speech, and minutes
later, when Bush pondered the relationship between the United
States and China, it made an encore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' Bush said, ``in my earlier answer, I said our greatest
export to the world has been, is and always will be the incredible
freedom we understand in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Bush was not the only candidate hewing to
predetermined prognostications. Gary Bauer has yet to meet a topic
that does not allow for a rosy invocation of former Presidents
Lincoln and Reagan, just as Hatch can pivot from just about any
subject to a pitch for his campaign's Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   And at least Bush nails most of his lines. As Steve Forbes tried
to make his way through an obviously planned joke about lobbyists,
mosquitoes and swampland, he ended up in his own oratorical
Okefenokee.
</P>
<P>
   But for a constellation of reasons, including the fact that Bush
rose so quickly in politics, he is the candidate battling the rap
that he is insufficiently schooled in policy and insufficiently
engaged in serious matters.
</P>
<P>
   He is the one whose failing performance on a televised pop quiz
about lesser-known leaders of countries in turmoil launched a
thousand quips, helping to turn him into Leno's favorite whipping
boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush released his new slogan today: `He'll Get Tough
with What's-His-Name','' Leno joked last month.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Letterman cracked, ``The guy may have bonehead
stamped all over him.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, during the forum in Manchester, N.H., Bush
was asked to rattle off a reading list. On Monday night in Phoenix,
he was asked to prove he had slogged through one of the books on
it, the Acheson biography.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bush's response, a collection of lines from a recent foreign
policy address, possibly indicated nothing more than his refusal to
play the dutiful student for judgmental and occasionally
condescending teachers.
</P>
<P>
   But it opened a door, and as McCain nudged through it with his
own observations about Acheson, the McCain campaign's
communications director, Dan Schnur, sought to make eye contact
with reporters in the press room and flashed them a devilish,
triumphant smile.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said on Tuesday, ``In a minute's time, it's hard for me to
give a full book review, but I was able to convey what I wanted to
convey.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was asked during the debate what he would do if the robust
surpluses he projected did not materialize; he simply insisted that
they would, and forged ahead with tangentially related, mostly
rehearsed remarks about how his tax plan would help low-income
families.
</P>
<P>
   This may simply have portrayed a disciplined candidate sitting
wisely on a big lead, and several political analysts said that
Bush's answers seemed thoughtful and considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making progress,'' said Tony Dolan, a former aide to
President Ronald Reagan who is advising Hatch. ``I think his
handlers may have made a mistake in keeping him out of sight early
on, because I think he matures through this kind of process.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has yet to exude the kind of confidence and comfort
that he has in some of his policy speeches, and his rivals have
cleary taken note of that.
</P>
<P>
   Schnur declined to detail Bush's vulnerabilities, but talked up
the strengths that McCain brings into debates in a way that seemed
designed to draw a particular contrast.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the best things we have going for us is John McCain's
experience, his knowledge of the world, and his knowledge of both
public policy and the historical context behind that policy,''
Schnur said. ``The great thing about a debate like this is it gives
him a chance to show how well prepared he is to be president in all
those respects.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
