u s BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     12-07 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CHOOSING HIS FAMILY OVER MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mets lost a first baseman Tuesday but Lynda Olerud gained a
fulltime grandson. She gets to have 15-month-old Garrett Olerud
living only 20 minutes away from her.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like your own parents, when you want to go
away on a short trip, or just for the afternoon.'' she said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   She would not celebrate blatantly because the Olerud family has
only good things to say about New York and Toronto, where her son,
John, has played his entire major league career.
</P>
<P>
   It is a huge continent. Even in first class, the spine starts to
ache somewhere over the Dakotas, and then there are the time zone
changes, living out of a suitcase, to satisfy the deep need to see
loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is a destination city for thousands and thousands of
young people who have heard the siren call of the internet and the
coffee bars on a misty night and the views from many a hillside.
For John and Kelly Olerud, it was about parents and grandparents,
church and home.
</P>
<P>
   Any fan who observed John Olerud's calm persona in his three
years at Shea Stadium would understand that the Oleruds never tried
to hold up the Mets for extra millions, for an extra year on the
contract, as a payoff for the separation. Olerud missed a stable
life near his family around Bellevue, Wash., just east of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real family man,'' Lynda Olerud said Tuesday. ``I'll
tell you, it was an agonizing situation. There is such charisma in
New York, we were treated so well. John is very loyal, and I think
he does not like disappointing people.''
</P>
<P>
   The son held off his decision because he truly enjoyed the city
and the people and the team. His manager in Toronto, Cito Gaston,
had made the bizarre prophecy that John would be so unsettled by
the rowdy demeanor of Met fans that he might retire at an early
age. In fact, Olerud lived in Manhattan and occasionally rode the
No. 7 elevated train, the easiest way to go at rush hour, and he
smiled wryly at the intensity of the big city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never had so much fun as in New York,'' his mother said
Tuesday. ``John and Bobby Valentine just clicked right away. The
infield.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while last summer, overheated Mets' fans were claiming
that Olerud, Edgardo Alfonzo, Rey Ordonez and Robin Ventura were
the best defensive infield in history.
</P>
<P>
   Well, New Yorkers do tend to be grandiose. The Oleruds are the
opposite. They hark back to the placid Norwegians who survived the
plains and the Dirty Thirties of the Depression. Some of them
stayed in their respective Lake Wobegons while others found their
way to salt water again.
</P>
<P>
   The family's roots are deep in Seattle. John Olerud, the father,
caught seven years in the minor leagues and went to medical school
and became a dermatologist. Tuesday the son recalled how excited
they were in 1977, the first year of the Mariners, when he turned
9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember they had the Pepsi Junior Mariners, where you got a
certain number of tickets and a batting glove,'' the son said
Tuesday, recalling that his first favorite player was Bruce Bochte,
a .282 hitter who played five years in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sense of security in being close to each other. When
John was a baseball star at Washington State, he fell down one day
while running a lap. His father grabbed the first plane to the
school and slept in his son's hospital room for a week, until the
specialists discovered the aneurysm, which was repaired in a
six-hour operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``John has been very lucky in a lot of ways,'' the mother said.
Up to now, they considered themselves lucky just to be in touch
long distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I went to spring training,'' Lynda Olerud said
Tuesday. ``With the satellite dish, we could watch every game, and
there is always the telephone. Kelly came back five or six times a
season.''
</P>
<P>
   With the arrival of Garrett Olerud, the mother admitted, ``I
felt a little more needy.''
</P>
<P>
   When John became a free agent after the season, his family
members made their feelings known.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty overt,'' John said Tuesday. ``People said,
`Selfishly, this is what I would like, but ultimately it's your
decision.'''
</P>
<P>
   His mother admitted she voiced her opinion, but she added, ``I
don't know if my vote counted.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, John Olerud took $20 million for three years, less
than he probably could have extorted from the Mets, but as Lynda
Olerud said Tuesday, ``There are some things money can't buy.'' You
cannot hug a grandchild via the satellite dish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
