<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGES IN DISAPPEARANCE OF MADALYN MURRAY O'HAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (no byline) 
(mg) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A federal grand jury on Tuesday indicted a
Michigan man on kidnapping, extortion and robbery charges in the
1995 disappearance of the atheist leader Madalyn Murray O'Hair and
two of her relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment accused Gary Paul Karr of Novi, Mich., and
several accomplices of kidnapping O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray
and her granddaughter, Robin Murray-O'Hair, and robbing them of
$500,000 in gold coins, vehicles, watches and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also accused Karr of transporting stolen property
across state lines and of using interstate communication facilities
to commit an act of violence. If convicted of all the charges,
Karr, 51, could face life in prison without parole.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment was the latest chapter in a mystery that began
when the three, who are believed dead, vanished without a trace
shortly after Murray bought $500,000 in gold coins from a dealer in
San Antonio on Sept. 29, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Karr, who is in custody on federal felony firearms charges, was
not charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair, one of America's best-known atheists, was a plaintiff in
a 1963 Supreme Court case that led to a prohibition on prayer in
public schools. The investigation into her disappearance was
stymied until March 24, when federal authorities searched the
Austin apartment of David Waters, a convicted felon who had worked
as an office manager at the Austin headquarters of O'Hair's
organization, American Atheists Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Although Waters, 52, was not mentioned in the indictment,
federal officials consider him a suspect in the disappearances.
</P>
<P>
   In a 36-page affidavit released shortly before Waters pleaded
guilty to federal firearms charges on Aug. 20, Edmund Martin, a
special agent with the Internal Revenue Service, said the Karr and
Waters ``planned and executed the scheme to abduct, kidnap and
murder'' the three.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors declined to comment on whether Waters would
be charged.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Blagg, the United States Attorney for the Western
District of Texas, said the indictment of Karr was ``not the final
chapter of this investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   `` We are continuing our throughout effort to make sure that
justice is served in this matter,'' Blagg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
