<HEADER>
A2151 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-AMADEUS-THEATER-ART-2     12-07 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMADEUS-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ACTOR CREATES A FEARFUL, BUT STILL BRATTY, MOZART  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Matt Wolf is the London theater critic for Variety and a regular
writer on the arts from Europe.  
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ My tongue is stupid, but my heart isn't,'' remarks the
errant genius Mozart in ``Amadeus.'' And a sprightly genius he
proves to be, too, in Peter Shaffer's metaphysical melodrama, which
combines speculative historical musings with a meditation on divine
injustice.
</P>
<P>
   Here is perhaps the defining musical figure of our waning
millennium, burrowing about under his wife Constanze's dresses and
spewing forth largely unprintable language _ when he is not
composing ineffably beautiful sounds. These are the very same
notes, of course, that have made a possible murderer out of his
envious colleague, the court composer Salieri.
</P>
<P>
   How can a supreme artist be such an ignoble imp? The question is
tackled in Shaffer's play, a revival of which opens Wednesday at
the Music Box Theater on Broadway. It is being directed by Sir
Peter Hall, after successful engagements in Los Angeles and, last
season, in London, both with the same British leads.
</P>
<P>
   David Suchet, the veteran character actor known in the United
States as the enduring (and portly) detective Hercule Poirot on
television, makes his Broadway debut as the resentful Antonio
Salieri, a self-described ``mediocrity'' whose abiding argument is
not with Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart but with God.
</P>
<P>
   Among his complaints: that Mozart's very laugh is God's way of
mocking Salieri, an artistic hack consumed by self-loathing and yet
admired _ wrongly, as he well knows _ by the Austrian court of
Emperor Joseph II.
</P>
<P>
   Portraying the object of Salieri's cascading fury is another
Broadway newcomer, Michael Sheen, 30. Playing a prodigy so
poisoned, whether literally or figuratively, that he dies in 1791
at the age of 35, Sheen has been acclaimed for laying bare both the
fear and unknowable brilliance behind his character's brattish
persona. As Suchet said admiringly of his co-star: ``He avoids the
trap of just being a giggling fool.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheen explained how he does so over coffee in London shortly
before traveling to Los Angeles for the play's pre-Broadway run.
``Mozart is possessed by his talent,'' Sheen said. ``It frightens
him if he thinks about his gift, which is why he can't think about
it, which is where, I think, a lot of the scatological stuff comes
from.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Mozart's way of switching off,'' added Sheen, his
accent flecked with the sound of his native Wales. ``There's
something so powerful inside him that he can express it as long as
he doesn't get in the way of it. But he can't sit around and talk
about it too much; that's too frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   About Sheen's performance, Sir Peter, the director, said:
``Michael has combined the part's two extremes. He's terribly
moving and also extremely badly behaved; he's got grace and wit and
a complete childlike anarchy let loose as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheen hardly seems the anarchist. In conversation, he bashfully
explained away several days of beard stubble as ``just laziness,
because I've had a week off.'' It was about to vanish in
preparation for his return that evening to the rotating repertory
at the National Theater, where he had opened nearly eight weeks
before as the abusive Jimmy Porter in a revival of John Osborne's
classic ``Look Back in Anger.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance, and Gregory Hersov's production, received
favorable reviews, with critics praising Sheen's ability to find
the defensiveness and hurt in one of modern drama's best-known
aggressors.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone willing to play both Jimmy Porter and Mozart shows a
fondness for roles pitched at extremes, which accounts in large
measure for Sheen's reputation as one of his generation's finest
British stage actors. He has played Romeo and Henry V, the latter
for the Royal Shakespeare Company, as well as the title part in
Ibsen's ``Peer Gynt,'' as staged for a world tour by Yukio
Ninagawa, the Japanese director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find myself more and more acting at 150 percent all the
time,'' said Sheen, whose onstage intensity belies a boyish
appearance that has earned him descriptions like ``elfin'' and
``puckish.'' ``I've got so used with Mozart and Jimmy,'' he said,
``as soon as I come onstage, to being right up there. Having to
work at that level and find subtlety and complexity while going at
100 miles an hour is tough, and you do learn a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Mendes, the theater and film director, called Sheen ``a
stage creature clearly'' and attributed that to the actor's Welsh
roots. ``I'm serious,'' Mendes said. ``He's Welsh in the tradition
of Anthony Hopkins and Richard Burton: fiery, mercurial,
unpredictable.'' Indeed, Sheen comes from Port Talbot, their
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   The role of Mozart poses a fiercely animated assignment, as
conceived by Shaffer, the author also of ``Equus'' and ``Lettice
and Lovage,'' among other plays. But experience indicates it is not
a role that wins prizes easily.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Broadway in 1980, the first time around, ``Amadeus'' won five
Tony Awards, including one for Ian McKellen's florid Machiavel of a
Salieri. Tim Curry's manic-eyed Mozart went unrewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Milos Forman's 1984 film of the play won eight Academy Awards,
among them best picture and for the screenplay adaptation by
Shaffer; F. Murray Abraham's gravely obsessive Salieri was another
victor, whereas Tom Hulce's infantilized Mozart was not. After
opening in London, the current version received five Olivier
nominations and won one, for William Dudley's costumes. In the
supporting-performance category, Sheen lost out to Brendan Coyle in
``The Weir.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sir Peter first staged ``Amadeus'' at the National Theater in
1979 and then on Broadway, returning to it fresh last fall.
Speaking of Curry's performance and that of Simon Callow, who
originated the role in London, he said: ``Simon gave us something
of the punk Mozart of that particular time. He was extraordinarily
outrageous and engaging, like a puppy you shouldn't have let into
the house. Tim on Broadway had a great deal of poetry in him, a lot
of humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheen, who was a child in 1979, did not see either original
production. Instead, he talks of the way in which playing Jimmy
Porter has helped him to deepen his understanding of Mozart.
``They're both, in a sense, tyrannized by themselves,'' said the
actor, who has found Mozart and Porter ``the two most similar
characters I've ever played.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With Mozart,'' he went on, ``part of the tragedy is you see
that it isn't just the establishment, as represented by Salieri,
that destroys him; you see that he's sort of destroyed anyway _ by
himself, by his own talent, by the double-edged nature of genius.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheen attributes his fondness for the stage to a childhood
steeped in Gilbert and Sullivan, musicals and amateur dramatics. It
didn't hurt, he said, that his father, who worked in personnel
management, ``would always have liked to have been an actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the simple fact that the theater offers he has
received have excelled those in film, though he did appear
alongside Julia Roberts' in the 1996 flop ``Mary Reilly.'' He was
seen to better effect last year in ``Wilde,'' playing Robbie Ross,
the romantic prospect Oscar Wilde passes over in favor of Lord
Alfred Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the stage, Sheen focuses much of his time around Lily,
his new daughter _ she will be a year old at the end of January _
by the actress Kate Beckinsale, Sheen's partner. The two met in a
touring production of Chekhov's ``Seagull'' in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Beckinsale has been making her name in films, from ``The
Last Days of Disco'' and ``Brokedown Palace'' to the forthcoming
movie version of Henry James' ``Golden Bowl,'' with Nick Nolte and
Uma Thurman. Sheen has mostly worked in the theater since leaving
the prestigious Royal Academy of Dramatic Art early in order to
appear on the West End in 1991 with Vanessa Redgrave in ``When She
Danced.''
</P>
<P>
   Because his stage roles have been so absorbing, Sheen has tried
to imagine what would happen were his various characters to meet.
``If you could combine Jimmy Porter and Mozart,'' he said, smiling,
``that would be a formidable force in the world.'' He paused:
``It's one long dinner party inside my head.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
