<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2161 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-FATAL-FIRE-BOS &LR;      12-07 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-FATAL-FIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAIR CHARGED IN FIRE THAT KILLED 6 FIREFIGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS AND MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ As firefighters raced into a burning
warehouse Friday night in search of reported squatters a homeless
couple who lived inside and allegedly started the fire during a
fight were a short walk away, listening to music knowing that the
building was ablaze, investigators said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Julie S. Barnes and her boyfriend, Thomas S. Levesque, never
reported the fire after they tried, but failed, to put out the
blaze that ultimately killed six firefighters, authorities charged.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Barnes, a 19-year-old high school dropout, and
Levesque, 37, were being held on $1 million bail after being
charged with six counts of involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Worcester authorities say the two accidentally started the fire
when they knocked over a candle during an argument.
</P>
<P>
   As the fire gained strength, destroying their belongings, they
tried to save their dog and cat, but gave up. So, authorities said,
they walked to the Worcester Center, a downtown mall, where they
listened to music, before spending the night at a friend's house.
</P>
<P>
   During their arraignment, Barnes kept her head down. Levesque,
whose hair was uncombed, tried covering his face with his arm and
winced as a judge read the bail amount.
</P>
<P>
   Little is known about the couple, who had reportedly lived in
the vacant Worcester Cold Storage and Warehouse Co. with other
homeless people for several months. Barnes dropped out of Wachusett
Regional High School when she was a sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night Levesque's father, Gerard Levesque interviewed
outside his home here, had little to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sorry for the people that died,'' Levesque said, his
voice cracking. ``That's all we're sorry for.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday firefighters continued to comb through the smoldering
wreckage in search of five firefighters still buried in the rubble.
The body of one of the firefighters, Timothy Jackson, 51, was
removed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Thurday a memorial for the six men at the Worcester Centrum is
expected to draw as many as 20,000 firefighters from across the
country and as far away as Australia. President Clinton is expected
to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a story that is already tragic, seemed even sadder,
as it became clear to some officials that the deaths of the six
firefighters might might have been avoided. It was a poignant
reminder of the heroism of the firefighters, officials said, who
went into the burning warehouse trying to save those at the margins
of society.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earlier you detect and report a fire, the safer it's going
to be for us,'' District Chief Walter Giard said. ``A fire in a
normal building doubles every minute, so in five minutes it's not
five times bigger but 25 times bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   The other five firefighters killed in the conflagration were
Paul Brotherton, 41; Jeremiah Lucey, 38; Lieutenant Thomas Spencer,
42; James Lyons, 34; Joseph McGuirk, 38.
</P>
<P>
   Though upset at the news of the arrests, many firefighters said
ther job was not to pass judgment but to respond to calls for help
and try to save anybody who might be in danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it you know firefighters are firefighters.
Many of us die because of our jobs, whether it's heart problems or
cancer,'' said Worcester Fire Inspector Victor George. ``We are out
there to save lives. No matter who it is _ good people, evil people
_ we still would've tried to save them.''
</P>
<P>
   Worcester Deputy Fire Chief Ralph Lombardi shared George's
sentiments: ``They probably just didn't realize what they were
doing,'' he said of the homeless couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had no idea what was going to happen. We expect people to
be responsible of course. Evidentally, they didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Lombardi said there have been numerous fires in the back of the
warehouse, which is separated from the rest of the building by a
brick wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a fire there last year, where (the homeless) had set up
like a loft,'' Lombardi said. ``It was a pretty good fire going up.
But we put it out.''
</P>
<P>
   He said homeless people who live there use candle light because
there is no electricity inside.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the neighborhood around the warehouse, known as
Grafton Hill, it was well known that squatters lived inside the
sprawling building. But city officials said they were unaware that
any homeless people were living inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have knowledge of homeless getting into the
building,'' said David Holden, the city building commissioner.
``There have been no complaints filed with this department of
homeless people living there.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there had been a complaint earlier this year of the
building not being secured. An inspector was sent to the site, and
ordered the owner, Ding On ``Tony`` Kwan, to secure any openings.
Within 24 hours, as required by state law, Kwan secured it, Holden
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was just one complaint involving the building's
security this year, Holden said there have been others in recent
years. He was unable to give specific dates because he gave his
records to the city manager, who is reviewing them. The city
manager, Thomas Hoover, did not return phone calls Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As firefighters continued to press their efforts to find their
five fallen comrades, the scope of the memorial continued to grow.
Amtrak is offerring firefighters who want to attend the solemn
event free transit aboard a special train departing New Haven early
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to address grieving firefighters and the
relatives of the six men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole nation is grieving over this, and I think it's
appropriate that our Commander-in-Chief be here,'' said
Representative James McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters are expected to flood Worcester. Busloads are
traveling from Cleveland and Toronto, said George Burke, spokesman
for the International Association of Fire Fighters. Others are
coming from California, Ireland and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   As a way of honoring the firefighters and teaching a lesson on
heroism, Worcester Mayor Raymond Mariano declared Thursday a ``Day
of Mourning.'' Schools will be closed and students will be required
to write an essay Friday on heroism and public service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heroes are not athletes who hit baseballs in front of
thousands of cheering fans,'' Mariano said. ``Heroes are ordinary
men and women who reach out every day to help their community.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, investigators found a regulator -- a device that
controls air pressure on breathing equipment used by firefighters.
Searchers had hoped the discovery would lead to a body, according
to Giard.
</P>
<P>
   The regulator was discovered in a 50-foot by 50-foot area in the
southeast corner of the building where investigators believe they
have the greatest chance of locating the five missing firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Cindy Rodriguez of the Globe staff helped prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
