<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2164 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-TEACHERS-CHEATING-     12-07 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TEACHERS-CHEATING-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS AND PRINCIPALS HELP PUPILS CHEAT, SAY NYC INVESTIGATORS
</HEADLINE>
  (with sidebar, NY-SCHOOL-CHEATING)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT32 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ School investigators on Tuesday charged that dozens
of teachers and two principals across New York City's public school
system had helped students cheat on the standardized reading and
mathematics tests that help determine how schools are ranked and
whether students move on to the next grade. The cheating incident
appears to be one of the largest in the recent history of American
public schools, the investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   At some schools, teachers and principals let students mark their
answers on scrap or notebook paper then told the them which answers
to correct when they filled in the bubbles in the official test
booklets, the investigators said. At others, they directed students
to erase incorrect answers, or even changed the answers themselves.
The investigators said that in a particularly egregious case,
Evelyn Hey, the principal of Public School 234 in the Bronx, had
used all three methods to improve the test scores of third graders.
</P>
<P>
   Students' performance on the tests improved remarkably at many
of the schools, and two were even removed from a statewide list of
failing schools, said Edward Stancik, the special investigator for
New York City schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their purpose was simply to improve their own reputations and
further their own careers by creating the illusion that they were
doing a good job,'' Stancik said Tuesday after releasing a report
that laid out the evidence against the teachers and principals.
``The Board of Education has failed to do an effective job in
uncovering or punishing cheating.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges of widespread cheating between 1995 and this year _
against 32 elementary and middle schools, 43 teachers, two
principals and two paraprofessionals _ come at a time when
educators are under unprecedented pressure to improve student
performance nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The pressure has been particularly intense in New York City,
where many students are performing below grade level. Schools
Chancellor Rudy Crew removed five district superintendents last
summer, largely on the basis of their failure to improve student
performance on state and citywide tests. And in new annual
evaluations that will determine whether they can keep their jobs,
school principals will be partly judged on student test scores.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, two school districts in Brooklyn are experimenting
with a merit pay program that gives financial rewards to teachers
and principals in schools where test scores improve, and Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani has expressed interest in expanding the program
despite warnings that it might encourage cheating.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The investigators did not criticize the increased emphasis on
test scores Tuesday, saying the Board of Education simply needs
more aggressive strategies for preventing cheating and weeding out
teachers who engage in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let the cheaters completely alter our education
policies,'' Stancik said. ``The way to deal with cheaters is to
single them out and punish them.''
</P>
<P>
   The tests of ``easily over 1,000 students were tainted'' by the
actions of teachers or principals, Stancik said. He added that
investigators had not attempted to track whether any students had
been improperly promoted or held back as a result of the tainted
tests.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference Tuesday, afternoon, Crew said the
allegations were disturbing, but added that he did not believe such
cheating was rampant. He said he felt ``very bad for the children
involved,'' and lamented that the charges would ``unfortunately
give the entire school system a black eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew said he had introduced precautions to discourage cheating,
including a requirement that schools keep test booklets under lock
and key from the time they arrive in schools to the time the tests
are administered.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have 1,100 schools in New York City, and there are
always going to be people who find it necessary in one form or
another to find a way of being able to try to gain an advantage by
virtue of doing something like this,'' he added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The suspected educators will be reassigned to duty at their
district offices while Board of Education officials study the
evidence and determine whether they should be fired, said Karen
Crowe, a spokeswoman for Crew. In his report, Stancik recommended
that at least 12 of the 47 educators charged with cheating lose
their jobs immediately. In addition to the 47, four principals and
an assistant principal were cited by investigators not for cheating
but for mishandling complaints.
</P>
<P>
   In his comments to reporters Tuesday, Crew alluded to his thorny
relationship with Stancik. In 1997, Crew even called upon Stancik
to resign, saying that his reports on corruption in the school
system tended to be exaggerated and that many unfairly damaged the
system's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Stancik said his office began the cheating investigation in July
1998, after teachers at two schools in District 9 in the Bronx came
forward to reveal a history of cheating in their schools. Stancik
began by investigating those schools, and eventually expanded the
investigation to include schools in all five boroughs, many of
which his office or the Board of Education had received tips about.
The investigators also singled out schools that had reported rapid
and steep improvements in student performance, Stancik said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators interviewed teachers and administrators, but
most of their witnesses were elementary and middle school students,
who described several methods teachers had used to manipulate their
test scores. Stancik said that for the students, the cheating had
the effect of ``an emotional roller coaster that occurs when the
tests go way up and then come way back down.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave the example of a fourth-grade girl whose reading score
increased from the 12th percentile _ meaning she outperformed only
12 percent of a nationwide sample of students _ to the 81st
percentile when her teacher gave her clues or answers. But the
girl's score plummeted back to the 19th percentile the following
year, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Crew and state Education Commissioner Richard Mills said Tuesday
that it was too early to know if the students or the schools
involved would face any academic consequences. But Stancik said the
evidence his office had unearthed should not be used to make
assumptions about the test scores of students systemwide.
</P>
<P>
   Stancik released the names of all the teachers and principals
accused of involvement in the cheating, but many did not return
calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Virgeous Bridgett, a teacher at Community Elementary School 4 in
the Bronx, said that she had never used any of the cheating
techniques described in the report. ``I'm really shocked that the
children would say these things,'' said Ms. Bridgett, who has
taught at the school since 1988. ``This definitely is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Hay, the principal at PS 234, said only, ``It's all based
on hearsay; I'm not at liberty to talk about it.'' The report
accused Ms. Hay of directing third graders to write their answers
on separate pieces of paper, then walking around the room and
telling the children, ``Do that one over,'' until all the answers
were correct. Only then did Ms. Hay tell students to write their
responses on the official answer sheets, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, a teacher at PS 31 on Staten Island pointed to
wrong answers on a 1998 math test taken by third graders, then told
students to ``try to get the answers right before putting them on
the grid paper,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Stancik said that he had no evidence of wrongdoing by Crew, but
he said the Board of Education's Office of Investigative Services
had repeatedly failed to root out cheating. He also said officials
in that office had impeded his investigation by claiming to have
misplaced information about some of the implicated schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``No longer should anyone assume that even if the cheating is
uncovered, it will be buried and just go away,'' Stancik said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
