<P>
   (NYT38) PITTSBURGH -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- HKN-PENGUINS-LEMIEUX-2 --
Mario Lemieux now goes to work in a building with a view of his old
office, the Igloo, in Pittsburgh. ``Obviously, it's a learning
process,'' he says. ```It was very important that I bring in some
people who know how to run a business and I can learn from these
people.'' (Gary Tramontina/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) UNDATED -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- OBIT-SWANSON-B&AMP;W -- Robert A.
Swanson, who co-founded Genentech Inc. and is considered the father
of the biotechnology industry, died Monday at his home in
Hillsborough, Calif., after a yearlong battle with brain cancer. He
was 52. (Terrence McCarthy/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) PRIMYKANIYE, Russia -- Dec. 7, 1999 - CHECHNYA-RUSSIA-5-
-- Lt. Gen. Vladimir Bulgakov, who led the Russian assault on rebel
positions in the region, on Tuesday with his troops. ``If we are
commanded to seize it, we will,'' Bulgakov said about taking
Grozny, the Chechen capital. Primykaniye is a rural settlement near
Grozny, and its capture was part of the Russian campaign to
encircle the capital. (James Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) UNDATED -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 12 --
MORIYAMA-PHOTOS-B&AMP;W -- ``Shibuya, 1967,'' by Daido Moriyama: a
scavenger eye whose often blurred, scratched and underexposed work
reflects a mistrust of controlled, perfect prints. Moriyama, 61,
has enjoyed a scholarly star treatment that no other Japanese
photographer has ever been given in this country. (San Francisco
Museum of Modern Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- BOX-JOHNSON-FAMILY -- At a
media-attended tribute to Stephan Johnson, the Brooklyn-born
fighter who died Sunday of head injuries he received in a bout in
Atlantic City two weeks ago, the boxer's mother, Ira Johnson,
comforts her daughter Nicole, who breaks down, crying ``I just want
Stephan back.'' Questions still linger about Johnson's medical
condition when he stepped into the ring. (Elizabeth Lippman/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) PITTSBURGH -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- HKN-PENGUINS-LEMIEUX --
Mario Lemieux taking in a Penguins game with his son, Austin. Three
seasons into retirement as a player, he is the team's principal
owner. (Gary Tramontina/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- NY-TEACHERS-CHEATING --
Edward Stancik, the special commissioner of investigation for the
New York City school district, points to samples of what he
characterized as evidence of cheating on standardized tests, during
a news conference on Tuesday. Exposing what they called one of the
largest cheating scandals in recent history, investigators charged
that 52 teachers and principals in 32 of New York City's public
schools have been helping students cheat on the tests that help
determine whether they move on to the next grade. (Frances
Roberts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) IN THE NEVADA DESERT -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
DEC. 12 -- UN-SCULPTURED-ART -- Workers pouring volcanic-cinder
concrete on a stele of Complex 2 at Michael Heizer's ``City'' in an
empty Nevada valley. What now exists of ``City'' has got to be one
of the most massive modern sculptures ever built. (Dia Center for
the Arts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) SEATTLE -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- SEATTLE-POLICE-CHIEF -- Norm
Stamper, left, shakes hands with Mayor Paul Schell, of Seattle,
after Stamper announced his resignation as the city's police chief
on Tuesday during a news conference. Stamper became the first
political casualty of the violent protests that disrupted the World
Trade Organization conference. (Paul Joseph Brown/The Seattle
Post-Intelligencer) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- GORE-RUBIN -- Vice President
Al Gore addresses the audience at New York University Law School on
Tuesday. Hoping to be seen as the trustee of America's economic
prosperity, Gore campaigned Tuesday alongside former Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin, standing at left, who called Gore the
``best equipped to lead our country into the next century.''
(Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 12 --
METROPOLITAN-OPERA -- Jane Eaglen and Ben Heppner in the title
roles of the Metropolitan Opera's new ``Tristan und Isolde.'' The
production, now near the end of its limited run, has been a
considerable success. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) LONDON -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 12 --
AMADAEUS-THEATER -- Michael Sheen outside the Royal National
Theater in London. Playing Mozart in ``Amadeus'' - a prodigy so
poisoned, whether literally or figuratively, that he dies in 1791
at the age of 35 - Sheen has been acclaimed for laying bare both
the fear and unknowable brilliance behind his character's brattish
persona. (Jonathan Player/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 12 --
LOAMY-ART -- William Dilworth, curator of Walter de Maria's ``New
York Room,'' a sculpture made up of 250 cubic yards of earth piled
22 inches deep. Some 10,000 people visit the piece annually. One
can't walk on it - a glass barrier contains the earth and keeps
people out - but a loamy smell definitely permeates the space. (Don
Hogan Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- NY-COSTUME-GALA-3 -- The
actors Liam Neeson and Natasha Richardson, right, and Anna Wintour,
the editor in chief of Vogue. at the Costume Institute's annual
gala at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. The dinner, which was
billed as a salute to rock style, attracted guests of a mix rarely
seen at a party in New York. (Philip Greenberg/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- NY-COSTUME-GALA-2 --
Celebrity daughters of celebrities at the Costume Institute's
annual gala at the Metropolitan Museum of Art: from left, Gwyneth
Paltrow, Stella McCartney and Liv Tyler. (Ms. McCartney and Ms.
Tyler's shirts say ``Rock Royalty.'') The dinner, which the Met
likes to call the party of the year, has always had a reputation
for being glamorous enough to attract a melange of designers.
(Philip Greenberg/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- NY-COSTUME-GALA-1 -- Puffy
Combs, with Jennifer Lopez at the Costume Institute's annual gala
at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, got the party rocking. The
dinner, which was billed as a salute to rock style, brought out a
spectacular array of musical and show business luminaries, to say
nothing of rhinestones and cleavage. (Philip Greenberg/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- NY-LENNON-CURFEW -- Visitors
Saturday at the mosaic circle in Central Park which honors John
Lennon, a former member of the Beatles, who was killed 19 years ago
Wednesday. The police say they will enforce a 1 a.m. curfew at the
memorial. Organizers complain that heavy police patrols have
brought an intimidating presence to an event honoring a musician
who championed freedom of expression. (Nancy Siesel/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) PHILADELPHIA -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- PLAIN-LANGUAGE --
William Lutz, an English professor at Rutgers University in Camden,
N.J., at his home recently. Lutz is perhaps the most famous
plain-language advocate today. The plain-language movement is
enjoying a resurgence, and this time it could have staying power.
(Laura Pedrick/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 12 --
AIR-FORCE-MEMORIAL-COX-- An artist's rendering of the proposed Air
Force Memorial designed by James Ingo Freed of New York City's Pei
Cobb Freed and Partners Architects. The memorial is planned to be
constructed on a Virginian ridge overlooking the Potomac River. The
Air Force chose this prime spot near the rows of somber white
crosses at Arlington National Cemetery. But the Marine Corps
charges that the site is too close to its famed Iwo Jima Memorial.
caption (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- WHITNEY-BIENNIAL-2 --
Polaroids by Dawoud Bey. The 2000 Biennial at the Whitney Museum of
American Art, which opens on March 23 and runs through June 4, is
one of the museum's largest, with 97 artists. It is also one of the
most international. Twenty-one of the artists in the show were born
abroad but have migrated to the United States. (Whitney Museum of
American Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- WHITNEY-BIENNIAL-1 --
``Infectious Migrations,'' a mixed-media work by Rina Banerjee. For
its much anticipated 2000 biennial, the Whitney and its new
director, Maxwell L. Anderson, had little choice but to look
entirely outside the museum. Twenty-one of the artists in the show
were born abroad but have migrated to the United States. (Whitney
Museum of American Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- BIOTECH-COMPUTER-BOS
-- Christopher Ahlberg, founder and chief executive of Spotfire
Inc, rises above his office's partitions. Ahlberg developed the
idea for Spotfire, a bioinformatics company, while a doctoral
student at the University of Maryland's Human Computer Interaction
Laboratory. Bioinformatics increasingly is viewed as the glue that
will hold the discovery of new drugs together, with its
capabilities linked closely to two other cutting-edge research
techniques; high-throughput screening and combinatorial chemistry.
(David L. Ryan/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) BOSTON-- Dec. 7, 1999 -- FEDERAL-CASELOAD-BOS -- In a
Boston courtroom, technician Chris Gross adjusts teleconferencing
equipment so that Chief Judge William Young can hear what is going
on in his courtroom in Phoenix. ``I much prefer that trials take
place with judges in a courtroom.'' Judge Young says. ``But these
people in Arizona are waiting to get justice in their cases.''
Judges in the Phoenix division carry an average caseload of 500
civil cases and 100 criminal cases, while federal judges in
Massachusetts have an average caseload of about 250 civil and 28
criminal cases. (John Blanding/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WORCESTER, Mass. -- Dec. 7, 1999 --
MA-FIRE-WORCESTER-2-BOS -- Firefighters look down into what remains
of a warehouse during a search for the remains of their colleagues
on Tuesday. Fire crews from around the state manned Worcester fire
houses to free the city's firefighters for the search. The body of
one of the six firefighters killed Friday night was recovered
earlier this week. President Clinton will travel to Worcester on
Thursday to take part in a memorial service for the victims. (David
L. Ryan/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WORCESTER, Mass. -- Dec. 7, 1999 --
MA-FIRE-WORCESTER-1-BOS -- Ed Zine, a firefighter in Brockton,
Mass., holds his daughter Brieanna while standing next to his wife
Joanne on Tuesday during a visit to the scene of a warehouse fire
where six firefighters lost their lives. Zine's friend Jeremiah
Lucey was one of the firefighters killed. President Clinton will
travel to Worcester on Thursday to take part in a memorial service
for the six firefighters who perished Friday night. (Bill
Greene/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) CHICAGO -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- CADILLAC-SMITH -- John F.
Smith, 48, is in charge of the Cadillac division at GM and is a
rising star in the corporation. ``You have to plan way ahead to
make sure you can play equally well to your personal and
professional life,'' writes Smith, who is also the father of
15-year-old Lindsey and 11-year-old Roland. ``I'm going to be
missing meetings occasionally because of my kids' audition or
performance.'' (Cynthia Howe/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WESTFIELD, N.J. -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- WORKPLACE-RETAIL --
On weekdays, Jonathan Glacken makes his living in the high-pressure
world of Wall Street; on weekends, he unwinds as a part-time worker
at a Williams-Sonoma store. ``The pace I go at all day at work is
one of absolutely never-ending phone calls,'' he says. ``At the
store, I get a chance to take it all in: the kids running around,
the people talking about their families, about cooking. I love the
customers.'' (Jeff Zelevansky/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- CHINESE-BOOK-REVIEW -- ``The
Chinese Kitchen'' by Eileen Yin-Fei Lo. Ms. Lo grew up in Sun Tak,
in Canton, before moving to the United States in 1959. She has
taught Chinese cooking for 20 years and has written six cookbooks.
But this one is her most ambitious, with 250 recipes plus chapters
on Chinese wines, teas, ingredients and culinary history. (The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- CHRISTMAS-COOKIES -- Holiday
cookie-making does not have to be a time-consuming project. From
left: peanut meringues, nut diamonds, orange mocha brownies and
apricot dreams are all made in quantity in sheet pans. (Tony
Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- SALADS-CHEFS-3 -- A
mesclun-shiitake salad with Nobu's dressing. Enter the stealth
salad dressing, invisible to the eye but evident to the tongue. The
inspiration for these new dressings are the baby lettuces and
fragile microgreens, like sunflower and buckwheat sprouts, that
have come onto the market. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- SALADS-CHEFS-2 -- Palladin's
vinaigrette atop sprouts and asparagus. Five to 10 ingredients, few
of them predictable, go into the subtle, light and tasty dressings
that are blended by the chefs at restaurants like Nobu, Palladin
and Local. (Boyd Hagen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- SALADS-CHEFS-1 -- Franklin
Becker of Local pours his sherry-shallot vinaigrette. Enter the
stealth salad dressing, invisible to the eye but evident to the
tongue. It is the reason that many salads in restaurants these days
have a delicious yet elusive quality that may puzzle diners trying
to replicate them at home. (Norman Y. Lono/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 7, 1999 - CLINTON-HEALTH -- President
Clinton, followed by Labor Secretary Alexis Herman, Richard
Davidson, president of the American Hospital Association, and
William Richardson, chairman of the Committee on Quality Health
Care in America, walk towards the Rose Garden for a news conference
on Tuesday. Clinton ordered the government to take steps to prevent
medical errors that kill tens of thousands of Americans a year. The
announcement comes one week after a study showed up to 98,000
people die every year due to medical errors. (Stephen Crowley/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) JERUSALEM -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- MIDEAST-ALBRIGHT -- Rabbi
Rabinowitz, right, assists Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak with
the lighting of Hanukah candles in Barak's office on Tuesday.
Israel said on Tuesday it would not launch new settlement projects
before a final peace treaty is signed, but the Palestinians said
the promise was not enough to bring them back to the negotiating
table. The crisis erupted just as Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright arrived in the Middle East to check progress in
negotiations on a final peace treaty. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ZNAMENSKOYE, Russia -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- CHECHNYA-RUSSIA-4
-- A woman paints a room at a refugee camp set up in the town in
northern Chechnya on Tuesday. The Russian military dropped
thousands of leaflets over Grozny, the Chechen capital, on Monday,
warning residents of the besieged city to get out by Saturday or
risk death. (James Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ZNAMENSKOYE, Russia -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- CHECHNYA-RUSSIA-3
-- A woman sells potatoes in a market on Tuesday. The Russian
military dropped thousands of leaflets over Grozny, the Chechen
capital, on Monday, warning residents of the besieged city to get
out by Saturday or risk death. (James Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ZNAMENSKOYE, Russia -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- CHECHNYA-RUSSIA-2
-- A group of women with goods purchased in a nearby market wait by
the side of a road near a Russian army checkpoint on Tuesday near
Grozny, the Chechen capital. The Russian military dropped thousands
of leaflets over Grozny on Monday, warning residents of the
besieged city to get out by Saturday or risk death. (James Hill/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
