equipment so that Chief Judge William Young can hear what is going
on in his courtroom in Phoenix. ``I much prefer that trials take
place with judges in a courtroom.'' Judge Young says. ``But these
people in Arizona are waiting to get justice in their cases.''
Judges in the Phoenix division carry an average caseload of 500
civil cases and 100 criminal cases, while federal judges in
Massachusetts have an average caseload of about 250 civil and 28
criminal cases. (John Blanding/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WORCESTER, Mass. -- Dec. 7, 1999 --
MA-FIRE-WORCESTER-2-BOS -- Firefighters look down into what remains
of a warehouse during a search for the remains of their colleagues
on Tuesday. Fire crews from around the state manned Worcester fire
houses to free the city's firefighters for the search. The body of
one of the six firefighters killed Friday night was recovered
earlier this week. President Clinton will travel to Worcester on
Thursday to take part in a memorial service for the victims. (David
L. Ryan/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WORCESTER, Mass. -- Dec. 7, 1999 --
MA-FIRE-WORCESTER-1-BOS -- Ed Zine, a firefighter in Brockton,
Mass., holds his daughter Brieanna while standing next to his wife
Joanne on Tuesday during a visit to the scene of a warehouse fire
where six firefighters lost their lives. Zine's friend Jeremiah
Lucey was one of the firefighters killed. President Clinton will
travel to Worcester on Thursday to take part in a memorial service
for the six firefighters who perished Friday night. (Bill
Greene/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) CHICAGO -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- CADILLAC-SMITH -- John F.
Smith, 48, is in charge of the Cadillac division at GM and is a
rising star in the corporation. ``You have to plan way ahead to
make sure you can play equally well to your personal and
professional life,'' writes Smith, who is also the father of
15-year-old Lindsey and 11-year-old Roland. ``I'm going to be
missing meetings occasionally because of my kids' audition or
performance.'' (Cynthia Howe/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WESTFIELD, N.J. -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- WORKPLACE-RETAIL --
On weekdays, Jonathan Glacken makes his living in the high-pressure
world of Wall Street; on weekends, he unwinds as a part-time worker
at a Williams-Sonoma store. ``The pace I go at all day at work is
one of absolutely never-ending phone calls,'' he says. ``At the
store, I get a chance to take it all in: the kids running around,
the people talking about their families, about cooking. I love the
customers.'' (Jeff Zelevansky/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- CHINESE-BOOK-REVIEW -- ``The
Chinese Kitchen'' by Eileen Yin-Fei Lo. Ms. Lo grew up in Sun Tak,
in Canton, before moving to the United States in 1959. She has
taught Chinese cooking for 20 years and has written six cookbooks.
But this one is her most ambitious, with 250 recipes plus chapters
on Chinese wines, teas, ingredients and culinary history. (The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- CHRISTMAS-COOKIES -- Holiday
cookie-making does not have to be a time-consuming project. From
left: peanut meringues, nut diamonds, orange mocha brownies and
apricot dreams are all made in quantity in sheet pans. (Tony
Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1999 -- SALADS-CHEFS-3 -- A
