<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2172 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLA-MUSEUM-BATTLE-COX     12-07 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-MUSEUM-BATTLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Company, state say family must leave
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMDALE, Fla. _ Decades before Disney made Florida safe for
cartoon-based tourism, Tom Gaskins Sr. built the quirkiest of
roadside attractions from the boiled and peeled knees of cypress
trees.
</P>
<P>
   The late craftsman's creations were gnarled, enigmatic and
otherworldly, covered with Elephant Man-like lumps or shimmering
like satin. Transformed, the knobby growths resembled almost
anything imaginable: polar bears and poodles, Adolf Hitler and
Groucho Marx, Spanish castles and a lady hippopotamus wearing a
Carmen Miranda hat _ even, to one classically minded connoisseur,
the Trojan priest Laocoon and his sons being strangled by serpents.
</P>
<P>
   Now a $46 million land deal is threatening to strangle Gaskins'
collection of arboreal artifacts, encased behind streaked glass in
a squat museum far removed from Florida's theme park mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   The sale, by the agricultural giant Lykes Bros., gave the state
nearly 60,000 acres of land and development rights along Fisheating
Creek west of Lake Okeechobee. That included ownership of the
15-acre homestead where the Gaskins family has lived and worked
since 1936.
</P>
<P>
   The state says Gaskins' heirs must leave the land by April. And
if that happens, son Tom Gaskins Jr. says, he'll probably have to
close the family-run Cypress Knee Museum just across U.S. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The Gaskins family holds a deed to the 2 acres where the museum
sits. But Lykes owns the land where they live, by all accounts
under a vaguely worded gentlemen's agreement 63 years ago between
the elder Gaskins and the company.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a handful of houses that the Gaskinses built by hand
from cypress shingles and palm logs, the homesite includes a
workshop where tourists can buy the family's popular line of
handcrafted turkey calls. It also features a narrow wooden catwalk
that lets visitors view the protruding cypress knees in their
natural habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gaskins Jr. is fighting to stay, and supporters hope he can
make a deal with Lykes and the state. State and company officials
offer little hope, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to make any fuss or wrangle with anybody,'' said
Gaskins Jr., 58, who has crafted many of the cypress knees himself
and lives on the homestead with his wife, Billie Jo, and their two
sons and a daughter-in-law. ``I just want to be a little cypress
museum curator and a real good turkey call maker and live and let
live.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he can't help feeling discouraged about the
pressures facing the museum, which also has been buffeted by
disrepair, dwindling tourism, run-ins with state transportation
officials and some attempted burglaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I've got sharks and jackals trying to dismantle my
father's life work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As often happens in such bureaucratic impasses, the people in
charge say their hands are tied.
</P>
<P>
   Lykes corporate counsel Beth Waters said the state is insisting
that the company remove Gaskins from the homesite to remove any
questions about title to the land. ``We really don't have any
choice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither does the state, said Eva Armstrong, director of state
lands for the Florida Department of Environmental Protection. She
said the state bought the land with money from its Preservation
2000 program, which requires the property to be used for
conservation _ not private homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't mean the man ill will at all,'' she said. She added
that if Gaskins thinks he has some legal claim to the land, ``His
dispute is with Lykes.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said the state is giving Gaskins a break by allowing
him until April to make arrangements to leave, even though the sale
closed last week. He also can take whatever property he's entitled
to _ though that might not include the houses he and his father
built.
</P>
<P>
   Waters said she hopes Gaskins won't close the museum, especially
since Fisheating Creek will now feature a state wildlife area
expected to draw tourists. ``I would think the museum would only
benefit from this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gaskins said he's afraid of what might happen to the museum
if he's not around full-time to keep an eye on it. He said he's
already caught a Miami physician in the middle of carting away
cypress knees, and once he scared away intruders breaking into a
display case.
</P>
<P>
   Gaskins owns 20 secluded acres a mile away, but he said he'd
rather trade that land to Lykes than move there. Much about the
case remains in dispute, including whether Lykes has ever formally
told Gaskins he must leave. (Waters said the company sent him a
certified letter last month. He denies receiving it.)
</P>
<P>
   Both Gaskins and Lykes agree that his father had no fancy
contract when he moved onto the company's land in the midst of the
Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Gaskins said Lykes told his father, ``Come down here and build
all you want to.'' He said Lykes also encouraged his dad to cut the
cypress knees to the ground to clear grazing space for the
company's cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, offering a slightly different account, said the elder
Gaskins agreed to pay the company part of his earnings. Lykes
hasn't gotten a check for a while but has allowed the family to
stay, Waters said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gaskins Sr. used the land to create an art form and an
eccentric slice of Old Florida as he wandered the swamp barefoot
harvesting the knobby knees that protrude up from the cypress
trees' roots.
</P>
<P>
   He'd look for interesting-shaped specimens, harvest them, steam
or boil them like potatoes and peel away the bark, sometimes using
dental tools. Sometimes, as an experiment, he would encourage the
knees' growth into odd shapes by scarring them or inserting
arrowheads and bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Creativity runs in the Gaskins family. Tom Gaskin Sr.'s father
invented a roach trap that he sold all over the world, and his
grandfather invented a type of railroad car coupler.
</P>
<P>
   The knees landed Tom Gaskins Sr. on The Tonight Show during the
Johnny Carson years. But later he succumbed to Alzheimer's disease
before dying last year, and time has been unkind to his collection.
In 1992, Tom Gaskins Jr. had to take down the
cypress-and-plywood-advertisements that used to line 25 miles of
U.S. 27. Now they mostly cluster above the museum, somewhat
resembling the stick figures in the movieThe Blair Witch Project,
offering come-hithers to tourists who have already arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``HI FOLKS,'' says one. ``LOVELY DAY ISN'T IT,''
</P>
<P>
   says another. Yet another proclaims: ``FLORIDA HERITAGE AWARD IN
88,'' with one ``8'' drooping.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1960s to 1980s, the museum took in 100 to 175 visitors
each day during the winter tourist season. These days, ``we're
lucky to have a dozen people come through,'' Tom Gaskins Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonder the place has survived,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And if it doesn't, neither would his lifelong dreams and a piece
of Florida history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have basically sacrificed my whole dang life,'' he said.
``My whole business is here. If somebody kills this place, they've
killed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert P. King writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: bobking(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
