<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2173 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-WB-2TAKES-$ADV12-N     12-07 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WB-2TAKES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 RUNNING A NETWORK LIKE A '30s FILM STUDIO  (af) 
 Margy Rochlin's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about
Albert Brooks.  
 By MARGY ROCHLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a rival decided to take a few shots at the WB network in a
recent series of trade ads, at least one WB executive's response
was shock. Not at the attack, but at the package that it came in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, it almost looks like a Crazy Eddie ad,'' said Bob
Bibb, who is co-president of marketing at WB. ``There's no element
that states who they are.'' Then Bibb conducted his version of an
impromptu blind taste test. ``Close your eyes,'' he instructed.
What, he asked, do you think of when you hear that other network's
name? ``Now what images come to mind when you hear `WB'?''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it was a loaded question. Bibb knows that ``UPN''
conjures up, well, the letters U, P and N. Whereas, with ``WB,''
pictures and sounds flood in: camera-friendly, soulful-eyed young
stars, knowingly witty dialogue, lilting sulk-pop songs that
underscore story lines involving teen-size traumas.
</P>
<P>
   That you might also picture their embarrassing logo _ a cartoon
frog _ seems only to support the network's touching defense of its
corporate mascot, which is that although it has drawn ridicule, at
least it attracts attention.
</P>
<P>
   Bibb would probably prefer not to play his WB word association
game with some television columnists, though. Especially the
crankier ones who hear the netlet's name and can only think ``evil
trendsetter.''
</P>
<P>
   For three years running, WB has been the favored child of
Madison Avenue ad buyers, media types and teen-age-girl America. It
was only a matter of time before an onslaught of youth-oriented
series from every other broadcast network would hit the airwaves,
hoping to duplicate WB's success.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next reflects a television fact of life: highly
rated shows spawn a slew of pasty imitations, which ultimately
tank. The first casualty was Fox's ``Manchester Prep,'' which was
pulled before the broadcast of a single snide installment. The most
recent is ABC's ``Wasteland.'' Only 3 of 13 completed episodes of
this singularly uncaptivating Gen X evening soap were shown.
</P>
<P>
   This news, along with each notice of a youth-show expulsion, has
been greeted with a joyful cry from mortgage-holding,
property-tax-paying pundits who seem to be under the impression
that every cancellation is a victory for 40-somethings everywhere,
that maturity has bravely beaten back the hormonal tide of
adolescent viewers.
</P>
<P>
   But what if this season isn't about the waning of a trend but
about the entrenching of a network that runs itself as if it were a
self-contained television theme park? Over at WB, a trio of
freshman shows are doing well: ``Popular,'' ``Roswell'' and
``Angel,'' the last an offshoot of WB's flagship, ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer.'' Of course, none of the new shows have gone above
No. 107 in the ratings, but by WB standards they're hits.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three has growing buzz and critical support. Each is
harmonious in tone with the returning WB standard-bearers:
``Dawson's Creek,'' ``Felicity,'' ``Charmed'' and ``Buffy.'' Each
is set in the present day in one of three WB preferred locations:
high school, college or flunky-job-early-stage adulthood. Each lets
an ensemble of three to six characters wrestle with rotating stock
problems: best friend betrayals, crushes from afar, blossoming
romantic feelings, dwindling romantic feelings, whether or not to
go all the way and parents who just can't seem to grasp the genuine
breadth and gravity of their kids' mini-tempests.
</P>
<P>
   (In the case of ``Roswell'' and ``Angel,'' these predicaments
can be presented as both real and metaphorical. The former is about
three stranded-on-earth extraterrestrial teenagers, while the
latter involves an introspective vampire who hopes to offset
200-plus years of neck-biting barbarity by working as a do-gooder
for hire in Los Angeles.)
</P>
<P>
   Complementing these traits is the contract player quality of the
various casts. The network achieved this by hiring from what Lewis
Goldstein, the other co-president of marketing, calls the WB
``stable of stars.'' By this, Goldstein means young, but perhaps
inexperienced, actors who've turned in a memorable guest
performance or been the third or fourth lead on another WB series,
who are then shuttled from show to show and, occasionally, if
ready, promoted out of the chorus.
</P>
<P>
   It's an idea modeled after film studios in the 1930s, ``where
you'd see Frank Morgan in `The Wizard of Oz' and in the next movie
he'd be a Park Avenue sophisticate,'' said Bibb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I think everybody is saying, `I want to make sense
of what I'm watching,''' he added. ``I find a great comfort in the
History Channel. When I turn it on, I know I'm probably going to
see something about Nazi Germany or the Pyramids, but at least I
know what I'm going to get.''
</P>
<P>
   For WB's comfort recipe, remove scratchy footage of Der Fuhrer
and substitute a love triangle, say, or brooding close-ups of an
actor whom viewers have seen before. The whole ``stable of stars''
concept still has a corny ring, but it ensures a consistent,
all-important familiarity, which is perhaps WB's shrewdest
maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   For example, WB didn't have to introduce its target 12-to-34
female demographic to Jason Behr as Max, the sensitive-guy alien
lead on ``Roswell''; they'd already met him as a preening Don Juan
last season on ``Dawson's Creek.'' Before Sara Rue made the
transformation into the acceptance-hungry Carmen on ``Popular,''
she was a wheelchair-bound bully on ``Zoe, Duncan, Jack and Jane.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As for David Boreanaz, he was, of course, Buffy's taboo vampire
boyfriend on ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' before being transferred
over to ``Angel.'' As spinoffs go, ``Angel'' appeared destined to
flop. What do you do with a hero who can function only after the
sun goes down? And what about Boreanaz's uncertain range and
reined-in line readings?
</P>
<P>
   Yet one reason ``Angel'' works is its double dose of WB-style
familiarity; the hilarious Charisma Carpenter, also shipped over
from ``Buffy,'' is a perfect complement to the deadpan Boreanaz.
And the pesky daylight problem? Judging from the frequency you see
sunshine pouring through the venetian blinds of Angel's office
window, the creators' solution is to hope you just don't notice.
</P>
<P>
   What does an ill-finessed franchise expander look like? Flip the
channel to Fox on Monday nights and check out ``Time of Your
Life.'' The premise is workable enough: Jennifer Love Hewitt takes
her super-chipper ``Party of Five'' waif, Sarah Reeves Marin, to
Manhattan. Here WB's familiarity mandate (is there a magazine cover
Ms. Hewitt hasn't been on?) has been employed, albeit with a twist:
if you feel as if you're already acquainted with the community of
personality types assembled around Ms. Hewitt, it's because they
were established last year on WB's New York girl show,
``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, lack of originality on ``Time of Your Life'' isn't the
show's worst fault. What hurts it most is that its upbeat air of
innocence and personal discovery seems to clash with the cynical
mood of its gleefully ribald follow-up, ``Ally McBeal.'' Shouldn't
it be linked on the weekly schedule to its parent series, ``Party
of Five,'' or even the grandparent of modern youth shows, ``Beverly
Hills 90210''?
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he'd do, WB's chief executive officer, Jamie
Kellner, balked. ``I don't comment on Fox's programming,'' said
Kellner, who was president and chief operating officer at Fox
before joining WB in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Kellner, however, has WB carefully considering the pairing of
new shows with returning ones, forming seamless two-hour
programming blocks this season. It seems logical to roll out
``Buffy,'' then ``Angel.'' Even more cagily, the snipefest
``Popular'' is matched with ``Charmed,'' starring the snipe-doyenne
Shannen Doherty.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year our flow is exceptionally strong,'' Kellner agreed.
In fact, a recent poll revealed that of the 20 television shows
most popular with teen-age girls, 10 are on WB.
</P>
<P>
   ``But last year we made horrendous mistakes,'' he said. ``That
really shook us up back into the rules of scheduling in a
multichannel universe, which is flow, flow, flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that WB is blunderproof. Devoting most of its meager
promotion budget to ``Roswell,'' the network ignored this season's
real breakway hit, ``Popular,'' which teenagers are now watching
more than ``Friends.'' Sitcom success still eludes them. And though
WB boasts about being the network that gives imperfect shows time
to fix themselves, its patch job on its hourlong drama ``Hyperion
Bay'' was adding to the cast Carmen Electra?
</P>
<P>
   And is there such a thing as television jail for whoever let
Keri Russell's blond locks go? Ever since the shearing of Ms.
Russell's bountiful My Little Pony tresses, ``Felicity's'' ratings
have dipped.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence? Kellner doesn't seem to think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should have never cut Keri's hair,'' Kellner said.
``The audience is clearly not happy with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he offered a final WB bylaw: ``Never fight the audience.
You'll lose every time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
