<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-TOBACCO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Action on tobacco plan unlikely this year
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ It's a near certainty that Gov. Bob Taft will
have to wait until next year for the legislature to send him a
final plan for spending the $10.1 billion Ohio is expected to
receive in the national tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Jo Ann Davidson, R-Reynoldsburg, said Tuesday that
the House will vote on its tobacco plan Thursday, probably in the
afternoon. By that time, senators are expected to have finished up
their work for the year and gone home.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson said that if, as expected, the House version differs
from the one approved Nov. 9 by the Senate, a conference committee
probably would be formed to settle the differences. The conference
committee could report back to the legislature early next year,
Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Milburn, Taft's spokesman, said that the governor hoped to
have the plan approved by the end of the year because next year's
schedule already is loaded with issues such as the capital
improvements budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Taft) wants to try to get this done by the end of the
year. If that's not something that is going to be possible for them
(legislators), he would like to get done as quickly as possible . .
. He (Taft) can understand that there is only so much time,'' Scott
Milburn, Taft's spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Milburn said Taft is very pleased that the House appears to be
leaning toward the 26-year spending plan he endorses. The Senate,
by a 17-16 vote on Nov. 9, approved a 13-year plan for spending
about $5 billion of the settlement. That means future legislatures
will have the chance to plan for spending the remainder of the
money.
</P>
<P>
   Money from the tobacco settlement is an integral part of Taft's
12-year plan to spend $10.2 billion in state money on school
buildings. He has cited the plan in the brief he filed with the
Ohio Supreme Court, asking it to reverse a lower court decision
that the state's school funding system is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson and Finance Committee Chairman Robert Corbin,
R-Washington Twp., said that they believe there is enough support
in Corbin's committee for it to approve a 26-year plan today and
send it to the House floor Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the speaker took the extraordinary step of appointing
herself and Speaker Pro Tempore Randall Gardner, R-Bowling Green,
to fill two Finance Committee vacancies to vote on the tobacco
bill. She and Gardner are familiar with the issue, Davidson said.
She also suggested that they provide added support for the 26-year
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson said that she does not believe that carrying over the
tobacco issue until next year will cause the legislature to start
over.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Scott Nein, R-Middletown, who voted against the bill in the
Senate , said that ``the longer this thing sits around it's great.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ought to be a lot more discussion, a lot more discussion
by all members of the legislature . . . I hope they go back to
square one,'' said Nein, who favors returning the money to
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the Republican-controlled Finance Committee turned
back a Democratic proposal to spend more than Taft wants to on
smoking prevention programs, with the extra money coming from funds
Taft wants to use for school buildings and technology. Taft's plan
calls for spending more than half the $10.1 billion on school
construction and technology.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also allocates money for health programs, law
enforcement, biomedical research and help for tobacco-farming
areas.
</P>
<P>
   William Hershey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
