<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: PARTY RE-ELECTS SCHROEDER
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder tightened his control over his
fractious Social Democratic Party, easily winning re-election as
chairman. Left-wing members have resisted his plans to slow the
rise in pension payments and reduce government spending about $16
billion a year. But Schroeder's popularity got a lift when he
backed the bailout of a major construction company and proposed
higher inheritance taxes, and delegates seemed more interested in
unity.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: EMPLOYERS OF FORCED LABOR
</P>
<P>
   The American Jewish Committee listed 255 companies, including
many new names, that reportedly used forced labor during the Nazi
era. The list is on the Web at www.ajc.org.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE: TURKEY THREATENED WITH VETO
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister George Papandreou said Greece would veto
Turkey's membership in the European Union if Turkey failed to
accept Greek demands in disputes over Cyprus and Aegean oil.
Members meet this week in Helsinki, Finland, to review enlargement
of the bloc. A Greek veto could end the detente that developed when
the countries aided each other after serious earthquakes this year.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: CRITICISM OF INDIA
</P>
<P>
   The military ruler, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, said India's leaders
have rejected the peace overtures he has made for Kashmir. A
solution to the stalemate over Kashmir is the first step to peace
in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: STEP FORWARD FOR MOSQUE DOORS
</P>
<P>
   Averting a potential confrontation with Muslim leaders, Prime
Minister Ehud Barak rejected demands that he rescind his
authorization of new doorways to an underground mosque at Haram
al-Sharif. The complex includes the Dome of the Rock, a mosque
sacred to Muslims, and the Western Wall, venerated by Jews.
Orthodox Jews and rightist politicians said the project could
damage unexcavated remains of an ancient Jewish temple. The new
doorways will provide emergency exits for the crowds during
Ramadan, the Muslim holy month, which begins Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
