<HEADLINE>
MAJOR CONTRACTS CANCELED WITH EUROPE'S LARGEST INFORMATION
TECHNOLOGY COMPANY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Mass., Okla., Mich., Ill., N.Y., Texas)   By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This fall, large corporations were expected to begin using a new
national center to process donations that their workers made to
United Way through payroll deduction, phasing out the need to cope
with the varying practices of the 1,300 local United Ways.
</P>
<P>
   But in its first test, the system, built by the American arm of
Cap Gemini Group, Europe's largest information technology company,
was unable to process gifts from employees of the Williams Co., the
Oklahoma pipeline and communications concern. United Way of America
then retained Deloitte &AMP; Touche, the consulting firm, which found
400 serious problems.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, without any public announcement, Betty Beene,
president of United Way of America, terminated Cap Gemini's
contract and scrapped the project, which cost $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Another large nonprofit group, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
canceled its $75 million contract with Cap Gemini on Aug. 31,
saying that the company ``consistently and systematically has been
unable to deliver what the contract required.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an antiquated computer information system built by Rube
Goldberg,'' said Frank Coleman, a spokesman for the chamber.
``Unfortunately, we hired Rube Goldberg's nephew to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   The president of Cap Gemini America, D. Michael Meyer, was too
busy to be interviewed, said his spokeswoman, Mary Ellen Horn. She
would not acknowledge that the company had a contract with United
Way of America but did say that the company ``met all the
contractual requirements'' under its contract with the chamber. Cap
Gemini and the chamber are suing each other in federal district
court in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Cap Gemini has several other troubled projects, according to
court records and interviews with executives who have done business
with the company.
</P>
<P>
   The parent company was hired for 400 million francs, or $62
million, to develop research and tracking software for the
Bibliotheque Nationale de France, but the software did not work,
according to reports in Paris newspapers. Both the library
administration and the union representing the library workers told
reporters that the work by Cap Gemini was the main issue in a
strike by library workers. The French government has since removed
Cap Gemini from the project.
</P>
<P>
   Cap Gemini America has numerous contract disputes in the courts,
records show. One client, International Micro Systems of
Carrollton, Texas, hired Cap Gemini to build a custom software
system but sued in February when it abandoned the project. ``They
felt the project was too small to make money, so they just stopped
working on it even though we had a contract,'' said the company's
owner, Sid Saber. The case has been settled, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saber said that a steady turnover of Cap Gemini employees
plagued his project. United Way of America and the Chamber of
Commerce reported similar problems.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Mrs. Beene confirmed to a reporter that she had
terminated the Cap Gemini project, and hours after Cap Gemini was
asked to comment on the contract termination, a Cap Gemini lawyer
called United Way of America. Mrs. Beene said the Cap Gemini lawyer
complained that the charity should have kept the matter
confidential and threatened litigation, which she said she wanted
to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Horn, the Cap Gemini spokeswoman, said the company would
have no comment on the lawyer's call. She also declined to comment
on other issues, referring a reporter to a Cap Gemini official in
Paris, who did not respond to two requests left in her voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   No donor money was lost, but the collapse of the United Way of
America project has thrown into disarray plans to make payroll
giving more efficient and attractive to companies with nationwide
operations.
</P>
<P>
   It has also renewed a struggle between United Way of America and
four large regional United Ways _ Boston, Chicago, New York
Tri-State and San Francisco _ which operate pledge processing
centers. The regional centers now want to expand and take over this
business, which would increase their power and generate fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dead,'' Virgil Carr, president of the Detroit United Way,
said of the goal of a national center. Ms. Beene said she was not
sure what would happen next.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
