<HEADLINE>
LESSONS FROM A WAGNERIAN VEGAS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Matthew Gurewitsch writes about the arts for The Wall Street
Journal and other publications.  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ What news on the Rialto?
</P>
<P>
   Since spring, they've finished construction on the bridge and
filled the Grand Canal; a few blocks down, a new Paris has its
Opera, Eiffel Tower and Hotel de Ville; and ``O'' has spoiled me
for ``The Ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Greetings from Las Vegas, self-styled Entertainment Capital of
the World, where I have lately landed to contemplate new frontiers
for opera: opera, for the purposes of this discussion, standing for
something greater than itself. Somewhat to the surprise of
commentators unattuned to the cyclical rhythms of cultural history,
an art form that not so long ago was being written off as a
moribund anachronism is experiencing something like a renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Though critics complain of a repertory in stagnation, every
season brings new titles anticipated with genuine excitement, and
archaeological work in areas long abandoned (Handel, the French
Baroque, early Mozart, bel canto) has expanded our sights quite a
bit.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the ascendancy of the stage director,
understood as the visionary in charge of the entire look, feel and
meaning of a production, has transformed opera into the paradigm of
theater itself. If opera has proved remarkably hospitable to
dabblers from the worlds of spoken drama, dance and all manner of
visual art, the reason is that everyone wants a piece of the
operatic action. All theater, it now seems, aspires to the
condition of opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prima la musica, poi le parole,'' or vice versa? What comes
first? The words or the music? In the contemporary climate, the
terms of that hoary debate seem oddly off the mark. On the list of
what makes opera the glorious folly it is, spectacle now vies for
supremacy with those two. Words are nothing in Las Vegas shows, and
the music is at best atmosphere. But the point of this pilgrimage
is spectacle, and spectacle is a commodity Las Vegas has always
cultivated in spades.
</P>
<P>
   Learning of my destination, some true believers in opera as our
grandparents knew it were openly contemptuous. ``Better you than
me,'' sniffed one, summing up the general attitude and suppressing
a yawn at the thought of the predictable fare awaiting him on his
usual circuit of lyric temples. Well, he had made his bed. My own
hope was to be jolted awake, my hunch being that opera could do
worse than to steal a page or two from the new Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The new Vegas! In old-time show-biz algebra, of course,
spectacle plus Las Vegas equaled girls, girls, girls: flamingos of
the floor show asparkle in beads and sequins. Then came the boys
from Germany, bearing big white cats and magic tricks.
</P>
<P>
   The latest extravaganzas are of a different order: pageants so
rich and strange that they refresh our concept of what operatic
stagecraft might be, potentially as influential as the ceremonies
of Robert Wilson once upon a time (but a lot more fun).
</P>
<P>
   The older shows are still eye-catching in their way, and an
opera director might have occasion to lift a page from them now and
then. In the interminable Captain Marvel fantasy that is Siegfried
and Roy's long-running show at the Mirage, a golden army rattles in
lock step, each knight hooked up to four empty suits of armor.
Elsewhere, Siegfried meanders among flower-petal maidens like a
senior Parsifal, encountering his Klingsor in the form of Roy, who
levitates in a ring of fire. The fearless pair also encounters a
dragon, Fafner to a heavy-metal T. The package has made a fortune.
(The figure one hears is half a billion dollars.)
</P>
<P>
   But the mind's eye of an opera fan adrift in Las Vegas can
project opera just about anywhere, free of charge. The exterior of
the new Venetian is ready-made for an alfresco ``Gioconda'' (all we
need is the girl). In the maze of Caesar's Palace, a Peter Sellars
``Clemenza di Tito'' is waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Idomeneo,'' cruise down to Mandalay Bay, with its man-made
seashore and its six-foot breakers. Glazed eyes in stony faces keep
from sight any demons clawing at the heart, yet the card tables at
the casinos evoke ``The Queen of Spades.'' The wheel of fortune
whirls as in ``The Gambler,'' though without the narcotic hum we
hear in Prokofiev.
</P>
<P>
   I came to Las Vegas for the waters. ``O,'' Cirque du Soleil's
site-specific aquatic spectacular, its title punning on the French
for that most seductive element of the four, occupies a
custom-built theater at Bellagio: a theater unsurpassed in boldness
by the Bayreuth Festspielhaus itself.
</P>
<P>
   Through the '90s, a string of touring shows established Cirque
du Soleil as the brand name for a New Age art of the circus. That
its aesthetic might also point new directions for opera might have
seemed far-fetched. Now that a show and its showcase have been
conceived in a single imaginative act, the kinship to the
integrative ideal of opera is plain to see.
</P>
<P>
   Misreading the literature, I understood ``O'' to take place
entirely underwater, behind one wall of a tank specially
microperforated so as not to fog up, with unseen respirators and
frogmen in place to supply the performers with air.
</P>
<P>
   The frogmen and respirators are there, beneath the surface of a
pool 100 feet across. But that surface, rather than the usual stage
floor, is what is seen from the house, and what is perforated is
sectional platforms that rise and drop undetectably under the
water. For dives from the 60-foot tower, the relevant sections sink
to their maximum depth of 25 feet. At other times, the whole
platform rises clear to stage level, and the cast seems to be
skipping on water, until the floor dries and is, temporarily, just
a floor.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the show, 16 pairs of feet sprout straight out
of the pool and start dancing upside down. Later, a kaleidoscopic
bevy of damsels clamber and balance into pyramid formation on a
floating raft, observed by four beach boys who, between plunges,
grace the pool's edge like so many Nijinsky fauns.
</P>
<P>
   Water is the sovereign element here, no question, but the others
count as well. At ground level, earth, an eerie procession files
by, led by the sharp-beaked demon that the Klytemnestra of
``Elektra'' saw in the watches of the night. In the air, gymnastic
phantoms man the ghost of a ship tossing through a tempest fit for
``The Flying Dutchman.'' Most soul-shaking of all are the fires.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
