<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2187 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-LAS-VEGAS-OPERA-2NDTA     12-07 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAS-VEGAS-OPERA-2NDTAKE-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LAS VEGAS: the fires.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picture this: Over here, a juggler bounds in, tumbling and
flying around the ball of fire he swings on a chain. Over there, a
hobo settles into his chair, reading his newspaper, unruffled as
flame starts to lick at the toe of his shoe, unruffled as it
spreads, enveloping the chair, his coat, his hat, his paper. At
length he rises, unperturbed, and calmly makes to leave. Ah, but
hasn't he forgotten something? Sure enough: the chair. Slowly he
turns, collects his property and turns again to vanish, slowly,
into the wings. What Tamino has ever done the like?
</P>
<P>
   The curtain is up. In the theater's ample wings, trailing
seaweed hair, masked nymphs limber up, as loose-limbed mermen hose
off and serene riders mount their airborne steeds. Flashlight in
hand, the technical director, Phil Jordan, ex of the Boston Ballet,
is conducting a private backstage tour. From the catwalk, we have
seen the curtain rip like the veil of the temple, then whisk out of
sight. Below stage level, behind plate glass as in an aquarium, we
have watched the clockwork choreography of the frogmen, all in
black, always in the right place at the right time with air.
</P>
<P>
   For the wet and scantily clad, the temperature is comfortable. A
civilian in their midst is finding the air a shade tropical. But
who cares? Before my eyes, in flesh and blood, are the
Rhinemaidens, the Dutchman's phantoms, the Men in Armor for ``The
Magic Flute'' of my dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to juggle on the street,'' explains Ray Wold, the
blazing hobo, his fires now out. ``People walked right by. I said
to myself: `I've got to make them stop. I'll set myself on fire.'''
As modest and affable a fellow as you could hope to meet, Wold
wears flame-resistant Kevlar from the crown of his bowler to the
tips of his shoes, but nothing to shield his face. This act is his
very own ``Nessun dorma.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mystere,'' Cirque du Soleil's first Las Vegas creation, is
still running strong in a custom-built theater of its own at
Treasure Island. In the fashion of so much contemporary theater, it
is ``nonlinear,'' but a series of images showing the transformation
of grub to butterfly sustains a clear arc of continuity.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes obviously, sometimes elliptically, the acts and
imagery develop a pervasive theme of growth and transformation. A
design motif of bulging oval bellies, like pregnancies affecting
the male as well as the female may please viewers with a stronger
taste than mine for the grotesque.
</P>
<P>
   But there are sequences that would shine in any setting: the
crystal-clear, stop-and-go group acrobatics on the ring of
vertical, ``Chinese'' poles, or the thunderous ritual pounding of
the Japanese drum, suspended in midair. Most wondrous of all _ and
in a metaphoric sense, the most musical _ are Marco and Paulo
Lorador, brothers from Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Their slow-motion hand-balancing routine (a dream of flight so
intimate that it feels almost too private to watch), unfolds like
the dialogue for violin and cello in the White Swan adagio of
Tchaikovsky's ``Swan Lake,'' which, as it happens, the composer
recycled from the love duet of his abandoned opera ``Undine.''
</P>
<P>
   Of perhaps more concrete interest to the visiting opera
impresario, ``Mystere'' features bungee aerialists, whose volleys
would adorn any number of operas of the exotic and supernatural,
from Monteverdi, Cavalli, Lully, Rameau, Handel, Haydn and Gluck
through Meyerbeer and Verdi to the fables of Rimsky-Korsakov,
Prokofiev's ``Love of Three Oranges'' and Henze's neglected ``Konig
Hirsch.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the latest ``Ring des Nibelungen'' at the Lyric Opera
of Chicago used lip-synching bungee Rhine-maidens, who got their
moves from Debra Brown, Cirque du Soleil's resident choreographer.
(``Die Walkure'' had silent doubles, too: spear-brandishing
Valkyries who bounded and somersaulted through the air from hidden
trampolines.) Ms. Brown has also worked on the premiere productions
of operas at the Metropolitan (``The Ghosts of Versailles'') and
the Canadian Opera Company (``The Golden Ass''), experiences she
treasures. Still, she wonders how far the unfamiliar medium will
allow her to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find myself in opera because of work I've done in circus,''
she says. ``But coming from circus, where there's no fourth wall,
I'd like to bring the action closer to the public, and I'm not sure
that's appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opera is the most prestigious of the arts. Circus is born on
the streets. That affects how they're delivered, the relationships
inside the creation. There's a whole different rhythm at the heart
of it all. Circus has no unions. People work for hours on end.
Their skills are honed on the street. They develop an exceptional
sense of timing. If they didn't grab your attention, they would
die. Their art is what puts food on their table.''
</P>
<P>
   But the differences may not be so profound after all. Opera,
however lofty it grows, has roots in popular entertainment, too,
and a singer has to grab your attention no less than a juggler.
Cirque du Soleil, as it has evolved, is no closer to the street
(and no farther) than La Scala. The question is, can the Cirque
aesthetic, fusing material of humble origin into a process akin to
opera at its most lavish, ever contribute more to opera than
fetching accents?
</P>
<P>
   A simplistic answer is no. Cirque du Soleil's shows develop as
self-standing artistic creations, generated through the synergy of
its director, Franco Dragone, and his production team, on one hand,
and the specific talents of the available performers, on the other.
The usual business of an opera house, in contrast, is to stage the
sort of pre-existing work we like these days to call a ``text.''
</P>
<P>
   Now factor in the economics. The theater at Bellagio was built _
with a proscenium stage and theater-style seating in place of the
cramped cocktail tables and banquettes of Vegas tradition _ at a
cost of $70 million; producing ``O'' came to another $22 million:
figures to strike terror in any impresario's heart. And running
costs?
</P>
<P>
   ``Still to be determined,'' answers Pavel Brun, an alumnus of
the Russian Theater Academy with credentials in pantomime,
choreography, Soviet jazz-rock and the aerial high bar, and the
artistic director of Cirque du Soleil's two Vegas shows.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 2154EST &QL; 
