<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2188 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-LAS-VEGAS-OPERA-3RDTA     12-07 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAS-VEGAS-OPERA-3RDTAKE-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LAS VEGAS: Vegas shows.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There's no prior experience in theater history for a
long-running aquatic show,'' Brun explains. ``We can get comparison
figures from related areas like bridge construction, cruise ships,
military operations.'' He warns against focusing on the green
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do a black-and-white show with sawdust, and it might
impress you just as much as this one,'' he declares. ``I'm very far
from believing that a humongous budget can surmount artistic
problems. Our touring show `Quidam' cost only $2 million Canadian,
which would be about $1.5 million American. That's nothing,
moneywise, but it had so many things to say.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, in any case, the bottom line for ``O'' remains
elusive. Fortunately, Steve Wynn, the chairman of Mirage Resorts,
has deep pockets. His was the entrepreneurial panache that
initiated the Cirque du Soleil shows as exclusive and, he hopes,
permanent Vegas fixtures. As for the income stream, tickets to
``Mystere,'' in a 1,500-seat theater, go for $70 a pop; for ``O,''
with 1,800 seats, the prices are $90 and $100.
</P>
<P>
   Each show does 476 performances a year, and most sell out. Thus,
box-office receipts from ``O'' must total some $80 million a year,
and Wynn's license to print money should be coming through any day
now.
</P>
<P>
   Again I ask, would a production anything like ``O'' be possible
in an opera house? Maybe the answer will be less simplistic this
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask if it would be possible to apply Cirque's style,
techniques and technology in the opera house,'' Brun shoots back.
``Definitely. I can't wait to see it happen. Are there plans? I
wish.''
</P>
<P>
   Brun reminds me that Cirque du Soleil is, after all, still in
the business of putting on a circus. The elements it integrates are
the ones that have been filling tents big and small for centuries.
What is different is the framework _ and the purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern opera and the modern circus have the same problem,'' he
says. ``Ballet, too. Technique becomes the star of the show, the
target of performance. That's wrong. Technique should be a
language.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see wonderful singers, but their technique is overwhelming.
We don't see a character, because the whole concentration is on the
voice. It's the same with a trick at the circus. The ringmaster
comes in and announces, `Now we'll show you the quadruple
somersault.' So what? For that I can go to the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   What is the most valuable lesson Cirque du Soleil might teach
the opera crowd? ``That production means much more than nice
costumes, a nice set, a nice budget,'' Brun answers. ``The job of
the director is to develop a vocabulary that goes for everybody,
from the diva down to the last chorus girl. It can't be done
quickly. The job is to create superior individuals. If the 15th
girl on the right is picking her nose, she's the one you see.''
</P>
<P>
   Could the Cirque team make this happen in an opera house? Could
an opera house do the job on its own?
</P>
<P>
   ``Without me, they can do nothing,'' Brun says, like other
ex-Soviets keeping a straight face when striking the peremptory
note.
</P>
<P>
   But he exaggerates. Over the centuries, excellence in operatic
production has broken forth from time to time. Even today, it is
not unknown. Living witnesses can testify to the power _ total, on
the right occasions _ of Wieland Wagner, Giorgio Strehler,
Jean-Pierre Ponnelle, John Dexter (especially in collaboration with
David Hockney), Gotz Friedrich, Harry Kupfer, Peter Sellars,
Herbert Wernicke, Liliana Cavani, Luc Bondy, Nicholas Hytner,
Dieter Dorn, Graham Vick.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lord Elgin in Athens or Napoleon in Egypt, an opera
producer on the loose in Nevada may catch the itch to plunder. Take
all you can afford that will serve your purposes, say I. But most
of all, look past the surface. Take fire, not window dressing. Let
vision guide you. Shun hollow effect. Return to first principles.
The gauntlet is down. Las Vegas has raised the bar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
