<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE LITTLE GUYS ARE BIG HEROES IN DEMANDING SPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My ultimate sports heroes are the jock kingdom's bravest, yet
they wear colorful silk shirts to work, don't outweigh a fashion
model, and stand about as tall as a bar stool.
</P>
<P>
   In the pursuit of their craft, they might have more
second-guessers within 90 seconds than Troy Aikman does in an
entire football season.
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association lists their profession as this
country's most dangerous. There are more deaths and serious
injuries in this line of work than coal mining, hanging steel on
skyscrapers or coaching the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Guaranteed contracts are nonexistent. You win or you don't eat,
but even when you do eat, it amounts to birdseed. At a mere 125
pounds, you'd be considered fat, lazy, out of shape and definitely
out of work.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, pound-for-pound you must be physically
stronger than any football player, hockey player or weight lifter.
Powerful hands, arms and legs are an absolute necessity. This must
be achieved on a constant diet of lettuce and cucumbers.
</P>
<P>
   It is a business where you can become famous and, in limited
cases, almost a household name in sports. But the overall respect
factor when compared to other jock stars is not even remotely
close.
</P>
<P>
   This is an injustice, but so it goes in the world of
thoroughbred race riding.
</P>
<P>
   Jockeys are my ultimate heroes, even when I cuss 'em like crazy
over some $20 win ticket that went uncashed because a preferred
steed didn't hit the wire first. No matter the athletic skill,
instinct, muscle and bravery, the jockey is always at the mercy of
a 1,200-pound animal who is running 35 mph with a mind of his own.
Over a measly $20, I sometimes forget that part about the horse.
</P>
<P>
   But on other days, there's also the perfect ride, when the
jockey got more out of his animal than you thought the horse had.
Particularly if you own part of that horse with a group of buddies,
and the date was Jan. 16, 1997, and the place was famous Santa
Anita Park in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Zika was our horse, and he would never amount to much, but late
that afternoon nearly three years ago, we were prouder of the Z-man
than the owners of Secretariat. In a maiden claiming race for
$40,000, he won like a champion, but what really mattered was he
was ridden by a champion.
</P>
<P>
   The win picture on the wall at home is autographed by Laffit
Pincay Jr.
</P>
<P>
   If the racing gods are with him, and there are no crippling
crashes, this week Pincay will become the all-time leading rider of
thoroughbreds. Entering Wednesday's racing card at Hollywood Park,
Laffit needs three wins to break Bill Shoemaker's record of 8,833.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no sports world countdown for the soon-to-be
53-year-old Pincay _ horse racing doesn't get that kind of media
play. But in reality, this record is more impressive than Aaron,
than Gretzky, than Rose. Just the injury factor and the strict
weight restrictions alone say it's impossible to have stayed at the
top of your game for Pincay's 36 years of climbing aboard winning
horses.
</P>
<P>
   And for ol' Zika to have been one of his 8,834, it just proves
Pincay is part miracle worker.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want to define an entire career with one ride, that
also has a local angle. It was last June at Lone Star Park at Grand
Prairie (Texas) in the National Jockey Championship.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of Lone Star's most popular events with the fans,
who see the nation's leading riders converge on Grand Prairie. But
they are here for charity to benefit injured riders, and the big
names lose money by leaving mounts at such tracks as Hollywood,
Churchill and Belmont to ride at Lone Star.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, some riders treat it as an exhibition. Others,
however, don't. For instance, Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   On a claiming race on the grass, Alex Solis, a Southern
California-based rider, had his horse veer sharply out of the gate,
hitting another horse, and then Solis tumbled to the ground,
thankfully uninjured.
</P>
<P>
   But that left a loose horse on the track, which is dangerous to
the other riders. One famous West Coast jockey immediately took his
mount to the outside and jogged him for the rest of the race,
staying well clear of the riderless horse.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay, however, was atop Gold Nugget, owned by two of the
nicest people in Texas racing, Sue and Leland Cook of Corsicana.
</P>
<P>
   On the turn for home, Gold Nugget was full of run. But as he
charged down the stretch, the loose horse was between Pincay and
the rail. There was only a small opening and no one knew what the
riderless horse would do. One wrong move and Pincay's next ride
could have been in an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   But Laffit never hesitated. He took the rail route, a totally
fearless decision that told you everything you ever needed to know
about the guts of Laffit Pincay, native son of Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Gold Nugget won the race. Pincay won even more admiration as a
true champion. And this week, the numbers will make it official. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
