<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-YAHOO </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Yahoo Stock Up 24%, Joins S&AMP;P Today  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A lot of people own Yahoo shares. A lot of people made a lot of
money yesterday.
<P>
   Yahoo's stock soared $67.19, or 24 percent, to close at a record
$348 prior to its debut today in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index.
</P>
<P>
   It is up no less than 52 percent since its inclusion on the S&AMP;P
was announced a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   While much of yesterday's surge is attributable to index fund
managers doing some last-minute shopping _ when an index changes,
corresponding mutual funds have to buy or sell stocks to match the
index _ analysts say Yahoo's hefty gain indicates another force at
work: day traders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever there's an artificial demand for a stock, you get
wild swings above and beyond the intended selling because people
are piling on,'' said Scott Reamer, an analyst with SG Cowen
Securities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   By his thinking, once the institutional big boys took an
interest in Yahoo, the day traders saw the stock pick up momentum
and jumped aboard for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   They jumped off after the market's close. In after-hours
trading, Yahoo gave back $11.75, to $336.25.
</P>
<P>
   Geri Hom, senior portfolio manager at San Francisco's Charles
Schwab, said a stock will typically rise between 5 percent and 15
percent after its inclusion in the S&AMP;P 500 is announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The S&AMP;P effect gives it some oomph,'' she observed. ``But it's
a volatile stock that moves a lot already. It's the nature of
Internet stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara's Yahoo certainly has covered some ground this year.
In fact, the company's share price has more than doubled since
January, giving the portal a market capitalization of $91.6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, real-world media giant Time Warner has a market
value of $82 billion, and Disney weighs in at just $56.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's truly a happy stock,'' said Jeff Goverman, research
director at Pacific Crest Securities in Portland, Ore. ``No one's
lost any money on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo is only the second Internet company to be added to the S&AMP;P
500. The other is America Online, which also has more than doubled
in value this year. Both are among the most widely held Internet
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   They're both also the most widely recognized Internet brands on
the planet.
</P>
<P>
   In Yahoo's case, the portal ranks as the single-most-popular
U.S. Web site, according to Media Metrix. It also holds the top
spot in Britain and Japan, and is the second-most-popular site in
France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research shows that Yahoo is just at the beginning of
building a global media brand,'' said Carolyn Luther Trabuco, an
analyst at First Union Securities in New York. ``Yahoo has
demonstrated an ability to manage its growth.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Yahoo is no longer a darling of just the day traders
and retail investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Institutional investors are waking up to the fact that they
have to join the party,'' Trabuco said. ``Yahoo is demonstrating
itself as being a premier media name.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, she also believes the stock still has plenty of
upside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fourth quarter is looking like a record for media
companies, and for Internet companies in particular,'' Trabuco
said. ``I like Yahoo because it's the dominant Internet company.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
