<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-SCHWAB </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Schwab Changes Strategy, Will Charge for Advice  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
With competition among online brokers reaching unprecedented
heights, Charles Schwab Corp. plans to increase the custom-tailored
advice it offers retail investors, taking it further than ever from
its discount broker roots.
<P>
   And, in a radical departure for the San Francisco firm, it will
start charging a fee for some forms of investment advice, marking
the first time in its nearly three-decade history that Schwab has
asked customers to pay to speak with its representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab will roll out two fee-based advice programs. The first is
described as a portfolio checkup, in which a representative will
evaluate whether a customer's assets, including those held at other
firms, are in appropriate investments for their age group, economic
circumstances and financial goals.
</P>
<P>
   The second program will be preparation of a financial plan using
a prepackaged product provided by a third-party vendor.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab has been selectively testing the services for several
months and will begin offering them in all its 320 branches
nationwide sometime next year. It says it is still deciding how
much to charge and stresses that its representatives will continue
to offer less-detailed investment help for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at how to provide personalized service and
advice without grossly inflating our expense structure,'' said
Susanne Lyons, Schwab's chief of retail client services. ``We think
personalized advice is worth paying for.``
</P>
<P>
   The moves comes as traditional brokers, most notably Wall Street
behemoth Merrill Lynch, invade the low-priced Internet investing
space that Schwab dominates. Merrill this year has unveiled two
online brokerage options, including a $29.95-per-trade Internet
account targeted directly at Schwab's slice of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional firms specialize in offering clients specific
investment recommendations, including suggestions on which mutual
funds, stocks and bonds to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Schwab has stepped up the degree of customer
hand-holding it offers. Company representatives now will suggest
what kinds of assets clients should put their money into and refer
them to investment-selection tools, but stop short of specific
stock recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Given the new competition from traditional brokers, not to
mention the ever-broadening array of services offered by online
rivals such as E-Trade Group, analysts say Schwab has to give
investors more investment ideas to keep their loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   But, analysts say, customers might resist paying for something
they think they should get for free. Schwab must make it clear that
it is charging for new advice programs, not simply slapping fees on
services it used to do for free, analysts note.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can add value and service, customers may accept it,''
said Amar Mehta, an analyst with the brokerage CIBC World Markets.
``And, if you look at what Merrill charges for advice, it's still
likely to be higher that what Schwab charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill's services aren't strictly comparable, but its basic
account offering investment advice charges an annual fee of 1
percent of assets with no commissions on stock trading.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab could also face objections from some of the 5,600
independent investment advisers it works with, who manage about 30
percent of the firm's customer assets.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab has built relationships with outside advisers advisors &LR; 
 &LR; to manage the accounts of customers who aren't comfortable
handling their own investments. Some of those advisers may view
Schwab's new programs as substitutes for their own services. Schwab
says its programs are aimed at a different group of customers than
those who go to independent advisers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
