<SLUG> BC-VC-VC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Venture Fund Aimed at Small Investors  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Draper Fisher Jurvetson, one of the Bay Area's well-known venture
capital firms, said yesterday that it is helping create a new &LR; 
 &LR; $500 million venture fund for the masses.
<P>
   ``Venture capital has historically only been available to
millionaires and large institutional investors,'' said founder Tim
Draper. ``We want to allow the small investor a chance to
participate in this important driver of the U.S. economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Draper Fisher Jurvetson of Redwood City has about $1 billion
invested in six funds and recently has been generating better than
100 percent annual returns for its institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   The venture capital firm firm's  &LR; plans to invest $500 million
from its proposed fund in Internet startups.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, though, has turned over to Internet startup firm
meVC.com the job of raising the money and other ``front end'' tasks
such as setting up the first national venture capital investment
management firm and winning approval from the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The new fund is breaking new ground in the U.S. venture capital
industry, a $40 billion business that is usually reserved for a
select few. ``Typically, only institutions and high net worth
individuals with at least $200,000 in annual income or $1 million
net worth can invest,'' said meVC.com chief executive Any Singer.
</P>
<P>
   MeVC.com hopes to lower the financial bar. The minimum
investment in the new fund will be $5,000, and investors must have
either a net worth of at least $150,000 or $50,000 net worth plus
gross income of at least $50,000 a year. Investors also will be
restricted from investing more than 10 percent of their net worth.
</P>
<P>
   But don't send in your investment checks yet. Although meVC.com
has filed a registration statement with the SEC for its first
venture capital mutual fund, the review and approval process could
take several months.
</P>
<P>
   Like other venture capital funds, the fees will be substantial _
2.5 percent of capital contributions and 20 percent of any profits.
</P>
<P>
   Singer, a former investment banker with Robertson Stephens, set
up meVC.com six months ago. The first $800,000 investments in the
company came from individuals, including former BankAmerica Chief
Executive Officer Richard Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Draper Fisher Jurvetson also has invested $4.5 million in
meVC.com, which has hired financial industry experts from such
companies as GT Global, Montgomery Securities and Charles Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
