r f BC-MACROMEDIA-MACROMEDIA     12-07 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACROMEDIA-MACROMEDIA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Macromedia Signs Up `South Park' Duo  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The raucous duo behind the ``South Park'' cartoon and movie will
bring their unique and sometimes controversial humor to an original
animated series for Macromedia's entertainment Web site.
<P>
   The San Francisco software company will announce today that Trey
Parker and Matt Stone have signed a multiyear deal to create 39,
two- to five-minute episodes of an as-yet unnamed series for
Shockwave.com. The online cartoon will debut early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the deal weren't disclosed, but
representatives of Parker and Stone said they have received
``significant'' equity in Shockwave.com and will maintain creative
control of the animations.
</P>
<P>
   The series will feature original characters, not Web versions of
Cartman, Chef or the other crude, sometimes foul-mouthed stars of
the Comedy Central show and ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut''
movie that have made the two Generation Xers famous.
</P>
<P>
   Other details, such as the animation style or the type of
characters, weren't available.
</P>
<P>
   Macromedia chief executive Robert Burgess said the series will
bridge the gap between the Internet's burgeoning entertainment
industry and the 18-to-34-year-old Web surfers hungry for such
content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, virtually everything on the Web has been created
for some other purpose. ... TV, video games, and then people used
the Web as another way to market it,'' he said. ``This is the other
way around. (These are) the first big stars that are creating
original properties for the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Best known for its graphics development software and Shockwave
plug-in, which lets Internet users play clips of video, games,
music and other forms of media, Macromedia spun off Shockwave.com
this summer to separate the entertainment-oriented site from its
traditional business.
</P>
<P>
   Shockwave.com offers visitors access to games, music, cartoons
and searches, as well as links to sites like Comedy Central
(comedycentral.com).
</P>
<P>
   In the months since its debut, the company has focused on
landing deals with high-profile content creators for the site. Last
month Shockwave.com signed an agreement with Spiderman creator Stan
Lee to develop a comic, or Webisode, for the site.
</P>
<P>
   And this week, Macromedia will announce a deal with San
Francisco's animation firm Mondo Media.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts appear to have paid off.
</P>
<P>
   According to Media Metrix, a New York firm that tracks Web
traffic, Shockwave.com received 2.35 million unique visitors in
October, up from 1.75 million in September.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the success of the shorts, the new Parker-Stone
creation may jump to television or film, Burgess said. Under the
deal, Parker and Stone will have lead distribution rights for any
non-Internet media.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that perk, Parker and Stone were attracted to
Shockwave.com's considerable backing, said Kevin Morris, a Los
Angeles attorney for the pair. Last year, Macromedia had $150
million in revenues. Last week, venture capital fund Sequoia
Capital and Internet entrepreneur Jim Clark invested $44 million
investment in the Shockwave.com unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The size and weight of Macromedia and the strength of their
business plan was very appealing to Matt and Trey,'' Morris said.
``(Shockwave.com) wasn't just a startup site looking for sticky
content.''
</P>
<P>
   The site, ranked No. 32 in Media Metrix's
news/information/entertainment category, relies mainly on
advertising _ about $3 million a quarter, according to Burgess. But
it will expand its revenue streams to include subscriptions and
pay-per-view as it ramps up more entertainment features.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking the site now to the next generation,'' Burgess
said. ``We're moving very rapidly into original content that's
designed for the Web and with Web sensibilities in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
