<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUETOOTH-BLUETOOTH </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Bluetooth Trial Shows Power To Link Items  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Bluetooth, a short-range radio technology designed to link cell
phone, notebook computers and other mobile devices without wires,
moved a step closer to reality yesterday when Intel demonstrated it
running in a pair of portable PCs.
<P>
   Intel said it will begin marketing its Bluetooth hardware and
software to notebook manufacturers next year, in time for products
to ship around the middle of the year.
</P>
<P>
   By then, some mobile phones are also expected to be
Bluetooth-capable, and one of the first applications of the
technology will likely be to create a link between such notebooks
and phones, enabling users to send e-mail and even surf the Web
without cables or wires.
</P>
<P>
   Another early use for the technology, which phonemaker Ericsson
demonstrated at last month's Comdex computer trade show, will be in
wireless headsets. Eventually it's expected to be used for data
exchange among a wide variety of mobile devices, including digital
cameras and personal organizers, as well as stationary PCs and
printers and even cars.
</P>
<P>
   Cahners In-Stat, a market research group, predicts that by 2005,
there will be more than 670 million Bluetooth-enabled devices
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was announced in May 1998, Bluetooth has garnered broad
support in the computer and communications industries. More than
1,300 companies have joined the Bluetooth Special Interest Group, a
trade organization of companies planning products based on the
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Microsoft, 3Com, Lucent and Motorola joined the
group's leadership committee, alongside its five founding
companies, Ericsson, IBM, Intel, Nokia and Toshiba. Microsoft had
previously been cool to the technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Intel demonstration, before a conference of Bluetooth
developers in Los Angeles, showed two prototype notebooks
synchronizing data wirelessly. The company's mobile products group
developed the radio module, which is mounted on a circuit board
measuring only about 1.25 by .75 inches, and software to use it
with Windows 98 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it has no plans to develop Bluetooth for
Windows CE, Microsoft's stripped-down operating system for
handhelds, which is usually run on non-Intel processors. Other
companies, however, are expected to deliver Bluetooth for a variety
of other operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Adding Bluetooth will initially cost notebook manufacturers
about $30, including hardware, software and support, an Intel
spokeswoman estimated. Over the next couple of years, that figure
should decline to around $10.
</P>
<P>
   Bluetooth uses unlicensed radio frequencies in the 2.4-gigahertz
band. It's designed to carry 1 megabit of data per second, making
it almost 20 times faster than a 56K modem, but its range is
limited to 10 meters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of BLUETOOT (25112 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
