<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   How to Reinvigorate a Stagnant Business 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Q: I've successfully started my own business and have run it
profitably now for nearly two years. Although I'm working really
hard, growth seems to have stalled. How do I get my business
growing again?
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: If money is no object, which is a long shot, buy up your
competitors and throw money into marketing. More likely, capital is
scarce and you will have to be creative.
</P>
<P>
   There are no magic formulas, according to business consultant
and certified public accountant Howard Thomas of the Thomas
Consulting Group in Los Gatos. But he offers five tips to
entrepreneurs who hit the wall:
</P>
<P>
   _Start by looking inward to rekindle the characteristics that
got you this far. Find a way to renew your passion for the
business.
</P>
<P>
   _Do some strategic soul-searching to find ways to get the
business back on a growth path. Start by putting yourself in the
place of the customer. Review each place a customer comes in
contact with your business and objectively evaluate the customer's
experience. Be brutally honest in assessing how relevant your
products or services are. You might want to hire someone to conduct
focus groups or a customer survey to get both quantitative and
qualitative feedback.
</P>
<P>
   _Take a look at your business model to see if it is still
relevant. How do you make money now? Can you generate revenue some
other way in the future? Can you create new revenue streams? Are
there hidden businesses in your business? Be creative.
</P>
<P>
   _Read magazines about your business, go to trade shows, visit
your competitor's locations and see what's going on. Buy some
market research. Talk with your friends, colleagues, financial
partners and, above all, current and former customers, to find out
if your products or services are still tops.
</P>
<P>
   _Finally, take action. Create a next-phase plan with specific
goals for growth and sell it to those who are interested in your
business _ your customers, employees, partners and suppliers. Have
a time line and make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Thomas suggests hiring a consultant. But then,
that's how he makes his business grow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
New SBA Resources
</P>
<P>
   The federal government's main Web site for business information
has been substantially rearranged and upgraded to provide more
electronic services at higher speed. If you haven't checked it out
already, you might want to click on the U.S. Small Business
Administration's U.S. Business Advisor site (www.business.gov).
</P>
<P>
   Started in 1953, the SBA provides financial, technical and
management assistance to help Americans start, run and grow their
businesses. The revamped Web site offers connections to most every
government agency, from the Administration on Aging to the White
House, plus links to subjects such as taxes, laws and regulations,
international trade, workplace issues and Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Among other services, the new Web site can be used to:
</P>
<P>
   _Access electronic commerce services, from loan information to
trademark registration, export licenses, payroll benefits and tax
filing.
</P>
<P>
   _Find equity capital, contracting opportunities, trade leads and
research grants.
</P>
<P>
   _Create a tailored Web page to support international trade
activities.
</P>
<P>
   _Seek and receive e-mail advice and counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, on Monday, the President's Committee on Employment
of People with Disabilities will introduce a Small Business
Self-Employment Service for adults with disabilities. With a
jobless rate exceeding 70 percent, Americans with severe
disabilities increasingly see the Internet as a viable option.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about the service, including help on
starting and managing a business and relevant disability issues,
call (800) 526-7234. The government also has a Web site with links
to other resources: janweb.icdi.wvu.edu/sbses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to entrepreneurs &LR; sfgate.com, or to
Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 2211EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
