<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2203 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-INCUBATOR-INCUBATOR_S     12-07 1389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INCUBATOR-INCUBATOR </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Incubators Provide Day Care for Net Startups  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Venture Frogs is not your typical venture or angel capital firm.
<P>
   To stay close to their tadpole clients, co-founders Tony Hsieh,
25, and Alfred Lin, 26, located their business incubator in the
same building where they live. They are even putting in a
restaurant so their adopted offspring can concentrate on building
their products and market share rather than foraging for food.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept is to get everyone to work all the time and never
leave the building,'' said Hsieh, only half-jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   Venture Frogs is renovating 10,000 square feet of space in the
Marquee Historical Building at 1000 Van Ness Ave. in San Francisco
to create a nursery for up to 15 Internet startups.
</P>
<P>
   Last January, soon after Hsieh and Lin sold LinkExchange, their
previous company, to Microsoft, they bought lofts in the building,
which is also home to an AMC Theater complex. The two, who are
investing $27 million of their own and other investors' money in
more dot-com companies, now live upstairs from their offices beside
the old Cadillac showroom.
</P>
<P>
   Venture Frogs is not alone in jumping into the startup breeding
business.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the National Business Incubation Association in
Athens, Ohio, identified nearly 600 incubators in North America
that created about 19,000 companies and 245,000 jobs. More than
half were nonprofit organizations designed to create jobs and spur
economic development. Nearly a third were affiliated with colleges
and universities and designed to turn research into real products
and services. Only about 10 percent were run by investment groups
like Venture Frogs for profit.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether the backers set up incubators to do good
or do well, their practices are similar. Fledgling companies need
coddling as well as cash in order to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   It has been widely reported that as many as 80 percent of new
businesses fail within the first five years. By contrast, a study
by the Small Business Administration, Coopers and Lybrand and the
National Business Incubation Association suggests that companies
starting out in incubators have a 65 to 80 percent chance of
surviving beyond the five-year milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Incubators typically offer offices equipped with computers,
Internet connections, phones, conference rooms, copiers and fax
equipment. They also often provide access to legal and financial
advice, engineering and human resources consultants and plenty of
hand holding from those who have already been successful developing
a business and marketing plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This allows entrepreneurs to focus on growing their business
without having to worry about core necessities,'' said Hsieh.
</P>
<P>
   Hsieh and Lin began their business relationship at Harvard,
where Hsieh ran a pizza restaurant in his dormitory. His best
customer was Lin, who would buy two or three pizzas a day at
discount and then mark up each slice for sale to his housemates.
house mates.  &LR; From pizza arbitrage, Lin went on to get a master's
degree in statistics, become vice president of finance at
LinkExchange and then co-found Venture Frogs.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Hsieh and Lin planned to invest in dot-com companies
but not run a day care facility for them. They bought lofts in the
1000 Van Ness building because they liked the urban location and
proximity to the cinema. (They also got 100 free movie tickets each
when they bought their units.)
</P>
<P>
   It soon dawned on Hsieh and Lin how much time they and their
clients were wasting on the road. Another advantage of sharing the
same space is cross-pollination of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Venture Frogs has invested $20 million in
about a dozen companies in $300,000 to $3 million increments. One
venture that received $1 million and is sharing space with Venture
Frogs is Web Juice. Started by Eric Liu, another LinkExchange
veteran who also lives in the building, Web Juice provides
engineering consulting services to other Internet startups that
need help training their own employees and getting to market
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   OpenTable, an online restaurant reservation service that
received $650,000 from Venture Frogs, already has 72 employees and
is too big for an incubator. But CEO Chuck Templeton, who has
experience in both the restaurant and semiconductor equipment
fields, said Venture Frogs has helped his company get set up at a
new location.
</P>
<P>
   For years, venture capital firms have lavished management
attention as well as dollars on their fledgling companies. They
recruit managers and technical help. They sit on their boards.
Their cell phones are on day and night. And some, like Kleiner
Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers, have entrepreneurs-in-residence who can
take the helm.
</P>
<P>
   Incubators, though, go a few steps further and usually are
creations of proven entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, SEEQ and Chips &AMP; Technologies founder Gordon
Campbell started Techfarm in Mountain View six years ago. Knowledge
Adventure founder Bill Gross created Idealab in Pasadena three
years ago and was perhaps the first to focus on nurturing dot-com
companies. And Idealab has opened a branch in Sunnyvale, and now
Internet incubators are springing up like mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the Women's Technology Center, which received its
initial investment from the Three Guineas Fund, a ``venture
philanthropy'' organization started a year ago by former Cisco
Systems marketing executive Catherine Muther.
</P>
<P>
   This 22,000-square-foot nonprofit incubator in San Francisco's
South of Market neighborhood has room for up to 30 female-owned
software, multimedia, Internet and e-commerce companies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to support from Muter's Three Guineas Fund, Women's
Technology Cluster has gained the financial support of the city of
San Francisco and various corporations and foundations. Some of the
early tenants include MsMoney.com, a financial services Internet
portal for female investors; LifeGuides, which offers guidance,
college prep and career planning services for teenagers; and Latino
Link, an Hispanic-focused a Latino-focused  &LR; news site.
</P>
<P>
   In Palo Alto, four veterans of USWeb/CKS started another
Internet incubator last June called Intend Change with backing from
Japan's Softbank Technology Venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capital is important but in our view it is only one-third of
the process,'' said co-founder Toby Corey. ``The other two-thirds
is `venture construction' _ providing the strategic,
administrative, marketing, recruiting and other resources to
accelerate the process of getting to market.''
</P>
<P>
   Intend Change expects to raise as much as $200 million on top of
the $100 million it already has. So far, it has invested in four
companies, including InveSmart.com, a retirement financial services
company, and Electron Economy, a service to manage e-commerce from
customer purchase to product delivery.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, another Internet hatchery is expected to be announced
by ex-Adauction executives David Wamsley and Neil Cohen. Their San
Francisco incubator is code-named Net2Future.
</P>
<P>
   Large companies from Intel to Panasonic and government agencies
such as the Korean Ministry of Information and Scottish trade
mission also have set up local incubators or opened their labs to
outside innovators. Like other investors, they are interested in
tracking hot ideas and entrepreneurs and striking partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   A number of nonprofit incubators like Renaissance
Entrepreneurship Center in San Francisco, Center for
Entrepreneurial Development in San Jose and Oakland Small Business
Growth Center focus on helping women and minority entrepreneurs
launch inner-city enterprises. Unlike most for-profit incubators,
high tech is not a required component.
</P>
<P>
   Another major difference is that most nonprofit incubators are
happy to publicize their efforts to help entrepreneurs start
companies and create jobs. By contrast, most for-profit incubators
have been private about their activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's generally been invitation-only,'' explained Tyler Orion,
executive director of the Pacific Incubator Network and a San Diego
incubator development consultant. ``They don't want 100 business
plans from people who are patently unqualified.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
