<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2211 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV14-     12-07 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV14-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEASON OF GIVING FOR SUKIE'S FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif, Md., Minn., the Bahamas, Mexico)   (For release Tuesday, Dec. 14)  
(DW) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sukie Miller doesn't have immediate family except for her cat,
Harry. ``It never occurred to me that someone would give me a
kidney,'' she said. But she does have a large extended family and
after learning that Sukie's kidneys were failing so bad she'd soon
need a transplant, a friend sent a letter out to more than 250
other Sukie friends around the world asking them to donate.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen friends, type O blood compatible, offered. One former
boyfriend wrote, ``I'm type O. I have two kidneys. You can have
one.''
</P>
<P>
   But these things are tricky. People don't automatically qualify
and even those who are willing change their minds. A close friend
agreed and even passed a battery of tests that showed her to be a
match but in the end her family was against it. She has four kids
and they didn't want her risking elective surgery. Another wanted
to donate but was eliminated because she has high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Others were willing but not as healthy as they thought. One
potential donor confided to Sukie that lately he'd been going to
the bathroom a lot and was always thirsty. Sukie suggested it
sounded like diabetes and it was. Another went through the medical
screening to be a donor and doctors discovered early evidence of
leukemia. Still, her friends pushed on and early last month Sukie
had two strong prospects. But then one changed his mind and the
other started to waiver.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sukie, who wants to have a transplant without going
on dialysis first, says ``We're in a bit of a chase. My doctor
thinks I'll make it, but he says I'm living on the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, out of the blue, a second cousin, from Bethesda,
Md., called and said, ``I'm an O.'' Now, Cynthia Goldner, an
artist, a creative redhead like Sukie, looks to be a better match
than anyone. The friends are ecstatic. One wants to send Cynthia to
Esalen for a week to thank her. Another promises New York theater
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all counting on Cynthia,'' says Sukie. If she gets the
all-clear the two will go to Los Angeles in January for doctors to
remove one of Cynthia's kidneys and transplant it into Sukie. But
Sukie says, ``I don't want to count my kidneys until they are
transplanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia says, ``I just told her we're not doing this on New
Year's. I don't want to be hooked up to an IV on Y2K.'' In answer
to why she decided to be a donor, Cynthia says, ``Here's an
opportunity to enhance the quality of someone's life. I'm honored
and grateful to be healthy enough to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a strange odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sukie Miller is an author, psychotherapist and lecturer, a
New Yorker moved to California but still a New Yorker in style and
humor. ``Kidneys? Who thinks of kidneys?''
</P>
<P>
   A professional interest of late is how different cultures view
death and what happens after people die. Sukie's house in Penngrove
is decorated with folk art from Mexican Day of the Dead
celebrations and carved wooden angels. Her second book on the very
tough subject of children dying, (``Finding Hope When a Child
Dies,'' with Doris Ober) came out this year and it was in preparing
for a round of public readings that she discovered her kidneys were
going.
</P>
<P>
   In New York for an interview for a Bill Moyers show on dying,
she went to see a diet doctor. ``Makes sense. You have a book
coming out, you decide to go on a diet.'' It was that doctor who
found out that her kidneys were in trouble. This was not a total
surprise. Twenty years before she'd learned there was an excess of
protein in her urine, but that doctor said it probably wasn't
anything to worry about. ``He told me that my kidneys would outlive
me.''
</P>
<P>
   But something changed in the meantime and now at age 58 her
kidneys are in a dive. Her California doctor found that her kidneys
were operating at 23 percent and told her in March that she had
maybe two years before she'd need to go on dialysis and be put on a
transplant waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   Back then she decided to keep it to herself. ``I thought between
now and two years I'll figure something out.'' Still, she went home
and cried and took stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to myself that I was never going to feel as well as I
did right then, so what did I want to do for myself.'' She decided
on three things: to revisit the Bahamas, walk around New York City
by herself and introduce a Brazilian friend to New York.
</P>
<P>
   She got her wishes, all flukes. She was invited to go to Nassau
to lecture at a yoga retreat. A TV show flew her to New York for an
interview which gave her time to wander the city on a spring day.
Her Brazilian friend called and suggested they meet in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also decided that I'd had a wonderful life and if this was
it, this was it. You know I write about this stuff and it's nice to
find out when I was up against it, feeling my death as a very real
possibility, I wasn't scared. I have hope that there is more and
that hope has made death OK although not desirable.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-year window, however, started to close this summer when
her kidneys dropped to 16 percent function and considering a
transplant became critical. That's when her friend took over and
sent out the ``Dear Sukie's Friend'' letters. One woman Sukie knew
as a VISTA volunteer offered but didn't qualify. A man she met in
Minneapolis while speaking at his organization's conference also
offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew I was kind of popular,'' says Sukie, ``But I am
blown away by the amount of love from people.''
</P>
<P>
   A New York friend connected Sukie with a New Jersey woman who's
had a kidney transplant. Sukie calls her ``my kidney buddy'' and
they talk regularly. Another friend developed a group e-mail for
Sukie updates. If all works out, several of Sukie's friends will
begin the millennium as her transplant team.
</P>
<P>
   There's a sign-up sheet of people willing to go to Los Angeles
to help with her recovery there and when she returns home _ people
who already consider second cousin Cynthia family.
</P>
<P>
   The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
