<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2214 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-RUBIN-ART-NYT &LR;      12-07 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-RUBIN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BRADLEY PROMOTE PLANS ON ECONOMY AND HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Wash.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 29 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE and JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With Robert Rubin, the former treasury secretary and
one of the architects of the current economic expansion, vouching
for his fiscal wisdom and discipline, Vice President Al Gore
continued Tuesday to lash out at his opponents as fiscally
irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the budget proposals of former Sen. Bill Bradley, his
rival for the Democratic presidential nomination, and Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, the leading Republican, would take ``unnecessary
risks with our prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that if the economy ain't broke, then let's make
sure that we build on the strength that we have,'' Gore said.
``Their theme is, if the economy ain't broke, let's break it.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Gore attacked Bradley's fitness to oversee the economy,
Bradley released statements by two prominent economists who vouched
for him.
</P>
<P>
   The two, Paul Volcker, a former chairman of the Federal Reserve
Board, and Henry Kaufman, president the financial consulting firm
of Henry Kaufman &AMP; Co., praised Bradley for understanding the
economy, being fiscally prudent and playing a central role in
passing the 1986 Tax Reform Act.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman also said that Bradley was more honest than Gore in
laying out the cost of his proposals and for refusing to take a
pledge against raising taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Markets rely on trust and truth,'' Kaufman said. ``Bill
Bradley has told the truth about the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was speaking in an auditorium at New York University Law
School to 400 students. The event provided a platform for Rubin,
the former co-chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and now an executive
at Citigroup Inc., to endorse Gore and for that endorsement to
resound on Wall Street, where Bradley and Bush both enjoy
substantial support.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has held open meetings in living rooms and school
gymnasiums in New Hampshire that have been casual and personable.
Tuesday's, his first such forum in New York, was far more formal,
with Gore standing in a suit on a stage with elected officials like
Carl McCall, the state comptroller, and university officials. His
speech focused on the economy, and the questions covered a range of
domestic issues, from gun control (which he favors) to the
legalization of marijuana (which he opposes).
</P>
<P>
   Rubin portrayed Gore as a full partner with President Clinton in
bringing the nation out of its morass of deficits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you,'' Rubin said, ``after sitting with the vice
president in the White House, the Oval Office and the Cabinet room
over six-and-a-half years, that he was consistently sound,
sensible, practical and willing to fight politically difficult
issues with respect to the broad array of economic matters before
this administration.''
</P>
<P>
   With this stamp of approval, Gore resumed his relentless assault
against his opponents' economic proposals, with a particularly
harsh assessment of Bradley's.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Bradley's budget proposal was ``hastily
constructed'' and would spend the entire surplus. As recently as
Monday, Bradley, citing the uncertainties of the future, refused to
rule out ever raising taxes to pay for his plan to make health
insurance available to most Americans. But he said he was not
proposing a tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   Gore seized on this Tuesday and characterized Bradley as
admitting that he may have to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bradley would spend the surplus ``mostly to provide
subsidies for health coverage to people who already have health
coverage, many of them in high income brackets,'' adding, ``That's
why he's admitted he may have to raise taxes to pay for his plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore went on to say of Bradley, ``To propose a possible tax
increase, not because of some contingency related to unknowns in
the economy but because of an inability to cover a huge gaping hole
in a campaign promise that can't be covered in any other way _ that
is unresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's spokesman, Chris Lehane, said that Gore has ruled out
raising taxes except for some unforeseen disaster. Gore's 1993
tie-breaking vote in the Senate on the budget, however, included
the largest tax increase up to that time in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   And Bradley has pointed out that in 1992, Clinton refused to
pledge not to raise taxes, saying such a pledge would be
irresponsible. Bradley says that he and Gore have essentially the
same view but that Gore is grossly distorting his.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign announced endorsements from three Democratic
members of the House of Representatives: George Miller and Fortney
Stark of California, and Jim McDermott of Washington. Stark and
McDermott are both considered experts on health care, while Miller
worked closely with Bradley on California water issues in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The new endorsements double the number of House members who have
come out in support of Bradley. He has also been endorsed by three
senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The collapse of affordable health insurance for middle- and
lower-income Americans is the problem of the decade, and Bill
Bradley has shown more vision and courage in addressing this key
issue,'' Stark said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also released new television commercials in New
Hampshire and Iowa on Tuesday touting his plan to make health
insurance available to almost all Americans. The 30-second spots
are drawn from actual town hall meetings Bradley held in the two
states, and feature the former senator describing the broad
outlines to groups of voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's health plan has been fiercely attacked by Gore as too
expensive and incapable of providing adequate coverage to
low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Bradley campaign released a statement accusing Gore
of making false statements about Bradley's health care plan and his
position on school vouchers. The news release also asserted that
Gore has exaggerated or obfuscated his own record during the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Bradley campaign asserted that while Gore
recently claimed to have long supported the death penalty, he
repeatedly voted against it in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign also criticized Gore for having taken
credit in a Time Magazine article for being an author of the Earned
Income Tax Credit, which helps low-income workers. The credit,
according to the Bradley campaign, was created in 1975, a year
before Gore was elected to Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
