u f BC-SHIFTS-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      12-07 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHIFTS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVERAL COMPANIES MAKE DECEMBER THE TIME OF YEAR TO CHANGE THEIR
AGENCIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Typically, as the year draws to a close, the pace of agency
changes among advertisers accelerates. This month is proving no
different as several marketers make shifts involving their
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard consolidated the creative account for its
electronic services units, with billings estimated at $60 million,
at Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners in San Francisco, part of the
Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco office of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, part of Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi PLC, had previously handled those duties. Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi
continues to handle other Hewlett-Packard assignments that include
creative tasks for products, worldwide media buying and
international media planning.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Fox, a spokeswoman for Hewlett-Packard in Palo Alto,
Calif., confirmed a report this week in the trade publication
Adweek about the additional assignment for Goodby, Silverstein. The
agency already handles the Hewlett-Packard corporate branding
account, with spending estimated at $200 million during the next
year, as well as domestic media planning duties.
</P>
<P>
   The change reflects the company's desire to centralize at one
agency the creative accounts for overall branding, digital imaging
and e-services, Ms. Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   CKE Restaurants in Anaheim, Calif., expanded its relation with
Johnson/Ukropina Creative Marketing in Irvine, Calif., by awarding
the agency the creative account for its Hardee's fast-food chain.
Billings were estimated at $50 million to $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came less than two weeks after Hardee's parted ways
with its agency of 13 months, the Leap Partnership in Chicago,
owned by Leapnet Inc. Johnson/Ukropina has handled the
merchandising account for Carl's Jr., another fast-food chain owned
by CKE, for six years and recently worked with Hardee's on a
merchandising project.
</P>
<P>
   Quotesmith.com, an online insurance price comparison service,
awarded its account, which had been done in-house, to the Chicago
office of BBDO Worldwide, part of Omnicom. Billings were estimated
at $100 million for the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Willard Hemsworth II, who is the senior vice president for
marketing at Quotesmith.com in Darien, Ill., part of the Quotesmith
Corp., said the decision followed a review narrowed to BBDO and
several agencies he declined to identify.
</P>
<P>
   The Principal Financial Group, which offers products and
services like insurance and mortgage banking, awarded its account
to Publicis &AMP; Hal Riney in Chicago, part of Publicis SA. Billings
were estimated at $25 million to $28 million.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after a six-month review that had been
narrowed to Publicis &AMP; Hal Riney and two other agencies: Jordan
McGrath Case &AMP; Partners/Euro RSCG in New York, part of the Euro
RSCG Worldwide unit of Havas Advertising, and the Chicago office of
Ammirati Puris Lintas, part of the Interpublic Group of Companies.
Brown Marketing Communications in Chicago, which had handled the
account for 25 years, was invited to participate but declined, said
Dave Wozniak, advertising director at Principal Financial in Des
Moines.
</P>
<P>
   Winstar Communications in New York placed its account in review
after three years at Trone Advertising in Greensboro, N.C. Billings
were estimated at $15 million to $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Sando, a spokesman for Winstar, a telecommunications
company, confirmed a report of the review in the fax edition of
Advertising Age. Trone was invited to participate but declined, he
said, adding that a decision is expected early next year. The
review is being handled by Pile &AMP; Co. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil in Irving, Texas, the oil giant formed with the
recent acquisition of Mobil by Exxon, named the DDB Worldwide
Communications Group in New York _ the unit of Omnicom that is the
longtime Mobil agency _ to create a multimedia campaign to promote
the formation of the merged company. Spending through the end of
January was estimated at $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is being scrutinized by Madison Avenue because of
speculation that Exxon Mobil might rearrange its agency roster with
the completion of the merger. The longtime Exxon agency is
McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising, part of the McCann-Erickson
World Group in New York, a unit of Interpublic.
</P>
<P>
   And Garden Ridge in Houston, a home decorating retailer, named
the Dallas office of Publicis to handle its account, which had been
at Fogarty Klein &AMP; Partners in Houston. Billings were estimated at
$10 million to $15 million. A Publicis sibling, Publicis Technology
in San Francisco, will handle online marketing and the Garden Ridge
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Fogarty Klein will continue handling public relations for Garden
Ridge. The agency is being bought back by senior management from
its parent, Lois/USA, as part of the recent filing for federal
bankruptcy protection by Lois/USA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
