<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CENDANT TO PAY $2.8 BILLION TO SETTLE SHAREHOLDER SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Cendant has agreed to pay its stockholders $2.8 billion to
settle charges of accounting fraud that wiped out billions in the
company's market value. The settlement is the largest ever in a
securities class-action suit.
</P>
<P>
   The shareholders contended that CUC Inc., one of two companies
that merged to form Cendant in 1997, had inflated its profit
figures and that executives no longer with the company sold shares
before the irregularities were publicly disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   SHARES OF CYGNUS SURGE ON NEWS
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Cygnus rose $8.8125, or 95.9 percent, to $18, after an
advisory panel to the Food and Drug Administration recommended
approval of the company's GlucoWatch, a device that helps diabetics
monitor the level of glucose in their blood by using a low
electrical current. The device is meant as an alternative to the
finger-prick test that many diabetics perform several times daily.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMAKERS SELL SUPPLY NETWORK
</P>
<P>
   Major automakers and their key suppliers have sold a computer
network that they use for ordering supplies and services to a
private company.
</P>
<P>
   PENSION AGENCY SECURITY IS CALLED WEAK
</P>
<P>
   Security experts easily broke into computers at Pension Benefit
Guaranty Corp., the federal agency that guarantees pensions,
acquiring the power to create fictitious beneficiaries and send
them money, a report to be made public Tuesday shows.
</P>
<P>
   CAP GEMINI HAS SERIES OF SETBACKS
</P>
<P>
   Cap Gemini, the largest information technology company in
Europe, has suffered a series of business setbacks, including the
cancellation of contracts by two major nonprofit organizations in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   `SOUTH PARK' CREATORS IN WEB DEAL
</P>
<P>
   The Creators of the television show ``South Park'' have agreed
to make a series of 39 cartoons to be shown on Shockwave.com in the
latest example of how Hollywood is trying to turn the Internet into
an entertainment venue.
</P>
<P>
   ZARB DENIES ALLEGATIONS IN LAWSUIT
</P>
<P>
   Frank Zarb, the chairman of the organization that runs the
NASDAQ stock market, denied in court that he intentionally misled
Philip McConkey, the former New York Giants star, about a buyout.
McConkey is suing Zarb, the insurance brokerage firm Alexander &AMP;
Alexander Services and Aon, contending that Zarb had dismissed
rumors of a pending takeover that left McConkey without a job.
</P>
<P>
   AIR CANADA EXTENDS OFFER FOR RIVAL
</P>
<P>
   Canada's largest airline, Air Canada, extended its offer to
purchase struggling rival Canadian Airlines until Dec. 23.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE TAX REFORM FALTERING
</P>
<P>
   Nobuaki Usui, an official of the Japanese Ministry of Finance,
suggested that the country might fail to meet an April 2001
deadline to change corporate taxation in ways that would encourage
companies to become more efficient and competitive.
</P>
<P>
   WORKER OUTPUT GAINS; COSTS DECLINE
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department said worker productivity grew at a rate of
4.9 percent and labor costs declined by 0.2 percent in the third
quarter, indications that economic and consumer growth remains
strong.
</P>
<P>
   HEINZ PROFIT BETTER THAN EXPECTED
</P>
<P>
   H.J. Heinz said its second-quarter operating profit was $234.8
million, or 65 cents a share, one cent higher than expectations.
</P>
</TEXT>
