<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SAFRA-NURSE-NYT &LR;      12-07 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRA-NURSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANCE OF A LIFETIME FOR A NURSE LED TO A RICH BANKER'S DEATH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, N.Y.)   By JANE GROSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORMVILLE, N.Y. _ There are signs that Ted Maher had a yen for
the finer things in life, even here on a dirt road in this Dutchess
County hamlet. The house that Maher had built, for his wife and
three children, was grand by local standards, a sprawling Cape Cod
with stone pillars out front and a gargoyle guarding the main
entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Maher, a 41-year-old nurse who the authorities say has confessed
to setting the fire that killed the banking magnate Edmond J. Safra
in his Monte Carlo penthouse on Friday, also owned two acres of
nearby woodland, spliced by a rushing creek, where he had been
clearing a hillside to build another house, which would be worth
more than $200,000 in the booming market here.
</P>
<P>
   But Maher called a sudden halt to the project several months
ago, with the fence posts fresh in the ground and plans for a
bridge to span the creek. He had stumbled on an opportunity too
good to pass up, he told neighbors here: Safra, who was suffering
from Parkinson's disease, had asked him to join his medical team,
with a $600-a-day salary and a lifestyle more opulent than any he
had imagined.
</P>
<P>
   The offer had come, Maher excitedly told neighbors near the
building site, as the result of a chance good deed at
Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center in Manhattan, where he had
worked for nine years in the neonatal intensive care unit. In the
maternity ward one day, Maher said he had found an expensive
camera. He located its owner, an associate of Safra's, who
reciprocated with a job recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called it a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity he couldn't
afford to pass up,'' said a young woman who lives across from the
building site with her husband and infant son. She spoke on the
condition of anonymity, out of respect for Maher's family, who have
refused to comment on the events of recent days.
</P>
<P>
   The woman added that she had met Maher only a few times and did
not claim to know him well. But she had been impressed by his
friendliness, his relationship with his three towheaded sons _ a
10-year-old from a previous marriage and two toddlers _ and his
interest in her child.
</P>
<P>
   Maher went to work for Safra five months ago as part of a staff
of more than a half-dozen nurses and several doctors who cared for
him in palatial homes around the world. According to Monaco's chief
prosecutor, Daniel Serdet, Maher set a fire on Friday in a
wastebasket at Safra's Monte Carlo penthouse, slashed himself with
his own switchblade, then called the police, saying that the
apartment was under attack by two hooded men with knives.
</P>
<P>
   The fire killed Safra and another nurse, who had taken refuge in
a bathroom and were overcome by smoke. In his confession, the
prosecutor said, Maher described a rivalry with another member of
the medical staff. He created the emergency, Serdet said, in the
hope of emerging as the hero who had saved his employer's life.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor said Maher will be charged with arson without
intent to kill, which could bring a life sentence, but he will
first be examined by psychiatrists to see if he is competent to
stand trial. Serdet described Maher as psychologically fragile and
under the influence of sedatives at the time of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   That assessment would surprise workers at
Columbia-Presbyterian's children's hospital, where Maher was a
respected nurse in one of the most high-pressure settings in
medicine, caring for seriously ill newborns and trying to soothe
distressed parents. A nurse with Maher's credentials _ he is a 1989
graduate of Dutchess Community College, earned his license in 1990
and has no record of disciplinary action _ would earn roughly
$60,000 a year, a union spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Raymond I. Stark, a neonatologist at the hospital and a
professor of pediatrics at Columbia University College of
Physicians and Surgeons, was unambiguous in his praise of Maher's
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cared deeply for the kids he took care of,'' Stark said.
``In a setting with a lot of tension and a lot of anxiety, he was a
bright light and a wonderful man. He had some very special moments
with the parents that are well known to him and them, so private I
would not share them with a newspaper. This is inconceivable to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   But others who have crossed Maher's path found him difficult and
abrasive. A landlord in Auburn, Me., where Maher was born and
returned for a spell in 1991, described him as a man who easily
``flew off the handle.'' The landlord, Colby Dill, who rented a
two-bedroom apartment to the Maher family, said his tenant had a
``mean streak'' and was verbally threatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were glad when he left,'' Dill said. ``All I can tell you
is he wasn't a person you wanted to be around too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Maher also had arguments with his neighbor across the street
here in Stormville, Leonard Lavelle, a retired carpenter. Their
squabbles led to complaints and cross-complaints to the East
Fishkill Police Department, according to its chief, Brian Nichols,
who said the bickering began with a dispute about a property line
and escalated over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The police declined to give details of the incidents, but a
person with knowledge of the disputes said that in one
confrontation Maher shoved Lavelle to the ground and knocked off
his glasses after an argument about the nurse's driving a tractor
on the one-lane dirt road.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of his 70-mile commute to New York City and his
demanding job, Maher is not well known in this hamlet, where
developments are springing up amid tumbledown barns, decrepit
houses and a rural landscape of rolling hills and small lakes. His
29-year-old wife, Heidi, a former per diem nurse at Columbia, is a
regular at a nearby video store, where Maher, employees say, was
only an occasional and curt customer.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Maher, who was raised in Stormville and is the daughter of
a real estate broker, is recalled as telling the clerk at the video
store that it had been a quiet Thanksgiving without her husband and
that she looked forward to his return.
</P>
<P>
   After the authorities in Monaco announced Monday that Maher had
confessed to setting the fatal fire, his wife and children took
refuge with her parents, Joan and Werner Wustrau, who live nearby
in a stone house high on a hill next to the Green Haven
Correctional Facility. Mrs. Wustrau declined to talk to a reporter
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
