<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FIRST TIME, MRS. CLINTON DIRECTLY CHALLENGES GIULIANI 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c. 1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton issued her first direct policy
challenge against her likely Senate race opponent Tuesday, calling
on Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani to express a position on a bill that
would increase the number of people eligible for benefits under the
Family and Medical Leave Act.
</P>
<P>
   Shrugging off the challenge, Giuliani responded by saying that
he generally agreed with Mrs. Clinton's position and would likely
support an expansion of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Until late last month, when she announced her intention to run
for the United States Senate in New York, Mrs. Clinton had been
careful not to refer to Giuliani, her likely Republican opponent,
by name or title. And even in her announcement she mentioned his
name only briefly, declining to draw contrasts between herself and
the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   But in a shift in strategy that suggests many more policy
challenges to come, Mrs. Clinton pointedly singled out Giuliani by
name and title, first at a breakfast fund-raiser in Midtown
Manhattan and again in an appearance on the trading floor of an
investment bank at the World Financial Center, demanding that he
tell New York voters where he stands on expanding the family leave
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to run for the Senate on the issues that I think
are important to the country,'' Mrs. Clinton said, ``and I am going
to be telling New Yorkers where I stand on those issues, and I
would hope that the mayor would also tell New Yorkers where he
stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton first challenged the mayor on the issue Tuesday in
a speech to about 1,000 people at a breakfast fund-raiser for her
Senate campaign at the Grand Hyatt Hotel in Midtown. The event was
sponsored by a group of women who support Mrs. Clinton. She
followed up on those remarks during a visit to the Canadian
Imperial Bank of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among the many issues that I think are important is the one I
mentioned this morning about family and medical leave and expanding
it,'' she said. ``I am firmly in favor of it, I would champion it
in the Senate, and I think the mayor needs to tell us where he
stands on that issue.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``I think we need to start talking about the issues
that will be before the Senate in the year 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   The family leave act was the very first bill signed into law by
President Clinton and provides up to 12 weeks of unpaid leave, job
protection and continued health insurance coverage to American
workers who need to care for a newborn or adopted child or to tend
to a sick relative.
</P>
<P>
   The law only applies to workers at businesses with 50 or more
employees, but in his State of the Union address this year, Clinton
urged Congress to expand the law to include employees of small
businesses. The Clinton administration proposal would apply to
workers at business with 25 or more employees, a move that would
make about 10 million more people eligible for the benefits.
Congressional Republicans, including the Senate majority leader,
Trent Lott, have so far opposed the extension.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani, at his daily news conference at City Hall, said
that he, too, would likely support the expansion. But he said he
was not familiar with the specific proposal now before Congress and
would need to see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the family leave act was an advance,'' he said. ``I
think it's something that's good.'' He added, ``I would have to
look at the specific proposal, but it's something that I would be
open to expanding.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he might support the expansion despite the
opposition of the Republican leadership in Congress. ``Oh, you
negotiate all these things,'' he said. ``That's how the Senate
operates.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani added that he might be better positioned than Mrs.
Clinton to accomplish the expansion. ``I would think, actually, a
Republican would have a better chance of getting that done,'' he
said, ``than a Democrat could do in a Republican-controlled
Senate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
