<SLUG> BC-NY-PERELMAN-DUFF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SIDES WITH BILLIONAIRE ON CHILD SUPPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (mg) 
By JAMES BARRON   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In another chapter in the long-running case of
Anonymous vs. Anonymous _ the not-so-anonymous child-support case
involving the billionaire financier Ronald Perelman and his former
wife, Patricia Duff _ a judge ruled on Tuesday that Perelman would
have to pay $12,825 a month to raise their 4-year-old daughter,
Caleigh.
</P>
<P>
   To put that figure in perspective, it is $825 a month more than
Perelman had been paying, but $119,175 a month less than Ms. Duff
had asked for.
</P>
<P>
   In a 22-page decision laced with words like ``absurd'' and
``rubbish,'' the judge, Franklin R. Weissberg of State Supreme
Court in Manhattan, rejected Ms. Duff's demands for as much as
$132,000 a month in child support.
</P>
<P>
   Before announcing the $12,825 figure, Weissberg said he hoped
that Ms. Duff and Perelman could teach Caleigh ``to value people
for who they are, not what they have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The mother's argument assumes that only material things matter
in the life of a child, and that if Caleigh is denied any
imaginable luxury, she will be emotionally damaged,'' the judge
wrote. ``It does not require a degree in psychiatry to know that
this assumption is rubbish. There are far more important things in
the life of a young child than private jets, yachts, obsequious
staffs and pandering guests. The reality is that Caleigh will never
suffer a shortage of material comforts.''
</P>
<P>
   After initially refusing to comment on the decision, Ms. Duff
said later: ``This has never been about money. It's just, you know,
that I want what's best for my child.''
</P>
<P>
   A Perelman spokesman, Howard J. Rubenstein, would say only,
``Justice Weissberg's decision speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Duff's many lawyers _ she has had more than 20 since the
case began _ have argued that she cannot afford the same expenses
for Caleigh that Perelman paid while he and Ms. Duff were married.
</P>
<P>
   Weissberg found that Perelman does makes more than Ms. Duff _
Perelman's income ranges from $40 million to $60 million a year,
the judge said, while Ms. Duff's is about $2.4 million a year. (The
judge said Perelman's net worth varied from $5 billion to $9
billion and that Ms. Duff's net worth is ``approximately $24
million.'')
</P>
<P>
   But the judge said that ``in every significant aspect of her
life, Caleigh now enjoys the same opportunities and high standard
of living as she would have if the marriage had not dissolved.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Ms. Duff's argument that the couple's financial
differences would affect Caleigh's ``self-image and psychological
well-being,'' the judge said: ``There is not a shred of evidence in
the record to support these conclusions. What little there is, is
to the contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge noted that Perelman had been paying $12,000 a month in
child support, but that Perelman had argued that Ms. Duff was
spending no more than $5,000 a month on Caleigh.
</P>
<P>
   Weissberg said Ms. Duff had never submitted her expense records
to the court. ``Her failure to do so was obviously deliberate,''
the judge said, ``and creates a very strong inference that she did
not do so because she cannot credibly challenge the father's
contention.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Duff, who lives in a $30,000-a-month apartment in the
Waldorf Towers, had argued that Caleigh would be hurt emotionally
if she realized that she was living on less than her half-sister
Samantha. Samantha is Perelman's 8-year-old daughter from his
earlier marriage to Claudia Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Ms. Duff said that she needed $4,400 a day for the
next 14 years, or $132,000 a month, for child support. That was
substantially higher than the $87,000 a month she requested in a
June 1998 affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Duff's lawyer, Richard D. Emery, would not discuss the
decision. Rita Warner, who represented Ms. Duff until she was
disqualified by the court, called the figure ``much too low'' and
added, ``Husbands with far less income and assets pay far more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
