u s BC-HKN-PENGUINS-LEMIEUX-     12-07 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PENGUINS-LEMIEUX-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEMIEUX STARTS OVER AS A ROOKIE OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Canada)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 33 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The young man on the elevator was unhappy and vocal about it.
This was at the Civic Arena in Pittsburgh last week after the
Penguins lost by 5-2 to San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barrasso really stunk tonight,'' the man said, referring to
Tom Barrasso, the Penguin goalie.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he recognized a fellow passenger: the Hall of Famer
Mario Lemieux, the best player in Penguins history, a personal
friend of Barrasso's and now the principal owner of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry!'' the fan said, but Lemieux remained gracious.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're entitled,'' he told the fan.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Lemieux elaborated. ``They pay their money, they
have their opinions,'' he said. ``I respect that.'' And Lemieux
does not want to alienate any paying customers from a team with an
8-13-3-4 record before playing the Devils Tuesday night in the
Meadowlands. Only 11,485 attended last week's home game against the
Sharks in the 16,958-seat building nicknamed the Igloo.
</P>
<P>
   It was Pittsburgh's smallest crowd this season and a big hint of
how tough a job Lemieux assumed in September after a settlement in
Bankruptcy Court. Lemieux exchanged about $30 million owed to him
for control of the business. He recruited 10 other investors to put
up $50 million more, but he still seeks another $15 million. With
the help of judges and elected officials, Lemieux and his aides
renegotiated their arena lease and their local television contract.
Although Lemieux says the Penguins should break even this season,
it is widely believed that their future depends on a new arena to
replace the current one, which was built in 1961 and is the oldest
in the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux has faced big challenges before. In a 12-year career
that produced 613 goals and 881 assists in 745 games, Lemieux
survived Hodgkin's disease and back surgeries along with the
slashes, hooks, holds and trips of legions of defenders. Now 34 and
in his third season of retirement, Lemieux is a rookie again,
viewing the Igloo and the franchise's fortunes from a big window of
a business suite across Center Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's a learning process,'' Lemieux said from behind
the desk in his lightly furnished corner office. On this day, from
this view, only bright, blue sky could be seen above the arena's
curved, white roof. ``I've adjusted pretty well,'' he said. ``It
was very important that I bring in some people who know how to run
a business and I can learn from these people.''
</P>
<P>
   He works in his office five days a week, except for Monday
afternoons, when he teaches his 3-year-old son to skate. He attends
most home games with his children and some of the road games alone.
He often visits the locker room. He meets once a week with the
three other members of his executive committee _ Craig Patrick, who
has been the general manager for 10 years; Tom Rooney, the chief
operating officer, who returned to the franchise at Lemieux's
urging; and Ken Sawyer, the chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux seems to be the type of executive who is smart enough to
know what he doesn't know and to hire those who do. He never went
beyond the 10th grade and he spoke little English until he was
drafted by the Penguins in 1984. But Lemieux has shown a canny
intelligence both on and off the ice. His English flows with only a
slight accent of French from his native Montreal. He speaks in
complex, confident sentences, although he rarely volunteers more
thoughts or words than required. Talk, dark and handsome, Lemieux
can seem, in close quarters, both alert and aloof, projecting the
same tense energy in a business suit that he used to exude in his
hockey uniform. His personal charisma in the community could be
essential to the survival of the franchise and to the protection of
his own financial stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been a bright young man and a quick study on
everything,'' Patrick said. ``He doesn't meddle. He doesn't call me
and say, `Craig, you should do this or that.' Or, `What the heck's
going on here?' But he likes me to talk to him about it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the financial dealings, Rooney said: ``Mario's instincts
are extremely good. He could have had additional revenue fairly
easily, but he is very selective about the company that he wants to
keep. He is by no means groveling.''
</P>
<P>
   The bookcases and shelves of Lemieux's office were almost bare.
Outside, the reception lobby seemed more like a shrine to Lemieux,
the walls filled with pictures. One showed him shaking hands at the
White House with President Bush after the Penguins won the first of
their two consecutive Stanley Cup championships in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few of those teammates are still with Pittsburgh, but
many current Penguins played either with or against Lemieux in his
final season, 1996-97. Jaromir Jagr, a rookie in the first
championship season, has inherited the captain's C from Lemieux.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, there is no difference,'' said Jagr, the NHL's most
valuable player last season, when asked how Lemieux has changed
since then. ``I don't look at him like an owner. I look at him like
a player and a friend I played with.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kevin Constantine, coaching Lemieux's Pittsburgh hockey team
is not like managing George Steinbrenner's New York baseball team.
``He's come in and been supportive and available, but pretty
removed from the day-to-day hockey operations,'' Constantine said
of Lemieux. ``I think he's concentrated more on the business
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Aleksei Kovalev, the right wing, said of Lemieux: ``You see him
a lot. He comes into the locker room and brings his kids.
Everybody's happy to be back in Pittsburgh again because nobody
knew where we were going to end up. In the summertime, we were kind
of guessing where we were going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   That was because Roger Marino, the team's third owner of the
decade, had filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection. Lemieux
rejected Marino's offer of a settlement for less than he was owed.
A move of the franchise was a possibility. So was folding the team
and selling the assets. U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz
assigned another bankruptcy judge, M. Bruce McCullough, as a
mediator, and the creative solution to the bankruptcy was worked
out.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy filing came at a bad time for the league's image.
Bruce McNall, the former owner of the Los Angeles Kings and
chairman of the NHL board of governors, had just gone to prison for
financial fraud. John Spano's brief stint as owner of the Islanders
had ended in a bank and wire fraud indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux said he agreed with recently published figures that show
the franchise value as $100 million, 20th in a 28-team league, with
a debt of $23 million. ``Pretty low, compared to other teams,'' he
said of the debt. ``A lot of people thought we were crazy to get
involved with the team, but I was always optimistic we could make
the right deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux, whose desk had many sheets of paper with numbers on
them, said his administration had reduced the ticket prices of many
seats but that the full-season subscriber base ``is up only by a
few hundred.''
</P>
<P>
   With a smile, Lemieux acknowledged that he had asked Michael
Jordan, a golfing buddy, ``five or six times'' to invest in the
Penguins and that Jordan, the former basketball star, had turned
him down. Speaking of his own investment, Lemieux said: ``I forgave
the company $7.5 million, I took $20 million in debt and put in $5
million of my own money on top of that. That's how much I believe
in this franchise. I've been involved with this franchise for 15
years. I believe in this city. The team has made some bad deals in
the past. We were able, through bankruptcy court, to rectify a lot
of those things.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest concern for the franchise will be getting a new
arena. Rooney, a nephew of Pittsburgh Steelers founder Art Rooney
and first cousin of the current Steelers owner Dan Rooney, said
that with separate baseball and football stadiums being built for
the Pirates and Steelers, the Penguins' strategy would be to
patiently wait for a critical mass of momentum to merge with
positive feelings toward Lemieux.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the new buildings open, there will be a crescendo of warm
and fuzzy feelings,'' Rooney predicted. ``What else do we need?
They'll look at our 40-year-old building and say, `How does that
present Pittsburgh for the next millennium?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest challenge is measuring Mario out in small parts,''
Rooney said. ``He's got an aura about him. When somebody adopts
Pittsburgh the way Mario has, it solidifies your own
self-confidence in your environment. In this town, he's a
quasi-biblical character. People just want to touch his cloak.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
