<SLUG> BC-EXXON-MOBIL-GAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN CORPORATE WORLDS COLLIDE: EXXON'S DECISION ON BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long after the layoffs, corporate mergers often create another
type of employee fallout: unhappiness over policies that change
because the acquiring company has a much different way of doing
things than the acquired one.
</P>
<P>
   While conflicts of corporate culture are usually thought of as
something that occurs in the executive suite, they can have a more
down-to-earth effect, like how much a company contributes to
charities and civic groups, where it moves its headquarters and
what benefits it offers employees. For example, employees of
Warner-Lambert are anxiously watching to see who wins the battle
for their company: Pfizer Inc., which analysts say has the best
rank-and-file benefits in the pharmaceutical industry, or the
American Home Products Corp.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the process of melding the different cultures that
are Exxon, the conservative, tight-lipped Texas oil company, and
Mobil, its more outgoing Virginia-based merger partner, began
creating a firestorm. Gay rights advocates publicized a move by
Exxon Mobil, the name of the new company, to revoke a Mobil policy
that provided health care coverage to the partners of newly hired
gay employees.
</P>
<P>
   The action goes against a trend of private and public employers
increasingly offering such ``domestic partner'' benefits, though
gay rights activists note that 85 percent of large United States
companies still do not offer such health care coverage.
</P>
<P>
   They credit Lucio Noto, the former Mobil chairman and now Exxon
Mobil's vice chairman, for pushing Mobil to adopt what they
consider to have been gay-friendly policies. ``Mobil took the lead
in trying to be sensitive to employee needs,'' said David M. Smith,
communications director for the Human Rights Campaign, the gay
rights advocacy group in Washington that publicized the Exxon Mobil
policy on domestic partner benefits.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, advocates note that earlier this year Exxon
shareholders voted down a proposal at the company's annual meeting
that would have forced the company to offer domestic partner
benefits. The proposal, which Exxon's board recommended be
defeated, failed by a 16-to-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
   In the new company, former Exxon executives will have the lion's
share of the key jobs, including more than two-thirds of the board
seats and roughly three of every four senior officer positions.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tom Cirigliano, a company spokesman, the decision
to revoke Mobil's domestic partner policy for new employees _ those
who are already covered will get to keep their benefits _ was made
by members of a human resources transition team and approved by a
management transition team.
</P>
<P>
   Cirigliano said none of those executives were available for
comment. Employees learned of the policy in meetings during the
last week, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Cirigliano said that the same transition teams also decided to
provide several benefits more generous than what Mobil had offered,
including bigger pensions and 401(k) contributions for many
workers. And he challenged the idea that the two companies were all
that different.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cultures in so many ways are so much alike,'' he said,
including both companies' attitudes about wringing efficiencies
from the business and maximizing returns for shareholders. Both
companies, Cirigliano added, have always had ``very strong
commitments to the communities we're in.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
