u w BC-JUDGES-INTERNET-NYT &LR;      12-07 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGES-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMITTEE BLOCKS RELEASE OF FINANCIAL INFORMATION ON FEDERAL
JUDGES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Days before an Internet news service was to put the
financial disclosure forms of all 1,600 federal judges on the World
Wide Web, the chairman of a special committee of judges has blocked
the release of the information and says the panel will review the
matter this week.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Redmond, a spokesman for the Administrative Office of the
Courts, said that while the information had been generally
available to people who applied as individuals, several judges had
become concerned that a wholesale dissemination of it could
threaten their security.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, William J. Zloch, a federal trial judge in Florida
who is chairman of the Committee on Financial Disclosure for the
Judicial Conference, the governing body of the federal courts,
ordered last week that the release of the records to the Internet
service, APBnews.com, be barred.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Zloch put a hold on some three dozen other such
requests, from individuals and groups, and called a meeting for
Friday in Washington, where the committee, composed of 15 sitting
judges, will discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Like high-ranking officials in both the legislative and
executive branches, federal judges have been required by law since
1979 to report all family assets within broad ranges of estimated
worth.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Redmond explained that until now, a request by an individual
for a judge's financial disclosure form led to the judge's being
notified before the information was released. A judge who
considered the applicant a possible security threat could have the
file edited to eliminate information that might be used to locate
him or his family.
</P>
<P>
   If the financial disclosure data was put on the Web, Ms. Redmond
said, those who see it could not be screened as they are now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very concerned about the security of the procedures,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   All this seems overstated to Bob Port, a senior editor at
APBnews.com, whose site features criminal-law issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``On its face, the security concerns sound reasonable,'' Port
said. But in fact, he said, there is little information in the
forms that could be used to threaten a judge. The forms do not show
home addresses or telephone numbers, for instance, although among
the things that officials are obliged to disclose on them are the
general locations of assets like mountain or lake cottages that
produce income.
</P>
<P>
   Port also said the practice of notifying judges of the identity
of those seeking access to the forms only discouraged people like
litigants and lawyers, who, he said, have a legitimate need to see
them, to check for judges' conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Port and his colleagues at APBnews.com requested the disclosure
forms last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Port explained that publishing the forms seemed a helpful thing
to do as it would allow lawyers and litigants to look at the forms
``without being intimidated by the knowledge that the judge would
know they had requested it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 1, APBnews.com mailed a check for $2,516 to cover the
cost of copying 12,580 pages of documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had everything ready to put it into the system this week,''
Port said. ``We had equipment to scan the pages and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Judges' financial disclosure statements have, by law, been
available to the public in the same fashion as the forms for
cabinet officers, senior administration officials, members of
Congress and some of their senior aides.
</P>
<P>
   But judges generally consider themselves to be entitled to
greater privacy than those in the other branches of government.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a long history of being reluctant to give out
information,'' said Port. ``I understand that it's an invasion of
privacy, but unfortunately, they're in public service, they have a
job for life and this comes with the territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Congress amended the law to allow judges to withhold
information temporarily for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Redmond said the congressional action explicitly recognizes
the security dimensions when it comes to the disclosure of judges'
finances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
