r a BC-WILSON-AZR &LR;      12-07 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRAIT TO KEEP OUT OF THE WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   George McGovern, the 1972 Demo cratic presidential candidate,
wrote a bum essay the other day that deserves attention. &QL; 
Not for the argument he makes _ a tortured defense of Lyndon John
son's presidency _ but for remind ing us of a vital attribute of
presidential leadership as we survey the current crop of
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   That attribute is the ability to admit mistakes and change
course, the kind of open-mindedness that LBJ's oversized ego didn't
allow.
</P>
<P>
   I always liked McGovern, a decent and thoughtful Midwesterner.
When Richard Nixon beat his brains out in the '72 election _
McGovern carried only Massachusetts and the District of Columbia _
I thought the better man lost.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern's views were too left for most Americans, but even if
you didn't buy his liberalism you could respect his principled
opposition to the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   He recognized then what most historians agree on today: The
costly war was a colossal mistake. He properly chastised both
Johnson and Nixon for their handling of it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, writing in Sunday's New York Times, McGovern praised LBJ's
domestic record and let him off the hook on Vietnam because he
didn't start it and because of doubts Johnson voiced on White House
tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had been up to Lyndon Johnson, we would not have gone
into Vietnam in the first place,'' McGovern wrote. ``It would be a
historic tragedy if his outstanding domestic record remained
forever obscured by his involvement in a war he did not begin and
did not know how to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern said he was motivated by a recent speech by economist
John Kenneth Galbraith, who lauded Johnson and lamented that the
Vietnam War has ``become the totally defining event of those
years.''
</P>
<P>
   According to McGovern, the White House tapes show that John son
had ``terrible doubts and re grets'' even while he was escalating
the war.
</P>
<P>
   Talking with national-security ad viser McGeorge Bundy in May
1964, Johnson said, ``I don't think it's worth fighting for, and I
don't think that we can get out. It's just the biggest damn mess I
ever saw.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation the same day with Georgia Sen. Richard
Russell, LBJ talked about how he would feel if one man he knew, a
sergeant with six kids, was ordered to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what the hell are we going to get out of his doing it?''
Johnson said. ``It just makes the chills run up my back.''
</P>
<P>
   While such comments strike Mc Govern as evidence of Johnson's
humanity, they lead me to respect his presidency less. Sending thou
sands of Americans to die in a war he was convinced had to be
fought is one thing. Sending them into a war he didn't think worth
fighting is something else and morally indefen sible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me think worse of him that he had these serious
doubts and didn't act,'' said Ken Goldstein, assistant professor of
political sci ence at Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's honorable to express doubts, but not to continue to
pursue a policy that you know in your heart is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trying to disengage, Johnson chose to rationalize his
decisions and demonize his critics. When members of his
administration tried to warn him that enlarging the war would be a
mistake, Johnson considered them disloyal and kept them out of his
office.
</P>
<P>
   LBJ's grandiose self-image didn't leave much room for reversing
policy decisions. He saw himself as a larger-than-life character, a
presi dent who accomplished things lesser leaders couldn't pull
off. His record for getting things done in Congress was
unparalleled. Winning in Viet nam would have been one more coonskin
to nail on the wall of the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   As this year's presidential candi dates talk up their
credentials, voters would do well to remember LBJ, a large and
forceful man with many political strengths. Being big enough to
change his mind when it counted most wasn't one of them. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 2320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX(EQ)JOHNSON-FAMILY     12-07 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX(EQ)JOHNSON-FAMILY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTER REMEMBERED AT SERVICE AS QUESTIONS ARISE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of memorial service (NYT34) is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mg) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ira Johnson on Tuesday stood in the dingy ring at
Gleason's Gym in Brooklyn where her son, Stephan, had trained for
his last fight, a bout that led to his death on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   She talked about her son's fascination with boxing, how she had
begged him to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stephan once told me, `Stop asking me to quit boxing,''' Ira
Johnson said as the cacophony of the gym became a respectful hush.
``He said: `I have never been to jail. I never done drugs. So just
let me pursue my passion.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was a tearful memorial held by the family of Stephan Johnson,
the Brooklyn-born fighter who died of head injuries that he
received in a bout on Nov. 20 in Atlantic City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   But questions remained on Tuesday about Johnson's medical
condition when he stepped into the ring and whether boxing
officials in at least three states had erred in allowing him to
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the questions, his family is not considering a lawsuit,
said Mercer Cook, an investment banker who has served as a
spokesman for the family.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said the neurosurgeon who cared for Johnson, 31, for 15
days at the Atlantic City Medical Center has told the family that
there was no clear evidence of a previous injury to Johnson's brain
before he suffered the coma in his last bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not blaming anyone for what happened,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of fighters in sweats, some with their hands wrapped in
tape, some with faces bearing the scars of past bouts, stopped
their workouts for a few minutes on Tuesday to listen to Johnson's
mother and his fiancee talk about his love of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's fiancee, Bonnie Smith, said Johnson was a man ``rich
in goodness'' who had influenced many people through his devotion
to boxing and his teaching at the Equinox Health Club. She broke
into tears when she said the measure of a man's life was not the
number of years he lived, but the number of people he touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stephan prepared for this last fight as if it was his first,''
Smith said. ``He never gave up his dream of being a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Paul Vaden, the boxer who knocked Johnson out in Atlantic
City, sent a message, saying Johnson ``was a champion who now
belongs to the sanctioning body of God.'' Vaden's manager, Elvis
Phillips, then gave Ira Johnson a ceremonial champion's belt from
the International Boxing Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a journeyman fighter who perennially had been one fight
away from becoming a contender, won the IBO's middleweight title
last year when he upset Sam Garr but had never received a belt.
Teary-eyed and surprised, his mother held the belt up.
</P>
<P>
   While the family tried to put the best face on Johnson's death,
some of the fighters muttered that Johnson should not have been
allowed to fight in Atlantic City. Several questioned whether the
state boxing commissions had been diligent in looking into
Johnson's medical history after he was knocked out in Toronto last
April.
</P>
<P>
   In that fight, against Fitz Vanderpool, Johnson dropped his
hands, staggered backward and lost consciousness after receiving
what appeared to be several light blows. He had to be hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shouldn't have been allowed to fight,'' said Edwin Viruet,
a lightweight boxer. ``If he fainted over there, why did they
accept him over here?''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether he had an brain injury when he entered the
ring against Vaden, Johnson's death offered a look into the often
haphazard way boxing is regulated in the United States and Canada.
The Canadian authorities suspended Johnson for 60 days and required
him to undergo a CT scan, a brain-wave test and a series of
psychometric tests involving memory and motor skills.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who told friends he suffered dizziness after the
Toronto fight, had the scan done at Mount Sinai Hospital on April
16 and later sent the results to the Canadian authorities. The
Ontario athletic commissioner, Ken Hayaschi, said there were slight
abnormalities in the scan that warranted further tests and refused
to lift the suspension. Johnson was still suspended in Canada when
he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was normal, but it was borderline normal,'' Hayaschi said
of Johnson's test. ``I would never have let him fight again based
on that CAT scan alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson nevertheless managed to persuade boxing officials in
South Carolina, Georgia and New Jersey to let him fight on the
strength of the same scan.
</P>
<P>
   James Knight, a spokesman for the South Carolina State Athletic
Commission, said commissioners decided they were not bound by
Ontario's ruling. The state approved a fight on Aug. 7 against
Otilio Villareal, which Johnson won in 10 rounds. Georgia officials
also looked at the test and let him fight Calvin Moody on Oct. 2 in
Albany, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, an official at the State Athletic Control
Commission, Sylvester Cuyler, approved Johnson's application on the
basis of the April CT scan, an eye test, an electrocardiogram and
an HIV test, said a spokeswoman for the commission, Rhonda
Utley-Herring.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy on Monday showed Johnson had died of a ``closed head
injury and left subdural hematoma with multiple complications,''
Dr. Hydow Park, a medical examiner, told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the truth about his medical condition, Johnson's
friends and relatives said the fighter had told them he was
confident after the tests at Mount Sinai that his health was good
enough to let him continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly felt comfortable,'' a friend, Charles Jamison,
said. ``It's obvious that more communication among jurisdictions
could have helped, but clearly, from our talking to Stephan, he
felt he was qualified to get into the ring.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
