<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2360 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-CENDANT-MARKETPLACE-1     12-07 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENDANT-MARKETPLACE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: CENDANT AGREES TO SETTLE FRAUD CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to correct full name of CUC in 2nd graf and to change
description from `computer' to `online.' Inserts response from
Ernst and Young as 4th graf in 2nd take.) 
(mk) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cendant Corp., the big franchiser that operates Ramada Inn
hotels and Avis car rental agencies, agreed Tuesday to pay its
stockholders $2.8 billion to settle charges of widespread
accounting fraud that wiped out billions in the company's market
value. The settlement is by far the largest ever in a securities
class-action suit.
</P>
<P>
   The shareholders, led by the pension funds of New York state,
New York City and California, contended that CUC International, an
online and telephone shopping services company that combined with
HFS Inc. in 1997 to form Cendant, had greatly inflated earnings and
profits and that executives no longer with the company sold shares
before the irregularities were publicly disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a company that engaged in egregious and fraudulent
practices,'' said H. Carl McCall, the New York state comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office in Newark, N.J., and the Securities
and Exchange Commission are continuing criminal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Cendant plunged to $19 from $35 on April 16, 1998, a
day after the company announced widespread accounting
irregularities at CUC, reducing the company's value by $14.4
billion. McCall said that the New York State Common Retirement
Fund, the New York City Pension Funds and the California Public
Employees' Retirement System lost a combined $89 million on that
day. .
</P>
<P>
   McCall said the pension funds, which held 11.7 million shares
when the fraud was disclosed, expected to recover 40 percent to 60
percent of their losses.
</P>
<P>
   Cendant did not detail the accounting irregularities in April,
but the company reported in August 1998 that more than $640 million
in profits reported for the previous three years had been
fictional. The inflated profits, state officials said, helped to
drive up the share price of CUC and make it attractive to potential
merger partners. CUC executives, along with other shareholders,
benefited individually as the stock price rose.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than two weeks before the August announcement, the
former chairman and chief executive of CUC, Walter Forbes, and
eight former CUC directors resigned from the board. Forbes has
denied any knowledge of the accounting irregularities. Four other
senior CUC executives resigned after the disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $2.8 billion settlement, Cendant also agreed,
at the insistence of the pension funds, to several changes in its
corporate structure to create a more independent board and to
prevent executives from increasing stock option benefits without
the consent of shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a unique class action waged by large plaintiffs and
not your typical class action by owners of 100 shares or so,'' said
John Coffee, a Columbia University law professor who specializes in
corporate governance.
</P>
<P>
   ``These large pension funds,'' he said, ``were properly trying
in this action to not only recover financial losses but to realize
their priorities in corporate governance.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Silverman, the chief executive of Cendant, said the
settlement ``brings closure to this most unfortunate event.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who negotiated the settlement said they could not
discuss how much of the $2.8 billion they would receive because
U.S. District Judge William Walls had placed the terms of their
payment under seal until all litigation is complete. But James
Newman, an expert on class-action suits and the publisher of
Securities Class Action Alert, said it was likely they would
receive about 15 percent of the $2.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining portion of the settlement is to be distributed to
shareholders in proportion to their loses, said Leonard Barrack, a
partner in the Philadelphia law firm of Barrack, Rodos &AMP; Bacine,
which worked out the settlement with Cendant along with its
co-counsel, Bernstein, Litowitz, Berger &AMP; Grossmann in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders and Cendant are suing Ernst &AMP; Young, the company's
former accountant. The suits contend that the auditor certified
CUC's false financial statements. In its suit, Cendant accused
Ernst &AMP; Young of malpractice and breach of contract. As part of the
settlement, Cendant said it would pass on half of any monetary
awards in its case against the auditor to its shareholders. Ernst &AMP;
Young has said that Cendant's claims are without merit.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Parnell, a spokesman for Ernst &AMP; Young, said, ``Our
contention is that we suffered fraud in that both CUC management
and subsequently Cendant management provided to the firm financial
information they knew was false.'' He said Ernst &AMP; Young had
contersued Cendant and that it had been discussing a possible
settlement with the shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.8 billion is nearly double the $1.5 billion that
Prudential Securities paid in 1994 to settle claims by investors,
many of them elderly, who lost money on high-risk limited
partnerships they could ill afford. But it was roughly 10 times
greater than the $270 million that American Continental Corp.
agreed to pay investors in its Lincoln Savings &AMP; Loan unit in a
series of settlements in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The settlements are starting to be much larger,'' Newman said,
``because of the overheated stock market. The prices of shares are
so inflated that when bad news comes out billions of dollars are
lost and investors are finally getting a decent recoupment of their
losses.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall and Alan Hevesi, the New York City comptroller, said the
state and city pension funds had no plans to sell their stock in
Cendant. ``The culture or philosophy of our pension fund management
is to invest for the long run, not for a quick hit,'' McCall said.
``If we can have an influence on the company for the long run,
that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we pulled out now,'' he added, ``we would suffer some
losses because the stock is worth less than when we bought it.''
Aides to McCall said they could not immediately determine the
average cost of shares to the pension funds but that they
calculated their losses from the mid-30s price when the stock
plunged. Cendant closed at $18.375 Tuesday, up $1.1875 on news of
the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cendant can again be valued based on the performance of our
businesses without the overhang of this litigation,'' Silverman
said. He said that the investigations by the U.S. attorney's office
and the SEC ``will not affect the company or its current officers
and directors.''
</P>
<P>
   The pension funds leading the suit reached an agreement with
Cendant that the majority of its board would be independent, that
the audit, nominating and compensation committees would be made up
of independent board members and that all directors would be
elected annually.
</P>
<P>
   Elliot Bloom, a spokesman for Cendant, said that several changes
had already been made. Nine of the board's 14 members are
independent directors, he said, and independent directors make up
the entire membership of the audit and compensation committees. He
said a new nominating committee was being formed.
</P>
<P>
   He said Cendant planned to ask shareholders to approve one-year
terms for board members at the annual meeting next spring,
restoring a practice at HFS before the merger with CUC.
</P>
<P>
   The measure on stock options was designed to prevent a practice
known as ``repricing'' in which the exercise price of options is
lowered when a company's market value drops. ``Many times
management is responsible for a drop in the stock price, and they
shouldn't be compensated for that,'' Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom said Cendant had put the stock option requirement into
effect immediately by executive order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
