<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRAIT TO KEEP OUT OF THE WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   George McGovern, the 1972 Demo cratic presidential candidate,
wrote a bum essay the other day that deserves attention. &QL; 
Not for the argument he makes _ a tortured defense of Lyndon John
son's presidency _ but for remind ing us of a vital attribute of
presidential leadership as we survey the current crop of
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   That attribute is the ability to admit mistakes and change
course, the kind of open-mindedness that LBJ's oversized ego didn't
allow.
</P>
<P>
   I always liked McGovern, a decent and thoughtful Midwesterner.
When Richard Nixon beat his brains out in the '72 election _
McGovern carried only Massachusetts and the District of Columbia _
I thought the better man lost.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern's views were too left for most Americans, but even if
you didn't buy his liberalism you could respect his principled
opposition to the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   He recognized then what most historians agree on today: The
costly war was a colossal mistake. He properly chastised both
Johnson and Nixon for their handling of it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, writing in Sunday's New York Times, McGovern praised LBJ's
domestic record and let him off the hook on Vietnam because he
didn't start it and because of doubts Johnson voiced on White House
tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had been up to Lyndon Johnson, we would not have gone
into Vietnam in the first place,'' McGovern wrote. ``It would be a
historic tragedy if his outstanding domestic record remained
forever obscured by his involvement in a war he did not begin and
did not know how to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern said he was motivated by a recent speech by economist
John Kenneth Galbraith, who lauded Johnson and lamented that the
Vietnam War has ``become the totally defining event of those
years.''
</P>
<P>
   According to McGovern, the White House tapes show that John son
had ``terrible doubts and re grets'' even while he was escalating
the war.
</P>
<P>
   Talking with national-security ad viser McGeorge Bundy in May
1964, Johnson said, ``I don't think it's worth fighting for, and I
don't think that we can get out. It's just the biggest damn mess I
ever saw.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation the same day with Georgia Sen. Richard
Russell, LBJ talked about how he would feel if one man he knew, a
sergeant with six kids, was ordered to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what the hell are we going to get out of his doing it?''
Johnson said. ``It just makes the chills run up my back.''
</P>
<P>
   While such comments strike Mc Govern as evidence of Johnson's
humanity, they lead me to respect his presidency less. Sending thou
sands of Americans to die in a war he was convinced had to be
fought is one thing. Sending them into a war he didn't think worth
fighting is something else and morally indefen sible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me think worse of him that he had these serious
doubts and didn't act,'' said Ken Goldstein, assistant professor of
political sci ence at Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's honorable to express doubts, but not to continue to
pursue a policy that you know in your heart is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trying to disengage, Johnson chose to rationalize his
decisions and demonize his critics. When members of his
administration tried to warn him that enlarging the war would be a
mistake, Johnson considered them disloyal and kept them out of his
office.
</P>
<P>
   LBJ's grandiose self-image didn't leave much room for reversing
policy decisions. He saw himself as a larger-than-life character, a
presi dent who accomplished things lesser leaders couldn't pull
off. His record for getting things done in Congress was
unparalleled. Winning in Viet nam would have been one more coonskin
to nail on the wall of the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   As this year's presidential candi dates talk up their
credentials, voters would do well to remember LBJ, a large and
forceful man with many political strengths. Being big enough to
change his mind when it counted most wasn't one of them. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
