<SLUG> BC-MONEY-BAG-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
Found fortune? Couple picks $300,000 off street 
 
By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The blue bag lying in the middle of a busy thoroughfare
looked like a student's book tote.
</P>
<P>
   But its contents caused a Duncanville, Texas, woman to
hyperventilate.
</P>
<P>
   It contained nearly $300,000, a chrome 9 mm handgun and 18
rounds of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   After retrieving the bag from traffic and inspecting its
contents, the woman and her husband immediately flagged down a
police officer. The officer summoned a supervisor to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did the smart thing by turning the money in,'' said
Dallas Deputy Police Chief Danny Garcia. ``If there is a strong
indication that found money is part of a criminal offense, a
citizen has an obligation to turn it in. The gun is a strong
indicator of a criminal offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Surrendering the cash was smart for another reason, Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was part of a drug payment drop, the owner could have
seen them take it. That could create a danger for them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The husband and wife were not identified by the police.
</P>
<P>
   The police report states only that the couple found the bag near
the Dallas suburb of Duncanville.
</P>
<P>
   Police have not been able to trace the origins of the money, but
Garcia said there have been no reports of large robberies in the
area. Therefore, he said, it may have been part of an aborted or
blundered drug transaction.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the couple may yet get the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If nobody else claims the money,'' Garcia said, ``they can
file a claim to it. Getting it that way will be safer than if they
had kept it in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   They won't get the gun, though. A city ordinance requires that
it be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 2332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
