<DOCNO> NYT19991207.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-WARRIORS-N     12-07 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-WARRIORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING WARRIORS _ AND STARKS _ NEARLY SHOCK KNICKS _ AND
SPREWELL 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A percolating John Starks was ushered around his old
haunt by the applause from the thousands who still embrace the
boyish shooter with the bounce in his step. But the house was
divided in loyalties between the cherished past and the current
cool of Latrell Sprewell for only so long.
</P>
<P>
   By the surprisingly tight end of the game, the Madison Square
Garden folks were nervously coaxing their team to hold off the
inspired Golden State Warriors. They had seen the Knicks blow a
16-point, third-quarter lead to Denver on Sunday, and now an
11-point, fourth-quarter lead had melted to 2 points with 4.1
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't Starks or Sprewell who settled things. It was the
reliable Larry Johnson. He hit two free throws with 2.9 seconds
left to secure the Knicks' 89-83 victory and boost their record to
11-9. Starks finished the game 3 for 12 with 7 points; Sprewell
ended 9 for 20 with 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State Coach P.J. Carlesimo lingered at midcourt after the
game to shake the hands of some of the Knicks who passed him, but
Sprewell was not among them. Sprewell departed in a different
direction after a game that was not nearly the blowout he had been
counting on.
</P>
<P>
   Using second-chance points from Antawn Jamison and an extra
effort from another former Knick, Terry Cummings, the Warriors
(2-15) were within 85-82 with 37.4 seconds to play. Instead of
stopping the nonsense, Allan Houston shuffled his feet with the
ball and was called for traveling with 21.3 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Houston had a chance to redeem himself, though. He stripped the
ball from Chris Mills with 6 seconds left, but when he went to the
free-throw line with 5.4 seconds to play, Houston inexplicably
missed both shots, the second game in a row that he has come up
empty in a critical situation.
</P>
<P>
   With 5.1 seconds left, the Warriors still had a chance. Chris
Carr was immediately fouled on the inbound pass. With 4.1 seconds
left he hit the first free throw and intentionally missed the
second. But the rebound was grabbed by Thomas with 3.5 seconds
left, and the Golden State strategy had misfired.
</P>
<P>
   After starting out so well, Sprewell missed 10 of his last 12
shots and was of no help to the Knicks down the stretch. With
Houston also groping to find his rhythm, the Knicks had to rely on
the Warriors to miss on their chances. Mookie Blaylock did just
that, missing on a 3-point attempt to tie the score with 8 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   There was an undercurrent of anticipation before the game. Would
Sprewell shake the hand of the coach he assaulted two years ago?
No.
</P>
<P>
   Carlesimo made an attempt when the two met last month, but he
did not venture out to catch Sprewell's eye this time. It would
probably have been futile if he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to sit here and say 'm going to approach him,''
Sprewell said before the game. ``With the seriousness of what
happened, it's not like you shake hands, say, OK, it's fine. And
that's it. It's not that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell insisted his edge to this game did not conjure up the
angry edge that he had when he stepped into the hostile vibes
crashing around the New Arena at Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   When his name was announced there, boos rushed through his head.
Last night, the atmosphere was much different for Starks' arrival.
Starks' name was the first one announced, and on cue, he popped
through the gantlet of Warriors, blew four kisses to the screaming
crowd and stood alone, bouncing like a kid on box springs during
the 15 to 20 seconds of applause.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, a few seconds after the opening tip, Starks
plunged right into the feel-good moment. In an effort to save the
jump ball that began the game, Starks leaped into celebrity row.
Everyone roared approval.
</P>
<P>
   It was Starks' night; even Sprewell understood that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think it'll be an emotional game,'' Sprewell had said
earlier. `'But I don't know if it'll be as emotional for me as it
will be for John Starks. It's really kind of flip-flopped.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, so were the performances. Sprewell seemed too hyped,
too emotionally charged to find his shot in Oakland. Starks, under
pressure to perform well in an arena he had always adored as a
Knick, seemed as tight as a clenched fist to begin the game.
</P>
<P>
   Still backpedaling after every shot _ some things never change _
Starks was off his mark. He was long, short, and he missed
completely as he finished the first half 0 for 4 from the floor.
His counterpart to the emotional night, Sprewell, was just the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was the offensive supplier for the Knicks. While
Houston struggled to hit 2 of 7 shots, Sprewell made 7 of his first
8 shots and ended the first half with 21 points, helping to give
the Knicks a 49-38 lead.
</P>
<P>
   A revolving door of defenders _ from Starks, to Mills to
Blaylock _ tried to put up a resistance to Sprewell, but it was in
vain. On one made-for-television move, Sprewell drove past Mills,
tiptoed through the paint and a thicket of defenders, launched
himself and sent a double-pumped scoop shot into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Sprewell's performance overwhelming Starks', the
Knicks were not running away with the game. They built a 13-point
lead in the second quarter, but a drought that left them scoreless
for a four-minute stretch, plus their inability to come up with
offensive rebounds, allowed the Warriors to creep within 39-34 with
4:23 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   The second-chance points players like Jamison, who had 18
first-half points, were firing over Kurt Thomas, Chris Dudley and
Marcus Camby to keep the Warriors close.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as Sprewell, who took a three-and-a-half-minute
rest, returned, the Knicks were able to gather themselves, score
points and hold their 11-point lead at the half. Although the
Knicks held the Warriors to 24.5 percent shooting from the field,
they were outrebounded, 33-24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
