<SLUG> BC-HASBRO-CUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FORCE LEAVES HASBRO WITH JOBS CUT AND A $97 MILLION
RESTRUCTURING CHARGE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The toymaker Hasbro Inc. said Tuesday that it was eliminating
2,200 jobs, or more than 20 percent of its work force, and taking a
restructuring charge of $97 million, or 50 cents a share, in the
final quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro hopes to increase sales by expanding its offerings of
electronic toys and CD-ROM games and its popular Pokemon line. But
analysts said retail sales of Hasbro's ``Star Wars'' line were
sluggish as the latest movie failed to meet the hype-induced
expectations at the box office. The company, based in Pawtucket,
R.I., hopes to compensate with Pokemon trading cards, one of this
year's sensations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The force is with Pokemon, not `Star Wars,''' said Tony Gikas,
an industry analyst at U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Krutick, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, said Hasbro
had sold $600 million to $650 million of ``Star Wars'' products to
retailers in 1999, but they were not exactly flying out of the
stores, raising concerns in the industry about a crimp in demand
for new toys next year.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon sales exceeded $100 million, bolstered by Hasbro's
purchase of the maker of the cards, Wizard of the Coast. Industry
analysts projected $750 million or more in combined sales for
``Star Wars'' and Pokemon next year as Pokemon gains.
</P>
<P>
   The company said Furby dolls, another strong seller, brought in
$300 million this year. Total 1999 revenue will be about $4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toy industry is switching to electronics,'' said Jim
Silver, publisher of The Toy Book, a monthly trade magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirteen of the top selling items this year had electronic
bells and whistles,'' he said, adding that Amazing Ally, an
electronic smart doll made by Playmates Toys Inc., was already sold
out in most New York stores.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Gustafson, a senior portfolio manager in Chicago with Stein
Roe &AMP; Farnham, which owns Hasbro shares, said Tuesday's
announcements were ``an admission that Hasbro has to change the way
it does business in order to adjust to the changing environment for
toy companies.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that big customers like Wal-Mart Stores were insisting
on delivery on demand for hot products, pushing the costs of
maintaining inventories back on the toy makers. ``As a result,
Hasbro has to cut its cost structure to absorb that inventory
expense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Hasbro declined 18.75 cents Tuesday, to $21.25, on the
New York Stock Exchange. Mattel Inc., the biggest toy maker, was
down 37.5 cents, to $14.50.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the Hasbro announcements were anticipated, and the
company said it expected earnings for the quarter and year would
meet expectations on Wall Street. About 40 percent of Hasbro sales
come in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it expected to squeeze out cost savings of $16
million next year and $23 million in 2001. But next year, at least,
Hasbro said the savings would not be reflected in higher earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro plans to close plants in Tijuana, Mexico, and Ashford,
England, and move production to China and other Asian countries.
The company is eliminating 2,200 jobs, about 300 in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Charness, a senior vice president of Hasbro, said it was
also closing its flight simulation studio in Alameda, Calif.,
because production costs were high and sales volume was low.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are focusing on higher profit margin categories and mass
market categories,'' he said, as well as ``untapped potential'' in
new versions of brands like Monopoly and Scrabble.
</P>
<P>
   About half of Hasbro's sales are in board games of all sorts,
including electronic versions, he said. Analysts said Hasbro was
the third-largest maker of entertainment games for personal
computers, behind Electronic Arts, which makes sports games, and
French-based Havas Interactive.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro forecast $300 million in sales of interactive products
this year, or about 7.5 percent of its $4 billion total, compared
with $150 million last year, or 4.6 percent of 1998 sales of $3.3
billion. Toy industry sales in all categories are growing at only
about 5 percent annually.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
