<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2373 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      12-07 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Today's game against the 76ers will be billed as Charles Barkley's
return to Philadelphia, the city where he began his Hall of Fame
career in 1984, and rightfully so.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barkley, who has announced he will retire at the end of the
current season, will be the subject of most of the interviews and
will be honored by the Sixers during tonight's game at First Union
Center.
</P>
<P>
   But the game represents a homecoming for another Rocket, too.
</P>
<P>
   Cuttino Mobley, a Philly native, attended Cardinal Dougherty
High School in Philadelphia before spending a year at Maine Central
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley, however, learned most of his basketball lessons in the
Philadelphia schoolyards, where he was tutored by some of the
city's best, including Eddie Jones, now with the Charlotte Hornets,
and current Sixer Aaron McKie, who grew up in Philadelphia and
attended Temple University.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley is especially close to Jones, a Florida native who played
with McKie at Temple. It was Jones, who has that same long-armed,
slender physique that Mobley possesses, who took the relatively
unheralded player under his wing and showed him how to play the
game at a higher level.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my mentor,'' Mobley said of Jones. ``Since I was 15 or 16
years old. He and Aaron McKie. I've been watching and playing with
them since I was around 16 years old, just playing and learning
more. And (Temple's) John Chaney is right there, who is a great
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was things like when you're on defense, keeping your hands
active. Just being a complete player. I've always said that I model
myself after Scottie Pippen and Eddie Jones because they don't have
a weakness. They do everything. They might not be excellent at one
thing, but they're good at everything, and that's what you need to
be. That way you're more valuable to your team.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mobley is certainly that to the Rockets _ one of the most
valuable assets on a team that seems to keep losing key pieces with
each passing game. Mobley's success with the Rockets, however, begs
the simple question: Why did he last so long in the draft?
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing for a high-profile program at Rhode Island,
Mobley lasted until the 41st pick in the 1998 NBA draft. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Mobley just shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a point in time when they were saying, `Oh, he can't
handle the ball. Oh, he's too small (to play shooting guard),' and
all this and all that,'' Mobley said. ``And these people have never
even played basketball before, but they're the critics. How can you
never have played the game, even in the streets, and then go tell a
person that they can't play basketball?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an overachiever. I graduated college with a double major,
and it wasn't food nutrition; it was psychology and communications.
I'm just an overachiever. I love it when people say I can't do
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he's used to being overlooked. During his high school
days in Philadelphia, Mobley was easy to overlook since Simon
Gratz, the No. 1 team not only in the state of Pennsylvania but in
the nation, featured a kid named Rasheed Wallace who hogged all the
attention. And any remaining ink spilled over to Philadelphia's
Roman Catholic, which was the 20th-ranked high school team in the
nation, or to Olney High, which starred 6-11 Jason Lawson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like that little bug that's surrounded by a lot of big
bugs,'' Mobley said. ``You get overshadowed. It really doesn't
matter to me. I don't need the (publicity). I don't need anything,
really. I just want to play and go hard. We have 30-something pros
in Philadelphia every summer, and they live there and are from
there. So it's kind of hard to not get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can go to the hole there and get beat up like that, I
don't care where you are in the country, you'll do well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets kept their fingers crossed in the draft, hoping they
could still nab the 6-4 guard in the second round. And if they had
any doubts at all after selecting Mobley at No. 41, they were
erased during the prolonged lockout, when Mobley spent his time
playing in high-level pickup games around Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he was good, and then during the lockout people who
had been around on the East Coast and had been working out and were
around Cuttino kept coming back with stories about how this guy
could really play,'' coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``And we knew
that he was good. We just couldn't wait to get him here because
everybody was talking about his talent and his attitude toward the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude is what keeps Mobley on the upward curve when it
comes to learning his craft _ another byproduct of his days with
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   A point guard last year, Mobley has made the move to shooting
guard with the arrival of super-rookie Steve Francis. And Mobley
has responded well, giving the Rockets an added dimension of being
able to break defenses down with his one-on-one moves.
</P>
<P>
   Already a 3-point threat, Mobley, who is averaging 13.5 points,
has worked on his midrange game as well, all to keep defenses off
balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie told me to always work on every single thing,'' Mobley
said. ``And I try to work on everything possible. A coach can't
say, `OK, he (Mobley) is the type of guy who's either going to
shoot the 3 or go inside for a layup.' Or, `He's only going to go
left or only going to go right.' I try to work on every single
thing possible, and it helps me.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that work ethic that has allowed Mobley to develop into
one of the top young guards in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Is he surprised?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say no because people will take that as too
cocky,'' Mobley said. ``I've been practicing a long time. I've been
playing (against) pros since I was 16. That's six or seven years,
so I've just been ready. It's not that I surprise myself, but I
think I've surprised a lot of people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
