<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDRUSH-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOTHEBY'S CANCELS SALE OF GOLD SALVAGED FROM 1857 WRECK 
 &HT;    (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.C., Va., Ohio, Panama, Britain   By RITA REIF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The auction house Sotheby's has canceled an auction
of millions of dollars in Gold Rush treasure after a federal court
ruled against the sale. The auction was scheduled to begin
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   An injunction was issued last week by the 4th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals in Virginia to prevent the sale of the gold, which had
been expected to bring between $7 million and $10 million,
Sotheby's said. Sotheby's identifies the gold's consignors as a
group of American and British insurers or their successors.
</P>
<P>
   The auction was to take place at Sotheby's in New York on
Wednesday and Thursday and then Thursday night on a Web site
operated by Sotheby's and -Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   The gold was recovered from the paddle steamer Central America,
which sank in the Atlantic in 1857. It was salvaged in the late
1980s by the Columbus America Discovery Group of Ohio, founded by
the engineer and explorer Tommy Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, after a decade of battles over the gold's ownership,
the U.S. District Court in Norfolk, Va., awarded the insurers
nearly 400 pounds of gold _ about 8 percent of the total _ with the
rest going to the salvagers.
</P>
<P>
   David Redden, an executive vice president of Sotheby's, said
Tuesday night that negotiations had been taking place between the
insurers and the Columbus group from the time the injunction was
issued through Tuesday afternoon. ``We were notified this evening
that discussions had broken down and that the sale had to be
canceled,'' Redden said.
</P>
<P>
   Three tons of gold bars, ingots, coins and dust was shipped in
August 1857 from San Francisco bound for New York. It was
transferred to the Central America in Panama, but the boat sank in
a storm 160 miles off Cape Fear, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's said that it hoped the auction could be rescheduled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
