<HEADER>
A2379 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AFRICAN-FILM-FEST-NYT     12-07 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICAN-FILM-FEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANIMATED, REVEALING AFRICAN FOLK TALE
</HEADLINE>
  (mg) 
 By LYNDA RICHARDSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an animated film that has been a hit in France, a
tiny boy demands to be born, only to crawl out of his mother's womb
and find his African village terrorized by a witch.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by a blend of West African fables, the film, ``Kirikou
and the Sorceress'' shows how the innocence and perseverance of the
boy, Kirikou, help him prevail over ignorance and cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   The film is scheduled to be released in the United States in
February during Black History Month. It will open first in New York
followed by Chicago and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kirikou and the Sorceress'' is one of the highlights of the
seventh annual African Diaspora Film Festival in New York, which
ends on Sunday. This year, the two-week festival, at various sites
throughout the city, has scheduled 52 films from 25 countries.
Organizers of the festival, Reinaldo and Diarah N'Daw-Spech, have
obtained the United States distribution rights.
</P>
<P>
   With a musical score by a renowned Senegalese musician, Youssou
N'Dour, this simple, graphic tale would seem to be a natural for
the big screen. And yet the film's director, Michel Ocelot of
France, was told by European and American distributors that the
animated feature would never sell because the female characters
were bare-breasted and the boy was naked.
</P>
<P>
   The distributors wanted bras on the women and pants on the
newborn Kirikou. Ocelot refused and went ahead anyway. He spent two
years raising the $4 million needed to make the film and four more
years producing it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the concerns about nudity, the film has become a success
in France, where it has been seen by more than one million
moviegoers since its release a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In June, ``Kirikou'' won the grand prize for best animated
feature at the International Festival of Animated Film in Annecy,
France. And in October, the film received first prize from juries
of both children and adults in the Chicago International Children's
Film Festival, the first time that has happened in the festival's
16-year history.
</P>
<P>
   For the festival organizers, the film succeeded precisely
because it does not present a sanitized or distorted view of
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The Spechs, a husband-and-wife team who are the founders of
ArtMattan Productions, one of only a few black distribution
companies in the country, said the film conveyed positive images of
Africans.
</P>
<P>
   The film also reflected the couple's own international
sensibilities. They lived in France before moving to the United
States. Spech was born in Cuba of Haitian and Jamaican descent; his
wife, Diarah, is French and of Malian heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no monolithic black experience,'' Spech said. ``There
is a diversity of experiences that people of African descent have
been dealing with for many centuries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that a white person goes into our culture and comes
out with an artistic product of value shows you the
interrelationship between cultures and how things are happening in
the world today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the United States, where the subjects of race and sex are
more sensitive than in Europe, the Spechs have admitted to worrying
about how American audiences will react to the nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Before signing a contract for the distribution rights, the
couple conducted an informal survey of 20 people who watched the
film and received no complaints about the nudity. The Spechs also
have received some reassurance from the reaction of groups of
schoolchildren who clapped and sang along to the film's folk tales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never came up once,'' said Mrs. Spech, who also works as
the budget manager at Teachers College, while her husband is a high
school teacher in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's natural for kids in Africa to be running around naked
until they are a certain age,'' she said. ``It's part of the
culture. Over all, people are not as hung up on nudity as they are
in the West.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Chicago film festival, the reaction was similar. But the
festival director, Rebekah Cowing, said the French distributors
initially did not want to enter the film in the festival because
they had been warned by American distributors that it would not
play well because of the nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cowing said the film had something that was missing from a
blockbuster like ``The Lion King.'' The film is about people, not
talking animals, she said. ``It shows African culture. It was
really refreshing that it features people with black skin who
weren't just sidekicks. It reinforces the positive role models.''
</P>
<P>
   Ocelot, the director, said the film explored African themes that
were true to his own memories of a childhood in Guinea. He said
those memories were of beauty, the importance of family and of the
group, and of a certain harmony with the body. He said the
partly-clad women were part of his memories, though he conceded
that the practice was now more confined to rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid, all over the streets were bare-breasted
women,'' he said. ``They are not naked women; they are dressed
normally. That's what people understand when they see the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Ocelot said he decided against using celebrities on the
soundtrack in favor of Senegalese voices in the French-language
version and black South African voices in the version dubbed in
English, to retain the flavor of Africa. He also decided to use
music by N'Dour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do it to make money,'' Ocelot said. ``I did it to
make you feel good and to have one hour of some kind of pleasure
and something which stays afterward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
