<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENSIONS-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDITORS IN DEEP DISGUISE CRACK PENSION COMPUTERS 
</HEADLINE>
 (mg) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Security experts easily broke into computers at the federal
agency that guarantees pensions, acquiring the ability to create
fictitious beneficiaries and send them money, according to a report
expected to be made public on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   For three months beginning in May, the auditors rummaged through
high-level administrative and financial system computer files at
the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp. in Washington, their activities
undetected.
</P>
<P>
   The break-ins succeeded even though Wayne Robert Poll, the
benefit corporation's inspector general, told officials in advance
that he had retained PricewaterhouseCoopers, the auditing firm, to
penetrate the computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   The report warns that the computers at the pension guarantee
agency are ``vulnerable to malicious external and internal
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   David Strauss, the agency's executive director, maintained in an
interview on Tuesday that, had the hackers tried to make a payment,
other security measures would have prevented any checks from being
issued.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to having the power to create fictitious
beneficiaries and send them money, the auditors reported that they
could have altered or deleted files on individuals and changed the
internal systems used by the benefit corporation to manage its
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The corporation, which is owned by the federal government,
guarantees that the 42 million Americans with defined-benefit
pension plans will get their retirement checks even if their
employer goes out of business. It holds $18 billion in assets, pays
$900 million annually to more than 200,000 people and will pay
benefits to at least 300,000 others when they reach retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   Access was gained in two ways. One was through dial-up modems.
Using software readily available to hackers, the auditors found
passwords that gave them high-level access. The second technique
was to masquerade as benefit corporation employees who needed a new
password or other help logging into the system.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors failed, however, to penetrate the firewall that
protects the benefit corporation's Web site from outside attack.
</P>
<P>
   The chairmen of two Senate committees that have oversight of the
benefit guarantee agency said they were disturbed by the ease of
entry and would hold a hearing in February on computer security at
the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's computer security ``has more holes than Swiss
cheese,'' said Sen. Charles E. Grassley, Republican of Iowa and
head of the Select Committee on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher S. Bond, Republican of Missouri and chairman of
the Small Business Committee, said ``their inspector general told
them he was setting the alarm clock, but the agency chose to hit
the snooze button.''
</P>
<P>
   Strauss, the agency's executive director, termed Bond's remark
``ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say we are on a very high state of alert here,''
Strauss maintained.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the security gaps have been filled, Strauss added. He
argued that even with access, the auditors could not have actually
sent money to people who were not entitled because of other
security measures, including a system of checking each new
beneficiary manually and randomly assigning which employee
authorizes each new or changed payment to a beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the auditors could not break in through the
Web site because in 1997, the agency hired consultants to make it
secure.
</P>
<P>
   Government agencies and companies often devote much more
attention to protecting against attacks over the Internet than over
telephone lines, said Fred Rica, partner in charge of penetration
studies for PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In almost 100 percent of the penetration tests I have done or
managed,'' Rica said, ``we have been able to penetrate through a
dial-in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
