<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELE-FLEXIBILITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO DEVELOPMENTS OFFER COMMUNICATIONS FLEXIBILITY
</HEADLINE>
  (mg) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the communications equipment industry continues to advance at
a white-hot pace, two small companies intend to announce on
Wednesday the development of products meant to increase the
flexibility of big communications networks.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore Networks Inc., which mounted a successful initial
public stock offering in October, intends to announce the
development of a communications switch that is possibly the first
to use light instead of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   And Ennovate Networks Inc., which has been underwritten
primarily by Japanese conglomerates and venture capitalists,
intends to announce that Psinet, a large Internet carrier, will be
the first customer for Ennovate's main product, which allows
corporations to tie far-flung offices together with ``virtual
private networks.'' Ennovate anticipates that it will make an
initial public stock offering next year.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Sycamore and Ennovate products differ, the
announcements highlight the importance that major communications
carriers are placing on delivering flexible services rather than
raw capacity. Such capacity is largely becoming a commodity,
forcing big carriers to offer customized services that relate
directly to the core operations of their corporate customers. That
requires new equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The Sycamore product could prove revolutionary. Optical
technology has been widely used for at least a decade to transmit
data between fixed points. But the network ``intelligence'' that
figures out what goes where has remained electrical, increasing the
complexity and preventing carriers from manipulating light waves as
finely as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore's product may solve those problems, allowing
communications carriers to direct different light waves to
different places with mere keystrokes. That could allow carriers to
provide large communications links to companies on demand and for
flexible amounts of time. Sycamore intends to announce that iaxis,
a small, new carrier in Europe, has agreed to try the product.
</P>
<P>
   Ennovate's product allows a corporate customer to construct
national or perhaps global networks that appear to be based on
private, dedicated communications lines. In reality, that company's
data will travel intermingled with those of other enterprises,
reducing costs, but Ennovate's product will help keep each traffic
stream separate and secure.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the deal said that Psinet has agreed to
purchase $15 million worth of equipment from Ennovate over four
years.
</P>
<P>
   That is a relatively small number, but small numbers haven't
hurt Sycamore. The company posted only $11 million in revenue in
its last fiscal year and it now has a market value of about $19
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore's technology, however, is more far-reaching than
Ennovate's and Ennovate, based in Boxborough, Mass., is unlikely to
reach that sort of valuation.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Sycamore, based in Chelmsford, Mass., closed on
Tuesday at $247.125, up $6.6875, in Nasdaq trading. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-99 2356EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
