<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2386 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k BC-HEASTER-BANKS-KAN &LR;      12-07 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-BANKS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL BANKS WILL SURVIVE DESPITE BIG-BANK CLIMATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The recent
dismantling of the banking industry's Depression-era regulatory
relic raises implicit questions as to whether this historic
development finally gives the industry's giants too much market
power.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The reality is that the world of big banking is indeed likely to
get bigger, according to a St. Louis Federal Reserve Bank
economist. Nevertheless, he says, the liberalization of banking
regulations hasn't necessarily sounded a death knell for small
banks.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy J. Yeager, in an analysis titled ``Down But Not Out: The
Future of Community Banks,'' wrote in the October edition of the
bank's publication, The Regional Economist, that small banks would
survive because of the personal service they can offer both
individuals and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, community banks, which are generally defined as
institutions with less than $300 million in assets not owned by
large bank holding companies, find safety in numbers. Of the 8,567
commercial banks in business during this year's first quarter,
Yeager notes, 82 percent were community banks.
</P>
<P>
   And while their market share is declining and probably will
continue to do so, their prospects are reasonably bright because of
the personal marketing touches they can offer. They have, for
instance, a particular edge over larger banks in the realm of
small-business lending, Yeager says.
</P>
<P>
   This edge derives from grass-roots knowledge of the local
community and its players not readily available to chain banks.
This is especially the case, Yeager points out, when prospective
business and individual borrowers are bank depositors because loan
officers can more readily and accurately track cash flows.
</P>
<P>
   Yeager concedes that improving technology combined with
deregulation have reduced some of the competitive advantages
previously enjoyed by community banks. This means community banks
must continue to distinguish themselves with innovative marketing
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   One area Yeager explores is what he calls economies of scale vs.
``economies of scope.'' Whereas large bank holding companies can
exploit economies of scale and thus operate at lower average costs,
for example, smaller banks ``can use their edge in originating and
monitoring small business by exploiting economies of scope.'' This,
he says, is the ability to produce two or more related products
more cheaply than producing them individually.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt smaller banks are a diminishing breed. From
1983 to 1998, the percentage of assets held by banks with assets of
$300 million and under fell 50 percent, while banks with $15
billion and more in assets saw their share nearly double. Meantime,
the number of $300 million-and-under banks declined nearly 40
percent, while the number of $15 billion-and-over banks increased
150 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these numbers, Yeager appears relatively confident that
imaginatively managed small banks will find niches in which they
not only will survive, but also prosper. Much of that market, he
predicts, will be outside urban areas and among prospective
customers willing to pay a premium for personal service, ``rather
than just be another anonymous face at a growing regional or
national (bank) chain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
