<SLUG> BC-BOARD-SCIENCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS BOARD VOTES TO SEND SCIENCE STANDARDS TO REVIEW BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE BEEM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   TOPEKA, Kan. _ The saga of the Kansas
science standards continued Tuesday, with the state school board
voting to send them to an outside reviewer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a 9-1 vote, the Kansas Board of Education agreed to send the
standards to a reviewer, which the board probably will select at
its January meeting. Education Commissioner Andy Tompkins said it
would be February at the earliest before any reviewer would be
finished with the standards.
</P>
<P>
   In August the state board approved the standards, which are
guidelines for what students should learn and be tested on. The
standards have caused much controversy because they downplay
evolution and leave out some references to the age of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   The standards reappeared before the board Tuesday for review
after substantial portions were rephrased by state staff members.
The rewrite became necessary because three national science
organizations, citing the August vote downplaying evolution,
refused the state's request to use their copyright material.
</P>
<P>
   Several state board members pushed for the review. Janet Waugh
of Kansas City, a moderate, proposed the move, saying the standards
approved in August were substantially changed from those written by
a 27-member committee of science teachers and professors. Those
original standards were reviewed last winter by the Council for
Basic Education in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Bingman, a Shawnee Mission West High School biology teacher
and writing committee member, suggested the second review to the
board Tuesday. When he learned of the board's vote, Bingman let out
a whoop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked, didn't it?'' Bingman said. ``It has to be better
than them just adopting them on the spot. Here's another shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Case, another writing committee member, said the action
kept the standards controversy from fading away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it pushes everything back to February or March before
they even can get an external review and can act,'' Case said.
``Then what are we _ five months from the primary?''
</P>
<P>
   Five of the 10 board members will be up for election next year,
including four of the six who voted in August to approve the
revised standards: conservatives Linda Holloway of Shawnee, Steve
Abrams of Arkansas City, Mary Douglass Brown of Wichita and Scott
Hill of Abilene. Moderate Bill Wagnon of Topeka, who voted against
the revised standards, is the fifth member up for election.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who helped write the August standards, said after the vote
that he thought an external review was an expensive redundancy. He
and the two other writers _ Abrams and moderate Harold Voth of
Haven _ based their document on the committee's standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if certain board members need a $20,000 comfort pill, I'm
open,'' said Hill, explaining his vote in favor of the review.
</P>
<P>
   Wagnon was the lone dissenter. He said after the meeting that he
could not support the process that led to the August standards. The
previous review cost between $18,000 and $20,000. Wagnon said the
board would pay that again to find out something he already knew
about the standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're fatally flawed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the board's open forum Tuesday morning, several evolution
supporters spoke. Some vowed to work for the defeat of board
members who supported the August standards. Others, like Bingman,
urged the board to reject the standards.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Ruden, a University of Kansas professor, told the board
he was representing a new organization called ROUND, or Remove Our
Uncivil Nonscience Delegates. Ruden called Holloway uncivil because
``she tried to file an arrest warrant for Steve Case.''
</P>
<P>
   Holloway told the board as Ruden stepped away from the lectern
that she did not seek to have Case arrested. Later, during a break
in the meeting, she confronted Ruden, who was sitting near Case,
and told him his facts were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway said she did talk to the Shawnee police about an e-mail
message Case sent her, requesting that she stop attacking him and
the writing committee or he would ``not hesitate to explore how I
can stop you.''
</P>
<P>
   Shawnee Lt. Jim Morgan confirmed Tuesday that Holloway
approached police when she received the message. However, an
investigating officer saw no threat in the message. Police offered
to make an informational report for future referral, but Holloway
declined, Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway said she sought police help because she felt
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is what he said,'' she said. ``I don't know what he
meant.''
</P>
<P>
   Case has said he wrote the note after Holloway publicly
criticized the writing committee. Case said he considered her
comments slanderous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
